<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS'S MOVES PUT SPRINGIN THEIR STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The grit was obvious. The passion was there, almost as
if there is a switch that every coach tells his player doesn't
exist. The Bruins played their way back into their playoff series
vs. Buffalo Sunday with that ol' tyme hockey that has kept Bruins
fans flocking to Causeway Street, ever-faithful, ever-hoping, since
the time of Eddie Shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys had to reach down,'' said Don Sweeney, ``and see what
they had inside.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the subtext and near-delirium of a fine afternoon of
hockey, it must not be lost that grit, grinding, and passion _ the
cliches of the game that do matter _ were hardly the sole
contributing factors to the Bruins putting some meaning back into
what had become a sorry washout of a series.
</P>
<P>
   After watching three games of lackluster play, coach Pat Burns
shook up his line combinations and made a key insertion on defense,
adding the quick-and-mobile Mattias Timander to the blue line. At
one point, Burns also made Kyle McLaren a left winger on the power
play. We'll say that again, just in case you thought your typist
has slipped into postseason dementia: McLaren played up front on a
five-on-four advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my job _ I had to go out and do it,'' said McLaren.
``I'm basically a big body, and that's what (Burns) wanted, go in
there, make some traffic and take the punishment. I know what it is
to take it, because I'm usually the one dishing it out.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren didn't poke one home on the power play, nor did he set
up a goal. Not every move works according to the grand plan, in
this case a grand plan born in the truth of a 3-1 series deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only change we made,'' said Burns, ``was desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, of course. Oh, the Bruins played with desperation, and
that was different, but the different deployment of the bodies made
the key difference of the day. Different folks were taking
different strokes, and from there the emotion, and the grit and
that ol' tyme whatchamacallit began to ooze out of those Black 'n
Gold uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there was the Timander factor. Right now, this is
simply a better team with Timander playing than it is with either
Grant Ledyard or Darren Van Impe (injured) in uniform. Timander
lacks some experience and isn't the grittiest guy going, but he is
a fluid skater and has a pretty impressive shot off the point.
</P>
<P>
   With a little Michael Jackson moonwalking move (sorry you Fred
Astaire fans), Timander stopped a Buffalo clearing attempt midway
through the second period, moved toward the slot, and belted a high
slapper past Dominik Hasek for a 3-1 lead. Maybe Van Impe or
Ledyard could have made that play, too, but the reality is neither
got the job done when he had his chance to do it. It was someone
else's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Timander ranks as one of those NHL/AHL guys who finds himself
down on the Boston food chain, slotted below the likes of Dave
Ellett, Van Impe, and Ledyard. Maybe it was desperation that got
him in the lineup. Whatever it is/was, he should be back there.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Burns's whole shake-and-bake approach to his
forward lines. He attempted to turn things over some in Game 4 when
he put Jason Allison between Steve Heinze and Anson Carter _ Joe
Thornton's usual wingmen. Thornton instead had Landon Wilson and
Sergei Samsonov. Those lines might have brought some spark, too,
but Thornton had to exit early after running head-first into Vaclav
Varada's knee, and the night quickly dissolved into one of the
worst postseason showings in recent Bruins history.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Mario Lemieux and Jaromir Jagr wearing the spoked B
would have made much of a difference that night, noted Allison. The
Boston cause was that shapeless, spiritless, hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5, Burns kept running through line combinations as if he
were standing at the Convenient Mart lottery machine before the
night's $74 million drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   1. Sweeney scored the tying goal (1-1) with help from Samsonov
and Tim Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   2. To start the second, Samsonov connected for the go-ahead goal
off some heady forechecking work by, guess who, Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov is the most gifted stickhandler on the Boston roster.
Suddenly, he found himself playing on a line with Taylor and
DiMaio, two-thirds of the club's voracious checking line (P.J.
Axelsson, the other third, plugged into whatever line needed a
right wing). A virtual spare part for much of the series,
Samsonov's value and effectiveness rose immeasurably with his new
steel-chinned linemates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to get the puck,'' said Burns, recognizing the fact
that the Sabres rendered Samsonov useless by tying up the speedy
winger's previous centers. ``You play with those two guys, you get
the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with elimination, there finally was some inventiveness in
the Boston game. What next, Hal Gill parked in the slot, a la Tim
Kerr, on the power play? Will we see Sweeney playing like Reijo
Ruotsalainen, one second a defenseman, the next doing Curly Howard
360s around the cage? Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing was certain: Had Burns used the same ol', same ol'
lineup Sunday, and used it the same ol', same ol' way, then those
guys would be cleaning out their lockers at the Vault this morning,
after one more same ol', same ol' conclusion to the Bruins' season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of different line combintions,'' said
Allison, who poked home his second goal of the series _ and
postseason _ with 43 seconds to play. Oh, and Axelsson had the key
assist with a muscle shot at the left post. ``I don't think the
combinations matter too much on our team, because all the guys play
on different lines all year.''
</P>
<P>
   From that diversity, came strength, with a little emotion tossed
into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what your line is, who you're playing with,'' said
Allison, ``you have to come out with passion and pride. And we did
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
