<SLUG> BC-KITTY-COLLECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY HOLDS WEALTH OF FELINE FACTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DONNA HUFFAKER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Welcome to all things cat.
</P>
<P>
   Cat astrology. Cat psychiatry. Cat anatomy. Cat photography.
Kitty history. Kitty litter.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you want to know why your whiskered pet prefers napping
on a book shelf to snoozing on a sofa cushion or you just have an
affinity for felines, The Cat Collection at Glendale Central
Library will appease even the most finicky of readers and
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   With 30,000 items, including books, magazines, journals, art and
photographs, the rare collection is touted as the world's largest,
said Nora Goldsmith, a library manager who oversees the special
collections department.
</P>
<P>
   The Cat Collection lines scores of shelves in the reference room
with nearly 6,000 books. Its broad range reaches beyond the
second-largest public cat collection at Yale, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The collection at Yale's Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript
Library, which began in the 1950s with a personal donation,
features 3,000 literary works about cats, said Patricia Willis,
curator of Yale's Collection of American Literature. Unlike the
Glendale collection, which widens a little each month, the Yale
library no longer accepts materials, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, nine miles north of the L.A. Civic Center, there
are books on cat spiritualism, complete with tarot cards to discern
kitty karma and ``unlock the mysteries'' of their nine lives. Books
on cat yoga, to help relax furry friends. Books of cat photographs
and books about taking cat photographs. And in case you're at all
worried about the relationship with your persnickety pet, ``You're
OK. Your Cat's OK.'' will help you establish a meaningful
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The library recently received a $600 donation and another load
of published cat material from the estate of Roberta Billig, the
88-year-old cat connoisseur who, with her late husband, Harvey
Billig, amassed volumes of cat breeding and research materials in
the 1940s. When their collections outgrew their space, the Billigs
donated them to the Glendale library in the mid-1950s. Thus began
the library's cat collection.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Billig was an orthopedic surgeon who studied the
movements of cats to aid his research of polio, said Lee Argabrite,
the Billigs' granddaughter. One day, he brought two Siamese cats
home with him, and their meowing stole her grandmother's heart,
Argabrite said this week from her home outside of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she had up to 31 cats in her house, including
kittens,'' Argabrite said. ``She just really loved cats.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Billig was so moved by the agile animals that she and
her husband rallied other cat aficionados and formed the Jewel City
Cat Club in 1964. The club, still in existence today, sponsored cat
shows. Roberta Billig ended up being a cat show judge, even flying
to Tokyo for a contest, Argabrite said.
</P>
<P>
   Billig collected books on breeding that dated to the 1890s,
Goldsmith said.
</P>
<P>
   But the oldest book in The Cat Collection is a German-printed
``Puss in Boots,'' published in 1823. Goldsmith retrieved the
delicate, time-worn treasure from a locked cabinet. It, like the
rest of the collection, is listed in the computerized card catalog.
It may not be removed from the special collections room, however.
</P>
<P>
   The rare German book is part of a 2,000-piece collection
accumulated by the late Marianne Sisk Stewart, a former L.A.
resident, cat lover and book collector.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, also a member of the city's cat club, left her personal
collection to the library in 1997. It was presented to the city in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The sizes of Stewart's collectible books are as varied as their
content, Goldsmith said, noting the smallest one is 1 and one-half
inches tall and the largest is 24 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything else like it,'' Patricia Anne Kovacs,
a member of the Jewel City Cat Club said of Glendale's prized
collection.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old Los Angeles resident said she's one of the
younger cat club members. Glendale's sea of cat materials could
answer virtually any question about felines, she said. Not to
mention, it provides quite a history of breeding and genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a chair with Tinker, one of her four cats, Kovacs said
the group today focuses on raising money for small organizations
that support spaying and neutering pets. She is one of about 20
members in the club who meet once every two months.
</P>
<P>
   The cat enthusiast has read books from the Glendale collection
over the years, she said, adding it is thrilling to know she's part
of a club that made the Billigs' treasures available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   People use the collection as a reference source to answer a cat
question or just to find rare literature on cats, both alley and
domestic, Goldsmith said. Sometimes people pop in on a Saturday
with stumpers like, ``How many bones are in a cat's tail?'' A quick
check of any of the anatomy books leads to the answer: 22.
</P>
<P>
   Cats, much like the diverse collection, are all different from
one another in some way, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what you're getting when you get a cat. But
you're going to like it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
