<SLUG> BC-FARM-EQUIP-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER IS SEEN OF TWO MAKERS OF FARM GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Case Corp. and New Holland N.V., two of the
world's largest makers of farm and construction equipment, are
expected to announce plans to merge on Monday, people who have been
briefed on the talks said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   According to those close to the negotiations, Fiat S.p.A. in
Italy, which owns 71 percent of New Holland, a Dutch company based
in London, would pay about $55 a share in cash for Case, an
estimated $4 billion, and merge it with New Holland. Fiat would
become the majority shareholder in the new company, which is
expected to be renamed.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would create a company with more than $12 billion in
revenue, mostly in the United States and Europe, and forge a much
stronger competitor to Deere &AMP; Co., the world's largest maker of
farm equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes at a tough time for companies involved in the
agriculture sector, which has been beset by low commodity prices
and weaker demand for American crops and farm equipment worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Case, based in Racine, Wis., has seen a sharp drop in profit
over the last few quarters despite strong demand for its
construction equipment. The new company would be based in Racine
and be headed by Jean-Pierre Rosso, the chief executive at Case,
people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that Case and New Holland were in talks came last
week when shares of Case and New Holland climbed. A spokesman at
Case refused comment on Sunday; officials at New Holland could not
be reached.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, Case, which was spun off from Tenneco
Inc. in 1994, would be part of a company that is almost as big as
Deere, which is based in Moline, Ill., and had sales of about $13
billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Case had sales of about $6.1 billion and earnings after
taxes of $160 million, down from $403 million in 1997. New Holland
had sales of $5.7 billion and earnings after taxes of $298 million
in 1998, down from $477 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, shares of Case rose $2, to $44.8125, on the New York
Stock Exchange; shares of New Holland fell 43.75 cents, to
$17.5625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
