<SLUG> BC-AIDS-ACTIVIST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS ACTIVIST GOES FROM VERBAL BOMB-THROWER TO QUIETER PERSUADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He was a verbal ``bomb-thrower'' with ACT-UP, an AIDS
activist whose tools of the trade were dramatic civil disobedience
and protest.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Steve Johnson has been wearing a suit and tie, meeting
with bureaucrats and elected officials to affect change through
more traditional means _ lobbying in the marble halls of Olympia,
Wash., and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of Johnson, 35, who resigned Friday after
three-and-a-half years as director of policy for the Northwest AIDS
Foundation, in many ways mirrors how AIDS as a social and political
issue has changed in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on fire back then,'' Johnson said of his ACT-UP days.
``We could turn out hundreds of people at demonstrations at a
moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early '90s, members of ACT-UP were the
unpredictable guerrilla fighters in the war against AIDS. The
Northwest AIDS Foundation was often treated by Johnson and others
in ACT-UP as an adversary, a stodgy consensus-oriented organization
that needed constant prodding.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and other activists would often target individuals,
using publicity as a weapon to get what they wanted. When property
owners fought a plan for an assisted living residence for people
with AIDS, the activists showed up at a social event, screaming
epithets and eventually embarrassing them into backing down.
</P>
<P>
   Street demonstrations, disruption of meetings and a very
un-Northwest style of angry public speaking were the order of the
day. Even health officials, doctors, scientists and others who were
also fighting AIDS became targets if they failed to adhere to the
activists' manifesto.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have any regrets, it would be that I was too focused on
the issue at the time to be able to step back and realize that good
people can come to different conclusions,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was basically a bomb thrower,'' said Robert Rohan, a
Seattle attorney and one of the founders of the AIDS Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Rohan said he opposed Johnson joining the foundation years ago
because he thought Johnson would, like some activists, simply
continue to throw verbal bombs and make a scene. Not that dramatic
activism doesn't have its place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what they did was focus attention on what was needed
for people with AIDS,'' Rohan said. ``What Steve and the others did
often had a positive effect ... I just didn't think he would adjust
to working on the inside after attacking from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Stone, executive director of the AIDS Foundation, said
Johnson has done more than adjust. Stone credits Johnson with
helping energize the organization, move it in new directions and
effectively changing his tactics to accomplish the same goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all had to learn how to operate differently as well,''
Stone said. New HIV drug therapies that have extended the lives of
people, along with the changing demographics of AIDS (more women,
minorities and young people), have altered the political and social
nature of AIDS, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the promising new therapies, Stone said, there is
still no cure or vaccine. People are still getting infected, he
said, and still having problems with access to health care,
discrimination and privacy concerns
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of work still to be done,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agreed, noting he's already lined up work with the San
Francisco AIDS Foundation doing lobbying in Sacramento on some of
the same issues he's worked on in Seattle _ assuring privacy in
tracking HIV cases and advocating for hypodermic needle exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   But he may move away from AIDS advocacy, he said. After a decade
of AIDS activism, Johnson wants to focus more on his personal life.
He's leaving Seattle because his partner recently left the
University of Washington radiology department to take a job in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson may not remain with AIDS issues forever, but he'll
likely remain an activist of sorts. His activism appears to be
ingrained, first appearing when he was in elementary school in
Lewiston, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``At school, I started a petition drive against chicken fried
steak,'' he laughed. ``The cooks were just devastated because I got
hundreds of signatures. I felt terrible that I had hurt their
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of principle, Johnson also once broke somebody's
arm. While studying at the University of Oregon, someone wrote an
anonymous letter to his mother, claiming he had had sex with
Johnson and infected him with HIV. His mother hadn't known he was
gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt her terribly,'' Johnson said. He discovered that the
letter-writer was a jealous acquaintance of a friend, went over to
his house and beat him up. ``I broke his arm .. I couldn't believe
it. I'd never done anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he has always preferred the persuasive power of
words to physical force. He has come to prefer behind-the-scenes
discussions to making a scene diatribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can come to a solution most of the time if people are
willing to talk to each other,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
