<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS NOW FIND HIM CHARISMATIC CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ There have been 24 Triple Crown bids, 11 of which
have been successful, most recently by Affirmed in 1978. However,
Charismatic has taken a rougher road to the threshold of greatness
than his elite predecessors, including running in claiming races.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic went off 31-1 when he won the Derby May 1, and he
was 8-1 when he took Saturday's Preakness, and the reason was that
many of the bettors, plus many of the selectors, could not get past
the fact that Charismatic twice ran for a $62,500 claiming tag.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, trainer D. Wayne Lukas warned everybody not to
make that mistake, but most did, anyway. ``I know the story line of
the week, all week, is that this horse is a claimer who got lucky
in the Derby,'' admonished Lukas. ``Don't discredit the horse. If
you have to blame somebody, blame me. Don't discredit the horse
because I was foolish enough to run him in claimers.'' Those who
listened to Lukas were rewarded with an $18.80 win mutuel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Charismatic heads for the Belmont June 5, and this time he
will be the favorite. The Belmont is run at a mile and one-half,
too far for all but the sturdiest thoroughbreds, and if there's one
thing Charismatic is, it's sturdy. He's run four races in six weeks
_ Santa Anita Derby (fourth), Lexington Stakes at Keeneland
(first), Kentucky Derby, and Preakness _ and hasn't missed an oat.
``Remember,'' said Lukas, ``I said he was fat. I didn't say he was
slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fact that he took the Preakness with relative ease by
coming around the field, which was totally against the
speed-favoring bias of the Pimlico strip, Charismatic looks strong
for the Belmont because, before he even ran in the Derby, Lukas was
touting him as a Belmont horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the Lewises (owners Bob and Beverly), in April that he
was a Belmont horse,'' said Lukas. ``We'll find out if I was right.
The Belmont is always a concern, we'll watch him, and we'll make
some adjustments. We've got three weeks between races this time,
and that's huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic looks as if he hasn't even run. What I like about
him is that he's developing that devastating move. He's got that
acceleration. He showed a greater turn of foot in the Preakness
than he had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic doesn't have eye-catching speed, but he can run all
day, and that's what wins the Belmont. The bluebloods might have to
move over to make room for a claimer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, the 2-1 Preakness favorite, chased Charismatic home
with a nice rally, but could do no better than second. After the
race, his trainer, Elliott Walden, speculated that he may hold
Menifee out of the Belmont. But Sunday Walden put Menifee back on
the Belmont bandwagon. ``If he's all right, we'll go,'' said
Walden. ``I'll take Menifee back to Churchill Downs for a couple of
weeks, then bring him to Belmont in time to have one work over the
track. I think he'll really like those big turns. He's a big horse.
Wayne's horse is in a zone now. I can't feel bad standing here with
the second-best 3-year-old in the country. If I had to get beat, I
would rather have it be the Derby winner (Menifee was also second
in the Derby). It's beginning to look like it's between the two
horses. I really haven't seen another one that's with them right
now.'' . . . Both Excellent Meeting, the filly who was eased, and
Torrid Sand, who was 11th, suffered a displaced palates. ``We
scoped her and she's OK,'' said Bob Baffert, who trains Excellent
Meeting. ``We think she displaced her palate and lost her air. It
may have happened when Kent (Desormeaux) had to check real hard as
she went under the wire the first time. She seemed to be in
distress later, so he pulled her up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is those claiming affairs, but Charismatic certainly
doesn't frighten anyone. The Derby and Preakness both had full
fields, before scratches, and the Belmont, which allows 16
starters, might draw a full gate as well. In addition to
Charismatic, the connections of Menifee, Badge (third in the
Preakness), Stephen Got Even (fourth), Patience Game (fifth),
Adonis (sixth), and Kimberlite Pipe (eighth), are all interested in
contesting the third jewel of the Triple Crown. Lukas will not run
Cat Thief, who faded to seventh after taking the lead, and will
point him, instead, toward either the Jim Dandy at Saratoga in
August or the Swaps at Hollywood Park in July . . . Lee Ferrell,
22, of Bel Air, Md., the man who went on the track and interfered
with the running of the seventh race on the Preakness card, was
being held Sunday at Baltimore's central booking facility on a
first-degree assault charge. Ferrell initially was taken to Sinai
Hospital for a psychiatric review, but was released Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
