<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION MUST PROVE METTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A year ago, the Revolution had earned 10
points in eight games and had just embarked on their annual
nine-game losing streak. After a 2-0 loss at Columbus Saturday
night, the Revolution have 7 points in eight games and have not won
a match in regulation time since April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The team has enough elements to likely prevent such a collapse
again, starting with player-coach Walter Zenga, but this is a
crucial time as the Revolution prepare for visits to Los Angeles
Sunday and the MetroStars May 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not a discouraged team in that locker room,''
Revolution investor Jonathan Kraft said after the game at the new
Crew Stadium. ``They are hungry to get out and play again. When we
get our best 11 out there we will be able to compete with any team
in the league. We need to get everyone full speed and full
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga and assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi have cast the
Revolution as a pragmatic, resourceful team. So far, they have
avoided the lopsided losses that exacerbated problems and led to
crises in confidence. But the Revolution have yet to prove they can
overcome what last year became a combination of an inferiority
complex and unrealistic self-assessment.
</P>
<P>
   All sorts of explanations were offered last year about how the
Revolution were not as bad as their record. Now, the only excuse
offered is injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has been preaching patience, since the objective is to
finish the regular season in the top four in the Eastern
Conference, a goal which likely can be attained simply by remaining
organized and maintaining team morale. It also helps greatly to
have Zenga as goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution soon are going to have to demonstrate either
a more effective attack or a more ruthless defense. They seemed
either naive or unmotivated in surrendering an early goal to the
Crew's Jeff Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   After that, a combination of misfortune and resourceful play by
Columbus extended the Revolution scoreless streak to 250 minutes.
Their last goal was on a Joe-Max Moore free kick in a 2-1 loss to
Colorado May 1, and the Revolution have not scored in the run of
play since a 3-2 victory at D.C. United April 24.
</P>
<P>
   John Harkes returned from a sprained right knee ligament for the
final 15 minutes against Columbus, his first Revolution appearance.
Mike Burns (hamstring) and Richard Goulooze (calf) should also
return soon. But the Revolution will have to develop either better
cameraderie or better chemistry when they do.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams also have struggled with injuries. Columbus was
missing Brian McBride (broken cheekbone), but the Crew's attack was
dynamic. Neither Trinidadian defender Ansil Elcock nor Polish
midfielder Robert Warzycha started, but Columbus began the match
with aggressiveness and poise, dictating terms.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first Revolution loss of the season by more than a
goal. How the team responds this week could go far in determining
its fate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
