<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL PAIN, NO GAIN FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It's too late for Red Sox reliever Kip Gross, who had
it made in Japan, to reconsider his decision to sample life again
on this side of the international date line, where he has now come
undone not only in the US but Canada, too.
</P>
<P>
   And after giving up a walkoff, three-run home run to Toronto's
Carlos Delgado in the ninth inning of the Blue Jays' 9-6 win Sunday
over the Red Sox, Gross's next destination is an open question. It
may not be Boston, especially with the Sox in need of another
infielder after third baseman John Valentin couldn't play any
longer on a sore left knee, which he had suffered in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, who came out in the fifth inning of a game in which
the Sox were unable to hold leads of 4-1 and 6-4, said he will not
play Monday night and expects to undergo a magnetic resonance
imaging when the club returns home to play the New York Yankees
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin said he has had tendinitis in his knee periodically
dating back to last year, but had said little publicly about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For it to bother me as long as it has, I definitely need to
see if there's anything wrong,'' said Valentin, who was limping
badly after his third-inning double. ``Obviously, it affects your
play. The thing is, I've always played hurt. I don't let a little
pain take me out of a game. So obviously, it's bothering me a whole
bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin's replacement, Jeff Frye, had his own pain to deal with
after taking a fastball off the left elbow from reliever Billy Koch
with the bases loaded in the eighth inning, which accounted for the
sixth Sox run.
</P>
<P>
   Frye, the only backup infielder on Jimy Williams's roster, said
he intends to play Monday night, but the Sox are expected to call
Pawtucket for reinforcements. The Framingham Kid, Lou Merloni, is
most likely to be put on a plane to Toronto for Monday night's
series finale, and Gross qualifies as most expendable if a roster
spot is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hurting,'' said Frye, whose elbow was encased in an ice
pack almost as big as the one wrapped around his surgically
repaired left knee. ``But I'm not coming out unless I physically
can't play. At the time, all I had to do was run, so I figured
hopefully it would loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have anybody else who was really an infielder. I had
to stay in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, did Gross, after Williams had all but emptied
his bullpen with unhappy results, as both Rheal Cormier and Derek
Lowe blew save opportunities. Cormier, who replaced Pat Rapp with a
4-1 lead after the Sox starter walked Shawn Green to open the sixth
inning, gave up a double to Tony Fernandez, a sacrifice fly to
pinch hitter Pat Kelly, and a two-run home run to Jose Cruz Jr.
that tied the score at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jefferson's third home run, off lefty Paul Spoljaric,
restored the Sox lead to 5-4 in the seventh, before singles by
Scott Hatteberg and Darren Lewis and a walk to Jose Offerman
preceded Frye's painful RBI.
</P>
<P>
   While Cormier had been a model of consistency, Lowe has been
maddeningly erratic, and Sunday was no exception. He replaced lefty
Mark Guthrie in the eighth after Delgado hit a rocket off
Offerman's glove in short right field that was scored an error,
then changed to a single.
</P>
<P>
   Damage control? Hardly. Lowe walked Fernandez on four pitches,
and after Hatteberg made an acrobatic catch of Kelly's bunt attempt
behind the plate, he issued another pass to Cruz that loaded the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Kevin Witt followed with a turf special, which was
chopped in front of the plate and took an exaggerated bounce past
first baseman Mike Stanley, both runners scoring. Lowe struck out
the next two batters, but having pitched in all three games this
weekend, and throwing 24 pitches Sunday, he was not an option to
pitch the ninth, in Williams's view.
</P>
<P>
   That left Gross, whose presence this spring has come to signal a
Sox loss. Only once in his 11 appearances have the Red Sox won, as
he has been used mostly in a mopup role. On the rare occasion he
has been asked to step out of that role, disaster has struck, most
notably in Oakland, when he made an emergency start and gave up a
first-inning grand slam to Matt Stairs, then three days later gave
up another bomb to Stairs, this one a game-tying home run in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Gross held form Sunday. He walked Alex Gonzalez, threw a wild
pitch, then gave up a hard single to Green, Gonzalez holding at
third. Delgado swung at the first pitch and drove a changeup into
the second deck, just below the Hard Rock Cafe, and just more hard
times for Gross.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like to see what's happened twice now,'' Gross said.
``You definitely want better results. That (expletive). That's
plain ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clubhouse that had begun the day sharing first place with
the Yankees but now had dropped a game behind, there would be no
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to lose a game like this,'' Valentin said. ``We had
an opportunity to win, and let them back in. That's a game we
should have won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
