<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TVG NETWORK TO MAKE DEBUT JULY 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seldom do the words ``horse racing'' and ``cutting
edge'' appear in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the sport of horse racing is anything but cutting
edge.
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change. On July 1, through a multimillion-dollar
partnership formed by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., racetracks
around the country and cable television providers will begin
bringing the races and parimutual wagering into living rooms
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give horse racing a face lift,'' said Tony
Allevato, 33-year-old executive producer at the Television Games
Network, known as TVG. ``Horse racing is going to be ahead of
everybody else for the first time ever.''
</P>
<P>
   TVG viewers will be able to set up an account with the network
and place bets on races through their remote control, via telephone
or through the Internet. TVG executives hope that their system will
pump millions (perhaps billions) of dollars into the sport,
increasing handles and purses while attracting a new generation of
fans.
</P>
<P>
   There are some caveats: Only eight states currently allow
at-home gambling; and there is a bill before the U.S. Senate that
would outlaw Internet gambling altogether. Mark Wilson, TVG's
president has said he hopes those glitches will be corrected soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is walk a tightrope here and grow new
fans and be an entertainment program, not just a bunch of racing
signals crammed together,'' Wilson told Backstretch Magazine. ``I
want to bring new people into this sport.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Allevato has developed a 15-minute pilot for TVG
that is much like ESPN's SportsCenter but focuses exclusively on
racing. When launched in July, the channel will provide 12 hours of
live racing and 12 hours of replays and other programming devoted
solely to horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually TVG will offer a full 24 hours of live horse racing
from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   During any given hour of live airtime, TVG will air four races.
An anchor and an analyst will work the studio providing information
that appeals to the expert and novice alike, Allevato said.
Reporters in the field will interact with the anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Take note: Allevato promises those television personalities
won't be a couple of crusty old track touts reading lines from the
Daily Racing Form. Instead, TVG is in the process of hiring young,
good-looking upstarts who have some working knowledge of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want fresh, young faces,'' Allevato said. ``If you just
show a couple of guys reading out of the Daily Racing Form, that's
not going to get new fans. People are just going to get bored.''
</P>
<P>
   The arcane language of racing will also be eliminated or at
least translated for the casual fan, Allevato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't know what we mean when we talk about a
horse's sire and dam,'' Allevato said. ``Instead we're going to
talk about a horse's parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Other innovations will include a computerized race-tracker on
the television screen's upper right-hand corner. The tracker will
show where the pack of horses is during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one feedback that we're going to get is that the shows are
too light and too full of fluff,'' Allevato said. ``But if we can
pull this off and do it right, it will be the biggest thing to hit
racing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 0011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
