</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-FENWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS, ZIMMER FANS OF FENWAY PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
 PARK-CLEMENS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESSIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don Zimmer has richer memories of Fenway Park than
Roger Clemens, but the former Red Sox manager and the former Boston
ace both were delighted to learn that the prosposal for a new
Fenway will resemble the old park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fenway is like I am,'' said Zimmer, the Yankees' interim
manager. ``It's old. It's been one of my favorite places in the
world. But I think they need a new ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who was traded to the Yankees from Toronto in the
spring, didn't even know about the proposal until told by a
reporter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' he said. ``Particularly if they get a
new park and try to keep it close (in structure) to the old one.
Fenway Park is one of the last of its kind, especially for guys of
my generation. There are only a couple places left: Detroit, Yankee
Stadium, and obviously Fenway. I still have some dirt off the mound
at Fenway at my home in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, 68, spent seven seasons at Fenway Park, doing two stints
as coach (1974-76, 1992) and four years as manager (1976-80).
During his tenure he developed strong opinions of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inviting,'' said Zimmer. ``The Wall there has helped some
guys but it hurt a lot of others. Guys who were straightaway
hitters might have tried to become pull hitters. The Green Monster
has probably helped lefthanded hitters more than righthanders just
by them being able to hit the opposite way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did Fred Lynn hit in Boston? Something high. What did he
hit in California? He could get hits going the opposite way in
Fenway. They'd be outs in most ballparks. I always thought Jim Rice
was something special. With his strength, it would have been
awfully easy for him to go there and say I'm a pull hitter. He
didn't and it probably helped him to stick as a real good hitter.
Of course, with his strength, he usually didn't need The Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens says it would be difficult to pinpoint his best day at
Fenway. His 20-strikeout game against Seattle in 1986 ranks near
the top. He won three of his five Cy Young Awards while pitching
for Boston. He has posted a 96-55 record in 192 starts at Fenway, a
park many pitchers consider a graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt that way,'' said Clemens. ``I've always pitched
inside pretty much. Some guys are afraid the hitter will pull the
ball. I've always tried to feature the ball there. The Wall has
taken away home runs but it's also given some. Fenway is a
challenge. But there are others today. Cleveland is smaller. The
ball carries at Baltimore. It's a hitters park. What (Fenway) takes
away in left field it gives a little bit to lefthanders in right
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer said a lot of hurlers never learned the secret of
pitching in Fenway. Conversely, if a lefthanded hitter learned how
to work The Wall, he could prosper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Boston with Butch Hobson in 1992,'' said Zimmer.
``That was Mo Vaughn's first year. How many times did you think Mo
Vaughn hit the ball on The Wall or in the net from center field to
the left-field line. He did it a lot because he used the whole
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl Yastrzemski? In 1967-68 he was a pull hitter. But Yaz
learned how to put the ball in the net and he was a solid hitter
the rest of his career. I just got a feeling that lefthanders had
just as much success as anybody just taking advantage of The Wall.
Bernie Carbo was built that way from Day One. He had great
inside-outside power.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens and Zimmer will be in Fenway this week, starting a
three-game series with the Red Sox Tuesday. Clemens, who has been
on the disabled list with a strained left hamstring but will come
off it this week, may make his Yankee debut at Fenway Park
Thursday. A final decision will come after he throws Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be healthy,'' said Clemens. ``That's my main
priority right now. Everything else takes a back seat to that. We
have bigger goals around here. I'm not thinking about the short
range. You think about getting yourself in position in August,
finishing off in September, and get ready for a playoff around
here. That's what this situation is about. Here, they don't think
of anything else. They don't care about who wins or who gets wins.
As long as we win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
