<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of
<TEXT>
<P>
   the NYTimes News Service for Monday, May 17. If you have any
questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602) 444-8286.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SLEEPWALK-MURDER (Phoenix) _ After stabbing his wife 44 times in
their home in 1996, court records show, a Phoenix man put on
gloves, dragged her body to their pool, rolled her in and held her
head under. He then sealed a blood-splattered face guard, clothes
and the knife in a Tupperware container, stuffed it in a garbage
bag and hid it in the back of his Volvo. But the man says he cannot
remember any of it. He claims he wasn't even awake. When his trial
starts Wednesday in Maricopa County Superior Court, he will argue
that he is innocent of murder _ not because he didn't stab his
wife, but because the entire incident occurred while he was
sleepwalking. By VICTORIA HARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
USSARIZONA (Phoenix) _ When the USS Arizona sank in 1941 during the
attack on Pearl Harbor, a treasured sculpture of a frontier-era
miner was presumed lost. A Sun City West grandmother found it.
Lorraine Marks-Haislip, a 75-year-old widow of a &UR; former crew &UR; member
of theill-fated warship, learned through tireless research that the
sculpture and other long-sought-after artifacts were packed away
andforgotten in a U.S. Navy warehouse. In the two years since the
amateur historian made the discovery, the Arizona State Capitol
Museum has been trying to cut through red tape and have the 40-inch
bronze miner returned to Arizona. By DAVID PARRISH. Story will move
in the ``A'' category.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
