<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NELSON-LEDE-HNS &LR;      05-17 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ The GTE Byron Nelson Classic wasn't so much a golf
tournament as it was Exhibit A that the young have not yet
inherited the sport. At least not totally.
<TEXT>
<P>
   How else to explain Loren Roberts _ who has seen more years than
brat-packers Tiger Woods and Sergio Garcia combined _ winning the
event named for an 87-year-old legend and doing so with his
83-year-old father watching him play for the first time in nearly a
year?
</P>
<P>
   All while the sport mourns the loss of 97-year-old Gene Sarazen,
who died Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts hugged his father on the 18th green after claiming a
sudden-death victory for the aged, nipping Steve Pate at the
Tournament Players Club at Las Colinas. Then Roberts summed up the
events of the week perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger and Sergio and David Duval, that's the future of golf
right there,'' Roberts said. ``Obviously, we have Mr. Nelson, Gene
Sarazen _ that's the greatness of the past of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of fit somewhere in the rest of the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways. Roberts, 43, has been a PGA Tour player for
nearly two decades now, but it's only in midlife that he has found
a way to win. He collected the sixth victory of his career Sunday
by overcoming a double bogey on the 14th hole, getting into a
playoff against Pate, then making a wonderful sand save on the
first extra hole while Pate could not do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts never has been flashy. But he has become known as one of
the best putters on the planet, and for this week he was better
than anybody, period. He shot a 2-under-par 68 Sunday for a
tournament-record total of 262, 18 under par. It was only good
enough to get him in a playoff with Pate, who fired off a brilliant
66 Sunday to force the tie after 72 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, perhaps doing his best Loren-ce of Arabia
impersonation, threw his 45-foot bunker shot on the first playoff
hole (No. 18) to within two feet for a par. When Pate couldn't get
up and down on a longer shot from the sand, Roberts had the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The playoff hole started with Roberts driving into the right
rough. With a tough left-to-right wind whipping, Roberts figured he
was at a disadvantage after Pate's drive found the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught a reasonable lie in the right rough and hit a 5-wood
out of it,'' Roberts said. ``The one thing I didn't want to do was
hit it in the right bunker because that's almost an impossible
up-and-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little lucky in the playoff because I was very
surprised that Steve put his second shot over there.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Pate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aiming 20 feet right of the pin, thought it was 40 feet
right, and it ended up 60 feet right,'' Pate said. ``You can't feel
the wind and how strong it is when you're down there in the
fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that shot, Pate really couldn't fault himself for his
play down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything stupid,'' he said. ``I didn't really bail
out on anything. The only thing is the wind grabbed that last
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate's sand shot stopped 15 feet shy of the hole, and he missed
the putt, handing the title to Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' father was never better than an 18-handicap, lefthanded
hacker. But Hugh Roberts was the man responsible for acquainting
his son with the game of golf more than 30 years ago, which made it
special that the father was present as the son proved he still has
plenty of golf left in him at an age when he was beginning to doubt
his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how excited and happy I am about winning this
tournament,'' Roberts said. ``Two months ago, I was sitting around,
43 years old and wondering if maybe I was too old to do this
anymore. I can't tell you how good it feels to get back in the
winner's circle. I wasn't quite to the point where it was time to
quit. But I'd missed a bunch of cuts and played miserably at
Augusta (in the Masters). I was starting to think, `Gosh, have I
still got it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's been a pretty big emotional swing over the last couple
of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said a talk with his former coach before the Shell
Houston Open two weeks ago was a big reason he has been able to
come back strong after missing three cuts in a row in March and
early April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Houston, I talked to my old coach, Jim Swagerty, who I
hadn't worked with in years,'' Roberts said. ``I talked to him on
the telephone, and he said, `So I see you're swinging the club now
and not turning on it.' I heard that and started concentrating on
making a full turn on the ball and keeping the club in front of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like a light bulb went on, Roberts said, as he finished
tied for fifth at The Woodlands. And that bulb was shining brightly
Sunday, when Pate and Roberts were playing head-to-head virtually
all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw some good punches back and forth the whole day, I
thought,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' best comeback of the day didn't come in response to
anything Pate did but rather offset his only poor swing of the
final two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts came over a 5-iron on the par-4 14th and hit the lake
fronting the green. He wound up making a double bogey, which put
him behind by a shot, the first time he trailed all day.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts needed something to revitalize himself. So he socked a
3-iron from 190 yards and watched it trickle just three feet behind
the cup. That birdie on 15 tied the match, and the pair parred
their way into the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed that to really kind of get back into the
tournament,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pate: ``That was a pretty impressive comeback. He had a
hard shot on 14, especially after seeing me go over the green. And
then to come back like that after making double, that was
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the fact that Roberts' father was able to attend the
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 83 years old, and he's had a tough time taking care of my
mother,'' Roberts said. ``She was diagnosed with Alzheimer's
disease 2{ years ago, and it's been tough on him taking care of
her. This is the first time since the (U.S.) Open last year at
Olympic Club that he's been able to come out to a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him that I was thrilled to have him here and that
I love him. And I know Mom's watching at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a great golf supporter of me, and he loves to come
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
