r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-MURDRE-AZR &LR;      05-17 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-MURDRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING TO BE MURDER DEFENSE: HUSBAND'S CLAIM HAS EXPERT
SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ From the facts alone, it would seem that Scott Falater
was a very deliberate, very efficient murderer.
</P>
<P>
   After stabbing his wife, Yarmila, 44 times in their Phoenix home
in 1996, court records show, Falater put on gloves, dragged her
body to their pool, rolled her in and held her head under.
</P>
<P>
   He then sealed a blood-splattered face guard, clothes and the
knife in a Tupperware container, stuffed it in a garbage bag and
hid it in the back of his Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   But Falater _ an engineer, inventor, loving father and leader in
his church _ said he cannot remember any of it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he claims, he wasn't even awake.
</P>
<P>
   When his trial starts Wednesday, May 19, in Maricopa County
Superior Court, Falater will argue that he is innocent of murder.
Not because he didn't stab his wife, but because the entire
incident occurred while he was sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy County Attorney Juan Martinez intends to prove Falater
knew exactly what he was doing in the early hours of Jan. 16, 1996.
He is seeking the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's attorney, Michael Kimerer, is bringing in three
experts to testify that his client's claim is not only possible,
but likely.
</P>
<P>
   They are the same trio that helped acquit Canadian Kenneth
Parks, who testified he was sleepwalking when he stabbed his
mother-in-law to death in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep tests conducted on Falater show he fits the profile of a
sleepwalker, Kimerer said. He also has a history of sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his sister, Laura Healy, will testify that he once
threw her across a room when she interrupted him during a
sleepwalking episode. Several relatives also are known sleepwalkers
and talkers, Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Falater's cellmates are expected to take the stand to say
he walks and talks in his sleep in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Stress and sleep deprivation can bring on episodes of
sleepwalking, said Roger Broughten, a sleep-disorders expert who
will also testify.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the murder, Falater was under stress from his job
as a products manager for Motorola's semiconductor unit, court
records say. He was told he might have to lay off as many as 20
people in the unit.
</P>
<P>
   To add to his stress, Falater was bothered by a malfunctioning
pool pump; on the night of the murder, he and Yarmila were awakened
by noise and suspected an intruder, court records say.
</P>
<P>
   According to the records, when police arrived, they found a
flashlight turned on near the pump and some of its wires were cut.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer said one theory is that Falater walked in his sleep to
the pool pump, picked up the knife and was interrupted by Yarmila,
Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   His client is ``devastated'' by the death of his wife, Kimerer
said. She was Falater's high school sweetheart and the mother of
his two children.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Falaters seemed to have an ideal family life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a totally loving couple,'' Kimerer said. ``He was
liked by his family, friends and everyone who knew him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had a history of violence or temper. He's a very
bright man who is very involved in the Mormon Church. He's just not
the type of person you'd think would commit a violent crime like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater converted to Mormonism after the two married, and
Yarmila joined the church a bit later. Falater traveled extensively
in his job, while Yarmila, an artist, taught church women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   Falater moved up from a counselor in one church to a member of
the high council over a stake of eight churches. He was a doting
father, and Yarmila was a Cub Scout den mother. Both of their
children are honor students.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Martinez, however, is expected to argue that all was
not as it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Yarmila had complained to friends over the years that Scott
wanted her to participate more in the church, court records show.
She resisted, and at one point disliked the church's influence so
much that she would leave the house when Scott's Mormon friends
came over.
</P>
<P>
   He also pressured her to have more children, a friend testified
in a court interview. Yarmila again resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Then when the church changed boundaries a few years ago, she was
cut off from old friends. She became depressed, court records said.
</P>
<P>
   Overweight and often unkempt, Yarmila did not seem to care about
her appearance, one friend testified. Then, shortly before her
death, she lost about 40 pounds, started riding her bicycle and
paying more attention to her hair and clothes, the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said in a court hearing that one of the Falaters sought
an examination for a venereal disease.
</P>
<P>
   And a psychologist who interviewed Falater after the murder
noted that Scott believed his wife had committed the
``unforgiveable sin'' and was not ``growing with him,'' Martinez
said at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Violence during sleep is extremely rare, most experts agree. But
there are documented cases of people who have engaged in elaborate
behavior while in a sleeplike state.
</P>
<P>
   There are examples of people who have lashed out at someone or
thought they were being attacked while asleep, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   There are documented cases of sleepers who have walked out of
upper-story windows or through plate-glass doors and seriously
injured themselves. Some have thrown their children out of windows
and driven cars and killed pedestrians or people in other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But only a few have mounted successful sleepwalking defenses for
murder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, an Ohio man who said he'd been sleepwalking for years
was found innocent of beating and stabbing a man and trying to
choke the man's mother after testifying he had no memory of the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Canadian Supreme Court upheld the acquittal of
Parks, who said he was sleepwalking when he drove 14 miles, stabbed
his mother-in-law to death and seriously injured his father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly publicized case in Arizona in the early 1980s,
attorneys for Steven Steinberg called psychiatrists to testify that
he may have been sleepwalking or in a ``dissociative mental state''
when he stabbed his wife 26 times.
</P>
<P>
   After jurors heard lengthy testimony that his wife, Elana,
nagged Steinberg and drove him mad by spending money faster than he
made it, Steinberg was found innocent on the grounds he was
temporarily insane when he killed her.
</P>
<P>
   If acquitted, is there a chance Falater could kill again if he
sleepwalks?
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer said that would be extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution though, Falater would likely take a drug that
prevents sleepwalking, Kimerer said. &QL; 
Victoria Harker can be reached at (602) 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
