<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-AUCTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDDING WAS WORTH CHECKING OUT AT LIBRARY FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK HARBOR, Wash. _ Lest anyone think the Friends of Oak Harbor
Library are dowdy, let it be known they served wine punch at their
Sunday afternoon celebrity book sale down at the Elks' Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   The spiked punch may have been responsible for the heated
bidding war over the first edition of J.A. Jance's 1999 novel
``Breach of Duty,'' between bidder No. 39 _ Jenny Brown _ and
Bidder No. 24, whose name will be lost to the ages, much like his
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding started at $15. It got tense in a hurry, observed in
silence by bidders who dropped out and by Clyde the nine-point elk,
whose stuffed head decorates the lodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen, $15, do I have $17.50, $17.50, yes, I have $17.50, do
I have $20, $20, yes I have $20,'' auctioneer Pat Gregory intoned,
goading four bidders to join the fray. ``It's only money _ and we
take credit cards so it's not really money at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the bids topped $35, only two remained.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, dressed in a black blouse and khaki pants, huddled over
her deviled eggs. She waved her auction paddle by raising her arm,
then extending it.
</P>
<P>
   Her competition was No. 24, a white-haired older man in sport
shirt and expandable pants. He had cookies in front of him,and held
his paddle to his chest, tipping it forward to signal his bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five, do I have $35? $35, do I have $37.50, $37.50?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown looked determined and kept raising her arm. Up and out. Up
and out. Mr. 24 scratched the table between his bids. Clyde the
nine-point elk seemed uninterested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-five, $45, do I've have $45, $47.50, do I have $47.50,
come on you're doing this for the library.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty? Do I have $50?'' Tip of the paddle. ``Fifty-two fifty,
can I get $52.50?'' Up and out.
</P>
<P>
   And Mr. 24 blinked.
</P>
<P>
   The Jance book went to Brown, an Oak Harbor resident who said
``I'm just a big Jance fan. I've read all the books, but I haven't
read this one, and so that's a plus, and the autograph is a
bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   The bidders _ along with about 40 other people _ were there to
bid on popular novels that had been autographed by their authors as
a way to raise money for the Friends of the Oak Harbor Library.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a bolder, better fund-raiser than the
group's annual used book sale, which nets about $2,000 each year,
though total proceeds had not been counted last night.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was louder than the used book sale.
</P>
<P>
   Various versions of the standoff between Brown and Mr. 24, with
Gregory egging them on, happened Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The group sent about 500 queries to authors its members selected
as worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Letters went to literary heavyweights such as John Updike and
Philip Roth, and more popular novelists, like Stephen Coontz and
O.J. Simpson attorney Robert Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   The library received 179 autographed books back in return. Tony
Hillerman sent three. George and Barbara Bush autographed a Random
House pocket dictionary. Lord knows why.
</P>
<P>
   Children's writer Beverly Cleary sent a first edition of her
1987 book ``The Growing Up Feet,'' and the local Payless Shoes
store threw in a package of children's socks.
</P>
<P>
   Win the bidding on Earl Emerson's 1998 ``Catfish Cafe'' and get
a harmonica from the Whidbey Music Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was an eclectic mix, as eclectic as some of the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   A first edition of John LeCarre's 1996 ``The Tailor of Panama''
sold for $62. A deluxe, leather-bound first edition of Roth's
``Operation Shylock'' went for $42.50. Mario Cuomo's 1995 book
``Reason to Believe,'' sold for $30, the result of Gregory's
urging.
</P>
<P>
   The former New York governor and perennial speculative
presidential candidate's book was hailed as almost unreadable by
critics.
</P>
<P>
   But it had a nice inscription, and perhaps that's what sold it
to the bidder: ``Any friend of a library is a friend of mine. In
Friendship, Mario Cuomo, 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-autographed dictionary? It was the top seller at $250.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
