<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST OF TRADING A-ROD MORE THAN M'S CAN AFFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the context of the Mariners' season-long pitching
travails, Sunday's game stood out like Gandhi at a soccer riot.
</P>
<P>
   Unleashing his repertoire of marshmallows and sofa pillows,
Jamie Moyer threw eight shutout innings. Along with the offense's
nine timely hits, only one of which was a home run, the Mariners
had a 5-1 win, in a tidy 2 hours, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not a hint of hysteria anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As you can imagine, it was no fun at all.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up 23 runs on 36 hits in the first two games of
this weekend series against the profoundly nondescript Kansas City
Royals, the expectation Sunday was that the Mariners would lead yet
another half-dozen rookie pitchers to slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer spoiled the bloodletting. If the Mariners' team ERA is on
course to mark the worst pitching staff ever in baseball _ and it
is _ how does a well-pitched game fit in to this eye-popping
pursuit of history?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was no way to build the momentum to trade Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   That is the only solution for Mariner pitching right now, isn't
it?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Mariners manager Lou Piniella, ``I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Yankees were in a similar situation, do you think they
would trade Derek Jeter? If the Red Sox were in a similar
situation, do you think they would trade Nomar Garciaparra?''
</P>
<P>
   But as Piniella knew well before the rebuttal came, the Mariner
franchise isn't the Yankee franchise. It isn't the Red Sox
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will never be a top-tier club until they stop being
the Mariners. They will stay bound to mediocrity, new stadium or
not, as long as they fail to break the historic pattern of bailing
on their game-breaking talent.
</P>
<P>
   In surrendering stars, recall what the Mariners did in:
</P>
<P>
   -- 1993, trading shortstop Omar Vizquel to Cleveland for DH
Reggie Jefferson and shortstop Felix Fermin.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1995, trading first baseman Tino Martinez and relief pitcher
Jeff Nelson to the New York Yankees for pitcher Sterling Hitchcock
and third baseman Russ Davis.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1997, trading outfielder Jose Cruz Jr. to Toronto for relief
pitchers Mike Timlin and Paul Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1998, trading pitcher Randy Johnson to Houston for pitchers
Freddy Garcia and John Halama and second baseman Carlos Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   What remains of nearly half an all-star team are the three
Houston players and Davis. That's all. Oh, one other thing _ a
reputation as a baseball laughingstock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have taken it to another level if we had kept some of
the talent that's been in this clubhouse,'' Rodriguez said Sunday.
``Seems like everybody who's winning is doing it with players we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the same owner/management team is in place that made all
those deals, why in the world is there talk that the Mariners would
get value for Rodriguez?
</P>
<P>
   Not only is management insufficiently competent to get full
value, and ownership too shortsighted to protect its current
investment by increasing player payroll, few if any teams in
baseball would part with market value, given that A-Rod will be a
free agent after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Most every other team runs the risk that Houston did in
acquiring Johnson _ sacrificing young talent for short-term gain.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Rodriguez for 1{ seasons is better than half a season.
But after this year, the new team has to consider locking him up
for the $100 million-plus contract or deal him below market to one
who would.
</P>
<P>
   Plain and simple, the Mariners will get hosed in any trade of
A-Rod. Now, and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get Alex and Junior (Griffey) signed and build the
team around them,'' Piniella said with unusual emphasis. ``We have
other position players we can trade. Trading A-Rod is not the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the Seahawks trade their quarterback to get an offensive
lineman? Do the Sonics trade their good 7-foot-2 center because
they don't have guards?''
</P>
<P>
   While Piniella's rhetoric of comparisons sounds good, his
alternative doesn't hold out much hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to build a pitching staff for quite a few years, not
just one that's passing through,'' he said. ``At times, it will be
rough. We'll go through a few more (pitchers) before we're set. But
the strength of this organization is its young arms.''
</P>
<P>
   While that sounds swell, Piniella's optimism can be greeted only
with forehead-slapping skepticism by the longtime Mariners
follower, who has seen virtually no young pitcher develop and
flourish with the big club during Piniella's regime.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is a better choice than dealing Rodriguez. That
is a dead man's option taken too many times for a franchise now
entering its field of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership has little choice. Chris Larson, Howard Lincoln et al.
must do what most fans and others in baseball think is impossible _
make an all-out effort to sign Griffey and Rodriguez _ or do what I
suspect they planned to do for some time: Sell to an ownership who
can play in baseball's preposterous marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   And please don't buy the nonsense that such money isn't in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Rodriguez is a guaranteed loser. Any other alternative
at least comes without a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 0056EDT &QL; 
