<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SAMSONOV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMSONOV WAS FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The game was just a few minutes old when Sergei
Samsonov made a nifty move to set up a fine Bruins scoring bid by
Mattias Timander.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek stopped that one.
</P>
<P>
   But he wouldn't hold off Samsonov and his high-flying new
linemates _ Tim Taylor and Rob DiMaio _ for long.
</P>
<P>
   Nine minutes into the game Taylor passed to Samsonov, who
carried into the Sabre end and this time popped the puck back to
Don Sweeney. Sweeney beat Hasek for the first of four straight
goals that put the Bruins in control of Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov and Co. were on the ice for the first three Bruins
goals. Samsonov scored the next one himself, set up by Taylor from
behind the net after Taylor did a nice forechecking job on Alexei
Zhitnik.
</P>
<P>
   Timander stretched it to 3-1 midway through the period. That
goal was unassisted, but was also aided and abetted by Samsonov's
line, pestering the Buffalo defense down low. A Sabre tried to
clear it around the boards and Timander cut it off and fired it in.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and DiMaio, usually defensive specialists when paired
with P.J. Axelsson, worked the puck down low, got it to Samsonov
and the new line _ for a night at least _ was an instant hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're two guys who like to pressure the puck,'' Samsonov
said. ``Everyone thinks they're a checking line, but I feel pretty
comfortable with them getting a lot of offense. It was really fun
to play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly looked it. The Samsonov gang was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting the puck, that's the difference,'' said Bruins
coach Pat Burns of Samsonov, the league's Rookie of the Year last
season. ``He has to have the puck. Playing with those two guys you
know one thing, he's going to get the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov got the puck. Made himself some space and then took
full advantage of it. And thanks largely to him and his linemates
the Bruins are headed back to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   This has not been the smoothest of sophomore seasons for
Samsonov. He has not done a lot of scoring in the last half of the
year. Consider: In the Bruins' first 38 games he had 15 goals and
18 assists. In his last 41 regular-season games he had 11 goals and
eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer skates on the Bruins' most feared offensive unit
with Jason Allison and Dmitri Khristich. And Sunday's goal and
assist marked his first 2-point game since Feb. 21. He did have two
goals against Carolina in the last playoff series and he had two
assists in this one entering Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov sat out Game 3 of this series with back spasms and said
he probably will take treatment on it Monday, but it feels pretty
good.
</P>
<P>
   With the team struggling to score and his own scoring down, he
didn't feel any added pressure, Samsonov said. Nor were there any
special secrets to his and the team's success.
</P>
<P>
   Just basic end-of-the-season-in-sight desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it could be your last game,'' he said. ``You're
probably a little afraid to lose. It keeps you going.''
</P>
<P>
   Going straight to Buffalo where you can expect to see Samsonov,
Taylor, and DiMaio together again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was flying, right from the get-go,'' said Taylor of
Samsonov. ``I could tell he had good legs and was right in the
game. It was a case of mixing things up and trying new things and
today it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Having Samsonov did change the line's approach a bit, Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, taking P.J. off the line does take away a little of
the defensive mind of it,'' he said. ``We had to make sure one guy
was back a little more, but it was good knowing we could go in real
hard and try to create turnovers and get Sergei the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   When they did, good things tended to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie and I realized that if we can get Sergei the puck, it's
in the net,'' Taylor said. ``So that's what we tried to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
