<SLUG> BC-BKO-PARMER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARMER'S SWEET CROSSOVER TO ELITE COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Changing a perception wasn't high on the
to-do list heading into his senior season, but there is no doubt
that Los Angeles Verbum Dei High point guard Marlon Parmer set out
to prove to his critics that he was more than capable of being a
true playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem stemmed from his junior season, when at
times he played like a point guard without the ``point'' in his
game. In other words, his shoot-first, pass-second style rubbed
scouts the wrong way, and had some questioning whether he was
merely an undersized shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   That perception went by the wayside in 1999, as the 6-foot-2,
185-pound star recorded a staggering 12 assists per game in leading
the Eagles to a second consecutive Division IV state title.
</P>
<P>
   Parmer still got his points, as his 30-points-per-game average
will attest. But becoming a better distributor of the ball, and a
string of super fourth-quarter performances that lifted him to cult
status among Eagles followers, made the floor leader one of the
most sought after players in the country during the late-signing
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought as far as performance, he had the best season of any
senior in Southern California,'' Joel Francisco of Los
Alamitos-based So. Cal's Finest Scouting Service said. ``Every
game, he just had ice in his veins. His passing ability improved
dramatically his senior year. He's still a scoring point guard, but
he can make the pass when it's there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like most is that Marlon doesn't care who he's
playing against, he always plays at the same level,'' Francisco
added. ``You know exactly what you're going to get from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Parmer, whose ability to take over games down the stretch
reminds some of the fourth-quarter magic performed by former
Inglewood star and 1994-95 BIW top vote-getter Paul Pierce, said he
just loves to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at everybody as a competitor, so I'm going to play hard
against whoever is out there,'' said Parmer, who recently turned
down Michigan, USC and UNLV to sign with New Mexico. ``Every time I
step on the floor, I try to put forth my best effort. And I don't
take anyone lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   BOOZER'S BIG DECISION
</P>
<P>
   Most prep athletes agree that the toughest part of the
recruiting process is deciding which college to attend. The proper
decision could help lead to a pro career and a contract worth
millions.
</P>
<P>
   Things were no different for Juneau, Alaska, Douglas star Carlos
Boozer, who is one of the most highly regarded prospects in the
country and a unanimous selection in this year's Best in the West
poll. Boozer trimmed his list of schools to three Duke, UCLA and
St. John's and while he was rumored to be headed to UCLA, he
actually spent most of his senior season agonizing over the choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult ... for a while, I didn't know where I
wanted to go,'' he said. ``But after looking at everything, I felt
Duke was the perfect place for me. It's a wonderful environment,
and they have Coach (Mike) Krzyzewski, who's the best coach in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Duke) was where he felt most comfortable,'' Douglas coach
George Houston
</P>
<P>
   said. ``He really liked Mike Jarvis and St. John's, and he spent
so much time around the UCLA program over the years, he felt real
comfortable there. But ultimately, he felt the best place for him
was Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Boozer said Blue Devils' star power forward Elton Brand's
decision to enter the NBA draft had absolutely no effect on his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wish he had stayed,'' Boozer said. ``I think
practicing against him would have been unbelievable. You can't get
any better than playing against the best player in college
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   With Brand gone, former BIW first-teamer Chris Burgess
(Woodbridge) transferring and talented freshman swingman Corey
Maggette announcing Saturday he is bolting to the NBA, count on
Boozer and fellow BIW teammate Michael Dunleavy playing big minutes
for the Blue Devils next season.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL TOWN, BIG GAME
</P>
<P>
   With a population of roughly 2,000, the city of Knappa isn't one
of the larger municipalities in Oregon. In fact, with one flashing
light, one restaurant and one store in town, those who blink twice
while driving down Highway 30 just might miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking rural in every sense of the word,'' Craig Cokley
</P>
<P>
   said with a laugh. ``But it's a great place to raise a family,
and basketball is our passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cokley watched that passion swell the last two seasons while
coaching the Knappa boys basketball team. The school won 48
consecutive games on the way to capturing back-to-back Division 2-A
state titles.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason for the success has been standout forward-center
Brian Jackson, who might be the sleeper of the national Class of
'99 and whom Cokley compares favorably to NBA star Keith Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some very unique skills for a 6-10 guy,'' Cokley said
of Jackson, who averaged roughly 28 points and 12 rebounds per game
this season. ``He has had no professional coaching or training, so
his upside is tremendous. He has the physicality, skill and heart
to play at the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Cokley also has no worries about whether his small-town stud can
make the transition to big-time basketball when he plays next
season at Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty big step ... from Knappa High to the Pac-10,''
Cokley said. ``But I'm excited about his potential, and I know
Brian will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   KEEP AN EYE ON ...
</P>
<P>
   Wonder who the top prospects in the West will be heading into
2000? While the top five prospects figure to be the subject of much
debate, there is no doubt Fresno Washington Union junior Deshawn
Stevenson stands head and shoulders above the rest of the class.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, a muscular 6-5 shooting guard with a deadly outside
stroke and jaw-dropping athleticism, is a consensus top-five
prospect nationally and the West Coast's first serious national
Player of the Year candidate in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach Jordan's Travon Bryant, a 6-7 forward, is arguably
the second-best prospect in the West. Bryant is also considered one
of the top 25 seniors-to-be nationally heading into the crucial
summer evaluation period.
</P>
<P>
   Other top juniors include:
</P>
<P>
   Post players Keith Brooks
</P>
<P>
   (6-6, Compton Dominguez); Patrick Dennehy
</P>
<P>
   (6-9, Santa Clara Wilcox); Teyo Johnson
</P>
<P>
   (6-6, Everett, Wash., Mariner); Garner Meads
</P>
<P>
   (6-9, Salt Lake City Brighton); Ellis Myles
</P>
<P>
   (6-7, Compton); Jesse Pinegar
</P>
<P>
   (6-9, Salt Lake City Brighton); Luke Whitehead
</P>
<P>
   (6-6, San Francisco St. Ignatius); Andrew Zahn
</P>
<P>
   (6-9, Redondo Union).
</P>
<P>
   Guards and wing players Nick Booker
</P>
<P>
   (6-5, La Jolla The Bishop's School); James Davis
</P>
<P>
   (5-11, Vancouver, Wash., Evergreen); E.J. Harris
</P>
<P>
   (6-2, Crenshaw); Luke Jackson
</P>
<P>
   (6-5, Creswell, Ore., Creswell); Steve Moore
</P>
<P>
   (6-2, Compton Dominguez); Luke Ridnour
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
