<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS AVOID CZECHMATE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ And on the 10th day Dominik actually worked.
</P>
<P>
   He had put in some decent labor in Game 1. We'll give him that.
But Games 2, 3, and 4 represented little more than a paid vacation.
Dominik Hasek could have been sipping pina coladas and munching on
the nachos out there. The Bruins never bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but Sunday they made the great man work up a sweat. And they
also did something else _ they drove him from the game.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK. That's an exaggeration. But let the record show that
after two periods of Sunday's series-extending 5-3 victory over the
Buffalo Sabres the Bruins led, 4-1, and coach Lindy Ruff decided
that it was better for his meal ticket to take a seat and start
thinking about Game 6 than to subject him to any more shots from
the aroused Bruins, who had been treating him as if he were _ are
you ready? _ mortal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's human,'' confirmed Kyle McLaren. ``He can be beat. We
proved that in Game 1, and I think we proved it again today.''
</P>
<P>
   In between was another matter. The winning Buffalo scores in
Games 2, 3, and 4 were 3-2, 3-1, and 3-0, respectively. When Don
Sweeney slapped one past him at 9:01 of the opening period Sunday,
it represented the first Bruins goal in 116 minutes 13 seconds.
This mortality thing comes and goes.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like we can start calling him The Sieve. ``Dom may not
have had his A game, but there were a couple of times the puck had
eyes,'' said Buffalo center Wayne Primeau. ``There was a two-on-oh
break,'' reminded Curtis Brown, ``and that should never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to a Jason Allison-Dmitri Khristich
collaboration in the second period, when a Buffalo gamble turned
into a nice Bruins sashay into Dominik's living room. Allison, on
Hasek's right, put one right on Khristich's stick, and all the
maligned winger had to do was ram it home. There was not much
anyone could do about that, not even Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's goal had to have been a huge psychological lift for
the Bruins. If the scoreless streak had been allowed to drag into
the second period, it is quite possible the hometown team might
never have scored. But the redoubtable Bruins defenseman, who is in
the apparent process of transforming himself into the new Paul
Coffey, beat the great Czech goalkeeper with a wicked slapper for
his third goal of the playoffs. This matches a playoff career-high
goal count attained eight years ago at a time when he had sustained
about a zillion fewer hits and wasn't being listed as not just
game-to-game, but more like second-to-second with a bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, as you may know, is not very good at this
self-promotion stuff. ``We just put more pressure on him today,''
he said. ``If we play the perimeter game and keep passing the puck
and not crash and bang, you're not going to score many goals
against Dominik Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one goal that demonstrated the fact that Hasek had
come with something less than his A game, it was a Sergei Samsonov
tally that made it 2-1 at 1:15 of period two. Samsonov simply beat
Hasek to the far side with a shot the great man usually gobbles up.
The fourth goal against Hasek was a long Mattias Timander slap shot
quite reasonably assumed to be a screen job.
</P>
<P>
   But when you are Dominik Hasek, you don't grab onto the ready
excuse known as a screen. That's why he's Dominik Hasek, who makes
routinely spectacular saves every game he plays and who believes
you either stop the puck or you don't. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Screen?'' he shrugged. ``I don't remember. The shot went in.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus was that the Bruins had gotten too cutesy after
taking that 1-0 series lead. Well-meaning people were trying to
make plays when they would have been better-advised to let the puck
rip. Let Hasek deal with some flying rubber. Stop allowing him to
bring the morning paper and a nice paperback novel to the job.
Remind him why he's there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot,'' smirked a feisty Bruins coach Pat Burns. ``Shoot.
That helps. It really helps. You don't have time to be picking
corners, and whatnot. Just shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Hasek wouldn't admit to being screened on the Timander
goal, so, too, would it have been absolutely ridiculous to ask him
about his left knee. The fact is he took one in a vulnerable area
off a Dave Ellett blast in Game 3, and he did not participate in
either the subsequent offday practice or the morning skate on the
day of Game 4. He did join his mates in Saturday's workout, but no
one did much of anything. It was clear that Ruff just wanted to get
his people out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? A slight lack of mobility could have been the key to
the Samsonov goal. When you're talking about Hasek, you've got to
look for reasons when things appear to be a bit funny. Again, not
that he would admit that anything is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, naturally, won't offer any clue. ``He was screened on
one,'' he declared. ``There was a two-on-none on another. I guess
you expect him to stop those, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek expressed no anger or embarrassment for being lifted in
favor of former UMass-Lowell goalkeeper Dwayne Roloson before the
third period. ``I did not play well,'' he admitted. ``There is
nothing I can do about it now. I just have to forget it and get
ready for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Want a mortal lock bet for Tuesday night's Game 6? The Buffalo
Sabres will be ready. Dominik Hasek will really be ready. Did
someone say ``traffic'' in front of the net? If it doesn't look
like Boylston Street 20 minutes after a Red Sox game, the Bruins'
season definitely will be over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
