<HEADER>
A9540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-REFEREES-B     05-17 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-REFEREES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHISTLE-STOP TOUR CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Did someone mention the officiating? No? Didn't matter.
Pat Burns was primed to rant whether or not he was given the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Bruins' 5-3 victory over the Sabres Sunday at the
FleetCenter, which enabled them to extend this best-of-seven
Eastern Conference semifinal to a sixth game, Burns turned a
tangential question into a diatribe on the refereeing in general.
And when Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff, advised of his counterpart's
comments by those notorious provocateurs of the press, returned
fire, the series had a genuine subplot, if not a legitimate
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Burns was asked about the impact of the Sabres' first goal, by
Joe Juneau on a power play just 37 seconds into the action, and
suddenly, he somehow had the makings of a federal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean the one that went off the referee's (Stephen
Walkom's) back?'' he said, his voice brimming with the sarcasm that
is his favorite weapon at many press briefings. ``Sometime things
like that have to happen in the playoffs for teams to have success.
Like that shorthanded goal (by Buffalo's Michael Peca in Game 4
Friday) a couple of days back where the puck hit something, nobody
knows what. The referee's back.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the officials' positioning that truly inspired his
vitriol. It was basically their position on penalties _ which he
considers heavily weighted in the Sabres' favor throughout the
series.
</P>
<P>
   And without further ado, or questioning, he was off on a
full-fledged harangue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting much help,'' he said. ``I stay away from
whining as much as possible. I leave that to Lindy _ he does a good
job of it. I sort of backed off and didn't say much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the second efforts, the flying elbows, the punches upset
me . . . and if anybody here didn't see it, you're as blind as a
couple of guys on the ice today.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to name names, but he couldn't possibly have been referring
to Walkom and fellow referee Dan Marouelli, could he?
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Sabres are) getting away with a lot of things,'' Burns
continued without pause. ``. . . Robbie DiMaio got sent to the
penalty box for being punched. Peca gets away with whatever he
wants . . . and we say Ray Bourque gets away with anything he
wants. Peca gets away with murder. I mean murder . . . Peca dropped
his glove one time and took a swipe at Ray Bourque's head. Lucky he
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget the peripheral victims of arbitrary
justice, such as Bruins muscleman Ken Belanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Buffalo's Paul) Kruse goes out and runs guys, gets everybody
low,'' said Burns. ``I send Ken Belanger out there for one shift,
and the first guy he touches, he's gone. The poor guy can't play
one shift. Kruse can run around, attack guys behind the net,
cross-check them. Belanger steps out there, and automatically,
there are four sets of eyes looking at him. There can be all kinds
of stuff going on behind the play and it doesn't matter. As long as
Belanger is out there, `We're gonna get you, kid.' Kruse can run
around, (Erik) Rasmussen can run around, cross-check people . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are those manipulative Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the game, I had to hang around the bench,'' said
Burns, ``because they wait for the referee to step off and then
they sit there crying to him for 15 minutes. Today I waited and
waited because I wanted to see exactly what happened. Sure enough .
. . I said, `There you go. That's exactly what happens.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately given the opportunity when he succeeded Burns at the
microphone, Ruff wasn't above taking the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Informed that Burns considers him a whiner, the Sabres coach
laughed heartily, the calm before his volley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to like Pat, I'll tell you,'' said Ruff. ``I was
worried some of our guys were going to get hit with cheap shots.
Bourque, the way he carries his stick, DiMaio . . . There were
enough cheap shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But not by his innocents, Ruff hastily added. ``I thought they
were good hits. Peca ran over Bourque. (Alexei) Zhitnik ran over
Bourque.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from Burns, Ruff turned an unrelated question _
why did he lift goalie Dominik Hasek after two periods with the
Sabres trailing, 4-1? _ into a plea to stop the insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about the cheap shots,'' he said. ``Belanger,
DiMaio, (Tim) Taylor . . . I was worried about somebody breaking
their stick over Dom.''
</P>
<P>
   Victim/villain Bourque evoked laughter when he was asked about
the elbowing by Peca and said, ``Which one?''
</P>
<P>
   The aggrieved Bourque went on, ``Yeah, it was an elbow. I don't
know what they see. The ref's right there and he's watching it. But
I don't wear the stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the accused, Peca, provided the only semblance of
perspective on the matter, with some sarcasm for seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody died out there, so I didn't get away
with murder,'' he said. ``I think both teams are getting away with
cheap shots. I think that comment is an injustice because both
teams are getting away with it. We'll see how much I get away with
Tuesday night.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be Game _ or Round _ 6 in Buffalo. It may decide the
series, but that's trivial. Seeing how the referees call it will be
the main attraction. Just ask the coaches. In fact, you don't even
have to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
