<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR START FINISHED SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ During a power play at 9:11 of the third period Sunday,
Sabres center Brian Holzinger raised his stick in triumph as the
puck went . . . oops, it went over the net. Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   That hardly was Buffalo's lone mistake of the afternoon at the
FleetCenter. Just about everything went wrong for the Sabres until
it was far too late. As a result, they were guilty of the one thing
they had vowed to avoid after assuming a 3-1 lead in this
best-of-seven Eastern Conference semifinal: letting the Bruins off
the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's 5-3 victory, fueled by a three-goal second period that
built a 4-1 lead and chased wondergoalie Dominik Hasek from the
Buffalo net, emphasized to the Sabres a point that was long
overdue: A hockey game is not a faucet.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3 Wednesday at Buffalo, they had overcome a dreadful
start with a dominant third period that produced a 3-2 victory. In
a similar position Sunday, they again revved up for the final 20
minutes, closing the deficit to 4-3 at one point. But this time two
lethargic periods were fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably had five or six guys give us that 80 percent,''
said coach Lindy Ruff. ``They said to themselves, `Dom played a
great first period (when the Sabres were in a 1-1 tie after being
outshot, 16-6). We can let it slide.' They played an easy game.''
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't get away with it in the second period, when Boston
took command with goals by Sergei Samsonov and Mattias Timander _
both set up on giveaways by defenseman Alexei Zhitnik _ and by
Dmitri Khristich after the Sabres lost the puck in the Bruins' zone
as a power play expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gambled,'' said Ruff, ``and maybe lost in our gambling a
couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that killing four penalties in a 14-minute
stretch after they took a 1-0 first-period lead didn't enhance the
Sabres' cause, but all in all, he wasn't pleased with his team's
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the goals, we gave them pretty much every
chance they had,'' said center Joe Juneau. ``They didn't really
have to work for them. Breakdowns, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuttering starts are not unfamiliar to the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tendency to do that sometimes,'' said center Wayne
Primeau. ``We get lackluster in the third period, figure we can
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Sabres almost did after Ruff decided to send them a
message. He shortened his bench, ignoring forward Michal Grosek in
particular, in the third period ``and went with the guys who were
battling,'' said center Michael Peca.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres hope the message and momentum won't be forgotten
Tuesday in Game 6 at Buffalo _ when the Bruins get a second chance
the Sabres gave them when they knew they couldn't afford to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
