<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9549 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDER-GRANDMOTHER-CR     05-17 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-GRANDMOTHER-CRUSADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN DEVOTES TWO YEARS OF LIFE TO FREE GRANDSON CONVICTED OF
MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gladis Spencer stood on the street where Maya Streeter died and
wept.
</P>
<P>
   She wept for Streeter, dead at 23. She wept for Streeter's three
children, left motherless.
</P>
<P>
   And she wept for Derek Spencer, her 20-year-old grandson, who
she believes was wrongly convicted of shooting Streeter during an
East Tacoma party in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the jury after the verdict that God knows he didn't do
it _ that they didn't have the last word,'' Spencer said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's beliefs have propelled the retired phone company
worker into a two-year odyssey to prove her grandson's innocence.
And whether Derek Spencer is in fact guilty of the charges of which
he was convicted _ first-degree murder and first-degree assault _
his grandmother has shown a zeal on his behalf seldom seen in the
families of defendants, say attorneys familiar with the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Washington state Court of Appeals will hear
Derek Spencer's request for a new trial based on several issues in
the case, including how he was sentenced. The arguments will not
touch on evidence or testimony in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But for Gladis Spencer, there are other burning issues in the
case, issues she will pursue if the appeal fails, despite diabetes
and a limited retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   She asserts there is no physical evidence tying her grandson to
Streeter's death, no fingerprints on the murder weapon, no tests
run on him after the shooting for gunpowder residue. Several of the
people who testified against him admitted to drinking or using
drugs before the shooting. And some of the witnesses, with criminal
records of their own, gave testimony that differed markedly from
statements they gave to police, she alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said at trial that Derek Spencer was a gang member
and was outside a party when members of a rival gang rolled up.
They say he pulled out a gun during a confrontation that followed.
</P>
<P>
   When someone suddenly tossed a bottle against a car, Derek
Spencer turned and recklessly fired into a crowd of people standing
next to the street, prosecutors allege. Maya Streeter, who was
getting out of a car parked at the curb, was shot through the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   And while the witnesses who testified against Derek Spencer may
not have had completely consistent testimony, it does not mean they
lack credibility, prosecutors said at trial. Such inconsistencies
are understandable based on the traumatic events of the evening,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   But Derek Spencer and his attorneys contend that while he was
indeed standing outside at the party, he did not have a gun. And
they say the trajectory of the bullet that killed Maya Streeter
could not have been fired from the spot where witnesses placed him.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Spencer is now a little less than two years into a 47-year
sentence for the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Streeter's family could not be reached for comment. But Michael
Sommerfeld, a Pierce County prosecutor, said he believes Derek
Spencer's appeal has no merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly our office is extremely regretful about the
suffering Mr. Spencer's family has endured, but we obviously feel
the greater suffering was the loss of Maya Streeter's life ... and
the suffering felt by her family,'' Sommerfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Gladis Spencer says she can understand a little of how
Streeter's family must feel. She lost her own 23-year-old sister at
the hands of a murderer. And like Streeter, her sister also left
behind three children, children Spencer raised.
</P>
<P>
   But having the wrong man convicted in Streeter's death does her
memory no honor, Spencer insists.
</P>
<P>
   She has been joined in her quest by her daughter, Tammie
Jackson, Derek Spencer's aunt. Together, the pair managed to scrape
up $10,000 from savings and donations from family members to hire
the firm of Monte Hester, the most prominent criminal defense
lawyer in Pierce County, to handle an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still owe $618,'' said Spencer, who raised seven children
as a single parent. She will call more relatives, appealing for
them to reach for that extra dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer and Jackson have pored over all documents in the case,
including the 726-page transcript from Derek Spencer's trial, each
page neatly encased in a plastic sleeve. Testimony they believe is
inconsistent or untrue is highlighted; sticky notes remind them of
questions to ask their lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   They have sent letters to many prominent African Americans such
as Oprah Winfrey, Bill Cosby and Johnnie Cochran requesting their
aid in the case.
</P>
<P>
   They've called numerous television stations and newspapers,
begging them to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   And they've called some of the lawyers responsible for freeing
defendants wrongly convicted of child sex-abuse in Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   They've met with little success. The letters and pleas have gone
unanswered, their phone calls unreturned.
</P>
<P>
   But Gladis Spencer, driven by love and conviction, hasn't given
up. She is fortified by her faith in God that her grandson will be
freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Lord,'' she says simply. ``I believe in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who fiercely loves her nephew, has had a harder
struggle with her faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so hard to undo what has already been done,'' she says.
``Now two years of his life are gone and he can't get them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a bus driver, is the mother of two children, ages 8 and
14. She sometimes worries the campaign to prove her nephew's
innocence has shortchanged her own children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become my whole world,'' Jackson said. ``It's like my
whole life just stopped when this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Fricke wrote the appeal for Derek Spencer and will argue
it before the Appeals Court Tuesday. He and his firm recently won a
major federal appeals case upholding a judge's decision to cut more
than seven years off the prison sentence of a woman who shot and
wounded her abusive husband on the Fort Lewis Army base.
</P>
<P>
   They took the case because they believe there are major legal
issues connected to the conviction, issues that demand attention
from the courts, Fricke says.
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues, Fricke alleges in his appeal that Derek
Spencer's constitutional right against double jeopardy was violated
by his conviction for both first-degree assault and first-degree
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Derek Spencer was incorrectly ordered to serve
time on each conviction consecutively, rather than concurrently,
Fricke asserts in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Fricke says he feels positive about his legal arguments. But he
said it's always hard in court to surmount prejudice and negative
feelings connected to anyone convicted of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about these kind of cases, we don't have the
emotions on our side,'' he said. ``You've always got to get above
that hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors assert in court papers that Derek Spencer did not
face double jeopardy for his twin convictions on both first-degree
murder and assault, saying that ``proof of either offense does not
necessarily prove the other ... the elements of the two crimes are
not at all the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, state case law permits Derek Spencer's 26{-year
sentence for murder and 10-year sentence for assault to run
consecutively, they say. Derek Spencer also faces two additional
five-year terms for use of a firearm in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Spencer was largely raised by Gladis Spencer after he was
born to her 16-year-old daughter. Jackson was 9 at the time, and
she, too, helped raise him. The family lived in Anchorage, Alaska,
for much of his childhood, moving to Tacoma in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In Anchorage he was a good student, and Spencer eagerly shows
his academic and skiing awards, honors she carries in a box along
with his court records. His Cub Scout scarf is draped over one of
his elementary-school photos on a wall in her apartment, alongside
numerous other family portraits.
</P>
<P>
   His family doesn't assert his conduct was completely angelic in
Tacoma. He hung out with a rough crowd, many of whom had gang
affiliations, and he didn't finish high school. But he had no
criminal background, they point out, and was never known to be
violent.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals case doesn't touch on all of the issues Spencer and
Jackson believe are so important, including their doubts about
quality of the evidence and testimony introduced at trial. Nor will
it address the issue of whether he received adequate representation
at trial, which Spencer and Jackson say was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Fricke said those issues may well be worth exploring. If they're
unsuccessful on appeal, they will have to go through a personal
restraint petition. Such a petition is a way to bring up issues of
newly discovered evidence, to explore whether Derek Spencer
received effective council at trial, and to examine whether
evidence was properly presented, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things that certainly has piqued my
interest, although it's not on appeal on this time,'' Fricke said.
``Whatever happens on appeal, it's not necessarily going to end the
case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
