<HEADLINE>
ROBERTS MAKES FORTYSOMETHINGS EVERYWHERE PROUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
IRVING, Texas _ Youth will be served on this PGA tour, a couple of
kids named Sergio Garcia and Tiger Woods reminded us this weekend. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in the meantime, there is Loren Roberts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, he had wondered. A golf professional since 1975,
the year that Woods was born, Roberts had missed successive cuts in
Florida at Bay Hill and Sawgrass then had trashed together
back-to-back 76s at the Masters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, not two months ago,'' Roberts said yesterday, ``I
was thinking that, 43 years old, and maybe I'm a little too old out
here now with all of these young guys.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to be a gentlemanly confession yesterday, after
Roberts and Steve Pate had gone middle-aged crazy and nearly lapped
Woods and the rest of the Byron Nelson Classic field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Together, Roberts and Pate, 37, finished the 72 holes at
18-under-par and seven Geritol-flavored strokes ahead of the
nearest scrum of challengers. Woods himself was nine behind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lesson to be learned was that you can bring in the
bulldozers and stretch the golf courses to Yellowstone lengths, but
sooner or later you're going to have to hit a few greens and sink
some putts.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so short that I can't get to the par 4s,'' Roberts
said. ``And I figure that if I can get it on the green, then
everybody, they're playing in my home stadium.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His roost is the putting green. Blame it on maturity. Attribute
it to his wise old nerves. Roberts' prowess with the putter has
earned him the tour nickname, ``Boss of the Moss.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a blustery final day at the TPC at Las Colinas course, where
the winds blew and caution reigned, Garcia, Woods and the other
pursuers never really had a chance. It was not the day to leapfrog
the field and close Roberts' sizeable gap. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it would turn out, Roberts himself had the day's most
significant birdie, after he beamed a 3-iron on No. 15 to a scant
three feet. The birdie had been preceded by a wet double-bogey on
the par-4 14th, a turn of events that had pushed Pate into a brief
lead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knotted again, the two charged into sudden-death overtime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, they just walked.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who grew up in San Luis Obispo, Calif., teased about
his age but he admits that he is a golfing late bloomer of sorts.
He turns 44 next month, but in dogleg years, he didn't come of age
until the 1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His is not your basic, Tigeresque, ordained-from-birth resume.
He began playing the game in the 11th grade, but his high school
didn't have a golf team. He went on to college at Cal Poly-San Luis
Obispo, but the school dropped its men's golf team, blaming Title
IX. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberts ended up working as an assistant club pro in his
hometown. Since the driving range was always busy, he whiled away
his hours on the practice putting green.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His golfing mentor, Jim Swagerty, finally pointed Roberts in the
right direction. If Loren had the dream, he should pursue the
dream, Swagerty told him. The practice range in San Luis Obispo
would still be there if things didn't work out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 19 years after he first turned professional and seven
years after he had to earn his tour playing card for the final
time, Roberts won his first PGA event, the Nestle Invitational at
Bay Hill. He had won four other tournaments before the Nelson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm not as broken down as I should be at my age,''
Roberts joked yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the doubts had begun to creep in, like mailings
from the AARP, and Roberts said, ``I wasn't questioning to the
point of thinking it's time to quit or anything. But I was
thinking, `Gosh, have you still got it anymore?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a move that fortysomethings everywhere can appreciate,
Roberts went home and started digging through his old journals and
scrapbooks. He found a hint here, a reassurance there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a pretty big emotional swing from two months ago to
now,'' he said yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' face showed it. In an emotional scene on the 18th
green, as he was presented with the championship trophy, Roberts
had embraced his 83-year-old father, Hugh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the Roberts men, Loren and Hugh, it has been a draining 2
1/2 years. Loren's mother, Joan Roberts, has been diagnosed with
Alzheimer's Disease and was admitted to a care facility two months
ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first week that he's been able to get out and come
to a golf tournament,'' Loren said. Hugh Roberts had never before
seen his son win a professional golf tournament.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Embracing after the playoff, Loren said: ``I just told him, `I'm
so thrilled you're here, dad, and I love you.' I said I know mom
was watching at home.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, he had wondered. Silly ``old'' man. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
