<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HAVE DEVIL OF A TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For the sake of perspective, consider Dave
Silvestri.
</P>
<P>
   Silvestri wasn't good enough to make the Tampa Bay Devil Rays'
major-league roster out of spring training. He played one game for
their Triple-A affiliate in Durham, N.C., before being released by
the organization altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, he was the Anaheim Angels' starting left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Devil Rays beat the Angels 7-4 in front of 35,064
at Edison Field, taking the series two games to one.
</P>
<P>
   In eight three-game sets this season, the Angels have won only
one _ their sweep of the Yankees last week. They've lost the other
seven.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Angels is they are only 4{ games out of
first place in the AL West. The bad news is it's a team that looked
more like an expansion team Sunday than did the expansion team in
the visitors' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays starter Wilson Alvarez (2-2) wasn't at his best,
according to Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild, but was good
enough against a lineup heavily dependent on Mo Vaughn. Perhaps too
dependent.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hit his eighth home run of the season in the fifth to cut
a 7-0 lead to 7-2. Garret Anderson and Todd Greene homered in the
eighth and ninth innings, respectively, to make it a little closer.
Vaughn has been hot since returning to the DH spot last week. In
six games there he's hitting .455 (10 for 22) with four homers and
14 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he is the key to our lineup,'' manager Terry Collins
said. ``If Todd (Greene) and Garret (Anderson) start swinging _ and
Garret has been _ they'll start picking up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing Mo does is he prepares so good. He goes up there
and looks for something and he doesn't miss it. One thing that's
happening right now (with everybody else) is I'm seeing a lot of
foul balls going straight back. That means we're getting pitches
but just missing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Steve Sparks (1-4) struggled again. He had thrown
two exceptional games but lasted only three innings in his most
recent start last week against the Yankees. He had trouble again
Sunday, giving up six runs and 10 hits in four-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks came out after allowing back-to-back homers to Dave
Martinez and Jose Canseco in the fifth, and Collins got out of the
dugout so fast after Canseco's homer he cut in front of Canseco as
he crossed the third-base line on his way to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had crossed it before the pitch crossed the plate,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Sparks' trouble is the nature of the knuckleball _
you never know what you're going to get. But Sparks wasn't buying
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the nature of the knuckleball,'' Sparks said. ``I
didn't do a good job of changing speeds with it. The bottom line is
I've got to do a better job of keeping the hitters off stride and
mixing up my pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez enjoyed Sparks' problems, hitting triples in his first
two at-bats before hitting his homer in the fifth. With 10 total
bases, Martinez set a Devil Rays record. However, it wasn't his
personal best _ while with the White Sox, Martinez had 11 total
bases in a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense got 10 hits but not when they needed them.
Greene, for example, stranded six baserunners in his first four
at-bats, then homered with nobody on in his fifth at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're missing balls we should be hitting,'' Greene said. ``I'm
hitting dumb right now. I'm making dumb mistakes. I was too excited
today (coming off a three-game suspension). I was jumping at balls.
Mo told me to realize the situation _ the pressure's on him. I just
need to relax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
