<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-PREMIERE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITY SCREENING OF NEW `STAR WARS' EPIC GENERATES RAVE REVIEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHIL DAVIS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget the critics. The celebrities and other
lucky folks who attended a $500-a-ticket charity screening of
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' pronounced the movie
an overwhelming success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, it was great,'' said actress Jennifer Tilly said
after Sunday's screening. ``The special effects were really
fantastic. It really took you to other worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite moments: dizzying lightsaber fights between Jedi
knights Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) and Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan
McGregor) and their evil nemesis and some excellent laser
marksmanship by Queen Amidala (Natalie Portman).
</P>
<P>
   Any disappointments? No sex and no peek at McGregor's buff
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needed a little bit of sex,'' Tilly said. ``But I really
like it when the lightsabers come out. And there's a lot of that. A
guy in this one has two.''
</P>
<P>
   The premiere gave celebrities a rare chance to pan the critics,
who have pronounced ``Episode I'' a poorly directed but visually
intriguing film that fails to live up to its abundant prerelease
hype. The film opens on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just bitter,'' actress Christina Ricci said. ``People
who criticize `Star Wars' obviously just don't get the point.''
</P>
<P>
   The point? ``It's pure fantasy,'' she said. ``It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie delivered for the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS
Foundation, one of 11 charities nationwide chosen to host an
advance screening of the ``Star Wars'' prequel. Sunday's event
raised more than $1.2 million for the foundation _ all going for
pediatric AIDS research, said co-founder Kate Carr.
</P>
<P>
   The costs for the red-carpet screening and an elaborate
after-party at the UCLA/Armand Hammer Museum were paid for with a
$250,000 check from corporate sponsor FlexJet.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the event sold out in 24 hours, filling three
theaters _ 1,400 seats _ at the GCC Avco Theater in Westwood. The
audience was a mix of corporate executives and several dozen
celebrities. Many sponsored kids and families who are dealing with
HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome _ really great. I really liked that robot
R2-D2. He's pretty funny,'' said 17-year-old Cameron, one of the
hundreds of AIDS Foundation kids who saw the movie and rubbed
elbows with celebrities at the ``Star Wars''-themed party. ``My
brother just saw Dustin Hoffman in the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities were glad to put their star power and checkbooks
behind the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful day,'' said former Los Angeles Lakers star
Magic Johnson, who has HIV. ``The sun is shining, and this has
raised more than a million dollars for pediatric AIDS. Elizabeth
Glaser must be smiling down from heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Episode I'' stars Jake Lloyd and Samuel L. Jackson turned out
for the screening. Lloyd said he's enjoying his moment as the
coolest kid in America, though he's trying not to let it go to his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like walking down a press line and having
everyone scream your name _ Jake, Jake, we want your picture. I
love it,'' he said, flanked by a trio of scowling bodyguards. ``But
the big ol' movie star thing doesn't really suit me. I'm going to
try and remain as normal as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The savvy 10-year-old also didn't forget the theme of the day.
``I'm very excited. All this money is going to pediatric AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite overwhelmingly negative reviews, few on Sunday were
disappointed in director George Lucas' latest addition to the
``Star Wars'' saga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was soooo good _ really exciting,'' said actress Fran
Drescher, whose sparkling rhinestone-studded Gucci pants rivaled
many of the movie's outlandish costumes. ``The fashions were
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see how a `Star Wars' fan can see it and say, I'm
disappointed,'' said actor Bruce Boxleitner, who tried out for the
role of Luke Skywalker in the original movie. ``The moment `Star
Wars' appears on the screen and the music starts, you say, I'm
home. If nothing else, it's a feast for the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Drew Carey agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worlds and creatures were amazing _ a lot of eye candy,''
he said. ``I'm glad I didn't pay attention to all the hype and
stuff. I was really surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Rob Schneider wasn't overwhelmed by ``Episode I,'' but
he thought it laid an excellent foundation for Episodes II and III.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the backlash is all B.S.,'' he said. ``It's
visually spectacular and a phenomenal piece of filmmaking, but
nothing can live up to this hype. I'm looking forward to a darker
film next time _ with less puppets.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer Melissa Etheridge, who admits she was ``blown away'' by
the original ``Star Wars,'' went into the theater on Sunday
expecting to be pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting to be lifted off the ground here,'' she
said. ``I'm expecting to see a good movie by an old friend.''
</P>
<P>
   More highlights and minutiae from Sunday's ``Episode'' I
screening:
</P>
<P>
   _ Indie film queen Ricci, who comes from a family of ``Star
Wars'' fans, confessed a dark obsession with Jabba the Hutt, the
corpulent, computer-generated crime lord who appears in ``Episode
I,'' ``Return of the Jedi'' and a computer-enhanced remake of the
original ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just so gross and icky,'' she said. ``It's sort of like
watching a car wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Basketball great turned businessman Johnson confessed that he
loved the original ``Star Wars'' so much he hid in a Lansing,
Mich., theater bathroom between shows so he could see it again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed all day from the very first movie to the last,''
Johnson said. ``This is one of those engaging movies that we're
always going to want to go see. We're hooked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
