<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-17 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The end was frustrating. It was disappointing. The trials of the
season were discouraging, the playoff series with the Lakers often
disheartening.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But now, considering the events of the past four months,
considering the losses that put the Rockets in this situation and
the matchup that was against them from opening night, the end could
not be considered surprising.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had become the fifth seed in the Western Conference
and were then beaten on schedule, in four games of the first round.
And though they left believing that at their best they could beat
any team, they knew the one that had shown them the door was
better.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, it was not a sudden development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't just start in the playoffs,'' Rockets forward
Scottie Pippen said. ``We saw this happening through the regular
season. We were very inconsistent. We weren't winning the close
games. We allowed home-court advantage to slip away from us. You
could see bumps in the road along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The bumps were at times mountainous, made more obvious as they
came in tandem with their finest moments.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets ended March with a nine-game winning streak. But
they began April by blowing a 15-point fourth-quarter lead in Utah,
a loss that seemed to take weeks to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   They regrouped in Minnesota, recapturing the emotion of their
March run, and began playing some of their best basketball of the
season when they grabbed a 23-point first-half lead in San Antonio.
But they again were beaten at the buzzer, with ex-Rocket Mario Elie
making sure it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Having played the Jazz for a share of first in the Midwest
Division, they had played the Spurs for third in the Western
Conference. Losing that, they set their sights on at least holding
the home-court advantage in the first round. But in the weeks that
followed, they lost to the Mavericks at home twice, stumbled at the
Clippers and were routed in Phoenix to fall to the fifth seed,
forcing them to open the playoffs in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the Rockets seemed to have regrouped again. During
their late-season slide, they beat the Lakers by 22. And in Game 1,
they took a lead into the last 10 seconds before a Pippen slip and
a controversial call against Sam Mack helped the Lakers take early
control of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a competitive team,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``On April 1, we were playing for first place in Utah. We had
our ups and downs during the year. We had some opportunities going
all the way to the opening game of this series when we could have
put ourselves in better position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over now. But I think if we would have taken care of the
first game, it changes the psychology of this whole deal,
especially where they were a team just regrouping. In their first
time out in a playoff game, if we could have won that one, it could
have changed it. It didn't happen, but we still had an opportunity
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't break the dam. We couldn't get over the
hump.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that of the last game. But he could have been talking
about the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Pippen said, the season will be remembered as one in
which he could not deliver on the promise he brought when he
carried his six-championship portfolio to the Rockets in a
sign-and-trade deal. He did not even mind that supposition, even
sharing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot on myself,'' Pippen said. ``I have to face our
management, our owner Les (Alexander), Robert (Barr), C.D. (Carroll
Dawson). Coming in, I felt like I was the one piece they needed to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen was not a clear, well-defined piece to be plugged
into an obvious void. He did bring the variety of talents the
Rockets found so attractive. But he did not have a definitive
offensive style, pet moves or favorite plays to make the adjustment
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen never seemed at ease with the Rockets' offense or his
place in it. Almost two months after he went public with his
complaints in Phoenix, he went 0-for-7 and scored three points in
the Game 2 loss in Los Angeles. Ironically, he seemed to prove the
offense was not the problem when he led the Rockets to their lone
playoff victory, scoring 37 points without simply firing
3-pointers, in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie has to take some blame for that,'' Rockets forward
Charles Barkley said. ``He's got to be aggressive like he was in
(Game 3). Let's say I went to the Chicago Bulls. I wouldn't expect
them to change the triangle (offense). He just has to be more
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever difficulties the Rockets had adding their most
celebrated piece, none of their changes went easily or proved
enough. Centers Antoine Carr and Stanley Roberts had injury
problems that led to conditioning troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie backcourt of Cuttino Mobley and Michael Dickerson,
once it hit the playoffs, finally seemed to act its age, especially
when the Lakers refused to leave either open to double-team inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say our young guys struggled in the playoffs,''
Barkley said. ``I was hoping it wasn't true. But it came true.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some promise there. Michael Dickerson has a chance to
be a really good player. Cuttino, they have to find a position for
him. As well as he played, he's not a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would help Scottie, too. Scottie expends so much energy
bringing the ball up the court all the time. Scottie would be more
integral in the offense if we get a guy who plays the point.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Pippen, the rookies and the other newcomers
seemed to need time the lockout-shortened season did not provide.
And if it seemed an odd mix to have an all-time top-50 front line
averaging 35 years old with an all-rookie backcourt, the Rockets
had a team that needed time to mature led by mature stars running
out of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' guard Brent Price, who had a breakthrough
season, said of promise he considered unfulfilled. ``I look at our
team, and we have a lot of weapons. We have some very explosive
guys offensively and defensively. It seemed like it was a battle
all year to get it all jelling, to get it all on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, despite his matchup problems with Shaquille
O'Neal, and Barkley had solid seasons, certainly better and
healthier than a year before. But they remained the keys to the
Rockets' chances, perhaps too much so.
</P>
<P>
   And though Barkley argued they will get older, they seemed to
have gotten younger since last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an interesting year,'' Barkley said as he considered
making this season his last. ``I've never been through anything
like it. It was very monotonous, and time-consuming and tiring. It
was also fun. We had such good guys. Those rookies have great
personalities. They're fun to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take a lot for me to come back and play basketball
again. We've talked a lot privately. I've talked with all my
friends. I can leave now in peace. Last year, we had a lousy team
and a lot of problems in the locker room. I really enjoyed this
team a great deal. I enjoyed playing with Scottie. Hakeem has
always been terrific. I thought the rookies did a great job under
the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed it ended. I can honestly say we got beat by a
better team. But I enjoyed this year a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As rushed and too brief as it was, it at least was never dull.
But the Rockets left it, believing it could have been much more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
