<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-17 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IN retrospect, it was a silly notion, assembling the Rockets in
such a strange fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly given the particulars of such an odd season.
</P>
<P>
   Zero experience in the backcourt plus almost a half century of
experience in the frontcourt equaled a 54-game exercise in
futility, which ended with a perfunctory first-round playoff loss
to the more traditionally structured _ albeit dysfunctional in
their own right _ Lakers. The NBA had never seen a lineup of
extremes quite like Houston's, and now we know why.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters and the codgers wouldn't mix much better than oil
with water over the compressed course of the lockout-shortened
schedule. The combination never clicked.
</P>
<P>
   It might, might, have had a chance under normal circumstances,
with 82 tipoffs and liberal amounts of teaching time in preseason
camp plus regular-season practices. But the mad sprint to the
finish line did the Rockets no favors.
</P>
<P>
   Just when we thought the kids were all right, the playoffs
started, and everybody got a jolting reminder of how the second
season is the cruelest season for those who are unprepared for its
rigors, more mental than physical.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley and Michael Dickerson, offensive busts against
the Lakers, won't be blindsided in the future. They both figure to
have long and prosperous careers, as should the third training
wheel, Bryce Drew, who could be the best of the lot in the end. But
that fact does them not a bit of good for the present as they sit
around wondering what hit them.
</P>
<P>
   What hits some of the rest of us, in our 20-20 hindsight, is how
valuable a battle-proven veteran guard (hint: His initials are
K.J.) might have been to stabilizing the Rockets' dichotomous
recipe. With every killing jumper the Methuselan Derek Harper
swished for LA on Saturday afternoon, the more of a yearning we
felt for Charles Barkley's unemployed former teammate, Kevin
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Johnson wouldn't have helped, but today it's an intriguing
question to ponder. Moot, but intriguing nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Rockets won a championship with a rookie guard, Sam
Cassell, taking their reins in the fourth quarter. However, Cassell
could do that then because the man in the center of it all, Hakeem
Olajuwon, was at the absolute apex of his career. He was the NBA's
most dominant player, making everyone around him a notch or two
superior simply by association.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Against a Shaquille O'Neal _ Olajuwon's heir, nothing
apparent about him _ Hakeem was a borderline liability. As Mobley,
Dickerson and Drew ascend, Olajuwon is descending, perhaps
precipitously. There's no chance the former trio and the latter
hero will be in the right place at the right time together.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Sir Charles seems inclined to take his leave. He is
a realist. He can read the handwriting on the wall without reaching
for his bifocals. While Barkley acknowledges the rookies have
bright futures, he can't speak so emphatically for himself, Dream
or the enigmatic Scottie Pippen, upon whose shoulders the
short-term future of the Rockets must rest.
</P>
<P>
   (A scary thought, that, given the flickering fire in Pippen's
belly this year.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chuckster wanted to leave on a high note, and if he is
indeed out of here, then he succeeded _ at least personally. His
effort against the Lakers was phenomenal, if ultimately futile.
Alas, subtracting him from the equation takes away more than a
single husky torso. He provided the Rockets with a preponderance of
what leadership, direction and inspiration they had. The stuff of
which he's made isn't easily replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley has threatened retirement before, so maybe it's just
talk. Olajuwon, for one, said he ``can't imagine Charles not being
here'' next season. What Barkley is asking of the Rockets in
return, though, is a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   He requires some tangible proof they will be significantly
improved next fall. Where remains to be seen, given anticipated
payroll constraints. A significant free-agent acquisition is almost
mandatory, yet the huge sum they have tied up in Pippen _ never
mind Olajuwon _ creates a bucks bottleneck.
</P>
<P>
   And picking up the paltry million dollars Barkley would leave on
the table is almost laughably irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets probably should be in a rebuilding mode. Instead,
they are trapped somewhere between contending and starting over, in
a special kind of purgatory that doesn't figure to satisfy anyone
without a major surprise or two along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Had they been able to acquire, instead of the 33-year-old
Pippen, a strapping young star on the rise such as Antonio McDyess
to complement the neophytes on the perimeter, there might appear to
be more method than madness in their intentions. As it stands, the
ratio looks shaky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
