NYT-05-17-99 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9565 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     05-17 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NOW the real work begins.
</P>
<P>
   Not making excuses or rationalizations, but plans to pick up the
pieces of a broken season and finding a way to rearrange the
puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the Rockets who went down in four games to the
Lakers will be the same Rockets returning for training camp in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, including Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to doubt the sincerity of his words or the depth of
his emotional hurt when in the aftermath of Saturday's elimination
he brought up the subject of retirement again.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that nobody plays the game harder or with more of a
sense of personal passion than Barkley, and that means nobody takes
losses more to heart.
</P>
<P>
   The Chuckster finished up his 16th NBA season with a black eye
and a 36-year-old body that had been pushed to the breaking point
with that amazing 30-point, 23-rebound performance in Game 3. And
the natural reaction, at his age, is to ask himself if he can make
the commitment to do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Does he want to work diligently to get his aging body into shape
for one more run? Does he want to subject himself to a grueling,
non-lockout, 82-game regular season to take one more shot at a
championship?
</P>
<P>
   They are the questions that led John Elway to walk away from the
Broncos, and they are legitimate. But it says here that Barkley
will ultimately make a different decision than Elway for two
reasons:
</P>
<P>
   Despite his protestations, he desperately wants a title to cap
off his Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   He, as much as anyone, influenced Scottie Pippen to sign with
the Rockets and will not walk out on him after just one abbreviated
season, Pippen's own finger-pointing playoff betrayal
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you give him the $14 million that is allowable under terms
of the new collective bargaining agreement. Because those same
rules prohibit you from offering that money to another free agent
and also because he was the Rockets' best player this season. By
far.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, it might have been hitting bottom in Games 1
and 2 that finally flipped the switch in Pippen's confused mind
about his role. Even while struggling with his shot once more in
Game 4, he was the active, aggressive force the Rockets need him to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in order for Pippen to expand his game and thrive
next season, there will have to be adjustments made in the offense,
mainly in shifting the primary focus away from a double low post
with Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident from his play against the Lakers that Olajuwon
would be the first to welcome such a change. The torch as the
game's most dominating center wasn't passed, but snatched away by
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon cannot win a toe-to-toe inside battle with Shaq, who
has not been given enough credit for working hard to expand and
improve his game. And there are other younger big men _ Tim Duncan,
Alonzo Mourning _ who can beat him down low. But Olajuwon, who says
he wants to play just two more years, is no worse than the
fourth-best center in the league and still possesses enough skills
to be effective. Rudy Tomjanovich must utilize him facing up to the
basket, shooting jumpers from near the free-throw line or along the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff has to find a way to mine the extraordinary
physical gifts of Michael Dickerson on a consistent basis. He has
all the skills of a young Clyde Drexler. The question is whether he
has Drexler's drive not only to play the game but to excel. In a
word, he is soft.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley has all the sharp, hard edges but not the
instincts of a point guard. That job should belong to Brent Price,
who has overcome so much and has the outside shooting skills.
</P>
<P>
   This is a franchise walking a tightrope between having an
outside chance and being over the hill. But that choice was made
when Pippen was signed. The intent was to take advantage of
Olajuwon's twilight years.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the Rockets must commit themselves to the regular
season and stop falling back on the crutch of the 1995 miracle run
from the No. 6 seed. They set themselves up as first-round fodder
when they couldn't finish the job this year, failing to overtake
the Spurs for the No. 3 spot and then losing to Dallas (twice) and
the Clippers to give the Lakers the No. 4 seed and home-court
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, when San Antonio beat Utah in the 1996 playoffs,
people said that was the end for the Malone-Stockton regime. Now
here's the Jazz, taking a run at a third straight trip to the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not too late for these Rockets. If they're now
willing to do the real work.
</P>
</TEXT>
