<HEADER>
A9566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUATEMALA-VOTE-1STLD-     05-17 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUATEMALANS DENY CHANGES FOR INDIANS AND THE ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By MIEREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMALTENANGO, Guatemala _ Guatemalans on Sunday appeared to
have voted down constitutional changes to recognize officially for
the first time the rights of the country's Mayan majority, a
rejection that supporters of the measures said would set back
efforts to consolidate peace after a 36-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Electoral officials said on Sunday night that turnout for the
referendum was extremely poor, about 21 percent of Guatemala's 4
million registered voters, because of Guatemala's high illiteracy
rate and the scarce effort to inform residents about the proposals.
But preliminary results for Guatemala City, where nearly half of
all eligible voters reside, indicated a vote of 77 percent to 23
percent against 50 amendments to the Guatemala constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where the indigenous majority has faced genocide
and poverty and long been excluded from power, the reforms would
have declared Guatemala ``multiethnic'' and for the first time
granted equal status to the languages, religions and customary laws
of the Mayan peoples, who account for about 60 percent of the
population. The proposals would have also reined in the role of the
military and overhauled the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   The vote posed what President Alvaro Arzu Irigoyen had called
``a decisive test'' in Guatemala's willingness to build a more just
society after decades of war between the government and leftist
guerrillas that killed about 200,000 people. The proposals also
would have made the first tangible changes in the army and the
government called for by peace accords signed in 1996 and that
supporters consider crucial to the country's lasting transformation
to an inclusive, democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the reforms, including business people, politicians
and intellectuals, said they mainly objected to the decision by the
Guatemalan Congress, which devised the measures, to divide a wide
range of amendments among four ballots and make voters decide on
blocks of changes rather than each one individually. But the
opposition also underscored deep racial divisions, with many
warning of the danger of ``Balkanizing'' the country by granting
legal privileges to some ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can bring about another war,'' said Roberto Orozco, 50, a
businessman in the department of Sacatepequez, east of here, who
said he voted against all 50 changes. ``We're going to turn into
Kosovo, with each tribe taking up arms to go to war.''
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats and U.N. officials monitoring the peace
process here had said a ``no'' vote would set back the political
momentum for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote would tell us how many people support the broad
mandate of democratization,'' Jean Arnault, the U.N. special
representative here, said during an interview a few days ago. ``I
can't say the referendum speaks for the people as a whole, but it
represents the views of those prepared to be politically active at
this stage. It will mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendments, however, also counted on the
support of the leadership of of major political parties, including
the ruling National Advancement Party, known as PAN. Oscar Berger,
Guatemala City's mayor and a presidential candidate for PAN in this
November's elections, said in an interview that, if elected, he
would find other ``mechanisms'' to pass the reforms required by the
peace agreements, such as a constitutional assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments would restrict the army to territorial defense
and end its control of internal security, a role that has led to
scores of political killings and human rights abuses. The
Presidential General Staff, the military unit found to have engaged
in many abuses, would be replaced by civilians. The post of defense
minister could then also be filled by a civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Other important changes aim to increase checks on the executive
branch and reform the judicial system, which has routinely allowed
much crime to go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wide range of the proposals, public debate before
the vote focused almost exclusively on the handful of amendments
that recognize the rights of Guatemala's indigenous peoples.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, they have been excluded from government and
relegated to alarming rates of poverty and illiteracy in a country
where wealth and power have been dominated by the Ladinos, the
mostly white and mestizo minority.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment would define this country of 11 million as
``multiethnic, multicultural, multilingual,'' specifically
acknowledging not only the Mayan majority but also minorities like
the Garifunas, descendants of Caribbean blacks, and the Xinca, a
nearly extinct indigenous group.
</P>
<P>
   Another would grant official status to 24 indigenous languages,
a change whose effect in making education, health care and other
public services available in languages other than Spanish will
depend largely on bringing indigenous people into civil service
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms would boost a Mayan movement that has become more
united and organized over the last decade, bringing together
hundreds of groups despite language and other differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
