<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9591 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-GIANTS-HNS     05-17 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
There was no second-guessing by the Astros on Sunday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker made the call.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio put down the bunt.
</P>
<P>
   And the San Francisco Giants snapped the Astros' season-high
five-game winning streak with a 5-4, 11-inning victory before a
turn-back-the-clock crowd of 29,671 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the top of the 11th, Armando Rios delivered the
decisive run with a pinch-hit solo homer off Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers led off the bottom of the 11th with a walk off
rookie Joe Nathan, bringing Biggio to the plate. Instead of
allowing Biggio, who rarely hits into a double play, to swing away,
Dierker called for a bunt.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Scouting reports indicated Giants rookie reliever
Joe Nathan had a quick delivery to the plate, which would make
attempting a steal difficult for Spiers or, if he reached on a
fielder's choice, Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have jobs to do. We're not here to question
(decisions),'' said Biggio, who in his previous at-bat had
delivered a game-tying two-run double. ``That's the way he wanted
to play it, so I did what I was told.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell followed with a groundout to shortstop, and Nathan, a
fireballing rookie, struck out Jeff Bagwell with Spiers at third
base for his first career save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could bunt or not bunt,'' Dierker said. ``The (scouting)
report was he was quick to the plate, and it wouldn't have been
easy to steal. I figured we could get the man in scoring
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton (2-1) allowed one run and two hits in one inning. Rios'
homer off him was the rookie's third in 14 career pinch-hit
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Elarton before in the minors,'' Rios said. ``He
worked me away to start and then came back with a cutter. It had
movement, and that's what I was hoping for.''
</P>
<P>
   Robb Nen (1-1) pitched 2 scoreless innings, allowing one hit
while striking out two.
</P>
<P>
   Nen did, however, blow a save opportunity. The Astros trailed
4-2 in the eighth before Biggio tied the game with his two-out,
two-run double off the left-field wall vs. Nen.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo led off the inning with a double, and Giants
reliever John Johnstone then walked Tony Eusebio. Russ Johnson laid
down a sacrifice before reliever Rich Rodriguez struck out Spiers.
Biggio followed with a shot that was so close to being a home run
that the fireworks at the Astrodome went off prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it pretty good,'' Biggio said. ``That wall helps our
pitching staff, and it sometimes hurts us. Tonight it hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, whose shooting-star uniforms were replicas of those
worn by the team in its first Astrodome season of 1965, concluded
their nine-game homestand 6-3. They batted .314 (102-for-325) over
the nine games and outscored the opposition 64-34.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good homestand, but I don't think anybody is thinking
about that after losing (tonight),'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants took a 3-1 led in the sixth on a two-run homer by
Rich Aurilia, his sixth of the season, off Astros starter Sean
Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sliced the deficit to 3-2 in the sixth on Eusebio's
two-out RBI single to center field, but the Giants went back in
front by two runs on Brent Mayne's run-scoring single in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio and Carl Everett accounted for four of the Astros' nine
hits in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman allowed four earned runs and eight hits over six-plus
innings. At one point, he retired 12 straight batters and limited
the Giants to two hits through five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Russ Ortiz held the National League's top-hitting
team to seven hits and two runs over 6 innings. He has not allowed
more than three earned runs in any of his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros wasted a golden opportunity to put some runs on the
scoreboard when they left the bases loaded in the seventh. Spiers
walked to lead off the inning, stole second and advanced to third
on a wild throw by catcher Mayne. One out later, Derek Bell walked
to put runners at the corners. Johnstone relieved Ortiz and hit
Bagwell on the left hand to load the bases. But the Astros failed
to come up with a timely hit as Ken Caminiti struck out and Everett
flied out to left field to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros stranded 11 runners, giving them 290 for the season,
fourth-highest in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so many chances,'' Dierker lamented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
