<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX     05-17 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Gingrich's drivel resurfaces
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is scarier than Newt Gingrich in office? Newt Gingrich out
of office.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich had been little heard from since the bollixed
Republican congressional campaign last fall chased him from the
House and its speakership, but he came roaring back last week in
Washington, with a speech that was red meat to the lionesses of the
Republican Women Leaders Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich says he had to choose between work as House CEO or as a
visionary and picked visionary. Gingrich's visions remain pretty
much as they always have been _ of liberal academic, political and
media elites who menace the country like monsters from a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The Gingrich most voters learned to dislike as speaker was in
fact the cleaned-up version of the firebrand Gingrich of the
Republican far right. The speakership forced occasional moderation
on the temperamentally immoderate Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   With the wraps off again, Gingrich, who in the past blamed
Democrats for Susan Smith drowning her two little boys and for
Woody Allen running off with Soon-Yi, now blames the Columbine
school massacre on a ``35-year experiment in a unionized,
bureaucratic, credentialed, secular assault on the core values of
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazenly comparing himself to French writer Emile Zola, who
bravely accused his nation's powers of anti-Semitism in the
notorious Dreyfus case, Gingrich says he will henceforth similarly
challenge America's liberal elites.
</P>
<P>
   Unions and credentialed teachers, he says, ``have driven
knowledge out of the classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich just minutes later would sneer at Democrats as ``the
party of trial lawyers'' but first suggests liability litigation
could be used to force Hollywood to make only decent movies _
presumably as Newt Gingrich defines decent.
</P>
<P>
   Charging that ``as good liberals,'' President Clinton and Vice
President Gore ``don't believe in a strong America leading the
world,'' Gingrich, shockingly, wonders why the Joint Chiefs of
Staff haven't resigned over the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   What's new in the unleashed Gingrich is the degree to which he
is working the God hustle. In the past, Gingrich, not famously
devout, contented himself with the usual political pieties.
</P>
<P>
   Now he demands prayer in public classrooms, dares Gore to say
whether he wants ``God or psychobabble'' in the schools and says,
``God has been driven out of the classrooms. We see the result in a
secular, atheistic system in which God is not allowed to exist.''
(It must come as news to God that he's kaput.)
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich says (wrongly) that students are not being taught the
Declaration of Independence because (wrongly II) the word
``Creator'' is in it.
</P>
<P>
   All this in reference again to Columbine, though it is clear to
anyone who has been paying attention that Littletown is a
thoroughly churched town. Its students refer often and easily to
God, Jesus and faith. Gingrich seems to doubt their sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's political tent is very much open for business again,
and he's hammering home the ideological wedges that have always
been his tent stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
