A9793 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN18-COX     05-17 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fear of June brings May's gloom
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Parents and children have mirror-image
countdowns to school's end and summer's start.
</P>
<P>
   The period from the May 19 Star Wars National Holiday to the
last day of classes is, for students, the time of the Last Big Push
followed by steadily slower days of coasting.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, by contrast, coast along until the fear of summer
and the belief that everybody else has figured out summer for the
kids induce panic.
</P>
<P>
   These curves of anxiety intersect sometime around mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   A generalization, to be sure, but not an unreasonable one. Yes,
some schools provide meaningful and stimulating instruction to
motivated pupils until the last bell of the school year sounds.
Yes, some parents mail in summer camp deposits as soon as the
Thanksgiving turkey is cleared off the table and the last guest
heads for the door and has his concealed weapon returned.
</P>
<P>
   But more common is a feeling of stomach-gripping shock when you
lift the May calendar page and find nothing but June on the next
leaf. It seems a cruel prank.
</P>
<P>
   You haven't finished the year's second box of ice cream
sandwiches but somehow it's already summer.
</P>
<P>
   This is so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are parents alone in their surprise. Teachers rush to
shoehorn in the last few things before school ends. This is an
academic pattern I have experienced from kindergarten to graduate
school.
</P>
<P>
   History teachers gallop across centuries in these weeks. English
teachers will order a forced march of a final dozen writers and
avoid works too much longer than a haiku. Math teachers will
introduce the last few concepts as though they were familiar actors
bowing for a curtain call. Science teachers will allude darkly to
information contained in the clean, new-looking pages in the last
quarter of the textbook.
</P>
<P>
   Then the grades are compiled and videotapes and endless
discussion sessions are the rule for the final couple of weeks. The
concluding week is a mere cooling-off period and the school is one
big holding cell. During this time, little constructive work is
accomplished but students are held under close watch lest their
premature release imperils the natural order.
</P>
<P>
   And then it's summer and it's the parents' turn.
</P>
<P>
   Myself, I intend to give my children the full benefit of an
enriching summer experience. It will be a time of leisure
punctuated by the enrichment of new ideas and experiences. A time
when they retain what they learned in the past year, and move
forward to prepare for the next.
</P>
<P>
   And all I need to accomplish this is three months off from work
at extra pay and to find no more than a half dozen camps, classes
and special programs with reasonably priced yet exciting activities
that don't have waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I might just let them vegetate, sleep in,
graze out of the refrigerator, watch reruns of the Jerry Springer
Show, and listen to bad rock from bands that take their name from
loathsome diseases until I get home from work.
</P>
<P>
   They will lie about in August like lizards sunning themselves on
rocks, exerting themselves only to complain that ``there's nothing
to do.'' All abstract thought will dry out of their heads under the
beach's big sun.
</P>
<P>
   Which of these summers will it be? I can't wait to find out. I
do, however, have my suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are a summer people, deciding to become a country in
the middle of summer vacation. A time when the people charged with
running us probably were out of town and stunned to find out what
happened while they were away from the office.
</P>
<P>
   So we pay particular honor to the season and insist on the
shortest school year of any industrialized people on the planet.
And for large chunks of that time, most working families and single
parents have only a vague notion of what they're going to do with
the kids.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a fear of summer so paralyzing that I can't make
myself flip ahead in my organizer. Normally blank pages speak of a
life that's placid and under control. For the next few chapters in
this book, though, each blank page inspires a paralyzing fear of
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing it's not June yet.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
