<HEADER>
A9794 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAUER-COLUMBINE18-COX     05-17 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUER-COLUMBINE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A reporter remembers Columbine
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Rachel Sauer, along with Patrick Cleary and Chris
Barker, covered the Columbine High School shootings for The (Grand
Junction, Colo.) Daily Sentinel last month. They all said it was
the toughest story they have ever covered. What follows is Sauer's
recollections of that week in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ John Tomlin was one of the 12 students
murdered in the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School. His
name was released the Thursday after the shootings, so I looked up
his Littleton address in a phone book and drove to it unannounced,
and I cried the whole way there.
</P>
<P>
   When I got there, John's grandfather was standing in the
driveway smoking, so I approached him and he started talking about
his slain grandson and we stood together crying. Then he went
inside to ask if Michelle Oetter, John's girlfriend, would talk to
me and she agreed.
</P>
<P>
   She and I went to the cluttered basement and sat on the couch.
She told me good memories and funny stories about John, and pretty
soon Brandon Sokol, John's best friend, wandered down, and soon
after that John's brother and sister, Patrick and Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   We talked and laughed, and they climbed all over each other to
get to the punch line of certain John stories first.
</P>
<P>
   After we were done I walked upstairs to reassure Michelle's
mother I would write a good story and send her a copy after it ran.
When I got to the top of the stairs I saw John and Doreen Tomlin,
John's parents, standing still in an impossibly tight hug. Doreen
had her face buried on John's shoulder and they both cried the
enduring tears of parents who lose a 16-year-old son. They
whispered things to each other about John _ what a good son he was,
how much they loved him _ and told each other they were so, so
sorry.
</P>
<P>
   And I had no right to be there seeing that. And I knew I had a
closing for the story I would write about John, a few
heart-bruising paragraphs so readers could see how tremendous and
personal and unbearably sad this situation is.
</P>
<P>
   The whole week Chris Barker, Pat Cleary and I spent in Littleton
was like that: People sobbed and wilted and held on to each other,
and we took notes on how they looked, what color coats they wore,
how tightly they closed their eyes, what mementos they laid on the
memorials. If we were lucky, people laid open their hearts, talking
about sorrow and loss, anger and fear and 15 deaths, and we wrote
it into stories that went national.
</P>
<P>
   People pleaded for space, or time, or privacy, and we couldn't
give them much of any. We had deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   The response to what happened at Columbine High School _ one of
the worst school shootings in U.S. history _ was enormous. More
than 300 members of the media descended on Littleton from around
the world. Most were sympathetic and professional; some were a
disgrace. Tens of thousands came to Clement Park, most to mourn,
think and pray, some to grandstand and promote personal agendas.
</P>
<P>
   It was a challenge to sort through it all: The new information
being released hourly by beleaguered Jefferson County employees,
the throngs of reporters crowding around the compelling stories,
the heavy, wet snow that fell all week and turned Littleton into
mud, the waves of emotion that followed the first explosion and
gunshot.
</P>
<P>
   That probably presented the biggest challenge, seeing the
suffering, confusion and anger and asking ourselves where we
stopped being reporters with certain obligations to professionalism
and started being just people who didn't want to do this anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I never quite figured it out. I don't think Chris or Pat did,
either. One night Pat called his wife and three daughters while we
were at dinner and his oldest, Kieran, 7, asked him if the parents
of the kids who were killed got to hug their babies before they
died. Chris, who grew up in Denver, stayed with his mom and watched
her worry about her students at the Denver public school where she
teaches.
</P>
<P>
   We heard and saw things so sad our hearts wobbled and wavered
and broke a thousand times. One Columbine sophomore told me, in
explanation of kids made into outcasts, ``You have no idea how hard
it is to find a place to hide and eat lunch because you don't want
anyone to see you have nobody to sit with.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tomlin told me he missed his son.
</P>
<P>
   I hope I never hear things like that again, but I probably will
because tragedies happen and the media report them. That's how it
works. But if I have to report on another tragedy I hope it's
followed by the immeasurable sympathy, support and unity that
poured into Littleton from around the world. I hope I see that
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday after the shootings, I saw a note on one of the
growing Clement Park memorials that was written by Sam and Nick in
red crayon on yellow construction paper. With very young spelling
and just-learned-to-write letters they said they were sorry this
happened, sorry two big bullies did this. They told the killers
they could not believe it and reassured the parents of the victims
that their children are safe in heaven, and they ended with
``Sorry!''
</P>
<P>
   I thought Sam and Nick got it right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
