A9795 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN18-COX     05-17 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If you catch me being weird, don't worry _ that's my job
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The morning bell hasn't rung yet, so most of
my eighth-graders are hanging out in the hall catching up on the
latest gab. Bobby wanders in, pulls over a chair, and gets in my
face. ``Ms. Schuett,'' he begins as he eyeballs the graded essays
piled on one corner of my desk to see if he can catch a glimpse of
his latest contribution to the world of adolescent literature, ``I
don't mean to be rude or nothin'. ...'' I correct his double
negative and he begins again. ``OK. I don't mean to be rude or (SET
ITAL)anything(END ITAL), but you're weird.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what's your point?'' I ask, not looking up from the middle
desk drawer where I've initiated a last-ditch search for my
favorite red pen _ the one I've been warned not to use by education
experts because I'm liable to damage some adolescent psyches as I
point out grammar lapses and run-on sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write little notes in the margins with a blue or black pen,''
the simpering edu-guru tediously explained to a captive audience of
tired teachers one dismal afternoon. ``Only suggest where there
(SET ITAL)might(END ITAL) be a problem and the student will find it
and make the necessary repairs. Your youthful writers mustn't be
discouraged by ugly red marks on their work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman just got off the boat from Oz,'' I muttered to a
nearby colleague who was doing her best to catch 40 winks with both
eyes still open.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby gabs on as I dig. ``You write funny stuff on our papers.
It used to make some of us mad. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Angry,'' I correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's another thing _ you correct our grammar the whole time
we're in class, even while we're just talking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job,'' I remind him. ``That's why the Brinks truck
backs up here every other Friday _ to help me carry my big fat
paycheck (the one I get for picking on you) to the bank.'' Bobby
snickers and tells me I'm doing that weird thing again. I deny it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't even know when you're doing it. All the kids say
you're funny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny _ odd, or funny _ ha ha?'' Bobby says probably both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby,'' I begin as the pen search moves to another drawer,
``why are we having this conversation? Can't you see I'm really
busy here?'' He asks doing what. I tell him my red pen is gone. He
says it's up front, on the podium next to the stapler. I accuse him
of hiding it from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, you know when you'd holler,
`Bobby! Shut up and write!' I thought you were being rude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No you weren't. You were being weird.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you tell the difference?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you don't hate us.'' I ask him how he knows that and
he says it's just a kid thing. ``We can tell when a teacher hates
us, even if she's talking real sweet.'' He thinks for a moment
before he adds (with a sly grin), ``But
</P>
<P>
   you're still W-E-I-R-D.''
</P>
<P>
   I commend his spelling of a tricky word and reach for my morning
can of V-8. I ask him if he wants one. He grabs his nose between a
thumb and forefinger and makes gagging noises. I ask him if that's
a ``No, thank you'' and he says it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Bobby, are we over the `weird' conversation here?'' Bobby
turns to look at the clock over his shoulder, and says it's almost
time but he has to stay another two or three minutes. I ask why.
``Are we being timed? Am I a social studies assignment?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he giggles, ``I just needed a place to hang out until
the bell rings because if I go out in the hall, Teddy is going to
move my nose over to my left ear. He said so on the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have gone to the office with that,'' I tell him. He
shakes his head and says that's not a cool thing to do. I suggest
neither is having his nose rearranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be OK, Ms. Schuett,'' Bobby assures me. ``Teddy'll be
over it by lunch and I'll still be cool because I didn't tell on
him.'' I remind him he's telling me but he says that's OK. ``The
kids know you're weird _ and that's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   I slap Bobby on the shoulder and tell him thanks a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime,'' he grins.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio. E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
