<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN18-C     05-17 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer experts quiet the alarm bells
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine Paul Revere jumping down from his horse and
shouting, ``Never mind! The British aren't coming after all.''
</P>
<P>
   For many who have been following the computer software problem,
commonly called the Y2K bug, that is exactly what has happened this
spring. The ``Paul Revere'' of computer glitches _ consultant and
author Peter De Jager _ has dismounted and stopped sounding alarms.
He now believes enough progress has been made on fixing Y2K flaws
that earlier end-of-the-world predictions no longer make sense.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, De Jager has booked a flight to London on Dec. 31,
1999. When the date flips to 00:00, 01/01/00 Greenwich Mean Time,
he'll be toasting the New Year somewhere over the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   With seven months to go before the full brunt of the Y2K problem
is expected to hit, many software experts are joining De Jager in
saying that the worst-case scenarios, such as widespread power
outages and bank collapses, will not come true.
</P>
<P>
   So has the Y2K panic ended ever before it began? Can we throw
out the canned goods and dried soup mix and start planning a big
New Year's Eve bash? Maybe not. Despite his rising optimism, even
De Jager is not yet ready to proclaim the coast entirely clear.
Many small businesses and local governments have plenty of
headaches ahead. And even major corporations and the federal
government have a long way to go to be fully bug-free.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is a pervasive programming flaw that could cause many
computers to misread the date when the calendar changes to 2000.
That's because the original programs were designed to read only the
last two digits of a date, making 1999 read as 99. When 2000
arrives, older computers may read the date as 00 and interpret it
as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing the flaw is time-consuming, labor-intensive and
expensive. Virtually all Y2K experts agree that even under the
rosiest scenario, many small businesses and state and local
governments will have significant computer problems in January
because they lack the money to attack the problem this year. Larger
firms have been spending vast sums. For example, Merrill Lynch, the
brokerage and mutual fund company, said it is spending $425 million
on fixing date-sensitive computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K remediation effort began when De Jager published a
ground-breaking article called ``Doomsday 2000'' for Computer World
on Sept. 6, 1993. But this March on his Web site, De Jager
published a new article, ``Doomsday Avoided,'' saying ``we've
finally broken the back of the Y2K problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, just as computer experts are becoming less afraid,
new Paul Reveres are saddling up to different sound alarms. In a
speech in Chicago earlier this month, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said he fears the media and its coverage of Y2K: ``I know
the evening news is going to play it as though we are looking at an
asteroid which is about to hit us.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fears could prompt millions of people to take money out of
their bank accounts, touching off a crime wave as thieves try to
get the cash stashed in mattresses. ''The safest thing to do,'' he
said, ``is to keep your money in the bank'' where the federal
government insures it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9797 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN18-COX     05-17 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Rejoining workforce an adjustment for stay-at-home
moms
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ You can get into some pretty serious conversations
on the sidelines of kids' soccer games. Not long ago, a
stay-at-home mom who was thinking about re-entering the work force
asked me how I made the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you suddenly see yourself as a professional after
being at home for so long?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just bluff your way through it until it begins to feel
normal,'' I joked.
</P>
<P>
   Although there's some truth to that, it is a question worth
thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who spent years at home nursing, feeding, burping,
reading to, playing with and rearing our children made a conscious
choice _ if we had the good fortune to be able to choose at all.
And I will argue that nothing is more ``professional'' or profound
than raising the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   We do ourselves a grave injustice, then, when we underestimate
what we can bring to the ``professional'' world. Show me a woman
who can organize a PTA project or charity fund-raiser and I'll show
you a top-flight manager. Show me the woman who can mediate the
neighborhood children's after-school playtime free-for-all, and
I'll show you a crackerjack human resources director.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when we re-enter the work force, we encounter a major
paradigm shift. After spending years in our ``own space'' at home,
we suddenly find ourselves in a new space that isn't ours at all.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned to work last year, the first thing I did was
personalize my office. I brought in family pictures and plants. A
friend gave me was a beautiful stained-glass cross that I hung in
my office window. Whenever I felt like an stranger in a strange
land during those first weeks, I would look at that cross and
instantly feel reconnected and loved.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, you adjust. You find your own pace and rhythm. You
establish new rituals that seem insignificant but nevertheless are
comforting. You learn to tackle overwhelming projects ``one bite at
a time.'' You also learn when to spit it out and start all over.
And you learn that making a mistake isn't the worst thing that can
happen. You're not an unproven, immature kid anymore; you've
experienced real life and survived. With that comes confidence.
</P>
<P>
   As I was considering all these things, my friend asked me,
``What did you have to give up?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we do have to make tough choices. I'm not as intimately
involved with my children's after-school hours as I used to be.
Given the mood they're usually in when they get home, that's not
necessarily a bad thing. Instead, we make more of an effort to
connect once I do get home.
</P>
<P>
   I've given up some of my volunteer activities. I'm not quite as
active in church work, although I still manage to teach a Sunday
school class each week.
</P>
<P>
   Although I've given up some things, I've gained others. I have
dusted off and put to use skills that had lain dormant for years,
and they came back in good stead. I have a new sense of
accomplishment and pride in what I do. I have broadened greatly my
circle of acquaintances, many of whom have become new friends.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the underlying question here is ``How hard is change?''
It's what we all fear to a certain extent _ leaving the known and
comfortable and jumping into the new and untested. We must put
ourselves to the test once again to see if we measure up.
</P>
<P>
   When I first started back to work, I bemoaned to my eldest son
that I was having to prove myself once again in midlife.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a major change of his own _ college _ he looked at me
with no small amount of exasperation and said, ``That's what life
is, Mom. Get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
