<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Site encourages kids to read
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If your child has not taken to reading with the same
enthusiasm and skill as he has taken to video games, there's a new
Web site that might help.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.bookadventure.com, is brought to you by the Sylvan
Learning Foundation, the same folks who developed Sylvan Learning
Systems, which operates about 750 learning centers.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site is part of a free reading program. Kids can set up
an account for use at home and at school. Kids create reading lists
from a collection of more than 3,000 titles and then log on to take
quizzes on what they've read.
</P>
<P>
   The site is aimed at elementary school students, who, in
general, are reading less and reading poorly.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Department of Education, three out of
every four fourth-graders read below their grade level. Some 60
percent of fourth-graders watch between three hours and six hours
of television each day, yet only 46 percent read daily, according
to the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   Registering at the site is simple. Just log on to
www.bookadventure.com, click on ``kids,'' then on ``school play''
and then on ``new user.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids are required to enter their first name and last initial, to
create an online name and a password, and to come up with a
question to which the password is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Parents have mixed feelings about kids exploring Internet
</P>
<P>
   Parents see the Internet as a way to help their kids. But they
also see it as a way their kids can be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   This push-pull appeal of a parent's view of the Internet is part
of a study on the Net and the American family. The study was
conducted by the Annenberg Public Policy Center of the University
of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the increasing number of PCs in homes and
their growing popularity comes despite the concerns of parents
about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns are similar to _ but not mirrors of _ concerns
voiced during the introduction of movies, television and cable
television, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Unique to the Web is its wide-open nature _ easy access to
sexuality, values that seem questionable to many families and
commercialism. And another difference is the Web's interactivity,
the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that 70 percent of parents with computers
in their homes see the Internet as a place for their kids to
discover fascinating, useful things, and 60 percent say kids
without access to it are at a disadvantage compared to kids with
it. But more than 75 percent of parents polled said they are
concerned their kids might give out personal information and view
sexually explicit images on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   About 32 percent of parents use software to filter what their
kids can see on the Internet, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The study divided parents into three types: online worriers,
disenchanteds and gung-hos. The gung-hos, the most positive group,
make up 39 percent of online parents.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the study found that parents' views of the
Internet are not influenced by their access to it.
</P>
<P>
   Parents with home computers without Internet access fall into
groups that are similar to the online parents' groups.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the level of income and education do not indicate whether
a parent is likely to have Internet access, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The most important predictor of a parent's tendency to have
Internet access at home is the parent's experience with the
Internet outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released earlier this month, included interviews with
1,102 parents in homes with at least one working computer and at
least one child between ages 8 and 17. The interviews were
conducted in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   The entire study can be read online at www.appcpenn.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
