<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The downside of e-commerce
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The force was not with me. I simply cannot believe the
Internet let me down.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, by the time you read this, I will have some tickets
to see ``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have taken me 34 weeks to see the first ``Star Wars''
movie (and I know it was 34 weeks because the marquee on the
theater read ``It's STILL Here! Star Wars 34th Week!''), but I was
pretty naive then and thought that ``Star Wars'' was just some
dorky space movie watched endlessly weekend after weekend by the
dorky boys in my earth science class.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now I know better. I realize that ``Star Wars'' is an
artistic and cultural phenomenon, a 20th century landmark,
something that has shaped the lives and values of millions of
people all over the world. I mean if Entertainment Weekly says so,
then it must be true, right?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so while my friends were busy programming the number of the
local megaplex on their speed dials and zipping out of work late
Wednesday afternoon to try to snag tickets in person, I just sat at
my desk, working away.
</P>
<P>
   I was so smug. I was going to buy my tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fools,'' I thought to myself. ``Using phones, standing
in line, how quaint, how 20th century can you possibly be?'' You
can just log on the Web, type in MovieFone.com, click on ``Star
Wars,'' and voila! _ instant tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Around 4:30 p.m., I finally got around to logging on to
MovieFone to order my tickets. I got into the MovieFone Web site,
clicked on the ``Star Wars'' logo and waited. I waited some more. I
stared at the little hourglass. Then it happened.
</P>
<P>
   That horrid little gray box popped up. ``There was no response.
The server could be down or not responding,'' it said. What do you
mean ``not responding''? How dare you not respond! I tried again.
And again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   I could not log on to the MovieFone Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, so many people flooded the MovieFone Web site
in search of ``Star Wars'' tickets that it practically shut the
online ticketing service down. A MovieFone spokeswoman insisted
that everything was going along beautifully. ``Thousands of
transactions are being conducted every minute,'' she told The
Associated Press. ``But people are getting through, and we are
processing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her advice to those of us who are not getting in? ``Keep
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, keep trying. Who knew my browser's ``reload button''
would become the online equivalent to my telephone's redial button,
and in a situation like this, about as useful.
</P>
<P>
   Major news Web sites, like CNN, MSNBC and ABCNews.com, know to
clear the decks for breaking news events. Experience has shown them
that thousands of people will all be storming online at once. They
strip down their pages to the least number of images possible, so
the pages will load quickly and make a number of internal
adjustments so every user who wants to access the pages will be
able to.
</P>
<P>
   Now, MovieFone is not just a Web site. It's a Web site whose
primary business is selling movie tickets. If you have never
visited the site, it's filled with lots of bright graphics, images
and text. It has a funky style that suits a site that's all about
movies and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's an accident waiting to happen, if half the online
population suddenly decides to order tickets all at once on the
same day. It's not as if MovieFone didn't have any advance warning
to prepare for that fateful Wednesday. It knew when the tickets
were going on sale. They should have known that a science fiction
movie like ``Star Wars'' would likely have a disproportionate
number of computer-literate fans who would most likely take to the
Net to order tickets. For first-time users, the MovieFone
experience was probably unpleasant enough to put people off on
using MovieFone ever again.
</P>
<P>
   So many Web sites seem to be caught unawares in recent days,
whether it's Amazon.com underestimating demand for books or
MovieFone unable to cope with the ``Star Wars'' onslaught. Charles
Brewer, who runs the Internet service provider MindSpring, often
says the Internet will be the prime telecommunications service of
the future. I would like to suggest that maybe we're halfway there
today.
</P>
<P>
   News outlets already know how many people look to the Web for
quick information. Why can't online retailers and merchants
understand that a significant number of people look to the Web to
buy things, like movie tickets or other specific items, quickly?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I am consoled by a poll in the ``Star Wars'' section
of Snap.com, which says 45 percent of the people surveyed wouldn't
even dream of waiting in line to see ``The Phantom Menace'' on
opening weekend. There are also plenty of sites with movie reviews,
articles and, of course, official merchandise to keep me going
until I do get some tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it took me 34 weeks to see it the first time. With a little
willpower, I can probably wait that long the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
