<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady visits refugees
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton visited with Kosovar
refugees in Macedonia last week.
</P>
<P>
   She told them the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, or NATO,
allies will help them return home to Kosovo, a region of
Yugoslavia. She stressed the United States would not abandon the
780,000 refugees who were driven from their homes by the Serb amy.
(Serbs run the Yugoslavian government.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO bombing pounded the country's three largest
cities. The bombs knocked out electricity and destroyed supplies
hidden in tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Beloved author dies
</P>
<P>
   Readers around the world were saddened last week by the death of
author Shel Silverstein. He wrote such children's favorites as ``A
Light in the Attic'' and ``Where the Sidewalk Ends.''
</P>
<P>
   He was 67 when he died of a heart attack in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Kids loved Silverstein's poems, which he illustrated with
pictures of characters like walruses with braces. Silverstein also
wrote songs and plays. Here's an example of one of his poems titled
``Listen to the Mustn'ts''.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the MUSTN'TS, child,
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the DON'TS
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the SHOULDN'TS
</P>
<P>
   The IMPOSSIBLES and WON'TS
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the NEVER HAVES
</P>
<P>
   Then listen close to me _
</P>
<P>
   Anything can happen, child,
</P>
<P>
   ANYTHING can be.
</P>
<P>
   Bank uses eye-scan to ID customers
</P>
<P>
   A Texas bank is competing with Austin Powers and James Bond for
the coolest gadget. The Bank United of Texas in Houston has placed
an eye scanner on its ATMs to identify its customers. The scanner
examines the iris and compares it to a photo in its database.
</P>
<P>
   A person's iris is even more distinct than his fingerprint. It
contain 266 measurable characteristics, while a fingerprint
contains about 35. It can even tell the difference between
identical twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a very high cool factor,'' said Ron Coben, a bank
official. ``We think of it as James Bond-meets-stocks-and-bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
