<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mercedes S-Class gets an update, still epitomizes luxury
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If having it all is what a true premium luxury car is
really all about, then Mercedes-Benz's S-Class may be on a page by
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The totally new body design 2000 S-Class boasts one of the most
extensive lists of safety, performance, comfort and convenience
features.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the S-Class has been perceived as a very
``masculine'' automobile: heavy, cosmetically conservative and
physically bulky. The new S-Class offers an attractive package that
has trimmed 500 pounds. This results in the S-Class being slightly
shorter, lower and narrower than its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of all it has lost, the new S-Class has gained in other
areas, including interior space.
</P>
<P>
   The old S-Class has long been recognized as one of the few
vehicles that can accommodate a wedding dress. The lighter, slimmer
2000 S-Class actually provides increased rear legroom. Six-footers
will be able to cross their legs in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, all S-Classes will be powered by V-8
engines. The S430 will feature a 275-horsepower 4.3-liter, while
the S500 gets a 302-hp 5.0-liter version. Both will be linked to a
five-speed, driver-adaptive automatic transmission equipped with
TouchShift that allows the driver to manually control upshifts and
downshifts.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry is aware that safety features have become a
major factor in the purchase process.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dual front air bags and the standard four
door-mounted air bags, the S-Class adds a side-curtain-type air bag
that _ working in conjunction with the door-mounted bags _ is
capable of reducing upper body injuries by as much as 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Petite drivers and those with adolescent children will
appreciate that the front air bags incorporate smart-air-bag
technology. This means the bag inflates according to the severity
of the collision.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Class also uses sensors to determine if someone is seated
in each particular seat and deploys the air bags only if it is
occupied. That can result in major savings in the cost of accident
repair.
</P>
<P>
   Included is a console-mounted navigational and information
screen that can tell you just about everything except what to cook
for dinner. Every U.S. market S-Class comes standard with the
Global Positioning Satellitenavigational system. You'll never have
to ask directions again.
</P>
<P>
   Working in conjunction with the cell phone, the system has the
ability to send for emergency help when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical problems? The Protection One Operations center will
dispatch the necessary help. A life-threatening emergency? Just
depress the S-Class' rearview-mirror-mounted SOS button, and the
center will call for emergency care. In the event of an accident
that deploys the front air bags, the S-Class' systems
(navigational, GPS and cell phone hookup) work in concert to
request emergency help to the specific location.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it has all the expected goodies such as a Bose
stereo, voice-activated phone system that actually understands
dialects and accents, anti-lock brakes, traction and stability
control, leather interior, steering-wheel-mounted audio controls,
14-way powered adjustable front seats, integrated garage door
opener, and power windows.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about the new 2000 S-Class is driving it. It
rides like a luxury car, handles like a sports sedan and feels like
wearing a new Armani or Versace outfit to your most important gala.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
