<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wired schools get graded by FamilyPC
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How wired is your school? Now you can compare, using
the latest issue of FamilyPC magazine. The May issue includes a
list of what the magazine considers the top 100 wired high schools.
Among those that qualified were Armada Senior High School in the
town of the same name in Michigan. Others were Hunterdon Regional
High School in Fleming, N.J., Ketchikan High School in the Alaskan
town of the same name and Mashpee High School in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The same issue of FamilyPC takes a look at what, if any, role
the Internet played in the tragedy in Littleton, Colo. It offers a
package of articles examining the Internet, violent software and
the effectiveness of programs that filter Net content. Not
surprisingly, the magazine concludes that it's hard, if not
impossible, to understand whether the Internet played a decisive
role in the school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   The school year is ending, but that doesn't mean your kids have
to stop learning. Microsoft has released a collection of
educational software for elementary school kids. The package of
computer CDs is called ``My Personal Tutor: Grades 1st and 2nd.''
The software offers educational games designed to help kids sharpen
their math, reading and thinking skills. Its available only for
Windows PCs and workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Graphic artists, take note. Deneba Software in Miami has
released the latest version of its graphic design program Canvas 6.
This version blends illustration, photo editing and typography into
one package. The program also includes 30,000 clip art images and
2,450 fonts. Available for both Macs and PCs, Canvas 6 retails for
$375. Upgrading an earlier version costs $200.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Workshop, producer of ``Sesame Street'' and other
popular kids' shows, has created a Web site designed for mothers
with babies and toddlers. The site provides advice on caring for
young kids and keeping them busy in healthy ways. It also offers
scads of other links to useful sites. You'll find this site, called
Baby Workshop, at www.ctw.org/babyworkshop/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
