<P>
   SAUER-COLUMBINE _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Rachel Sauer, along
with Patrick Cleary and Chris Barker, covered the Columbine High
School shootings for The (Grand Junction, Colo.) Daily Sentinel
last month. They all said it was the toughest story they have ever
covered. Sauer's recollections of that week in Littleton. (Sauer,
Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. This week: Imagine Paul Revere
jumping down from his horse and shouting, ``Never mind! The British
aren't coming after all.'' For many who have been following the
computer software problem, commonly called the Y2K bug, that is
exactly what has happened this spring. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ The students say I'm weird, but really I'm just
doing my job. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Re-adjusting to the work place can
be a challenge for moms. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Parents and children have
mirror-image countdowns to school's end and summer's start. The
period from the May 19 Star Wars National Holiday to the last day
of classes is, for students, the time of the Last Big Push followed
by steadily slower days of coasting. The parents, by contrast,
coast along until the fear of summer and the belief that everybody
else has figured out summer for the kids induce panic. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
