<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: My girlfriend wants to know what the alcohol content of fully
cooked frijoles borrachos is. _ Norman H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Most recipes for beer beans call for the beer to be added at
the beginning of the process. Beans come to a boil, then cook for
several hours. By then, says Travis County Extension Service's
Ramona Kellam, alcohol boils and dissipates in the steam. You do
not need to worry about the alcohol content of these flavorful
pinto beans. Q: I am unable to afford high prices for a lawyer. Can
I write my own will? Does it have to be notarized? What does a
lawyer charge? _Billy R. A: Properly dated holographic wills _
written entirely by the person whose will it is _ in Texas do not
require witnesses. Other wills must be properly executed, witnessed
and signed by two people in the presence of the person whose will
it is, says attorney Sara Atkins of Saunders &AMP; Norval, LLP. When
writing your will, be as specific as possible and remember most
wills are probated, so appoint an independent executor to serve
without bond. There are many ways to cause problems for heirs. Why
not spend a few hundred dollars up front to make sure the will is
properly drawn?
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter teaches third grade and they are struggling with
learning the 50 states. She remembers a song from her school days
named ``Fifty Nifty United States,'' but she doesn't remember all
of the words. Could you help us locate it? _ D.V. Parsons
</P>
<P>
   A: This catchy ditty was written and arranged by Ray Charles, no
less. The song is a great teaching tool: ``Shout 'em, scout 'em,
Tell all about 'em. One by one 'til we've given a day, To ev'ry
state in the USA ...''
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of the choral music ($1.50), contact Shawnee Press at
(800) 962-8584.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I attempted to park at a parking meter located in front
of a popular Austin restaurant, I was told to move by the
restaurant's valet parking service. The service said they had
exclusive rights to the spaces. How can a private company have the
right to run me off from a space paid for with my tax dollars? I've
also noticed that these same valets will double-park cars on the
streets in front of the restaurants, causing traffic jams. Where is
the Austin Police Department? _ R. Walker
</P>
<P>
   A: Show them this column. The company does not have a right to
metered spaces. Even a sign indicating a passenger loading zone
means everyone _ valets and customers alike _ may use the space.
Alan Hughes, city traffic engineer, says we do not have valet
parking zones. Both valet parking services I quizzed (VIP Valet
Parking and Valet Parking Service Inc. of Texas) do not allow
valets to shoo away anyone from metered spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Should double-parked cars cause a problem, call 911 to have an
officer dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have accidentally spilled some brown hair dye, Just for
Men, on almond-colored painted wood and a dark blue carpet. I have
not been able to clean off the stains using ordinary cleansers. I
am considering bleach or paint thinner, but I want to avoid harming
the painted surfaces and bleaching the carpet. I would rather not
have to repaint. _ J.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Oops. This is a dye, so whatever is tried may only have
marginal success. Combe Inc., makers of Just for Men, predicts you
will have to repaint the wood. Try the paint thinner _ you have
nothing to lose. The carpet may be saved by using a half
ammonia-half water solution on the stain. (Try it on an unobtrusive
spot first to test for colorfastness). Others report success with
Resolve carpet cleaner. Need more from Combe? Call (800) 431-2610.
Some men use this line to order the product directly rather than
face the prospect of a public purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in knowing when you may use ``Junior'' after
a name. How can you use the ``II''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ruth Maxfield
</P>
<P>
   A: Follow closely _ these are murky waters, says David A. Baskin
of the Texas State Library and Archives. Junior always denotes
descent. A man can call himself Jr. when he has exactly the same
name as a living father _ or grandfather, if the father has died.
When the father or grandfather dies, the Jr. is dropped. When a
grandson bears the Junior appellation, any of his younger cousins
with the same name uses II. There may be more than one II in the
same generation. By the way, when someone is named for his uncle,
he is II and never Jr. With me? Someone who shares a name with both
his living father and grandfather is called III. When the
grandfather dies, he becomes Jr. Q: Who can change the foot pedals
to hand controls on the dash of a car? I am going to have an
amputation soon but still need to be able to drive a car a while
longer. I am on Medicaid. I have heard they can handle that, but
whom do I ask to make sure? _ E. Smith
</P>
<P>
   A: The conversion can be done locally by outfits such as Para
Driving Aids (385-0808). A set of hand controls runs about $545 _
less if you elect to have portable controls, which require more
strength. Unfortunately, Nancy Nichols of the Texas Department of
Health says this expense is not a federally allowable benefit of
Medicaid. For more information on Medicaid call (800) 252-8263.
Details on recovery programs are available from the Texas
Rehabilitation Commission inquiry line at 424-4060. Q: I bought a
letter signed by Joan Fontaine and I would like to know where to
request a picture. _ Joe V.
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact the star of Hitchcock's ``Suspicion'' and, my
favorite, ``Jane Eyre'' in care of Gage Group, 9255 Sunset Blvd.,
515, Los Angeles 90069. Born Joan de Beauvoir de Havilland, young
Joan took the name Fontaine on the advice of a fortune teller. Q:
My best friend and I disagree on something and I told her you would
know the answer. I was recently invited to a bridal shower and
wedding. I purchased a gift for both occasions. My friend said if
you buy a shower gift you are not expected to buy a wedding gift.
What is proper etiquette? A lunch may ride on the answer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teresa Adams
</P>
<P>
   A: Get ready for a free lunch. Two events, two gifts. The
wedding gift is your main offering to the couple. The shower gift
may be just a token _ a framed photo of you and the bride, for
example. Brides and grooms need to be mindful of how many
gift-giving opportunities (showers) there are and how often each
name appears on these lists. Q: I am looking for a product by
Oral-B called Interdental Woodsticks. They are like toothpicks but
work better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Helen Reed
</P>
<P>
   A: This round-ended device is used in addition to flossing. Pick
up a package of 100 at Wal-Mart or Kmart or order by calling (800)
765-2959.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some readers find powdered ginger capsules prevent motion
sickness. They take these over-the-counter capsules, found in the
vitamin section, and say their world is a little more stable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anniversary lovers will enjoy these terms from the Suburban
Library System: 10 years, decennial; 15, quindecennial; 20,
virgintennial (proposed); 30, trigentennial; 40, quadragennial; 50,
jubilee or quinquagenary; and (should it come to this) 15,000
years, quindecimillenial.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
