<HEADER>
A9822 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE18-COX     05-17 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online TV listings go far beyond daily schedules
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once upon a time, it was considered a technology that
had the potential to tear apart the American home.
</P>
<P>
   Parents worried that kids would get the wrong ideas from it.
Some people spent way too much time using it and _ in the process _
lost opportunities to take part in real life. Some experts wrote
long articles praising it, saying that the technology would change
education and bring arts to the masses. Others said it was the tool
of the devil.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about television. Long before there was an
Internet, many of the same fears and hopes were fanned by the other
box that invaded the home. Obviously, these two technologies have a
lot more in common than their flickering monitors. So it's only
fitting that we spend today talking about how to use the Net to
make TV watching more fun and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   At the most basic level of the marriage between PC and Web,
there are the online listings for programming. Several sites offer
listings, but one of the best comes from the folks at Yahoo! You'll
find the listing at tv.yahoo.com/yahoo/moretopics.dpg.
</P>
<P>
   It's a well-designed service. On that page, you'll find about 30
topic areas, including romance, science-fiction, adventure, comedy,
religion and movies. To show you how the listings work, click on
``movies'' and see what happens. You're zapped to a page that looks
very much like a newspaper listing of TV movies. It automatically
pops on the screen for today's date, but you can use pull-down
menus to change the date or the way the information is presented.
Once you have set up the page to suit your taste, you can browse
the movies on tap for that day from AMC, TBS, TNT or any of the
networks or programming services that offer movies.
</P>
<P>
   If you find a movie you like, you can click on the title and get
a mini-review. You'll also find links on this page that will take
you to listings for the major satellite TV services including USSB
and DirecTV.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, however, that you want your TV listings served up
according to where you live and the cable TV provider that serves
that area. Simply stick with Yahoo! but go to tv.yahoo.com/. Enter
your ZIP code and you'll get the listings (if there is more than
one provider serving your area, you'll get a pull-down menu that
lets you pick the cable company).
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of giving too much space to Yahoo!, let's take a
look at one other service provided by the search engine: a soap
opera update that you'll find at tv.yahoo.com/soaps/soap.dpg?d
</P>
<P>
   &QC; 1&AMP;wk &QC; 1. If, for instance, you forgot to tape last week's ``The
Bold and the Beautiful,'' you can simply click on the listing for
that soap opera to get the latest details. This is detailed, if
drably written, stuff. For instance, a recent summary explained:
``Rick tells himself over and over again that he is married to
Amber and they have a son. Brooke confronts Amber and her mother
and boasts that she knows the terrible secret about the baby and
why Amber couldn't give birth with anyone around.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the idea that Yahoo! is the only place to get TV
listing information. Here's a page with links to almost any TV
listing service you can name: www
</P>
<P>
   .buttle.com/tv/schedule.htm. And, since it offers worldwide
television listings, you may enjoy browsing the listing services
for South American and European networks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
