<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NEWSPAPER-BOS &LR;      05-17 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NEWSPAPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER HELPS KOSOVARS ADJUST TO REFUGEE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOULA VLAHOU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TETOVO, Macedonia _ In a dingy office at the foot of still
snow-capped mountains, Baton Haxhiu has revived a dream that seemed
a casualty of Slobodan Milosevic's repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In exile, Baton, as everyone calls him here, has re-created the
irreverent and militant newspaper that published in the Kosovar
capital, Pristina, until Yugoslav forces began expelling hundreds
of thousands of ethnic Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   With financial backing from the British Foreign Office, donated
office space, and 12 journalists, the 16-page Koha Ditore (Daily
Times) covers Kosovo-related news from many sides of the conflict.
The newspaper is distributed for free in the nine refugee camps in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the newspaper to be a bridge between the people here
and those in Kosovo,'' said Baton, 33, lanky with a red beard and
darting green eyes. NATO had mistakenly reported him killed near
the start of the 54-day air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The vacuum in the political leadership for the ethnic Albanians
``was the motive to restart Koha Ditore,'' he said. The newspaper
in exile published its first edition April 26 with the headline,
``KOSOVO MUST BE THE WINNER IN THIS WAR.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping ethnic Albanians informed, he said, will help to calm
Macedonia, where tensions have exploded several times not only over
the influx of refugees but because of opposition to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   There is probably no better place inside Macedonia to start his
project than Tetovo, a western region of the country where 47,000
Kosovar Albanians with contacts and money have found refuge. Unlike
their poorer cousins in the camps near the Macedonian capital of
Skopje, most refugees here are living with other ethnic Albanians,
who make up nearly 83 percent of Tetovo's 130,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Baton hid in nine basements in as many days before he escaped
from Kosovo into Macedonia. He left without his wife and 3
1/2-year-old son, but that is a sacrifice he says he made for
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Between bites of a chocolate-covered sundae in a restaurant
across the street from his office, Baton explains that his
newspaper is keeping the same iconoclastic tone it had in Pristina.
The paper challenges not only the Yugoslav regime but the policies
of pacifist Kosovar leader Ibrahim Rugova. It also takes aim at the
inexperienced political leadership of the Kosovo Liberation Army
guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
   These perceived leaders, he says, have ceased to exist in the
minds of most ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a morally bankrupt political structure,'' Baton said.
Rugova betrayed his people, Baton says, when he met Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president, last month. He should have refused, sacrificing
his personal needs for the greater good of Kosovo, Baton says. On
the other hand, the KLA's poorly planned tactics have failed to
protect the Kosovar Albanians, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of political leadership is creating confusion and
desperation among the refugees, who, in addition to a myriad of
worries, are torn between remaining until the end or leaving for
another country and effectively accepting Milosevic's ethnic
cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no political voice to tell these people that everyone
must make sacrifices for Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suffering seems more distant in this picturesque town than
in Kosovo or the camps. Many refugees in Tetovo, like Baton and his
journalists, sit in cafes sipping cappuccinos or eating ice cream.
They are middle-class professionals, affluent business owners and
intellectuals who had the means and the contacts to avoid the
camps. This picture of normalcy is an illusion made more profound
by people who feel too helpless to do anything but sit at cafes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going crazy,'' he said. ``Look at that young Kosovar
Albanian girl over there. She looks like she's on holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Impatient for a broadening of the NATO campaign, Baton says his
newspaper will stop publishing July 1 to protest the international
community's reluctance to send in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our paper helped the international community. We gave hope to
Albanians,'' said Baton. ``Now they must do something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
