<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     05-17 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL DAY OF PRAYER EVENTS EXCLUDE MORMONS AND MUSLIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 5, President Clinton issued a proclamation designating
May 6 as a National Day of Prayer. Governors of 48 states followed
with their own prayer day proclamations. Fortunately, few Americans
paid attention _ the government has no business poking its nose
into religion, or exhorting its citizens to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer day has been an annual event ever since Congress gave it
a seal of approval in 1952 and then the backing of law in 1988,
establishing the first Thursday of May as National Day of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Congress also passed a resolution in 1988 that
states: ``religion is most free when it is observed voluntarily at
private initiative, uncontaminated by government interference and
unconstrained by majority preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson, who wrote Virginia's Statute for Establishing
Religious Freedom, refused to issue prayer proclamations when he
became president because he believed to do so is unconstitutional
and that it would sow dissention among the citizens of the nation.
Jefferson wrote, ``every one must act according to the dictates of
his own reason, and mine tells me that civil powers alone have been
given to the president of the United States and no authority to
direct the religious exercises of his constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in his presidency, James Madison noted that the government
does not have the moral authority to ``speak to the faith and the
consciences of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable, then, with this tradition in Virginia,
that its governor refrained from issuing a proclamation declaring a
day of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura surprised many by also refusing to
sign a proclamation making May 6 a day of prayer. The Associated
Press quoted Ventura saying: ``I believe in the separation of
church and state. We all have our own religious beliefs. There are
people out there who are atheists, who don't believe at all.
...They are all citizens of Minnesota, and I have to respect
that.'' Ventura had an arm lock on the real issue and refused to
let go. And he is right.
</P>
<P>
   There are well over 100 religious groups in the United States
today represented by more than 300,000 churches. Religion thrives
in the United States precisely because of our freedom from
religious coercion.
</P>
<P>
   As the French social philosopher Alexis de Tocqueville pointed
out long ago in his book, ``Democracy in America,'' ``every man is
allowed freely to take that road he thinks will lead him to
heaven.'' We don't need government authority to point us to
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The founders, like Jefferson, Madison and James Mason, took
seriously the tenet that religious belief is a natural right
bestowed upon an individual's conscience and cannot and should not
be the subject of government interference.
</P>
<P>
   This year a group calling itself the National Day of Prayer Task
Force sent out a ``resource manual'' of instructions that states a
prayer day ``volunteer must be a Christian who has a personal
relationship with Christ.'' Further, the manual instructs that in
these prayer ceremonies: ``the only people who get to the
microphone are those we know have a personal relationship with
Christ.'' The manual also makes it clear that Mormons and Muslims
and other religious groups are not invited to these National Day of
Prayer ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the NDP Task Force manual could be confused
to be endorsed by the U.S. government. The group held a prayer
event in the U.S. House of Representatives' Cannon Office Building.
A number of elected and public officials attended. Mormons and
Muslims were excluded. By allowing a prayer ceremony that excludes
a large diversity of religious beliefs to be held in a federal
building, the House leadership has given such exclusion its
blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the NDP Task Force is affiliated with James Dobson of
Focus on the Family and other leaders of the Religious Right, like
Gary Bauer who is campaigning to be the Republican Party's
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   According to Americans United for Separation of Church and
State, a church-state watchdog group based in Washington, D.C., the
NDP Task Force scheduled its events at government buildings and
sought the ``endorsements and participation by governors, mayors
and other elected officials, thus giving the events the appearance
of official sponsorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Barry Lynn, Americans United executive director, concluded,
``Most Americans are sure to think this Christian prayer event is
sponsored by the government and that sends a negative, exclusionary
message to religious minorities who are being told they are not
welcome.`` Lynn urges Congress to repeal the National Day of
Prayer, so that religious leaders of all beliefs can set their own
special days of prayer _ without government meddling.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Walker, general counsel for the Baptist Joint Committee, a
coalition of Baptist organizations, said in an interview Friday,
``The National Day of Prayer has been used as part of the political
agenda of the far right.'' He stressed the point that Jefferson had
made long ago, ``Civil magistrates shouldn't be leading us to
national prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the Religious Right are using prayer day to
discriminate against religions that are in the minority in the
nation. They pretend to have the imprimatur of federal and state
governments. They sow the seeds of divisiveness that could fracture
our society along religious lines. They play a dangerous game.
</P>
<P>
   If you did not remember that May 6 was national prayer day,
suffer no guilt or regrets. Disregarding prayer day may be the best
way to ensure religious liberty in our nation and safeguard our
religious beliefs _ no matter how diverse they are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9872 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV23-NY     05-17 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 23)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every sailor enforcing a blockade knows the term of art for the
warlike act of stopping a ship suspected of carrying contraband:
 &UR; board and search &LR; . However, in cutting off the supply of oil to
Serbia, NATO's crack nomenclature specialists devised a more
blockade-runner friendly term so as not to offend vessels being
frisked. The new, sugarcoated pill of war:  &UR; search and visit &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   As Naval Reserve Officer Seth Cropsey pointed out in The
Washington Times,  &UR; board and search &LR;  ``is an invasive maneuver in
which an armed naval vessel trains its weapons on the merchant ship
and radios for it to stop and allow sailors to board to search. The
sailors make their way by small craft ... armed and loaded. It is
not a relaxing situation.'' But Cropsey notes that `` &UR; search and
visit &LR;  sounds like what most of us do when we are on vacation in an
unfamiliar place.''
</P>
<P>
   Every war develops its own set of terms. The leader of the enemy
requires consistent derogation. In the Persian Gulf war, Saddam
Hussein of Iraq was a  &UR; bloodthirsty dictator &LR;  and the  &UR; butcher of
Baghdad &LR; , similar to the  &UR; genocidal madman &LR;  often applied to Adolf
Hitler. Although many critics of Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia
called him a  &UR; war criminal &LR; , that term was unavailable to anyone in
officialdom, because it prejudged a potential prosecution and also
might make it awkward to negotiate with the one so called.
</P>
<P>
   The castigation of choice is  &UR; thug &LR; . In 1991, The Boston Herald
was first to refer to ``Slobodan Milosevic, the Stalinist  &UR; thug &LR; 
who rules Serbia.'' Three years later, Anthony Lewis in The New
York Times castigated ``aggression by a  &UR; thug &LR; , Slobodan
Milosevic.'' This year, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas joined many
other presidential candidates in using the phrase ``a  &UR; thug &LR;  like
Milosevic.'' In the Dow Jones database, the name of the Serb leader
and the word  &UR; thug &LR;  appear near each other 343 times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Thug &LR;  may be the earliest word of terrorism, perhaps predating
 &UR; assassin &LR; , a member of the hashish-smoking terror group that
struck at the Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindi  &UR; thag &LR;  is the root, meaning ``deceiver,'' from the
Sanskrit  &UR; sthaga &LR; , ``thief.'' The  &UR; Thugs &LR;  were an organization of
murderers and thieves in India who specialized in strangling
travelers. The purpose of strangulation was to preserve the
victim's blood, symbolically offered as a sacrifice to Kali, often
called the Hindu goddess of destruction and pictured as a
three-eyed deity smeared with blood and sporting a necklace of
severed heads. Many Hindus consider this grisly portrayal
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Thugs &LR; , its membership said to number 10,000 at its peak,
practiced their predatory system of  &UR; Thuggee &LR;  for at least six
centuries, killing more than a half-million people, making them
history's longest-lasting terror group. In 1833, the British
governor-general of India launched a campaign that captured 3,200
of the murderous cult's members, hanged several hundred and
effectively ended the terror.
</P>
<P>
   The historian Thomas Carlyle in 1839 was first to extend the
term beyond India by decrying ``the Glasgow  &UR; Thugs &LR; ,'' and he also
coined  &UR; thuggery &LR; . The adjective  &UR; thuggish &LR;  was not minted until
1953 by William Burroughs in his novel ``Junkie.'' The `` &UR; Thug &LR; 
Life'' was a best-selling 1994 album by the rap group of the same
name, whose young star, 2Pac, was gunned down in a gang killing two
years later. So much for the word  &UR; thug &LR; ; what about the word
 &UR; core &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   We've heard it a thousand times to define an international force
that would ensure the safety of the Kosovar homeless when they
return. At first, that was a ``NATO force''; then it fell back
slightly to ``a NATO-led force,'' and then, as the Russians started
to broker a deal between the warring parties, it became ``an
international force with NATO at its  &UR; core &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The center of a piece of fruit containing seeds is the  &UR; core &LR; ;
by association with the French  &UR; coeur &LR; , it has come to mean ``the
heart of the matter,'' and the noun can be used as a modifier, as
in  &UR; core values &LR; . Because it also has a connection to the French
 &UR; corps &LR; , ``body,'' Pentagon officials can paraphrase Gen. Douglas
MacArthur's farewell to West Point by saying, ``My last conscious
thoughts of NATO in the occupying force will be of the  &UR; core &LR; , the
 &UR; core &LR;  and the  &UR; core &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   What is the term of art for the altercation between NATO and
Serbia involving warplanes, surface-to-air missiles, prisoners of
war, propaganda, population removal, blockades and promises of
prosecution of war criminals? Not  &UR; war &LR; . That nasty term has legal
overtones, including declarations, rights and obligations of
belligerents and neutrals, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Some use has been made of  &UR; international armed conflict &LR; , as in
``the Korean  &UR; conflict &LR; ,'' which was the official U.S. designation
of the Korean War. (For a time, President Harry Truman referred to
it as a  &UR; police action &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the circumscribed nature of the  &UR; conflict &LR;  with
Serbia, rather than call it a  &UR; limited war &LR; , which has a
connotation of quagmires, the choice of NATO word warriors has been
 &UR; campaign &LR; . This has a general meaning of ``a series of military
battles during a phase of a war,'' and in the case of the current
semi-rubblization process, a specific meaning of the sustained NATO
 &UR; bombing campaign &LR; . However, in light of the coming political
campaign, notably what critics have called President Clinton's
``permanent campaign,'' this word lost favor in Washington to the
neutral  &UR; military operation &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it was we were fighting, Defense Secretary William
Cohen hedged: ``We're certainly engaged in  &UR; hostilities &LR; ; we're
engaged in  &UR; combat &LR; . Whether that measures up to a classic
definition of  &UR; war &LR; , I'm not qualified to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
