<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIANCA JAGGER SPOTLIGHTS PLIGHT OF KOSOVARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Even now, her T-shirt smeared with grime, her
fingernails rough from work, Bianca Jagger is haunted by her
ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   It's been forever since she was married to Mick, but she did
keep the last name of the Rolling Stones's lead singer _ a name
that brings her celebrity and snickers. Strangers who spot her in
Albania wonder what she is doing here and who she brought along to
pamper her.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Jagger _ the human rights campaigner _ packs her
own suitcases. She wears a touch of makeup, even in the midst of
war, but otherwise dresses down appropriately. And she doesn't
demand private helicopters, suffering the nerve-rattling eight-hour
drive from Tirana to the border town of Kukes like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might surprise people who only recognize me from my
marriage. But that's not all I am,'' said Jagger, 49, who put in
more than a few appearances at New York's Studio 54 when it was the
late 1970s hot spot, but also studied at the Institute of Political
Science in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Jagger doesn't want to name names, but she does say that she
resents being lumped in with celebrities who show up in hot spots,
grab some attention, then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like being put in the same category as people who
don't really know the situation,'' said Jagger. ``For them it's
like a photo opportunity. People spend one day and then they go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jagger recently spent five days in Albania and was headed to
Macedonia for another two or three. As a representative of the Save
the Children organization, she said her aim was to document the
plight of Kosovar children living in the refugee camps and focus
international attention on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
ethnic cleansing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community needs to decide what its aims
should be: To save and protect the civilian population in Kosovo,
to stop the genocide and ethnic cleansing, to do what?'' said
Jagger. ``It's clear they're not succeeding. To allow the
deportation and murder and atrocities in Kosovo is unconscionable.
We should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Having seen war up close before _ in her Nicaraguan homeland and
other Central American countries, as well as in Bosnia and other
Balkan countries _ Jagger speaks knowledgeably about the
effectiveness, or ineffectiveness, of airstrikes alone. She talks
for 15 minutes about Milosevic and war tribunals and holding war
criminals accountable for their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   She cites statistics, pulls a dog-eared map out of her bag to
illustrate her point. She also insists that she is a pacifist, even
as she insists that the only way to end the Kosovo tragedy is to
send in US troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is amazing to a lay person like me is how could they not
have a contingency plan,'' said Jagger, who speaks often on behalf
of the Washington-based College of International Justice and has
testified before Congress. ``I'm not an advocator of military
intervention; I've said so all my life. But I think if we had said
we will use any means necessary, we might not have needed to send
in ground troops. There comes a moment when you see atrocities and
you have to take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jagger, however, wasn't in Albania to air her views on war
strategy. She was in Tirana and border towns to make a film for
Save the Children.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, Jagger recounts, she personally took a young boy
she found on the street into a refugee camp. The 17 other members
of his family, however, refused to let him go alone. She says she
persuaded the camp, run by Doctors Without Borders, to take in all
of them together.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is human rights, of course,'' Jagger said before
heading off to Macedonia. ``And that includes the rights of
refugees and children during conflict. This is what I do now, who I
am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
