<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-RULES-BOS &LR;      05-17 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-RULES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S FAIR IN WAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN _ Genocide. Torture. Rape of civilians. Forced
removals of whole populations.
</P>
<P>
   Horrors like these aren't supposed to happen anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of World War II, the international community has
adopted an ever-growing canon of principles to govern combat and
protect civilians from abuses by governments _ their own or those
of others. There are now 374 conventions that deal with 25
categories of international, humanitarian, and criminal law, from
drug trafficking to the torture of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the past half century has witnessed, according to one study,
more than 250 conflicts that have claimed _ by one careful estimate
_ up to 170 million lives. Kosovo is but the latest on a long list
of tragedies; the killing fields of Cambodia and Rwanda, brutal
repression in Chile and South Africa, the massacre at My Lai are
among the many more.
</P>
<P>
   So have these laws of civilized conflict done any good at all?
And is there any way to make them more effective?
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross is trying to find
out. On the eve of the 50th anniversary in Aug. 12 of the signing
of the Geneva Conventions _ the cornerstones of international
humanitarian law _ the Red Cross is attempting to increase
awareness of the rules of war and to mobilize public pressure
against states and combatants that disobey them.
</P>
<P>
   The ``People on War'' study spans a dozen countries affected by
war, and six others at peace. In El Salvador and Somalia, Georgia
and the Philippines, the project has assembled focus groups of
either soldiers or civilians to relate their experiences amid war,
state repression, and other violence. To encourage a frank
exchange, participants' names were kept confidential. Washington
pollster Stanley Greenberg will draw together an analysis of the
country-by-country reports later this year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the research suggests that even if people do not know
the specific terms of international humanitarian law, most seem to
believe that certain principles of fair play should apply in
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall I get the impression that there is a fair awareness of
at least the spirit of the Geneva Conventions and that people do
see that the `rules of war' were designed to assist them,'' said
Kim Gordon-Bates, the international spokesman for the Red Cross
study. ``There is, of course, some element of doubt as to their
efficiency _ especially in places like Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   International humanitarian law covers armed conflict, genocide,
and crimes against humanity. Enacted on Aug. 12, 1949, the original
four Geneva Conventions seek to limit suffering in time of war.
Some 188 countries are now party to the codes, which bind them to
safeguard wounded armed forces on land or at sea, prisoners of war,
and civilians. Most of those states have also signed the 1977
protocols _ added rules to protect victims of armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
   And new laws are being added from time to time. Earlier this
month, parties to the 1997 Land Mine Ban Treaty convened their
first meeting to review its implementation in Maputo, Mozambique.
The treaty has been signed by 135 nations, although the United
States is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the US has a less-than-stellar record when it comes to
such matters. ``The US has signed virtually none of the major human
rights conventions,'' said Makau Mutua, a visiting professor of
international law at Harvard University. ``The US has the worst
record for ratifying interntional human rights agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   But, leaving aside US reluctance to participate, why have such
laws not resulted in a safer world? A major reason is the weakness
of the enforcement mechanisms. The six-year-old International
Tribunal on war crimes in The Hague and last year's treaty creating
an International Criminal Court represent the first real mechanisms
to enforce compliance. Few law schools teach international law, and
the field is little understood by the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, says Cherif Bassiouni, a scholar on humanitarian
law at Depaul University, is that governments apply the rules of
war differently depending on who the adversary is, and rebel
movements often don't observe them at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Militaries have a strong incentive to comply with the Geneva
Conventions if they confront another military. They have a mutual
interest,'' said Bassiouni, who last year conducted the study of
conflicts since World War II. But armed conflict is increasingly a
domestic phenomenon, resulting in a ``complete breakdown of such
laws in these situations.''
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, national militaries and police forces end up
warring against their own people rather than protecting them. And
insurgents, expecting no mercy at the hands of the state, feel
little imperative to practice higher principles.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Twala understands what Bassiouni means. A youth who grew
up amid South Africa's violent township upheavals of the late
1970s, Twala joined Umkhonto we Sizwe, the African National
Congress's military wing, so he could kill the whites who were
oppressing his people. By the time he went into action as part of
an urban sabotage unit after nearly two years of political and
military training in exile, his target was no longer white people,
but the structures of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were imbued with a capacity to understand that we had a
system that was a crime against humanity, and we needed to crush
the system,'' Twala said in an interview after a Red Cross focus
group on Robben Island _ a discussion that examined whether it is
possible to adhere to humanitarian principles while fighting an
enemy that blatantly disregards them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle was guilty of excesses,'' he said. ``But to say
that the ANC violated human rights is too sweeping: It fails to
account for the pressures we faced. The apartheid system never
inculcated humanitarian principles on that side. Those guys had
carte blanche.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boundaries of acceptable conduct in war can look just as
blurred from the other side. In a focus group held in Bosnia,
soldiers talked of their responses to civilians who become
participants in conflict. One told the story of a villager who led
a group of enemy soldiers into an ambush in which six of them were
killed. For that soldier, telling the story, the civilian's action
made him a legitimate target.
</P>
<P>
   Other focus group discussions have wrestled with difficult
questions concerning the rules of war. In Colombia, a group of
rebels grappled with the ethics of land mines. One said if he laid
a device to blow up a military convoy and a bus ran over it
instead, the civilian casualties would not be his fault. Another
objected, and a lively debate followed. In Lebanon, participants
said they could justify the use of violence to retaliate against
Israeli attacks, but they could not rationalize kidnappings,
torture, and the use of terrorism in their own civil war.
</P>
<P>
   By stirring debate across the lines of past conflicts the Red
Cross, which monitors the Geneva Conventions, hopes to raise public
intolerance for the kind of gross violations of human rights now
unfolding in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a correlation between the ethos of any given society
and the way warriors behave,'' Gordon-Bates said. ``Hopefully the
project will contribute to raising the humanitarian content of this
social ethos'' _ and raise the standards of conduct for all armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, focus only on the wholesale bloodshed of the past 50
years is to miss the reality that thanks to the Geneva conventions,
norms have changed. Although war remains a common feature in human
relations, Mutua, the visiting professor of international law at
Harvard University, sees important advances in how states relate to
their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both human rights and international humanitarian law are
recent international phenomena which, in terms of their
constructive enforcement, are still in their infancy,'' said Mutua.
``But there is no question today that what a state does within its
own borders is not its own business. No state today would boast of
violating human rights. There is now a substantial body of
humanitarian norms _ where 50 years ago there was a blank slate.''
</P>
<P>
   But inscribing that slate was just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   On the western edge of Cape Town, on the slope of Table
Mountain, a single white church rises from a conspicuously barren
stretch of land. It is one of the few original buildings spared in
the demolition of District Six, a thriving interracial community
that was systematically destroyed by the apartheid government,
starting in the late '60s. On a recent Saturday afternoon, former
residents of District Six gathered in the church, now a museum to
their lost neighborhood, to share their stories with the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Schaffers walked across a wide floor map of the old
community to the street where he was born. When the apartheid
police came through, he said, they tortured people and shot at
children. They tore down everything _ houses, shops, and theaters
with beautiful facades _ and dug up the streets. Residents were
scattered to poorly developed townships.
</P>
<P>
   International law was supposed to prevent such atrocities, he
said, but even today, it seems to make little difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is NATO in Kosovo now? Because the Geneva Conventions were
being contravened,'' he said. ``But they have come in at a late
stage. It was the same in Rwanda. They waited. What happened here
was a total violation of human dignity. It shouldn't have been
done. But nobody came to stop it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
