<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, May 17, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ZEDILLO-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.) _ When Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo arrives Tuesday in California, his first stop will
be a state Capitol jammed with hundreds of immigrants and Latino
activists. The timing of Zedillo's visit with the annual ``Hungry
for Justice Immigrant Day'' is coincidental, officials insist. By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COURTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ A panel appointed by New York's chief
judge to study public trust in the justice system says increased
funding for legal services and higher pay for court-appointed
lawyers is crucial in fostering confidence in the courts. By JOHN
CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSHER-SEX (Undated) _ Rabbi Shumley Boteach believes sex builds
the intimacy that is the glue binding people together for life. His
book, ``Kosher Sex'' (Doubleday, $19.95), draws on his counseling
experience and Jewish tradition to put joyous sex as a priority for
couples. By RICHARD VARA.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND-WEDDINGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ You're going to marry. Anew. If
this is your second time around the dance floor, ladies and
gentlemen, relish your freedom. But being older, wiser and possibly
better funded won't wipe out complications. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about a bug
that is chewing small holes in the leaves of his vegetables.
Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   CALCIUM-TEENS (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's a ``calcium crisis''
among teenagers, according to health and nutrition experts. Nearly
nine out of 10 girls and seven of 10 boys get too little calcium.
The National Academy of Sciences recommends 1,300 mg of calcium
daily for teens _ the equivalent of four eight-ounce glasses of
milk. It's needed because 15 percent of adult height and half of
all bone mass are added during the teen years. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FEATURE-STAR (San Francisco) _ They came in droves, like
battle droids on the warpath. About 1,300 eager moviegoers _ along
with filmmaker George Lucas _ marched into the Galaxy Theatre
Sunday for a charity premiere of the long-awaited space- myth flick
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' By JASON LLOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS NEWS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-FISHING (SAn Francisco) _ As thousands of California king
salmon amass deep in the ocean off the San Francisco coast,
commercial fishermen have been waiting for the robust winds to die
down. Usually the San Francisco fleet of 500 boats heads out on an
annual May 1 pilgrimage to catch the prized king _ or chinook _
salmon. But this year, high winds caused by La Nina have made it
too difficult for most boats to go trolling. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Fransisco) _ We are watching Defense
Secretary William Cohen on C-SPAN and talking about how much things
have changed in the war department. Says my friend, who served in
the peace-time Navy: ``I think I liked it better when we didn't
apologize and make excuses. What do people think war is these days?
Can you imagine William Westmoreland saying, `I'm sorry,' and
promising to investigate every bomb that hit the wrong target?'' By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Either the United States has
incompetents running the intelligence establishment or the bombing
of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade was an attempt by one element of
the U.S. government to sabotage Clinton administration policies.
Insofar as the Chinese want a more thorough investigation and to be
told of its findings, the American people should require no less.
By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Every time a member of the
Texas Legislature kills reasonable gun-control safeguards, they are
increasing the likelihood that criminals will use guns to kill
people. The government, including the Texas Legislature, can do a
better job of making it as difficult as possible for criminals to
acquire the deadly tools of their trade. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
</TEXT>
