 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2542 - May 17, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2542 -- May 17, 1999 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. CLONING THE WOOLLY MAMMOTH If you thought reproducing sheep
and mice was a leap ahead, you won't believe what the Japanese have
in mind : cloning a woolly mammoth that last walked the earth
during the Pleistocene Epoch. This bizarre quest may sound
unbelievable, but there is no science to deny the viability of the
idea. The only catch is finding a small bit of well-preserved
mammoth tissue containing normal DNA. To what lengths will the
Japanese team go to realize their cloning dream? By Richard Stone.
Discover magazine. 1,100 words + photos.
</P>
<P>
   2. BRAIN ABNORMALITIES MAY BE COMMON IN TEENAGERS
</P>
<P>
   BORN PREMATURELY More and more premature infants are surviving
today due to advances in neonatal care. But these infants are frail
and their brains, in particular, are vulnerable to injury. British
researchers report that teenagers who were born more than five
weeks prematurely are much more likely to have abnormal brain
scans, neurological and behavoural problems and low reading scores
than children who had normal births. By Michael McCarthy. The
Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   3. SECURITY BREACHES, THEN AND NOW Edward Teller, a senior
fellow at the Hoover Institution and director emeritus of the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, compares the U.S.
nuclear-information leaks to China to a situation half a century
ago, when vital nuclear secrets were leaked to the Soviet Union by,
among others, Klaus Fuchs, speeding up Soviet research by many
years. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   4. WHAT'S DOING IN LOS ANGELES Events, sightseeing, hotels and
restaurants in Los Angeles. By Todd S. Purdum. From The New York
Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
ALL STATIONS FOR ART NOUVEAU In devoting the year 1999 to the
rediscovery of Art Nouveau, the eastern French city of Nancy is
celebrating a particularly fertile period in its cultural history.
Three current exhibitions look at the origins of Nancy's
international fame towards the end of the last century, not only as
a source of a fashionable decorative art, but as a veritable centre
of creation. Its artists and industrialists were in close touch
with other, larger 'capitals' of the Art Nouveau movement in
Vienna, Brussels, Barcelona and Paris. By Michele Champenois. From
Le Monde. (English translation available.) 1,500 words. 6. FROM
NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 BST
Wednesday, May 19)
</P>
<P>
   A. GM CORN COULD BLOW OUT THE BUTTERFLY BALL Genetically
modified corn could kill caterpillars far from the cornfield. By
Henry Gee. 300 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. HUNTING DOWN HUNTINGTON'S DISEASE Huntington's disease is a
tragic and terminal hereditary disease that causes devastating
neuro-degeneration in about one in every thousand people. New
research suggests a possible ray of hope. By Sara Abdulla. 400
words.
</P>
<P>
   7. From NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Brazil, Australia, New
Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   A. OUT OF THE WRECKAGE We can't blunt a tornado's fury, but
after the recent mayhem in Oklahoma, twister prediction should take
a big step forward. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. GET STUCK IN Footballers should be able to get off the mark
faster, thanks to boots equipped with a new type of pyramid-shaped
stud. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. THE GREATEST APES The DNA of chimpanzees is almost identical
to ours. Find the difference and you'll find what makes us human.
2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   D. PAPER GOES ELECTRIC The future may be written in electronic
ink. This article heralds the greatest advance since papyrus. 2,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   E. STONE AGE KALASHNIKOV It launches projectiles at high speeds,
kills at 40 metres and can even be fitted with a silencer. This
25,000-year-old weapon (a spear and stick combination known as an
'atlatl') is surprisingly sophisticated. Thousands of people in
America and Europe are making atlatls, competing in international
tournaments, and even hunting with them.
</P>
