<HEADLINE>
GUN-SHY LEGISLATURE SHORTCHANGING PUBLIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Senate was less a lawmaking body than
a theater of the absurd last week when Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower
Mound, offered a bill to prohibit vendors at flea markets from
selling certain health-related items.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which would have banned the sale of infant formula,
over-the-counter medicine and contact lenses, was probably a good
idea. The object was to protect people from unknowingly risking
their health by purchasing outdated products in an unregulated
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, meanwhile, had an even better idea.
He proposed that anyone trying to buy an assault weapon at a flea
market be required to submit to a criminal background check.
</P>
<P>
   West also was trying to protect the public health. But when he
tried to attach his proposal as an amendment to Nelson's bill, one
would have thought he was trying to burn the U.S. flag.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate almost erupted into a full-fledged fight before Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry intervened and West withdrew his amendment and
Nelson withdrew her bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although I don't want to downplay the potential health risks of
bad medicine on an unsuspecting public, it is impossible to
overestimate the health risks of an assault weapon getting into the
wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to law enforcement officers, that frequently
happens at flea markets and gun shows, which are exempted from the
criminal background checks that the federal Brady law requires of
people purchasing guns from licensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Nelson nor any other member of the Legislature wants
criminals to use guns to kill people, but each time lawmakers kill
reasonable gun-control safeguards, they are increasing that
likelihood.
</P>
<P>
   All the over-the-counter medicine in the world _ purchased from
a flea market or a grocery store _ isn't going to repair the damage
from a direct hit by an assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Yes! I also know that all the laws and regulations in the world
aren't going to keep criminals from getting _ and using _ guns.
</P>
<P>
   But government, including the Texas Legislature, can do a better
job of making it as difficult as possible for them to acquire the
deadly tools of their trade.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, someone with a criminal record could skirt a background
check by arranging with a seller to purchase a gun across the
street from the flea market.
</P>
<P>
   Someone also could buy bad baby formula the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Nelson shouldn't try to protect the public health
by banning baby formula sales from flea markets? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Any law the Legislature passes can and will be circumvented or
violated. But that doesn't mean lawmakers shouldn't do their best
to protect the public health and safety. People, unfortunately,
violate laws against murder and robbery every day, but no one has
ever proposed that we legalize those acts.
</P>
<P>
   If the logistics of conducting criminal background checks at
flea markets would be too cumbersome, a simpler approach would be
to ban the sale of assault weapons entirely at such events.
</P>
<P>
   Any law-abiding citizen who believes he or she really needs an
assault weapon could still buy one from a licensed dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the protestations of the National Rifle Association,
whose influence obviously is very strong in Austin, West's proposal
didn't represent a threat to the Second Amendment or this year's
hunting trip.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did a broader bill, which died earlier this spring, that
would have required criminal background checks of all weapons
purchased at gun shows in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, in a news conference following the Colorado
school shootings, endorsed criminal background checks at gun shows.
But he never tried to get the bill passed, and the measure already
had been killed by a House committee only hours before the governor
finally spoke out.
</P>
<P>
   Pressured by gun-control advocates to try to revive the bill,
Bush replied that the measure was flawed. He said background checks
for gun show purchases should be addressed in federal law.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress began debating federal gun show legislation last
week, Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm asked if the
Republican governor had called U.S. senators, urging them to
support the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very good question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
