<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
May 18. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY: Private contractors of the Department of Energy -
including Allied Signal and Midwest Research Institute of Kansas
City - are doing little to curb excessive travel costs, a recent
government audit shows. The 32 contractors failed to meet the
department's 1995 goal to cut $35 million a year in travel.
Altogether, we footed $250 million for their travel last year. Some
firms show little interest in containing costs - paying $1,000 + on
airline tickets they could get for less than half that amount and
spending $300 a night on hotel rooms. Kevin Murphy. 28 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN: Sam Beckett is the Kansas City Royals new organist. It's
been eight years since an organist has been at the K to play for
the team. Fans, in their surveys, have consistently asked for an
organist to return. We profile a man and his music, plus talk to
fans about Sam. Ruth Igoe. 15-20. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   EXERCISE: The road that circles the Downtown Airport has become
a mecca for skaters, joggers, bicyclers and wheelchair racers, who
want a secluded place to exercise over the noon hour. M. Rice. 27.
Photos.
</P>
<P>
   AIR: Air Quality Forum meets Monday and will likely discuss
impasse over new road construction. Also, Sen. Kit Bond holds news
conference at Chouteau Bridge at 3 PM to complain about federal
sanctions. Mike Mansur. 15. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOYS: Michael Gurian, author of ``A Fine Young Man: What
Parents, Mentors and Educators Can Do To Shape Adolescent Boys into
Exceptional Men'' spoke in Kansas City Monday morning. Gurian is
credited with bringing ``the boys movement'' into the national
spotlight and has been interviewed widely on the Littleton, Colo.
shootings. 12-15 in.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER (business) _ What a long, strange trip to the altar for
Western Resources Inc. and Kansas City Power &AMP; Light. By Steve
Everly. with art
</P>
<P>
   WEST (business, with MERGER) _ Western Resources reports sharply
lower quarterly earnings. By Steve Everly
</P>
<P>
   MOBIZ (business) _ Wrap-up of key business issues before the
Missouri General Assembly this year. By Rick Alm
</P>
<P>
   CHOW (business) _ Boyd Gaming Corp. has won a decadelong court
battle against the IRS folks over the corporate tax deductibility
of meals provided to employees. The ruling cuts across all
industries and will avoid taxing employees on the value of the
meals they recieve. Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   BAKE (business) _ Interstate Bakeries didn't do everything it
was supposed to do when it acquired Continental Grain, Dept. of
Justice says. Jennifer Mann
</P>
<P>
   USBANK (business) _ US Bancorp of Minneapolis is pulling out of
Kansas. The 20 branches are being bought by Intrust of Wichita,
Kansas' biggest holding company which finally will raise its
profile a bit in the Kansas City area. Charles Crumpley
</P>
</TEXT>
