<SLUG> BC-COURT-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIKES DOWN CALIFORNIA WELFARE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday struck down as a
``discriminatory scheme'' a 1997 California law that would have
granted the state's newcomers lower welfare benefits than those
received by residents who have lived there longer.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' 7-2 decision said California's limit on benefits
for new residents violates the constitutional right to travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens of the United States, whether rich or poor, have the
right to choose to be citizens of the state wherein they reside,''
Justice John Paul Stevens wrote for the court. ``The states,
however, do not have any right to select their citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``California's legitimate interest in saving money
does not justify this discriminatory scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision will force California to restructure
its welfare policy. The state has the nation's largest number of
welfare recipients _ about 2.6 million _ and a $6 billion budget to
aid them.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also will affect other states that have enacted
similar laws under the welfare restructuring law that Congress
passed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After the law was enacted, California, like 14 other states,
redesigned its welfare system to pay new residents _ those in the
state less than a year _ who apply for aid only as much as they
would have received in their former states. Newcomers could receive
full California benefits after one year of residency.
</P>
<P>
   Since California ranks sixth highest among the 50 states in
welfare benefits, the vast majority of newcomers would have
received far less money than longer-term residents. For example,
California would have paid $673 a month to a family of four who had
been in the state more than a year, but if that family had recently
arrived from, say, Mississippi, it would have received $144 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the two-tier system to prevent states with
higher benefits from becoming ``welfare magnets'' that would
attract migrating poor people. Many lawmakers said that if such a
migration were to happen, states might engage in a ``race to the
bottom'' to lower their benefits and make themselves less
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Before the California law went into effect, however, a single
woman and a family of welfare recipients challenged the law, saying
the limit on benefits _ along with California's high cost of living
_ could deprive them of the basic necessities of life.
</P>
<P>
   The family, listed under the fictitious name of the Roes, had
moved to Long Beach, Calif., from Oklahoma and would have received
$307 per month compared with the in-state resident benefit of $565.
The anonymous woman, called Anna Doe, had moved to Los Angeles from
Washington, D.C., when she was six months pregnant and would have
received $330 per month compared with an in-state resident benefit
of $456.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court ruled on April 1, 1997 _ the first day
that the California law would have become effective _ that it was
unconstitutional. The court said the law penalized migration
between states in violation of the equal protection clause of the
14th Amendment. The next year, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals agreed unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   During his arguments before the high court in January,
California Deputy Attorney General Theodore Garelis argued that
while the law might have impeded migration to California, it would
not have prevented freedom of travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People move for a host of reasons, with welfare benefits being
only one,'' Garelis said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the law would not have ``hurt'' newcomers because
they would have received some benefits and those payments would
have risen to California levels after a year. ``In the end, they're
no worse off than if they had stayed in their original state,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevens wrote on Monday that while it may be reasonable to
assume that some people might move to a state to receive higher
welfare benefits, ``the empirical evidence ... indicates that the
number of such persons is quite small _ surely not large enough to
justify a burden on those who had no such motive.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin
Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the two, Rehnquist called the California law a
``reasonable measure falling under the head of a `good-faith
residency requirement.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other states with lower welfare benefits for newcomers are
Florida, Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Minnesota, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New York, North Dakota, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island,
Vermont, Washington and Wisconsin. Several of those laws have been
challenged in court and have been barred from taking effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
