<HEADER>
A9978 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAREWELL-TO-HOME-IMPR     05-17 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAREWELL-TO-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICIA RICHARDSON: SHE'S LEAVING `HOME' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Patricia Richardson with Tim Allen in a
scene from ``Home Improvement.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much like the show she stars in, Patricia Richardson has never
really been given her due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Pat Richardson there would be no `Home Improvement,'''
Tim Allen said at the 1999 People's Choice Awards.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, while the media has spent eight years focused on
Allen's every move, Richardson has quietly bloomed in the
background. Along the way she's survived a divorce, successfully
raised three kids and even made her directorial debut earlier this
season.
</P>
<P>
   With the show's final episode set to air on May 25, Richardson
admits that she's had little time to reminisce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a wreck,'' she says during an interview on the show's
set, shortly before filming the finale. ``I keep telling myself
that I'm happy for it to be ending _ I think it's the perfect time.
But it's been so stressful. The last two episodes have been
constantly in flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also,'' she adds, ``for the last couple of months I've been
single-parenting my kids seven days a week, because my ex-husband
(actor Ray Barker) and I share custody, but he is in New York doing
a play. So I'm totally stressed and exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Her children are taking the end of the series hard, the actress
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is devastating for them,'' she says. ``My son (Henry) was
6 when it started, now he's 14. And the twins (8-year-olds Roxanne
and Joseph) have never known me not to be working on this show.
It's finally starting to sink in that Mommy is not going to be
doing this any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place has been such a fixture in their lives,'' she says
with a laugh. ``They're going to have a hard fall when they have to
go back to the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   It was widely reported that ABC executives _ as well as many at
Disney, the network's parent company _ were upset by the decision
of Allen and Richardson not to continue ``Home Improvement'' for a
ninth season, despite having achieved some of the show's highest
ratings in its eighth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Disney and ABC aren't really happy with us for
making that decision,'' Richardson concedes. ``They thought they
should get another year out of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think we did them a huge favor,'' she says with a
smile. ``They would have paid so much to get us back next year, and
we would have been like `Mad About You' _ they would have spent all
that money and we would have been down in the 40s or 50s (in the
ratings).
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they'd feel like fools, because they'd be paying all that
money for what?''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Richardson didn't really need the money. ``Home
Improvement'' has left her financially secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something an actor never expects,'' she says, ``and, as a
single parent, I really, really appreciate it. If I'm careful and
invest right, I've done well enough to never have to work again.
The really great gift, though, is having money for my children's
education, because the one thing that no one can take away from you
is what you've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress has signed to do a couple of films for Disney, but
not right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' she says, ``I really want to just lie down and
take a lot of naps. I'm taking the summer off and renting a house
in Malibu _ I'd like some time to just walk on the beach and think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to put my whole life together,'' she adds. ``I've been
through a divorce, and I know that losing the show is going to
reawaken those feelings of loss.''
</P>
<P>
   While Allen has lived the high-profile life of a television
megastar, complete with tabloid hype about a long-ago prison term
and continuing problems with alcohol abuse, Richardson has managed
to fly under the media radar, for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim flies around in jets and has three houses,'' the actress
says with a laugh. ``He has a whole different deal, and is in
another world than I'm in, which has its price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I really manage to have a normal life,'' she says.
``Here in L.A. it's kind of cool to not pay attention to
celebrities, so you really can pretend that you're a normal person.
I have a very well-paid, fun job _ other than that, I live like
other people do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretend I'm a normal person to such a degree that I'm still
surprised when someone does come up and speak to me,'' she adds.
``It sounds stupid, but I still find myself taken aback. It can be
really jarring.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson claims not to have a favorite ``Home Improvement''
moment, either for her or for her character, but she's proud of
Jill and what she's represented to many viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a favorite child, and I don't have a favorite
episode,'' she says. ``When I try to think of my favorite times on
the show, it all becomes a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel such pride in the work that all of us have done here,
and I really do feel proud about Jill,'' she adds. ``I was a
feminist going into the show, still am. But I've always prided
myself on not being a defensive feminist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few times during the run of the show I did become
defensive,'' she admits, ``simply because I felt a little
overwhelmed by the testosterone levels on the other side of the
table. But I worked really hard to never have Jill be abrasive in
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Allen, she says she doesn't expect to miss him. But no,
not the way that sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving Tim is not that hard,'' she explains, ``because we
both live in L.A. and I know he'll continue to be an ongoing person
in my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you one unique thing about him that I will always
cherish,'' she says. ``It's his laugh. You don't see it much in the
show, but you see it in a lot of the outtakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has this kind of bark, this laugh that comes out like an
explosion. It is so infectious. For me, it's his defining
characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked so hard to get him to laugh like that,'' she
concludes, ``because it was such a reward to hear it. It was always
a real joy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Home Improvement,'' consult
the ABC Website at http://abc.go.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
