<SLUG> BC-NATALIE-PORTMAN-IN-STAR-WARS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIRL WHO WOULD BE QUEEN: NATALIE PORTMAN TALKS `STAR WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Natalie Portman in a scene from ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Sometimes a lightsaber is your only hope. Other times, a No. 2
pencil comes in handier.
 &HT;    On May 19, while the rest of the world is lining up for ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace,'' Natalie Portman won't be seeing the
film she stars in. She's got bigger things to worry about.
 &HT;    ``On the day `Star Wars' opens,'' she says, ``I'll be taking my
biology final.
 &HT;    ``I would love to get out there and see the movie with my
friends,'' the 17-year-old says, ``but I'll be sitting at my desk
and not worrying about the box office. My biggest concern that
weekend will be getting at least a 95 percent on the test.''
 &HT;    As Queen Amidala of the planet Naboo, she battles alongside Jedi
knight Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) and Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan
McGregor) to save her people from the evil Trade Federation, but in
real life Portman has more modest goals.
 &HT;    ``In my life, `Star Wars' is important, but equally big is that
the prom is right around the corner,'' she says, giggling and
sipping bottled water.
 &HT;    Sitting for an interview at New York's Regency Hotel, Portman
easily could pass for a queen, or at least a princess. Long,
flowing brown hair cascades over her shoulders, while large,
doe-like eyes shimmer warmly.
 &HT;    Not your typical high-school student, in short.
 &HT;    ``My life is much stranger than a normal teen-ager,'' she says.
``For instance, it said in my Vanity Fair article that I didn't
have a prom date _ but they interviewed me in February. Obviously,
I didn't have a date back then.''
 &HT;    For the first time all morning, she sounds rattled.
 &HT;    ``You know,'' she says, ``it made me sound like a big dork.''
 &HT;    Not to worry _ this summer, Portman pretty much has cornered the
market on cool. ``Star Wars'' can do that for you, even if the
actress wasn't originally sure she wanted anything of the kind.
 &HT;    ``It's always a concern when you do something like `Star
Wars,''' she explains, ``because you worry that people will forget
you also do other stuff.''
 &HT;    For the record, she does. Her track record includes a starring
role in ``The Professional'' (1994) and working with Al Pacino in
``Heat'' (1995). She displayed the charm and vulnerability of a
young Audrey Hepburn as a lovestruck kid next door in ``Beautiful
Girls'' (1996).
 &HT;    And now ``Star Wars,'' in a role which writer/director George
Lucas offered her the first time they met.
 &HT;    ``George was just so real and sweet,'' she recalls. ``Initially
we just sat and talked for a long time.''
 &HT;    The director offered her the role at that first lunch, but
Portman didn't immediately say yes.
 &HT;    ``Of course, I was honored and flattered,'' she says. ``But I
had to think about it because of the size of the film. Plus I had
to sign on to do three prequels. It's hard to sign on for eight
years of work when you're only 14 years old.
 &HT;    ``I honestly thought, `What if I don't even want to be an
actress eight years from now?'''
 &HT;    Another concern was what she calls ``the recognizability
factor.'' The notoriously private Portman _ she won't reveal her
hometown, her school or her real last name _ didn't want to be the
new poster girl for sci-fi freaks.
 &HT;    ``I knew they would suddenly be interested in every aspect of my
private life,'' Portman says.
 &HT;    Besides, doing the film involved an arduous shoot deep in the
Tunisian desert.
 &HT;    ``On an average day it was 150 degrees in the shade,'' the
actress says. ``It was exhausting. Plus I had to wear these
incredibly heavy robes and gowns, plus headpieces that gave me a
constant headache.''
 &HT;    During one battle scene Portman was injured in a mistimed
explosion _ a widely reported incident which, she says, was wildly
exaggerated.
 &HT;    ``This spark went near my eye,'' she says. ``It wasn't really a
big deal. I went to a doctor and he just washed the debris out.''
 &HT;    She shakes her head.
 &HT;    ``A lot of people had it much worse than me,'' she adds. ``There
was fainting in the desert. One person had a heart attack. But that
was their own thing _ I don't think it was `Star Wars'-related.''
 &HT;    It wasn't all gloom and doom, though. Portman and co-stars
Neeson, McGregor and young Jake Lloyd could get downright silly at
times.
 &HT;    ``One day it was so hot that we decided to see if we could fry
an egg on R2-D2's head,'' she recalls, adding that it worked.
 &HT;    Did Lucas mind?
 &HT;    ``No,'' Portman says, giggling. ``R2's head has a Teflon
surface. The egg came right off.''
 &HT;    Egg-frying may not be a typical movie-star pastime, but it's not
so surprising for a younger-than-she-seems actress whose parents
still drive her to school and pack peanut-butter-and-jelly
sandwiches for her lunch _ she's a strict vegetarian.
 &HT;    ``I have a very stable family life,'' Portman says. ``I go to a
public high school. My friends are regular people and they're each
outstanding in some field, whether it be music, science or writing.
I have these people around me who treat me like any other girl.''
 &HT;    Born in Jerusalem, Portman is the only child of a
fertility-specialist father and a full-time mother. A brief
modeling career, which began when a talent scout spotted the
10-year-old at a Long Island pizza parlor, led her into acting. She
made her movie debut at age 11 in ``The Professional,'' as a waif
who bonds with a hired killer (Jean Reno).
 &HT;    Portman went on to appear in ``Mars Attacks!'' (1996) and as
Pacino's daughter in ``Heat,'' before stealing scenes from Uma
Thurman, Timothy Hutton and Matt Dillon in ``Beautiful Girls.'' On
the stage, the young actress won rave reviews as the star of a
Broadway revival of ``The Diary of Anne Frank'' (1998).
 &HT;    Next up is a whole new challenge _ college.
 &HT;    ``When I go home from this interview, I have to study for my
first college-placement exams,'' the actress says with a sigh.
 &HT;    ``It's never been an issue for me whether or not I'd go to
college,'' Portman adds. ``I don't feel ready to enter the world. I
don't have enough education.''
 &HT;    She won't say what school she'll be attending, though she
reportedly has been accepted at several Ivy League colleges, and
she hasn't settled on a major, though she says she's interested in
politics and foreign policy.
 &HT;    Not drama?
 &HT;    ``At 20 I might say, `I've had enough of acting,''' Portman
says.
 &HT;    For now, though, she's keeping her hand in. This fall she'll be
seen in the mother-daughter drama ``Anywhere But Here'' with Susan
Sarandon, and her school vacations in 2000 and 2002 will be spent
filming the next two ``Star Wars'' episodes.
 &HT;    She scoffs at rumors that James Van Der Beek will play the
teen-age Anakin in the next installment.
 &HT;    ``Do the math,'' she says. ``Anakin is younger than the queen,
and he's three years older than me.''
 &HT;    Actually, Portman adds, she thinks all the ``Star Wars'' hype is
sort of ridiculous.
 &HT;    ``You get to this point where you start to think that the whole
world revolves around a big movie,'' she says. ``But you know what?
For most people, movies are a weekend thing. That's real life.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Star Wars: The Phantom
Menace,'' consult the official Website at www.starwars.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
