<HEADER>
A9980 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGH-GRANT-IN-NOTTING     05-17 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGH-GRANT-IN-NOTTING-HILL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROMANCE IS BACK FOR HUGH GRANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Hugh Grant in a scene from ``Notting
Hill.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Hugh Grant wants you to know who he isn't.
 &HT;    When the charming, witty British actor became an overnight star
with the release of ``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' (1994),
everyone compared him to another actor with a similar name _ Cary
Grant.
 &HT;    Hugh Grant didn't know what to say.
 &HT;    ``The awful thing was that I was so cinema-illiterate then that
I didn't quite know who Cary Grant was,'' Grant admits. ``Now I've
watched a lot of his films, and I'm humbled and humiliated that
people said that. He was good, really good.
 &HT;    ``I've seen Cary Grant, and I'm no Cary Grant.''
 &HT;    Ah, there's that Brit wit, a mix of charm, self-deprecatory
humor and an awkward quality which is infallibly winning. Toss in
his catnip-for-paparazzi relationship with head-turner Elizabeth
Hurley, and it's no wonder that Grant's appeal has survived several
resounding box-office flops and even some unwanted Divine
intervention.
 &HT;    Actually, Grant may soon be more popular than ever, as he
returns to romantic comedy _ the genre most favored by his fans _
for ``Notting Hill,'' opening May 28 and co-starring Julia Roberts.
A Mafia comedy ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' will follow later in the
summer.
 &HT;    ``Notting Hill'' has all the hallmarks of another ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral,'' a thought which doesn't entirely delight
the actor.
 &HT;    ``I suppose it could start all over again,'' Grant says,
wincing. ``We'll see.''
 &HT;    For the last few years Grant has been absent from movie screens,
which many have attributed to an effort to let the scandal over his
arrest for patronizing a prostitute blow over.
 &HT;    ``People write such crap,'' he says. ``I just didn't want to do
any films. I'm not the world's keenest actor, and I don't like
living the life where you're permanently on E!
 &HT;    ``I wanted a normal life,'' he adds. ``I knocked around. I
worked behind the scenes on `Mickey Blue Eyes,' helping with the
script, even getting caught up in picking the crew hats.''
 &HT;    ``Notting Hill'' returns Grant to his ``Four Weddings'' persona
as a charming-albeit-bumbling English lad. He plays William
Thatcher, proprietor of a struggling bookshop in the Notting Hill
section of London, whose mundane existence turns upside down when
Anna Scott (Julia Roberts), the world's most famous actress,
wanders into his store.
 &HT;    ``Notting Hill's'' ``Four Weddings'' touch isn't surprising,
since it reunites several alumni of that film, including Grant,
producer Duncan Kenworthy and screenwriter Richard Curtis.
 &HT;    ``Richard told me about `Notting Hill' during `Four Weddings,'
so I always assumed it was coming,'' the affable Grant says during
a conversation at London's Dorchester Hotel. ``It took forever for
Richard to finish writing, though, because he got involved in
trivial things like saving the world's starving and having
children.
 &HT;    ``Then it was written and I wasn't really offered it right
away,'' he adds. ``I never knew what happened, but it finally came
together.''
 &HT;    Both Grant and Roberts have had their share of the troubles that
come with fame, but he insists that the movie isn't any kind of
revenge. Nonetheless, he admits that its look at the tabloid press
and the paparazzi hit home for him.
 &HT;    ``It's very difficult for celebrities to sit and say, `Uh, it's
a nightmare in our lives. It's inhuman what the media do to us,'''
Grant says. ``That always sounds unattractive and looks bad,
because we're earning all this money and flying around on the
Concorde.
 &HT;    ``The film says some very difficult things,'' he concludes.
``I'm glad that Richard says them for us, and he says them in a way
that might jolt people a bit.''
 &HT;    Roberts denies that her performance in ``Notting Hill'' is
autobiographical, but Grant dismisses her dismissal.
 &HT;    ``She claims Anna is not her, but I think she's lying,'' he
says. ``I think there's a lot of her in the part, and that's why
she's so effective. She bares her soul _ you get to see a Julia you
haven't seen before on film.''
 &HT;    The two stars actually met years ago, when an unknown Grant was
invited for a 1991 audition with Roberts for a film called
``Shakespeare in Love.''
 &HT;    ``I was one of many actors paraded in front of her to play
Shakespeare,'' Grant says. ``We were all thrown away like so much
trash. Nevertheless, I got on quite well with Julia and went back a
second time.
 &HT;    ``The film never happened,'' he says, ``but years later, after
`Four Weddings,' I was doing `The Englishman Who Went Up a Hill'
(1995) at Pinewood Studios. I was standing in the carpark having a
cup of tea, and two great big Range Rovers screeched to a halt next
to me.
 &HT;    ``And out jumped Julia, who gave me a big hug. She was shooting
on a neighboring soundstage, and was pleased for me about `Four
Weddings.'
 &HT;    ``It was an incredibly friendly thing to do,'' he says, ``and it
was fantastic for my credibility with the other actors on
`Englishman.' Of course, I was still terrified of her when she
arrived on `Notting Hill,' but I got over it.''
 &HT;    Grant's next film, ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' casts him opposite an
actor who's intimidating in a different way _ James Caan, best
known as Sonny Corleone in ``The Godfather'' (1972).
 &HT;    ``Just the idea of me with Caan, I think, is ridiculous,'' Grant
says. ``We're the odd couple, but we got on very well.''
 &HT;    The film casts Grant as an Englishman living in New York who
falls in love with a Brooklyn girl (Jeanne Tripplehorn). The only
catch: Her father (Caan) is a mobster.
 &HT;    ``It's a fish-out-of-water story, with me dealing with the Mob
coming into my life,'' Grant says. ``It doesn't have anything
important to say, but it's bloody funny.''
 &HT;    Grant and Hurley co-produced ``Mickey'' through their company,
Simian Films, and he says they spent time in New York hobnobbing
with real-life mobsters.
 &HT;    ``Elizabeth absolutely adores them,'' Grant says, ``and they
worship the ground she walks on. She was out every night with them.
 &HT;    ``Everywhere she goes now in New York, two or three big guys are
around her, and they'll do anything for her,'' he adds.
```Elizabeth, anything you want, anything you need, you just tell
us.'
 &HT;    ``It's nice to know, especially if we're being tabloided in
England,'' he says, tongue in cheek. ``Who knows? Maybe one day
there'll be a knock on somebody's door.''
 &HT;    Come the fall, Grant will jet back to New York to star in Woody
Allen's next film, playing a sophisticated Englishman struggling to
instill some class in a vulgar, nouveau-rich couple (Allen and
Tracey Ullman).
 &HT;    One can never be sure with the Woodman, but it sounds like a
comedy, which should please his fans. Grant likes to stretch _ his
credits include the gay-themed drama ``Maurice'' (1987), the Jane
Austen adaptation ``Sense and Sensibility'' (1995), Roman
Polanski's sex saga ``Bitter Moon'' (1992) and the medical thriller
``Extreme Measures'' (1996) _ but his fans like him best when he
shuns drama for romantic comedy.
 &HT;    Actually, the same is true of Roberts, who has rarely scored
with anything but comedies.
 &HT;    ``Julia and I didn't discuss that while we were doing `Notting
Hill,''' Grant says. ``I do feel a little locked in sometimes, but
just a little bit. As I say, though, I'm really not the keenest
actor in the world, and I've never needed to do a million different
things.
 &HT;    ``Really, I'm not desperate to play some psychopath in a
wheelchair in darkest Africa.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Notting Hill,'' consult the
official Website at www.notting-hill.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
