<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTRY-FOLK-SINGER-E     05-17 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-FOLK-SINGER-EMMYLOU-HARRIS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST CALL IT MUSIC: EMMYLOU HARRIS KEEPS ON NUDGING MUSICAL
BOUNDARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country/folk singer Emmylou Harris. 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Three decades after she began recording, Emmylou Harris has
found herself labeled ``the Queen of Contemporary Folk.''
 &HT;    Whatever that is.
 &HT;    ``I guess I'm just getting into this now,'' the 51-year-old
Harris says with a laugh. ``I spent the last 25 years trying to
figure out what country music is.''
 &HT;    Whatever the genre may be, though, Harris is clearly among its
leading lights. Her last studio album, ``Wrecking Ball'' (1995),
won a Grammy Award as Best Contemporary Folk Recording. And her new
live album, ``Spyboy'' (1998), was up for that same award this
year. She lost out to Lucinda Williams on that one, but did share a
Grammy for Best Country Collaboration with Vocals for her work in
``Same Old Train.''
 &HT;    Its queen isn't entirely sure what contemporary folk is, but
that doesn't bother her much,
 &HT;    ``I think the category has just come into its own because there
are a lot of artists who are making music that can't be
categorized,'' she says. ``So contemporary folk is a catchall, and
thankfully it's there to give recognition to some albums that can't
seem to be placed anywhere else.
 &HT;    ``But you know what?'' Harris adds. ``To me music is music, and
a good song is a good song. Because I don't come from a country
tradition or a folk tradition, I just got turned onto music. So
maybe I'm breaking the rules, but I'm not doing that in a
rebellious way. It's because I just don't know what the rules
are.''
 &HT;    Harris began 1999 on a high note, with the long-awaited release
of ``Trio II'' (Asylum Records), the sequel to her platinum 1987
collaboration with fellow songstresses Linda Ronstadt and Dolly
Parton.
 &HT;    Teamwork continues to be the theme, as a duets album with
Ronstadt is slated to be issued in July. Harris will tour in August
and September, and is also putting the finishing touches on an
all-star tribute album to her mentor, Gram Parsons, on which she
and Beck join forces for ``Sin City.''
 &HT;    Some of her fans will see the music she sings as country, some
as folk and some as something else. But according to Buddy Miller,
the songwriter/producer who also plays guitar in Spyboy, Harris'
band, that's not all that important.
 &HT;    ``What I like is how she keeps herself open to everything,''
Miller says. ``A lot of people think of Emmylou and they think of
her as a country artist. She's always been so open to and searching
for just soulful music, wherever it is. I know that, through
playing with her, I've been exposed to a lot of things I wouldn't
normally have been exposed to on my own.''
 &HT;    In a sense, the contemporary folk designation brings Harris full
circle. It was folk music that lured the Birmingham, Ala.-born
singer/songwriter _ raised in North Carolina and Virginia, where
she was a beauty queen and a saxophonist in the high-school band _
away from her drama studies at Boston University and into the folk
scene in New York's Greenwich Village.
 &HT;    There she hung out at legendary clubs such as Gurley's Folk
City, the Gaslight and the Bitter End, soaking in the influences of
Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the other 1960s regulars, as well as
performing on her own.
 &HT;    ``I started out doing folk music, but it's just because I was
afraid of drummers in the beginning,'' Harris says with a laugh.
``Folk music always focused on the lyrics, because it's a kind of
storytelling. I got into the lyrics early on, which is what drew me
into folk music. So that's always been an extremely important part
of how I picked songs _ it's all pretty much lyrics first.''
 &HT;    After the failure of Harris' first album, ``Gliding Bird''
(1969), she divorced songwriter Jon Slocum and, with the first of
her two daughters, moved first to Nashville and then to her
parents' farmhouse in Maryland.
 &HT;    Eventually proximity drew her into Washington's lower-profile
but still vibrant folk community, and it was there that she met
Parsons.
 &HT;    He had pioneered a fusion of rock and country, first with the
Byrds on their landmark album ``Sweetheart of the Rodeo'' (1968)
and then with his own group, the Flying Burrito Brothers. Impressed
with the young singer's voice, Parsons used her prominently on his
two solo albums, ``GP'' and ``Grievous Angel.'' After he died of a
heroin overdose in 1973, Harris vowed to continue the spirit of his
work.
 &HT;    ``I think I learned to be a singer by singing harmony with Gram
Parsons,'' Harris says. ``Now that's just as natural for me as
breathing.''
 &HT;    Her major-label debut, ``Pieces of the Sky'' (1975), launched a
bold and challenging career. Much to her surprise, however, she
found that the rock-oriented musical establishment didn't know what
to do with her. She found herself pigeonholed as a country singer,
which at the time meant very few opportunities for mainstream radio
play.
 &HT;    ``Nobody has ever told me what to do,'' Harris says. ``I've
always been working in a collaborative way with people who I think
are of the same mind and heart as far as what we're going for.
Radio is the last place it ends up, and they certainly tossed
enough things back at me over the years.
 &HT;    ``But fortunately I have an audience that has sought me out
regardless of whether I'm on the radio or not,'' she concludes,
``and I'm very grateful for that.''
 &HT;    If it appears that Harris has kicked into overdrive this year,
it's partly an illusion. ``Trio II'' was actually recorded four
years ago, she explains, but abandoned when the three singers'
schedules interfered with promoting it. Each took a few tracks for
her own albums and, Harris says, all three were surprised when
Asylum contacted them about finally putting out the album itself.
 &HT;    ``I didn't think it was ever going to come out, because it was a
very expensive record to make, and I didn't think any record
company would want to touch it,'' she says. ``But they said, `We
don't care. We just want this record,' even though we weren't going
to promote it extensively. So we said `Well, OK, we love it and
want to see it come out.'''
 &HT;    Her duet album with Ronstadt, Harris says, is simply ``a bunch
of really good songs produced by Glyn Johns,'' including originals
by both Harris and Patty Griffin, as well as covers of songs by
Bruce Springsteen and Leonard Cohen.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't say it falls in any category,'' she adds. ``It's
not a traditional record, and it's not particularly a country
record. It's just two women who have always been in love with a
song getting together and singing.''
 &HT;    Which, Harris notes, is the way she's always gone about things
in her genre-defying career.
 &HT;    ``I'm just not going to let anything stand in the way of me
singing a song that I like to sing,'' she says. ``I'll leave it up
to other people to decide what it is and what category it's
supposed to be.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
