<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NEEDS TO TAKE A FRESH LOOK AT CHINA POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When Chinese students, carrying placards
emblazoned with their demands, rallied for democracy 10 years ago
in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, they gathered around a scaled-down
version of the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   To Americans, the statue's symbolism struck home. While few
Americans could read the words proclaimed on the banners, each one
could instantly grasp the aims of Beijing students because of that
model of Lady Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Overcome was a difficult language barrier as well as vast
cultural and political differences, so that we appeared to
understand each other. A decade later, the Beijing students
apparently no longer look to America as the emblem of the freedom
to which they aspire.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the bombing by U.S.-led NATO planes of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, in which three Chinese died and some
20 were wounded, came student demonstrations of a scale not seen in
China since Tiananmen Square. This time the students equated
America not with Liberty but with oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, their banners made clear, the Nazi kind. This
time, as well, the government carefully modulated the violence,
which put under siege the American Embassy and consulates.
</P>
<P>
   We are informed by press reports out of China that resentment of
the United States as a world power, and even of things American
from Coca-Cola to KFC, was always just below the surface. All the
while, probably most Americans in their optimism assumed that a
good relationship was being constructed incrementally over the past
quarter century or so.
</P>
<P>
   All that it took for the true feelings of the Chinese to surface
was the bombing incident, for which NATO and the United States
apologized and to which Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
President Clinton added their personal expressions of profound
regret.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese dismissed the apologies and the explanation of
the bombing as a tragic mistake. The Chinese president at first
wouldn't pick up the telephone when Mr. Clinton called.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese can hardly be blamed for refusing to accept the
excuses so far offered. On their face they do look rather
ridiculous. For the bombing to have resulted from not having
updated maps to conduct what is hailed as precision bombing, means
one of two things. Either the United States has incompetents
running the intelligence establishment or the bombing was an
attempt by one element of the U.S. government to sabotage Clinton
administration policies.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as the Chinese want a more thorough investigation and to
be told of its findings, the American people should require no
less. But the Chinese government wants a good deal more than what
passes for equity when events of this kind occur between reasonably
friendly countries. They want to defeat American policy in the
Balkans and they want concessions from Washington in order to
obtain membership in the World Trade Organization. They also
apparently want a halt to the newspaper and congressional
complaints about the theft by China of American nuclear weapons
secrets for a large number of years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ostensibly inner and disguised animosity against
America that the Chinese people all along retained hasn't impeded
the flow of their students into American university graduate
programs. Nor has it interfered with the development of economic
relations that have made China, in a handful of years, a major
exporter of consumer goods to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, if instead of developing growing
nation-to-nation cordiality, the Chinese in their heart of hearts
still consider us the implacable enemy, then the United States has
to respond to that reality.
</P>
<P>
   The concessions we have made over the years to Beijing,
including the one-China policy that sacrifices the future
independence of Taiwan to Chinese hegemony, need to be revisited.
It was one thing to reach that position, however painful, to
accommodate new ties that would reshape the face of the
geopolitical world. It is another thing entirely, when we find out
that nothing really has changed, except that we have been taken for
fools.
</P>
<P>
   What goes for America's compromise on Taiwan is redoubled for
selling China the kinds of sophisticated technologies that, it
turns out, might very well be used against us down the road. What
is the sense of bartering our scientific advantages, that the
Chinese either buy or steal from us, for the sake of some
corporations' bottom lines?
</P>
<P>
   What values does that reflect?
</P>
<P>
   By calling the embassy bombing a war crime, the Chinese
obviously are attempting to trivialize what a war crime
constitutes, and thereby deflect an accusing finger from their own
more seriously violative behavior in Tibet and Cambodia, not to
mention running tanks over their own citizens. The United States
owes itself a sobering review of its China policy with a vigorous
emphasis on our own national interests and security. That analysis
should be shaped by the now-revealed understanding that China
regards us not merely as a rival, but as an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
