<HEADER>
A0002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATIONAL-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      05-17 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNC HONORS ITS GRADS WHO DIED FOR DIXIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Memorial days come early in the South _ a
month earlier, like the greening of the land itself, than up north.
</P>
<P>
   And here, on the campus of the University of North Carolina, on
an almost New England-like morning early this month, the mall lined
with 19th-century college buildings, they gave a cathedral-like
solemnity to one of the memorial observances scattered throughout
the former Confederate states.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small event _ no bands, no rifle-fired salute, barely
even an audience. So small an event, it was, that were it not for
the unlikely appearance in that setting of four middle-aged,
business-suited men carrying furled flags and a younger man lugging
a laurel wreath, it could have passed without notice.
</P>
<P>
   With the absence of a single regionwide Confederate memorial
day, memorial services in the South tend to be low-key, according
to Patrick Griffin, commander in chief of the Sons of Confederate
Veterans. Often, Griffin said, they commemorate a Civil War event
that occurred in the local camp's community, or honor that
community's veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the memorial ceremony honored the university's 257
Confederate dead _ ``the flower of Tarheeliana,'' as Nicholas Ladd
of the local Sons of Confederate Veterans camp described them in a
reference to the state's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   It took place before a memorial statue quite unlike the Civil
War monuments familiar from New England greens and commons. The
soldier figures on northern monuments are most often in a solemn
parade-rest position _ symbolizing ``preparedness,'' rather than
``militancy,'' as Kirk Savage has said in his study of Civil War
monuments, ``Standing Soldiers, Kneeling Slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of North Carolina's idealized soldier-figure _
``Silent Sam,'' as he is known on campus _ is carrying his rifle in
the port-arms position, as if advancing into action with shoulders
squared, chin lifted, advancing into the death and glory of the
lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the visiting northerner who came upon it by chance, the
ceremony began as if it would follow in the pattern familiar from
more-familiar Memorial Day observances _ a few opening remarks, an
invocation, the Pledge of Allegiance. But that was followed
immediately _ and without the slightest sense that it was anything
exceptional _ by a ``salute to the Confederate flag'' which had, by
then, been unfurled along with the United States flag, the North
Carolina state flag, and the state's secession flag.
</P>
<P>
   And in an odd way, the brief remarks that followed seemed
directed particularly to that northern visitor _ although Ladd had
written them out beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate flag, Ladd wanted to make clear, ``is not a
racist symbol'' _ although, he added, some have used it that way.
``By today's standards,'' he acknowledged, slavery is ``morally
repugnant.'' But while it was the economic system suited to the
South's agricultural economy, Ladd noted, ``the vast majority'' of
those who fought for the Confederacy were not slave owners, had
little interest in slavery, but were fighting ``to defend their
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then began a reading of the names, the flag-holding men stepping
forward in turn. They read them out by university class, starting
with Leonidas Polk, class of 1821, a graduate also of West Point
and an Episcopal bishop. To the South, a bishop's taking up arms
was seen as evidence of divine support for the cause. But he was
not much of a general, by most accounts, and was cut down by
artillery fire during the skirmishing before the Battle for
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the list went, captains, lieutenants, privates, a naval
ensign and two surgeons. One name that stood out was that of J.
Johnson Pettigrew, class of 1843, who led the North Carolina troops
who valiantly charged the entrenched Union positions at Gettysburg
and died of wounds received there. And finally, William H.C. Webb,
class of 1864, a lieutenant who was mortally wounded at Gettysburg
in July 1863. He was 20.
</P>
<P>
   And when all 257 names had been read out, the entire assemblage
sang ``Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the sprightly ``Dixie'' familiar from Boston Pops July
Fourth concerts, but the saddest, slowest ``Dixie'' you could ever
expect to hear. Slow as a funeral dirge, with the final words,
``Away. Away. Away down South in Dixie'' stretching out slowly into
silence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
