<HEADLINE>
A PATENT THAT COULD HELP HALT COUNTERFEITING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The advent of super-high-quality color photocopiers has led to
an apparent boom in counterfeiting of money, particularly in
economically destabilized countries such as Russia, where by some
estimates 20 percent of the US currency circulating is bogus.
</P>
<P>
   During the 12-month period ending last October, authorities
seized $153 million worth of counterfeit bills, including just
under $70 million in the US. Worldwide, more than $200 million of
fake American legal tender _ about $1 of every $1,800 circulating _
is thought to be counterfeit, and relatively cheap color copiers
have now made it worthwhile for people to forge $5 and $10 bills
they can more easily pass off than fifties and hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Besides prompting the US Treasury Department to launch a
controversial redesign of currency, including most recently the $20
bill sporting an enlarged, off-center portrait of President Andrew
Jackson, the problem has encouraged inventors to develop a host of
new machines to detect fake bills.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a veteran electrical engineering professor
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, George W. Pratt of
Wayland, Mass., won patent 5,899,313 for such a device.
</P>
<P>
   Many existing systems rely on a visual inspection of bills or
test the ink used in printing portraits and borders of to make sure
it is properly magnetic. In contrast, Pratt's system checks whether
the paper it is printed on is the real stuff used by currency paper
maker Crane &AMP; Co. of Dalton, near Pittsfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiching a bill between two electrically charged plates,
Pratt's machine measures the ``dielectric properties'' of the
paper, or the way electricity flows through it. Real Crane paper,
which is heavy in cotton content, has what could be called a unique
electric signature compared to other kinds of paper, and fakes can
be identified in a matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   So far Pratt has what he calls a ``Rube Goldberg lab-type
prototype'' that has worked well enough in tests helped by the
Secret Service that it has elicited strong interest from
manufacturers he met through MIT's industrial liaison program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to have a gadget to test bills that is cheap,''
Pratt said. ``I want something I can put in a laundromat or at a
cash register.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, an MIT graduate who has been on the faculty since 1960,
has some other inventions to his credit, including a sonic device
manufactured by Waltham-based Hologic that measures bone density in
people with osteoperosis. Notably, the device originated in his
interest in race horses and desire to make a system identifying
horses with weak bones.
</P>
</TEXT>
