<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0025 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-BLACKS-ART-BOS &LR;      05-17 1692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-BLACKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK ALUMNAE REVISIT SMITH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHAMPTON, Mass. _ One administrator told them they were a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The 69 young black women made up 10 percent of the Smith College
Class of '74, the largest group of blacks this prim Seven Sister
campus would ever see. Their arrival would have been unusual on any
college campus in 1970, but it was especially so here, amid the
Mary Margarets and Crickets with their Ivory Girl faces, their
horses and maids at home.
</P>
<P>
   The black women were informed they were merely guests, and they
themselves resisted becoming ``Smithies.'' They teased out their
Afros to frighten the white girls and refused to wear caps and
gowns to graduation, instead donning orange or red dresses so no
one could ignore their color or their sass.
</P>
<P>
   And they have harbored more than the usual dose of ambivalence
toward the formative college years _ despite how they cherished the
bonds among them, despite their striking success in fields not
traditionally open to women, much less black women.
</P>
<P>
   As they gathered here for their 25th reunion this weekend, these
women might have been expected to indulge in a bit of nostalgia.
But the black women of '74 also came with a mission: to hold
themselves up as examples _ to young black Smith students, to the
college, and to the nation _ of the power of diversity and open
doors. Now surgeons, bank executives, lawyers, PhD's, they have
been out long enough to appreciate the chance Smith gave them, and
they want to give back, with money, with mentoring, and by example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a commitment to the experiences we would like to
see other young black women have,'' said Linda Smith Charles, chief
organizer behind the reunion blitz of teas, lunches, and pajama
parties. ``Twenty-five years out, we find ourselves in positions
where we can give back, and we are prepared to step up to the
plate. If we can see volumes of black women doing that, we can
really influence change.''
</P>
<P>
   Their return was inspired in part by what has changed. Smith had
a male president when they were here; now it is a black woman. But
they also came because of what hasn't changed: the numbers of
blacks at Smith remain at about 4 percent, and colleges across the
country are struggling for diversity in a post-affirmative-action
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to share our history, set the tone, challenge the
black women at Smith today to assume the same responsibility,''
Charles said. ``There's a spirit about us, and we want to keep that
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Spirit seems an understatement, seeing the energy at a weekend
event ill-described by its official title as a ``tea.'' The room
becomes a swirl of hugs, exclamations, and shrieks of embarrassment
as the old photos come out. (``My blue suede hot pants!'' cried Amy
Robertson Goldson, a Washington lawyer whose clients include the
Congressional Black Caucus.)
</P>
<P>
   This group's bonds started before they arrived as freshmen in
the fall of 1970. The women came from a range of backgrounds. Some
applied to Smith because their parents had wanted their daughters
to attend a Seven Sisters school. Others were encouraged by
teachers, some by the Urban League, which paid their application
fees. But most didn't expect to end up at an all-women school in
the sticks of Western Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   It all changed at an event in the spring of 1970 officially
known as Prefreshmen Weekend, but still recalled here as The Party
of Life. Black students from Smith had invited blacks from half a
dozen other campuses in the Northeast in the hopes of convincing a
sizable group of them to attend the next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dispelled two reservations: one that there wouldn't be
other black folks around, two that there wouldn't be any men,''
said JoAnne Lyons Wooten. ``It showed me that there really was an
opportunity to be part of a community with people who shared my
culture, my political viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleges were eager to increase their numbers of minorities,
which in those days meant almost exclusively blacks. Smith lured
them with hefty scholarships, and arranged for them to live
clustered in three dorms. The black students were given privileges
that now seem extraordinary: a credit card, a van for trips to
classes on other campuses or late-night runs to Friendly's Ice
Cream. When a few students asked for a course in jazz, the school
flew in Miles Davis and Archie Shepp to teach it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what the students wanted more than anything was to be
treated normally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't about going to class and being recognized as a
student,'' said Gail Lewis Lewis, now the special assistant for
medical residency programs at the Los Angeles County Health
Department. ``It was about going to class and being recognized as
just a student, and not as a black student.''
</P>
<P>
   Going unnoticed would not be easy. Many of the white students
said it was the first time they'd been around blacks. They wanted
to touch the black girls' hair and skin. They called them ``the
dressy-up ones.'' The black students had their own questions, like
how a freshman girl could afford a Mercedes, why the white girls
walked barefoot in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   The black students felt antipathy, too, from administrators and
the faculty, which at that time included no blacks. Several women
recalled how the director of financial aid called them one by one
into her office to explain that they had calculated their
admissions offers so that only about 30 blacks would accept; they
hadn't expected so many of the black women to attend.
</P>
<P>
   They sensed the increasing campus security for their parties,
which included black students from campuses across New England.
Store owners in Northampton's quaint downtown would trail the black
students as they browsed. A black student once arrived home from
class to a black national flag burned on her door.
</P>
<P>
   Most people acted not out of racism, but out of ignorance. Lewis
recalled how she wanted to take a horseback-riding class. But, a
college administrator replied, ``You didn't bring your horse!''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the black students considered leaving, but few did.
At least at Smith, there was strength in numbers. They used that to
their advantage, fighting for black faculty and a black studies
major.
</P>
<P>
   They came out with the closest of friends, and a degree that
allowed them to defy anyone who suggested there was anything they
couldn't do. The experience also trained them to be, in the words
of one alum, ``foreigners,'' which was a role they would play again
in the wider world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still facing many of the same issues we had at Smith,''
said Portia Gordon Ketosugbo, a research scientist at Albert
Einstein College of Medicine in New York. ``I've always been the
only African-American in my lab, and I'm constantly feeling I have
to prove myself more than anyone else. I've been there because I've
been very good. But it's a constant struggle to prove that.''
</P>
<P>
   Being out in the world has softened their bitterness toward
Smith; the experience there might have given them a taste of
ignorance, but they have seen worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith took a chance on us, and we're thankful for that,''
Goldson said. ``We think we've represented Smith well, too, and we
want to show that.''
</P>
<P>
   As they hear the national debate on affirmative action and
diversity, they can't help but think of their own experience, and
where they would be without their Smith degree, where they might
have ended up if colleges had not opened their doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affirmative action didn't mean that we didn't have the grades
to get in here, we did,'' Goldson said. ``What it meant was
leveling the playing field, reaching out and making the opportunity
visible.''
</P>
<P>
   The women might not have expected the numbers of black students
to rise after they left _ the national average was less than 8
percent black students when they graduated. But they were
disappointed to discover the numbers decreasing so sharply.
</P>
<P>
   They have stayed close outside of Smith, several traveling to
the Virgin Islands for a collective 40th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But with the inauguration of Ruth Simmons as Smith president
four years ago, they began to think about what they could do for
the college. The first black woman president of any Seven Sister or
Ivy League school, she has lit a spark under them, talking to
audiences across the country about the importance of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Planning this year's reunion, they sent out a letter urging
their black classmates to think of what each could do to make Smith
``the type of institution where all women can grow, learn, and
realize that there are no limits to their potential.''
</P>
<P>
   In three months, they raised $30,000 in scholarship money, with
29 of the original class donating, compared to six donations and a
total of less than $3,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when people felt quite anxious about things
like this,'' Simmons said. ``The notion was somehow that you ought
to march off into the great beyond, nobody should be identified as
black, everybody was part of the same big happy family. The reality
is, the experiences that one goes through shape you, and you want
to share those memories.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend has been a reminiscence of what was, and a
recognition of how far this class has come. Presenting Simmons with
the check, Benita Jo Walton, a reconstructive surgeon, cried and
noted that Ruth Simmons was the first president she could call by
her first name. The Class of '74 urged the Class of '99 not to wait
25 years to ''reengage and reconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   They laughed recalling how they refused to dress like everyone
else on their graduation day 25 years ago. And Saturday morning,
they joined with Smith tradition by dressing in white and red and
marching in the Ivy parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if it says that we have accepted Smith, or that
Smith has accepted us,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking a minute, she decided it was both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
