<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-17 1676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING SHORT WEIGHT TO AN OUNCE OF PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the failure of prevention. It may be American health
care's biggest flaw. And its consequences are especially dire for
elders.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, doctors are failing to prescribe the tests, pills,
and lifestyle changes known to lower mortality and avoid needless
suffering. Despite libraries full of weighty tomes telling
physicians how to minimize the toll of heart disease, high blood
pressure, cancer, diabetes and other killers, medicine's full
potential lies tantalizingly out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many gaps in care that are so maddening,'' says
Dr. Thomas H. Lee, whose job is to figure out how to fill those
gaps for the more than 1.2 million patients who get their care
through Partners Community Healthcare &UR;  &LR; in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The care gaps are ``pretty pervasive, pretty striking and pretty
distressing,'' agrees Dr. Joseph P. Frolkis of the Cleveland
Clinic. ``People are struggling with this problem all across the
country,'' adds Dr. David E. Wennberg of the Maine Medical
Assessment Foundation and Dartmouth Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Study after study documents the problem. Last month, for
instance, Wennberg and his Dartmouth colleagues published an annual
``atlas'' of US health care for elderly Medicare beneficiaries
showing, among other things, that:
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than one-third of older American women get mammograms
every two years, as they should; only 12 percent of elders are
checked in a two-year period for colorectal cancer; and among
elderly diabetics, fewer than half have eye exams to detect early
disease that leads to blindness if left untreated.
</P>
<P>
   That just scratches the surface of what many call the
``prevention gap.'' When people hear ``prevention,'' they often
think of lifestyle changes such as smoking cessation, healthier
diets, weight loss, and regular exercise. These are matters of
personal habit that are largely the patient's responsibility,
ideally with a nudge from the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a large realm of prevention that requires medical
intervention. One sort, which doctors call ``primary prevention,''
encompasses measures to detect early disease in individuals without
symptoms. This includes mammography for breast cancer; rectal exams
and monitoring of enzyme levels to pick up prostate cancer; and
diagnostic tests for colon cancer. Primary prevention also includes
vaccinations against influenza and pneumococcal pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring lapses in preventive medicine, however, involve
``secondary prevention,'' which focuses on the millions of
Americans with ailments such as high blood pressure, heart disease,
and diabetes. Overwhelming evidence shows the health care system is
doing a poor job of applying measures known to prevent serious
disability and death _ often things as simple as prescribing a
beta-blocker drug following a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Take high blood pressure, for instance. With effective control
through diet, exercise, and medication, its worst downstream
effects _ heart attack, stroke, and kidney disease _ can be reduced
by as much as 50 to 75 percent. Yet among the 50 million Americans
with hypertension, the proportion who are aware of their problem
has actually declined over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most disturbing recent evidence on the prevention
gap concerns heart disease, the nation's leading killer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Pearson, chairman of preventive and community
medicine at the University of Rochester, recently concluded a study
of 5,620 patients admitted to 50 US hospitals because of a heart
attack, worsening cardiac symptoms, or the need for a coronary
bypass or angioplasty procedure. These people are at high risk of
death or disability.
</P>
<P>
   Such patients typically have at least two major risk factors _
red flags signalling the need for medical intervention. But Pearson
found that heart specialists typically did not note risk factors in
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Only half of those with high cholesterol had it recorded, along
with fewer than half with diabetes, and less than a third with high
blood pressure, pearson reported at a recent conference in Waltham
sponsored by the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown was not simply a matter of record-keeping. At
hospital discharge, only 42 percent of these typical heart patients
went home with recommendations for cholesterol-lowering drug
treatment. This is despite strong evidence that lowering ``bad
cholesterol''levels reduces the chance of a second heart attack or
death by 25 to 40 percent _ a benefit, Pearson notes, that ``rivals
or exceeds'' costly bypass and angioplasty procedures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unchecked diabetes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such missed opportunities are not restricted to heart disease.
``The majority of diabetes patients referred to me have not had
most of the five or six things that should be checked regularly,''
says Dr. David M. Nathan, chief of Massachusetts General Hospital's
diabetes center. ``Sometimes it's pretty frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kind of disconnect,'' observes the Cleveland
Clinic's Frolkis. ``Physicians, when interviewed, support the idea
of prevention and are often quite knowledgeable about the content
of specific guidelines. But they follow them only 20 to 60 percent
of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the fault is the physician's. The patient is to blame,
of course, if she or he fails to take the prescribed medication or
follow dietary orders. Of the three billion US prescriptions
written annually, only half are thought to be filled and taken as
directed. Nearly 90 percent of patients with hypertension taking
their pills within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet is this always the patient's fault? Among 3,260 Medicare
enrollees, more than a third of English-speakers and 54 percent of
Spanish-speakers were found to be ``medically illiterate'' in a
recent study in the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medically illiterate'' doesn't necessarily mean patients can't
read, but rather that they cannot grasp doctors' instructions and
health messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing a good job of communicating with patients,''
says Dr. Harlan Krumholz of Yale University. ``For instance, I
recently saw a 77-year-old black woman with a history of heart
attack. She didn't know what blood pressure was, what her blood
pressure target should be, what relationship blood pressure has to
heart disease. She couldn't name foods high in fat, salt, or
cholesterol.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A word of advice
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of patients' education level, research shows they
need clear information and encouragement to stick with chronic
treatment regimens.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologist Richard Pasternak and his colleagues at
Massachusetts Genral Hospital are launching a program to telephone
elderly patients who have not filled their prescriptions. And
Cleveland Clinic doctors are beginning to send heart patients home
from the hospital with written treatment instructions, since they
found that heart specialists weren't addressing post-hospital
treatment _ even when prompted.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe major gaps in preventive care will narrow only when
patients take a more active role, such as pressing their doctors
about a mammography or prostate exam, a blood pressure reading,
cholesterol test, or an eye exam if they haven't had one in awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, experts are doing more than wringing their hands over
the situation. Momentum is building behind major efforts to close
health care's prevention gaps. But those who have tried warn that
it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Counting heads
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The argument has often been made that managed care plans will
improve care because they have a stake in keeping patients healthy
_ especially within ``capitated'' plans that put doctors at
financial risk if their patients fall ill and consume more
resources. But many now doubt that premise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capitation has not been a friend of prevention,'' says MGH's
Pasternak. Tina Brown Stevenson, a Partners vice president, agrees:
``No one wants to invest in prevention. The payoff is way down the
line when someone doesn't have a stroke or kidney disease. Most
health plans say, `In three years the patient will be with another
plan.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is some evidence that health professionals do respond
to concerted efforts _ especially when the stakes include monetary
rewards and public disclosure of their performance. When Tufts
Health Plan offered Partners a $400,000 bonus if they could raise
the rates of mammograms and flu shots among the elders in the
Tufts' Secure Horizon's plan, Partners doctors hustled _ and
exceeded the 20 percent improvement target.
</P>
<P>
   There are major efforts at the national level too. The federal
Health Care Financing Administration, which runs Medicare, is
embarking on a campaign to get doctors to prescribe more aspirin
and beta-blocker drugs to heart attack patients. ``We think we
might be able to reduce mortality from a repeat heart attack on the
order of 3,000 lives a year at the end of the three-year period,''
says Dr. Stephen Jencks, the agency's director of quality
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   And the National Committee on Quality Assurance (NCQA), a
voluntary group that tries to improve care in health maintenance
organizations, has begun to require health plans to measure and
publicly report what proportion of their subscribers have their
cholesterol below specified targets and, next year, how many have
their blood pressure under control.
</P>
<P>
   Because competition among HMOs is so keen, the hope is that
public disclosure of performance on these measures will get care
providers' attention as nothing else has. ``In terms of public
health, we all feel this will have more impact than anything we've
been involved with in our careers,'' says Lee, the Partners
official, who is on the NCQA committee. ``These measures will save
many, many lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox's e-mail address is knox(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-17 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO CITY HALL AWES AND SUBTLY INSPIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- When Oscar Wilde visited this city 100 years
ago, he made the usual remarks. ``San Francisco is a really
beautiful city,'' he said, ``the most artistic town I have ever
come across.'' The Irish playwright added the observation that San
Franciscans ``have determined that they will have nothing about
them that is not beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude persists in spite of fire, flood, and earthquake.
Mostly earthquake. On April 18, 1906, the earth shook for 48
seconds, registering 8.25 on the Richter scale. The damage and
subsequent fire killed 700 people and destroyed 28,000 buildings,
including City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting a plan by Daniel Burnham, the city planned a civic
center with a new City Hall in the Beaux-Arts style, its dome
rising 307 feet above Van Ness Avenue, 40 feet higher than the US
Capitol. From 73 entries, the winners were John Bakewell Jr. and
Arthur Brown Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Their curlicues and cornucopias of marble and granite greet
visitors today. Finished in 1915 at a cost of $4 million, it is one
of the grandest public structures on this continent. City Halls in
Albany and Minneapolis have their charms, but this one awes and
subtly inspires.
</P>
<P>
   When its city council, the Board of Supervisors, meets to decide
about stop signs and one-way streets, it gathers in a chamber fit
for a medieval monarch. Ornate columns of Manchurian oak soar above
the bureaucratic babble.
</P>
<P>
   A ceremonial staircase, featured in several movies, rises under
the dome, leading to the office where 10 mayors enjoyed the view
until the evening of Oct. 17, 1989, when a 7.1 magnitude earthquake
struck in Loma Prieta. Although the death and damage did not match
that of 1906, City Hall was declared unsafe and forced to close.
San Franciscans had to decide what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Seismic retrofitting would be expensive. Hoisting a 90,000-ton
structure onto the equivalent of roller skates would also take
time. The building now rests on 600 ``base isolators,'' allowing 26
inches of lateral movement. Workers spent years hauling 30,000
pieces of carved marble to warehouses, returning them to
steel-reinforced upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's politicians have always been adept at wangling
federal funds, so $78 million for earthquake damage became
available, along with $27 million from the state of California. To
finance the rest of the $300 million project, citizens had to
approve a bond issue of $293 million for seismic repair of public
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Had the vote been taken in one of California's other 57
counties, the result may have been a low-rise trailer park
dedicated to the instincts of taxophobia. San Franciscans approved
the bond issue, staying true to their belief ``that they will have
nothing about them that is not beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mayor James (Sunny Jim) Rolph placed the cornerstone in
1913, he said, ``This an event made possible by the liberality,
optimism, pride, and confidence of our own citizens in their own
city.'' The current mayor, Willie L. Brown Jr., was told when he
was elected in 1995 that his office would not be ready until the
next century. Like many successful mayors, he is obsessive and
urgent. Brown replied, ``That project will be finished in my first
term.''
</P>
<P>
   City Hall re-opened early this year, with user-friendly touches.
In hearing rooms, padded seats protect spectators. Two ``light
courts'' have been restored on the first floor, once honeycombed
with desks and low ceilings. Sunlight floods a 60-by-120-foot
chamber where visitors enjoy a cafe and memorabilia shop.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions San Franciscans have made give the city an
architectural dignity and unity that is almost Parisian. Aesthetics
and politics blend happily here. Mayor Brown is an
African-American. Architect Arthur Brown, who also designed Coit
Tower and other notable buildings, was not. Say, Mr. Mayor, are you
guys related? Willie's cool reply: ``We're checking the DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SILLERMAN-2ND &LR;  &UR;      05-17 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SILLERMAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... right price.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There are some,'' Sillerman says in response to concerns like
this, ``who say `I am afraid of the SFX presentation' and I say to
them: `See what the other 90 or 95 percent of the people who are
willing to work with us _ and continue to work with us _ say. Be
open-minded and do what's best for you and your fans.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But is SFX itself doing what's best for concertgoers? Or is
Sillerman building this empire only to sell it, as he did with SFX
Broadcasting? And to sell it, perhaps, to one of the media
mega-conglomerates like Disney or Time Warner?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never founded a company for the purpose of selling it,'' he
responds. ``I happen to be the largest shareholder in this
company,'' with a reported 9 percent of the stock. ``If somebody
came in and said `Here's $200 a share,' if I didn't agree to that
I'd be sued and maybe killed.'' (SFX currently trades at around $60
a share.) But in the meantime, ``we're operating the company as if
it's going to be here forever,'' says Sillerman, adding that he
fantasizes about the day when his daughter Mckinley, now 6, might
take over.
</P>
<P>
   Pollstar's Bongiovanni is not convinced Sillerman is around for
the long haul. ``A lot of people expect that (selling out) is his
real endgame. Time will tell. He's had great taste in the assets
he's bought. But he's carrying a huge debt load'' _ $742 million,
according to published reports _ ``and I'm not sure they can
challenge that with concert business. The rule of thumb is most of
the money goes to the artist and representative and the risk goes
to the promoter. You may make 5 or 10 percent on a sellout.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, of course, the bottom line is ticket prices, and
the concern is that a near-monopoly like SFX will raise them. A box
office manager whose company is now part of the SFX chain says we
should look for more and more corporate boxes and worse seats for
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what you are asking in terms of pricing,'' says
Sillerman, ``so I'm by no means avoiding the question. But when one
has a certain financial capability, it does provide you with the
ability to take more risk, and no individual event becomes that
important. . . . We presented 13,000 events last year . . . and
from our point of view, a show doesn't need to make money in
Boston, it needs to make money'' nationally.
</P>
<P>
   A time of fear
</P>
<P>
   Says Metropolitan's Scher: ``I think the consumer has a great
deal to fear and we are living that fear right now. It's a topic of
conversation all the time. Contrary to Economics 101, where a
monopoly reduces the price to the talent, they, not yet being a
monopoly, are trying to exclude competitors. . . . On that basis,
they're significantly overpaying talent.''
</P>
<P>
   People paid $150 to see Neil Young recently. Top price is $115
to see Bob Dylan and Paul Simon this summer; the best seats for
Cher _ Cher! _ will cost $75. Is this the future of paying to hear
``superstar'' acts?
</P>
<P>
   Sillerman: ``First of all, I don't set the ticket prices. It's a
misnomer that the promoter does that. There has been no analysis of
supply and demand. Last summer we surveyed five shows in nine
amphitheaters, 45,000 tickets, and found for the front 1,000 of any
of those shows none of the people paid face value. They bought them
through scalpers and ticket agencies. Whether it's a blockbuster or
a lesser show, there is a core group of people that will pay an
increased amount of money. The fact that that money was not
captured by the artist or the promoter actually inflated the price
of the other tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, if X amount of money is needed to cover the costs, why
not have the high rollers pay a big chunk of it directly, rather
than have the scalpers and ticket agencies siphon off the money?
``Then,'' says Sillerman, ``the back rows are going to be priced
less expensively. This `auction process,' if you will, is taking
money away from (artists) and precluding us from lowering prices
elsewhere. One hundred percent of our amphitheaters are going to be
tiered so that there will be more expensive tickets, but there will
be many more that are less expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sillerman says the Tweeter Center, for example, should have
three or four different tiers. ``It doesn't make any sense that
most shows were the same price,'' he says. ``Clearly, different
acts have different appeal, so therefore what we're going to do is
what Sam Walton clearly approved of: Lowering prices is brilliant,
and we'll get more people in the amphitheaters. That is in our best
interest and the artist's best interest. If there's 1,000 tickets
where prices are increased, there'll be 2,000, 3,000, or 4,000
where they are decreased.''
</P>
<P>
   Bongiovanni says the public shouldn't fear SFX, but says,
``There's no doubt we've seen a dramatic increase in pricing levels
in the last several years for the best seats at the biggest
concerts _ at least for the ones that draw an older demo, with the
presumption being that the audience can pay for it. That trend
predates SFX's entrance into the marketplace, but it's pretty clear
they've embraced it. Concert tickets are a volatile commodity, it's
a supply-and-demand economy, and the public has already dictated
that concert tickets are undervalued by its wilingness to pay
ticket brokers exorbitant fees. You're a schmuck if you don't do
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little more cynical'' about multitiered pricing,
Bongiovanni adds. ``Artists want to make as much as they can and
also want to play to a full house. It's a delicate balance. A lot
of times, the hardest tickets to sell are the cheap seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us full circle to Sillerman's question: Why talk to
him about the concert business? Does Robert F. X. Sillerman know
what he's doing?
</P>
<P>
   The QB approach
</P>
<P>
   At the companies SFX has bought, apparently, it's pretty much
business as usual. To that extent, it would seem, Sillerman hasn't
made much direct difference. Says one higher-up at such a company:
``We're like today's quarterbacks in the NFL. We're running the
plays, but we're not calling them.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the man who is calling them delivered that keynote
speech to his colleagues in the business. It was a rambling,
somewhat puzzling speech that was criticized by some in the
industry for its vagueness. Sillerman championed the communal value
of the concertgoing experience in an Internet age _ pretty much ABC
stuff. ``It was amazing,'' says one promoter. ``He's in a roomful
of promoters explaining why it's important to do live shows.
(itals)They already know.(unitals) He's obviously a smart guy, but
everyone was waiting to hear what the point was, and he's trying to
be one of the boys, but it backfired.''
</P>
<P>
   Added another industry source: ``He's not one of the boys.''
</P>
<P>
   And as to SFX's plans _ what everybody really wanted to know _
Sillerman didn't say much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Moses coming down from the mountain revealing the
tablets,'' says Werlin, of Great Northeast, of the anticipation in
the room. ``Here's a man who has so much influence, and it was
astonishing he would impart so little useful information about his
intentions or whatever his dream is _ good, bad, or indifferent.
It's what he didn't say _ like in jazz, the space between the notes
is resonant.''
</P>
<P>
   Sillerman says he was operating under strict guidelines not to
say much, because of a pending business deal. ``But if people
expected us to come out and say `This is how it is going to be
different and this is what we are going to do that is going to
change your lives, and it is either going to be better or worse,' I
have no such statements to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fundamentally good and sound business,'' he
concludes, one that would benefit from ``the integration of
previously disparate and sometimes inefficient'' companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
