<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE AT DEFENSE: MAKE APOLOGIES, NOT WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We are watching Defense Secretary William Cohen
on C-SPAN and talking about how much things have changed in the war
department.
</P>
<P>
   Says my friend, who served in the peace-time Navy: ``I think I
liked it better when we didn't apologize and make excuses. What do
people think war is these days? Can you imagine William
Westmoreland saying, `I'm sorry,' and promising to investigate
every bomb that hit the wrong target?''
</P>
<P>
   When I say ``the war department,'' by the way, I mean it
generically, not as a reference to the long-gone U.S. Department of
War. Since 1947, America officially makes defense, not war.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, we seem to make particularly defensive defense.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, sorry about that convoy of ethnic Albanians, that
hospital, that train of civilians, that Chinese Embassy. We have
soda straw views from 10,000 feet, you know. And old maps. Really
sorry. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   On C-SPAN, Cohen and his much-decorated chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, Army Gen. Henry Shelton, are asking the Senate
Budget Committee for billions of dollars for the Department of Make
Defense Not War.
</P>
<P>
   What Cohen and Shelton want is not as much as some senators
think they should have but more than a few want to give. Because
several senators have asked, Cohen defends defense efforts in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there have been some mishaps, he says, but they must be
looked at in context: 18,000 missions in 45 days, 4,000 of them
attack missions. Some 10,000 munitions have been dropped even
though bad weather has provided NATO air forces with only five or
six ``really clear'' days.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic, says Cohen, has lost 100
percent of his oil refining capability, 60 percent of his
ammunition production facilities, nine of his 14 MIG-29s, 30 to 40
percent of his existing ammunition, two of his own residences and
multiple headquarters of such entities as his army, air force and
political party.
</P>
<P>
   As for the United States, adds Cohen, we have lost a couple of
Apache helicopters, a couple of planes and no lives.
</P>
<P>
   I try to picture Robert McNamara or Melvin Laird _ the
secretaries of Make Defense Not War when Gen. Shelton was a Green
Beret platoon leader in Vietnam _ cast in this role.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's voice is soft and careful. His sensitive, always
startled-looking eyes seem especially wounded as they make contact
with the likes of Sens. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., and Judd Gregg,
R-N.H. Try as he might to present a poker-face to senators, his
whole body seems to register every lukewarm compliment, every
subtle put-down, every overt insult.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, during his Senate confirmation hearings,
Cohen was considerably less defensive. Facing the Armed Services
Committee on which he'd served for three terms, he said he wanted
the world to know that all U.S. troops would be out of Bosnia after
June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to end at that point,'' Cohen said. ``We are not
and cannot become the world's policeman, neither can we become a
prisoner of world events, isolated and tucked safely away in a
continental cocoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Milosevic missed that speech. It is nearly June 1999
and we are deeper than ever into the Balkans; we are both the
world's police and the prisoner of its events.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps toughest of all for Cohen and Shelton, we are making war
on Serbia, but we are not fighting a war.
</P>
<P>
   How many reporters asked if it was absolutely necessary to
destroy all of Dresden? How many misdirected U.S. bombs killed how
many Vietnamese civilians? How many ``oops'' were shuffled out the
back door of even Desert Storm by the Pentagon's sophisticated
media-briefing machine?
</P>
<P>
   Today, nothing gets lost in the shuffle. There is no chaos of
war because there is no war. Thanks to CNN and the Internet, every
mishap and mistake stick out like neon-lit tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's motive is suspect _ even the generals' _ and every
move is second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my friend's nostalgia, I'll bet that we will be a
better, more peaceful people for these changes. Some day.
</P>
<P>
   But the transition period may be long and awkward. Especially
for the people who work in the no-win Department of Make Defense
Not War.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
