<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSHER-SEX-HNS &LR;      05-17 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSHER-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBI DRAWS ON JEWISH TRADITIONS TO HELP COUPLES IMPROVE SEX LIVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rabbi Shmuley Boteach believes sex is dead. That's why
he is working passionately and religiously to resurrect romance and
love in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old, bearded, bespectacled rabbi, who married the
only girl he ever dated, is the author of ``Kosher Sex''
(Doubleday, $19.95). Dispensing wry humor, pop psychology
statistics and thoughtful observations from Jewish tradition,
Boteach (BO-te-ya) is crusading against the decline of marriage and
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex is dead because a fulfilling sex life cannot be had
without (emotional) intimacy,'' said Boteach, a London-based rabbi
who lectured in Houston recently. ``Today people are making love
with an emotional condom.''
</P>
<P>
   Boteach rattles off statistics and observations:
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of single men and women over 40 have not had sex
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Married people have sex twice a week that lasts 5 1/2 minutes
at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes six minutes to brew a good cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Boteach focuses on enduring relationships as a result of his
parents' breakup when he was 8. He has made it a life's work to
find qualities that make marriage both permanent and happy.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the genders today are characterized by
bed-hopping, casual sex, lack of commitment _ and much unhappiness,
said Boteach, who is a family counselor as well as a chaplain at
Oxford University. He and his wife have six children.
</P>
<P>
   Too many young men are afflicted with emotional distance even if
they are living with very compatible women, he said. And some
women, failing to have their emotional needs met, resort to
coercive or obsessive acts to force a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more she pushes him, the more he withdraws. Both sexes are
responsible for the downward spiral of this gap and divide
separating the sexes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The unhappiness is evident in marriage. ``How can (American)
society sustain a 50 percent divorce rate?'' he said. ``And let's
not forget that the divorce rate does not acknowledge how many
people break up before they marry.''
</P>
<P>
   One survey found that American men and women averaged six
serious breakups before marrying. ``That is a heart that has been
broken a lot of times,'' he said. ``The result is that people are
afraid of falling in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Marriage today often includes prenuptial agreements, separate
bank accounts and separate names.
</P>
<P>
   Boteach said premarital sex is part of the problem. Men and
women have become experts in sex. They wind up rating each other,
ratings that can turn a promising relationship into a sex derby, he
said. But great sex doesn't mean the couple is benefiting from
emotional sharing and bonding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are connecting but remaining strangers to each other,'' he
said. ``On an intimacy scale of 1 to 10, you may physically be at
10, but emotionally only at a 2 or 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasis on sex results in men and women focusing on their
bodies rather than their inner characters and attributes. ``If you
continue to have passionate sex and no intimacy or no closeness, if
you just rub bodies together and create friction ... you are going
to go off the whole sexual thing,'' he said. ``Sex will die.''
</P>
<P>
   But a fulfilling life of shared emotional intimacy between a man
and a woman cannot be sustained without passionate sex, he writes
in his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only sex has the power to call forth our deepest, most
powerful emotions,'' he writes. ``Sex and commitment are the
ultimate forms of human closeness, and we cannot be close and
distant at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Boteach pointed out that one of the biblical words for sex is
``to know,'' as in ``Adam came to know his wife Eve'' (Genesis
4:1). It is that intimate knowledge of the other that solidifies
husband and wife, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boteach provides several suggestions for husbands and wives to
avoid destructive boredom and routine. One is based on the Orthodox
Jewish ban on intercourse during menstruation.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that couples voluntarily abstain from sex for two
weeks and focus on sharing activities and building good
friendships. That will prepare them for passion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He advocates the return to modest dressing: ``An immodest
generation loses the right of attraction to the human body.''
</P>
<P>
   All human senses need to be involved in the relationship,
Boteach said _ not just sight. Hearing, smell and touch should be
part of a couple's intimate moments. And he advises people to keep
their eyes open during sex: ``We close our eyes during sex; what
we're trying to do is tune out our partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance is not going to go well in the bedroom if it is not
going well in the living room,'' he said. Too many couples regard
sex as the relationship's goal rather than the culmination of
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the book's advice is rather direct, which has caused
some conservative-minded Jews to be critical of his candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe 10 percent of Jews are afraid of modernity and believe
that sex is something dirty that should not be discussed in
public,'' he said in response.
</P>
<P>
   While a devout Jew, Boteach does not use religion to cause
guilt. He avoids negative concepts such as sin in favor of positive
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to ``Kosher Sex'' convinces Boteach that a sexual
counterrevolution is under way. The book has been well-received in
England, the United States and South Africa. It is being translated
into French, German, Spanish and Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are feeling the crisis in intimacy,'' he said. ``They
are tired of being strangers; it has become a very lonely world.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants the religious community to deal with sexuality and
sexual morality more openly with similar books. Religion, he said,
has allowed the secular community to take the lead on sexuality.
``What has happened is that we let sex be discussed by purveyors of
sleaze rather than sanctity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His fans turned out for his lecture at the Jewish Community
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In modern America, people go from relationship to relationship
to relationship and get involved sexually very quickly,'' said
Holly Cin, a married Rice University graduate student in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The book) addresses why you shouldn't do that and about the
practice of monogamy,'' Cin said. ``It is old advice, but not
common advice anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Relationships are in trouble,'' said a psychologist who asked
not to be identified. ``He makes some very good observations about
relationships today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he said anything entirely new, but he has a way
of saying it that makes you want to listen,'' the psychologist
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Jew who lives in the perimeters of Houston should have
been here, including the rabbis,'' Berte Toppell said. ``He said it
so deliciously, `Don't go by the surface.'''
</P>
<P>
   Toppell lost her husband after 52 years of marriage and was
delighted to hear Boteach advise spouses that a little jealousy
doesn't hurt. ``I adored my husband, and I was so jealous of him,''
she said joyously.
</P>
<P>
   Dorit Golan, a single mother of three and twice divorced, came
to hear ``how to keep a relationship going with a man the
old-fashioned way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 10-year-old daughter,'' Golan said. ``I want her to
learn what my mother never taught me: how to have a relationship
with a man and not have sex before you get married. ... That's
where my generation needs to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
