<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CATS, BALD IS BEAUTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; see the producers of the upcoming movie ``Austin Powers: The
Spy Who Shagged Me,'' have high hopes for Mr. Bigglesworth,
fearless furless feline companion of Dr. Evil, Powers's nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   An item in a recent Entertainment Weekly reported that New Line,
the studio releasing the ``Austin Powers'' sequel, has launched a
plush (but, I assume, not too plush) toy in the likeness of the
film's ``bald baddie,'' portrayed by a cat actor named Mel Gibskin.
Other Mr. Bigglesworth products may be forthcoming, among them Evil
Cat Chow.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Mr. Bigglesworth can supplant
Gidget, the Taco Bell dog, as top pop-culture creature of the
moment. Hairless cat vs. (nearly) hairless dog? Bald is indeed
beautiful, among celebrity animals at least.
</P>
<P>
   Cats magazine named Mr. Bigglesworth Cat of the Year. Cat Fancy
magazine recently profiled Bigglesworth's breed, the sphynx. And
fans of the comic strip ``Robotman'' know that another hairless
cat, Fleshy, is also a media star, a key player in several story
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Even a determined cat lover may have reservations about the
sphynx. I met my first at a recent cat show. He looked like a cat.
He sounded like a cat. But he was totally bald. I wanted to pet
him, but touching the entries is bad cat-show form. I asked his
owner what he feels like. ``A warm peach,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sphynx breed is very controversial, according to Desmond
Morris's ``Cat World: A Feline Encyclopedia.'' It's a fairly recent
breed, having arisen from a mutation, a hairless kitten born in
Toronto in 1966. Morris notes that it has been called ``the ugliest
cat alive,'' but that other people have said the cat is ``so ugly
it's beautiful.'' Sphynx fanciers, he notes, believe that its
unusually sociable and affectionate nature more than compensates
for its bizarre appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Kelly of Kelly Cattery in Dighton, Mass., who breeds the
sphynx, vouches for their friendliness. ``They're very outgoing,
very people-oriented, very playful,'' she says. ``They like to jump
on your shoulder and balance there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly points out another reason for the growing popularity of
the breed: they're hypo-allergenic. Most people who can't tolerate
cats can live quite happily with a sphynx, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also breeds bengals, spotted cats that originated as a
cross between a domestic cat and the wild Asian leopard cat. She
was looking for another unusual breed when, almost 20 years ago,
she saw her first sphynx. At that time the cat was quite rare. Ten
years passed before Kelly was able to acquire a breeding female.
</P>
<P>
   The sphynx is not the easiest cat to rear because the kittens
are very vulnerable to cold. ``They have to be kept very warm in
the first weeks or they'll die,'' Kelley says. ``The babies are
very fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   The adult cats, too, require a warm environment. Kelly advises
sphynx owners who don't want to keep their homes at at 80 degrees
or higher to make sure their cats wear sweaters. ``You can make
them out of sweat shirt sleeves,'' she says. ``The cat's head goes
through the cuff, and you cut little holes for the legs.''
</P>
<P>
   When a sphynx is cold it tends to grow fur, ``a little fuzz,
like a kiwi fruit,'' Kelley says. (Apparently these cats are
destined to be compared with various fruits.) The more fur, the
less valuable the cat. But fuzzy or not, the sphynx is expensive. A
show-quality cat can cost $2,500, a pet quality animal $700.
</P>
<P>
   If Mr. Bigglesworth prompts a sphynx boom will we eventually see
lots of hairless cats in shelters? Kelly doubts it. ``There aren't
that many breeders,'' she says. ``This is one cat that can't be
mass-produced.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRUSH-MAN-ART-BOS &LR;      05-17 1571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUSH-MAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FULLER BRUSH MAN SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yup. He's still around.
</P>
<P>
   He's still walking neighborhood sidewalks, ringing doorbells,
pulling out his wares from a satchel.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he's become increasingly obsolete over the years. But not
in Newton, Mass., where Al Cohen pounds the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   At age 47, Cohen is a six-day-a-week door-to-door Fuller Brush
salesman. Or as he puts it when he knocks on doors: ``Hello, Fuller
Brush man here.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who came of age any time from the '30s to the early
'60s, those words bring back memories of the friendly fellow who
came to front doors with a case filled with mops and brooms and
brushes. A fellow almost as endemic to the neighborhood as the
milkman.
</P>
<P>
   But that was back when most women were housewives. Keeping the
home clean was a top priority, and they were always looking for new
products to achieve their goal. Plus, it was a time when locks were
rarely turned, on house or car doors, and neighborhoods were more,
well, neighborly.
</P>
<P>
   So how can Cohen survive in today's world of women in the work
force, how can he compete with sprawling suburban shopping malls,
the Internet, the Home Shopping Network, and the millions of
catalogs that flood American mailboxes? And now that the streets of
suburbia are a bit meaner and doors are locked and often stay
locked even when folks are home _ just who keeps this brushman in
business?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the last of a dying breed,'' admits the 30-year sales
veteran, who is short, jocular, and dressed in a red windbreaker, a
checkered shirt, striped tie, and gray pants. ``But I have a
customer base of about 1,000 that I've built up over the years and
I enjoy serving them. Many of them are retired, but I've got a lot
of boomers, too. What's most difficult is that people have so
little free time these days. And it's hard to catch them at home.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement. Drive along any street in his
territory _ Newton and the southern part of Brookline _ and the
curbs and driveways are carless. Houses sit with blinds drawn and
little red alarm buttons signal that they're armed and empty. There
are no kids or bikes on the lawns, nor women hanging laundry on the
backyard clotheslines of yesteryear. There's just an eerie
stillness as Cohen steers his small red Toyota along the barren
streets _ hoping he'll find a car in a driveway and thus a human at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not always the key,'' says Cohen, who started
selling Fuller Brush products in Hull during the summer he turned
16. ``Some people actually put their cars in their garages. So I
stop and knock on doors even when there aren't any cars around.''
</P>
<P>
   In and out. In and out. Cohen gets in and out of his car dozens
of times a day. When he leaves home, he selects a neighborhood,
then a street. He parks his car. He gets out. He opens the back of
his hatchback. He grabs his satchel and a carpet sweeper. He locks
the car, walks up to a house, and rings the doorbell. Only twice,
never three times _ he doesn't want to be bothersome. If no one is
home, he retraces his steps and heads for the next house. He always
carries his bag of products and trusty carpet sweeper.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an exciting job, but it can be a dangerous one.
Several years ago, Cohen was bitten in the stomach by a customer's
overprotective German shepherd. It can also be a cold and windy
job. To avoid a repeat performance and the jaws of two Doberman
pinschers, Cohen conducted business with a client while shivering
in the driveway of her home one winter day _ the two pointy-eared
beasts barking at him from the warmth of their living room. And it
can be a conspiratorial job. He helped a customer hide $100 worth
of purchases in the basement _ all the better to keep the stash
hidden from her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gray, vice president of consumer sales and marketing at
Fuller Brush, a division of CPAC, a chemical manufacturing firm
headquartered in Leicester, N.Y., says Fuller Brush is ``alive and
well.'' ``There are an estimated 10,000 independent Fuller Brush
distributors nationwide,'' says Karen McCulley of CPAC's
marketing/media department. ``But that figure fluctuates from month
to month.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 10,000 representatives do not all work full time, like
Cohen. The majority, says Earl Goff, 71, of Rehoboth, who is
celebrating his 50th year with Fuller Brush, are women who do not
go door to door but sell part time to friends, friends of friends,
and co-workers. Although Goff made a good living and supported his
family through his sales, Cohen says he takes home only $15,000 to
$17,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have made more if I recruited people to work under me,
but I like being independent,'' says Cohen, who grew up in Hyde
Park and moved to Newton, where he lives with his parents. ``And I
like my customers. After all these years, I pretty much know what
people need and want, so I don't mind leaving a catalog under their
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Such catalogs are relatively new. Fuller Brush first began to
print them in 1988. Since then, the company has also opened 10
factory outlets and plans to expand its Web site _ but must be
careful not to interfere with the sales of loyal local
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Hartford, Conn. in 1906 by Somerville, Mass. native
Alfred C. Fuller, the company became a household name during the
'30s and '40s. It became synonymous with the image of the
suitcase-toting door-to-door salesman. But with and the growth of
malls and women in the workplace in the '60s and '70s came a
rapidly shifting sales territory. And Fuller Brush went the way of
many small companies: It was bought by Consolidated Foods in 1968
and in 1994 by CPAC.
</P>
<P>
   It was also in 1968 that Cohen began his trekking for Fuller
Brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at my parents' summer home in Hull and we were talking
about the job I'd lined up for the summer. I was going to start the
next day at Nemo's hot-dog stand in Paragon Park,'' says Cohen, who
during the summer still sells in Hull, a resort area just outside
Boston, and lives in a basement apartment in his parents' cottage.
``While we were talking, the Fuller Brush man came to the door and
overheard us. He said, `Do I have a job for you!' And he signed me
right up.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked on and off for Fuller for 20 years and full time since
1989. Cohen worked in his father's appliance store for 10 years and
then owned his own businesses in Boston and suburban Norwood before
high rents sent him back to Fuller Brush full time. ``There are no
sales territories today, so I have Newton to myself. I think I've
knocked on every door in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of my clients are 45 and up,'' says Cohen, who
averages 300 miles a week on his rounds. A lot of young people
aren't familiar with the name. He hits the homes of regular
customers once or twice a year, or he'll go more often if they call
with an order. January is his slowest month. From October until the
holidays is his busiest time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a door slammed in my face,'' he says, adding
that he's even dated a couple of his regular customers' daughters,
but has never married. ``I don't feel at all nervous about knocking
on doors cold _ I've been at this too long.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent crisp, sunny morning, Cohen heads for Newton's Oak
Hill neighborhood. He knocks on 14 doors before he gets a hit _ 2
of the 14 doors were opened by women who were ``too busy'' to talk.
At the 15th house, the customer buys three mop sponges.
</P>
<P>
   At the next house he's greeted by ``Oh Al, I've been waiting for
you. I need some kind of brush to clean the tiles in my bathroom.''
Cohen has the ``perfect'' product, he says, and makes a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a retired male customer greets Cohen by name
and buys almost $70 worth of merchandise. This is second-generation
selling _ Cohen used to sell to the man's mother. At the next
house, things look good. The woman is interested in a pair of
poultry shears, but when she shows them to her husband, she comes
back and shakes her head. No sale. Still, she takes a catalog.
Cohen is confident he'll get a call. She's bought from him before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's such a very nice young man,'' Vivian Graham, one of
Cohen's longtime customers, says during a phone conversation.
``I've been buying from him for 10 or 12 years. He's not pushy and
(is) so polite. I've bought several of those little carpet sweepers
_ one for my home here, one for our Maine house, and one for my
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also sells to small businesses _ insurance agencies, hair
salons, and restaurants. Mary English, an administrator for Hammond
Realty in Newton, has been buying from Cohen for about eight years.
``He's so sweet,'' says English. ``He's happy when you buy
something from him and just as pleasant if you don't. He's not one
of these high-pressure types. He comes by the office three or four
times a year and we all buy something from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long he'll continue his door-to-door career, Cohen
pauses and says he's not sure. ``I got my real estate license
several years ago, but most places want me to work 60 hours a week
and on weekends. I'm not used to that. I don't want to work those
kind of hours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
