<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0055 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-EXPOSURE-BOS &LR;      05-17 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EXPOSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID BREASHEARS TAKES READERS TO `HIGH' PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HIGH EXPOSURE 
An Enduring Passion for Everest and Unforgiving Places 
By David Breashears 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 319 pp., illustrated, $26 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Breashears, mountaineer and cinematographer, is one of
those rare people who turns a childhood dream into reality. The
Brighton resident became widely known after his IMAX film team
became involved in the 1996 Everest disaster. Breashears, 43, had
already achieved prominence in climbing and film circles, but with
the subsequent large-format blockbuster ``Everest,'' he became
hero, sex symbol, and adventurer extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't address that sudden fame in his captivating
autobiography, ``High Exposure,'' but he does offer up other
intimacies _ about his violent father, a failed marriage, and his
own difficulties with anger and control.
</P>
<P>
   His father, an Army officer, left the family of three sons and a
daughter when Breashears was 10. He writes: ``It was during this
bleak time that I discovered the book `Mountains' and the photo of
the Sherpa Tenzing Norgay atop Mount Everest. I was transfixed.
Tenzing's pose on that barren slope of rock and snow _ the highest
point on the face of the earth _ bespoke honor and hope and
transcendence. It imparted directly to me a promise that up there,
on that forbidding mountain, lay a path of clean and simple
nobility.'' And so Breashears took a pilgrimage to Everest, first
in his heart and later in reality (he has now reached the summit
four times) to find the sanctuary and security that was snatched
from him as a child.
</P>
<P>
   His first foray into climbing was in high school in Wyoming
(he'd lived in several states and overseas): He and his buddy Danny
used hemp rope and knew next to nothing about safety precautions.
He was able to get a scholarship to the National Outdoor Leadership
School, and his climbing education began in earnest. In his senior
year, the family moved to Denver. While other kids were playing
football, listening to Pink Floyd, and doing drugs, he found his
high at Boulder Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   This early part of Breashears's book is sweet and moving, and
includes wonderful family and climbing photos. Here's a teenage boy
obsessed with climbing and Everest well before mountaineering was a
cool thing to do, even in Colorado. His defining moment came after
completing a route that other more experienced climbers could not.
``The moment lifted me off the earth and elevated me into their
rarefied realm. At last I belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   Though his filmmaking career began by accident (he served as a
gofer, hauling camera equipment and provisions), once the bug bit
him he attacked the craft much as he had mountaineering, by
learning from anyone who would teach him and by taking calculated
risks. In 1986, he took on an assignment from the BBC, in search of
the body of George Mallory and his camera. Finding an undeveloped
summit photo would prove that Mallory had beaten Norgay and Edmund
Hillary to the top of Everest. The mission was unsuccessful. (Just
two weeks ago, climbers retracing the route found Mallory's body
lying on a windswept ledge, frozen there since 1924.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Breashears blames himself for the breakup of his
marriage to Veronique Choa, an independent and adventurous woman,
he doesn't delve deeply into the relationship. In fact, he skims
over much of his adult emotional life and focuses on the physical.
</P>
<P>
   The final quarter of the book is devoted to the 1996 Everest
assignment, including some stupendous photos. By now, most everyone
knows the story of how the IMAX team not only dropped what they
were doing to help with the rescue but also gave out valuable
supplies, such as bottled oxygen, that were to be used for their
own ascent to the summit _ to help victims and other rescuers. When
you read the painstaking preparation that went into the $7 million
project before Breashears even left for the Himalayas, you see what
a sacrifice that really was. After much experimentation, IMAX
redesigned its original 70-pound large-format camera (lovingly
called ``The Pig'' because it eats 5.6 feet of film per second ) to
weigh 42 pounds and withstand temperatures to minus 50. And, of
course, the air at 29,028 feet made every physical feat that much
more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Breashears mourns those who died on the mountain but busies
himself with the rescue work, including a gripping narrative of
helping the severely frostbitten and nearly dead Beck Weathers:
``He braced his forearms on my shoulders as we started down. One
glance to my left or right and I was staring at Beck's frozen
claws, just inches away. The sight of those useless appendages and
the utter helplessness of the man was deeply unnerving. . . . He
didn't complain. He was so thankful. He had a profound effect on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMAX team eventually decided to carry on with the film after
the accident because, Breashears explains, ``I wanted to prove that
Everest was _ in its grandeur _ an affirmation of life, not a
sentence of death.'' As with most everything else he sets out to
do, Breashears succeeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
