<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WYOMING-BOS &LR;      05-17 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WYOMING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNIE PROULX GOES WESTERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who understand the West beyond the Dakotas will tell you
that the place is bigger than darkness itself and half again as
cruel _ high plains and rattlers and a wind that can kill you just
by wearing you down. It's also a place of such unearthly beauty, of
staggering skies and stars and so much romance, that you love it
more than any fool ought to and will commit acts of madness in
order to stay. This lunatic spirit is what settled the big sky
country of Wyoming and Montana and what defines it still, at least
so far as its human inhabitants are concerned. Which, it must be
mentioned, don't seem as though they amount to much in the relative
scheme of things. When you've just witnessed an August snowstorm
that took down a hundred of your herd, then left you with a perfect
afternoon, it's hard to believe that any grand design had you
positioned at the head of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Proulx, whose bleak poetic prose has snared the icy
coastline of Newfoundland as well as northern Vermont, seems to
know Wyoming as only the wandering artist or devoted transplant
can: seems born to the place and yet far enough away to grasp its
glorious contradictions. She resettled there several years ago, in
the aftermath of the acclaim she received for her 1992 novel, ``The
Shipping News,'' but the witness listening to how these people talk
could have been eavesdropping in the state all her life. More
startling is the psychic and physical milieu captured in the
stories in ``Close Range,'' the standoff between geographical and
human hubris that most natives couldn't put into words. When it
comes to the land, Proulx may be the most onomatopoeic writer in
America, and her prose begs to be read aloud: Her stony cliffs
sound like rock-hard places on the tongue; her geysers and rivers
and wide morning sun soar with the cadences of water and light.
Good thing all that beauty is around, given what she's describing.
This is a bright, hard corner of the world where a knife fight can
signify an act of love and a cut fence is far worse than aggravated
assault. No romantics here, and no innocents, either. Evil may not
go by that name in Proulx's Wyoming, but it sleeps in the shadows
of everyone's barn.
</P>
<P>
   Few writers feel equally at home in the novel and the short
story, and in the acknowledgments of ``Close Range,'' Proulx admits
that ``short stories are very difficult for me.'' That hardship may
be worth the struggle, because these stories, all written in the
past few years, are tough as flint and on occasion breathtaking;
together, they stand with Proulx's best work. John Updike included
``The Half-Skinned Steer'' in Houghton Mifflin's recent ``Best
American Short Stories of the Century,'' and ``Brokeback
Mountain,'' which broke a lot of hearts when first published in The
New Yorker, has already been anthologized as well. I'm always
startled by the relentless cruelty in Proulx's fiction, though I'm
not sure why; certainly there's nothing coy about the way she
introduces her version of the truth. It's probably a matter of
timing: We know from the outset (hell, from the title) that ``The
Half-Skinned Steer'' is going to be a terrible thing to behold, but
two readings of it had me still unprepared for the shiver-inducing
ending. ``People in Hell Just Want a Drink of Water'' warns you
with its opening line _ ``You stand there, braced.'' And yet this
story about two families pushed to the brink by trouble and
bad-tempered weather is as tension-packed as summer thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ferocious impact of Proulx's writing comes from her
precision of form, as free-fall confident as a jazz saxophonist.
``The Mud Below,'' which beautifully captures the lure and agony of
riding bulls, has the nerve to deliver what is essentially a
30-page riff _ all in the name of telling us about the slump
Diamond Felts got himself into on the rodeo circuit. Such moments
are dazzling without being showy, and they bestow a special
pleasure to the reading of ``Close Range,'' for behind every tall
tale or killer story, there's an homage to the language that
encompasses it. The method is one of stripped-down poetry, hard
meter without a wasted word. Here's a guy hitching a ride into the
Big Horn Mountains just before dawn: ``the big car slingshot at the
black hump of range, dazzle of morning an hour behind the rim, not
a dozen words exchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Love is a harsh but necessary commodity in ``Close Range,'' no
more trustworthy than Wyoming weather and about as likely to take
you down as to bless your day. The women are hard and resigned,
like Mrs. Freeze, the bourbon-sipping ranch forewoman in ``Pair a
Spurs,'' or sometimes just half-wild from fighting life, like the
barstool queen of ``A Lonely Coast.'' The men tend toward sinew and
silence, though not of the introspective sort _ living among the
seasons of birth and death, there's just not all that much to say.
But psychological revelation is not what one looks for in ``Close
Range''; it's instead a roughshod testament to the land, an account
of the human bedlam that goes on beneath that frighteningly
infinite sky. Such elemental stakes tend to make you mean or give
you a fine sense of humor; Proulx's fiction manages some of both.
In ``The Bunchgrass Edge of the World,'' an old tractor proves to
be smarter than any of its mortal owners; in ``Pair a Spurs,'' it's
a pair of hand-tooled silver riding spurs that ultimately calls the
shots. As in Proulx's most recent novel, ``Accordion Crimes,'' here
the object becomes the symbolic link among love and death and
serendipity, somehow finding a connecting design within the
day-to-day chaos of getting through.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a friendly book. It's full of broken bones, seething
grudges, and unexpected deaths, and it's about as sentimental
toward the West as a broken whiskey bottle on a Saturday night. The
Wyoming of the past two decades has seen the influx of millionaire
cowboys, ecofreaks, survivalists, and land-use outrages, all of
which Proulx attends to with splendid irony. If her Car Scropes,
the antagonist of ``Pair a Spurs,'' is a comic nod to Faulkner's
famously awful Snopeses, two brief stories _ ``The Blood Bay'' and
``55 Miles to the Gas Pump'' _ are blackly funny evidence of the
lunacy the West can spawn. But the gorgeously painful ``Brokeback
Mountain,'' about the decades-long love between two range riders,
does some of the best things a story can do. It abolishes the old
West cliches, excavates and honors a certain kind of elusive life,
then nearly levels you with the emotional weight at its center. It
may be 400 miles of forever between Cody and Cheyenne, but Annie
Proulx has driven it alone and unafraid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
