 ART ADV.: Photos with SMITH-BLACKS and BRUSH-MAN are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO-TARGETS (Undated) _ More significant than NATO's target
errors is its choice of targets. By Fred Kaplan. 875 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NEWSPAPER (Tetovo, Macedonia) _ In exile, Baton Haxhiu
has re-created the irreverent and militant newspaper that he
published in Pristina until Yugoslav forces began expelling ethnic
Albanian Kosovars. By Toula Vlahou. 735 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WAR-RULES (Cape Town) _ Genocide. Torture. Rape. Forced
removals. Such horrors aren't supposed to happen any more. Yet the
past half century has witnessed, according to one study, more than
250 conflicts that claimed up to 170 million lives. By Kurt
Shillinger. 1750 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Tirana, Albania) _ As a representative of Save
the children, Bianca Jagger spotlights the plight of the Kosovars.
By Lynda Gorov.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ Robert Rubin's legacy: a
prosperity not seen since the '60s. By Thomas Oliphant. (w and k
coding)
</P>
