<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HELPING-A-FRIENDLESS-     05-17 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELPING-A-FRIENDLESS-CHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES TODAY 
 Q&AMP;A 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (The following is a sample column by Dr. T. Berry Brazelton,
America's favorite baby doctor and longtime columnist for The New
York Times Syndicate. Dr. B.'s Q&AMP;As and essays are a magnet for
lifestyle and health sections. For more information about becoming
a client, call toll-free 888-269-8796 and you'll automatically be
connected to a New York Times Syndicate sales executive.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (North American and Latin American rights.) &QL; 
 &UR; By T. BERRY BRAZELTON, M.D. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My 10-year-old daughter is very friendly and enjoys
playing with other kids, but she has no friends. She calls kids on
the phone, but they don't call back. She has had classmates come
over to our house, but no one invites her to theirs. She is in
extracurricular activities such as Girl Scouts and dancing class,
but she does not see anyone after these activities are over.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't complain, but I know she longs for a playmate and
friend. Any suggestions? _ L.K., Leesburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   DR. BRAZELTON: Maybe this is revealing something about your
daughter that you don't see yourself. If you could understand why
other children aren't attracted to her, you would be better able to
help her.
</P>
<P>
   When other children can't or won't relate to a child, that child
may have a deeper problem. For example, your daughter may bully
other children or try to control them because she feels insecure
herself.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, I would take this situation seriously. Consult her
teachers or a psychologist who can evaluate her. Meanwhile, try to
find your daughter a child who is like her in temperament. Woo the
other child by taking them to a museum or a movie. Try to get them
together regularly for something they can enjoy. If your daughter
can make one friend, it will be easier for the two of them to enter
a peer group _ together.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm a single mom of a 2-year-old son. He was 4 months
old when I left my husband and moved from Arizona to Tennessee so
that my parents could help me raise him. My ex-husband never
contacts us anymore, and I have no idea where he is living now.
</P>
<P>
   My son and I will soon be moving back to Arizona. I have always
been open with him about his daddy, telling him, ``Every child has
a mommy and a daddy; yours just lives in another state.'' But when
he gets older and starts to understand more, how do I explain to
him that his dad just couldn't handle the responsibility of raising
a child? I don't want him to think he is the reason he has no daddy
_ or blame me! _ No Name, Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   DR. BRAZELTON: You may never be able to explain it
satisfactorily to him. A child will always long for the other
parent. He is likely to blame himself (and you) for losing his
father: ``If I were a better boy, he would have never left me.''
</P>
<P>
   You need to be ready to repeatedly reassure him that his
father's abandonment had nothing to do with him. Tell him that you
and his dad couldn't make it together. You need to assume the blame
to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   You should also assure him that you will never leave him. A
child without one parent always fears the loss of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Is it necessary for you to leave your supportive family now?
Being a single parent can certainly be difficult, and it may be
hard for your son to be without an extended family or close friends
as cushions when stressful times hit.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My 10-year-old daughter is very loud when she eats or
drinks. The sound she makes is like a moaning/heavy breathing. It's
nearly impossible to get through a meal without telling her to
quiet down.
</P>
<P>
   Should I ignore this and hope she grows out of it, or keep
reminding her about it so she doesn't embarrass herself at social
functions? Could this be a health problem? _ R.T., Clinton
Township, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   DR. BRAZELTON: I am not familiar with a physical reason for her
heavy breathing at mealtimes, but I suggest that you consult her
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no physical reason for the breathing, she may be
trying to get a response out of you. If this is the case, ignoring
it is the best way to diminish it.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to let her know that others may find the heavy
breathing socially unacceptable, say that once _ and then shut up.
More pressure from you may just cause her to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Questions or comments should be addressed to Dr. T. Berry
Brazelton, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales Corp., 122
E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general interest
will be answered in this column; Dr. Brazelton regrets that
unpublished letters cannot be answered individually. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 by T. Berry Brazelton, M.D. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
