<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAME-SEX-MARRY-BOS &LR;      05-17 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAME-SEX-MARRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LINES FORM OVER SAME-SEX MARRIAGE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Massachusetts Legislature this week begins
debating a bill to deny legal recognition to same-sex marriages,
taking on an issue that has opened a new battle front between gay
activists and religious conservatives across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, advocates on both sides, including Christian, Jewish,
and Muslim leaders, will converge on Beacon Hill for a State House
hearing on the state's Defense of Marriage Act.
</P>
<P>
   For a large coalition of religious leaders, the bill, which in
its first draft excluded same-sex marriages from official
recognition in Massachusetts, will firmly define the act of
marriage in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The current version states that the state will recognize
marriages only between men and women. Governor Paul Cellucci has
publicly voiced his opposition to gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be religious groups all standing up and saying the
same thing _ that the Commonwealth should hold the definition of
marriage as a union of a man and woman,'' said Matt Daniels,
president of the conservative Massachusetts Family Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels has organized religious leaders who will hold a news
conference hours before what is expected to be an intense
legislative hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are speaking for what we believe the biblical view of
marriage is, and that's between a man and a woman,'' said the Rev.
Ray Hammond, pastor of the Bethel African Methodist Episcopal
Church in Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   Alveda King, niece of Martin Luther King Jr., is scheduled to
join religious leaders in declaring support for the bill, Daniels
said.
</P>
<P>
   For gays and lesbians, the right to marriage has emerged as a
critical gauge of whether they will be treated as equals in
American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue, more than any other in the gay community, is one
that is not political, but comes from our hearts,'' said Denise
Fetonte, a member of the Pride Interfaith Coalition, a Boston-based
advocacy group for gays and lesbians of faith. ``Many of us want to
have the rights and responsibilities of a recognized marriage as an
expression of our love and commitment. I've been married to the
same person for 26 years in every way possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of gay marriages say recognizing them threatens
the very foundation of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is intended by nature and we believe by God to be
between a man and a woman in a monogamous relationship which is
open to new life, which means, of course, children,'' said John
Walsh, a spokesman for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston.
``It has nothing to do with oppression of people. It's just we
believe that is what is best for society.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the leaders of the four Catholic dioceses in
Massachusetts _ possibly Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston _ is
expected to speak in favor of the bill, according to Jerry
D'Avolio, executive director of the Massachusetts Catholic
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The bill filed last December by State Representative John H.
Rogers, a Democrat, was never intended to oppose gay rights, but to
strengthen the state statute on marriage, said Jeff Mahoney, a
spokesman for Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the initial draft, which was later amended, stated: ``A
purported marriage contracted between persons of the same sex shall
be neither valid nor recognized in the Commonwealth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of the bill was a mistake,'' Mahoney said. ``But
it was never intended to offend anyone. . . . Some people have
tried to make it an anti-gay marriage bill but we are trying to
define marriage and trying to make it a positive piece instead of
prohibitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists, however, say despite the change in wording, the
essence of the bill remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is clearly about divisiveness, intending to divide
people, because there is no need for it since gay marriages are not
legal in any state,'' said Jeremy Pittman, chairman of the Lesbian
and Gay Political Alliance of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of gay marriages broke into the spotlight three years
ago after the Hawaii Supreme Court ruled that barring homosexuals
from receiving marriage licenses was unconstitutional sex
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The decision unleashed a backlash from conservative forces,
particularly religious groups, who base their opposition to gay
marriages, in part, on biblical passages they say describe
homosexuality as a sin.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christian groups were key to helping win the
passage of a national Defense of Marriage Act in Congress in 1996.
The bill, signed by President Clinton, denies federal recognition
to gay marriages and permits states to ignore the union of gay
couples married in other states.
</P>
<P>
   So far 29 states have passed laws banning homosexual marriages.
</P>
<P>
   In response, gay and lesbian advocates, legal advocates, and
religious advocates have launched the Freedom to Marry Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, nearly 200 clergy and religious activists have
signed a declaration supporting the right of gays to marry. These
clergy and activists say they are driven by their biblically rooted
belief in social justice and human dignity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0091 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IS-BABY-DEAF?-NYTSF     05-17 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IS-BABY-DEAF?-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES TODAY 
 DOES YOUR CHILD HAVE A HEARING PROBLEM? 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (The following is a sample column by Dr. T. Berry Brazelton,
America's favorite baby doctor and longtime columnist for The New
York Times Syndicate. Dr. B.'s Q&AMP;As and essays are a magnet for
lifestyle and health sections. For more information about becoming
a client, call toll-free 888-269-8796 and you'll automatically be
connected to a New York Times Syndicate sales executive.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (North American and Latin American rights.) &QL; 
 &UR; By T. BERRY BRAZELTON, M.D. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Parents often worry about whether or not their baby's hearing is
normal. There is certainly reason for concern. Lack of hearing can
greatly interfere with an infant's development.
</P>
<P>
   Profoundly deaf babies are slowed down in all areas. They are
likely to appear depressed and unreactive _ slow to develop motor
skills and to reward parents' attempts at interaction. They may lie
in their cribs passively, or they may develop autisms _ such as
head rolling or other repetitive behaviors _ as if to fill up empty
space.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, their other senses, such as sight and touch,
become heightened. This can make a baby hypersensitive and easily
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are ways to test the hearing of a baby. I
find it is best to do it when she is asleep or as she is just
rousing. I use a soft rattle and a bell, in a quiet room. After
several startles, a baby with normal hearing will shut out or
ignore either of these sounds.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet room is one of the keys to this assessment. If I test a
baby in a noisy environment, she may have already shut out auditory
input. Then she can appear to be deaf, even though she's not. The
reason for the two stimuli is to test the range of her hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Another test would be to give the baby a chance to respond to my
voice when she's awake and looking at the ceiling. If she quiets
and slowly turns to my voice, I know that she hears me. If her
mother and I compete on either side of her, she should choose the
higher-pitched female voice.
</P>
<P>
   If there is concern about a baby's hearing, the primary
physician usually refers the child to an otolaryngologist (ear and
throat specialist), who can examine the ears and upper respiratory
tract. If the cause is a temporary condition, the otolaryngologist
will provide treatment. If the hearing loss seems permanent, the
child may be referred to an audiologist who can perform further
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Tests, such as auditory evoked responses (AER), can detect major
hearing impairment in babies _ before it interferes seriously with
the child's development. If there is any indication that a baby is
not hearing or hears in certain ranges but not in all, I'd suggest
a complete evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing loss may become more obvious in the second year, as a
child who is beginning to speak garbles words in a regular fashion.
I would always be aware of hearing impairment as a possibility in a
child who is not developing properly, particularly in areas of
communication.
</P>
<P>
   Otitis media (infection of the middle ear) can threaten a
child's hearing. Many infants develop a tendency to chronic otitis
media. After an acute earache, the pressure and the discharge seem
to linger despite antibiotics. Otitis media is sometimes called
glue ear _ as if the ear contained glue that was hard to mobilize.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic infection of the middle ear can cause hearing
impairment. Infants in group care or infants with older siblings in
school who are exposed to many different infections are
particularly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Ear infections may follow colds as often as every two weeks.
Each ear infection becomes more difficult to treat. Parents and
physicians get discouraged. The baby's general condition is often
affected; she seems to become rundown and vulnerable to everything.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, an ear and throat specialist should be consulted.
It may be necessary to use tubes in the child's eardrums. They
allow drainage, reduce pressure in the inner ear and prevent
hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Following the development of speech and other forms of
communication is the most important way of determining whether
there is hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   With an older child, if you are concerned about hearing, try
whispering in one ear or the other. Be sure to whisper something to
which you know she will want to respond, since there are many
periods in a child's development when ``selective attention'' can
be operating. Whisper a welcome question, such as, ``Do you want to
go to town with me?'' or ``Do you want a cookie?''
</P>
<P>
   In my office, I put my finger in one of the child's ears and
whisper in the other, ``Do you want a lollipop?'' This is almost
sure to get a response. If there are no responses and/or speech is
developing inappropriately, I refer the child for evaluation by an
otolaryngologist or testing by an audiologist.
</P>
<P>
   In future columns Dr. Brazelton will answer selected questions
from readers. Questions or comments should be addressed to Dr. T.
Berry Brazelton, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Dr. Brazelton regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 by T. Berry Brazelton, M.D. &QL;
</P>
