r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECOND-WEDDINGS-HNS &LR;      05-17 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECOND-WEDDINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEDDINGS ARE MORE COMPLICATED THE SECOND TIME AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You're madly in love. You're going to marry.
Anew. Time to get the rings, the dress, a tux, the hall, a cake. Or
not.
</P>
<P>
   If this is your second time around the dance floor, ladies and
gentlemen, relish your freedom. This time, you're the boss. Stuffed
your size 8 frame into your mother's teensy lace dress last time?
Don shorts and hit the beach. Ran to a Justice of the Peace at 18
and missed the party? This could be your big blowout.
</P>
<P>
   But being older, wiser and possibly better funded won't wipe out
complications. Yes, Cupid has struck. Yes, you feel young again.
But you're not a kid anymore. You have kids.
</P>
<P>
   And kids top the list of concerns for folks who remarry. When
Beth Reed Ramirez of Anaheim, Calif., remarried, she said, ``We had
to pick a day when we knew my ex-husband couldn't mess it up by not
delivering my daughter on time. It's amazing the games people do
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents who remarry should get their children involved, said the
Rev. Roger Coleman of Kansas City, Mo. He designed a Family
Medallion and special ceremony integrating children in the
remarriage. He first used the full ceremony and medallion for
athlete Bo Jackson's wedding in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 10,000 couples a year use Coleman's charm,
which has three connected circles at the end of a silver chain, a
symbol of two families merging to create a third.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman got the idea while performing courthouse ceremonies in
the early 1980s. ``I was stunned. I had more children than adults
at my weddings. I'd see the kids having all of this acting-out
behavior. They couldn't behave themselves for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It began to dawn on me: They came thinking something important
was going to happen, but nothing I did acknowledged them at all. I
was seeing confusion, anger and a feeling of not being part of
something. So I developed a little medallion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to hand them out to the kids and I got a whole
different type of behavior,'' he added. ``And the guests acted
differently. They would come up and start hugging the kids
afterwards. It became a tremendous bonding experience. It
incorporated the realities that many people find themselves living
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Some church leaders accused Coleman, a member of the Christian
Church (Disciples of Christ), of promoting divorce. (Not all
religions take kindly to remarriage. The Catholic Church stopped
excommunicating divorced and remarried members in 1977, although a
divorced Catholic must receive an annulment to remarry in the
church or to receive Holy Communion.)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the medallion is most popular among Catholics,
Coleman said. ``Once you start focusing on children, you don't have
room to really condemn the past as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarriage also prompted Beth Reed Ramirez to forge a new path.
Engaged a second time, Ramirez, now 40, scooped up an armful of
bridal magazines at the grocery store. They didn't help. She was
not 24. She was not a size 6. The magazines ``were 500 pages long.
I would tear out about 10 pages that I could use.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's special needs _ stepparenting, prenuptial agreements,
merging two households _ weren't addressed. Frustrated, she created
her own site on the World Wide Web. Last month, she launched Bride
Again: The Only Magazine Designed for Encore Brides, a quarterly
magazine that sells for $4.99 in grocery and bookstores. The only
national magazine dedicated to encore brides, Bride Again is
designed for female readers ages 30 to 45, with a median household
income of $47,474 and a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sizable market. Of the 2.4 million people who marry each
year in the United States, more than 1.1 million are remarrying.
``People are saying, `I can't believe someone hasn't done something
like this before,' Ramirez said. Or: ```I'm 45 and I'm not going to
wear puff sleeves. My parents aren't going to put out the
announcement or pay for the wedding.'''
</P>
<P>
   Encore brides and grooms are no longer second-class citizens,
Ramirez said. These days, divorcees do don white. A quiet City Hall
ceremony is no longer de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel like `This is a celebration! I've been through so
much with my first marriage or as a single mom. And now, by golly,
I'm gonna have it right!''' said Ramirez, who remarried three years
ago. ``You come with 15, 20 years more experience. You're happy
that you've got another chance and life is good again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bride Again offers tips on etiquette, dress, prenuptial
agreements, stepfamilies and ``his, hers or our house?''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez may have some male readers. Grooms get more involved the
second time around, she said. Her husband, Kelly Ramirez, chose the
location (the 18th hole at Mission Hills Country Club in Palm
Springs), the menu and the band. She picked the honeymoon spot (the
Fiji Islands).
</P>
<P>
   Theme weddings and theme showers are more popular for repeaters,
Finally, a word on rings: When it comes to jewelry, most couples
pick the opposite of what they had the first time, said Kelly
Lindbom, manager of Glennpeter Jewelers in Latham, N.Y. ``They want
something different. If they had a marquise cut, now they want a
round. If they had a solitaire, now they want something with side
stones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been through it all and you're not going to say, `Oh,
whatever you want, honey,''' Lindbom said. ``(Second-timers) get
equal to or better than what first-timers get.''
</P>
<P>
   But never smaller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
