</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-MUDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS SEE LEWIS CASE WITH MIXED VIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As malpractice lawyers publicly batter Dr. Gilbert H.
Mudge, one of Boston's most prominent cardiologists, many
physicians appear to empathize with his plight and say it reflects
the peril of treating a celebrity patient.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether they think Mudge made a mistake in his
treatment of Celtics star Reggie Lewis before his death in 1993 _
and some specialists say privately they believe he did _ doctors
who talked about the case last week said they felt for Mudge and
underscored the vulnerability of even the most competent physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that many people are saying, `There but for the
grace of God go I,' because these are paths that many of us could
have gone down,'' said Dr. Gregory Curfman, a cardiologist and
deputy editor at the New England Journal of Medicine. As is typical
in Boston's dense and interwined medical community, Curfman said he
is friends with two of the three defendants in the medical
malpractice suit brought by Lewis's widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, and
had studied under Dr. Roman DeSanctis, a leading cardiologist who
testified about his efforts to caution Mudge about his diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Curfman said ``it's unbelievably'' painful to watch the trial,
which is being covered on television and radio as well as in the
print media. ``I'm certainly glad I'm not on this jury because I
don't know how I'd go about making a decision on this case.
Everyone's waiting to see which way this thing is going to go,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriateness of Mudge's care of Lewis is at the center of
the suit against Mudge and two other physicians, Drs. Peter L.
Friedman and Mark A. Creager, whom Harris-Lewis accuses of failing
to diagnose her husband with a life-threatening heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   When a medical malpractice suit plays out in the public, most
physicians take notice and sympathize, said attorney Dr. Barry
Lang, who specializes in medical malpractice law and was an
orthopedic surgeon in New Bedford for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any medical malpractice suit chills physicians. No physician
purposely harms people, and Boston is such a visible medical
community. Absolutely no physician wants to see another one sued,''
Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   The empathy stems from the awareness of the potential
humiliation and loss of professional standing that a malpractice
judgment could bring, said Dr. Robert Leach, who was an orthopedic
consultant for the Boston Celtics between 1970 and 1989 and former
head of the US Olympic medical team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's personal worry for the man. There's personal worry for
the profession. I want us to be loved,'' said Leach, editor of the
American Journal of Sports Medicine and professor of orthopedic
surgery at Boston University School of Medicine. Leach said he did
not know Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   As an orthopedic surgeon, Leach said that most of the cases
involving high-profile athletes are not issues of life or death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a professional death, but not an actual death,''
Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   Few doctors were willing to predict an outcome in the Lewis
case: For one thing, few have had access to the complex and
sometimes conflicting documentation of Lewis's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   However, because studies of the electrical function of Lewis's
heart played such a large part in his case, the trial drew a lot of
attention at a meeting in Toronto last week of experts in that
field, said one participant, who has general knowledge of the Lewis
case and who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   He said that attendees at the meeting of the North American
Society of Pacing and Electrophysiology were largely convinced that
Lewis's life-threatening heart condition was so clearly documented
by his initial testing that he should have had a defibrillator
implanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wasn't Reggie Lewis, he would have been treated
appropriately,'' said the electrophysiology specialist. ``If he had
been an accountant, the doctors would have said'' that he needed
the defibrillator, like it or not. But instead, said the
specialist, there was great pressure on physicians caring for Lewis
to find a way of treating him without implanting the device, which
would almost certainly have ended his basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   After Lewis collapsed during a 1993 playoff game, the Celtics
assembled a so-called dream team of about a dozen physicians from
area hospitals at New England Baptist Hospital, where they held a
two-hour meeting to evaluate Lewis. During the malpractice trial,
Celtics physician Arnold Scheller testified that the team of
cardiologists was assembled ``across academic lines, across
hospital lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to have any politics interfering with medical
decisions, I wanted to get to the bottom of the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Mudge's diagnosis ultimately conflicted with that of the
dream team, Curfman at the New England Journal of Medicine said he
doubted institutional rivalries were the cause. ``I think with
(doctors) of this caliber, the ego thing may come in but they are
also quite capable of moving away from that. These are people who
can put ego in the background and do the right thing,'' Curfman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without access to the medical records and documents involved in
the case, Dr. David A. Meyerson, a cardiologist at Johns Hopkins
Medical Institutions and a spokesman for the American Heart
Association, said that the findings of the dream team and Mudge
could both have been ``partly correct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it would have been difficult for most university
cardiologists to issue an opinion contrary to the 12-member medical
panel that originally evaluated Mr. Lewis,'' said Meyerson.
``Clearly Mr. Lewis and his family had a vested interest in having
him cleared for activity at the highest level of human performance.
Not being privy to Dr. Mudge's data, I cannot honestly say what
kind of decision I would have made,'' Meyerson said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the case sends a message ``that we should remain
conservative until proven otherwise. We must be cautious to use the
same prudent guidelines and practices in evaluating any patient no
matter how famous they may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits like Harris-Lewis's create tremendous pressure on
physicians to make a diagnosis that will allow the athlete to
continue playing, even if the evidence may say otherwise, said a
Boston physician who asked not to be identified. The physician said
that other local doctors said they would rather not become involved
in taking care of a high-profile patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a worst-case scenario. If we were in the present
dilemma, most of us would have tried to avoid it,'' the physician
added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to concern about their reputations, money also
becomes an issue in considering whether to take a high-profile
patient. ``If you are taking care of someone whose future earnings
are such a huge amount, like a professional athlete, a malpractice
suit can ruin your career because you are being sued for so much
money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1352EDT &QL; 
