<HEADLINE>
WHY ARE FLAMES HOTTEST AT THE TOP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why is it hotter right above a flame than when you pass your
hand through the middle of it?
</P>
<P>
   E.B., Concord, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A bit of flame-speak first, then the answer. There are two
different kinds of flames, according to MIT Chemical Engineering
Professor Jack Howard. The first is a diffusion flame. A candle
creates a diffusion flame. So does burning wood. This one starts
with an ignition source that heats the fuel, like the wax, or wood
or coal or paper, until some of it turns into a gas. The gaseous
fuel molecules diffuse out to meet the oxygen in the surrounding
air. When the fuel vapor and oxygen mix to the right proportions
you have combustion.
</P>
<P>
   The other flame is a premixed flame. The flame in your natural
gas stove is an example. Mix the fuel and the oxygen first, then
introduce the ignition source, and you have a premixed flame.
Howard says this is important because your question really only
applies to diffusion flames.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature at the tip of a candle flame can reach an
incredible 2500 degrees Fahrenheit. But inside the flame, and just
below it, things are only a little above room temperature, just hot
enough to melt the wax. Ever put molten wax on your finger and
watch it harden? The heat you feel from that wax is the temperature
at the bottom of, and inside, a candle flame.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. Light a match and touch it to a candle wick and some
of the heat transfers down to the solid paraffin. It melts to a
liquid which is absorbed up the burning wick. The heat in the wick
converts the liquid paraffin to a gas and we're off to the
combustion races.
</P>
<P>
   The gaseous paraffin diffuses outward away from the wick. But so
far, it hasn't mixed properly with oxygen, so it really isn't a
flame yet. Finally, a few millimeters away from the wick when the
gas diffusing outward mixes with the oxygen in the surrounding air
and reaches the right concentration: WHOOSH. Where the flame goes
WHOOSH, it's hot. But inside, its not. What you see when you see a
flame is like an upside down ice-cream cone. It's mostly hollow
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it hotter the higher in the flame you go? The fuel gasses
flow upward, and the higher you go the more fuel has been burned,
Howardexplains.
</P>
<P>
   Now what explains the upside-down ice cream cone shape of a
flame? At its base, lots of fuel vapor is diffusing out. There's
more vapor than surrounding oxygen. The mixture is too fuel
rich/oxygen poor to burn.
</P>
<P>
   The little pocket of fuel vapor can grow wide before it mixes
with enough oxygen to ignite. But the higher you go in the flame,
the more fuel vapor has been used up. The mixture goes from
fuel-rich/oxygen poor at the bottom, tomore fuel-poor/oxygen rich
at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the top of the flame, where all the fuel has been burned
and it's at its hottest, that's what actually determines the height
of the flame,'' Howard says. ``Just as the flame is doing its job
most efficiently, it dies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
