<SLUG> BC-REOPENED-DIVORCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE BACK IN COURT AFTER FIRM'S $1.5 BILLION SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Before the Internet, before high-tech startups made
billionaires of entrepreneurs overnight, there was Mr. and Mrs.
Kenan Sahin.
</P>
<P>
   After toasting their marriage in the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology student union in May 1967, Selcuk and Kenan Sahin spent
the next 15 years juggling their careers as university professors
and caring for their three sons.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1982, Kenan Systems Corp., a Cambridge software company
and the brainchild of Kenan Sahin, was born.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Sahin scoured the country for the best technological
minds, while his wife, she says, scrubbed office walls and shopped
for discount supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The investment paid off in January, when Lucent Technologies
Inc. paid $1.48 billion for KSC.
</P>
<P>
   But the sensational payoff came too late for Selcuk Sahin, who
walked away with just $1.5 million in 1996 when her 29-year
marriage ended in divorce. At the time, a judge valued the company
at $4.9 million _ 300 times less than what it sold for 32 months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in what financial experts, technology specialists, and
divorce lawyers see as a crucial test of fairness and equity in
these high-tech times, the former Mrs. Sahin wants a new day in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just common sense,'' said corporate trial attorney Ned
Leibensberger, who represents Selcuk Sahin. ``At the end of the
day, he's got more than a billion dollars and she's got a million.
I think that in cases involving high-tech software companies,
judges have a very tough job trying to determine value. Now we see
this purchase. . . . Now we know for sure how much the company was
worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal specialists say the KSC case, and the drastic difference
between the court estimate and the market price, represents a
growing problem in divorce cases, where his-and-her expert
witnesses race to keep track of an exploding technology market.
</P>
<P>
   Boston business and tax attorney Kenneth Vacovec, who represents
many high-tech entrepreneurs, said he believes mistakes are common
in company value estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is just so unpredictable these days,'' Vacovec
said. ``The economy is very logical; that's headed in the same
direction. But some of the prices we are seeing are amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacovec thinks the Sahin divorce settlement should be voided,
solely because of the huge discrepancies in the estimated worth of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 divorce trial, Kenan Sahin's expert estimated
for the court that his company was worth $4.2 million; Selcuk
Sahin's specialist believed it was worth about $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Without a public stock exchange to consult, and two wildly
different estimates offered by expert witnesses, Norfolk Probate
and Family Judge Eileen Shaevel pegged the value of the company at
$4.9 million, saying that Kenan Sahin's expert used a formula that
seemed more logical.
</P>
<P>
   While neither spouse came close to estimating the true value of
the company, Sahin's former wife now says she has evidence that her
ex-husband knew his company's true worth, or close to it, long
before it was purchased by Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   Several legal specialists who have seen Selcuk Sahin's motion to
void her initial divorce action say the testimony of Dr. R. Glenn
Hubbard of Columbia University, an adviser to the president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York, may prove invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard concluded that financial data on 70 software firms
between 1996 and 1999 show that the $4.9 estimate was far low,
based on the sale price. In order for a company valued at $4.9
million in 1996 to sell for $1.48 billion in 1999 it would have had
to grow three times faster than the fastest-growing company in the
country, which he said was highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in the company's value cannot be attributed to a new
product or a signifigant change in demand for it, Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Sahin's attorney, Norman Jacobs, said the notion of going
back to court because his client's company has done so well is
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that the views she articulates are
outrageous,'' said Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   He called the notion that Selcuk helped build KSC ``ludicrous,''
along with her attorney's allegations that a closer estimate of
worth could have been provided at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs did acknowledge that the messy divorce is a sign of the
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States today, there must be hundreds of
companies that didn't even exist four years ago,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rapidly changing area of economy,'' he said. ``Forty
years ago, we didn't have problems like this in divorce court.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs added that Selcuk Sahin was not a credible witness at
trial.
</P>
<P>
   By her own account, Selcuk Sahin made mistakes throughout her
messy divorce. She parted ways with six attorneys before hiring
Leibensperger _ in some cases because she could not pay their
bills, in others because they differed on courtroom tactics.
</P>
<P>
   She admits that her courtroom conduct was harshly criticized at
the close of the trial by the same judge she will face in a hearing
scheduled for May 24, when her former husband will move to have the
prior decision upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sahin said, she realizes she needs to approach her divorce
as the trained researcher she is, without emotion and anger.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard University's School of Public Health,
Selcuk Sahin began a breast cancer foundation in 1990 with money
from KSC, but funding halted when she initiated the divorce, she
says, after years of private battles and her husband's threats to
divorce her.
</P>
<P>
   Now her biggest financial concern is her oldest son, Ayral, who,
despite having graduated from Boston College and displaying talent
and passion for music, is mentally challenged and cannot support
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I am mortal,'' Selcuk Sahin said. ``I don't want to
wait to make this right. I want to make this right now, for women
everyhwere, for me, but mostly for Ayral.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's two other sons are KSC employees, she said, who
have sided with their father throughout the painful process.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Sahin, citing his attorney's advice and the pending court
matter, refused to comment on the case or on any allegations made
by his former wife.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known divorce attorneys in the region, Monroe
Inker, who consulted with Selcuk Sahin early in her divorce
proceedings, said the problem of fair estimates for high-tech
companies will become even greater as they multiply.
</P>
<P>
   He's represented clients whose ex-husbands vowed that they would
not take their companies public, then did just that, he said.
Spouses often do not have the money to properly investigate the
potential of companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find today, with all these new issues, and new technology,
that you should always ask for shares of the stock if you can,''
Inker said. ``It's very tough to value this market.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is crazy,'' Inker said. ``You show me how you get the
difference between $4 million and $1 billion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
