<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-17 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO THE CORE HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 28 and a single engineer. I bought a condominium about a
year ago. I have no other liabilities and I am putting 2 percentof
my $48,000 salary into my company's 401(k) plan. I also have saved
about $10,000 and I would like to put some of it into Fidelity
mutual funds. I would like to know the difference between growth
and growth and income funds, and which is more suitable for
long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   R.S., Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The terms ``growth'' and ``growth and income'' have gone out
of fashion to a certain degree in the last few years, but they
still can be useful tags.
</P>
<P>
   Growth funds are those that build a portfolio of stocks
representing companies deemed to have above-average capacity for
growth, both in terms of growth in revenues and profits, and
particularly growth in stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Growth and income funds are those whose portfolios represent a
compromise of sorts _ seeking a certain degree of income while
still retaining some capacity for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Morningstar Mutual Funds, a couple of years ago people
began to characterize fund portfolios by putting them into a grid,
with portfolio characteristics ranging from value through blend to
growth, and with the market sectors that dominate the portfolio
designated as small-cap, mid-cap, and large-cap funds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the old growth and income funds are now classified as
large-cap blend funds; perhaps the archetypal Fidelity fund would
be its Spartan Market Index, which seeks to track the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index. A similar offering, but one that is actively
managed, is Fidelity Growth and Income.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the large-cap spectrum you would find Fidelity's
Equity-Income funds in the large-cap value part of the grid (with
portfolios dedicated to stocks with substantial dividend yields but
less prospect for growth), and Fidelity Growth Company at the other
end, holding a portfolio whose yield is a near-negligible 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who adopt a long-term investment plan begin with
what they consider their core holdings. These will typically be
large-cap blend funds for people whose investment time frame is
less than 15 years or whose appetite for risk isn't all that great.
It's large-cap growth funds for people who figure they can ride out
the invariable bumps in the markets, and for those such as yourself
who have many years to accumulate a retirement nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   If I were advising a 28-year-old on a long-term portfolio, I'd
suggest you put $2,000 in an IRA in Spartan Market Index, $2,500 in
Fidelity Select Health Care, and $2,500 in Fidelity Equity-Income
II.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Health Care fund holds a portfolio that falls in
the large-cap growth corner of the grid, it is a sector fund,
investing all of its portfolio in one industry; for that reason, it
is generally considered even more risky than a large-cap growth
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Equity-Income II falls in the large-cap value grid. (It's worth
noting that, in the current market, values are so high that even an
income-oriented portfolio such as this fund's yields only 1 percent
_ five times that of Growth Company, but still mighty low compared
with markets of old that typically delivered dividend yields in the
area of 2 to 3 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   I suggested the amounts above because both Health Care and
Equity-Income II have minimum initial investments of $2,500; for
regular accounts, Spartan Market Index requires a $10,000 initial
investment, but the amount is reduced to as little as $500 for IRA
accounts. Start by fully funding your IRA, and if you're unwilling
to commit a further $5,000, select one additional fund.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I wish you could contribute more of your salary to your
company's 401(k). For example, if you put 5 percent of your income
into the plan, your $200 monthly contributions would, by the time
you are 65, build a nest egg of $828,314, presuming average annual
returns of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear you thinking _ well, there will be time enough for
that later on, and there are lots of ways for a 28-year-old to
spend his or her money.
</P>
<P>
   But you should also consider the fact that the most important
dollar in your retirement portfolio is the first one in.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you decided to continue with your current $80 monthly
contributions until you are 40, and then bump up your contributions
to the point that's necessary to get to the same final result. At
age 40 you would have to take a giant step upward in the savings
rate _ from $80 to $482 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you can't take the jump from 2 percent to 5 percent,
anything you can add at this point should loom very large in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I invested $10,000 each for my five grandchildren, who range
in age from 3 to 10, putting the money in Pioneer Capital Growth
fund. Recent performance has been poor, with the account balances
down to $8,747 at the end of last year. Should I take the losses
and run, or do nothing?
</P>
<P>
   B.C., La Jolla, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This may be a success spoils the fund story, or perhaps an
illustration of the need to watch a fund very carefully after a
portfolio manager change. Either way, it's a bad news story for
owners of Pioneer Capital Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, this was a small-cap value-oriented fund, with a
long record of superior performance, ending in 1995. Since then, it
has generally operated at the bottom of its peer group. In its last
top-quartile year, 1994, fund manager Warren Isabelle managed a
$437.8 million portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of 1997, shortly before Isabelle left the fund
and turned the reins over to J. Rodman Wright, assets were $1.39
billion and growing. Although the fund gained 11.26 percent that
year, it trailed its peer group average of 25.27 percent growth
markedly; last year it lost 4.17 percent, which compared with a
1.40 percent gain for its average peer. Its portfolio also has
migrated from the small-cap value category to mid-cap value.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has recovered a bit this year, with Lipper Analytical
Services Inc. reporting a 10.67 percent year-to-date gain through
May 5, which compares with a 6.70 percent average gain for its peer
funds. That's a pretty significant turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, I would hang on, but tentatively, analyzing the
fund's performance on a monthly basis. If you see two consecutive
months in which the fund returns to its former subpar performance,
I'd then streak for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am interested in obtaining a listing of the companies from
which I could purchase common stock without the use of a broker,
and also whether they participate in a dividend reinvestment and
stock purchase plan.
</P>
<P>
   G.R., Lansford, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a number of companies issuing directories listing
both companies with dividend reinvestment plans and companies that
will sell stock directly to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The one I have been using is the annual ``Directory of Companies
Offering Dividend Reinvestment Plans,'' published by Evergreen
Enterprises of Laurel, Md., which you can reach by calling (301)
549-3939.
</P>
<P>
   The company will be issuing the 16th edition of the 160-page
directory shortly, and it will not only list all companies with
DRIPS, but also 99 companies that offer sales of securities
directly to owners.
</P>
<P>
   I think you'll find that virtually every company that offers
direct sales also offers a DRIP, but without seeking the new
edition, I can't promise that.
</P>
<P>
   I have always suggested that paring down the whole universe of
potential stock investments to fewer than 100 simply to avoid a
token brokerage fee _ and even more token now that discount brokers
have taken rates ever lower _ is a poor strategy for making an
investment decision.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I have said this, about a half-dozen people have
written telling of their success using this approach _ and have
suggested that I might go soak my head.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
