<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      05-17 1812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING MUSICAL COMPETITIONS INTO A WIN-WIN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nature is red in tooth and claw, and competition is one of the
facts of nature, where only the fittest survive. Every blade of
grass knows this, even if some critics of musical competitions do
not.
</P>
<P>
   Competition also seems to be an essential component of human
nature. Like most other aspects of human nature, it has been
responsible for much that is good, and much that is not. That's one
reason many people hold such ambivalent attitudes toward
competition, applauding it in sports arenas, rewarding it in
commerce with money and pink Cadillacs, while deploring it in other
fields of endeavor, and questioning the competitive instinct as
proper motivation for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Competition has nevertheless been a part of organized musical
life since organized musical life has existed. Wagner wrote two
long operas about singing contests in the Middle Ages.
Institutionalized music competitions are an invention of the 19th
century, like many other artistic institutions that are struggling
to continue existing at the close of the 20th. Their history is
interesting, remarkable, and, from the partial point of view
provided by hindsight, not particularly distinguished. Aesthetic
judgments lie in an area where the vagaries of taste intersect with
the solidity of fact. Greatness in musicianship is certainly
irrefutable _ people feel it, recognize it when they hear it _ but
it is also nearly always controversial _ it can't be judged by
objective criteria like the biggest zucchini or the heaviest
pumpkin at a state fair.
</P>
<P>
   The history of French music was written by composers who failed
to win the Prix de Rome, sometimes repeatedly. Some of the greatest
performing careers of the 20th century have been spurred on by
competitions, but one can hardly imagine that the extraordinary
talents of Emil Gilels or Martha Argerich or even Van Cliburn would
have languished in obscurity if these pianists had not won
competitions or even if they had not participated in them. Indeed
it can be argued that Cliburn's paradigmatic but unrepeatable
victory in the Tchaikovsky Competition in 1958 did him no personal
favors.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows the arguments against competitions. The members
of the International Federation of Music Competitions have heard
them more often than people in my equally disreputable line of work
have written them _ the corrupt juries, unfair voting systems, jury
walkouts and audience outrage, retrograde repertory, cookie-cutter
consensus winners that were everone's second choice, the ``losers''
who went on to great careers, the winners who self-destructed.
Every aspect of competitions has been roundly criticized. I have
been disturbed myself by the way competitions have competed with
each other to create bigger prizes, including too many concerts. A
winner who is equipped to take on a 100-concert schedule
immediately may not be the same person as the most compelling,
individual, and exploratory artist in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that some of the great pianists of the past
wouldn't have gotten past the first round of a high-powered
contemporary competition. Alfred Cortot is by common acclaim one of
the greatest pianists ever to have recorded Chopin, but would he
have survived the opening round of a Chopin competition today?
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up, the leading pianists in America were
Rubinstein, Vladimir Horowitz, Rudolf Serkin, and Claudio Arrau.
Four more individual and incomparable musicians would be impossible
to imagine, and you can just imagine what a jury would say about
each of them. Rubinstein was casually sloppy and simplified the
notes; Horowitz was vulgar and distorted the music; Arrau lacked
lightness and spontaneity; and Serkin struggled against the piano
instead of playing it.
</P>
<P>
   Together at the top
</P>
<P>
   Yet the obvious limitations of each of these artists in no way
obscures his greatness, and when you consider the group
collectively, a critical point emerges: At the top level, musicians
are not better than each other. Instead they are different from
each other, and that is why we value them; each of them brings
something unique to our experience of performance.
</P>
<P>
   Every component of our interactive musical ecology is being
blamed for the current crisis _ the disappearance of musical
training and experience as a part of general public education;
rapacious managers and superstars; arrogant orchestras and opera
companies; vulgar competitions whimpering through the last gasp of
the played-out, big-bow-wow repertory; the Vivaldization of radio;
the naivete and commercialism of the record companies; the
mean-spiritedness of crapulent critics. The media denounce the
decline of standards while making their own substantial
contribution to that decline. Yet at the same time, the musical
impulse still wells up in children and young people round the
world, the need and hunger for artistic expression, the need to
express themselves through music or to confirm and enlarge their
feelings by listening to it. Our current musical scene is woefully
deficient in many things, but not in talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education'' is the buzzword of the day, the hope for salvation
_ if we could only get music back into the schools, we would be on
the right track again. It's true, nothing will ever replace the
``hands-on'' experience of singing, playing an instrument, creating
new music; children who learn to make music become the adult
audiences for music. But access is at least as important as most of
what passes for education today _ and indeed, access is a
prerequisite to education. Because many of the avenues of access
today's concertgoers grew up with are now closed _ regularly
touring attractions, significant presence of concert music in the
media, affordable tickets _ the first priority of classical
musicians should be to open new ones, and competitions are well
placed to do so. They are exciting, dramatic, and human, and the
public loves them. Audiences can respond to competitions because
some aspects of the experience are already familiar to them, even
if music isn't. Competitions can lead audiences into the musical
world.
</P>
<P>
   To say this means adjusting the traditional focus of
comeptitions, which has always centered on what they can do for the
artist-contestant. What a competition cannot do anymore is create a
superstar, except maybe in singing, where the repertory coincides
with the attention span of the competing media, and where how a
performer looks is a conscious and important part of the equation.
It is careless of the media to use the subsequent celebrity of a
competition winner to validate, or invalidate, a competition. Yet
it is reckless for a competition to seek to validate itself through
this alone. To an outsider, competitions seem pathetically eager to
buy into an establishment that is at the point of well-deserved
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The repertory question
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the International Federation of Music
Competitions and the individual members of the Federation have
repeatedly considered and reconsidered every process and aspect of
the competition process _ selection of contestants; selection of
the jury; repertory; the adjudication process; the prizes; the
follow-up. All of these areas remain open to discussion because all
of them are open to refinement and improvement.
</P>
<P>
   There is not space to address all these aspects, but I would
like to make three quick points regarding repertory reqirements.
</P>
<P>
   --Not even the greatest pianists with the widest repertories
played everything equally well, so there is no reason to expect
that a young musician should.
</P>
<P>
   --High seriousness has won the battle but lost the war. One
result of this is that young pianists must prove their mettle by
scaling the highest peaks of the repertory every time out; the
``Goldberg'' and ``Diabelli'' Variations, the late Beethoven
Sonatas, and the other canonized masterpieces dominate recital
programs. One reason the solo recital has fallen out of popular
favor is that recitals have become solemn rites in the holy temple
of music, and musicians and audiences are afraid to have fun
anymore, at least until encore time. But you can identify a great
pianist at work in a few bars of a Chopin waltz just as easily as
you can in Beethoven's Op. 111.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this year I have heard audiences literally sigh with
pleasure during concerts, both times during ``unimportant'' works _
when Garrick Ohlsson played Chopin's C-sharp Minor Waltz and when
Dubravka Tomsic played Saint-Saens's Second Concerto with the
Boston Symphony Orchestra. I believe that there should be a special
``encore'' category in competitions that would probably be far more
revealing than the standard ``etude'' category, where nearly
everyone sounds alike.
</P>
<P>
   --Since the first Anton Rubinstein competition, there has been a
century's worth of important new repertory, a fact insufficiently
recognized in piano competitions by the inevitable presence of the
same handful of early 20th-century classics, or by the regular
commissioned ``competition pieces,'' few of which have actually
enriched the literature _ or even entered it.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that contestants should play something written in
their own lifetimes in their own country of origin, preferably by
someone they know. Resistance to this, I'm afraid, does not come
from artist-contestants or even from audiences, who always respond
to music played from inner conviction, as commissioned pieces
rarely are. Resistance is more likely to arise from the marketing
people, the managers, the competitions themselves. One effective
way to attract a young audience is to present a young artist
playing music by a young composer who is expressing his or her own
feelings and concerns and, indirectly, those of a generation. This
is one of the engines beyond simple commercial savvy that drives
popular music, and it works in the world of art music too. Our
colleages and friends in the guitar world know this better than the
rest of us, because guitarists have had to create their concert
literature within this century.
</P>
<P>
   Validation comes not from identifying a future superstar or from
the futile attempt to create one. Instead it comes from identifying
and helping some of the people who will lead rich musical lives,
and not always within the traditional boundaries. It should also be
measured in accomplishments that are not secondary, like service to
the community where the competition takes place and to the musical
community as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(This is an abridgment of a speech Globe music critic Richard Dyer
made at the annual meeting of the International Federation of Music
Competitions in Dublin in April.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
