 Monday, May 17, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURTS-GERRYMANDERING (Washington) _ In a ruling that could have
a major impact on politics around the country, the Supreme Court
limits judges' ability to strike down election districts drawn by
state legislatures on the grounds that the lawmakers used race as
the major factor in setting the boundaries. Judges now will have to
be more certain of the role race played in the legislators'
reapportionment plans. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-WELFARE (Washington) _ Calling California's welfare law
``a discriminatory scheme,'' the Supreme Court strikes down the
1997 measure, which would have granted the state's newcomers lower
welfare benefits than those received by residents who have lived
there longer. The 7-2 decision, which could affect 14 other states,
says the limit on benefits for new residents violates their
constitutional right to travel. By MARK HELM. (1stLd-Writethru of
story filed earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   Editors: Marianne Means is on vacation. Her MEANS-COLUMN, which
runs in the COMMENTARY (``k'') category will next be filed on June
1.
</P>
