<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Bird by Bird with Annie'' At a mere 40 minutes, Freida
Lee Mock's documentary on quirky author Anne Lamott is simply too
short to do justice to Lamott's expansive, complicated life as a
recovering-alcoholic born-again-Christian liberal feminist. But
scenes of her readings, a showcase for her considerable humor and
talents, make this brief glimpse worthwhile. (Unrated) (Renee
Graham) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``The Castle'' A winningly good-natured Aussie ``Brady Bunch''
that celebrates family togetherness and ignores bad home decor.
Such story as there is revolves around the family's way of rallying
to fight big money's attempts to bulldoze their homesite to expand
Melbourne's airport. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!! ``Tea with Mussolini'' There really is a tea with the
Italian fascist dictator in this film, which celebrates the style
and backbone of a colony of reality-denying Englishwomen. They're
determined not to notice, even as World War II approaches, that
Florence no longer is going to be their playground. It's overlong,
but Maggie Smith, Joan Plowright, and Judi Dench as the unsinkable
Brits will keep you from being bored. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``This Is My Father'' Almost radically unfashionable, this is a
beautifully crafted if decidedly leisurely film about a burned-out
Chicago history teacher who goes back to Ireland to learn about the
father he never knew. Moya Farrelly is a find as the teacher's
vivacious mother as a young woman, and Aidan Quinn touchingly plays
his passionate but bottled-up mystery figure of a father. This
family project was written and directed by Paul Quinn and
photographed by Declan Quinn. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Three Seasons'' A delicate take on four contemporary
Vietnamese working-class types _ street peddler, cyclo driver,
prostitute, and lotus harvester. But while Tony Bui's film, the
first American independent feature to be filmed in Vietnam, is long
on atmosphere, it seems rudderless and disjointed, a screenful of
ingredients waiting to be forged into a compelling whole. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! ``Trippin' What with the current deluge of teen films clogging
cineplexes, it was only a matter of time before a hip-hop version
of the trend found its way onto the big screen. Hence, there's
``Trippin' ,'' which manages to prove only that Hollywood finds
black teens as inane, uninspired, and sex-mad as their white
counterparts. (R) (Renee Graham) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! ``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream'' A
disappointingly pedestrian treatment of the Bard's moonlit comedy.
Instead of gossamer eroticism, it gives us mud wrestling
(literally), plus a lot of verbal grappling by insufficiently
equipped players. The best thing in it is Kevin Kline's Bottom the
Weaver, who captures not only the role's horseplay, but a wistful
romanticism that eludes the others. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
