<HEADER>
A0150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-FANS-BOS &LR;      05-17 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN BEFORE THE OPENING, THEY ARE WITH THE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a galaxy not too far, far away where people say a movie
changed their lives, where husbands do Jedi impressions for
oh-so-patient wives, and 30-year-olds sleep on 20-year-old
bedsheets that contain the faded image of Boba Fett.
</P>
<P>
   This week, after a 16-year hiatus, the age of the ``Star Wars''
fanatic is again at hand.
</P>
<P>
   They sit next to you on the T. They like NASCAR. They write TV
sitcoms. They design Web pages. And in three days, the latest phase
of their ``Star Wars'' lives officially begins with the release of
``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' George Lucas's latest, all-new,
much-anticipated celluloid baby.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing you can do to stop the estimated 2.2 million
people nationwide who experts predict will take an unofficial
holiday so they can see the movie when it opens Wednesday at 12:01
a.m. After all, these are the people who waited in line or online
or on the phone last week in order to scoop up the prized tickets
when they went on sale. Better to sit back, ask a few questions,
and try to figure out what makes these people's passion for this
movie burn hotter than a double-ended light saber.
</P>
<P>
   We begin at 9:30 on a quiet Sunday night in the Back Bay when
Mark Ennis, 22, and Phil Damour, 21, rounded the corner at the
teddy bear in front of F.A.O. Schwarz and witnessed what, to them,
was the impossible. They were No. 1 and 2 in line with 2 1/2 hours
to go before the store opened to sell the newest ``Star Wars''
stuff. By midnight, they would be joined by hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, said the two Boston University students when they realized
they would be the first ones in the door. ``We expected the line
would be around the block already.''
</P>
<P>
   When they were asked what makes ``Star Wars'' so special, there
was no easy answer. There never is.
</P>
<P>
   They said it's the best pulp sci-fi movie ever made and waxed on
about the lasers and the special effects and even Princess Leia's
gold bikini. Only one word was heard time and time again _
``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   A clawing mosh pit
</P>
<P>
   When F.A.O. Schwarz's doors finally opened to the strains of the
movie's familiar theme, Ennis, Damour, and their fellow ``Star
Wars'' aficionados galloped up the escalators and formed a clawing
mosh pit around the action figures. Display pegs were picked clean
in about 10 minutes. Workers began restocking the display pegs
after the crowds dwindled, indicating there was plenty more to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hassenfeld, the chairman and CEO of Hasbro, the company
that stands to make a pretty penny off all this plastic booty, even
showed up for the midnight sale. ``It's cool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the store was Tige Quintina, a 30-year-old Web page
designer from Revere, to whom ``Star Wars'' is as much a part of
life as, say, eating. He had seen the movie 15 times by the time he
was 8.
</P>
<P>
   And when girlfriend Rebecca Clements came into his life and he
invited her to his apartment, he didn't think twice about the
``Star Wars'' spaceships hanging from the ceiling, the crates
filled with action figures, or the faded ``Star Wars'' bedsheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very open about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew,'' said Rebecca, recalling that visit, ``that I was
getting to know another dimension of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the Internet, we found the craze is not limited to the
States. In London, Paul Rose is planning to fly to Boston to see
the premiere. Airline tickets were cheap, and the 26-year-old
investment banker said he couldn't wait until July 16, when ``The
Phantom Menace'' will be released in England. By that time, he
said, he'll know everything about the film via the scourge of
rumor-mill Internet sites that he checks daily.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Gabrielle, is coming, too. After all, she's been
putting up with Rose's habit of pulling his blue robe over his head
and repeating Jedi lines word for word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I get on her nerves quite a lot,'' Rose said. ``But
how I do wish that robe were brown and hooded.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, television writer Brett Dewey, 33, who has
written for ``Saved by the Bell'' and is currently writing for
``Malibu, CA,'' was thinking back to his Cape Cod youth in South
Dennis when he credited 1980's ``The Empire Strikes Back'' with
leading him into a career as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tape-recorded the entire movie,'' he said. ``And the first
script I ever wrote was a transcription of that tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewey is also the creator of an Internet site that has coined a
phrase bound to become all too common in three days _ wookie hooky.
</P>
<P>
   The site at http://wookieehooky.starwarsfan.com is a compendium
of pledges and excuses to be used on Wednesday: At the site,
nurses, congressional aides, and even parents and their willing
kids have pledged to shut down on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a holiday''
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who care about these movies, it's a holiday,'' said
Dewey. ``This has more meaning than Arbor Day or Flag Day to a
`Star Wars' fan. It's going to be mania.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people out here in Los Angeles who are my
age, and we're all motivated to get involved in movies and
television thanks to `Star Wars,' '' he said. ``At the time the
film was released, we had never really seen behind-the-scenes
specials about how films were made. `Star Wars' changed all that
and opened up this whole new world for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Suzanne Welke, 33, an associate producer for
television's ``Wings'' and ``Jenny'' in Los Angeles. Yoda came to
her wedding _ or at least a cutout-cardboard Yoda. Han was there
too, and Leia and Luke and, well, everybody, all in one-dimensional
form.
</P>
<P>
   The newlyweds accepted Jeffrey Dollars from Toys ``R'' Us as
wedding presents (all spent on ``Star Wars'' collectibles, all of
which are cataloged in a database). She had originally planned to
wear ``Star Wars'' outfits at the wedding, but Steve, her
husband-to-be, said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be: `Two freaks married in `Star Wars' wedding _ tape
at 11,' '' recalled Suzanne. ``Plus he was worried that his best
man would have to wear a Chewbacca suit.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, Julie Mackler, 10; Josh Mackler, 8; and
friend Korinna George, 10, were traipsing out of Skinner's Back Bay
auction house in Boston and into the bright sunshine when they were
asked about their impressions of ``Star Wars'' passion.
</P>
<P>
   A hint of adulthood shone on their faces. For after witnessing
an auction in which $41,342 had been spent on ``Star Wars''
posters, lobby cards, banners, and other adult toys, these kids
were dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would they pay so much for these things from, like, 20
years ago?'' asked Josh. ``They must love it. Or maybe they're just
going to sell it for more money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love `Star Wars,' '' added Korinna, ``but I wouldn't go so
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mackler, otherwise known as Dad, was still upstairs,
looking and examining and bidding. When the kids thought about him,
they nodded and realized what they were dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy who loves this stuff, science fiction and
all,'' said Josh. ``And when he's around it, he's more like a kid.
I guess he just thinks it's cool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
