<HEADER>
A0151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HYPE-BOS &LR;      05-17 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HYPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY THE HYPE BE WITH YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gentlemen, start your warp drives. If they haven't been warped,
that is. Or burned out. It's hard to believe that ``The Phantom
Menace,'' George Lucas's ``Star Wars'' prequel, will actually open
Wednesday. It seems as if it's been around for ages. Mea culpa
here, I guess. We of the media don't exactly occupy the moral high
ground on the overexposure issue. No writer or editor wants to be
caught behind the curve, especially in a time when people _ read
the ``Phantom Menace'' target audience _ are getting information in
new ways, mostly on the Internet. So it's going to be hard for
people to look at ``The Phantom Menace'' with fresh eyes, much less
a sense of discovery. Did somebody say information overload?
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago (last Sunday) in a galaxy not far away (a hotel on
Park Avenue in Manhattan), George Lucas sat, trying to play down
the whole ``Star Wars'' and ``Phantom Menace'' brouhaha, going the
spin-doctor route to head off backlash. Suggesting, in his coiffed
salt-and-pepper hair and matching beard, a Marin County ewok, Lucas
said it was only a movie and that obsessional fans should get a
life. No, ``Star Wars'' isn't a religion, he said, and was never
intended to be. But even Lucas seemed intimidated by the huge wave
of anticipation cresting over ``The Phantom Menace.'' ``I certainly
expect not to do well critically,'' he said _ an expectation borne
out by a few critics who jumped the gun with lukewarm reviews. ``I
expect to be trashed. When you have such high expectations, you
can't possibly live up to them,'' he said, adding that the whole
thing had gotten out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   No argument there. The culture has undergone a sea change
between the arrival of ``Star Wars'' in 1977 and ``The Phantom
Menace'' in 1999. ``Star Wars'' helped get it there. It hastened
the cyber revolution by amping it up to warp speed in the public
mind, ushered in the era of movies created in large part at
computer keyboards, as ``The Phantom Menace'' was. During the
shoot, whether in Tunisia or outside London, the actors mostly
acted against nothing. The backgrounds and creatures were added
later. Lucas sees ``The Phantom Menace'' as a way station to the
time when films will be made and projected digitally. Knowing he's
calling the shots here, he has been dictating terms to theaters. He
calls it quality control. To load his film down with trailers and
present it with what he regards as inadequate equipment is, in his
analogy, akin to ``playing symphonies on crappy stereos.''
</P>
<P>
   All eyes on the opening
</P>
<P>
   There's another warp-drive factor at work here. It has to do
with the importance attached to the opening weekend. Late on Friday
nights, interested movie-biz participants gather to learn the
grosses. Then, like pollsters who predict the outcome of elections
with only a few percent of the vote tallied, they predict the box
office fate of the film. It's a practice in synch with the
instant-gratification reflex of a society that can't infantilize
itself fast enough. Almost altogether gone is the practice of
platforming a film, allowing it to find its audience. The big-bang
theory has taken over. For years stars drove films, for a brief
while directors did, and now it's the marketers who occupy the
driver's seat in Hollywood. Picking the right weekend to open a
film _ especially in the summer, when the stakes are at their
highest _ has become the sexiest high-stakes game in Hollywood.
Marketing execs call the shots, even to the extent of assigning an
opening date before production execs assign a start date.
</P>
<P>
   You can't help enjoying one reversal attached to ``Star Wars.''
Lucas likes to refer to himself as this little independent
filmmaker outside off-the-beaten-path San Francisco. At the time of
the original ``Star Wars'' he was. He had to go hat in hand to the
studio, in this case 20th Century-Fox. Now studios go hat in hand
to him. This time around, Fox will earn only a distribution fee,
placed by unconfirmed reports at between 8 and 10 percent of the
worldwide grosses. By today's standards, Lucas is modest about the
whole box office thing. ``The Phantom Menace'' _ brought in at $115
million, chump change at current prices, and in any case $5 million
under budget _ won't unseat ``Titanic,'' he predicts, or ``E.T.,''
or ``Star Wars.'' He does expect it to wind up in the Top 10. If it
doesn't do well, it may mean no second and third prequels, says
Lucas, who reminds journalists that ``Star Wars'' paid for ``The
Empire Strikes Back,'' which in turn paid for ``Return of the
Jedi.'' They all paid for Industrial Light &AMP; Magic, the company he
invented to make the technology he needed for the first trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas says that the launching and running of ILM absorbed him to
the point where he had to hand the direction of the second and
third ``Star Wars'' sequels to others. One reason he waited so long
to get back to the saga, he says, is that he needed time to evolve
the technology he felt deprived of the first time around. When he
had it, he went back and touched up the first three films before
re-releasing them in 1997. ILM gave him the autonomy he wanted. So
did his foresight. At the time of the original ``Star Wars''
release, he cut his fee from Fox by $500,000 in exchange for the
sequel and merchandising rights. He didn't envision much more than
posters and T-shirts, and those only to promote the movie. Two
decades later, the toys and action figures have grossed something
like $5 billion. Lucas owns a piece of Hasbro, the toy
manufacturers. They paid him a $100 million advance on the
``Phantom Menace'' gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``A violent world''
</P>
<P>
   Partly because ``The Phantom Menace'' is aimed at younger
audiences, as Lucas admits, it's less gory than most of the films
``Star Wars'' hatched, for all the new film's laser sword fights
and explosions. Still, the toys send a message. As Pernilla August,
the Swedish actress who plays young Anakin's mother, says,
``There's no mommy action figure.'' Lucas answers the violence
question with the context answer, namely that you can't generalize
about scenes of violence but must evaluate each specifically and
ascertain its dramatic validity. ``Obviously, you can't be hurting
people for fun and enjoyment. That's the central issue. You have to
fight for freedom or self-defense. But we live in a violent world.
To deny it is almost as dangerous as glorifying violence,'' he
says. Yet there's a subtler and more profound form of violence
attached to the ``Star Wars'' movies, ``The Phantom Menace''
included.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has many times cited the mythic-religious core of the
``Star Wars'' films. He proudly cites his mentor-disciple
relationship with the late Joseph Campbell, whose classic study of
quest legends in ``The Hero With a Thousand Faces'' has spelled out
their workings for this generation. The films externalize internal
struggles, characters trying to do right, falling from grace, being
redeemed, spanning spiritual darkness with spiritual connections,
including love and family. As the Jedi code puts it, fear is the
path to the dark side _ fear leads to anger, anger leads to hate,
hate leads to suffering. Lucas is the first to point out that there
isn't enough in ``Star Wars'' to be a religion. Yet he says the
movies have been designed to make young audiences think about
larger entities.
</P>
<P>
   The wars in ``Star Wars'' stem from material greed. The ultimate
loss in ``The Phantom Menace'' is the loss of a trade franchise.
Yet these films that argue against becoming possessed by
possessions have themselves become a huge trade franchise. Is there
not a fundamental contradiction between the message of the films
and the message of the merchandising? Even in a culture where the
measure of a film has become its opening weekend gross and not its
content? ``It doesn't seem to bother the church very much,'' Lucas
replies, rationalizing that his practice of using the proceeds of
one film to finance the next is not unlike an Indian killing a
buffalo, not idly, or for so-called sport, but to use all of it _
the meat for food, the skin for clothing and shelter, even the
bones for tools. ``Besides,'' Lucas says, ``I like toys. I think
play is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is evident not only in Lucas's films, but in his
micromanaged, self-perpetuating empire. The minions at his
keyboards have become toymakers to the world, dominating American
pop culture just as American pop culture dominates the world by
giving it its images and models. Hollywood has always lived by the
blockbuster. But blockbuster means something new in a
more-wired-than-ever millennial world. Movies have merged with
commercials and television and music videos to become one
mega-delivery system for images. Millennial blockbusters, of which
``The Phantom Menace'' is the latest, now arrive at a cultural
nexus of unprecedented electronic proliferation and warp-speed
debasement of what's being proliferated. Lucas now can leap
light-years with a single keystroke. But he can't run faster than a
rampaging consumer society devouring films and anything else it can
get its teeth on. Dark side, schmark side. As long as the Trade
Federation gets its piece of the action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
