A0155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
m n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FEATURE-STAR-WAR     05-17 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FEATURE-STAR-WARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS PAY TOP DOLLAR FOR EARLY SCREENING OF `STAR WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JASON LLOREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They came in droves, like battle droids on the
warpath.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,300 eager moviegoers, along with filmmaker George Lucas,
marched into the Galaxy Theatre Sunday for a charity premiere of
the long-awaited space-myth flick ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Troyer, a die-hard ``Star Wars'' fan from Redwood City,
Calif., who paid $500 for his ticket and waited four hours in line,
emerged from the theater Sunday evening with a hearty thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was sweet,'' he said. ``It had a lot of plot
twists. And the light saber duels, I loved them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Fisher of San Francisco took her son Ryan, 6, and his
friend Madeleine Charters, 6. The kids arrived dressed as Luke
Skywalker and Princess Leia, complete with toy blasters and light
sabers. Madeleine even had the Princess Leia hair thing going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just loved it,'' Fisher said. ``I was afraid Madeleine
was going to be frightened by the film. But it was delightful.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, who has a reputation as a
cinephile, called the film ``fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just pure, unadulterated entertainment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The red-carpet event netted $500,000 for the San Francisco Boys
and Girls Club. San Francisco was one of 11 North American cities
where the benefit screenings were held.
</P>
<P>
   About 130 young people from the Boys and Girls Club attended the
screening. Before the film rolled, the kids tried out two computer
games that aren't yet on store shelves: ``Star Wars: Episode I _
The Phantom Menace'' and ``Racer,'' which recreates the film's
fast-paced ``pod'' race. The children also received a tote bag of
movie treats, including action figures and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   After the screening, attendees were treated to a gala at the
Regency Building across the street. A life-size Darth Vader statue
in the lobby greeted arriving guests. They quickly filled the
Regency ballroom, enjoying live music and munching on assorted
gourmet fare _ roast beef, sliced pork sandwiches, sushi, steamed
buns, jumbo shrimp and beer.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the steep price he paid to attend the screening,
Troyer said at the gala, ``Might as well get my money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Money raised at the event will be used to expand programs for
the club's 4,000 youths. The organization has five branches in San
Francisco and a summer camp in Mendocino County.
</P>
<P>
   The ``prequel'' is set before the events in the original 1977-83
trilogy _ ``Star Wars,'' ``The Empire Strikes Back'' and ``Return
of the Jedi.''
</P>
<P>
   It tells the story of the boy Anakin Skywalker (who eventually
transforms into the evil Darth Vader) against the backdrop of an
interstellar war involving Queen Amidala's planet Naboo and the
aggressive Trade Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar characters from the previous films _ Yoda, Jabba the
Hutt, Obi-Wan Kenobi, C-3PO and R2-D2 _ appear in ``The Phantom
Menace.'' The film opens in general release on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews of ``The Phantom Menace'' are mixed. But many
people who saw the film Sunday raved about its fast-paced spaceship
battles, the strange new aliens, the terrifying villains and the
light saber duels.
</P>
<P>
   John Vrolyk, 11, of San Mateo said he enjoyed the film so much,
``I'm gonna see it five times.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Yaki, a San Francisco city supervisor, said the event
reminded him of a packed ``Return of the Jedi'' benefit screening
he attended in college in 1983. He said he's been waiting for ``The
Phantom Menace'' for a long time and shrugged off the early buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the critics say _ they don't get it!'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas explained the public's fascination with Luke Skywalker,
Yoda, TIE Fighters, and all things encompassing the Force by simply
saying, ``It's based on old stories that resonate with people.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizations selected for the benefit premiere cover a
range of charities. The Los Angeles screening was to benefit the
Santa Monica-based Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation,
while proceeds from the New York event were to go to the Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
