<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans one page of stories, photos and
graphics on the Israeli elections:
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-VOTE (Jerusalem) _ Ledeall on the election: Ehud Barak,
the Labor candidate, is expected to claim a decisive victory over
the incumbent prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, while voting ends at 3 p.m. EDT, with exit polling
projects shortly afterward, we do not expect firm results until
early evening.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ If he wins, a Man-in-the-News profile
on Barak. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ A news analysis on the election. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis over Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Robin Cook, the British foreign
secretary, emerges from a meeting of NATO ministers and presses
again for allied ground troops to enter Kosovo before Serbian
forces leave. Other developments, including talks between Gerhard
Schroeder, the german chancellor, and Massimo D'Alema, the Italian
prime minister in the Italian port city of Bari. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BRITAIN (London) _ British politicians, editorial writers
and others are criticizing Tony Blair, the prime minister, for his
unstinting support of President Clinton's Kosovo policy. But they
don't want to end the campaign; they want to send in ground troops.
By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Developments in the air campaign
in Yugoslavia. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   And this related story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Even as the China's leadership tries to
calm the waters, the People's Daily, the party's mouthpiece, on
Monday offered a front page editorial blasting the U.S. for its
vision of world domination that will ultimately fail and other
harsh comments. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (See also CHINA-TRADE, listed under Financial.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ An emergency meeting of top
officials of the Congress Party set to deal with an open revolt
among Congress traditionalists who would oppose Sonia Gandhi if she
decides to seek the prime minister's post. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Hundreds of leaders of PRI,
Mexico's governing party, meet today to decide formally on new
procedures for selecting the party's candidate for the July 2000
presidential elections. This follows an announcement that President
Ernesto Zedillo will not exercise his traditional powers to select
his successor. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Sergei Stepashin now looks a shoe-in
for confirmation by the Russian Duma in a vote scheduled for
Wednesday. He offers some elements of his thinking on the economy
and dashes any possibility of bringing back any liberal reformers
into the government. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WELFARE (Washington) _ In a closely watched welfare case,
the Supreme Court says in a 7-2 decision that states cannot cut
benefits to new arrivals. This strikes down a California law, which
was never put into effect, and negates a provision of the federal
welfare reform bill. More than a dozen other states have such laws.
By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-VOTE (Washington) _ In the fourth version of a North
Carolina voting rights case, involving a challenge to a remedial
district, the high court unanimously says that a new trial is
needed and that a special three-judge panel that reached summary
judgment in favor of the white plaintiffs was wrong. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ A roundup of Supreme Court action
(excluding the welfare and voting decisions): The court agrees to
decide whether Congress violated the rights of states by preventing
them from selling to commercial enterprises the personal data from
drivers licenses. Other cases. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Developments in behind-the-scenes
negotiation on whether the bill to which all the gun-control
amendments are attached will go forward or not. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-WHALE (Neah Bay, Wash.) _ For the first time in more
than 70 years, Makah Indians seeking to re-establish their
whale-hunting tradition harpooned a gray whale off the Pacific
coast this morning. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-EMISSIONS (Detroit) _ In the latest sign that automakers
are beginning to compete to build the cleanest-burning vehicles,
Ford announces it will voluntarily reduce pollution from its pickup
trucks starting this autumn, making them roughly as clean as cars.
By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-PHOBIA-DRUGS (Undated) _ Pharmaceutical companies have
slowly discovered that there is a huge potential market in social
phobia, a disorder that affects an estimated 19 million Americans.
Moreover, they do not have to spend hundreds of millions of dollars
to develop a new blockbuster drug to do the job. SmithKline Beecham
won approval Tuesday from the Food and Drug Administration to
market its antidepressant Paxil for social phobia. And other
companies are close behind. By Sankaran P. Raghunathan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   USWEST-GLOBAL (Undated) _ Folo on the stock swap merger of
Global Crossing and US West. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., stocks were lower, with the Dow
industrials down 134, the S&AMP;P down 10 and the NASDAQ composite down
10. At midday, the long-bond was little changed at 5.90 percent.
European and Asian markets were also lower, with London's FTSE 100
down 1.8 percent, Frankfurt's Dax down 1.5 percent, Tokyo's Nikkei
off 2.32 percent and Hong Kong's Hang Seng index down 2.08 percent.
However, Russian stocks rose 11.56 percent on the day. By Kenneth
N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-GULFSTREAM (Undated) _ General Dynamics Corp., the maker
of the F-16 jet fighter, is acquiring Gulfstream Aerospace in a
$5.3 billion deal that marks one of the company's first big
purchases in commercial aircraft. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   HP-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Hewlett-Packard is expected to
