<SLUG> BC-CALCIUM-TEENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKLET OFFERS ADVICE ON CALCIUM FOR TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a ``calcium crisis'' among teen-agers, according to
health and nutrition experts.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly nine out of 10 girls and seven of 10 boys get too little
calcium. The National Academy of Sciences recommends 1,300 mg of
calcium daily for teens _ the equivalent of four eight-ounce
glasses of milk.
</P>
<P>
   It's needed because 15 percent of adult height and half of all
bone mass are added during the teen years. Blame soda for
adolescents' calcium deficit: As teens have double or tripled their
soda intake in the past two decades, their milk consumption has
fallen by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest pegs boys' soda
intake at two and half cans daily. For girls, it's two cans.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Clueless About Calcium,'' a free booklet with information,
comparisons, recipes and tips for including more calcium in a
teen-age diet, call 800-WHY-MILK (949-6455).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK MEMORABILIA: For the Woodstock fan of your
acquaintance, at least one of a certain age, consider a framed
original poster and unused ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be perfect paired with, for example, those surprise tickets
to this summer's July 23-25, 30th anniversary extravaganza in Rome,
N.Y. The collectible wall-hanging, which we found in an airline
catalog, wonders why the original tickets are unused, something
that wouldn't have occurred to us. After all, wasn't the whole
point of the first fest that almost nobody had tickets anyway?
</P>
<P>
   A comparison: Tickets to Woodstock '69 originally cost $8; the
framed ticket and poster sells for $125; an original ticket was
auctioned in 1995 for $150, suggesting investment potential; and a
ticket to Woodstock/Rome '99 (on a former military base _ how
antithetical!) goes for $150.
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-333-8998 to order the collectible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN CONTEST: As a reward for being messy, Sunlight
Dishwashing Detergent is giving away five grand prizes of a year's
worth of twice-monthly housecleanings, plus another 10 packages
good for six months' worth of the same service.
</P>
<P>
   All you need to do to enter is send in a photo of your
calamitous kitchen and a 25-word essay on why your home's food
center needs cleaning. Be clever and concise.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes are valued at $1,800 and $900 apiece. Mail to
``Sunlight Clean Up Your Kitchen'' Contest, P.O. Box 1477, Young
America, MN 55594-1477, by Sept. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
