<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COURTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES NEW YORK TO BOOST PAY FOR DEFENSE LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A panel appointed by New York's chief judge to
study public trust in the justice system says increased funding for
legal services and higher pay for court-appointed lawyers is
crucial in fostering confidence in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   A report prepared by the committee urges the state to establish
a steady, reliable funding stream for legal service programs.
</P>
<P>
   It also says that the fees paid court-appointed defense
attorneys _ $25 per hour for out-of-court time and $40 per hour for
in-court time _ are ``wholly inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   The rates haven't risen since 1985. ``As a result, capable,
experienced attorneys are declining to serve as appointed or
assigned counsel because they cannot afford to work at these rates
and meet overhead expenses,'' according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Judith S. Kaye appointed the Committee to Promote
Public Trust and Confidence in the Legal System in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that while public trust and confidence in all
governmental institutions has eroded over the last 30 years, an
overwhelming number of Americans _ about 80 percent _ remain
convinced that, despite its problems, the U.S. justice system is
the best in the world. However, only 14 percent of those surveyed
in an American Bar Association poll earlier this year had a
favorable impression of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, the committee concludes, stems from the low
fees, and seemingly low priority, afforded legal service lawyers
and public defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This creates the impression that the poor are not receiving
the attention their cases merit or that counsel takes the most
expedient route, by plea bargaining or settling cases, because they
are not sufficiently compensated or do not have the time to
vigorously pursue them,'' according to the committee co-chaired by
Appellate Division Justice William C. Thompson and state Supreme
Court Justice Evelyn Frazee.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, legal service funding is negotiated annually in
budget dealings, which means the long-term viability of such
programs is always subject to political whim. Kaye has proposed
transferring $40 million annually from the state's Abandoned
Property Fund to cover legal aid programs, but her plan has not
been acted upon by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Fees paid to court-assigned lawyers is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers are pushing for their first raise in 13 years,
noting that there is a push in Washington to increase the federal
rate to $75 per hour _ well above what New York pays. In addition,
defense lawyers are suing Kaye and the Court of Appeals, seeking an
increase in rates for lawyers who handle death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, attorneys who represent indigent defendants facing
the death penalty are paid between $100 and $125 per hour. That
rate was set in December after the previous pay range _ $150 to
$175 per hour _ resulted in a torrent of criticism from
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye's committee, in addition to recommending increased pay for
lawyers, also presented several other proposals to increase trust
and confidence in the legal system. Among the recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide statewide sensitivity training for judges,
prosecutors, clerks and others on issues of bias and prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Promote greater representation of minorities in the justice
system, particularly as judges.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forgive law school debts owed by graduates who agree to work
in an office that serves low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Streamline the court system so it is easier to understand and
navigate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage judges to become more involved in community
activities so they do not appear so isolated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
