<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0518-COX     05-17 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICANS JOINING WITH KOSOVAR REBELS FOR LOVE OF COUNTRY --
KOSOVO
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURREL, Albania _ Frank Mehmeti -- his friends call him
``Nitty'' back in the neighborhood -- fears boredom may get him
before a Serb bullet can.
</P>
<P>
   At a countryside cafe -- the distinct smell of goats in the air
-- it is disconcerting to hear American English, much less this
Bronx accent, flowing from a soldier in a Kosovo Liberation Army
uniform. ``I was at a boxing match in April when I get a call on my
cellular (cellulah),'' the solidly built 24-year-old says as he
recounts his odyssey to Albania. ``They told me to go to this
restaurant to sign up.''
</P>
<P>
   He applied to renew his passport, and a few days later Mehmeti
was on a chartered airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Mehmeti had twice put his name on lists -- once in Washington,
once in New York -- offering to join the fight in Kosovo. His
parents emigrated from the small Kosovar town of Llap in the the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mehmeti was born and raised in the United States,
and is about as American as they come, he has a deep affection for
his family's homeland, which he visited 10 years ago. Five years
ago, he had a friend tattoo the black two-headed eagle of the
Albanian flag across his sizable forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, when he saw television footage of a massacre at a
Kosovar village, he vowed he would join the fight to liberate
Kosovo from Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   He's now one of the approximately 80 Americans -- three of whom
are women -- training at a camp about seven miles from this poor
mountain village in the rugged mountains above Tirana, the Albanian
capital. They are called the Atlantic Brigade, an outfit composed
largely of Albanian-Americans from enclaves in New York, Detroit
and Chicago. Many wear U.S. flag patches on their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   They have been here about a month. They train six days a week
and have been taught how to use the weapons the rebel army has
acquired -- mostly an assortment of aging Russian and Chinese
rifles and machine guns. ``The training is very good, I think we're
ready,'' says Mehmeti, whose previous experience with weapons is
limited to hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mehmeti is a big man by Albanian standards, he was
assigned a heavy and powerful weapon, the name of which escapes
him. ``It's really awesome,'' he says with genuine enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Language is a major problem. He speaks the Albanian he learned
from his mother, but struggles to understand the accents here.
``Sometimes it's a problem with orders,'' he says. ``I don't know
if they're saying catch them or kill them. I guess I'll kill them
and ask questions later.''
</P>
<P>
   He borrowed the money in America to buy his uniform, helmet,
bullet-proof vest and other basics. He gets no pay beyond the
subsistence living the rebels provide recruits.
</P>
<P>
   At the cafe during a Sunday afternoon break from camp, he digs
in to a plate of goat meat, tomatoes, olives and cheese and bread.
``I have to tell you,'' he confesses with reluctance, ``The food at
the camp sucks. Fegeddaboudit.''
</P>
<P>
   At first the recruits were given bread and onions, standard
Albanian fare. But the Americans clamored for more substance --
particularly meat -- and soon their diet improved. Hot showers
remain a luxury. ``You have to wait in line behind all these guys
and then you just get a minute or two,'' he says. ``I haven't had a
shower in two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he misses America. ``I miss just being able to hang
around, the computer, my girlfriend,'' he says, a brief sadness
coming over him. For a moment, he looks more boy than man.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't think about all that too much; you gotta think
about today,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the present is a problem too. The Atlantic Brigade has
completed its training, and its members have watched as other
outfits have headed to the front. As NATO heads into its third
month of bombing Serb targets in neighboring Yugoslavia, it is
beginning to look as if the KLA leaders may be reluctant to send
the Americans into combat.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In Burrel, a KLA commander, who asked that his name not be used,
said that the rebel army makes no distinctions with regard to the
origins of its soldiers, many of whom have come from outside
Albania or Kosovo. ``They are all fighting to liberate Kosovo from
the Serb oppressor,'' he said. ``They are the same in our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehmeti has become so impatient that he asked to be transferred
to an Albanian unit headed to the front. ``They said 'no,' that I
have to stay with the unit I'm assigned to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The front, which shifts between the border between Albania and
Kosovo province, has been described by journalists as reminiscent
of World War I, with both sides dug in and firing at relatively
close range.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the guys who was with us, a French guy, got
transferred,'' Mehmeti says. ``We heard he was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he too is willing to die and is convinced he could kill
a Serb soldier. ``Hey, he'd kill me if I didn't,'' he said,
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from is a tough place,'' he says. ``We're used to
danger and guns. One of my friends was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get killed here, then it will at least it will be for a
purpose that's bigger than any one person,'' he says. ``If I get
killed at home, they'd say, 'Oh, it's just another street kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
