<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLANES-EARACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECONGESTANT IS FOUND USELESS FOR YOUNG FLIERS' EARACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study finds that giving children a decongestant does
nothing to ease the earaches they often suffer during takeoffs and
landings _ or, indirectly, the headaches that some neighboring
passengers sustain from the crying that follows.
</P>
<P>
   The news, unwelcome at any time of year, comes as many families
prepare to take airplane flights long and short over the summer
vacation season. The study appears this month in The Archives of
Pediatric and Adolescent Medicine, published by the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The most useful advice the article held out to parents was an
editor's note from Dr. Catherine D. DeAngelis, editor of the
journal. ``Give the child something to stimulate swallowing on
ascent and descent,'' she wrote, ``let nature take care of the
problem, and throw the medication out the door _ preferably before
you take off.''
</P>
<P>
   The study took a look at the effectiveness of pseudoephedrine, a
popular decongestant. Many adults who suffer from earaches when
they fly say the medication alleviates the problems. But although
parents are often advised by doctors or friends to try the drug if
their children have trouble flying, its effectiveness in children
has not been established, the authors of the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author, Dr. Brian J. Buchanan, a medical resident at
the University of California at Davis, said he began the study
because patients kept asking him about the drug and he was not sure
how to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers reviewed the experiences of 50 children who had
taken 91 flights. Parents of the children _ age 6 months to 6 years
_ were given either placebos or doses of pseudoephedrine to give
their children, along with questionnaires on which they reported
their observations.
</P>
<P>
   When doctors reviewed the results, they found that the children
who had been given the drug did not seem to suffer any less pain
over all than those who had been given the placebo. The children
who took pseudoephedrine did, however, appear drowsy 60 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But while drowsiness in the airborne young would delight many a
parent, the report cautioned against using pseudoephedrine to
achieve this effect.
</P>
<P>
   Earaches caused by air travel, known as aerotitis media, are
common, especially among young children. They develop as the plane
changes altitude and disparities occur between the air pressure in
the cabin and the pressure of the small amount of air within the
inner ear.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane rises and the cabin pressure decreases, the air
inside the ear expands, causing discomfort. Most children appear to
have more problems during the descent, as increasing cabin pressure
reverses the process.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors have suggested that children may be more prone to
the problem because of anatomical differences between their
eustachian tubes, the slender passageway responsible for equalizing
ear pressure, and those of adults.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that although he was not surprised the
decongestant had not proven helpful, he was surprised by the amount
of drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``While drowsiness is a known side effect of pseudoephedrine,''
he said, ``one would also expect to see a lot of excitability. And
we did not see as much of that as we expected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
