<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FUTURE-TOILET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMART TOILET' IS OUT OF MEDICAL SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Tokyo, the electronics giant Matsushita is working on a
prototype house of the future chock-full of gadgets to keep track
of the owner's health _ right down to the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Health is not the only selling point in the ``Warp Square Home
Information Infrastructure,'' which the company hopes to have on
the market by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   There's video-on-demand and a link from the living room to an
``electronic town hall'' of municipal services. But the model home,
described this month in The Lancet, gives an idea of what a
doctor-turned-architect with a bushel of microchips might achieve
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The bedroom, for instance, has an electrocardiometer, a
blood-sugar meter and a thermometer, among other gadgets, and links
that can transfer their data not only to the home computer or
doctor's office, but also to the refrigerator and microwave, which
can then recommend recipes geared to your dietary needs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is the bathroom where, at least in this vision of the
future, nothing will be secret. Sensors and microchips embedded in
the toilet can provide a ``morning checkup'' by measuring the
user's weight, fat content and urine sugar levels, plot the data
recorded and can immediately notify the user's insurance company or
doctor of the results _ if the user wants. There is also an
in-bathroom health and diet advice center linked to Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   Matsushita engineers say the technology to deliver on this
prototype already exists. But it costs: the ``smart toilet'' alone
would be more than $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Akira Kadota, a Matsushita spokesman, said the company hoped the
health features would appeal to the elderly, whose numbers are
growing in all industrial countries, most rapidly in Japan, and
eventually to others with a keen interest in their well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 21st century, information services will be part of the
so-called lifelines, like electricity and gas,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
