<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: HEEDING WARNINGS FROM DANGEROUS DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that people and pets are spending more time outdoors, the
incidence of dog bites is about to soar, which is why the Humane
Society of the United States in conjunction with other concerned
agencies is once again urging the public to learn how to act around
dogs and what to do to prevent dog bites.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are cause for concern. Each year, the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention estimates, 4.7 million people are
bitten by dogs, 800,000 of them badly enough to require medical
treatment. At least 60 percent of dog bites and 72 percent of fatal
bites involve children. Half of all children in this country are
bitten by a dog before their 12th birthday. And since children are
most often bitten on the face, many need plastic surgery to
minimize unsightly scars.
</P>
<P>
   Few people are schooled in how to behave around dogs, either
their own or someone else's, and many dog owners handle their pets
in ways that ask for trouble. Potentially disastrous encounters
between dogs and children _ or dogs and adults _ are extremely
common. A child tries to pet a dog on the street without first
asking if it is safe to do so. Or a child frightened by a dog runs
away, unwittingly inviting the animal to a chase. Adults, too, may
shout or flail at an aggressive dog or raise their arms to protect
themselves, which the dog may interpret as a threat that warrants
an attack. Or an adult may try to calm a frightened child by
saying, ``See, the dog is friendly, he's wagging his tail,'' when
tail-wagging can be a sign of anger or aggression as well as
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the concern is the fact that most bites are inflicted
not by strange dogs but by dogs belonging to the family, a friend
or a neighbor. In other words, the person bitten is known to the
dog but doesn't know how to behave around the dog to avoid being
bitten.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wayne Hunthausen, a veterinarian at Westwood Animal Hospital
in Westwood, Kan., who specializes in pet behavior, says children _
and, of course, adults too _ can learn how to act safely around
dogs and cats in just 30 minutes. That is how long it takes to view
the award-winning video he stars in, ``Dogs, Cats &AMP; Kids: Learning
to Be Safe with Animals,'' produced by Donald Manelli and
Associates and available for $19.95 plus $3.95 for shipping and
handling by telephoning (800) 337-3615.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should know, for example, how to read a dog's body
language and know when to keep away. A fearful animal holds its
ears down, tucks its tail under its body and may shake, growl or
back away. But trying to befriend it, which many would do
instinctively, is inviting an attack, Hunthausen says. Likewise,
stay clear of a dog that is angry or aggressively protecting its
territory: ears are up and forward, eyes look directly at you, tail
is up and may be wagging slowly, hair may be standing up on the
neck, back and tail, and the dog is likely to be barking or
growling with teeth exposed. Cut a wide swath around such an
animal.
</P>
<P>
   If you are approached by an aggressive dog, whether you are a
child or an adult, the best defense is to freeze. Act like a tree:
perfectly still with hands in fists held close to the body, don't
yell or say anything and don't look at the animal. Dogs interpret
direct eye contact as a threat or challenge. If a dog knocks you
down, act like a rock: roll into a fetal position with knees up,
elbows tucked in and hands in fists held against your ears.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of children are bitten by dogs they know. When
petting any dog, pet along the side or back of the animal's body,
not the head, face or ears, which are more sensitive. Don't tease
the dog or play rough with it. Play safe games like fetch or
Frisbee, not tug-of-war. Learn to respect the dog's private times.
Never bother a dog when it is eating, resting, sleeping or chewing
on something.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, Hunthausen said, ``kids assume they can treat a
neighbor's dog the way they treat their own.'' Don't pet a dog that
is not your own without permission. A dog belonging to someone else
should not be petted unless an adult is present. Ask whether the
dog is friendly and if it is OK to pet it.
</P>
<P>
   If you are given the go-ahead, move slowly toward the dog so as
not to frighten it, and don't immediately reach out your hand to
pet it. Instead, first make a loose fist and hold it out toward the
dog with the back of your hand up and a little ways from the side
of your body. Let the dog decide whether it wants to come up and
sniff your hand. ``If it doesn't, that's where the greeting should
stop,'' said Hunthausen, who is a co-editor or co-author of two
professional texts on pet behavior and training. Never chase after
a dog that is not interested in playing with you.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals
offers more some additional advice: Do not tease dogs behind
fences, do not go near dogs chained up in yards or tied to trees or
poles with leashes or ropes and don't touch dogs that are outside
and off leashes. Never go near a stray dog.
</P>
<P>
   If you are charged by a dog, don't yell or scream, but
immediately offer an article of clothing, gym bag, purse or other
item for the animal to tug on, recommends Jacque Schultz, director
of special projects in the A.S.P.C.A.'s animal sciences division.
And if a dog should grab your arm or leg, instead of pulling away,
push into the animal's mouth as hard as you can, Ms. Schultz
advises.
</P>
<P>
   It will cause the dog to feel like it is losing control of the
situation and it will let go and run away, she said. This tactic
will also keep your flesh from tearing against the dog's teeth as
you pull away. This technique was part of the protective training
she gave last year to field workers for Con Edison in New York, and
one worker already reported using it and escaping with just a torn
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The Humane Society notes that by spaying or neutering a dog,
owners can reduce by three-fold the risk that the animal will bite
someone. Owners should also be especially cautious when dogs are in
new situations or are around people they don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Every dog and its owner should go through behavior training,
preferably when the animal is young. Dogs should be properly
socialized to being with people and other dogs and in a wide
variety of situations so that they are less easily frightened.
Training is best done, Hunthausen said, when the dog is a 8 to 10
weeks old. At this age, they learn with lightning speed, much
faster than at 6 or 8 months, he said. Ask your local vet to
recommend a trainer or puppy classes.
</P>
<P>
   Hunthausen also said dogs learned best when rewarded for doing
the right thing, rather than when punished for doing something
wrong. He insists that owners should never use harsh physical
punishment, prong collars, shock collars and other painful training
techniques. In his experience, dog bites often follow harsh
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Owners must also supervise their pets, obey leash laws and deal
swiftly aggressive behavior. Hunthausen says owners often make the
mistake of trying to calm a dog by petting it when it acts
aggressively, but this only serves to reward the animal and
reinforce the unwanted behavior. As with any unwanted behavior, the
owner must let the dog know who is boss and that the boss is
displeased. In this case, the owner should take control and
immediately remove the dog from the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, an owner should never defend a dangerous dog. Any dog
that commits an unprovoked, uninhibited severe or fatal attack must
be destroyed. It is not safe to send it to another location or
owner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
