<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH A POST-TRAGEDY MEDIA PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grover Cooper found himself ``reliving a nightmare'' as he
watched the tragedy unfold last month at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   He watched as police tried to reach the dead and wounded in the
high school, then turned off the TV set and walked away. He
couldn't take it any more.
</P>
<P>
   He had had no choice but to ``take it'' a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was the superintendent of the Westside school district in
Jonesboro, Ark., when four students and a teacher were fatally shot
March 24, 1998, at Westside Middle School. Ten others were wounded
by two students at the middle school when they fled the building
after a fire alarm went off. (The alarm had been triggered by one
of the assailants).
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who is 67, retired last summer _ he had announced his
retirement prior to that tragic day in March.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped giving interviews to the outside news media shortly
after the shooting. He agreed to talk to me about his experience
with the media because of the intercession of his son, Roger, who
is an associate professor at TCU's department of radio, TV and
film.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Cooper said it was the outside news media that created a
major problem for him and others involved in the Jonesboro tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they came to give us a problem, but when they
jammed in, they did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said it didn't take long for the national media to arrive
after the school-ground shootings. ``It looked like the Super Bowl
parking lot,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was the insensitivity of many of the outside
reporters that most upset him and other residents of Jonesboro. The
insensitivity was often displayed in the questions they asked, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the question that upset them most was: ``How do you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you think we would feel after something like this
happened to us?'' Cooper said. ``... You usually are too numb to
know. One man answered, `How would you feel?' I wish I had said
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the journalists who went to Jonesboro acted as
if they ``had left their feelings someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper recalled one reporter who called ``at 10 or 11 at night
and wanted to ask some questions. I had just come in from three
funerals, and I told him I had two to go to tomorrow and I didn't
want to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reporter just kept pressing, Cooper said. ``I couldn't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the behavior of local journalists was in sharp contrast
to that of their colleagues from outside the area. ``Many were
crying as they worked,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He said he remembered one local TV reporter who approached him
shortly after the shooting. Cooper said he was hoping the reporters
would not ask him any questions at that particular moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in the world he did was slap me on the shoulder and say,
`Grover, I'm sorry,''' Cooper said. ``I won't forget that. It was
more than a story for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that after microphones and cameras had been shoved
in the faces of witnesses and other residents of Jonesboro, school
officials moved all of the news media to a parking area across a
road from the school grounds and said they could venture onto the
campus only with permission.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a few of the journalists protested but that he
replied, ``There is no negotiation on this.'' Only three or four of
the journalists violated the restriction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The retired school superintendent said he also was bothered by
the attitude of some of the outside journalists: ``They had the
attitude that `there is a story here, and you owe it to us to give
it to us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper characterized most of the reporting on the Jonesboro
tragedy as fair and accurate.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has given several speeches, mostly to school
administrators, about the shooting, and ``I always tell them that
probably 95 percent of the media people were all right, and that
probably is as good as you would get of superintendents.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked him what advice he would like to give to the press
concerning future coverage of such horrors. He said he would advise
them:
</P>
<P>
   _Be more sensitive, especially concerning the questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't stick cameras and microphones into the faces of those who
do not want to be interviewed or photographed. Ask their
permission.
</P>
<P>
   _Reduce the number of people sent to the scene so as not to make
a bad situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   _Respect the ground rules set up by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   He also had some advice for officials who will be confronted by
similar situations in the future:
</P>
<P>
   _Confine the news media to a convenient site off the school
grounds in order to provide protection to those who do not want to
be photographed or interviewed. (He stressed such a site should not
be ``on the north 40.'')
</P>
<P>
   _Hold regular press briefings so the journalists will be
provided with timely and accurate information.
</P>
<P>
   _Do not restrain those who are willing to be interviewed and
photographed.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at precord(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0314 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WARMING-WEATHER-A     05-17 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WARMING-WEATHER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the Arctic.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this stage of research, scientists cannot firmly link global
warming to changes in circulation patterns. But one study by
British and Italian scientists, reported recently in the journal
Nature, examined data on atmospheric circulation over the last 50
years in the Northern Hemisphere. The researchers looked to see
whether there had been any change in frequency of large-scale
circulation regimes. The data revealed that there had: in recent
decades, patterns had shifted to favor a warmer climate for most
land areas in the Northern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   In a general warming of the globe, the air above those land
areas would be expected to warm more than that above the oceans,
because of differing abilities to absorb heat. But the authors of
the new study postulate that the change in circulation patterns is
the main reason the land has lately warmed so much.
</P>
<P>
   That is, they say, the climate of the hemisphere shifts
naturally back and forth between two dominant regimes. Both the
North Atlantic and North Pacific oscillations are believed to be
affected by this shift. But if some external influence imparts a
warming or cooling impulse, the scientists say, the oscillation
could be tipped in favor of one regime or the other. The external
influence could be either natural, like a change in solar
radiation, or artificial, like carbon dioxide emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is that you can understand much of the
observed climate change in terms of that picture,'' said Dr. Tim
Palmer, a climatologist at the European Center for Medium-Range
Weather Forecasts in Reading, England, and one of the study's
authors. While the study does not prove that human-induced global
warming is what caused the change in frequency of circulation
patterns, he said, the change is consistent with it.
</P>
<P>
   Such global warming would not produce new types of weather
patterns, he said, but it would change the probability of
occurrence of existing ones, Palmer said. And differing regional
patterns of warming are a direct consequence of that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another oscillation, in the Arctic, involves the strength of
high-altitude winds that circle the North Pole near the Arctic
Circle. The winds oscillate between stronger and weaker states,
with consequences for weather and climate farther south. Some
experts believe that the Arctic oscillation is being altered by
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that at certain critical altitudes, roughly from 6
to 12 miles, increasing carbon dioxide has the effect of warming
the tropics but cooling the polar regions. This would increase the
temperature contrast between the two regions and thereby strengthen
the pole-girdling vortex of winds. This, according to the new
thinking, would in turn strengthen westerly winds off the Atlantic,
making northern Eurasia warmer and wetter.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists, like Dr. John Michael Wallace, an atmospheric
scientist at the University of Washington, think that the Arctic
and North Atlantic oscillations are so closely tied together as to
be the same thing. The effects of the Arctic oscillation over the
North Pacific, he said, are more subtle. ``It's hard to see them
clearly,'' he said, ``because another big thing is going on there;
that's the variability related to El Nino.''
</P>
<P>
   The El Nino-La Nina cycle is the strongest year-to-year natural
climatic oscillation. The two alternating states have markedly
different effects on weather. In a strong El Nino, for instance,
prevailing jet-stream winds slam into the southern tier of the
United States, producing floods, mudslides and tornadoes. In La
Nina, the central United States typically gets very cold weather as
well as tornadoes, while much of the East is warm and tranquil.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, El Nino has appeared every two to seven years,
with La Nina showing up less often. But over the last two decades,
El Nino has appeared more frequently than before, and in much of
the 1990s it seemed to go on more or less continuously. Could this
be related to global warming?
</P>
<P>
   A number of scientists have raised the possibility. Dr. Kevin
Trenberth, a climate researcher at the National Center for
Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., has postulated that the
time interval between El Nino visitations depends on how long it
takes to recharge the tropical system by re-accumulating heat at
the sea surface. Global warming, he suggests, may enable the system
to recharge more rapidly, thereby making El Nino appear more often.
</P>
<P>
   Another study reported recently in Nature appeared to lend some
credence to this view. The researchers, at the Max Planck Institute
for Meteorology in Hamburg, Germany, used a computerized model of
the climate system's general circulation to investigate the effects
of global warming on El Nino's frequency. In the past, these
climate models have been unable to simulate the behavior of the
tropical Pacific finely enough to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Max Planck researchers said they had overcome that problem,
and their computer simulation produced more frequent El Nino
conditions as well as more powerful La Nina events.
</P>
<P>
   None of this constitutes anything remotely approaching a last
word on the response of the climate system's natural churnings to
global warming. But as Wallace says, experts have begun focusing on
responses ``that look like distortions of natural patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   All those patterns are part of a single, integrated climate
system, and scientists are just beginning to zero in on how they
relate to one another in the context of a warming atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   That task only makes the problem of climate change more
complicated than ever. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
