<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0328 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-BOOK-TEX     05-17 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD YOU READ THE BOOK BEFORE OR AFTER YOU SEE THE MOVIE?
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies STARWARS-CHARACTERS, STARWARS-HYPE, STARWARS-TV) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is basically just one question about ``Star Wars: Episode
I _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you read the book before or after you see the movie?
</P>
<P>
   Read ``The Phantom Menace'' before and you know what's going to
happen onscreen. Computer geeks call such information ``spoilers.''
You won't be surprised when trunk-nosed Jar Jar Binks emerges from
some planetary ooze, and you won't be shocked when young Anakin
Skywalker does what he does in the big podrace.
</P>
<P>
   Read ``The Phantom Menace'' after you see the movie and you can
reminisce about favorite onscreen moments, but you won't be way
ahead of all your ``Star Wars''-obsessed pals who've been counting
down the days until the opening of George Lucas' long-anticipated,
second-force-be-with-you film trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Read ``The Phantom Menace'' any time and you'll be settling for
paste-and-cut pap. Sorry to have to say this, but it happens to be
true. It isn't in any sense, except print on paper, a ``real''
book. It's a Lucas moneymaker, just like those plastic action
figures that'll sell in the millions come Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   We forget, what with all the hoopla about the films, that ``Star
Wars'' as a story pretty much relies on the most ancient theme in
storytelling: Good guys, aided by some magic, vs. bad guys, using
corrupt magic. Essentially, ``Star Wars'' is King Arthur and his
Knights of the Round Table, but with better special effects.
Calling ``Star Wars'' derivative is not meant to be an insult; John
Steinbeck's superb ``East of Eden'' was revamped Cain vs. Abel. But
we can't give points for literary innovation where none occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ballantine hired a very good sci-fi writer, Terry
Brooks, to flesh out Lucas' screenplay. Brooks has a long,
honorable track record as a writer, starting with his ``Sword of
Shannara'' series that even charmed readers who ordinarily disdain
sci-fi. In his hands, ``The Phantom Menace'' is delivered in solid
style. There are colorful descriptions of new ``creatures'' and
lightsaber duels. Readers trundle along the dusty sands of desert
planets and consider the unique makeup techniques of a pubescent
queen. New bad-guy Darth Maul is much nastier-looking than Darth
Vader ever was. We learn more about the origins of the Jedi and
meet C-3PO and R2-D2 in their younger droid days.
</P>
<P>
   But the real excitement in ``Star Wars'' tales must always be
visual, which is why the movies are justly considered epics. And
although it's true that ``Star Wars'' knockoff novels have sold
pretty well, how many of their readers do you suppose don't also
own the first three ``Star Wars'' films in one of their many
videocassette formats?
</P>
<P>
   So ``The Phantom Menace'' bogs down in print. Instead of
creating their own mental images of characters and actions, readers
try to imagine what George Lucas is about to show them on a movie
screen. It's pretty much an impossible task.
</P>
<P>
   This is why I strongly recommend ``Star Wars'' junkies put off
reading ``The Phantom Menace'' until after they've seen the movie.
Accept it _ ``Star Wars'' will always be movie fare first and
foremost, with books lagging far behind. Wait to read the book
until after you've seen the film. The loss of cinematic surprise
isn't worth the limited charms of the story in print.
</P>
<P>
   And, should you doubt the book's purpose is more to make money
than to entertain, consider this: ``The Phantom Menace'' is being
published with four different dust jackets, each depicting a
different ``Episode I'' character. Do all four jackets come with
each single $25 book? Heck, no. You have to buy four different
books to get a complete collection of the covers, and a lot of
``Star Wars'' collectors will do exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Book: ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Terry Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Type: Science fiction
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Ballantine
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $25
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
