<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0329 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-HYPE-TEX     05-17 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-HYPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHRONOLOGY OF HYPE FOR `STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM
MENACE'
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies STARWARS-CHARACTERS, STARWARS-TV, STARWARS-BOOK) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   June 5, 1991: In a Los Angeles Daily News story, a spokeswoman
for George Lucas announces that he's planning to develop and
produce a second trilogy of ``Star Wars'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31, 1997: The original ``Star Wars'' is reissued in
theaters in a ``special edition'' with new scenes added, and
quickly resumes its position as the top-grossing movie of all time.
</P>
<P>
   June 13, 1997: Entertainment Weekly reports that Ewan McGregor,
then best-known for playing a heroin addict in ``Trainspotting,''
is the choice to play the young Obi-Wan Kenobi in the prequel.
Other cast members include Liam Neeson as a Jedi master, and teen
actress Natalie Portman as the mother of Luke Skywalker and
Princess Leia.
</P>
<P>
   April 3, 1998: 20th Century Fox, still riding high from the
success of ``Titanic,'' reaches agreement with Lucas and Lucasfilms
to distribute the second trilogy. Fox Broadcasting secures network
broadcasting rights to the first of the new films.
</P>
<P>
   June 24: Lucas' public-relations folks strike back at rumors
that the prequel is in trouble, plagued by budget overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 25: The sequel's title, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' is announced, to mixed reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 26: Hasbro releases the first ``Episode I'' spinoff toy, a
battle droid with STAP vehicle, and collectors eagerly snatch them
up.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 10: The designs for the theater banners and posters are
revealed, featuring the young Anakin Skywalker (Jake Lloyd) casting
the shadow of Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 17: The trailer debuts in theaters before, and reportedly
after, ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``The Waterboy.'' The film's official
Web site, www.starwars.com, tells fans when and where they can see
the trailer. Many viewers show up for the trailer and then leave
before the feature. Some viewers are rumored to be seen filming the
trailer with video cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 18: In what may be a journalistic first, the ``New York
Post'' publishes a prominent review of the first ``Phantom Menace''
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   February: Vanity Fair devotes the first of three covers to
``Phantom Menace.'' This issue features a number of exclusive,
on-set pictures by photographer Annie Leibovitz.
</P>
<P>
   March 5: Entertainment Weekly reports that PepsiCo shelled out
an estimated $2 billion for the ``Star Wars'' license, offering 24
different collectible cans and transforming its fast-food
franchises (Taco Bell, Kentucky Fried Chicken and Pizza Hut) into
different planets from the film.
</P>
<P>
   March 10: Claiming he wants to give families a better chance to
see the film on opening weekend, Lucas announces at ShoWest in Las
Vegas that opening day will be moved up from May 21 to May 19. He
also tells theater owners that ``Phantom Menace'' will be digitally
projected in four theaters and that both subsequent sequels will be
filmed digitally.
</P>
<P>
   March 11: In a promotional coup, Apple Computer begins offering
the second ``Phantom Menace'' preview on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   March 12: The second ``Phantom Menace'' trailer debuts in
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   March 14: Fox's ``That '70s Show'' feeds the frenzy when the
young stars experience ``Star Wars'' for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   March 26: Entertainment Weekly features its first ``PM'' cover.
</P>
<P>
   March 28: Lucas, in the final throes of editing ``Phantom
Menace,'' appears on an extended segment of ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   April 7: The first line forms outside of Mann's Chinese Theater
in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   April 7: The Associated Press reports that 20th Century Fox is
trying to place strict conditions on exhibition of ``Phantom
Menace.'' Among the hoped-for restrictions: Multiplexes must show
the movie only in their biggest and best theaters for at least two
months, with no more than eight minutes of coming attractions.
</P>
<P>
   April 13: Lucasfilm announces plans for early benefit showings
in several cities, including Dallas, to help raise money for
children's charities.
</P>
<P>
   April 16: For the first time ever, Premiere magazine dedicates
the bulk of an issue to one film _ ``Phantom Menace,'' of course _
with four different covers, no less.
</P>
<P>
   April 18: Venerable newsmagazine Time does a big, gushy ``Star
Wars'' issue, complete with a cross section of a lightsaber.
</P>
<P>
   April 30: About 40,000 fans show up in Denver for a ``Star
Wars'' convention. Coincidentally, it falls on the same weekend as
the National Rifle Association convention, and just 10 days after
the Columbine High School shootings in Littleton, Colo. Fans
petition the company that makes the ``Star Wars'' Customizable Card
Game, to create a card depicting one of the slain students as a
Jedi knight. The company declines.
</P>
<P>
   May 1: Rosie O'Donnell kicks off an entire month of shows
devoted to ``Phantom Menace,'' sneak-peeking commercials and
interviewing stars.
</P>
<P>
   May 3: At 12:01 a.m., the new ``Phantom Menace'' toys go on sale
to crazed collectors across the country. The music video for the
single ``Duel of the Fates'' debuts on MTV and VH1. Terry Brooks'
novelization of the film gives fans the first opportunity to find
out how it all ends.
</P>
<P>
   May 4: The ``Phantom Menace'' score by John Williams and the
London Philharmonic hits record-store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   May 6: Early reviews from theater owner screenings are mixed,
with some calling the film amazing, others saying it's too heavily
geared toward children.
</P>
<P>
   May 7: Rolling Stone, Variety, Hollywood Online and The New York
Times are the first of many news outlets to jump the gun, posting
online reviews of ``Phantom Menace'' 12 days before the film's
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   May 17: The talk-show blather begins with Lucas and the film's
stars scheduled to make appearances on ``Good Morning America,''
``CBS This Morning,'' ``Today,'' ``The Tonight Show with Jay
Leno,'' ``The Late Show With David Letterman,'' ``The Rosie
O'Donnell Show'' and ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
