<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0330 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-RELIGION-PRIZE-NY     05-17 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RELIGION-PRIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRIZES FOR SCIENCE AND RELIGION, THE PERSON OF FAITH IS RICHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., Tenn., Pa.)   (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite recent peace negotiations and displays of good
fellowship by partisans on both sides, it doesn't look as if the
centuries-old row between religion and science is any closer to
resolution than it was when Galileo nearly went to the stake for
defending the Copernican view of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that people cling to personal beliefs regardless of
debating points won or lost, and no amount of persuasion makes much
difference. But one thing that does make a difference is cash.
</P>
<P>
   For most people the ultimate measure of success is money, and by
that standard religion is gaining on science. The Nobel Prizes in
the sciences (which last year came to $978,000 each) have been
shouldered into second place by the Templeton Prize for Progress in
Religion, which is now the world's richest award.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Templeton Prize, this year worth $1.24 million, was
bestowed last Tuesday by Prince Philip at Buckingham Palace on Dr.
Ian G. Barbour, a physicist-turned-theologian from Carleton College
in Northfield, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   A ceremony honoring the new Templeton laureate was also
scheduled this week at a church in Moscow's Kremlin. The John
Templeton Foundation declared that Barbour had ``shown
extraordinary originality in advancing humankind's understanding of
God and/or spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was created in 1972 by Sir John M. Templeton, the
Tennessee-born founder of several investment funds, who was
knighted in 1987. Abundant money from the Templeton Foundation in
Radnor, Pa., seems to turn up these days wherever science and
religion come into contact.
</P>
<P>
   Some typical Templeton initiatives: a $10 million theological,
social and scientific study of forgiveness; a ``scientific study of
humility theology''; a string of new periodicals, including the
magazine Science and Spirit (devoted to articles deemed helpful in
reconciling religion and science); and the financing of many
experimental tests of religious tenets.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Templeton-sponsored experiments is a two-year study
to demonstrate the effect of prayer on 600 patients about to
undergo heart surgery. Two groups were told they might be prayed
for. One of these groups actually was the object of prayers while
the other was not, but neither group was told which was which. A
third group, also intended for prayers, was informed that it was
the beneficiary of prayer. Results of this experiment are not in
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Galton, a cousin of Charles Darwin, conducted a similar
experiment in 1872 and found no effect. Undaunted, religious
believers have continued power-of-prayer experiments, generally
failing to convince their scientist critics of any effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Templeton Foundation is not alone in supporting prayer
experiments. In his book, ``Healing Words'' (Harper San Francisco,
1993), Dr. Larry Dossey described four experiments in which yeast
fungus was exposed to cyanide poison. Dossey, a medical doctor,
wrote that when people prayed for the survival of a sample of
cyanide-tainted yeast, its survival rate was better than that of a
control sample bereft of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The Templeton Foundation pays handsomely to organize and
publicize discussions between intellectual leaders in science and
religion. Such a meeting, held under the prestigious aegis of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science, took place in
Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
   It featured a debate between Dr. Steven Weinberg, a staunch
supporter of the scientific paradigm, and Sir John Polkinghorne, a
former physicist who is now an Anglican priest.
</P>
<P>
   The Weinberg-Polkinghorne debate, while entertaining, did not
resolve any differences.
</P>
<P>
   However, theological debate in the right hands can yield good
fun, and once again, it has served as grist for the mill of Dr.
David Jones, alias ``Daedalus,'' whose weekly column in the journal
Nature has delighted readers for many years.
</P>
<P>
   The formal aim of the Templeton Foundation is to ``create and
fund projects to apply scientific methodology to the study of
religious subjects,'' and technically, the tongue-in-cheek
experiments proposed by Jones, a professor at the University of
Newcastle-Upon-Tyne, England, should meet the Templeton criterion.
</P>
<P>
   In two columns in Nature in April, Daedalus proposed experiments
exploring the thermodynamics of the spirit world and the molecular
basis of religious experience. He suggested that the spirit world,
like empty outer space, probably has a temperature of only three
degrees above the absolute zero: the temperature of the microwave
echo of the Big Bang. This would explain why a ghost invading the
warm material world from the frigid spirit world has a chilling
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive instruments, Daedalus wrote, should be able to discern
the leakage of heat from the material world into the spirit world,
and detect a different rate of heat leakage from a holy object than
from an object with no religious significance.
</P>
<P>
   Daedalus proposes another experiment carrying out brain scans on
monks and nuns at prayer, identifying the brain regions associated
with a sense of contact with God, and other regions suffering ``the
dark night of the soul,'' where prayer ``feels like talking into a
dead telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   A nuclear magnetic resonance scan of the divine-connection
region of the brain might reveal the composition of the molecules
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent laboratory synthesis of these molecules could lead to
production of ``Theological Prozac,'' Daedalus suggested, and
``With luck, the resulting illumination will bestow spiritual
comfort on the users, unaccompanied by the stern orthodox
convictions attached to it by the more doctrinal aspects of
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier columns Daedalus proposed attaching sensitive
piezoelectric transducers, accelerometers and other instruments to
dying people to detect the departure of their souls and to measure
the soul's mass, velocity and quantum-mechanical spin.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has not disclosed whether he intends to submit any of his
schemes to the Templeton Foundation for a possible grant or prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
