 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, May 18, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-VOTE (Jerusalem) _ Ehud Barak unseated Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in elections on Monday. Netanyahu conceded
defeat in an emotional farewell after exit polls projected a
sweeping victory for Barak. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ A news analysis on the election. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Britain is renewing its push to
persuade its NATO allies to consider launching a ground attack. In
separate appearances at NATO headquarters and with fellow foreign
ministers from the European Union, British Foreign Minister Robin
Cook revived an earlier British plan to send ground troops to
Kososo without a peace agreement and against a foe battered by
weeks of allied air bombardment. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WELFARE (Washington) _ In a closely watched welfare case,
the Supreme Court says in a 7-2 decision that states cannot cut
benefits to new arrivals. This strikes down a California law, which
was never put into effect, and negates a provision of the federal
welfare reform bill. More than a dozen other states have such laws.
By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-WHALE (Neah Bay, Wash.) _ For the first time in more
than 70 years, Makah Indians seeking to re-establish their
whale-hunting tradition harpooned a gray whale off the Pacific
coast this morning. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-OWNERS (Marriottsville, Md) _ Guns and gun owners are again
under attack as part of what's wrong with the country. But a
weekend shooting tournament in suburban Baltimore shows that for
many Americans, guns are just part of life. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UNPAID-TAXES (Undated) _ Internal Revenue Service tax
collectors, under intense pressure from Congress to be nicer to
taxpayers, have drastically scaled back efforts to collect unpaid
taxes, new statistics show. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
