<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMAIL-SUIT-NYTR &LR;      05-17 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-SUIT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY FILES LAWSUIT OVER DEROGATORY E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By RHONDA PARKS MANVILLE   
 Santa Barbara News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ A phantom menace of an e-mail kind has
infiltrated STAR Telecommunications, and the seventh-largest long
distance carrier in the nation is trying to stop it by filing a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants in the suit _ who are unknown at this time _ have
disrupted company business and harmed morale by sending a barrage
of e-mailings that denigrate the company, its management and staff,
according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Suits of this type are becoming more common as businesses using
the Internet find themselves maligned by anonymous critics, who
hide under pseudonyms and impersonate company managers. Filing suit
enables companies to subpoena Internet search engines for the
originators of harassing e-mail messages, and to sue in civil court
for trespass and other violations.
</P>
<P>
   A similarlawsuit was filed recently by Massachusetts-based
Raytheon. Raytheon's executives sued to get Yahoo Inc. to turn over
the names of employees who allegedly discussed company secrets in
an online chatroom. The employees used aliases that they thought
would protect their identities. Twenty-one employees ultimately
were named in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The detractors in the STAR case have engaged in ``parasitic
use'' of the firm's e-mail system to ``espouse their personal
agendas and to make derogatory and potentially defamatory
comments'' about management and staff, according to the STAR
lawsuit, which was filed last week in Superior Court in Santa
Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and employees at STAR, which is based in Santa
Barbara, as well as the company's lawyers, declined to comment on
the pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unsolicited e-mail, whether it's harassing or not, is a
problem on the Internet,'' said Dave Clark, general manager of
Silicon Beach, an Internet provider in Santa Barbara. ``If it's
continual, and it contains negative messages, it can constitute
harassment of sorts. Sometimes people abuse the Internet, just as
they do the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit charges the yet-unnamed defendants with
misappropriation of computer resources, trespass, nuisance and
violations of the Electronic Communications Privacy Act and the
Computer Fraud and Abuse Act. It seeks an unspecified amount of
damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to burdening STAR's computer system, these
derogatory mass messages have disrupted STAR's work environment by
detrimentally affecting employee morale and productivity, and by
diverting management attention away from the business of STAR,''
the lawsuit states.
</P>
<P>
   Since the phantom e-mails started turning up at the computer
terminals of employees last September, STAR has spent considerable
time and money trying to identify the offenders, the suit says. In
the meantime, management has had to sort through the barrage of
messages to separate legitimate e-mails from bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing numbers of businesses are being hurt by people on the
Internet who transmit defamatory information about companies in the
form of e-mail or postings on bulletin boards, said Santa Barbara
attorney Andrew Kent, who specializes in intellectual property and
other Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out there using the Internet are apoplectic at getting
found out and sued over this stuff,'' said Kent. ``They have no
idea when they do this that they can be tracked down.''
</P>
<P>
   The two cultures sometimes clash because people using the
Internet are accustomed to saying whatever they want anonymously,
without regard to defaming anyone, and businesses are intent on
protecting their good names against harmful comments, Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on civil liberties and privacy say lawsuits growing out
of such conflicts highlight the Internet's ongoing tension between
a right to anonymity and a need for accountability.
</P>
<P>
   A young company that has enjoyed phenomenal growth, STAR is one
of the largest telecommunications firms in the world. But the
company's earnings have been less than stellar lately, with a $7.6
million, first-quarter loss reported last week.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
