<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOVER-MOVIE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDIANS GET PEEK AT FILM ABOUT J. EDGAR HOOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Audiences here will get an advance look at
``Hoover,'' a movie starring Ernest Borgnine as FBI Director J.
Edgar Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   Described as a traditional or Hollywood-style preview _ where
filmmakers poll the audience and use their reactions to shape the
final print _ the producers of ``Hoover'' will be on hand to survey
audience members' opinions with cards and videotape crews.
</P>
<P>
   They will also introduce the film and answer questions from the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoover,'' which was shot at Universal Studios Florida in
nearby Orlando by filmmakers Rick Pamplin and Bob Fisher, will be
screened for the first time Wednesday and Thursday at the historic
Polk Theatre here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hollywood, when people open a movie, the filmmakers drive
about an hour in any direction and do a sneak preview to get the
paying public to come in,'' said Pamplin, who directed the film and
shares writing and producing duties with partner Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   At such previews the filmmakers sit in the back of the theater
to note audience reactions and then pass out note cards for viewers
to rate the film.
</P>
<P>
   The final print of ``Hoover,'' which will address many of the
controversies of Hoover's career and personal life, hasn't been
struck. Audience reactions could affect the actual film when it's
released later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Polk Theatre officials are thrilled with the chance to show off
the 70-year-old movie palace, which is nearing completion of a $1.4
million renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful to have an honest-to-gosh Hollywood sneak
preview like this, when you've got the filmmakers, producers and
investors coming,'' said Frances McCranie, executive director of
the Polk Theatre. ``This is something you hear about happening in
other places.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage its success, the Polk is lowering its usual
admission of $5 to $1.
</P>
<P>
   Pamplin and Fisher had worked in Hollywood as screenwriters,
story analysts and development executives for years before
relocating to Central Florida in 1994 to produce and direct their
own films. They each settled with their families in nearby Haines
City and opened offices for the Pamplin-Fisher Co. at Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, they produced ``Michael Winslow Live,'' a concert film
featuring the comedian and ``Police Academy'' star. ``Hoover,''
filmed on a Universal soundstage in late 1997 with Borgnine, was
planned first, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came to Florida, we were looking for an original
story, and we were also looking for something that could showcase
our talents without raising $70 or $80 million,'' Pamplin said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the two had met Borgnine, who won an Academy
Award in 1955 for ``Marty.'' He agreed to work with them, given the
right starring role.
</P>
<P>
   After finding that no definitive film had been made about
Hoover, Pamplin and Fisher researched their subject for several
years and wrote the script _ answering what they say are unproven
allegations about Hoover's personal life and professional dealings.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, made for less than $10 million, Borgnine's Hoover
confronts allegations of cross dressing and also discusses his
dealings with the Kennedys and Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
