A0405 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-SHEDS-LIFEBEAT     05-17 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SHEDS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLE GARDEN SHEDS TURN LUXURIOUS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color graphic of a garden shed (begin copy in door)
 By BILL DEAN AND MARY LOFTUS 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1896, Henry Ford built his first gasoline-powered vehicle,
the Quadricycle, in a backyard shed behind the home he and his
wife, Clara, rented on Bagley Avenue in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Cars have changed a bit since then, but backyard sheds have
retained their popularity as places to tinker, garden, invent or
repair.
</P>
<P>
   These all-purpose sheds, used to store everything from lawn
mowers and peat moss to old armchairs and half-finished bookcases,
can vary greatly in size and amenities. The most luxurious resemble
miniature houses, complete with windows, carpet and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Sheds fall into two general categories: ''portable'' sheds that
are fully manufactured in a factory and transported to a
homeowner's property, and less expensive ''kit buildings,''which
are sold by home and garden retailers and are put together by
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Portable sheds with floors begin at about 4 feet by 6 feet and
can be built as large as necessary _ up to a double-wide modular
building. Prices start around $600 and can go up to $10,000 or more
depending on size and features. What once were extras, such as
windows, electrical outlets, lights and locking doors, have become
standard features on many models.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our most popular model is 100 square feet, with a gable-style
roof, as opposed to a barn style,'' says Paul Johnston, owner of
The Shed Shop in Fremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   His shop builds wooden sheds on site for customers, at an
average cost of $2,000. Customers typically use them to store lawn,
garden and outdoor items such as tools, wheelbarrows, bicycles,
sporting gear and even small boats.
</P>
<P>
   But, Johnston says, a well-built shed has many other uses,
including serving as an art studio, workshop, playhouse or backyard
office.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he has used his own shed as a home office, hobby room
and even a guest room.
</P>
<P>
   ''One Thanksgiving, my daughters brought their boyfriends home
from college to visit and we had them sleep in the shed on portable
cots with a space heater...it was nice in there,'' Johnston says.
</P>
<P>
   His 10-by-14 foot shed, which has electricity and indoor-outdoor
carpet, now houses Johnston's expansive model railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do a nice Christmas scene every year, with snow, little
villages and pine trees, all lit up, and we have an open house,''
he says. Or an open shed, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's company offers only wooden sheds, which he says are
superior to metal both in function and form. Metal sheds tend to
rust within a year or two, dent easily, and gather condensation
inside as well as out, he says, which causes stored items also to
rust or mildew.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people have had their fill of metal sheds,'' Johnston
says. ''They're visual eyesores that don't blend in well with the
typical homeowner's back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being hidden away behind a carport or against a
fence, today's customized sheds are becoming backyard showcases,
some complete with French doors, painted shutters, flower boxes,
door lamps and customized paint jobs to match the primary
residence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pride ourselves on custom design,'' says Lynette Paulhus,
owner of Mini Barns in Sacramento, Calif. ''Some of our customers
want just a little storage shed for their patio furniture in the
winter, but more often than not, people are using sheds as
workshops, painting rooms, work spaces. We sold several recently as
teen-age rooms, for them to have a little space of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheds are especially popular in areas where ranch-style homes
without basements or attic space are common. For homeowners with
carports instead of garages, storage can be a pressing problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish I had gotten a bigger one,'' says Ken Snyder, a retired
trucking company manager whose barn-style shed is home to his lawn
mower, a small freezer, a power washer and tools. Snyder, who
divides his time between Lakeland, Fla., and Gary, Ind., has sheds
at both his homes and couldn't imagine living either place without
them.
</P>
<P>
   And Jay Wright, of Montgomery, Ala., says he believes a lot of
sheds are sold to men who want a place to escape the hustle and
bustle of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have friends who spend more time inside their sheds than
inside their homes,'' says Wright, who works at Thrifty Portable
Buildings in Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Thrifty's most popular shed is a ready-made 8-by-12 foot
building with a wooden frame, an aluminum roof and aluminum siding.
''I've got one in my back yard that's lasted 25 years, and the only
thing that happened to it is some damage I had to fix after a tree
fell on it,'' Wright says. He keeps a shop table at one end of his
shed and listens to the radio while working on his rods and reels
at the other.
</P>
<P>
   While sheds in the past may have been the domain of men, more
women are setting up sheds as craft rooms, gardening centers, art
studios and offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''The purchase of a shed isn't male-dominated anymore,''
Johnston says. ''A lot of women are using the space themselves. And
some are making their husbands get the shed to get organized and
clear the clutter out of the garage.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring is the busiest time for shed dealers, who say home owners
decide to spruce up the yard, buy a new mower or clean out the
garage when the weather warms.
</P>
<P>
   For the do-it-yourselfer, there are shed kits available at home
improvement centers that offer four walls and a roof. Home Depot
has metal and vinyl shed kits starting at $200 for a 8-by-10 foot
shed with no floor. Foundation kits are available for an additional
$50, wood not included.
</P>
<P>
   Sheds may need a placement or building permit from either the
municipal or county government, depending on the jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Some locales require permits to build any shed, while others
require permits only if the shed is considered a permanent fixture,
such as those attached to a poured concrete slab. Additionally,
plumbing or wiring are taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Most permits begin in the $50 range and cost more if the shed
uses electricity. In most cases, the permitting process is
simplified because many jurisdictions already have blueprints on
file of standard shed models from national manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mary Loftus writes for the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Bill Dean, a reporter for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.,
contributed to this story.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
