<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0406 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWBOY-MUSEUM-LIFEBEA     05-17 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-MUSEUM-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOY HALL OF FAME HOLDS HIDDEN TREASURES
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photos of Bobby Weaver and a bronc rider 
 Includes a 250-word sidebar
 By JAY ATKINSON 
 c.1999 Jay Atkinson 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the vault beneath the National Cowboy Hall of Fame and
Western Heritage Center in Oklahoma City, there are 400 military,
Native American, and western stock saddles dating from 1847, and
enough cavalry uniforms, feather headresses and firearms to
re-enact an epic frontier battle.
</P>
<P>
   In proximity to this rare collection, lies Academy Award-winning
actor Walter Brennan's leather couch, sagging in the middle and
speckled with bourbon-and-water stains.
</P>
<P>
   ''The West is kind of a mystical place,'' says Bobby Weaver, 61,
the Hall's assistant director, adding that Brennan's couch belongs
in the museum because the Hollywood myth of the cowboy and actual
frontier life have become intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver's path to the National Cowboy Hall of Fame was an
irregular one. As soon as he was ''big enough to tote iron,'' he
began working for his father on a tank building crew in the West
Texas oil fields. Over the years, Weaver indulged his passion for
history by attending college part-time, finally earning his Ph.D.
from Texas Tech at the age of 46. ''I was never gonna get rich in a
pair of greasy overalls,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Odessa, Tex., the bantamweight Weaver laughs when
comparing his folksy approach with that of more typical historians.
''Somebody told them they were smart once, and they never got over
it,'' he says, in his West Texas drawl.
</P>
<P>
   The 220,000 square foot Oklahoma City museum is home to
traditional exhibits like the Rodeo Hall of Fame, Hall of Great
Western Performers, western art from the likes of Frederic
Remington and Charles Russell and several collections of Native
American and frontier artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   But $100 million worth of the Hall's collection remains inside
the vault's foot-thick steel reinforced walls, in charcoal-filtered
cabinets which are kept at a constant 68 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody ever gets in here but the curators and me,'' Weaver
says, with a wink.
</P>
<P>
   As the Hall's coordinator of events, exhibits, educational
activities and research (two new galleries and an authentic replica
of an Old West town called ''Prosperity Junction'' will open in the
summer of 1999), Weaver spends most of his time in meetings and on
the telephone. But when the other curators have gone home, he likes
to wander through the 15,000 square-foot vault.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver points out a buckskin Ghost Dance shirt, worn during
southern Arapaho ceremonies which were meant to rejuvenate the
landscape and call forth the tribe's dead warriors. By 1890, when
the shirt was in use, most Native Americans were ''longing for a
time that was and that'll never come back, '' Weaver says.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring the Hall of Fame vault with Bobby Weaver also offers
insight into the practical side of American history. A cabinet full
of Confederate uniforms all look different because, unlike the
Yankee tunics made in northern factories, the Rebels used homemade
butternut dye and it faded to various shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver indicates the oldest piece of military headgear in the
museum, a tar bucket hat from 1833 that has a horsehair tassel and
smells faintly of mothballs. ''When it got all battered, you just
tarred it back up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A Sioux cradle board, ingeniously designed for carrying infants
on foot or on horseback, looks like two ski tips connected by
straps and a beaded leather bag. Weaver demonstrates how the device
would protect the Sioux infant, leaving only his eyes exposed. ''If
you drop this, there's hardly any way he can get hurt,'' says
Weaver, noting that today's child safety seats are modeled on the
cradle boards.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Hall's saddlery collection are two owned by the movie
star Gene Autry, the singing cowboy. One of the saddles is trimmed
in hand-tooled silver and engraved with Autry's initials, while the
other, decorated in the same pattern, is covered with tin. The
silver saddle was used in close-ups, Weaver explains, the replica
for stunt riding.
</P>
<P>
   It's poetic justice that Weaver has become a gatekeeper of the
Old West, according to Jim Pfluger, director of the Ranching
Heritage Center at Texas Tech University in Lubbock, and Weaver's
close friend for the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bobby's never met a stranger, and that helps when you're
dealing with someone who's going to donate money, a painting, or an
artifact,'' Pfluger says. ''He grew up on the oil patch, and a lot
of his donors and board members are ranchers. Bobby understands an
honest day's work.''
</P>
<P>
   When the two friends were employed at the Panhandle Plains
Museum in Canyon, Tex., during the 1980s, Weaver catalogued on
microfilm the archive of every newspaper in the state, a five-year
odyssey that took him through hundreds of dusty little towns. At
the same time, Weaver helped create the museum's 75,000 square-foot
wing dedicated to the history of oil exploration and development in
the Texas panhandle. In 1984, he lost an eye while operating a
power saw at the museum, but finished both projects.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure at Panhandle Plains, Weaver had a habit of
ignoring the carefully regulated state bidding process. After
making a purchase, he would simply drop the receipts on Jim
Pfluger's desk. ''Bobby would always say it was easier to ask for
forgiveness than permission,'' recalls Pfluger.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver has written eight academic books and published more than
100 historical articles. But he becomes more animated over the
Hall's 8,229 different specimens of barbed wire _ ''bobbed whar''
as he calls it _ than any theoretical aspect of his job.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most curators are romantics at heart,'' Weaver says. ''They
weren't there, but they really would've liked to have been.'' -30-
</P>
<P>
   sidebar
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Director Bobby Weaver and his curators have been
rummaging in the vault beneath National Cowboy Hall of Fame vault
for the past 10 years, picking out artifacts for an ambitious new
exhibit. On July 4, the museum will open a recreation of an
authentic western town.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by Design Craftsmen of Midland, MI, the 13,500
square-foot ''Prosperity Junction'' will provide visitors with an
experience far beyond the usual movie set facades. Ranged along a
whistle stop on the Great Plains are a livery stable, saddle shop,
train depot, cattle company, photography studio, bank, school house
and church.
</P>
<P>
   As visitors enter this life-size cattle town, they will hear the
tinkling of a vintage piano in the saloon and the quiet thrum of a
nineteenth century organ from the church hall. The time of day is
dusk, and gleaming lanterns are visible through the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 18 buildings will be accessible to visitors. Parts of
old cameras and sepia prints litter the benches in the photo shop,
and authentic 19th century desks form neat rows in the school
house.
</P>
<P>
   As the holidays come and go, Prosperity Junction will come alive
with banners and decorations. On such occasions, historic
interpreters dressed in period costume will entertain passersby
with tales and demonstrations from the era.
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing daily visitors with a trip back in time,
Prosperity Junction will become an integral part of the museum's
educational programming, according to Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jay Atkinson teaches journalism and fiction writing at the
University of Massachusetts, Lowell.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
