<HEADER>
A0409 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-FISHING-HNS &LR;      05-17 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-FISHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIND SLOWS START OF SALMON CATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As thousands of California king salmon amass
deep in the ocean off the San Francisco coast, commercial fishermen
have been docked at Fisherman's Wharf waiting for the robust winds
to die down.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the San Francisco fleet of 500 boats heads south of Half
Moon Bay on an annual May 1 pilgrimage to catch the prized king _
or chinook _ salmon for diners. But this year, high winds
attributed to the La Nina weather phenomenon have made it too
difficult for most boats to go trolling.
</P>
<P>
   In calmer weather, the fishermen can be found on weekends docked
at Fisherman's Wharf, selling whole salmon, some weighing up to 25
pounds, right out of their boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting for the ocean conditions to change,'' said Larry
Collins, owner of the Pavo Grande, (the Big Turkey), berthed at the
wharf. ``We're wiring up some whopper stoppers _ boat stabilizers _
and making sure the leaks aren't getting any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   While John Mellor did venture out last week to collect crab pots
in his 40-foot High Hope, ``the weather is too rough for salmon
fishing,'' he said. Every salmon is caught by hook and line. Six
steel cables trail behind a boat, each carrying up to 12 hooks
baited with anchovies or artificial lures.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, the fish are farther offshore, Mellor
said. ``You've got to travel two or three hours, which could turn
into five hours in this weather,'' he said. ``The salmon are
feeding on mostly krill, and hang out on the temperature edges
where the warm currents hit the colder water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surface temperatures are about 45 degrees, and that makes
the fish more dormant, more scattered and harder to locate.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Mellor and other fishermen bide their time, repairing,
sanding and varnishing their boats while they shake their heads
over 11-foot-high waves breaking every 9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather's really gnarly,'' Collins said. ``There are a few
guys out there catching salmon, maybe 10 boats out in bad weather,
getting from 25 to 70 fish a day. They're out in conditions that
aren't safe for most of the fleet. They've got the newer, larger
boats, and they're the tougher captains.
</P>
<P>
   We went the first week. We caught 20 fish, which is terrible.
But we knew the weather would get better, and the fish would show
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically at this time of year, most of the Sacramento River's
fall run of salmon is off Monterey, moving north up the coast
toward the San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In August or September, the 3-year-old adults will make their
way through the Golden Gate, the Delta and up the Sacramento River
and its tributaries to the exact place they were born. The largest
tributary rivers are the American, Feather and Yuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento fall run is the largest of four salmon runs in
the San Francisco Bay, and perhaps the largest on the West Coast,
excluding Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 279,100 wild salmon, the highest number since 1985,
returned to spawn. The warm currents of El Nino, reduced that
number to 180,900 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino is the name given to the unusual warming of waters in
the Pacific Ocean that affects global wind and temperature
patterns. La Nina refers to the rapid cooling of equatorial waters
in the central Pacific that can also disrupt weather patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries biologists say in El Nino's warmer waters, there are
fewer krill and anchovies, the salmon's main food supply. Other
species of fish fleeing Southern California's very warm waters head
north and compete for the dwindling food supply off the coast here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, last year's fall run was somewhat down, simply
because we had El Nino conditions in the ocean. But it's not in
major decline,'' said Rich Dixon, senior biologist for the
California Department of Fish and Game's Central Valley salmon and
steelhead restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1992, the fall run of wild salmon dipped
between 60,000 and 87,000, worrying fish managers that the lack of
freshwater flowing from the Sacramento and San Joaquin rivers
through the Bay and Golden Gate were hurting the run.
</P>
<P>
   In response, state and federal agencies shortened the commercial
salmon fishing season. They also put more pressure on water
agencies to provide freshwater for fish and wildlife, control
fish-killing farm chemicals and remove unnecessary dams and pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, the National Marine Fisheries Service will
announce more controls under the federal Endangered Species Act to
protect the Klamath River salmon run and perhaps the Sacramento
fall and spring runs as well, which could further limit commercial
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 500-boat fleet, down from 5,700 when Barbara and Larry
Collins started fishing in 1985, was hurt by a drop in salmon
prices last year. Fish processors such as Caito, H &AMP; N and Morgan
at one point in the season were paying less than $1 a pound to
commercial fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Some fishermen, including Mellor who has been fishing for salmon
in the fleet for 20 years, decided not to go out at all.
</P>
<P>
   The price drop triggered the historic direct marketing of salmon
last year when whole fish were sold for $3.50 per pound in the
first off-the-boat sales for king salmon at Fishermen's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   It was wildly popular with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were caught a little off guard,'' said Hedley Prince,
harbor master of Fishermen's Wharf. ``We were left stranded with
little policy in place. We think it's a good thing, but we want to
make sure it's safe for the public and that we limit our
liability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
