<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0417 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-TEX     05-17 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POST-DEATH DOUBLE STANDARD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LANCE MURRAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several weeks ago the Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported the
results of the toxicology tests run on the body of a volunteer
firefighter who died heroically battling a church fire. Two
professional firefighters lost their lives as well in one of the
greatest local tragedies in years.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner's report _ a public document available for
all to see _ revealed that the volunteer firefighter had cocaine
and marijuana in his system when he died. We reported that finding
in a front-page article and were criticized by many readers for
doing so. It was invasive, even cruel, they said.
</P>
<P>
   It was news, however, and it raised a legitimate issue of public
safety concerning volunteer fire departments. But to many readers
it was unnecessary, and they told us so.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have the drug-related death of Mark Tuinei, a retired
Dallas Cowboys player. He died of what authorities said was an
accidental overdose of heroin and a stimulant, a so-called
``designer drug.'' As in the firefighter's case, some people said
Tuinei's toxicology report was nobody's business.
</P>
<P>
   Star-Telegram sports columnist Randy Galloway expressed that
sentiment about Tuinei in his May 9 column. Some readers perceived
a double standard in reporting about the two deaths. Was the sports
hero getting special treatment, but not the heroic firefighter?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Here's part of what Galloway wrote: ``Of course, open-record
laws in this state will give the slimy sector of the local media
the opportunity to kick around a dead man. If, that is, the autopsy
shows Tuinei was involved in something he shouldn't have been,
resulting in his own death.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the Cowboys' recent image problems, Galloway wrote that if
the investigation found something illegal or if other Cowboys were
involved, then it was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it did,'' Galloway said this week by phone from St. Louis,
where he was covering the Dallas Stars. ``It changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway believes that the story should be fully reported in the
news sections. Cowboys running back Nicky Sualua was with Tuinei
and was the person who called 911, police said. Sualua's statement
to police has been the basis for much of the reporting about
Tuinei's death.
</P>
<P>
   But Galloway's original column caused several readers to assert
that the Star-Telegram was hypocritical and had a double standard.
We'd report about the firefighter, they said, but wasn't Galloway
saying we shouldn't do the same about a sports celebrity like
Tuinei?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all. Galloway's column was pointed squarely at those who
might promote sensationalism or controversy, not legitimate news
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was giving my opinion,'' Galloway said. ``That column was
aimed at sports talk shows ... and to point out that I'm a member
of that group.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway also is the host of a popular sports call-in show on
WBAP/820 AM. There is a big difference between talk radio and a
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a big difference between what a columnist writes
and what appears in the news stories we publish. A columnist writes
opinion _ his or her opinion. Reporters write and editors select
the news stories we publish each day. Sometimes it is difficult for
readers to separate the two.
</P>
<P>
   Just as readers can agree or disagree with Galloway, he can
express a strong opinion and take issue with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the newsroom didn't agree with Galloway. I didn't.
Neither did his boss, Ellen Alfano, managing editor for sports and
features, who despite her own feelings allowed Galloway to express
his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I may not always agree with Randy Galloway and our
other columnists, I support their right to express their opinions.
The role of columnists is to give readers their insights and points
of view in an entertaining and thought-provoking manner,'' Alfano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway writes about things that he feels passionately about.
He can be emotional, abrasive, sarcastic or funny. He can even be
contrite.
</P>
<P>
   Columnists can write almost anything, unless it is libelous or
false.
</P>
<P>
   If Galloway says that ``old Joe is a lousy coach'' or that a
player is not playing to his potential, it's his opinion. But if he
writes that ``old Joe is a crook,'' it must be true and he must
have the facts to support it. Columnists are bound by the same
rules of accuracy and truth that govern news reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Our columnists write their opinions about everything from
raising a family to local politics. We employ many reporters to
gather facts and write about a wide variety of topics, but they are
not allowed to interject opinion into their writings. They cannot
take a stance. In fact, all sides of a story must be reported,
allowing readers to decide for themselves which side they will
believe.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway wrote of remembering the good things about Tuinei and
his contributions to the Cowboys and the community. We should. We
will remember the heroic way in which those three firefighters lost
their lives. We should.
</P>
<P>
   But we cannot ignore the bad if there is a public need to know
and a lesson to be learned. In such tragedies as these, the
contents of medical examiners' toxicology reports are news, and we
must report them even if they are bad.
</P>
<P>
   But remember: Columns must be relevant, timely and true. They
are opinion. News stories must be relevant, timely and true. They
are not opinion.
</P>
<P>
   (Lance Murray is reader advocate for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can reach him by phone at (817) 390-7692; by
e-mail at lancem(at)star-telegram.com; and by mail at 400 W.
Seventh St., Fort Worth, TX 76102. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
