<HEADER>
A0430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-0518-1ST     05-17 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-0518-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: updates throughout to reflect Barak victory . . .
 &HT;    COLD, SMART AND AMBITIOUS, BARAK HAS LIVED ISRAEL'S HIGH POINTS
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-0518.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Powered by ego, brilliance and bravery, Ehud Barak's
own exploits have helped create Israel's image of daring and unity.
</P>
<P>
   As an Israeli commando, he has disguised himself as a flight
technician when raiding a hijacked airliner. On another mission, he
dressed as a woman to infiltrate Beirut and assassinate Palestine
Libertation Organization (PLO) terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to the point in his career that Israeli officers
customarily adopt Hebrew names, he dropped his family name,
``Brog,'' for ``Barak.'' It means ``Lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he's a quiet, calculating man known for long-term planning.
His hobby since childhood has been fixing old watches and clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 57-years-old, his time has come.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Ehud Barak, Israel's most decorated soldier, won
by a stunning margin to become Israel's next prime minister. He
promises to bring unity to a country with such deep and bitter
divisions that they seem to defy the mythic Israel Barak's heroics
helped create.
</P>
<P>
   ``These elections are maybe, in certain aspects, the most
crucial in a generation,'' he said recently, citing Israel's rifts
between rich and poor, and between religious and secular.
``Somehow, something happened in the last few years. The country is
at an impasse on every major issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's target, the man he repeatedly blames for everything
being ``stuck,'' is now-former right-wing incumbent Benjamin
Netanyahu, who once raided a hijacked airline with Barak while they
served in the commandos together.
</P>
<P>
   Barak says Netanyahu was a good officer. He was especially close
to his brother, Yoni Netanyahu, the only Israeli commando killed in
the raid on the hijacked airliner in Entebbe, Uganda. Barak helped
plan, but did not go on the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Old friends say they first began thinking of Barak as prime
minister material when he gave an eloquent eulogy at Yoni
Netanyahu's funeral in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   But, Benjamin Netanyahu got the prime minister's job first.
Right-wing and combative, he became an emblem for the
hard-to-manage Israel, a country of divisions that is stalemated on
the peace process with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak to set that straight, the former commando will need to
adapt to the give-and-take of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good fighter. I hope he will be a good civilian,''
says an old army commander, Shaul Givoli.
</P>
<P>
   Barak hardly appears either a commando or a politician. Short
and paunchy, he has soft features and still appears stiff in
public. He dodged campaign debates with the quick-tongued
Netanyahu. Friends say he is often shy or even coldly arrogant. He
and his wife, Nava, have three daughters, but they have been slow
to wade into the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Barak seems too analytical and blunt for politics.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would have become of him had he been born a
Palestinian, the career soldier said, ``If I were a young
Palestinian, it is possible that I would join a terrorist
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   It caused a stir in the media and was used against him in
political commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Barak was born on a kibbutz, one of the old socialist
communal farms formed by European Jews. His performance in school
and the army vaulted him into Israel's elites. He was pegged as a
leader, even when he made mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Givoli remembers when Barak got in trouble for losing maps
during an officer school exercise. Givoli considered expelling him,
but others persuaded him that Barak would one day lead the army.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Gil, one of Barak's early commanders, said he had
``discipline of steel and was always very obedient.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his army service, Barak got a physics degree at
Hebrew University in Jerusalem. Classmate Danny Michaelson said
Barak soon realized that physics did not offer enough ``action.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he ran reconnaissance teams behind enemy lines in the
war of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   He rose to head army intelligence and eventually become army
chief of staff. There, he became a close adviser to then-Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   He's considered a peacemaker in the Rabin style -- tough and
pragmatic -- and eschews idealistic talk about harmony in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he talks of a ``separation'' between the Jews and
Palestinians, with high fences and tight security.
</P>
<P>
   He was slow to accept the Oslo peace process in 1993. But, he
oversaw some troop withdrawals when land was initially handed over
to the Palestinians and now he promises to speed up the
negotiations that Netanyahu has halted.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of strategic thinking comes easily to Barak. It's the
politics, with its hand-shaking and conspicuous shows of emotion,
that will be harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the real test,'' according to Avshalom Horan, among
the hundreds of old commando buddies working on Barak's campaign.
``It doesn't rely on the cerebral. It's a matter of personality and
leadership. He sees that as the major task in the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
