<HEADER>
A0440 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     05-17 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV19-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO MUMMY LIKE AN OLD MUMMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, May 19)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't intend to see the new movie, ``The Mummy,'' because I
can tell by reading the reviews that I won't like it.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Mummy'' is said to be heavy on the special effects,
which serve no purpose other than to take your mind off the stupid
dialogue and the sad fact that Brendan Fraser and Arnold Vosloo
will never be another Peter Cushing or Boris Karloff, no matter how
many digitalized locusts you throw at them.
</P>
<P>
   Most depressing of all is that the modern Mummy is not a mummy
at all, but rather your basic, garden-variety rotting corpse. And
it has the ability to transform itself into a variety of distinctly
un-mummylike things. Like a sandstorm, for instance. C'mon, people,
let's get real.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to me: A mummy is not whirling dirt or scarab beetles
burrowing under your skin. It is a (semi) preserved dead person
swathed in bandages. Good mummies, or rather the mummies of good
mummy movies, are thousands of years old and, as you might expect,
a little slow-footed and creaky in the joints. You should be able
to wade through quicksand while carrying a fainted Yvonne Furneaux
and still be able to outrun a mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the bandages and, perhaps, a strict Egyptian
upbringing, mummies don't talk much or show a lot of expression.
Christopher Lee, in the 1959 version, brought the art of grunting
and eye-rolling to a level that has yet to be matched. If Lee's
mummy rolled his eyes upward, it meant he was preparing to strangle
Peter Cushing. If he rolled his eyes in a counterclockwise
direction, it meant he was in the process of strangling Peter
Cushing. If he grunted and rolled his eyes in a clockwise
direction, it meant that he was allowing amorous thoughts of Yvonne
Furneaux to distract him from the business of strangling Peter
Cushing. Etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing as it does in ancient curses and such, a good mummy
movie should have some elements that fly in the face of logic. For
example, there should never be any good explanation as to why the
mummy is so adept at catching his victims given the fact that he
possesses the foot speed of a box turtle. I mean, it's not like the
mummy exactly blends in with the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Seven feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Bandaged from head to foot.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling gait.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think a person like this would attract attention. But no.
Mummies have no problem blending in with society, which should tell
you all you need to know about society.
</P>
<P>
   In a good mummy movie, the victim should be sitting in his
living room, reading a book and smoking a pipe. Suddenly, a mummy
shuffles into the room. The victim reacts to this invasion by
turning the page and taking another puff on his pipe. The mummy
stands there for a minute or two, waiting for a reaction. Nothing.
You get the feeling the mummy could fix himself a sandwich or
perform a break dance on the living room floor and the victim
wouldn't notice. Finally, realizing that he's got to get moving if
he's ever going to get to the clinch scene with Yvonne Furneaux,
the mummy rolls his eyes upward and lifts the victim out of his
chair by the neck.
</P>
<P>
   (Because it is a good mummy movie, viewers do not question why
it is that a person who has been dead 3,500 years has such superbly
conditioned wrist and forearm muscles yet cannot outrun a lawn
statue.)
</P>
<P>
   In the end, you should feel sorry for the mummy, but not because
it is the undeserving victim of an ancient curse and is doomed to
inhabit the nether world between the living and the dead for all
eternity.
</P>
<P>
   You should feel sorry for it because someone in the future
(Stephen Sommers) will do a remake of the movie filled with
needless special effects and cheesy dialogue and it won't be around
to roll its eyes upward and extend a helping hand.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
