<SLUG> BC-PICASSO-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PICASSO IS SEVERELY SLASHED BY A DUTCH MENTAL PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A Dutch psychiatric patient wielding a kitchen knife
severely slashed a Picasso painting called ``Nude in Front of the
Garden'' in Amsterdam's Stedelijk Museum of Modern Art on Sunday,
then went to a newspaper office to brag about his act. The police
were called to the office, where the man was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the museum said that just as the museum was
emptying on Sunday afternoon, the man ripped a large circular hole
in the center of the canvas with a blunt knife before fleeing. The
man, identified only as P.G., whose age was given as 41, is a
patient in a psychiatric clinic in the nearby city of Utrecht and
had been given permission to leave, a spokesman at the clinic said.
The police returned him to the clinic, where he is now confined to
a closed area.
</P>
<P>
   He is believed to be the person who in 1990 sprayed acid on
Rembrandt's ``Nightwatch'' in the nearby Rijksmuseum, damaging the
varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Rudi Fuchs, the Stedelijk's director, said restoration experts
are examining the Picasso and the possibility of repairing it.
``This is a very dramatic incident,'' Fuchs said. ``The painting is
an essential piece of our collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mosterd, the museum spokesman, said that restoration would
not be simple because of the bluntness of the peeling knife that
was used. ``These are not neat cuts,'' Mosterd said, adding that
fragments of paint along the cuts had fallen off.
</P>
<P>
   The work, which Picasso painted in Cannes in 1956, shows a naked
woman reclining in a chair against a backdrop of a garden. It has
been in the museum since 1981 and is one of the museum's six
Picassos. Its estimated value is $5 million to $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The cut affects part of the woman's body and the garden behind
it. In Amsterdam and elsewhere the incident has again raised the
issue of the security of unprotected art in public places.
</P>
<P>
   The is the third time that a work in the Stedelijk has been
vandalized. In 1987 an Amsterdam resident slashed a painting by
Barnett Newman, ``Who's Afraid of Red Yellow and Blue III.'' The
same man struck again in 1997, this time ruining ``Cathedra,''
another Newman painting.
</P>
<P>
   By some standards, security in Dutch museums is casual, although
the debate about what kind of security is desirable and what is
acceptable will no doubt reopen, Amsterdam officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guards, we have video cameras, but we don't have metal
detectors or special doors,'' Mosterd said. ``We do not want to
turn into a fortress. We want to remain an easy, open place. It is
nearly impossible to protect yourself against madmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs said at a news conference that he would meet with
government and other museum officials to discuss security.
``Museums all over the world face a security problem,'' he said.
``It's a real dilemma. You can come in, you can look and
unfortunately you can pull out a knife and cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Paintings have glass only when it is physically necessary, he
went on. ``We would like to keep it that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the suspect struck at 4:30 p.m., half an hour before
closing. He spent more than an hour in the museum and apparently
waited to act until a guard walked into an adjacent room.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the museum unhindered, he went to the offices of
De Telegraaf to boast about his deed. The newspaper called the
police and the man was detained on the premises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
