<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO VISIT A TEST FOR CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ When Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
arrives in California on Tuesday, his first stop will be a state
Capitol jammed with hundreds of immigrants and Hispanic activists.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Zedillo's visit with the annual ``Hungry for
Justice Immigrant Day'' is, officials insist, coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just as well, because immigration and how California
Gov. Gray Davis has treated undocumented Mexicans will be a central
theme surrounding Zedillo's three-day trip to Sacramento, San
Francisco, Los Angeles and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other issue facing his 5-month-old administration,
Davis walks a delicate path when it comes to immigration, mindful
that former Gov. Pete Wilson hurt the Republican Party by appearing
too mean-spirited on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   However, Davis angered California Hispanics when he decided to
negotiate a court settlement over the remaining shreds of
Proposition 187, the 1994 ballot initiative to cut public services
to illegal immigrants that has been hobbled by court challenges.
They expected Davis to simply drop California's defense of the
initiative, but he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of angry people,'' said Gary Segura, a
professor at Claremont Graduate University. ``This is a very
complex issue, and I think it might blow over, but it got
simplified into: `Gray Davis tricked us.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Davis, who is a Democrat, quietly shut down a
Wilson border policy of interrogating immigrants about using state
health insurance. Those found to have used public services, such as
Medi-Cal for childbirth, were taken to court and forced to repay
the money, sometimes thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Hispanic activists applauded Davis' decision on the
border interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   But the political ripple over Proposition 187 spread as it
received much more media attention and sparked a public feud
between Davis and Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is ``trying to have it both ways, and he can't,'' said
Renee Saucedo, chairwoman of the San Francisco Immigrant Rights
Commission. ``Through some of his strategies, he has basically
betrayed the community that helped put him in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was elected by one of the largest landslides in modern
California history, with Hispanics voting overwhelmingly for him
over Republican Dan Lungren, 78 percent to 17 percent, according to
an exit poll taken by the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis promised during his campaign, in somewhat vague terms, to
end the ``wedge-issue'' politics of the Wilson administration,
which viewed many state-financed services as magnets for illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also is keenly aware that wedges can split a political
career both ways. A majority of voters supported Proposition 187
and another state initiative, Proposition 209, which ended
affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the major challenge Davis faces,'' said Mike Madrid,
former state GOP political director, ``is appeasing an increasing
and growing constituency that was largely responsible for his
overwhelming victory, and at the same time balancing his own
internal polling that shows the vast majority of Californians would
support Proposition 187 if it were on the ballot today. It's a
pretty big dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante, who is not related to the
lieutenant governor, acknowledged that Davis was balancing
constituencies in his decision to send Proposition 187 into
mediation to resolve legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters voted for this,'' Bustamante said, ``and the governor
will not disregard the vote that was cast, even though Proposition
187 was an initiative he believed was wrong and opposed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
