<HEADLINE>
NORMAN FOSTER TO REDESIGN BOSTON'S MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir Norman Foster, the 1999 Pritzker Prize-winning architect who
oversaw the recent redesign of the Reichstag in Berlin, has been
commissioned to produce a master plan for the expansion and
renovation of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The move, announced Monday by museum director Malcolm Rogers, is
part of a 10-year plan to enhance the institution. The selection of
Sir Norman, whose firm, Foster and Partners, has headquarters in
London, came after a yearlong search that considered about 30
architectural teams. The commission is the architect's first
full-scale project in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for an internationally recognized firm, which
would be able to create a landmark design for the museum,
integrating a modernist esthetic while remaining sympathetic to the
museum's existing historic buildings,'' said Graham Gund, an
honorary trustee of the institution. The museum has seen numerous
major expansions in its 130 years, most recently the
80,000-square-foot West Wing designed by I.M. Pei, another Pritzker
winner. The Pei addition was completed in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Norman likened the museum to its surrounding city. ``You
have this building with wonderful historic qualities which has
grown over time,'' he said. ``It has some outstanding parts and
some that don't work so well.''
</P>
<P>
   The architect's work is noted for its adherence to the esthetics
of 20th-century modernism, combining bold structures, a lavish use
of glass and dramatic interior spaces. In the Hong Kong and
Shanghai Banking Corp. building in Hong Kong, perhaps his
best-known project, tall, thin slabs of metal, glass and concrete
appear to be held together by three massive steel trusses. His
design for the Reichstag features a glass dome enclosing spiral
ramps. Other museum projects include the Great Court of the British
Museum in London; the Sainsbury Center for Visual Arts in Norfolk,
England; the Carre d'Art in Nimes, France, and a new wing for the
Joslyn Museum in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   The jury for the Pritzker Prize, architecture's most prestigious
award, called Sir Norman's work ``downright beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials expect Foster and Partners to complete a master
site plan and initial schematic drawings by early next year.
Construction is expected to take several years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
