<HEADER>
A0460 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-OFFICE-SURGERY-AR     05-17 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OFFICE-SURGERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEONS LEAVING THE O.R. FOR THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Calif., Ill., N.J., Mass., N.Y., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ancient art of surgery is on the move again. For hundreds of
years most surgical procedures were done at home on the kitchen
table. Only in the last century did advances in medical technology
move them into hospital operating rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now much of surgery is traveling again, into the less expensive
settings of doctors' private offices, and this has set off an
escalating nationwide debate on how to insure patients' safety as
the complicated modern technology of anesthesia and surgery floats
free of hospital regulations back into less-restricted settings.
</P>
<P>
   Although only a handful of states have enacted legislation
dealing with office surgery, virtually all are examining the issue
because of a few widely publicized deaths and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Favors, a day-care worker in Odessa, Texas, has to her
regret become an unwilling expert on the issue. Two years ago Mrs.
Favors' daughter, Kami, 9, went into a Texas doctor's office for
routine minor ear surgery. Kami's heart stopped from the anesthetic
before the surgery began, Mrs. Favors said. She was taken to a
nearby hospital but could not be resuscitated. A malpractice suit
was settled for $1.8 million early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my only child,'' Mrs. Favors said. ``I'm never going
to have another one. Tell people to do their surgery in a hospital
that's regulated. Tell them to make certain they have somebody
there and medicine to help if something goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the most recent year for which statistics are
available, 51 percent of the nation's surgical procedures were done
on people who were not admitted to a hospital, according to the
National Center for Health Statistics. The SMG Marketing Group, a
Chicago consulting firm, estimated that 26 percent of all these
outpatient surgeries were performed in doctors' offices, up from 5
percent in 1981. If current trends continue, the group estimates,
20 percent of all surgical procedures will be done in doctors'
offices by the year 2005, a total of almost 10 million operations a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The most common procedures performed in outpatient settings are
cataract surgery, examinations and biopsies of the lining of the
small and large intestines and plastic surgery. Some outpatient
operations can be done under local anesthesia, but a growing number
require more powerful drugs, including sedatives that induce a
short sleep that erases all memory of the operation, and more
powerful anesthetics that paralyze breathing during surgery and
require the placement of a breathing tube and the use of a
respirator.
</P>
<P>
   The farther from a hospital an operation is moved, the less
expensive it becomes. The per-hour cost of an operation in a
freestanding surgical center near a hospital, and with close
hospital affiliations, is about 50 percent to 60 percent of that in
a hospital, and in a doctor's office, about 33 percent, said Edward
J. Stygar Jr., a spokesman for the American Association for
Accreditation of Ambulatory Surgery Facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, patients generally find office settings more
pleasant, quieter and more private than hospitals, while medical
personnel almost always find working in an office more convenient
and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   But the farther from the hospital a surgical procedure moves,
the farther it also moves from the cadre of trained medical
personnel who can help in emergencies, and from the hospital's
thousands of regulations and protocols, including routine checks on
medical qualifications of surgeons and anesthesiologists,
maintenance of equipment, and procedures to follow if something
goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike hospitals and hospital-associated facilities, private
offices are largely exempt from routine oversight by state and
national agencies and subject to examination only when patients
file complaints. In most states, doctors are under no obligation to
report untoward incidents that happen in the office to the state
health authorities, nor do hospitals regularly track the emergency
and near-emergency cases that arrive in hospital emergency rooms
from doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   The state doctor-licensing boards lack the budget and manpower
for routine inspections of doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everyone else in state systems, medical boards are
suffering from limited resources,'' said Dale L. Austin, deputy
executive vice president of the Federation of State Medical Boards.
``They tend to go where there are complaints, where there are fires
to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there are few statistics on injuries or deaths from office
surgery, preventing the authorities from devising adequate
regulations. Still less is known about what kind of anesthesia
equipment is used in offices and how it is maintained, or how
commonly doctors perform surgery in their offices because they lack
the training or credentials to get operating privileges in a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is one of the few states to put doctors' offices
under the same tight operating regulations as those for hospitals.
New York and Connecticut are looking at the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Even in states without legislation, some safeguards on office
surgery exist, but they are voluntary. Three national independent
agencies can, for a fee, accredit offices where surgery is
performed. This means that office routines and qualifications of
personnel are periodically examined, much the way they are in a
hospital, and gross breaches of safety are picked up and corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Patients on their own are unlikely to sense when there is a
problem with a surgical office, said Dr. Ervin Moss, executive
medical director of the New Jersey State Society of
Anesthesiologists and a champion of the state's new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially plastic surgeons' offices,'' Moss said, ``You walk
in and it looks like Hollywood. People just don't know. They have
not been protected up till now.''
</P>
<P>
   Accidents during surgery do occur even in hospitals, but they
are increasingly rare. Deaths from anesthesia, a major cause of
surgical accidents, have declined by about 95 percent in the last
15 years, said Dr. Ellison C. Pierce Jr., an anesthesiologist at
Harvard University, who is executive director of the Anesthesia
Patient Safety Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement has resulted from better equipment for
monitoring patients, safer drugs and better training for medical
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Professional anesthesia organizations have developed guidelines
for administering anesthesia in offices, and many anesthesiologists
maintain that it can be given in the office just as safely as in a
hospital. But doing so requires an obsessive attention to detail
and safety procedures, said Dr. Marc E. Koch, an anesthesiologist
who works in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Koch has worked exclusively in doctors' offices,
wheeling portable anesthesia equipment on a luggage carrier into
private surgical offices to anesthetize patients for procedures as
simple as minor foot surgery or as complicated as an eight-hour
facelift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be one step better than a hospital,'' he said
recently, driving through city traffic for 8 a.m. breast surgery in
Great Neck, N.Y. Koch said he had walked out of surgical offices
with electrical hazards or unacceptable sanitation, and he
routinely carries a full array of emergency medication.
</P>
<P>
   A survey in the medical journal Plastic and Reconstructive
Surgery in 1997 examined more than 400,000 surgical procedures done
in accredited surgical offices and found complications in fewer
than 1 percent of the cases, comparable to the low rate in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But even if states make this accreditation mandatory, problems
with office surgery may persist. For example, California, one of
the states that regulate office surgery, required that all
office-surgery facilities be accredited as of 1996. Most surgeons
operating in their offices complied with the law, said Dr. Thomas
A. Joas, president of the Medical Board of California. But Joas
added: ``Were we left with a problem after that? Yes, we certainly
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the regulations were passed, three California women died
in medical offices from liposuction, the surgical removal of fat,
and another suffered gangrene of both legs from implant surgery to
increase the size of her calves. Legislation being considered in
California would further regulate office surgery, including
specifying how offices should be staffed and requiring full
disclosure of doctors' credentials to patients.
</P>
<P>
   But for states to dictate the parameters of private practice is
an enormously controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic surgery is ``the last bastion of the free enterprise
system in medicine, and it attracts physicians and surgeons of all
ilk,'' Joas said, referring to the fact that cosmetic procedures
are seldom covered by medical insurance and doctors are generally
paid in cash.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, and also because cosmetic procedures are
elective and the first to be bumped off hospital surgical schedules
for emergencies, cosmetic surgery is routinely performed in
doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   The most common cosmetic operation performed in the United
States is liposuction, which may cause a variety of
life-threatening complications. According to a report last week in
The New England Journal of Medicine, five people died in New York
City from 1993 to 1998 after liposuction, from dangerous shifts in
body fluid, blood clots that traveled to the lungs or complications
from anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, the dangers of cosmetic surgery have focused the
state's concern with office surgery in general. Last winter, a Fort
Lauderdale newspaper, The Sun-Sentinel, published a series of
articles detailing dozens of deaths that occurred during cosmetic
procedures in the state since 1986. Many of the operations were
performed in doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Florida Medical Board reacted to the series with
a set of stringent regulations governing office surgery, including
limits on the amount of fat that could be removed during an office
liposuction, and a mandate that office operations last no more than
six hours. Cosmetic operations, particularly when they include
several procedures, may take eight hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions on the amount of fat safely removed in an
outpatient setting is consistent with medical guidelines, said Dr.
Joel R. Studin, a Manhattan plastic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   But although some surgery, like an abdominal operation, is safer
when it is shorter, limiting the duration of cosmetic operations is
not known to increase their safety, said Dr. Edward Truppman, a
Florida plastic surgeon who is the immediate past president of the
Florida Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   The stipulation worries many Florida plastic surgeons. They fear
that to practice legally, they might rush procedures, Truppman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can regulate or legislate good surgical
judgment,'' Truppman said.
</P>
<P>
   And when states try to regulate not only surgical procedures in
offices but also who performs them, they may become entangled in
turf battles and stall efforts on regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, for instance, part of the state's 1998
regulations are on hold while certified nurse-anesthetists battle
the state in court over the requirement that an anesthesia-trained
doctor also be on the premises during some office procedures.
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, state Sen. Roy M. Goodman, Republican of
Manhattan, said that shortly after his office issued a report
detailing problems with office surgery in the state and implying
that only doctors with plastic surgery training should perform
liposuction, he was visited by a group of dermatologists who wanted
to emphasize their own qualifications to perform the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really needs to be done is to determine through some form
of survey what the bungle rate is of services that are being
performed by doctors in offices,'' Goodman said. ``What we have is
anecdotal information which is quite shocking. We have to try to
get some further information so that we can determine what
categories of things are most accident-prone and most likely to
cause an unhappy outcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
