A0486 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-JAIL-PA     05-17 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-JAIL-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FOUR JAILED REFUGEES RETURNED TO CAMPSITE, INS OFFICIALS
SAID
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 17 -- After a brief stint in Pennsylvania jails,
four ethnic Albanian refugees who used fake identities to gain
entry into the United States were returned Sunday to Fort Dix, New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The four were freed when immigration officials reversed their
position, deeming it ``unnecessary'' to jail refugees just because
they lacked the proper documentation, said Amy Otten, a spokeswoman
for the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had to follow the standard immigration
procedures which would be to detain someone while these questions
were answered,'' Otten said. ``But we reconsidered and now unless
it's an egregious situation or there are issues with the person's
criminal history, we don't have to go through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials, Otten said, now know the identities of the four
Ethnic Albanian refugees. The two men, one woman and one teenage
girl are unrelated, did not have criminal backgrounds and had been
slated to come to the U.S as refugees, Otten said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a case where they may have jumped ahead in line
or traded spots with relatives or friends in order to leave
war-torn Kosovo earlier,'' Otten said. ``We just didn't have the
right documents for them.''
</P>
<P>
   When the four arrived last week at Fort Dix, N.J., immigration
officials realized their names didn't match identification photos
taken in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, aged 21 and 22, had been held in Carbon County
prison, and a 22-year-old Kosovo woman was in a York County prison.
A 17-year-old Kosovo girl was kept at the Berks County youth
center, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting immigration hearings to determine if they could
remain in the country, the four refugees had been sent to
``dormitory portions'' of the jails and separated from the inmates.
But officials said there was no longer a risk the four would be
returned to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never believed they were criminals,'' Otten said. ``This is
a unique situation and we are having to create unique procedures to
reconcile our desire to help the refugees with the requirements of
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   An INS spokesman at Fort Dix said the four were ``relieved to be
back at the campsite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a four or five day detour,'' said Carl Rusnok, a
Philadelphia regional spokesman for INS temporarily based at Fort
Dix. ``It's a wonderful day here in New Jersey for those refugees
who are now back with the others at the picnic area and
playground.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials had announced they would tighten screening of refugees
in an effort to keep out Serb collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, INS officials received special training on
identifying criminals who may be passing themselves off as
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The four were in the second wave of ethnic Albanians who arrived
at McGuire Air Force Base in New Jersey earlier this month. The
U.S. has agreed to take in 20,000 Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Otten said there are about 29 other cases at Fort Dix where the
identities of refugees is unclear. But those cases will be handled
differently, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those refugees will not be sent to jails while the details of
their identities are sought,'' Otten said. ``We have had to
establish these procedures as we go along in these unique
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for The United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees, said the group was pleased INS had reconsidered its
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been better if they had never been jailed at
all, but we are very happy INS reversed itself promptly,'' said
Bemma Donkoh, a UNHCR spokeswoman. ``This is the right thing to do.
We hope this will mean good things for future refugees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
