<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, five feet of standing water covered the streets of
Dubuque, Iowa, as a slow-moving thunderstorm produced 3.7 inches of
rain in portions of the city. The storm was part of a larger
cluster of showers and thunderstorms that erupted as an approaching
cold front lifted a wedge of very humid air covering the Middle
West. Tuesday the front will forge eastward, bringing the threat
for potent storms to the eastern Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The day will dawn unusually warm from southern Ohio to western
New York. As the sun heats the ground and overlying moist air, the
atmosphere will turn more unstable, setting the stage for strong
thunderstorms to form by afternoon. An approaching jet stream
disturbance will enhance the volatile conditions, causing a few of
the storms to produce hail and damaging winds.
</P>
<P>
   Intervals of clouds and sun will cover the Northeast and Middle
Atlantic Seaboards Tuesday as an offshore low-pressure system
continues to circulate damp, ocean-chilled air westward. Farther
south, sunshine and humid conditions will persist over Florida with
isolated thunderstorms developing in the sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated potent thunderstorms will ignite across southern Texas
and the lower Tennessee Valley as a weak cool front crosses the
region. Behind the front, dry but warm conditions will envelop the
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional showers will dampen the Northwest as cool, onshore
breezes persist. Meanwhile, the Southwest will broil beneath
abundant sun. Readings will exceed 100 degrees near the
California-Arizona border.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Pending Monsoon
</P>
<P>
   Not a single raindrop has to fall during a monsoon. Derived from
an Arabic word meaning ``season,'' a monsoon is simply a seasonal
shift in wind direction. Over India, extreme heating in summer
fosters moist ocean winds that fuel showers. During India'Us
winter, however, the expansive Siberian high dominates, promoting
dry northerly winds that shut off precipitation. The onset of humid
winds from the Bay of Bengal initiates over Sri Lanka during the
next week. It takes most of June for the sultry winds to dominate
the subcontinent with tropical moisture not reaching Delhi until
early July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0498 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FUTURE-HEALTH-NYT     05-17 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FUTURE-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE FUTURE, SOME DOCTORS MAY BE GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Md., N.C., Utah)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every week, a group of doctors, engineers, scientists and
computer specialists get together at the University of Rochester in
Rochester, N.Y., to talk over ideas that might sound outlandish to
most people, including the notion that the future of medicine lies
in devices that are high-tech, cheap and controlled by patients.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the ``smart'' bandage covering a wound that would
instantly screen for common infectious agents and indicate whether
an antibiotic was needed, and if so, which one. Or memory glasses
linked to a databank of familiar faces that would display their
names to Alzheimer patients when one comes into sight. Or a body
scanner that would provide a daily body check in the shower and
report on the growth of any melanoma long before the person would
be likely to find it, or an ``emotion detector'' that would learn
the rhythms of a wife-batterer's rages and warn him as anger began
to build.
</P>
<P>
   None of these gadgets are ready for the drugstore or close to
it. But the cross-pollinating sessions that gave rise to them have
also given birth to the Center for the Future of Health, a new
partnership between the University of Rochester and the Media Lab
of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Their collaboration
points to the growing entwinement of computer sciences and the
healing arts and the degree of integration between fields like
pathology, biochemistry and electrical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Similar efforts are under way at Johns Hopkins, Duke and
Massachusetts General Medical Center, where doctors armed with a
Defense Department grant are trying to apply military technology to
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the devices under development at the center rely on a
new generation of microsensors that use inexpensive computer chips
not only to record but to analyze data. ``That allows you to know
what's happening to you virtually all the time _ to learn your
body's specific rhythm as opposed to the average pattern,'' said
Alexander Pentland, academic director of the MIT Media Lab.
</P>
<P>
   The devices could home in on more specific problems as well. For
example, diabetics often lose sensation in their feet, leaving
injuries unnoticed and untreated until they have grown more
serious. Sensors inserted in the fibers of socks could detect such
injuries before the wearer could, according to a center proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Langer, a professor of bioengineering at MIT with no
connection to the Rochester center, believes many of the proposals
at the center are promising, but wonders about their practical
application.
</P>
<P>
   ``These all sound like very good ideas, but the key issue is how
well are these things really going to work,'' he said. ``You can
make something small or cheap or efficient, but it's hard to do all
three. Sensors, for instance, have to be small enough to go where
they are needed, specific enough to focus in on what is being
looked for and sensitive enough to filter out background noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alice Pentland, a dermatologist who is the Rochester
center's medical director, and Pentland's sister, said one of the
program's goals was to get participants ``from each side of the
divide'' to be more aware of how the other side works. ``Engineers
are used to building something, trying it, taking it apart and then
building it again,'' she said. ``Physicians are more used to having
devices handed to them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, clinicians have a clearer idea of the needs
for which gadgets should be dreamed up. The smart-bandage project,
for example, grew out of a radio report Dr. Pentland heard about an
epidemic of drug-resistant tuberculosis in Russia caused by misuse
of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it takes weeks to get culture results for
identifying new strains,'' she said. ``I was thinking that sooner
or later we're going to get an influx of this, and wouldn't it be
nice to have something that could screen for it fast, and stop the
epidemic before it got into the general population.''
</P>
<P>
   The bandage works with an array of tiny sensors, each able to
recognize one characteristic of bacteria, which have telltale
patterns of sugars and proteins. In the presence of an infectious
agent, the reactions would create a current that would feed a
microcomputer, which would then compare the ``map'' of reactions
with stored data on bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   It took a team, including a microbiologist, biochemist, computer
scientist and electrical engineer, to conclude that the task was
doable. Dr. Philippe Fauchet, the center's director, estimates that
a working product is three to five years away.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the center's projects are trying to take recent
high-tech developments and spin off simpler counterparts. For
instance, its researchers hope to use a sophisticated robotic hand
developed by MIT and the University of Utah to develop
object-recognition software for a device that could help older
patients keep their pills straight.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pentland said she hoped that the approach could spill over
into a number of disciplines, like psychology. ``Imagine how a
behavioral therapist would benefit from something that would not
only monitor a session but give feedback as the therapy was
proceeding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposed psychological device, the emotion monitor, is
an example of how the center hopes to build on a fairly simple,
existing device _ a sensor worn like a wristwatch that monitors the
pulse and major muscle movements. The next stage would be to add
sensors that track respiration. The leap would come in developing
``intelligent'' software that could learn how those measures
correlate with the wearer's emotional state, potentially sounding
an alarm as a violent rage first starts to build.
</P>
<P>
   Officials concede that such devices raise staggering issues of
privacy, as do even simpler proposed devices like the melanoma
monitor, which would create a three-dimensional map of the body
surface and analyze changes for early signs of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Phelps, a health-care economist who is provost of the
University of Rochester, said it would be important to establish
the principle that the consumers who buy the devices own the data
they create. ``Think of a smart bed that records metabolic rates
and other information,'' he said. ``Insurers would certainly like
to get their hands on that data _ who is obese, who has heart
problems _ but there's no particular reason why consumers should
have to give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pentland said she hoped the data from such home monitors
would provide very specific individual health information for
consumers to use, for example, in the doctor's office. ``Right now
people come in with their piles of information from the Internet
about something that's far from the mark,'' she said. But if
patients are able to pose routine queries through interactive
medical records ``friendly enough for a mom to be able to use in
the middle of the night,'' and arrive armed with detailed data from
home monitors, ``this will free doctors up to do what they should
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into medicine to give emotional support and help people
with problems,'' Dr. Pentland said, ``not just to be a test-taker
and a paper-shover.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      05-17 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HEALTH AND FITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Mass., Ohio)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRO &AMP; CON
</P>
<P>
   Are Sports Drinks Better Than Water?
</P>
<P>
   Sports drinks offer many benefits over plain water or other
beverages like fruit juice or soda to maintain hydration status and
enhance performance.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have studies found that people can perform at higher
intensities for longer periods of time for endurance sports
(activities lasting over 90 minutes) like marathon running or
cycling, recent research shows that sports drinks improve athletic
performance in high-intensity, stop-and-go sports including
basketball and soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike water, sports drinks provide sodium, which is lost in
sweat, and carbohydrates. The small amount of sodium helps
stimulate the body's thirst mechanism so that the active person
drinks more than he or she normally would. In addition, these
ingredients speed fluid absorption from the gut into the
bloodstream, making dehydration less likely. Finally, the
carbohydrates in sports drinks provide a steady source of readily
available energy so that people can avoid the feeling of hitting
the wall when muscle carbohydrate stores are depleted.
</P>
<P>
   DR. LARRY KENNEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Professor of human physiology and kinesiology at Pennsylvania
State University and member of Gatorade sports medicine review
board
</P>
<P>
   For most active people, sports drinks are unnecessary, if water
is consumed before, during and after exercise. The vast majority of
active people do not exercise long enough or hard enough to reap
the benefits of rapid hydration that sports drinks provide.
</P>
<P>
   Those who exercise to lose weight should be reminded that every
quart of a sports drink contains 250 calories, so consumers have to
make sure to burn off well over 250 calories during a workout to
create a caloric deficit. It is possible that some people consume
more calories in sports drinks than they burn off during their
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Unless someone loses several pounds of sweat, equivalent to 2
percent or more of body weight, he runs little risk of becoming
dehydrated by drinking water rather than sports drinks. During most
workouts, people do not come close to approaching dehydration nor
do they lose so much sodium in sweat that they need to replenish
sodium during sports.
</P>
<P>
   If a person's urine lacks color and he urinates every two to
four hours, he is adequately hydrated.
</P>
<P>
   NANCY CLARK, M.S., R.D. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Author of ``Nancy Clark's Sports Nutrition Guidebook'' and
director of nutrition services at Sports Medicine Brookline in
Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK
</P>
<P>
   For Gay Teens, a Desperate Cry for Help
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers who are gay or bisexual are more than three times as
likely to attempt suicide as other youth, according to a
Massachusetts study reported this month in The Archives of
Pediatric and Adolescent Medicine. Young men are at particular
risk, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   The lead researcher, Dr. Robert Garofalo, a pediatrician at
Children's Hospital at the Harvard Medical School, also noted that
these young people were more likely to engage in other high risk
behaviors: alcohol consumption, drug and tobacco use and sexual
activities with multiple partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any clinician who works with youth has long suspected that
attempting suicide is an issue for a subset of gay youth,''
Garofalo said. ``I see the results of this study as a cry for
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo and his colleagues looked at self-reported data on
sexual orientation and suicide attempts among students in 9th
through 12th grade who participated in the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention's 1995 Youth Risk Behavior Survey.
Massachusetts was the first state to add a question about sexual
orientation. Answers were optional and anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 4,167 students surveyed, 3.8 percent identified
themselves as gay, lesbian, bisexual or unsure of their sexual
orientation. Researchers found these students were 3.41 times as
likely to report a suicide attempt within the previous year as were
heterosexual students.
</P>
<P>
   The number rose significantly when only young men were
considered. In the overall population, boys tend to commit suicide
more often than girls, the American Academy of Pediatrics says.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David H. Kaplan, a pediatrics professor at the University of
Colorado School of Medicine who is charged with revising the
academy's teen-age suicide policy, believes that solutions are
fundamental.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about engaging kids and making them feel that they
really matter and their thoughts really matter,'' Kaplan said.
``There is lots of homophobia these days, but those kids in a more
accepting environment do a lot better than those kids seen as
freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Beth Jackson
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR
</P>
<P>
   What Fills a Child's Garden of Fears
</P>
<P>
   Things may still go ``bump'' in the night, but school-age
children are actually more afraid of sharks and snakes, according
to an Ohio State University study examining children's fears and
anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved 90 boys and girls 8 to 12 years old and
included interviews with the children, human-figure drawing
analysis and questionnaires gauging anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the children reported 177 fears, and neither sex
appeared to be generally more fearful than the other.
</P>
<P>
   They were most often afraid for their safety, of animals or of
natural phenomena like storms, lightning or thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This age group has pretty vivid imaginations, which are part
of their charm,'' said Dr. Nancy A. Ryan-Wenger, chairwoman of the
department of community, parent, child and psychiatric nursing at
Ohio State University and lead author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're learning to differentiate between reality and fantasy,
but at the same time, they're not really sure that things they
fantasize couldn't happen,'' Dr. Ryan-Wenger said.
</P>
<P>
   Boys said they were more afraid for their safety (74 percent)
and of animals (40 percent) than were the girls (58 percent and 23
percent). Safety fears included people wielding guns or knives,
forced entries into their homes and frightening amusement park
rides.
</P>
<P>
   Animal feared included sharks, snakes, wolves and spiders. Girls
tended to be more afraid of natural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Boys also reported more fears than girls when the topic dealt
with supernatural phenomena like fear of aliens and monsters (14
percent versus 12 percent) and school.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve percent of the boys questioned admitted that they feared
school authority figures and failure, but just 7 percent of the
girls reported having the same fears.
</P>
<P>
   _Alisha Berger
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
