A0509 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-GERRYMANDERING-     05-17 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-GERRYMANDERING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT LIMITS JUDGES ABILITY TO INVALIDATE ELECTION DISTRICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a ruling watched closely by politicians around
the country, the Supreme Court made it harder Monday for judges to
invalidate election districts on the grounds that the state
legislatures setting the boundaries did so largely for racial
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   By forcing judges to be more certain of the role that race plays
before deciding to strike down any reapportionment plan, the
court's unanimous ruling could influence redistricting plans
nationwide after the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case was North Carolina's snake-shaped 12th
Congressional District, which was challenged in federal court as
having been drawn with racial factors as the predominant
consideration _ something the high court has ruled
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A group of white plaintiffs filed a suit in federal court
alleging that the North Carolina legislature drew the district's
boundaries in 1997 in an effort to get minority candidates elected,
violating the equal protection clause of the 14th Amendment, which
bans racial favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   But North Carolina argued that state lawmakers were trying to
draw a congressional district where Democratic voters, not
necessarily black voters, would be in the majority. The fact that
the district created was also heavily African American was merely a
coincidence, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, a three-judge U.S. District Court ruled 2-1 that the
12th District, containing parts of Winston-Salem, was
unconstitutional primarily because the legislature excluded many
adjoining precincts that were heavily Democratic but also largely
white.
</P>
<P>
   After considering the 12th District's shape and racial makeup,
the court made its decision in what lawyers call a ``summary
judgment'' _ which is used when judges feel that the facts in the
case are clear and that a full trial is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the high court reversed that decision, saying the
three-judge panel acted too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas, writing for the court, said the lower
court erred in not holding a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   But he indicated that he agreed with its verdict. ``Evidence
tends to support an inference that the state drew its district
lines to support an impermissible racial motive _ even though ...
(he plaintiffs) presented no direct evidence of intent,'' Thomas
said. ``Summary judgment, however, is appropriate only where there
is no genuine issue of material fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Still, a voting rights specialist at the Washington-based
Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights, said the court's decision,
while ``fairly narrow,'' does give civil rights advocates some
breathing room. ``If the state of North Carolina had lost this
case, it would have been disastrous for the civil rights
movement,'' Still said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time in six years that the high court has
examined the much-studied North Carolina district.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1993 ruling, the justices allowed people to challenge
districts that were ``extremely irregular'' and apparently designed
to ``segregate the races for the purposes of voting.''
</P>
<P>
   The boundaries for the 12th District were first struck down in
1996. At that time, it had a 57 percent majority of blacks among
registered voters. It was 160 miles long and for some stretches had
the width only of Interstate 85.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature redrew the district in 1997, making it wider and
cutting its length to 71 miles. This time blacks comprised 47
percent of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the Supreme Court has issued several redistricting
decisions elsewhere that shot down attempts by state and local
lawmakers to use race as the ``predominant factor'' in drawing
lines to preserve or enhance minority candidates' chances of
winning. Most of those rulings were reached by 5-4 votes that
reflected the court's ideological divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra
Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy united in those
cases to control the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting in those cases were Justices John Paul Stevens, David
H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, those four justices joined in the final result but
not in Thomas' opinion. Stevens wrote separately for the four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record supports the conclusion that most loyal Democrats
living near the borders of District 12 happen to be black
Democrats, and I have no doubt that the legislature was conscious
of that fact when it enacted the apportionment plan,'' Stevens
said. ``But everyone agrees that that fact is not sufficient to
invalidate the district.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina dispute now will return to the three-judge
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at (202) 298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
