<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-VALUES18-COX     05-17 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VALUES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEVEN YEARS AFTER 'MURPHY BROWN,' QUAYLE'S THEMES ARE ECHOING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The value-laden presidential campaign themes of
Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas have a
familiar ring, one that former Vice President Dan Quayle sounded
exactly seven years ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Quayle, himself a candidate for president, returns
to San Francisco to the same podium where he delivered his famous
``Poverty of Values'' _ or ``Murphy Brown'' _ speech, in which he
sounded an alarm over the decline of the two-parent family.
</P>
<P>
   While his 1992 speech to the Commonwealth Club of California was
widely ridiculed, Quayle's message of the importance of family
values in a culture awash in sex, drugs and violence now echoes in
the rhetoric of the presidential front-runners of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Even Quayle critics are now willing to concede that he spoke up
long before other politicians about the loosening of moral moorings
and social bonds in U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what he (Quayle) was saying was constructive,'' House
Democratic leader Dick Gephardt acknowledged, even if the speech
betrayed a nostalgia for the largely fictional ``Father Knows
Best'' America of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of his cut at this was a desire to go back in time,''
said Gephardt. ``But you can't go back. ... So, without discharging
parents of their responsibility, we have to help families succeed
in the modern world.''
</P>
<P>
   What has changed the course of the 2000 presidential campaign is
the recent shooting of high school students in suburban Littleton,
Colo. The deaths of 15 students have had ``a searing effect'' on
the American conscience, said Celinda Lake, a noted pollster and
public opinion analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Pew Research Center in Washington has found that the
tragedy at Columbine High School has evoked an extraordinary level
of public attention. It is the third highest ranked news story of
the decade in the center's survey of public attentiveness, behind
only the Rodney King verdict in 1992 and the crash of TWA Flight
800 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic front-runner, and Bush, the favorite in the
GOP field, have borrowed freely from Bill Clinton's 1992 campaign
and its emphasis on ``opportunity'' and ``responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither candidate took up Clinton's theme of ``community''
until the killings in Colorado sparked a rare period of national
soul-searching over the nature of Americans' obligations to their
children and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gore is talking about reaching beyond government to
integrating the role of community and religious organizations in
addressing social ills, and Bush is touting his record in Texas of
involving private and faith-based organizations in government
social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's commencement address Sunday to Graceland College in
Lamoni, Iowa, sounded as if whole pages came from Quayle. The vice
president noted that parents today lack the ``most precious''
commodity _ ``time with their children ... to teach them right from
wrong, time to pass on their best values.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when there is time, Gore added, ``challenges to the
strength of the family remain,'' mostly from a culture ``of chaotic
value'' _ a culture ``with too much meanness, and not enough
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has yet to venture outside of Austin as a
presidential candidate, his comments in interviews also echo
Quayle's concerns. In a post-Littleton interview with the Los
Angeles Times, for example, he said parenting ``tools'' such as the
television rating system are less important than cultural changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental question is going to be, can America
rededicate itself to parenting as the No. 1 priority for all of
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron insisted Monday that the former
vice president is ``not the kind of guy who says, 'I told you so.'
`` Still, Quayle couldn't resist reminding voters in New Hampshire
last weekend that he pioneered the values debate, at great
political expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's been through the meat grinder?'' Quayle said in Concord.
``Who's back up on his feet fighting for you and has the courage to
get back up and continue the fight for our values and for our
families?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '90s, people laughed him off the stage when he
talked about family values,'' said Mike Robinson, a Concord
businessman who had come to hear Quayle. ``If they took him
seriously back then, we might not have some of the problems we have
now _ like in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
