presidential candidate, his comments in interviews also echo
Quayle's concerns. In a post-Littleton interview with the Los
Angeles Times, for example, he said parenting ``tools'' such as the
television rating system are less important than cultural changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental question is going to be, can America
rededicate itself to parenting as the No. 1 priority for all of
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron insisted Monday that the former
vice president is ``not the kind of guy who says, 'I told you so.'
`` Still, Quayle couldn't resist reminding voters in New Hampshire
last weekend that he pioneered the values debate, at great
political expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's been through the meat grinder?'' Quayle said in Concord.
``Who's back up on his feet fighting for you and has the courage to
get back up and continue the fight for our values and for our
families?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '90s, people laughed him off the stage when he
talked about family values,'' said Mike Robinson, a Concord
businessman who had come to hear Quayle. ``If they took him
seriously back then, we might not have some of the problems we have
now _ like in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
