</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-SEASON-NYT &LR;      05-17 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC EXPANDS DRAMA LINEUP FOR FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC announced a new fall program schedule on Monday that
signaled a significant shift away from half-hour comedies and
toward drama, some based in comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Only two seasons ago NBC had 18 half-hour comedies in prime
time; this fall there will be 10. The network is dropping such
comedies as ``Mad About You,'' ``News Radio,'' ``Caroline in the
City'' and ``Lateline'' and adding only two, ``The Mike O'Malley
Show'' and ``Stark Raving Mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Several NBC executives cited a shortage of strong new comedies
to choose from this spring, partly a result of a boycott by studios
last fall, when NBC tried to force the studios to relinquish some
percentage of ownership of shows or charge NBC a single price for
the lifetime of a show. Normally there is a four-year license
period after which the price can rise.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will also add five dramas, three from producers associated
with NBC's strongest shows. John Wells, executive producer of
``E.R.,'' has two new dramas, ``The West Wing'' and ``Third
Watch.'' Dick Wolf, executive producer of ``Law and Order,'' has a
new drama that NBC wants to associate with that perennial hit: It's
called ``Law and Order: Special Victims Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The best spot for a new series on NBC schedules throughout the
1990s has been Thursday at 9:30 p.m. It still is, although the 9
p.m. comedy ``Frasier'' has proved far more vulnerable there than
``Seinfeld'' ever was, and ``E.R.'' at 10 p.m. has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has mostly wasted the 9:30 slot with such poorly received
fare as ``Veronica's Closet.'' The comedy inheriting the 9:30 spot
this fall will be ``Stark Raving Mad,'' which stars Tony Shalhoub
as a horror novelist and Neil Patrick Harris as his new, extremely
taxed editor. It is created by Steve Levitan of ``Just Shoot Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' (Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m.) stars that
comic as a man who decides at age 30 that it is time to become an
adult.
</P>
<P>
   The drama NBC has highest hopes for is ``The West Wing''
(Wednesday at 9 p.m.), a look behind the scenes at a fictitious
White House. It stars Rob Lowe as the communications aide and
Martin Sheen as the president. It was written by Aaron Sorkin, the
creator of ``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch'' (Sundays at 8 p.m.) traces the lives of
paramedics, firefighters and police officers on the night shift in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special Victims Unit'' (Mondays at 9 p.m.), once called ``Sex
Crimes'' before more cautious thinking prevailed, is about
especially vicious crimes against women and children. One
connection to ``Law and Order'' will have Dann Florek returning to
his role as Capt. Donald Cragen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Feet'' (Fridays at 10 p.m.) is a comic drama about the
relationship among three couples: One are new parents, one just
dating and one just married.
</P>
<P>
   The final drama, ``Freaks and Geeks'' (Saturdays at 8 p.m.), is
one of the new season's near endless parade of shows set in
schools, this one being a comic look at the out crowd in high
school in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had a couple of surprise survivors, including ``Veronica's
Closet,'' which will move to Mondays at 8:30 p.m., and especially
``Jesse,'' which won a second chance on Thursday at 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the NBC fall lineup:
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: 8 p.m., ``Suddenly Susan''; 8:30, ``Veronica's Closet'';
9, ``Law and Order: Special Victims Unit''; 10, ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Third Rock From the Sun''; 8:30, ``The Mike
O'Malley Show''; 9, ``Just Shoot Me''; 9:30, ``Will and Grace'';
10, ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Dateline''; 9, ``The West Wing''; 10, ``Law
and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: 8 p.m., ``Friends''; 8:30, ``Jesse''; 9, ``Frasier'';
9:30, ``Stark Raving Mad''; 10, ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: 8 p.m., ``Providence''; 9 p.m., ``Dateline''; 10, ``Cold
Feet.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: 8 p.m., ``Freaks and Geeks''; 9, ``Pretender''; 10,
``Profiler.''
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: 7 p.m., ``Dateline''; 8, ``Third Watch''; 9, Movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
