<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0538 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNEXPLORED-$ADV23-COX     05-17 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNEXPLORED-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS MILLENNIUM ENDS, SOME PARTS OF EARTH STILL UNEXPLORED
 &HT;    1070&AMP;adds. With UNEXPLORED-CENTURY. Moving in (l) lifestyle and
(i) international categories for release Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The explorers battled fat leeches and cliffsides so
steep and slippery, one false step could mean a plunge of thousands
of feet.
</P>
<P>
   They navigated a raging, treacherous river. They even heard
rumors of the Dugmas, a cult of females who attack outsiders with
snake venom concealed beneath their fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like an Indiana Jones-style adventure, but it was
real.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition, sponsored by the National Geographic Society
last November, took four Americans into the inner gorge of the
Tsangpo River, the world's deepest canyon, in a remote part of
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-day undertaking was a lesson in endurance, but the reward
was extraordinary: the sight of a thundering, 100-foot-high
cascade, dubbed ``Hidden Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's equally extraordinary is that a giant waterfall on a
major river had yet to be recorded. Indeed, on the eve of the 21st
century, there are lots of unexplored spots on the planet _ even in
North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we mapped every single inch of the globe? Certainly, we
have not,'' said Rebecca Martin, director of the National
Geographic Society's Expeditions Board. ``There are nooks and
crannies in the Grand Canyon no one has gotten to.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1888, the National Geographic Society's name is
synonymous with the exploration of exotic places. It publishes the
magazines National Geographic and National Geographic Traveler, and
recently launched National Geographic Adventure, designed to tell
readers ``where to get once-in-a-lifetime experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the world seems to have grown a lot smaller over the
last two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   It was only in 1806 that two American explorers, Meriwether
Lewis and William Clark, became the first people to traipse across
North America and reach the Pacific. In the early part of this
century, many large patches of jungle in Asia and Africa had not
been visited by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, explorers have reached the highest mountain (Everest,
29,029 feet), the deepest ocean (Mariana Trench in the Pacific,
35,839 feet), and the coldest ice field (Polyus Nedostupnosti,
Antarctica, minus 72 F annual mean).
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades it has seemed as though every far-off locale
has been charted, visited, or analyzed ad nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they've even been decimated. As more and more people
explore the Amazon, scientists estimate that up to 16 percent of
the original million-square-mile rain forest has been ravaged.
</P>
<P>
   These days, adventure travel is the rage. Growing numbers of
tourists trek through the Himalayas, while 10,000 tourists visited
Antarctica, the most isolated place on the planet, between November
and March. This year alone, National Geographic Expeditions will
escort travelers to sites as far-flung as the peaks of Nepal and
the Yangtze River in China.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all this, hundreds, if not thousands, of peaks and
mountain passes are still waiting to be mapped.
</P>
<P>
   From Tibet to New Guinea, to central Greenland and remote
reaches of Nahanni National Park in Canada's Northwest Territories,
to the Arctic and Antarctica, there are a host of sites that have
been accessible only to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, explorers haven't completely roamed the Ndoki forest,
on the border of Congo and Cameroon. They haven't fully surveyed
New Guinea, the world's second-largest island after Greenland. And
they haven't scaled all the mountains in the Antarctic, half as big
as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the Holy Grail of exploration is perhaps the ocean. The sea
covers 70 percent of the Earth's surface, and 80 percent of it _
packed with little-known plant and animal life _ remains
undiscovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can draw a parallel between the ocean and outer space,
because there's so much we still don't know about them,'' Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back on land _ or beneath it _ underwater caves hold a wealth of
opportunities for discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The world's longest underwater cave is Nohoch Nah Chich, located
in Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula. So far, only 32 miles have been
charted. Divers believe there's much more to be documented, but the
pitch-black labyrinth can be deadly for a diver who becomes lost
and confused.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, a National Geographic team is creating a
three-dimensional computer map of tens of thousands of feet of
submerged caves at Wakulla Springs, about 15 miles south of
Tallahassee, Fla. The vast network of caverns and grottoes is
believed to be the third largest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This digital mapping is wonderful, and it's going to help
people figure out how groundwater travels throughout Florida,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mountaintops symbolize the spirit of exploration. All 14 of the
world's mountains higher than 8,000 meters, or 26,250 feet, have
been scaled.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Everest was conquered in 1953 by Sir Edmund Hillary and
his Sherpa guide, Tenzing Norgay. The famous mountain has been
climbed so many times that today's challenge comes in trying to
break the endurance record. The current record was set this month
by a Nepali Sherpa, Babu Chiri Sherpa, 33, who spent 21 hours on
the summit.
</P>
<P>
   But mountaineers shouldn't be disheartened, because there are
still plenty of peaks waiting to be mastered.
</P>
<P>
   An abundance of unclimbed summits rise above 25,000 feet
throughout the Karakoram mountain range in Pakistan, near the
borders with Afghanistan and China. Another unclimbed peak is
Lhotse Middle, at 27,605 feet, in the Lhotse massif near Mount
Everest.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The higher the mountain, the more discoveries explorers seem to
reap.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, National Geographic announced the discovery of
three children found sacrificed atop Argentina's Mount
Llullaillaco, the world's highest archaeological site at 22,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Located under about five feet of rock and earth, the perfectly
preserved bodies apparently had been frozen for more than 500
years, leaving them to appear as though they had just been buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appear the best preserved of any mummy I've seen,'' said
archaeologist Johan Reinhard, co-leader of the team that discovered
them. ``Their arms looked perfect, even down to visible hairs.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's most uncharted places is the island of New
Guinea, north of Australia. The eastern part of the island is
occupied by the nation of Papua New Guinea, while the western part
is Irian Jaya, a province of Indonesia where up to 800 languages
are spoken by primitive tribes living on jungle-choked terrain.
</P>
<P>
   One researcher who has roamed Papua New Guinea is Bill Thomas,
an anthropologist who grew up in Youngstown, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   When he's there, he lives among the Hewa, eating mostly bananas
and sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I am over there, sometimes I forget what a privilege it
is to be in a place like that,'' said Thomas, 44, who's been
studying the effect of human activities on conservation. ``But when
I'm dead and gone, I'll have done something you only dream about
when you're a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While enthusiasm for exploration certainly hasn't diminished
through the years, what has changed is the nature of exploration.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the main goal was to find remote places that had
never before been walked on by a human foot. The emphasis now is on
being the first to examine and document sites, even those that have
been visited before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of explorers who've been in the most incredibly dense
rain forests in South America and hostile desert in Asia where they
couldn't imagine any human had ever walked before, but how can we
be sure?'' Martin asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important now is that people go out and record what
they see, and to share that with others,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After National Geographic announced November's discovery of
Hidden Falls, explorers from Arizona claimed that they had already
visited the lush, subtropical oasis reminiscent of the paradise
depicted in the 1937 Frank Capra movie classic, ``Lost Horizon,''
which made Shangri-la a household word.
</P>
<P>
   China didn't open the area to Westerners until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic officials have never denied that other
explorers had been in the gorge, but insist their expedition was
meant to conclusively document the legendary waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Barbara Moffet said dueling discoveries are nothing
new, pointing out that Christopher Columbus didn't really discover
America, although he's often credited for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one spot no one will ever fight over is Mount Kailas in
southwestern Tibet, a 4-mile-high pyramid of ice and rock.
</P>
<P>
   The peak is regarded as the home of Shiva, god of destruction
and rebirth, and is the most sacred summit on Earth for both Hindus
and Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
   For now, climbing the mountain is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
