<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   GULF-POPULAR _ It use to be that business jets were considered
an unecessary perk. Now, the global economy demands that company
executives be able to hop on one at the drop of a hat to seal a
deal or check on global operations. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/GULFSTREAM _ Gulfstream's announcement that it will be
acquired by General Dynamics in a $5.3 billion deal caps a strong
decade for the company that has become a leader in the high-end,
big cabin business jet market. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MARINER _ Mariner, an Atlanta-based operator of more than 400
nursing homes, announced results for the second quarter. The
company has been in financial difficulty. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SECURITY-FIRST _ Security First Technologies, a provider of
Internet-based software for the financial services industry,
willpurchase FICS and Edify to create a $1.4 billion company to
provide financial portal solutions for financial institutions. The
company also announced a $50 million investment from Intuit. Under
the agreement, Security First will be able to offer Intuit's
software (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CONSUMERS _ WASHINGTON _ FCC chief William Kennard, AOL CEO
Steve Case and Bell Atlantic CEO Ivan Seidenberg review
``Information Technology: Consumer Friend or Foe'' at National
Consumers League 100th anniversary conference. (Glass, Cox News
Service) ETA: 5 p.m. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0518 _ Sound reproduction for popular enjoyment has
come a long way since World War II. Today the options are numerous,
from the head-rattling bass systems youths install in cars to
``Star Wars'' banks of speakers in family rooms. (Holsendolph,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes one 5-column color
illustration of a man listening to his stereo speakers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS _ Even some of those who don't use Macs are
falling in love with Apple Computer. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes one 1-column color photo of an
Epson printer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY _ Over the weekend, I turned my PC into a
shortwave radio. For $300, I added on a computerized shortwave
radio. For the money, you get a radio that performs just about as
well as the fancy $2,000 shortwave transceiver I use in my ham
radio hobby. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1
column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRENDS _ A Texas company is making mice with personalities
_ custom-designed mechanisms with color, odd shapes and designs.
(Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes 2-column color
photo of man holding differently colored mice.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Keeping your computer security tight.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Internet/Intranet
Design Shop Gold offers a great Web page program. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: The downside to
online retail. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Online TV
listings. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ News on Apple and its products. This week: Apple's
Claris Home Page is helpful for both HTML novices and experts.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments. This
week: Sylvan site encourages kids to read; parents have mixed
feelings about kids exploring the Internet. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ This column will not move today.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS-CAMERA _ If you were lucky enough to give birth on
Mother's Day, the coincidence probably made an already magical
event even more special. The people at Kodak want to help you
celebrate the occasion by sending you a free camera to capture
images of the new addition to your family. And the camera they're
offering is one of the sweetest little gadgets I've seen in years.
Kodak sent a sample of its Advantix T550 camera, and the camera is
incredibly simple to use, it takes good pictures under a variety of
conditions, it's smaller than a pack of cigarettes and about as
lightweight and it takes pictures in three formats: classic, group
and panoramic. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 8. MOVED
</P>
