<P>
   MARILYNQUAYLE _ ATLANTA _Marilyn Quayle, wife of the
presidential candidate, speaks at the KSU ``Powerchicks
Conference.'' (Farber, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (Tentative)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ With the state GOP convention coming
up this weekend in Augusta, we reflect on last weeBig community
activist/civil rights love fest at Atlanta City Hall Monday, as hip
hop group OutKast presents $2,500 check to long-time voter
registration organizer Ella Mae Brayboy, as mayor, in turn,
recognized OutKast for community efforts. Meanwhile civil rights
icon Rosa Park is suing OutKast for writing a song about her
without permission. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-BYRD-FAMILY_ AUSTIN, Texas _After initial disappointment, a
relative of James Byrd Jr., a black man dragged to his death nearly
a year ago, on Monday said his family is angry that a proposal law
named in his uncle's honor will not pass this session. Darrell
Verrett was in Austin during much of last week's struggle between
Democrats and Republicans trying to find a compromise on the bill,
which would have written the state law to enhance crimes based on
bias against the victim. The Byrd family scheduled a news
conference in Jasper Tuesday to express their disappointment and
anger and to announce that they will return to Austin as often as
necessary to get a better hate-crimes law approved. (Elizondo,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   PAULA-JONES (6-8 inches) _ Boca Raton, Fla. _ Paula Jones'
husband and PR person are upset with a Boca man who runs the Paula
Jones Celebrity Psychic Network. Apparently Paula signed a release,
allowing the company to use her name for a one-time $15,000 fee.
Her husband told the N.Y. Daily News she's just so naive. The Boca
man has nine different 900 numbers for similar psychic services.
Jones' number cost $3.99 a minute. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
