<SLUG> BC-TV-BABY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFUL BABY? JUST WAIT TILL SHE'S A SEXY 6-YEAR-OLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(dal) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who are the main players in the country's proliferating baby
beauty contests? The stars, those painted, besequined tots whose
routines owe a lot to Las Vegas and more than a little to the
strippers of yesteryear? Their mothers, who are also their managers
and taskmistresses? The entrepreneurs who make a living out of
show-biz hopefuls, 3 million of them, age 3 months to 16 years?
</P>
<P>
   The question is not resolved in ``Baby Beauty Contests,''
Tuesday night's edition of ``Inside Story.'' But the hour offers
enough glimpses of events with names like Royalty Miss Pageant to
capture the heavy emotional investment of all parties in what
enthusiasts call tournaments and critics call travesties.
</P>
<P>
   The California families we meet do not seem to have cash to
throw around, yet the expense of fielding a tournament contender is
considerable: singing, modeling and hip-swiveling lessons;
costumes, hairdos, cosmetics, publicity portraits and other
essentials. And it's not just a sometime thing. One pageant hopper
says she spends $20,000 a year in hopes of getting some prize money
for her daughter or at least a trophy for Best Smile.
</P>
<P>
   All the mothers assert that for them winning is not the point.
The point, they say, is to give their little girls a good time. But
not every contestant seems to be having a good time; a few need a
bit of coercing to do their numbers, and one decides that the show
doesn't have to go on and stops in mid-performance.
</P>
<P>
   And not every mother is a good loser. One whose 14-year-old
didn't get first place in a pageant's Elegant Division has to have
her expletives deleted. ``Mom,'' her daughter says, ``you're mad
because I didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the participants, the contests are exhilarating high
points in family life. Less involved viewers may be a little
depressed at the exhibitions of young children, all dolled up and
drained of spontaneity, going through casino-lounge motions.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INSIDE STORY: Baby Beauty Queens'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, at 9 Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Shari Solomon. Steven Rosenbaum, executive producer.
Produced by BNN for A&AMP;E Network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
