<HEADLINE>
DON'T LOOK FOR THREEPEAT OF APRIL BUDGET FIGURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If expert prognostications are on target, Friday's Treasury
report won't be a repeat of the pleasant surprises of the past two
Aprils. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there probably was a significant federal budget
surplus for the month because of the tax-filing deadline, but it
isn't expected to be nearly the magnitude of those recorded in 1997
and 1998. Last year's April surprise totaled nearly $125 billion,
which topped the previous record of nearly $94 million set in April
1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if this year's April surplus isn't nearly as large,
however, it still should be more than enough to wipe out the $50
billion in red ink accumulated during the first six months of
fiscal 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April's huge budget surpluses of the past two years resulted not
only from rising personal incomes and corporate earnings, but also
from investors' taking some profits from their stock market gains
of recent years. April's tax collections also are considered one of
the year's most useful forecasting tools for anticipating full-year
budget results. This year's budget surplus is currently forecast to
come in at about $111 billion. &QL; 
Monday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Home Builders survey for May is due
for release. &QL; 
Tuesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another uneventful meeting is expected when the Federal Open
Market Committee convenes to mull monetary policy. As long as
inflation remains under control and the global economy remains
weak, monetary tightening isn't expected. Nor is loosening likely
as long as the U.S. economy remains strong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Housing starts are forecast to have eased slightly in April,
but the expert consensus also calls for a companion report on
building permits to show the same level of activity as the previous
month. The annual rate for starts is expected to be 1.75 million,
which would be a 1.1 percent decline, while permit issuance is
predicted to have remained at a 1.65-million-a-year rate. &QL; 
Thursday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another huge deluge of red ink is forecast when the
international trade balance for March is reported. Most analysts
expect the shortfall to be less than February's record $19.4
billion, and the consensus calls for a deficit of about $18
billion. If the call is accurate, it will bring the first quarter's
trade imbalance to more than $52 billion. &QL; 
Eye on the economy
</P>
<P>
   --Tuesday: No surprises from the Fed
</P>
<P>
   --Thursday: More trade red ink
</P>
<P>
   --Friday: No April revenue surprise
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
