<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENDRICKS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONE THAT DIDN'T GET AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE HENDRICKS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the substitute column for the one I intended to write
but put off because I didn't want to spoil my perfect day doing
something unimportant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like working. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You don't blow a perfect day if you don't have to. How often do
perfect days occur, anyhow? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About once a year, if you're lucky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet 99 out of 100 of us are too honest to call in sick on those
days, or don't even notice the day's perfection until it's too late
and we're chugging down the interstate, sucking in exhaust fumes
when we dare open the car window for a whiff of the perfect day
that got away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me of that other column. Not bad. I'd done all the
interviews, checked all the facts, experimented with a catchy
opening or two. A couple of lines, I figure, you'll cherish for two
or three seconds _ and the points made might even provoke some to
write their congressman or kick the dog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it can wait. Because on the morning I arose to write that
column, I realized something extraordinary had arrived with the
dawn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The perfect day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sky was the bluest I'd ever seen. Bluer than the rinse in
grandma's hair. Bluer than a bottle of Windex, bluer than ... gee,
I can't think of it right now, but it'll come to me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And in this blue-rinse, Windex sky was not a cloud, not a jet
trail marring its perfection. The high was to be 75 perfect
degrees. The car perfectly sparkled. The grass, already cut.
Perfectly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So there was no choice, it being May and all _ the perfect
month. I had to do the perfect thing. I had to go to the ball
game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sportswriters have to go to ball games, too, but it's different
with them. They have to go to ball games, otherwise what will they
write about? They'll write about their favorite TV highlights
shows, or revenue sharing, or they'll reminisce about seeing ball
games with Dad back in olden days when the players carved their
bats with bowie knives and fashioned mitts from worn-out Army
boots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness sportswriters go to ball games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Me, I had to go to the ball game for another reason. Where else
was I going to find cotton candy for my youngest kid on the perfect
day? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so we headed to the ballpark about noon, got a perfect
parking spot, and on this perfect day as we stood on line at the
box office, something perfect had to happen. And it did, of
course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A woman rushed up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, can you use these tickets?'' she asked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, we could. And as luck would have it, the
free seats were in the lower part of the upper deck -- section 310
-- just to the right of home plate. The view of the field and the
water spectacular was -- what else? -- perfect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free tickets meant there was more money left for hot dogs and
Polish sausages, which anyone knows are perfection at the ballpark
and the perfect first course before one partakes of the cotton
candy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which came in your choice of two flavors: pink or blue. And
there it was. The perfect image to stick up there in paragraph
nine. The sky was bluer than the cotton candy sold at Kauffman
Stadium in Kansas City, Mo., on a day that would have been perfect
beyond imagination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If only the Royals had won. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, you learn to cherish such days, fold them up in your
memory like love letters. Get them out and reflect upon them when
you awake some morning to find that the day ahead is not perfect at
all, but dark and forbidding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or worse, that it's Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
