<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0573 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNPAID-TAXES-ART-2TAK     05-17 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNPAID-TAXES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS COLLECTION EFFORTS DROP IN WAKE OF TAXPAYER PROTECTION LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service tax collectors, under intense pressure
from Congress to be nicer to taxpayers, have drastically scaled
back efforts to collect unpaid taxes, newly available statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
   Seizures of property are down 98 percent over the last two
years, according to the IRS. Levies and garnishments of bank
accounts and paychecks are just one-fourth the level of two years
ago. And the filing of tax liens, which make sure that back taxes
are paid when a property is sold, are down two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the drop-off in enforcement is because the IRS has been
shifting some resources to pay for customer service, new computers
and retraining. But IRS officers in six states said in interviews
that the biggest reason for the retreat was their fear of being
dismissed for running afoul of a new law intended to protect
taxpayers from overzealous collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some tax preparers are telling clients that they can
use the law to thwart collection of overdue taxes altogether, IRS
revenue officers and outside tax experts said. One tax preparer,
for example, threatened to bring a harassment claim if a collection
agent did not accept the preparer's terms for settling a case, said
Phyllis Vidler, president of the National Treasury Employees Union
local in Detroit, which represents IRS workers in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' fears prompted Charles O. Rossotti, the tax
commissioner, to send a memo with the March paychecks for the IRS's
98,000 employees assuring them that their jobs were safe unless
they willfully abused taxpayers' rights. On May 5, Rossotti issued
regulations aimed at carrying out the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The law says that IRS employees must be dismissed if, following
an administrative inquiry, they are found to have committed any of
10 acts, among them violating any constitutional or civil right of
a taxpayer, threatening an audit for personal gain, making a false
statement under oath or falsifying or destroying documents to
conceal mistakes. None of these provisions specify that conduct
must be willful, although others do, such as willfully cheating on
taxes or lying to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Tax experts who have worried that Congress overreacted to
complaints about the IRS said that the drop in collection efforts
would lead to widespread tax evasion if some balance was not
quickly restored to the political climate surrounding the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dumb law,'' said one critic, Donald C. Alexander, the
Nixon administration tax commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, now a Washington tax lawyer, said the fall-off in
collections was causing alarm among IRS executives. ``When someone
can fail to meet his or her tax obligations without a worry about
having enforcement actions taken, then other creditors are going to
come in first and get paid, and the deadbeat taxpayer wins,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for William V. Roth Jr., the Delaware Republican
who as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee was a principal
sponsor of the new law, said he saw no problems with its
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the senator's intention was not to either frighten
good IRS employees or encourage tax evasion,'' said the
spokeswoman, Ginny Flynn. ``His intention was to insure that IRS
employees do not treat either their colleagues or taxpayers
unfairly and to ensure that the tax commissioner can deal with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax collectors who act properly have noting to fear, she added,
``because the law requires proof, not just an accusation'' of a
violation.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp decline in collections comes as the agency is in the
midst of a cultural revolution whose success, Rossotti has warned,
is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the problems of collection, many veteran auditors
have chafed, for example, at being pulled off examining tax returns
to answer telephone calls from taxpayers. Other employees say that
Rossotti is naive and fails to realize how many taxpayers cheat,
requiring costly collection efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, meanwhile, has frozen the IRS budget just when
Rossotti is seeking billions of dollars to build new computer
systems, retrain the agency's staff and recruit managers from
outside the government. Some of the money to finance these moves
has come from scaling back audits and collection efforts, officials
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, who ran a successful computer consulting firm before
joining the government, gently suggested that IRS employees were
overreacting to the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to denigrate the fears and concerns of front-line
employees,'' he said, ``but the reality is that this law deals with
willful and serious misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In the six months ended March 31, the IRS seized property to
satisfy long overdue taxes 108 times, down from 1,150 seizures in
the comparable period a year earlier and 5,000 seizures two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Garnishments of paychecks and levies of bank accounts in the
latest six months fell to 458,000, down from 1.8 million two years
earlier. Liens, which ensure that taxes are paid when property is
sold, fell to 98,000, compared with 272,000 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS is expected to collect about $1.7 trillion this year,
with less than 2 percent, or about $30 billion, from enforcement
actions such as issuing liens, levies and seizing property.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS begins collection efforts after a taxpayer has failed to
pay taxes or to turn over taxes withheld from workers' paychecks.
But instead of stepping up pressure, one tax collector said, ``with
this new law if somebody says `I'm not paying,' then we just say
thank you and leave.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a revenue officer today I would have great hesitance
to take any enforcement action,'' said Alexander, the former IRS
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Richardson, the Clinton administration's first tax
commissioner, said that ``there is a lot of healthy skepticism''
among tax collectors about Rossotti's promise that only willful
acts will result in dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners who are habitually late turning over taxes
withheld from workers' paychecks also have begun using the law to
derail collection of overdue taxes, said Mrs. Vidler, the union
official, and other veteran tax collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want to pay your taxes today all you have to do
is say two magic words: installment agreement,'' said one IRS
collection officer in Washington state who spoke on condition of
anonymity because he feared retaliation by supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just say you want one, and even if the terms you propose
are ridiculous _ like $10 a week when you owe tens of thousands _
collection stops while your proposal goes up and down the chain of
managers, until 90 days later you are told no,'' the IRS employee
said. ``Then you just need to say another magic word _ harassment _
and because of this new law, the collection process stops while
your complaint gets reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, a Nebraska Democrat, noted that the provisions
of the new law relating to agency employees' conduct were not among
those recommended by a congressional commission that he co-chaired
on reforming the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to change at least four or five of the 10 items in
this law, or reform just isn't going to work,'' Kerrey said,
``because it creates a disincentive for IRS people to do their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   One veteran tax collector in Manhattan said he and others were
troubled that the new law mandated dismissals for several acts even
if willful misconduct was not proven _ including violations of the
Age Discrimination Act of 1975 or ``falsifying or destroying
documents to conceal mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You say `intentional,' I say honest mistake,'' this tax
collector said. ``I'm not going to risk my job on that, and I don't
believe anyone else would either.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   IRS agents and officials of their union point to the case of a
revenue officer in White Plains. The woman, they say, is under
investigation by the Treasury Department's inspector general
because her activity log failed to note whether she had included a
particular form in a delinquency notice she sent to a taxpayer. The
notice was returned by the post office as undeliverable because the
taxpayer had moved, said Frank Heffler, president of the local
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing happened here but a simple mistake of no consequence,
but now there are two inspectors working on this, and the revenue
officer fears she will lose her job,'' he said. ``Given the trouble
you can get into over a work log, I don't know anyone who would
execute a property seizure and risk their job.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, the tax commissioner, said the new law ``did create a
lot of concern and anxiety among many employees, understandably,
because it affects every one of them and some of the provisions are
rather complex.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in addition to his March memo, he is trying to
instill in IRS managers ``the difference between accidental versus
intentional mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Richardson, the Clinton administration's first tax
commissioner, said tax collectors are responding to the signals
sent by Rossotti.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big message is in the new IRS mission statement, which
says nothing about collecting taxes,'' she said. ``That was a
powerful message to the organization, to people who don't want to
pay and to unscrupulous tax professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   The new mission statement, written by Rossotti, says that the
IRS should ``provide America's taxpayers top-quality service by
helping them understand and meet their tax responsibilities and by
applying the tax law with integrity and fairness to all.''
</P>
<P>
   Montie Day, a former IRS criminal investigator and federal
prosecutor who now regularly sues the IRS on behalf of taxpayers,
said that Rossotti should take forceful action to restore
collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically there is no enforcement going on right now, and that
undermines the whole tax system,'' he said. ``And as word about
this gets out two things will happen: People who are inclined to
cheat will say to themselves that since they aren't going to be
made to pay up, they should cheat. And people who are inclined to
pay as the law requires will ask themselves, `Why am I doing
this?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
