A0576 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COLONIAL-GOLF'SFU     05-17 2965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-GOLF'SFUTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES LEAVE GOLF ON AN UNSURE COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ A fresh century beckons, causing havoc in the
computer industry and distress for executives unsure if their
company's software is Y2K compatible heading into a new millennium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But on the golf course, production is recorded with pencil and
paper, not megabytes and microchips. The primary mode of
transportation, at least during the MasterCard Colonial, is
footpower _ a method impervious to meltdown from an impending
computer glitch. Tools of the trade involve manufactured goods, not
software programs.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the growth industries in the United States, golf would
seem to be among the best-insulated from the impending threat of
global chaos some analysts predict when our clocks strike midnight
and our computers crash in unison on Jan. 1, 2000. Scratch the
surface, however, and there are plenty of issues that concern
professional golfers and tournament executives as the game heads
into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Call them the Y2K worries of the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   They might not be obvious to fans who attend the MasterCard
Colonial, where tournament rounds run Thursday-Sunday at Colonial
Country Club. But they weigh on the minds of competitors and
organizers who will spend this week at ``Hogan's Alley.'' They
figure to be determining factors in how long professional golf
continues to ride the wave that has seen PGA Tour events enjoy
rampant increases in attendance, television ratings and purses over
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the messiest potential minefield in the 21st century
involves a perceived need to curb technological advances in golf
equipment to prevent today's courses from becoming obsolete. The
issue is so hot, a lawyer with three decades of experience in
golf-related issues predicts an impending ``Armageddon'' between
manufacturers and the game's governing bodies over this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a major confrontation. It's the biggest
thing facing golf,'' said Leonard Decof, lead counsel in helping
Ping win the right to keep square-grooved clubs on the PGA Tour
after a court challenge was dropped in 1993 by then-commissioner
Deane Beman.
</P>
<P>
   Others consider the World Golf Championships, which debut this
season, as the biggest storm cloud on the horizon. Because their $5
million purses tend to drain the talent pools at surrounding events
on the PGA Tour calendar, many tournament organizers view the WGC
stops as a threat to the continued health and well-being of events
such as the Colonial and the GTE Byron Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are moving, I'm very concerned,'' said Wally
Schmuck, a past Colonial president and former tournament chairman.
``The \RWGC\S tournaments are going to impact a lot of events.
That's a reality. I just hope they never put one in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf officials also worry about:
</P>
<P>
   Finding enough title sponsors to meet the demand for upwardly
spiraling purses mandated by the PGA Tour's four-year, $650 million
television contract that expires after the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring a way to improve on the next round of TV negotiations
after doubling the take from a $325 million deal that expired in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way to appease a splinter group, the Tour Players
Association, that offers the potential for labor unrest in a sport
that has experienced little labor-related strife.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of moving parts to this thing, and every day,
they're going faster,'' said Patrick McEvoy, chairman for the 2000
Nelson Classic. ``I talk to people who look at all the uncertainty
and say, `It's going to be pretty wild in the next five years.' But
I think it's already wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel with us as we peer into our dimpled, crystal ball and try
to discern how various turn-of-the-century concerns will affect the
foreseeable future of professional golf: \Nsubheds:Technology
Clearly the game's hot-button topic, players and administrators
remain divided on what safeguards _ if any _ are needed to prevent
the next generation of golfers from overwhelming existing layouts
with equipment that allows them to hit longer, straighter shots
with greater margin for error than their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the topics being studied by members of the U.S. Golf
Association, regulator of equipment-related issues in the United
States, is placing a limit on the ``spring-like effect'' derived
from the club face of metal-headed drivers. The organization also
is studying a measure to eliminate the use of long putters, limit
shaft lengths on drivers and put a loft limit on clubs used in
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA's goal, said executive director David Fay, is ``to
establish a standard and draw a line'' that ensures technological
advances do not outstrip shot-making abilities in determining a
player's score.
</P>
<P>
   A noble goal, say proponents. A move long overdue, says Gary
Player, 63, who joins Ben Hogan, Jack Nicklaus and Gene Sarazen on
the short list of players to win all four of professional golf's
major championships during their PGA Tour careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way, any more, to compare the scores of today to
the scores that Ben Hogan shot. Technology is ruining the game, and
we have to do something about it,'' said Player, who likes Jack
Nicklaus' suggestion to make PGA Tour participants play with a
uniform ball that would limit compression, spin and ball flight.
</P>
<P>
   Without crimping today's technology, organizers of some PGA Tour
events fear that many of today's golf courses will become obsolete
before young stars such as David Duval and Tiger Woods are eligible
to hit their first 320-yard drives on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has got to be done with technology. Enough is
enough,'' said Phil Thomas, Colonial tournament chairman. ``I think
the PGA Tour will be the one that does something, when we finally
get some restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But something's got to give. You can't go and rebuild these
golf courses we already have. And you can't just keep building
newer, longer golf courses to play tournaments on. To find enough
land, you'll get them so far out of town that people will need
choppers to get to the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk rankles Decof, who represents Callaway Golf, one of
the nation's leading manufacturers of metal-headed drivers. He
considers attempts to limit driving distance ``misdirected''
despite the fact that three rounds of 59 have been recorded at PGA
Tour or Nike Tour events in the past 12 months. Until last May,
only two 59s had been shot in the history of professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   For those consumed with scoring records, Decof offers this
rejoinder: The PGA Tour's season scoring record remains 68.33, a
mark set by Byron Nelson in 1945. That was before the advent of
graphite shafts or metal woods, he said, making fears about
technology outstripping the game ``groundless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the USGA wants to try to do something about it, the ball
will be in their court,'' Decof said, pun clearly intended. ``There
will be ... Armageddon between the manufacturers and the USGA
unless there is some type of accommodation.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Daniel, a member of the LPGA Hall of Fame, prefers a limit
on future technology. She called for the USGA to take corrective
action or step aside and ``let the game go to another level,'' with
an inevitable flood of scoring records to follow as players become
bigger and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equipment bunches players. It's taken a lot of shot-making out
of the game,'' Daniel said. ``Now, you just aim at the pin and go,
which I don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   With today's rules, said Daniel, she can tailor her equipment to
meet the conditions of the day. It's something she does to remain
competitive but a loophole that Daniel would prefer to see closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a high-ball hitter,'' Daniel said. ``But if I'm playing in
the wind, I can use a lower-flying ball and special shafts to
offset that. It's easier to keep the ball down, and I don't need to
use any special ability to make the ball do something to get it to
do what I want. It helps my score, but I'd rather see people have
to play shots and work the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, author of professional golf's most recent 59 _ a
final-round effort to win the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic on Jan. 24
_ said a fresh wave of improvements to equipment would not bother
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's always taken advantage of what's the most advanced
technological equipment they could find. I have no problem with
that,'' said Duval, 27, a four-event winner on the 1999 PGA Tour.
``Nobody mentions that technology has gone into the equipment that
preps golf courses, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers from yesteryear, said Duval, ``didn't play greens that
were as hard or fast as we do. The rough was never as thick. The
fairways are tighter now. It all balances out.'' \Nsubheds:World
Golf Championships Despite an explosive growth in purses, which has
seen payouts for both the Colonial ($2.8 million) and the Nelson
($3 million) double since 1995, officials at both events wonder if
the extra dollars will continue to attract the type of marquee
players that Fort Worth-Dallas fans have grown to expect on an
annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point is the emergence of the World Golf
Championships, a series of high-dollar competitions between elite
competitors from all tours. The 1999 schedule includes three WGC
tournaments, each with a $5 million purse. A fourth event will be
added next season. More could follow in future years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, the biggest change in how we do our business
will come from the WGC events,'' said Frank Houseman, Nelson
tournament chairman in 1996-97 and current president of the
Salesmanship Club, which oversees the event. ``Who knows if, in
five years, there will be enough money out there that guys will
just play the four majors, The Players Championship, the Tour
Championship and the \RWGC\S events? Right now, that would be 10
tournaments, and they could make plenty of money just playing in
those. I hope that doesn't happen, but the concern is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Created by PGA Tour officials as an inducement to get the game's
best players together more frequently, the concept has an inherent
flaw, said Colonial champ Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' said Watson, ``is this will reduce the
number of tournaments players play on their respective tours.''
</P>
<P>
   In a roundabout way, Colonial officials already have felt a
backlash from a heightened emphasis on global golf. Five
high-profile members of the PGA Tour, including Woods and British
Open champ Mark O'Meara, are skipping Colonial to accept six-figure
appearance fees while competing this week at the Deutsche Bank-SAP
Open, a European Tour event in Heidelburg, Germany. Other absentees
include Ernie Els, Jesper Parnevik and Nick Price, the 1994
Colonial champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you can prevent that,'' said Schmuck, noting
the long-standing ban on appearance fees for players at PGA Tour
events. ``You just hope this is a one-year deal and that the
sponsor can't afford to keep paying those type of appearance fees,
year after year.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger concern, say Colonial and Nelson officials, would be
having a WGC event moved into a May slot on the PGA Tour calendar.
The WGC's match-play event in February relegated the Tucson Open,
played during the same week, to cable television and decimated the
field at the next tour stop, the Doral-Ryder Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd hate to be the tournament right behind or right before
one of those,'' Thomas said of the WGC tournaments. ``With the way
those events are placed, I don't think they will affect us today.
But I'm not going to say they won't in the future.''
\Nsubheds:Television and title sponsorships Minimizing the impact
of the WGC era on a traditional tour stop, say tournament
officials, will require solid television ratings and a long-term
commitment from a title sponsor. Both local events qualify in both
areas, placing them among the in-crowd on a PGA Tour calendar that
many envision to be divided between the ``haves'' and ``have-nots''
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Houseman predicted the Nelson, which offered a $1.5 million
purse in 1996, will hit $3.5 million next year and $4 million by
2002, the final year of the tournament's existing television
contract with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials vow they will be in the same neighborhood,
leaning on a long-term agreement with MasterCard (through 2002) and
enviable TV ratings to keep them in what Thomas termed ``the top
tier'' of tour events behind the major championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dedicated to being there and they \RMasterCard\S are
dedicated to seeing that we stay there,'' Thomas said. ``We
couldn't be happier with our arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Other tournaments caught bouncing between sponsors, like the
Compaq Classic of New Orleans, figure to face tough sledding in the
current climate. The New Orleans event changed title sponsors in
February. A Boston-based event was dropped from the 1999 schedule
after losing its title sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the next two years will be critical for the smaller
tournaments,'' said Paul Pulliam, who will be the Nelson chairman
in 2001. ``People have to make a commitment to try and keep up with
the WGC events or decide, `We can't get there' and move to another
level. To say which ones might fall back would be real difficult.
But there's no question the best places to be are in areas with a
big corporate base. With so many businesses in Dallas-Fort Worth,
that gives us and the Colonial an edge over a lot of tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   The local events will maintain that edge, Houseman predicted, as
long as they retain the two T's of survival in the 21st century: TV
ratings and title sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you put on a good show for TV and make your sponsor
happy, you're OK,'' Houseman said. ``If you lose the support of
either or both, your tournament could be in trouble.''
\Nsubheds:Labor relations Because PGA Tour participants are
independent contractors, they are not eligible for certification as
a labor union. That removes any threat of a labor strike.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped a group of golfers, known as the Tour
Players Association (TPA), from banding together and questioning
the direction the PGA Tour is headed as the 21st century
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Edwards is president of the group, which claims membership
of more than 50 but had only 14 players attend its January meeting.
Among its goals, said Edwards, is to bring golf salaries more in
line _ on a percentage basis _ with those of athletes in other
professional sports. TPA members also seek to gain a greater input
into the tour's financial dealings and have succeeded in laying the
groundwork for a new bonus system, proposed for next season, that
would help defray the cost of travel expenses for players who
finish in the top 125 on the 1999 money list.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards conceded TPA membership has been ``difficult to sell''
to peers because golf is riding a wave of increased purses and
increased popularity. But the numbers, he said, are undeniable:
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Jack Nicklaus led the PGA Tour in earnings ($305,463)
at a time when only 22 major-league baseball players earned more
than $100,000 and the average salary of those players was $133,000.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Duval was the tour's top money-winner ($2.6
million) in a season when 22 baseball players _ now unionized _
earned more than $6.6 million, with an average salary of $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Although the PGA Tour's 1998-99 annual report to members, which
was independently audited by an outside firm, shows 66.1 percent of
a projected $209,368,000 in income will be spent on players'
salaries this season, Edwards considers the percentage high. So
does Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks, the TPA treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   The figures, said Brooks, do not account for golf-related income
generated by tournaments like Colonial or the Nelson and kept in
local coffers. As a result, Edwards estimated that professional
golfers play for roughly 40 percent of the dollars that change
hands at tournaments, compared to 67 percent for NFL players, 57
percent for NBA participants and 55 percent for major-league
baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards called it ``one of the huge travesties in professional
sports.'' Nelson and Colonial officials said distributing a larger
chunk of tournament proceeds to players would cut into charitable
contributions that topped the $5 million mark last year ($4.3
million by the Nelson, $1 million by Colonial).
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the charities, but it's got to be reasonable. There's
got to be a formula where the people that generate the money get at
least a fair share,'' Edwards said. ``On the surface, it looks like
we're greedy. But the reality of it is when we go to the Phoenix
Open, \Rtournament officials\S generate $16 million, give $3
million to charity and we play for $2.8 million. That's not right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody runs their business and recognizes that cost of goods
sold is not 15 or 25 percent. Companies are not allowed to make a
75 percent margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet such numbers fail to inspire passion in most PGA Tour
participants. Asked about the TPA, Fort Worth resident Clark Dennis
said: ``I don't think there's a lot of interest in it. Most guys
are pretty happy with the way things are going on tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Brooks said he is glad to be part of the
organization so that it can serve in a watchdog capacity for the
financial dealings of PGA Tour executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer that it shouldn't go away,'' Brooks said.
``I wouldn't call it a loaded gun, but it's something that's there
in case they want to do something they shouldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, commissioner Tim Finchem, TPA members will be
tracking your every move. Through Y2K and beyond. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
