<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PARLIAMENT HINTS NEW PREMIER COULD SAIL THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After the fireworks of a failed impeachment attempt,
the Russian parliament's vote on Wednesday on a new prime minister
promises to be surprisingly tame _ and it is likely to be a ``yes''
vote.
</P>
<P>
   More politicians indicated Monday that they are ready to call a
time-out in their battle against President Boris Yeltsin and to
proceed swiftly with the approval of Sergei Stepashin, the
47-year-old Interior Minister named last week to succeed Yevgeny
Primakov as the leader of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other way out,'' said Aman Tulayev, a Communist
who is governor of the Kemerovo region. ``The sooner we form a
Cabinet, the sooner we have stability. Any fool can understand
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on television Sunday night, Gennady Zyuganov, leader of
the Communist Party, said he would not rule out a favorable vote
for Stepashin, although he said it will depend on his meetings on
Tuesday with party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The first confirmation vote in the parliament's lower house must
take place Wednesday. If the president's nominee is rejected three
times, then Yeltsin will be obligated under the Russian
constitution to disband parliament and set early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the collapse on Saturday of a Communist-led drive to
oust Yeltsin from office, many here had predicted that the
parliament would not push the crisis to a confrontation over the
Stepashin nomination. Now, after failing to get the two-thirds
majority required to push impeachment forward, the opposition is in
even less of a position to challenge the president.
</P>
<P>
   With his law-and-order background, Stepashin was already an
acceptable figure for many lawmakers. And with his promise over the
weekend not to appoint any `'odious'' figures to the Cabinet, he
appears to have assured opposition leaders that he will not be a
springboard for the return of such reviled liberal economic
reformers as Anatoli Chubais, the one-time privatization chief.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stepashin has promised to keep on most of the old
Primakov Cabinet, with the exception of Yuri Maslyukov, the old
coalition Cabinet's top Communist, who has already announced his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, who has been shown on television meeting with groups
of lawmakers in his shirt-sleeves, has offered them a
back-to-business respite from the political struggle. So far, his
strategy seems to be working.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view Stepashin, better than anyone else, can insure
political stability from the viewpoint of reaching a compromise
between the government, the parliament and the president,'' said
Oleg Morozov, leader of the moderate Russian Regions bloc, whose 45
members split on the impeachment issue on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's press spokesman, Dmitri Yakushkin, said Monday that
the president thinks that Stepashin's chances are ``not bad.'' He
said that recent statements from parliamentary leaders fill Yeltsin
``with a certain optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   Vowing to get tough on the theft and corruption rampant in
Russia and to curb the flight of capital, Stepashin echoed familiar
themes that are popular with all sides. He also promised to push
ahead with a legislative package that is considered crucial for a
debt relief package negotiated with the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the obligations assumed by the previous government will be
fulfilled,'' he said. But time is short, Stepashin said. ``The next
three months will be crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections just six months away, some members
have said that another round of clashes over a lame-duck government
is neither necessary nor worth the expenditure of further political
and financial capital. After Yeltsin fired his last government in
August, it took the parliament two votes and almost a month before
both sides settled on a compromise candidate, Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the members have already been warned that Stepashin
will withdraw his nomination if it is rejected on the first vote.
That would leave the door open to Yeltsin to propose an obviously
unacceptable nominee and to push ahead with disbanding parliament.
The president would then be free to leave his own government in
place until elections.
</P>
<P>
   Although Communist Party leaders have insisted publicly they are
ready to face early elections, many analysts say that the
Communists are likely to be reluctant to give up the perks and
privileges that come with office, all of which would come in handy
during an electoral campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
