<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Screaming about Littleton syndrome
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gregg Easterbrook argues that our critical celebration
of such gore-drenched moves as ``Scream'' (featuring torture and
graphic murder) and ``Pulp Fiction'' (in which hit men are snappy
and glamorous) should be held partly responsible for the massacre
in Littleton, Colo. Easterbrook, writing in The New Republic
($3.50) cites studies that correlate violent images with increased
aggression and nicely documents the swelling tide of killings in
television and movies. He fails, however, to demonstrate how the
rising murder rate on the big and little screens can be tied to
youth violence, which, according to some statistics, is actually
dropping.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE REAL BLUES: Singer Jennifer Holliday tells about her
battle with depression, which led to a 1990 suicide attempt and,
finally, to treatment. The star of ``Dreamgirls,'' who gained a
hundred pounds during her six months on Broadway in 1981, tells
Essence ($2.75) that her weight gain was a symptom, not a cause of
her illness. By 1995, she was seeking therapy and losing weight.
She also speaks of an encounter that year with singer Phyllis
Hyman, who eyed the trimmed-down Holliday and clearly wished she
could do the same. Three weeks later, Hyman committed suicide in
her New York apartment. An accompanying story explores an
``unrealistic'' belief in personal strength that can keep black
women from seeking help when they need it most. &QR;  DEAR PAPA: Fifty
years ago, Lillian Ross wrote a New Yorker profile of Ernest
Hemingway that laid his personality bare and was hailed as the
woman who destroyed the macho writer. But Hemingway considered the
article accurate, and the two remained friends. In this week's The
New Yorker ($3) Ross recounts years of correspondence with
Hemingway, quoting his retort to those who wondered why he was
still her friend: ``How can I be destroyed by a woman when she is a
friend of mine and we have never even been to bed and no money has
changed hands?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE LOCKDOWN: Questioning the wisdom of privatizing prisons,
Blaze ($2.95) suggests that profit-making companies such as
Corrections Corporation of America, which operates 70 prisons
worldwide, ``have a vested interest in stoking America's fear of
crime.'' Blaze interviews Junior Kargbo, 24, an inmate serving 20
years to life for murder at the Central Arizona Detention Center,
who calls the private prison's goal ``genocide. They hope you
commit another crime, so you can come back and fill bed space.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOME IMPROVEMENT: Rating the warehouse-size home centers,
Consumer Reports ($3.50) finds Home Depot is a shade better than
competitor Lowe's. The magazine also gives high marks to
California-based Orchard Supply Hardware and to Sears Hardware,
with most of its stores in the Northeast and Midwest. (Chains of
independently owned hardware stores such as Ace and True Value were
not rated.) Though these stores have almost anything the shopper
wants, only half of people surveyed said the stores were good at
helping them find it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CHOKING ON PROGRESS: Since the Clean Air Act was passed in
1970, Atlanta has never met EPA standards, reports Georgia Trend
($2.95). In a cover story on Peachtown's air pollution, the
magazine points out that in 1990, metro Atlantans drove 81.5
million miles a day. By 1997, it was 110 million miles a day, or
32.8 miles per capita, the highest in the nation, with single
drivers composing 78 percent of commuters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SECOND SIGHT: ``Implantable synthetic vision systems,'' or
robotic eyesight for the blind, is an eye-opening cover topic for
Technology Review ($4.95). Scientists are experimenting with
microelectronics to replace the functions of the retina's
photoreceptors and have already stimulated visual response with
electrical signals. This advance, says TR, doesn't mean blind
people will ever be able to read a newspaper or recognize faces,
but for some individuals it could spell the difference between
seeing nothing and seeing outlines, light and shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
