<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-MENACE18-COX     05-17 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MENACE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'I've got a bad feeling about this.'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ OK, I dare you: Just try not to shiver when those
tranquil blue letters flash onscreen: ``A long time ago in a galaxy
far, far away. . .'' But now for some bad news. Very little in
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' lives up to those
anticipatory tingles you feel when John Williams' familiar score
blasts the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Is George Lucas' new movie visually amazing? Yes. Exciting?
Sometimes. Emotionally involving? Almost never. As a technological
Everest (and the Mount McKinley of marketing), ``Menace'' is a
remarkable achieve-
</P>
<P>
   ment. Too bad writer-director Lucas left out the gee-whiz
enthusiasm of the original movies. He also left out memorable
characters. He left out the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Should you see it? Sure, you have to. It's a worldwide
phenomenon. So pity the poor critic who has to write about its
success as a movie. (For the record, I'm a series fan. I saw the
first ``Star Wars'' more than a dozen times in the summer of '77.)
</P>
<P>
   This first installment of a projected prequel trilogy,
``Menace'' introduces us to Jedi knight Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson)
and his apprentice Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan McGregor, doing a fine
vocal homage to Alec Guinness). We meet them as they intercede on
behalf of Naboo, a planet targeted for invasion by the powerful
Trade Federation.
</P>
<P>
   This fact is one of your first inklings that there's something
off about the movie. Tariffs, economic sanctions and blockades
aren't subjects that get your blood pounding. The movie is a
strange mix. It's full of skulduggery and political maneuvering
that children won't care about. But the action is delivered at a
frantic pace designed to keep kids with short attention spans in
their seats.
</P>
<P>
   The plot takes our knights to Naboo, where they meet Queen
Amidala (Natalie Portman), whose elaborate costumes make her look
like a sofa in some exotic bordello. Another new character is the
long-eared bumbler Jar Jar Binks (voiced by Ahmed Best). Next stop
on the tour: Tatooine, home of Luke Skywalker's future dad (and
Darth), young Anakin (Jake Lloyd) and his single mom, Schmi
(Pernilla August).
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about spoilers in this review. There's really not a
lot to give away. ``Menace'' doesn't have the grand surprises that
the last two ``Star Wars'' movies packed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the movie is filled with thrilling sequences and images: an
underwater art nouveau city. A breathless ``pod race'' through the
rocky Tatooine landscape. An urban skyline braided with endless
trails of hovercraft in flight.
</P>
<P>
   These are computer-generated effects, and Lucas packs nearly
every frame of film with some digital doodad. So many new creatures
and contraptions appear, ``Menace'' starts to feel less like a
movie, more like a product reel for the tie-in collectibles.
Instead of an embellishment, these effects have become the main
event, crowding the heroes out of their own movie. Sacrificed at
this digital altar, the humans become supporting players, like the
actors opposite the cartoons in ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie equates more with better. One panoramic shot of a
massive robot army lined up to attack Jar Jar's tribe is supposed
to inspire awe. It can't. We're obviously looking at CGI effects,
not creatures we care about. (Especially in the case of Jar Jar.)
For all its visual imagination, the movie becomes less engrossing
as it unfolds, not more.
</P>
<P>
   Too much tech and too little heart makes a bad mix. While the
old ``Star Wars'' movies gave us a yearning youth, a sassy heroine
and a rogue adventurer, the characters in ``Menace'' seem curiously
vague, undefined. (When old pals C-3PO and R2-D2 turn up, they make
you miss the old crew even more.) The new heroes fire their
blasters and murmur about the Force. But they're just going through
their paces, pawns of the plot instead of enacters of destiny.
Emotion is at a minimum, real danger is nil. It's hard to get
worried when Amidala teeters on a ledge above a precipice, or young
Anakin hurtles through the desert at Mach speed. It's a video game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of human Storm Troopers, Lucas introduces robot
soldiers, which means the good guys can ``kill'' guiltlessly,
without bloodshed. He stages spectacular, unsurvivable crashes in
the pod race, then makes sure we see the crash victims emerge
unscathed. Compare this to the original ``Star Wars,'' whose
swashbuckling was grounded in real human loss: Luke's aunt and
uncle, and heck, the whole planet Alderaan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Menace'' lacks the corny epic grandeur we associate with
``Star Wars.'' Lucas is so focused on FX, he blows what ought to be
big character and magic moments. You wait for Darth Maul (Ray
Park), the movie's scariest-looking thug, to develop into a major
villain. He barely gets any screen time. One character's death is
filmed so obliquely (almost apologetically), you hardly realize
what's happened. It's like a Wagnerian refrain played on the kazoo.
</P>
<P>
   The only indelible creature in ``Menace'' is Jar Jar, in the
worst way. He's a CG creation whose role as clumsy comic relief
grows grating fast. Plus, his Rastafarian-inflected pidgin English
is often incomprehensible. (Speaking of accents, it's questionable
that Lucas has two of the shadier alien species sounding Chinese
and Middle Eastern.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie has another big, little problem: Lloyd. He's a cute
kid, with his moon-round face and haystack hair. He delivers his
lines, hits his marks and says ``yippee'' and ``oops'' a lot. But
he's not what you'd call an actor. (When the Jedi knights start to
marvel about his powerful mystical vibe, you think, ``Who? The
moppet?'')
</P>
<P>
   Even the more experienced actors come off stiff, maybe because
they spent the shoot acting against blue screens, or talking to
creatures that were still incubating on someone's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, it's a ``Star Wars'' movie. It's an end-of-millennium
event. After you see it, you'll look forward to ``Episode II'' _
not to find out what happens next, but in the hopes that it will be
better. By then maybe Lucas will have rediscovered the wit, heart
and danger that made the first three movies more than just a slick
pastiche of old cliffhangers.
</P>
<P>
   His fans will cut him slack this time. If we can forgive him for
the Ewoks, we can forgive him for anything. Except, maybe, Jar Jar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode I
</P>
<P>
   _ The Phantom Menace''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liam Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman, Jake
Lloyd. Rated PG for sci-fi action/
</P>
<P>
   violence. At metro theaters starting Wednesday; some theaters
begin screening the film at midnight tonight or one minute after
midnight. 2 hours, 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Who cares what
</P>
<P>
   I think, you're gonna see it anyway. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Don't relieve the hype: Keep the Star Wars hysteria burning at
</P>
<P>
   Access Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star Wars'' hype still burns bright at Access Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR; www.accessatlanta.com/
</P>
<P>
   living/special/starwars.html
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
