<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-FIRST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intuit, Security First agreements called 'a big deal' by analyst
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Security First Technologies is buying two of its
largest competitors, FICS and Edify, for $1.4 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The move would create an Atlanta-based company, called S1, that
could dominate the market for software that lets people, small
businesses and corporations handle their money via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Edify and FICS deals are subject to approval by Security
First Technologies' and Edify's shareholders. They are expected to
be completed in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Intuit announced Monday it is buying a 2.5 percent stake
in Security First Technologies for about $50 million. The
investment includes an agreement that lets the two companies offer
Intuit's tax filing, payroll and tax payment products to financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The deals line up several companies and aim them, indirectly, at
one target: you.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect that in the near future the Internet will be the
place where people, small businesses and corporations file taxes,
balance books, transfer funds and get and pay bills.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Security First, which sells software that lets
customers of retail banks access their accounts via the Internet,
hopes Monday's deals will create a company that can offer almost
one-stop shopping for a bank wanting to set up online.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``rounds out our product offering and takes our
strongest competitor out of the marketplace,'' said James S. Mahan
III, Security First Technologies' chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were uncertain about the deal. Security First
Technologies's stock dropped $3, to close at $51. Security First
shares are up 234 percent for 1999. Edify closed at $14.93 3/4,
down 31 1/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   But research analysts liked the moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big deal,'' said Brook Newcomb, a senior analyst at
Forrester Research. ``It has created a giant among a bunch of small
vendors. A company looking for a front-end to its Web presence now
doesn't have to worry about looking for a whole bunch of vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the deal, Security First will issue 20 million shares
of its stock to Belgium-based FICS and 6.4 million shares of its
stock for Edify, based in Santa Clara, Calif. The $54 stock price
is based on Security First Technologies' May 14 closing price.
Security First had $24.2 million in revenue in 1998, a 123 percent
increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
