<HEADER>
A0586 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-F16-ENGINES-TEX     05-17 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F16-ENGINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$100 MILLION SOUGHT FOR FIXES TO F-16 ENGINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Air Force is asking Congress for $100 million
to repair about 1,800 F-16 fighter plane engines, fixes prompted by
seven F-16 crashes since November that were blamed on engine
failure.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which is gaining support among key lawmakers, would
allow repairs at bases worldwide. Air Force propulsion experts
believe that engine problems contributed to the crashes, none of
which was fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get the hardware into the field quicker,'' said
Robert May, manager of the Air Force's propulsion product group at
Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio. ``The faster you get the
hardware into the field, the quicker you get the risk out of the
fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   May said that the engine problems are not related to any design
flaw in the F-16. Lockheed Martin builds the fighter plane in Fort
Worth, but does not make the engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The F-16 is the safest single-engine fighter in the Air
Force's history,'' May said. ``We think it is extremely safe, and
we are proud of the record of the engines.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Hayden, a spokeswoman at Lockheed Martin Tactical
Aircraft Systems, said, ``Lockheed Martin takes any loss seriously,
and we are pleased that both the problems, as well as the
solutions, have been identified.''
</P>
<P>
   The program would ask Air Force maintenance personnel to install
several parts and make improvements to the F-16 engines, which are
made by General Electric in Cincinnati and Pratt &AMP; Whitney in West
Palm Beach, Fla. The two contractors build all F-16 engines.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both companies said their firms helped in the
investigations of the crashes and would help with the repair
program.
</P>
<P>
   The repairs would include:
</P>
<P>
   _Replacing the power-management control on the GE F110-100
engine.
</P>
<P>
   _Treating fan blades on some GE engines with ``laser shock
peening'' to make the blades more resistant to cracking.
</P>
<P>
   _Replacing some fan blades on the Pratt &AMP; Whitney F110-220
engine with more-durable blades.
</P>
<P>
   _Replacing the augmenter duct on the Pratt &AMP; Whitney engine with
a newly designed, chemically milled unit. The ducts help provide
thrust for engines by forcing air out of the nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   The work would be done on 1,860 F-16 engines, including those on
operational aircraft and others available as spares. The Air Force
has about 1,400 F-16s in its inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Without the $100 million being sought from Congress, the repairs
could take six to eight years to complete, Air Force officials
said. With the money, the repairs could be done in two to three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance personnel have already begun inspecting the suspect
parts. The inspection program includes F-16s in Europe, where the
fighters have been flying thousands of sorties in Operation Allied
Force.
</P>
<P>
   One F-16 crashed May 2 in western Serbia. Its pilot ejected
safely and was rescued. NATO officials initially said engine
problems may have caused the crash, but May said the exact cause is
not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   May said the engine problems are not the result of faulty
production work by either contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Engines are so complex that there are a lot of things you
cannot analytically model'' in development, he said. ``Basically,
you find some problems when you put them out in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of the recent F-16 crashes blamed on engine problems
occurred Nov. 19 at Shaw Air Force Base in South Carolina. The
engine lost thrust during takeoff and the pilot ejected safely.
</P>
<P>
   The last engine-related accident was on March 26 at Luke Air
Force Base in Arizona. The pilot ejected safely before the plane
slammed into the desert about 22 miles southwest of the base.
</P>
<P>
   Luke has been the site of four high-profile F-16 mishaps blamed
on engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., is among the lawmakers urging that
the F-16 repairs be made soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that this emergent requirement comes at a time
when our defense dollars are very tight,'' McCain said in a letter
to fellow members of the Senate Armed Services Committee. ``The
safety of our air crews and the combat readiness of our Air Force
are priority concerns that require our immediate attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said that the requested money is likely to
be in the 2000 budget, but that the Air Force will have to wait
until the budget is finished in several months.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the money would be in addition to the $328 million
the administration has proposed for purchasing 10 new F-16s from
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
