<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-OWNERS-ART-791(2     05-17 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-OWNERS-ART-791(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY AMERICANS, OWNING A GUN IS A WAY OF LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Ga., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARRIOTTSVILLE, Md. _ Short, slight, boyishly frail-looking at
60, James F. Laughland can pierce the pupil in the eye of a bull,
or its paper equivalent, shot after shot, with his .22-caliber
Winchester rifle or his mightier M-1A. A badge on his shooting
fatigue jacket says ``President's Hundred,'' putting him in the top
rank of thousands of shooters who compete in a national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aerospace engineer, Laughland spent this past weekend,
like most, working on his ``groups,'' the pattern of shots that
pierces a target's black center and surrounding rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sighting in and looking for the smallest group possible,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   With guns, he has hurt only one living thing, his own right
shoulder. It needed rotator-cuff surgery after more than 40 years
of pounding by recoiling rifle butts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the massacre last month at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., guns have seized the agenda of Congress more than
at any other time in recent years, and their owners have been
demonized, or at least oversimplified, in the pitched battle
between gun-control advocates and the National Rifle Association
and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the men, women and children at weekend shooting
tournaments like the one here at the Associated Gun Clubs of
Baltimore attest, there is another dimension to Americans and their
guns. According to the National Rifle Association, 60 million to 65
million Americans own 200 million guns, or about three per person.
As tools of sport and fun, guns are as entrenched in the culture
and life of many American communities as the Little League and
Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   That guns can be instruments for evil seems far removed from the
climate of America's thousands of rifle and pistol ranges, where on
this weekend in May, several million target shooters began their
annual cycle of tournaments and matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Gun Clubs' site here occupies 60 hilly acres of
brush, fields and maple trees, near stone quarries and horse farms
just beyond the western fringe of suburban Baltimore. Twenty-five
clubs with a total of 3,000 to 3,500 members support the site's
pistol, bench rest, rifle, trap and archery ranges, most with
covered firing lines to permit shooting in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Up at the trap range, 15 men and a woman armed with 12-gauge
shotguns take turns shooting in groups of five and six. Four men
are black, the others white. They run the gamut in age, from late
20s to late 60s, and have jobs, from mechanic and truck driver to
lawyer and engineer. They are skinny and fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sport for exercise,'' says Bob Baker, 51, an
informations system engineer and one of the beefier shooters. ''I
do this for sport,'' he said. ``I've never been hunting in my life.
I like this because the targets move. It's a little more
challenging than shooting at a stationary piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shanks, 49, a supervisor for a public transit agency, is
black. He spent his early childhood in Georgia and then moved to
Baltimore. He learned shooting in the Boy Scouts and fought in
Vietnam as a staff sergeant in the Green Berets. But he traces his
interest in shooting to the rural black America of an earlier
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a part of our culture,'' Shanks said. ``As a black person
in this country, you learn to survive by shooting game for food.
You learn to shoot .22's for rabbits and squirrels. You feel
comfortable with a rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting range, he says, is a great equalizer. ``When you
come here, you strip away all your prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanks, Baker and three other men load up. From a bunker-like
trap house _ a 2-foot-high concrete structure about 10 yards in
front of the shooters _ a hidden machine catapults small orange
saucers, or clay pigeons, into the air, simulating ducks bursting
from marsh.
</P>
<P>
   The saucers take off flying 60 mph in any of 52 directions.
Struck with a burst of buckshot, they shatter. Each competitor gets
25 pigeons. John Quinn, a mechanic at a Mack Truck dealership and a
frequent winner, sometimes hits all 25. He wins this round today,
missing just two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is 10 percent knowledge, 90 percent concentration,''
Quinn says. As the clay pigeon takes off, he explained, he keeps
the gun moving with it, and a little ahead and then fires. ``The
whole trick,'' he said, ``is to keep the gun moving. You stop, you
miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do trap, pistol and rifle, and I coach,'' Quinn said. ``I
come here at least every Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   He started bringing his daughter when she was 9. She became a
proficient shooter and met and married a member whose father and
uncle were also members. ``My son-in-law is a hunter, big time,''
he said. ``Their majority meat for the year consists of venison.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baker wonders what has become of Americans and their guns.
``A lot of us grew up with toy guns,'' he said. As a child in
Framingham, Mass., he said, he played cops and robbers with cap
guns. ``I used to get cowboy sets for Hanukkah,'' he said. ``I shot
BB guns in summer camp. I shot rifle in college.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Baker said, ``If a police officer sees a kid with a
gun, he's going to shoot and ask questions later.'' Kids get into
trouble, he said, ``talking about guns or drawing pictures of
guns.'' For the most part, he said he blamed violent movies for the
surge in schoolyard shooting by children.
</P>
<P>
   Safety is a big issue here. No one is allowed on the range
without a member's numbered orange badge, which indicates that the
bearer has mastered a full course of safety instruction. Typically,
the members bring several guns here to shoot on the different
ranges, and many attach trigger locks when they are not shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Shanks has built a cabinet into the wall of his basement, which
he locks, and when he loads up his van to go shooting, he attaches
locks to the triggers of his guns. When Baker resumed shooting six
years ago after a long hiatus, he said he bought a $350 steel safe
for his guns before he bought his first gun.
</P>
<P>
   Down at the benchrest section of the 100-yard range, John
Mathis, 43, a commercial printer, has brought his children, Mark,
12, and Christine, 15, for their first afternoon of formal
instruction. ``I have a room and everything in the room is in two
large cabinets,'' Mathis said. ``The cabinets are locked and the
room is locked.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed, Mathis said, since his days as a ``teen-age
plinker.'' Plinking _ picking off tin cans and other random objects
_ is confined today largely to the deserts of the West. ``There was
a time in America,'' he said, ``when if you were a marksman, that
was a good thing. Now if you say you're a good shot, someone thinks
you're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   A gun, Mathis said, builds character. ``It creates discipline
and responsibility. You have a tool in your hand that can be
hazardous. You learn to control that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis brought Christine out to the range when she was 8 and
bought a child's .22-caliber Chipmonk for her to use. Her interest
waned, but now, in the aftermath of Littleton, she wants to learn
to shoot. At school she has been assigned a debating class topic,
gun control, and to argue the case for it.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Mark, by contrast, has been tagging along with his
father to the range. While Mark needs a lot of work on his aim, he
seems smitten by the same thrills that hook most people here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best time,'' Mark said, ``was when I took out a bull's
eye.'' Taking out a bull's eye entails so riddling a target's black
circle with holes that nothing of it remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kept shooting,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark added, ``I like to come outside and spend time doing
something I enjoy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
