<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-800&AMP;AD     05-17 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR PRESSED TO END CLINTON'S STALLING ON GROUND FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY) 
(mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair is coming under increasing
pressure to stand up to President Clinton on the issue of using
ground troops to achieve a NATO victory over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction is taking hold in Britain that the war against
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia cannot be won on NATO's
terms without troops on the ground. Blair is being urged to use his
close friendship with Clinton to persuade him to confront
congressional and public misgivings over committing American
soldiers to such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting widespread public doubts about the American
president's stance, the lead editorial of The Financial Times said
Monday, ``Clinton's prevarication about offering the U.S. troops
that are vital to a successful outcome has left time on Milosevic's
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times of London said Monday that one of those moments that
makes for what Winston Churchill called the British-American
``special relationship'' is at hand and that it is up to Blair ``to
convince the president that his reputation and NATO's future
credibility rests upon a willingness to use the tools at his
disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   A former defense minister, Michael Portillo, said on TV Sunday
morning, ``If the government wants to achieve what it says it wants
to achieve, you can only do that by ground forces.'' And Paddy
Ashdown, leader of the Liberal Democrats and himself a former Royal
Marine commando officer, said he had never heard of anyone
``surrendering to an aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ashdown and William Hague, leader of the Conservative
Party, warned Blair in the House of Commons last week that time was
running out for a decision on ground forces. ``I am acutely aware
of the issue of time, and the issue of the Balkan winter and the
need for planning for all contingencies,'' Blair responded.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has not explicitly endorsed sending in the infantry, but
his emphasis on pushing for undiluted victory has inevitably cast
him in the position of being in favor of using ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend he responded directly and bluntly to British
critics of the American war effort, saying, ``The vast bulk of this
military operation is being carried out by U.S. forces, although
Kosovo is a very long way from Kansas. Their commitment and
leadership is something for which President Clinton should be
praised, rather than the sneers he receives from the right in this
country.'' He was speaking in a question-and-answer interview with
The Observer in what has become an almost daily habit of Blair's of
rallying public opinion on NATO's bombing over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Cook, the foreign secretary, who is flying to Washington
on Thursday, said Monday that NATO does not have to wait for a
negotiated settlement with Milosevic before sending in troops. ``We
are certainly not going to stand around at the border whilst we
wait for him to come to a signing ceremony with flags and cameras
and make an official treaty,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset of the bombing campaign seven weeks ago, Blair
has employed the brawniest rhetoric of any allied leader and has
described the conflict as a moral one and the acts of Milosevic as
war crimes for which the West must seek retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no half-measures to his brutality and there can be
no half-measures about how we deal with it,'' he told an audience
in Germany last week. ``No compromise, no fudge, no half-baked
deals,'' he said in describing the only acceptable resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to showing any signs that his loyalty to Clinton had
been shaken by any disagreement over the military campaign, Blair
flew Monday to Bulgaria and went out of his way to praise the
American role in the struggle. ``America has once again shown that
it has the vision to see that instability, chaos and racial
genocide in the heart of Europe will never affect Europe alone,''
he told an audience at Sofia University in the Bulgarian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Blair goes on to Albania on Tuesday in what is his second trip
to the Balkans this month. Two weeks ago, he saw refugee camps in
Macedonia and addressed the Romanian Parliament in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an unwanted measure of his success in portraying
himself as NATO's most forceful champion that Blair is now obliged
to respond to repeated reports that he and Clinton have serious
differences over the war, and that during his visit to the United
States last month he became frustrated at his inability to sway the
president to his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question we are all pondering is whether Blair knows
something we do not about American intentions, or whether he is
merely clinging to the hope that moral determination can prevail,
even when the military means to achieve a speedy decision in Kosovo
are lacking because the U.S. will not provide them,'' said Max
Hastings, the editor of The Evening Standard, writing a rare
column.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked about the reports, a spokesman for 10 Downing Street said,
``The press is portraying the prime minister as a hawk and Clinton
as not as fully committed, but that is nonsense. We have been
absolutely up front about the fact that the prime minister and the
president are of one mind about the war.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said he had been in the party accompanying Blair
to the United States and added, ``That was true before the prime
minister went to Washington, and nothing happened there to change
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said his trip to Washington was designed to ``demonstrate
the solidarity of our two countries,'' whose relations, he said,
are characterized by ``strong unity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no ideological dispute about the need for ground
troops,'' Cook said in a video link to Monday's Defense Ministry
briefing from Brussels, Belgium, where he was attending a meeting
of European Union foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in Washington he hoped to explore ``how we take
advantage of the success that we are achieving in Kosovo from the
military campaign from the air so that we are ready to go in as
soon as it is possible to go in safely and when it's appropriate to
do so to get the refugees back. We need to do that as quickly as we
can because we are all well aware that winter is coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
