<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0598 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BISHER-COLUMN-SAR     05-17 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BISHER-COLUMN-SARAZEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gone, but still _ and always _ here
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARCO ISLAND, Fla. _ They had said their farewell to Eugenio
Saraceni, son of an Italian carpenter and were now laying his body
to rest in Marco Island Cemetery. And so ends the 97-year-old story
of Saraceni turned Gene Sarazen, whose life was a biography of the
American dream. ``Leaving footprints in the sands of time that can
never be filled,'' to quote his great friend, Don Panoz.
</P>
<P>
   After a career of checking the world from one end to another,
this little island on the southwest of Florida is where he chose to
settle. They came here, his wife Mary and Gene, after she had
discovered the treasures of shells on the beaches. First, they came
for the winters, then later made it full-time, and hardly any
corner of this island hasn't been touched by the Sarazens. Now they
lie in adjoining plots.
</P>
<P>
   The service was high Catholic, celebrated by a priest who dealt
wittily in golfing metaphors, Father McConigal. Ken Venturi
delivered a warm and poignant eulogy. It was of note that Tim
Finchem of the PGA Tour had come to pay his respects, although the
Sarazen World Open that Panoz created has been deleted by the new
World Tour. The tournament at Chateau Elan fit in so well with
Sarazen's reputation as ambassador of golf, but so much for that.
It is significant that he has been revered in Japan for three
decades with a tournament in his name.
</P>
<P>
   Before airlines girdled the globe, Sarazen carried the gospel of
golf to every continent where the game is played, then went back to
the birthplace of the game and won the British Open, among his
seven major championships. He hit parts of the world Americans had
never heard of, when overseas travel was by steamship. He golfed
with sultans, kings, tycoons and princes. He missed the first
Masters because he had committed to a series of exhibitions in
South America and Australia. But he was only beginning to see the
world. One day, as he was haying in a field on his farm a car came
rolling up in a cloud of dust, and with it an offer to host the
``Shell Wonderful World of Golf.''
</P>
<P>
   He would say later, ``That brought me more attention and made me
more money than all of the tournaments I won.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finally did plant his feet, it was on a farm, odd as it
might seem. No recreational farmer, he. He owned three farms at one
time or another, but the last was his pride and joy, located near
Germantown, N.Y. He sold his second farm to Gabriel Heatter, the
radio newscaster, and bought 300 acres called Mountain Range. He
produced apples, cherries _ he loved cherry trees _ and hay and
kept a herd of Black Angus.
</P>
<P>
   ``My motive was strictly economic,'' Sarazen said in his book.
``I wanted something solid under my feet,'' speaking of a time when
the big Depression was upon us.
</P>
<P>
   He was Bobby Jones' closest friend among the professional
players, for not many flocked around an amateur who was beating
them at their own game. He and Jones were born within 18 days of
each other, both had wives named Mary and were married within days
of each other. A few years ago, he called from Florida and wanted
to stop off in Atlanta and visit Jones' grave site. He was taken to
Oakland Cemetery, and there had his picture taken by Jones'
headstone, a treasured experience in my life.
</P>
<P>
   He has had a special relationship with the Masters from the time
he delivered the historic double eagle in 1935. Jones himself
witnessed it from 50 yards away. Sarazen would later say, ``Any
club that wants to see how a tournament should be run should send a
few emissaries to study the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sarazen World Open filled a void in his life after Mary
died. She, too, had been smitten by the game, leading to a story he
loved to tell. ``I had just lost the U.S. Open by a stroke to Olin
Dutra at Merion and was coming home on the train. Mary met me at
Penn Station, and came running up and said, 'Gene, Gene, I shot an
84!' And I'd lost the U.S. Open by one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a million Sarazen stories, for here was a man who
captured America's imagination before television was there. He was
small in size, about 5 feet 5, with a big smile that was always
turned on. Now, though, we must adjust to thinking of golf without
the man who gave us the sand wedge and Lord knows how much more. On
a pedestal in front of the altar at San Marco they'd placed one of
his little white golf hats. It was almost as if he was there, and
in a sense he was and shall always be.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is Sports Editor of The Atlanta Journal, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
