<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-CUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WOMEN'S SOCCER CHOICES GOLDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only suspense was who the third goaltender would be. Almost
anybody who's watched the US women's soccer team play this year
could probably have ticked off virtually the entire 20-player World
Cup roster announced Monday, just over a month before the opener
with Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   That's how stable, and predictable, the squad has been since the
host Americans reloaded after winning the Olympic title in Atlanta
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen gold medalists _ most notably Mia Hamm, Michelle Akers,
Kristine Lilly, Julie Foudy, Joy Fawcett, Carla Overbeck, and
keeper Briana Scurry _ will form the core of a squad that has lost
only nine matches in six years and has won 54 of its last 55 on
home soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about this team,'' said coach Tony DiCicco, whose
squad will be favored to recapture the crown it lost to Norway four
years ago. ``I think it's the best the US has ever put together.''
</P>
<P>
   It's undoubtedly the most experienced. Eleven players were
members of the 1995 Cup squad and seven played in 1991. Eight have
competed in at least 115 international matches. Lilly, the
27-year-old midfielder, owns the world record for most caps (177)
and Hamm, the 27-year-old forward, needs only one goal to set a
global mark with 108.
</P>
<P>
   So DiCicco's decisions were mostly on the margins _ keep a
veteran bench player or go with youth? With the Olympics coming up
next summer, DiCicco stood pat more often than not. He chose Cup
veteran Saskia Webber over 21-year-old Siri Mullinix for third
keeper behind Scurry and Tracy Ducar of North Andover, Mass. And he
decided that 18-year-olds Ally Wagner and Susan Bush needed more
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   But DiCicco opted for Natick-born defender Sara Whalen, the
23-year-old former UConn star, because of her speed and
versatility. ``We think Sara's part of our future,'' said DiCicco.
``We're hoping this experience will vault her into the next
level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
