A0605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT     05-17 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILING TO RECEIVE SUPPORT, SONIA GANDHI QUITS AS PARTY LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born widow who
inherited the mantle of India's founding political dynasty,
submitted her resignation Monday as leader of the Congress Party
after a trio of party leaders revolted against her candidacy for
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The party's shaken governing body promptly and unanimously
rejected her resignation. But party officials said they were unsure
whether Mrs. Gandhi actually intends to quit or whether she will
relent. Senior Congress leaders rushed to her home Monday evening
to dissuade her from stepping down as president of a party they say
she has single-handedly rescued from a disastrous decline over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Sharad Pawar, a powerful Congress Party leader from the state of
Maharashtra, and two other senior Congress officials had openly
challenged the appropriateness of Mrs. Gandhi's candidacy for prime
minister because of her foreign birth and her lack of political
experience.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary letter that was delivered to her on
Saturday, the three party leaders also asked her to propose a
constitutional amendment requiring that the offices of president
and prime minister be held only by natural born Indian citizens.
The letter was leaked to newspapers, which carried accounts of it
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible that a country of 980 million, with a
wealth of education, competence and ability, can have anyone other
than an Indian, born of Indian soil, to head its government,'' they
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a party where many serve as sycophantic courtiers to the
Gandhi family, the rebels' letter was a stunningly open airing of
doubts about Mrs. Gandhi's fitness to govern. Mrs. Gandhi, whose
husband, Rajiv Gandhi, and mother-in-law, Indira Gandhi, both
served as prime ministers of India and who were both assassinated,
has never held any elective office. She has been president of the
Congress Party for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that party leaders considered her foreign birth a
political liability, she said in her letter of resignation that she
was ``pained by their lack of confidence in my ability to act in
the best interest of the party and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Though born in a foreign land, I chose India as my country,''
she wrote. ``I am Indian and shall remain so till my last breath.
India is my motherland, dearer to me than my own life.''
</P>
<P>
   After a day of frenetic behind-the-scenes meetings, the Congress
Working Committee, the party's governing body, Monday night
strongly endorsed Mrs. Gandhi's continued leadership.
</P>
<P>
   They said it was essential in the political battle against the
rival Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which they describe
as a political force intent on inflaming communal passions among
Hindus, Muslims and Christians. They also said that Mrs. Gandhi,
who became an Indian citizen in 1983, has united the party and can
ably lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The three rebels did not attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, a regal, austere figure who gives no free-form
interviews and offers few impromptu remarks, did not appear before
reporters Monday. Up to now, she has not declared her own intention
to be a candidate for prime minister, though party spokesmen have
repeatedly said she is the party's choice.
</P>
<P>
   The views of Pawar, who led the opposition in the lower house of
Parliament, and of the two other signatories, P.A. Sangma, a member
of Parliament and a Christian from the small, northeastern state of
Meghalaya, and Tariq Anwar, a Muslim leader from the state of
Bihar, are especially damaging because they echo and legitimize
statements made by the Hindu nationalists, Congress' main rival for
power in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   The nationalist party officials say it is a disgrace that India
should even consider electing an Italian-born woman who is a
political neophyte. And they have held up their leader, the
caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee _ a veteran
parliamentary leader and an Indian _ as the antithesis of Mrs.
Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist-led coalition lost a vote of confidence
last month by a single vote, with a healthy push from the Congress
Party. But afterward, Congress was unable to come up with a
majority to form a new government _ a failure that tarnished Mrs.
Gandhi's image for mature and cautious leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, almost seven years after her husband was
assassinated as he campaigned to be prime minister, Mrs. Gandhi
agreed to take over as president of the Congress Party and had been
credited with rescuing it from near oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   While the rebels praised Mrs. Gandhi, ``a daughter-in-law to
India for the past 30 years,'' for helping to revive the party and
said they hope she continues as party president, they drew the line
at her heading the government.
</P>
<P>
   They contended that the legacy of the slain independence leader
Mohandas K. Gandhi justified their insistence on the need for a
native-born Indian prime minister _ an interpretation of Gandhi's
views others disputed. Gandhi, known as the Mahatma, or Great Soul,
is no relation to Sonia Gandhi's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``India has always lived in the spirit of the Mahatma's words,
`Let the winds from all over sweep into my room,' '' they wrote.
``But again he said, `I will not be swept off my feet.' We accept
with interest and humility the best which we can gather from the
north, south, east or west and we absorb them into our soil. But
our inspiration, our soul, our honor, our pride, our dignity, is
rooted in our soil. It has to be of this earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion by Pawar is threatening, not only because of the
content of the missive, but also because he is a powerhouse in the
state of Maharashtra, whose capital, Bombay, is India's financial
nerve center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharad Pawar is the Richard Daley of Indian politics in his
creative use of patronage to build networks of support,'' said
Jairam Ramesh, a Congress Party official.
</P>
<P>
   Maharashtra provides the Congress Party with 37 of its 140
members of Parliament _ support the party cannot afford to lose if
it hopes to win power after the elections. Pawar, who is 58 and a
man with prime ministerial ambitions of his own, may see the
continued dynastic reign of the Gandhi family as shutting off all
hope that he can ever rise to the pinnacle of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
