<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;   Storied friendships, rivalry set aside as Hawks, Knicks look to
advanceBy Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even a year ago, the smile on his face told the world
that Dikembe Mutombo was simply happy to be here _ be it an
early-season game, a crunch game in April or a first-round playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   He's beyond that now.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, when Mutombo walks to the jump circle against his old
friend and mentor Patrick Ewing, his demeanor will be grim, his
visage bordering on a glower.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years into his basketball career in America, eight years
into his NBA career, three with the Hawks, the bright, angular man
from the Congo says he finally understands the quest for a
championship, as Atlanta plays the New York Knicks in the second
round of the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A month from his 33rd birthday, Mutombo says, ``I'm getting to
the middle of my career when I want to win something. You want to
win a championship, and now Chicago leaves the door open. I don't
see why I would miss the opportunity presented to me. It's a chance
to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The road to opportunity, however, goes through Ewing, 37, a man
whom many believe Mutombo accorded too much respect in the early
years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about Ewing's relationship with Mutombo and Miami's
Alonzo Mourning, coach Lenny Wilkens said Monday: ``Patrick always
had an edge on those two guys. He was friends with them but he was
professional on the court to start with. After the game, they could
be friends, but when we're out there as long as you've got that
uniform on, you're not my friend. And I think Mourning got to that
level. Now we have to get Deek there.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said that Mutombo needs to say to himself, ``I'll
respect you, but you ain't gonna run over me.'' The Mutombo-Ewing
matchup is the centerpiece in a series that is short on both
rivalry and history. The franchises haven't met in the post-season
in 28 years. Mutombo understands that the two centers will share
the spotlight, even if he is not the offensive focus of his team,
even if Ewing's creaky legs have made him a questionable but brave
participant throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick? I don't worry about Patrick. I'm worrying about New
York's offense,'' Mutombo said. ``Patrick and I can have dinner
before the game. We can have an orange juice after the game, but
when we come to the court, our friendship will be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo disagreed with the suggestion that Ewing's personality
has dominated him, but he does honors the older player's influence
on his career since the day he followed Ewing to Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something special to play against someone you know
half your life and grow up with _ in the game and off the court,''
Mutombo said. ``To physically and mentally play at this level and
face him on the court, I love to see it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing ``might be a lucky guy,'' Mutombo said with a sly smile.
``He played Mourning and me in the (playoffs) same year. I gotta be
the one that finishes him. I know that he finished Mourning. Now
I've got to finish him.''
</P>
<P>
   They will battle through the best-of-seven series, he said, then
meet up again in Georgetown where they spend their summers, honing
their game for the season to come, telling lies and boasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be there in the summer time when we go to dinner
and when we (are) playing in the gym. There is a lot of
trash-talking, about what I did to you in the regular season. I
told Patrick I got you already in the regular season and I'm going
to get you in the playoffs. It's just friends talking, two guys
that are enjoying themselves. This is what we all love to do, work
hard and then come to the big dance. And it's time to dance now.''
</P>
<P>
   They split the two regular-season games in which Ewing
participated. The Hawks took the finale when Ewing watched in
street clothes, saving his aching Achilles tendon. Ewing averaged
18.5 points and 7.0 rebounds against the Hawks, Mutombo 10.7 points
and 15.7 rebounds against the Knicks. With the bell ready to sound
for Round 2, Wilkens says, ``Dikembe is pumped up about the
playoffs. Whoever we play, he's ready. Whatever we ask him to do,
he's ready for that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
