<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-PLAID-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOTHING QUITE LIKE COLONIAL PLAID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ The champion of the 1999 MasterCard Colonial
will stride up the 18th fairway Sunday and into a casting call for
``Braveheart.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he embraces the trophy, his wife will force a smile to
disguise her horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egad, it's plaid.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just any plaid: It is Colonial Plaid, a one-of-a-kind,
made-to-order, 12-color Royal Tartan, worsted wool. It is milled in
Scotland and included on The Register of All Publicly Known Tartans
_ the official listing of the about 2,500 plaids recognized by the
Scottish Tartans Society.
</P>
<P>
   It is Forever Plaid. It is the plaid jacket, the sometimes
maligned but mainly coveted prize of the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, they don't let us take it out of the clubhouse,''
said 1994 winner Nick Price, who will not be playing this week
because of a schedule conflict. ``The only time we have to wear it
is on champion's dinner night. There's one other that's equally as
ugly, and it's from Hilton Head \Rthe MCI Classic in South
Carolina\S, but it's a tradition and a good tradition. I'd wear
another five jackets if I could win another five Colonials.''
</P>
<P>
   This one will be the 47th plaid jacket to be awarded since its
debut in 1952 (the Tournament Players Championship was played at
Colonial in 1975) when the tournament committee decided to emulate
the Masters and the Phoenix Open by offering a distinctive coat.
Then-tournament chairman S.M. ``Bing'' Bingham chose plaid because,
``Our officials should shine with the same brilliance as our field
for the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colonial is one of five tournaments that award jackets; the
others are the Masters, the MCI Classic, the Memorial and the
Bayhill Invitational. Although Colonial champions are awarded a
matching Colonial Plaid tie, a nationally recognized fashion maven,
commenting in ``Sports Illustrated,'' awarded the Colonial Plaid
jacket a ``bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Highland warriors, the tournament committee is quick to
defend its two-button, center vent, notch lapel, flap-pocket
tartan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wish they had one,'' said shootout committee
chairman Barry Smith, a men's clothier who has been custom-making
the jackets for 10 years. ``The Colonial is not about fashion. It's
about tradition, and it's about golf.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any clan plaid, only a select few are allowed to wear
it: tournament committee chairmen and vice chairmen, the Colonial
board of governors, former tournament chairmen, past champions and
the ``Pride of the Plaid'' _ those deemed to have given long-term
service to the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   They wear their jackets proudly at the sales kickoff dinner in
early spring, at functions during tournament week and at the trophy
presentation on the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``And most people do not put them on until right before the
awards because immediately, your shirt sticks to your skin,'' said
Mike Thomas, a past club president. ``It gets hot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why they have a jacket ready and waiting for the winner.
The presenters raid the champions locker room when it becomes
apparent who might win the plaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the same thing the Masters does,'' tournament director
Dennis Roberson said. ``We find another champion's jacket that we
think is the right size. We'll go down there with two or three
coats if we have to. If it looks like Corey Pavin or Craig Stadler,
we'll get a big one and a small one _ no offense to Craig Stadler,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he's coming down the fairway, we look out at Tom Watson and
say, `Hmm _ Is he an Ian Baker-Finch?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Baker-Finch took a dip in the water hazard on No. 13,
dropping his trousers and wading in, but failed to save par.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the tournament committee to save ``pair:'' At the
1994 champions dinner, Baker-Finch was presented a pair of Colonial
Plaid boxer shorts to match the jacket he won in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   That would be worsted wool in the worst way.
</P>
<P>
   But it gets worse: At the 1991 champions dinner, Lanny Wadkins
presented 1990 winner Ben Crenshaw a pair of custom-made Colonial
Plaid pants to match the jacket he won in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   And just think of all the yuks you've missed out on because
``you'' don't have one, and you probably won't get one any time
soon, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people with the jackets are very proud of them, and
they're not easily given up,'' said Scott Corpening, chairman of
special events. ``There's been a lot of fun poked at the jacket,
but I can assure you there won't be one guy that tees it up
Thursday that wouldn't love to have one. It's our heritage. It's
what we're proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   They're mad about that plaid. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
