<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT &LR;      05-17 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE LEADERS DIVIDED ON NEGOTIATIONS FOR JOINING WTO
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ While China officially remains committed to joining
the World Trade Organization, Chinese economists say that apparent
divisions in the nation's leadership are likely to further stiffen
Beijing's negotiating position and make agreement difficult to
achieve in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   With China experiencing a wave of nationalist politics after the
American bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on May 7,
orthodox politicians, skeptical about the benefits of forcing open
Chinese markets as membership in the global trade group would
require, seem to be gaining influence.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Zhu Rongji is widely considered China's strongest
proponent of entry into the trade group, which sets the rules of
global commerce. But Zhu has become vulnerable to accusations that
he was giving too much away in the broad concessions he offered to
American negotiators during his visit to the United States last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng said Monday that China had
not changed its basic negotiating position. But he also
re-emphasized that Beijing would join the trade organization on its
own terms. ``China will never enter the WTO at the expense of its
own basic interests,'' Shi said at a meeting with visiting
Australian officials in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant U.S. trade representative, Robert Cassidy, had
originally been scheduled to return to Beijing this week to resume
talks, but his visit has been indefinitely delayed.
</P>
<P>
   An economist in Beijing with close ties to the government said
that the mood surrounding the trade talks had darkened, and that
many economic reforms were likely to be delayed while the
leadership was occupied with a new campaign to promote nationalism.
``No one dares do or say anything until they see a direction from
the center,'' the economist said. ``It limits everyone's ability to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   After President Clinton turned down a deal on Chinese membership
in the trade group during Zhu's visit, Chinese and American
negotiators looked to early June as a deadline to reach an
agreement, when China's most-favored-nation trading status expires.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching a deal by then would enable the Clinton administration
to advocate a single vote in Congress to give China permanent
favorable trading status, as required under trade organization
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Without a deal, Congress would have to vote once to renew
Beijing's most-favored-nation status, and then vote again on giving
China that status permanently. With so many anti-China voices in
Congress, made louder by recent accusations of nuclear spying, the
administration wants to avoid giving Congress two chances to oppose
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet reaching a deal before June now looks increasingly unlikely.
Former Prime Minister Li Peng, now chairman of the Chinese
legislature, has been leading the ranks of old-line leaders in
attacking the United States for aggression in Yugoslavia, charges
that have no direct connection to the trade talks but that
inevitably affect the flexibility of Chinese negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Li argued that the bombing had enabled Chinese
people to see ``the hypocrisy of the democracy and human rights
advocated by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He denounced the Western view that student demonstrations in
Beijing and other cities had been orchestrated by the leadership in
order to gain better leverage in the trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said that the final areas of disagreement
with Beijing were over financial services. The Americans have
sought full rights for foreign banks operating in China to do
business in local and foreign currencies and to serve both Chinese
and foreign customers.
</P>
<P>
   Too many operating restrictions on American banks, insurers and
other financial companies are discouraging them from doing business
in China, American negotiators have said. In response, Chinese
officials maintain that making the rules even for Chinese and
foreign banks could disastrous for China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
