<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE CONDEMNATIONS OF U.S. COULD REFLECT POLICY SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's leaders are continuing to condemn the United
States in harsh terms following the NATO attack on the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, reflecting what may be an
important shift in China's view of global politics.
</P>
<P>
   A front-page commentary in Monday's People's Daily, the official
newspaper of the governing Communist Party, said that NATO's air
assault in Yugoslavia was part of an American ``global strategy for
world hegemony.'' It charged that the United States was engaged in
``a new form of colonialism,'' using pretexts like human rights to
turn other countries into dependents.
</P>
<P>
   The article called the air campaign an ``aggressive war'' that
was ``groundless in morality or law,'' part of a plot by the United
States and its partners to destroy Yugoslavia, expand eastward and
control all of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That portrayal of American intentions comes as China is also
telling the student demonstrators against the United States to get
back to work and urging Western companies to keep investing here.
But it contrasts with the more nuanced views expressed by leaders
here in the last two years, before NATO began its air attacks to
halt the persecution of Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, President Jiang Zemin praised President Clinton and
said China was pursuing a ``strategic partnership'' with the United
States despite disagreements over human rights, Taiwan and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Even before China's Embassy was attacked by mistake on the night
of May 7, causing an outpouring of anti-American rage here, China
strongly condemned NATO's military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   NATO had bypassed the United Nations, where China has veto power
_ a sign to China that its views were not respected. China also
sees the bombing in Yugoslavia as a dangerous precedent for
possible foreign involvement in Taiwan or Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, China has said it hopes to continue
building commercial ties with the United States despite the
anti-Americanism in evidence last week as students stoned the
American Embassy here. And life has returned to normal in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's article and continued praise of a speech Jiang made
last Thursday suggest that China may adopt a more assertive stance
on international political issues.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese defense experts are depicting the bombing of the embassy
in Belgrade as the latest in a series of American steps intended to
hem China in and obstruct its rise as a major power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eastward expansion of NATO in Europe, the strengthening of
the U.S.-Japanese military alliance in the Asian and Pacific region
and the launching of the current aggression against Yugoslavia,''
People's Daily said, ``all constitute an important step in the
United States' strategy for world hegemony.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, after eulogizing the three newspaper and news
service employees killed in the Belgrade embassy as ``revolutionary
martyrs,'' Jiang made a statement that officials have since been
instructed to study.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to keep China on the path of economic reforms. But he
also said, ``The United States continues to pursue hegemonism and
power politics, and wantonly interferes in the internal affairs of
other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats here are debating whether Jiang has had a true change
of heart or is seeking to pre-empt military leaders and other
hard-liners who feel that China has been too friendly with the
United States. In either case, the official line on the United
States has changed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
