A0630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-COX     05-17 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Knicks coach gets job done as team moves on
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The game was over. New York had knocked off Pat Riley
and the Miami Heat on Sunday. And as his team celebrated on the
floor, Jeff Van Gundy was on the sideline, yelling at an official,
as if a poor call had cost his team advancement to the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   It was Van Gundy at his best: always coaching.
</P>
<P>
   He rightfully was upset that, with 0.8 seconds left, Miami's
Terry Porter received an inbounds pass, pump-faked, dribbled and
still got off a shot before the final buzzer sounded. It appeared
to be too little time for anything more than catch and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Because the shot missed, it did not matter _ to anyone but Van
Gundy, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The embattled coach whose job security might have strengthened
with the Knicks' gutty conquest in Miami has endured as difficult a
season as anyone in the NBA, so maybe he was just letting off some
compressed steam before joining the hijinks.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Van Gundy stormed off the floor looking like
the loser, flailing expletives over his shoulder about a play that
didn't matter, which was more an indication of the winner in him
than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff and I had our differences when I was there,'' said former
Knicks guard John Starks, now with the Golden State Warriors. ``But
he realized, and I realized about him that we just want to win in
the worst way. He pushed me, he coached me. And I know that's what
he did with that team because that's what he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever was wrong with the team (earlier in the season), it
wasn't because Jeff didn't coach them right. I know that. He
learned under Pat Riley, and you can see that. He'll battle for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole season has been a battle for Van Gundy, 37. He was not
happy with the trade of Charles Oakley to Toronto for Marcus Camby,
a talented player whose grit and determination have been
questioned. And when he did not play Camby much early, Van Gundy
and Ernie Grunfeld, then the Knicks president, were at odds. When
it became clear that either or both could be fired, all kinds of
speculation spread, including a well-traveled rumor that Van Gundy
planted stories in the media to benefit him and belittle Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy would not dignify such talk, but Grunfeld ended up
getting fired by friend and Madison Square Garden president Dave
Checketts with eight games left in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks struggled to make the playoffs but have upset Miami
and now face a team with which they are evenly matched. High
expectations have returned to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Van Gundy's job isn't safe just yet. In an interview
during Sunday's game, Checketts said the coach would be evaluated
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a growing sentiment that the job he's done this
season has been superlative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the very best in the league,'' Riley said. ``He's
one of the youngest and brightest, and I think right now Jeff is
showing you why he is that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
