<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-WATSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON EAGER TO RETURN TO COLONIAL AS DEFENDING CHAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Week by week, Tom Watson has tried to maintain
a stoic approach to his farewell journey through the PGA Tour
schedule.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But he admits to occasional cracks in the facade. There are days
when the emotions race, the memories overwhelm and the tear ducts
seep.
</P>
<P>
   It happened at Pebble Beach Golf Links, site of Watson's
signature stroke in a hall of fame career: a chip-in for birdie on
the 71st hole of the 1982 U.S. Open that secured a victory against
Jack Nicklaus. It happened at the Hawaiian Open, an event Watson
never won but a trip he considers an annual highlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the handwriting on the wall,'' said Watson, 49, whose
focus will shift to the Senior PGA Tour when he turns 50 on Sept.
4. ``At tournaments I've really enjoyed, I'll think, `Wow. This is
the last time I'll ever play here.' There is a little nostalgia in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But no place, in Watson's estimation, figures to trigger a
warmer inner glow than the one he will feel on the first tee
Thursday in the opening round of the MasterCard Colonial. It will
be there that Thomas Sturges Watson, winner of 34 events during a
25-year career, will likely be introduced as a defending champion
for the final time at a PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   Watson considers his Colonial triumph, with which he displaced
Ben Hogan as the oldest winner in tournament history, as one of the
most emotional of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be my last victory on the PGA Tour. You bet, I'm
nostalgic when I think about that,'' said Watson, who has won twice
in the past 12 seasons. ``That was a very emotional, very special
day. It was a surprise because I wasn't sure if I'd ever win
another tournament. You can't help but think that way at my age.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ability to compete out here is winding down. But you never
know when you're at the end. Sometimes, I feel like I'm at the end.
Other times, I feel like, `Bring on Tiger.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, alas, will not have Tiger Woods to kick around at the
1999 Colonial. Enticed by a six-figure appearance fee, Woods will
compete this week at a European Tour event in Heidelberg, Germany.
Watson, on the other hand, hopes to collect a six-figure paycheck
the old-fashioned way: with a victory on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to do my best to fire one more parting shot,'' said
Watson, winner of eight major championships, including five British
Open titles. ``I want to beat these kids one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he knows that the deck appears stacked against him.
Slowed by a shoulder injury that required a cortisone injection in
April, Watson hasn't cracked the top 10 at a PGA Tour event this
season. He hasn't survived the cut at a major championship since
the 1997 British Open. But at Colonial, for one final fling, he
will be The Man.
</P>
<P>
   When September arrives, Watson might become the first
professional golfer to threepeat the Fort Worth-Dallas area as a
two-tour competitor in the same season. Watson, who participated
last week in the GTE Byron Nelson Classic, will be eligible to
participate in the area's new Senior PGA Tour event, the Bank One
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 17-19 event at Bent Tree Country Club in Dallas could
mark Watson's debut on the 50-and-older circuit. The Colonial champ
said he is undecided on his schedule for 1999 Senior PGA Tour
events. But he expressed plans to curtail a typical fall schedule
that leans heavily toward bird hunting in favor of trying to bag
more birdies on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   No one was happier to hear that news than Bruce Edwards,
Watson's caddie for most of 25 seasons as a PGA Tour participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to his age, it's tough trying to beat these
22-year-olds whose nerves are a little better than his,'' Edwards
said. ``There's no question he'll do very well on the Senior Tour.
Once he gets that feeling of winning again consistently, like he
had 20 years ago, he'll be off and running. I'm looking at the end
of this season and next year being similar to 1977, when he started
to dominate the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1977-82, Watson won 26 tournaments, an average of 4.3 per
season. Senior Tour participants do not question that it's possible
Watson could double that number in his first full season on a
circuit in which Hale Irwin won 16 events in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy like Tom raises the bar out here,'' said David Graham, a
Dallas resident in his fourth season on the Senior PGA Tour. ``When
he tees it up, a lot of other guys will start playing for second. I
expect him to have a big, big impact.''
</P>
<P>
   But September, and anticipated Senior PGA Tour success, must
wait. For four months, Watson must contend with the flatbellies on
the PGA Tour. And he must defend one more title, this week at
Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like I can compete, especially at a course where
I'm comfortable, like Colonial,'' said Watson, who boasts the best
career scoring average (69.96) of any competitor who has played in
at least 20 Colonials. ``Now, for Tom Watson, we let the chips fall
where they may. Certainly, it would be nice to go out strong.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
