<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT &LR;      05-17 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING BILL FULL OF PORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mississippi, Alaska, Utah, Pennsylvania, West Virginia)  (dal) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A little item temporarily attached itself, like a
barnacle riding a whale, to the $15-billion emergency spending deal
lashed together by congressional negotiators last week.
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the bill was $8.1 million to repair a storm-battered
Army National Guard armory. The public draft of the bill never said
the armory was in Gulfport, Miss., home state of Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, who requested the money.
</P>
<P>
   But the item vanished sometime between late Thursday night, when
the negotiators struck a deal, and late Friday night, when printers
struck the proofs of the daily Congressional Record, containing the
first public version of the bill in final form, said Senate and
House aides.
</P>
<P>
   It was a case of ``hot pork, cold feet,'' a Democratic aide
said. The spending for the armory had been erased at Lott's
request. ``Lott thought he'd show some leadership by asking for his
own little project to go,'' said a senior Republican aide.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's little project was not the only provision inserted into
the emergency bill without public discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Such programs flow from outbursts of altruism and opportunism
peculiar to Congress. The emergency spending bill, which helps
finance not only the war in Yugoslavia but disaster relief in the
Americas, is a perfect vehicle for them. Since the big bill, which
comes to the House floor for a vote on Tuesday, must pass, little
riders hop onto it. The process has been compared to feeding the
horses to feed the pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, said, ``Senator Lott is doing
everything in his power to make sure the bill is as clean and
skinny as possible.'' Democratic aides said Lott withdrew the money
after reporters inquired about it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lott and Speaker J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois urged
the Senate and House conferees to stick to the basics in the
emergency bill. The chairman of the House Appropriations Committee,
Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., worked to keep it free of riders and
amendments offered by House and Senate appropriators.
</P>
<P>
   The money ``is all about helping people,'' Young said. But if
the bill is passed as printed, its beneficiaries will include some
people beyond Pentagon personnel and victims of war and disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, home of Sen. Ted Stevens, the Republican chairman of
the Senate Appropriations Committee, commercial fishermen get $26
million to compensate them for federal fishing restrictions, and
commercial reindeer ranchers get $3 million to protect them from
deaths in their herds.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, home of the Republican Sen. Robert F. Bennett, Salt
Lake City gets $2.2 million for sewers for the 2002 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Washington, House pages get $3.76 million to redo their
dormitory, and the local airports get $30 million for renovations.
</P>
<P>
   In North Union Township in Pennsylvania, in the district of Rep.
John Murtha, a senior Democrat on the Appropriations Committee, the
local government gets to keep an unstated amount of leftover money
from a federally financed land-development project.
</P>
<P>
   One provision that, like Lott's armory money, appeared and then
disappeared into thin air, would have authorized the secretary of
the Air Force to lease up to six Gulfstream V executive jets for
nine of the nation's most senior generals and admirals.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force and congressional estimates placed the cost of the
lease at $478 million or more over 10 years. The House-Senate
conference did not debate the provision last week, and its public
working papers did not mention the Gulfstream jets by name or spell
out their potential costs.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican appropriations committee aide said the request for
the lease became ``a hot issue,'' given the original intent of the
military spending bill: financing the bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The unpublished Senate draft of the bill specified that a new
prison be built in West Virginia, home state of Sen. Robert C.
Byrd, the Appropriations Committee's ranking Democrat. The printed
version says ``a mid-Atlantic state'' will get the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The $15-billion bill going to the House floor on Tuesday grew
from President Clinton's requests for more than $7 billion for
military and refugee-relief operations in the Balkans and
disaster-assistance for hurricane victims in Central America and
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the $15 billion will finance NATO's military
operations in Yugoslavia. Another third will go to the Pentagon for
programs added by congressional negotiators, including a
$1.84-billion package of military pay and pension increases,
covering generals and admirals as well as privates and seamen. The
pay increase still must be authorized by Congress, and its final
form could change.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from Kosovo and the survivors of last year's hurricanes
in Central America and the Caribbean each will receive aid packages
of about $1 billion. American victims of tornadoes, storms and
floods will receive about $900 million. American farmers crippled
by low prices will get $547 million, $422 million more than Clinton
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Despite threatening a veto if the bill strayed beyond providing
for the needs of war and disaster, Clinton has indicated he will
sign it if Congress approves it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
