<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-PHOBIA-DRUGS-A     05-17 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-PHOBIA-DRUGS-ART-893(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGMAKERS SEE OPPORTUNITY IN TREATING SOCIAL PHOBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ariz., Pa., Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By ANURADHA RAGHUNATHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hasan Yildiz has never visited a friend's house because he has
never had a friend. He has never dated, either. And he never goes
to bars, restaurants or ball games because his chest tightens and
he breaks into a sweat when he is around people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a loner by choice,'' said Yildiz, a 19-year-old
freshman at Bronx Community College who rarely goes beyond
``hello'' in interactions with his classmates. ``I like being with
people, but I always get scared and nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Yildiz suffers from an extreme form of shyness called social
phobia. First formally identified in 1980, social phobia ranks
today as the third most prevalent psychiatric disorder in the
United States after substance abuse and depression, affecting an
estimated 19 million Americans, according to the Anxiety Disorders
Association of America. Many are too bashful even to talk to
therapists. Yildiz himself backed out of an appointment to have his
photo taken, saying he did not want his classmates to see him in
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't require group interaction to pop a pill. And just
as the pharmaceutical industry has introduced medicines in recent
years to alleviate such common afflictions as obesity, baldness and
sexual impotence, it now sees a huge market in social anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, companies do not have to spend huge sums to develop a
new blockbuster drug to do the job. SmithKline Beecham P.L.C. won
approval lasy week from the Food and Drug Administration to market
its antidepressant Paxil for social phobia. And other companies are
close behind. Solvay S.A. of Belgium is conducting pilot trials in
the United States of its drug Luvox, which it already sells under a
different name in the United Kingdom to treat the ailment.
Likewise, the American Home Products Corp. plans to begin clinical
trials for its antidepressant Effexor for the same purpose, and
Pfizer Inc. is experimenting with its Zoloft.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts view social phobia as the latest battleground for
the antidepressants known as selective serotonin reuptake
inhibitors. They believe the three leading drugs of this family _
Paxil, Zoloft and Eli Lilly &AMP; Co.'s Prozac _ can be used almost
interchangeably, making their manufacturers eager to find new uses
for them to make them stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is sure how much money is to be made from social phobia
medication _ but 19 million is a lot of people, representing about
7 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire mental health sector is at a stage where
cardiovascular diseases were at 20 years ago,'' said Stephen Scala,
a pharmaceutical analyst with S.G. Cowen Securities. ``There is
still a lot we do not know about these mental disorders. We are at
the very early stages of another big market opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Awareness of the malady's prevalence came slowly to the
industry. Dr. Michael Liebowitz, director of the Anxiety Disorders
Clinic in New York and a consultant to pharmaceutical companies,
said that in the early 1980s, studies indicated that only 2 percent
to 3 percent of the population suffered from social phobia. But a
decade later, he said, researchers were finding that the number was
closer to 8 percent or 9 percent. At that point, he said,
drugmakers started conducting clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 5 percent of the population that suffers from social
phobia is receiving treatment,'' said Bonnie Rossello, a vice
president with SmithKline Beecham's neuroscience division. ``This
disorder is very pervasive, but it is underdiagnosed and
undertreated.''
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers fear that in addition to social phobia, milder
forms of shyness are also going to grow. They say that the
increasing dependency on technology is creating a socially awkward
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are growing up with few opportunities for social
interactions,'' said Philip Zimbardo, a psychology professor at
Stanford University who started the Stanford Shyness Research
Program in the early 1970s. ``The cousins, uncles and aunts with
whom children practiced social skills are no longer around.
Moreover, an increasingly technological society has reduced human
interaction. There is more interface with ATM's, answering machines
and the Internet than with human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   But are drugs the answer? A lot of therapists don't think so.
They fear that many Americans suffering from ordinary shyness might
seek solace in prescription medication. Better, they insist, to
confront the problem the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is much easier to pop a pill; it is tough to do therapy,''
said Dr. Jonathan Berent, a psychologist who runs a shyness
institute in Great Neck, N.Y. ``Shy people have to go through scary
social situations week after week when they come for therapy.''
Berent criticizes drugs as too easy an alternative, adding, ``Once
patients discontinue the drugs there will be a relapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a cottage industry of psychotherapy has sprouted to ease
the social anxieties of the seriously shy. Whereas help groups were
almost nonexistent a decade ago, at least 15 major institutes and
100 support organizations cater to victims of the disorder today,
according to mental health specialists. In addition, more than
1,000 therapists with expertise in the field are listed with either
the Association for Advancement of Behavior Therapy or the Anxiety
Disorders Association of America.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Palo Alto, Calif., Lynne Henderson, a social psychologist,
runs a center called the Shyness Clinic for easing the
apprehensions of bashful Silicon Valley professionals. Participants
go through a 26-week therapy program and are given a thorough
rubdown on such social skills as how to make eye contact, how to
edit out embarrassing pauses in conversations and how to pick up
the phone and actually set a date to do something with somebody.
They also get homework assignments that include commenting on the
weather to strangers in the supermarket and saying hello to 10
people at an office party.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henderson, who charges $440 to $880 for diagnostic tests,
$60 for group sessions and $110 an hour for telephone
consultations, is a staunch advocate of therapy as the first line
of defense against shyness. ``We offer a social fitness model where
we emphasize that everybody needs to get in shape,'' she said. ``If
we see it as a disorder, it will be much tougher to get people to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, Dr. Thomas A. Richards is tapping into the shyness
market with entrepreneurial zeal. His Anxiety Clinic offers
sessions of games and exercises aimed at motivating patients to be
more outgoing. In one of them, called the Circle of Death,
participants go around the room introducing themselves to one
another. Patients have a choice between sessions lasting nearly two
hours and those lasting all day; the latter are videotaped and
played back to show participants how they are performing.
</P>
<P>
   Richards' price ranges from a few hundred dollars for
abbreviated programs to $6,860 for an intensive four-week course
for out-of-towners, though he lowers some fees based on income
levels. He is also preparing a set of instructional audio cassettes
that he plans to sell for $350.
</P>
<P>
   For some, therapy is a godsend. Barry Greenblatt, a 39-year-old
supervisor with the New York City Police Department's 911 emergency
line, recently completed a 10-week session at the West Side Social
and Performance Anxiety Workshop and plans to keep taking the $250
course until he overcomes his extreme shyness.
</P>
<P>
   Greenblatt said he had had a limited social life and found it
difficult to get a date because of his habit of staring fixedly at
people while they talk. ``Two years ago I felt that I had to do
something about this,'' he said. ``I felt that there was no need to
go on living if I could not get over this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the MCP Hahnemann University in Philadelphia, a treatment
program for adolescents is being offered without charge, financed
by a $600,000 grant from the National Institute of Mental Health.
``We are networking with schools here so that the kids can be
identified early on,'' said Dr. James Herbert, assistant professor
of psychology. ``The problem, however, is that teachers notice only
the acting-out kids. The shy ones are just not visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Visible or not, more and more companies are seeing the profit
potential of shyness. Studies by Zimbardo of Stanford University
and by Bernardo Carducci, director of the Shyness Research
Institute of Indiana University Southeast, indicate that 40 percent
to 50 percent of all Americans are shy.
</P>
<P>
   That is too large a market for publishers to ignore.
HarperCollins has just published ``Shyness: A Bold New Approach:
The Latest Findings Plus Practical Steps For Finding Your Comfort
Zone,'' by Carducci. And Simon &AMP; Schuster has come out with ``How I
Overcame Shyness: 101 Celebrities Share Their Secrets,'' edited by
Gary Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical companies argue that the two basic approaches to
treating social phobia _ therapy and drugs _ can coexist and in
some cases complement each other. They insist that antidepressants
should not be used for all forms of shyness, just for the severe
variety.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge lies in diagnosing the condition. Psychologists
and the sufferers themselves are constantly grappling with the
question of where shyness ends and social phobia begins. The rule
of thumb is that social phobia seriously impairs normal
functioning.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry has started a campaign to make
physicians and the general public aware of the distinction _ and of
the availability of drugs for the clinical cases. SB Pharmaceutical
has provided a grant of an unspecified sum to the Coalition on
Social Anxiety Disorders for a public awareness campaign with the
theme ``Imagine being allergic to people.'' The coalition members _
the Anxiety Disorders Association of America, the American
Psychiatric Association and a New York advocacy organization called
Freedom From Fear _ are also circulating a videocassette among
physicians describing the symptoms of social phobia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, research into the condition continues. The National
Institute of Mental Health has been financing research at
universities and private clinics to study the efficacy of therapy,
drugs and a combination of drugs and therapy for treating social
phobia. And the New York State Psychiatric Institute is studying
the relationship between social phobia and stuttering.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from damaging people's self-esteem and robbing them of
friendships and the pleasures of everyday intermingling, social
phobia can be a career-killer. ``You typically have people
performing much below their potential,'' said Herbert of MCP
Hahnemann University. ``I had an Ivy League school graduate who
took to delivering candy to vending machines because he thought
that job did not require interaction with people. That is when you
need intervention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
