<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PHANTOMBIZ _  &LR; George Lucas's new ``Star Wars _ Episode One: The
Phantom Menace'' is sure to be a huge moneymaker, maybe even the
biggest grossing movie of all time. But even if Lucas doesn't sell
a single ticket, he's already more than made up the cost of
production through various toy and book licensing deals. This was
Lucas's genius from the beginning: In 1977, he sold the first movie
to Twentieth Century Fox, but kept the merchandising rights.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the studios never realized the worth of such
ancillary products, but Lucas used that money to finance production
of all his sequels and build his empire in Marin County. And now we
see companies like Disney reaping far more revenues from selling
products based on movie characters than from the movie ticket sales
themselves. By Dan Fost
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SILIGAP &LR;  _ Silicon Valley's workforce falls short of meeting
high tech employers' needs by about one-third, a workforce ``gap''
that costs employers about $3 billion annually in recruiting costs
and lost productivity, according to report released Tuesday by
Joint Venture: Silicon Valley Network. Too many workers have to be
recruited from outside the valley, yet the study also shows Silicon
Valley high school students had little interest in pursuing
high-tech majors in college. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEC  &LR; _ The SEC charged two former executives at Insignia Inc.
of Fremont with fraud for understating product inventory to falsely
pump up revenue by nearly $1 million. The fraud, which occurred
during the first quarter of 1996, forced the company to restate
earnings the next year. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
