<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO DECIDE WHETHER STATES CAN SELL DRIVER'S LICENSE DATA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide
whether the federal government may order states not to sell
personal information gleaned from driver's licence applications to
companies and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, amid reports that a killer collected data about his
victim from an application, enacted the 1994 Driver's Privacy
Protection Act to bar states from selling the information. But
South Carolina challenged the law as an unconstitutional
infringement on the right of states to administer their records as
they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to hear arguments in the case, Reno
vs. Condon, this fall or early next year and render their decision
by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial federal law prohibits any state motor-vehicle
agency from ``knowingly'' disclosing or making available to people
or companies ``personal information about any individual obtained
by the department in connection with a motor-vehicle record.''
Exceptions to the law permit states to provide information for a
``state-authorized purpose relating to the operation of a motor
vehicle or public safety'' or to give the data to
automobile-insurance firms and towing companies after a car has
been impounded.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law after it was revealed that Rebecca
Schaeffer's killer, Robert John Bardo, was able in 1989 to track
down the California home address of the television actress through
state motor-vehicle records.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina challenged the law's constitutionality, winning
in both a federal district court and then in the 4th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals. The 4th Circuit called the federal restriction on
the state dissemination of driver's license information
inconsistent ``with the system of dual sovereignty established by
the Constitution'' between the federal and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   In successfully urging the Supreme Court to hear the case, the
Clinton administration said the federal law is necessary to protect
the privacy of citizens who seek only a license to drive.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Solicitor General Seth Waxman, the administration's chief
lawyer before the high court, noted that data, which can be gleaned
from driver's license applications, include the name, address and
telephone numbers of motorists, many of whom might otherwise seek
to keep that information private by refusing to list it in
telephone directories. In some cases, the information can also
contain a photograph of the motorist as well as his or her Social
Security number and medical information bearing on the person's
ability to drive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of driver's license records can also be quite lucrative
for states, as New York in one recent year earned $17 million from
individuals and businesses who sought access to the information,
Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   In other high court news, the justices on Monday upheld by a 7-2
vote the constitutionality of a Florida law that permits police
without a warrant to seize and search automobiles suspected of
having been used in the commission of a crime. Writing for the
majority, Justice Clarence Thomas said the Fourth Amendment's
prohibition on unreasonable searches and seizures does not apply to
suspect cars parked in public places because the police must act
fast before the cars are driven away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
