r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COLONIAL-2099-TEX     05-17 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-2099-TEX </SLUG>
 
What will Colonial's tournament look like in 2099? (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: From equipment to economics, the golf industry
faces several issues that could lead to major changes in the game
and the PGA Tour in the 21st century. How might they affect the
MasterCard Colonial? Join us as we peer into our dimpled, crystal
ball and check out final-round coverage of Fort Worth's annual tour
stop, circa 2099.
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Keeping alive a family tradition, Davis Love VI
collected the latest plaid jacket among a group of golfers who have
four generations of Colonial blazers in their respective closets.
</P>
<P>
   Love achieved his record-breaking triumph in a most
untraditional manner, however. Under the warm glow of floodlights
erected for the first night finish in the tournament's 153-year
history, he overpowered Colonial Country Club with a controversial
driver that is being investigated by U.S. Golf Association
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Love, 37, is the first player to successfully harness the new
Plutonic driver, which propels shots off the club face with the
explosiveness of plutonium but without the radioactive
repercussions. Combining the metal-headed club with an Elastiphite
shaft, a graphite-elastic mixture that permits wraparound
backswings and generates excessive clubhead speeds, Love routinely
blasted 400-yard drives during a closing round of 56 at the
American Airlines-Alcon-MasterCard Colonial presented by Rolaids
and Pace Picante Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Love's score, the lowest recorded at a professional golf
tournament, allowed him to come from 10 strokes off the pace to nip
third-round leader Leopard Woods by one shot. The victory was
Love's first in five years at a Samsung-Microsoft Global Golf Tour
event and sparked controversy about more than his choice of clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, great-grandson of five-time Masters champ Tiger Woods,
was assessed a pivotal two-stroke penalty on the 14th hole in the
final round. Videotapes taken from the ``caddie cam'' atop the
Robocaddie that carries Woods' clubs clearly show that the player
improperly grounded his wedge in his haste to hit from one of the
quicksand traps installed in 2076 to make scoring conditions more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, however, disputed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get it out of there quick, before the ball gurgled
beneath the surface. But I was sure I didn't touch my club to the
ground before I hit,'' Woods said. ``This is really disappointing.
I should have won this tournament. I just couldn't catch a break
from the rules official. I guess the Woods name doesn't carry the
same clout out here that it once did. `Gramps' told me that when he
missed a fairway, they used to move boulders for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday at Colonial, the primary mover was Love, who bagged 10
birdies and two eagles in mounting the greatest final-round
comeback in tour history. Playing under the lights to allow for a
10 p.m. finish, as mandated by the tour's new $64 billion network
television contract, ``created a few more shadows, but nothing I
couldn't handle,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of a tailwind, Love drove the green at No. 5, a
560-yard par-4 with a new tee box in Forest Park that forces
golfers to hit over vehicles traveling south on Rogers Road. He
rolled home a 70-foot eagle putt at No. 11, a par-5 that features
the Incredi-cup, an electronic device that keeps the diameter of
the hole in constant flux _ varying between normal size and the
width of one golf ball _ while players putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timed it perfect,'' said Love, who set a tournament scoring
record (22-under par) in addition to his single-round mark. ``The
hole widened out right as my ball got there. This was unbelievable.
I caught every break I could. I'm still pinching myself to make
sure it's not a dream. I've never had a day like this. No one
has.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, he said, was ``extremely emotional'' because the
first three golfers named Davis Love to etch their names on
Colonial's Wall of Champions were in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Included was Davis Love III, the player's 135-year-old
great-grandfather who is among the first wave of benefactors from
scientific research in 2020 that discovered that the wonder drug
Viagra, if taken with ginseng root and bee pollen, slows the aging
process in adult males to 1/100th the normal rate. The elder Love
competes on the Super Senior Tour, where the minimum age for
participants is 95.
</P>
<P>
   But this day belonged to the latest Love namesake, who shed
tears as club officials draped the same plaid jacket across his
shoulders that his great-grandfather first wore in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-six years later, it's still the ugliest jacket on tour.
But I've always wanted one,'' Love said. ``I remember when I was
little, Dad would wear his when he took me trick-or-treating. All
the neighbors would laugh their heads off. But I thought it was
neat. It made for some special memories.''
</P>
<P>
   With the $6.8 million winner's check, Love said, he plans to buy
``some matching pants.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he is unconcerned about a USGA probe of the
Plutonic driver, a club that debuted this season but which few
players have been able to control as well as Love. The 12-year
touring pro split 13 of 14 fairways and averaged 402.3 yards per
drive in the final round. Love hit no approach shots with a club
longer than a 9-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a secret to hitting it,'' Love said. ``I just figured
it out this week. But I'm going to be like Ben Hogan. I'm not
sharing my secret with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   USGA officials have said they will add the Plutonic driver,
which features a head made of a metallic mixture of nonradioactive
plutonium, titanium, chromium, barium and calcium, to the list of
clubs being studied to determine whether the club face produces too
much of a ``springlike effect'' at impact. The probe has been
ongoing since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see them outlawing it,'' Love said. ``They've never
won a major court case against a manufacturer yet. Until someone
yanks it out of my hands, I intend to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday at Colonial, he used it to move into the tour record
books. And to continue a family tradition. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
