<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-DISTANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSESSION WITH LONG DISTANCE DRIVES TODAY'S GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Drive for show
</P>
<P>
   Putt for dough''
</P>
<P>
   _ ancient golf wisdom
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit it long
</P>
<P>
   And you can't go wrong''
</P>
<P>
   _ modern golf thinking
FORT WORTH, Texas _ In 1980, Dan Pohl led the PGA Tour in driving
distance with an average poke of 274.3 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the ball that far in 1999 and you will find yourself about
34 yards behind the drives of PGA Tour distance leader, John Daly,
whose average whack pushes up toward 309. The game's top players,
David Duval and Tiger Woods, each drive it about 290 yards on
average.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Hale Irwin averaged 250 yards a drive and
still won a U.S. Open. Hit it 250 these days and you'll need a cart
to catch up to your playing partners.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the game has changed. Everyone's hitting it longer, if
not always straighter, but who cares? Distance is everything, or so
it seems, even to the high-handicap weekend player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to hit it from the back tees these days,''
says David Bridges, who has been playing golf for 50 years and
teaching it for 20, including his stint at Randol Mill Golf Center
in Fort Worth. ``If I had a sign up that said I can teach you how
to hit it farther, and a guy down the street had a sign that said
he'd teach you to hit it straighter, they'd all come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's responsible for this obsession with long drives? Golfers
cite club and ball manufacturers who try to increase sales by
developing and promoting equipment they say will add yards. Others
cite television's influence, noting that Daly's ``grip it and rip
it'' philosophy is seductive even to duffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can just see all the blood running out of their fingers,''
Bridges says.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for yardage off the tee is the subject of countless
instructional videos and books. In the May issue of ``Golf Digest''
alone, several articles including the cover story deal with how to
hit it farther.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: One teaching pro offered thoughts on how to hit it ``10
more yards.'' In ``Tiger Tips,'' long-bomber Woods suggests that
golfers widen their stance ``when you really want to crush it.''
Another piece, ``How to buy more distance,'' offers suggestions on
what clubs will help you hit it farther.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's cover boy Jason Zuback, the three-time reigning
national long drive champion, who is shown in an inside photo
spread, frame by frame, as he grips it and rips it. It's a hack
Mark McGwire would be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   Distance isn't a bad thing, of course. For one, it allows you to
hit beyond troublesome traps and over water. Also, it can make for
shorter, easier approach shots, the kind that allow you to hit the
ball high and soft, and to drop it close to the pin giving you a
better chance on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming you hit it straight, though, and that's assuming
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Penneman of Arlington, a competitor in long-distance drive
events, typically hits it well beyond 300 yards, and when all
conditions are right can push it up to about 400 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he says, ``I'd give up 25 yards if I could put it in the
fairway 50 percent more often.''
</P>
<P>
   Penneman said he sees the pros and cons of hitting it so far. On
the plus side, he says, his length carries through the bag: he can
hit a 1-iron 270 yards so he'll play that straighter club in lieu
of a driver on many holes, giving him the best of both worlds. His
prodigious blasts also earn him regular invitations to scramble
events where, he says, partners and competitors ``ooh and ahh''
about his smashes over the practice range fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit it 250 and straight all day and nobody will watch you,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Pavlet, a long-drive competitor from Phoenix who once sent
one 462 yards, said: ``It's like in baseball. Tony Gwynn has
probably been the best hitter in the game. But he doesn't have the
mystique of McGwire or Sammy Sosa. Everybody wants to see the
Waveland Avenue \Rstreet beyond the outfield fence in Chicago's
Wrigley Field\S ball.''
</P>
<P>
   On the PGA Tour, too, length has been a sticky issue.
Traditionalists fear that many revered older and shorter courses
will be rendered obsolete as pros find they are able to fly over
obstacles en route to record-smashing scores. Woods' taming of
Augusta National a couple years ago fueled such paranoia. There has
been much debate about restricting club and ball technology so
munchkins don't hit them 300 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so alarmist, however. Greg Norman, in Fort Worth
recently, downplayed the distance issue.
</P>
<P>
   Length, schmength, he seemed to say. High handicappers still
can't break 100, and even pros aren't firing sub-60s week in and
week out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at average scores,'' Norman said. ``They aren't much
different than 30 or 40 years ago. Sam Snead once shot a 59 with
older-style equipment. It doesn't make as big a difference as some
people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, for every advocate of the joys and competitive advantages
of distance, there are those who urge taking delight in small ball.
In the same issue of ``Golf Digest'' that depicts long driver
Zuback contorting and cranking, there is mind-game advice from golf
guru Dr. Bob Rotella, who advises, ``To excel, you don't have to
hit it big.'' He points to little guy short drivers who've won
recently on the PGA Tour, including Jeff Sluman, Billy Andrade and
Brandel Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age,'' Rotella wrote, ``when everything seems
to be about power, it's hard to believe that guys who look more
average than you do can win on tour, but it's true. And in their
success lies a lesson.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
