<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT UPHOLDS DECISION TO DISCHARGE HIV-INFECTED OFFICER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court bolstered the president's power
as military commander in chief Monday by upholding a decision to
discharge an HIV-positive Air Force officer imprisoned for having
unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   The justices unanimously ruled that the military's highest court
overstepped its powers when it blocked a move by the president and
various military officials to force Maj. James Goldsmith from the
Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   A military law enacted in 1996 allows the president, and Defense
Department officials acting on his behalf, to fire commissioned
officers jailed for more than six months under a court-martial
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith, who is infected with the virus that causes AIDS, was
ordered by a superior officer to inform his sex partners of his
health status and to use methods, including condoms, to protect
against spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Goldsmith was convicted of having unprotected sex with
two women _ a civilian in 1989 and a fellow officer in 1993 _ in
violation of the ``safe-sex'' order.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith was sentenced to six years at Fort Leavenworth, Kan.,
but retained his rank and active military status. His appeal of the
conviction was rejected by an Air Force appellate court, but his
sentenced was reduced to three years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Goldsmith was notified that the Air Force was taking
steps to have him forced out _ or dropped from the rolls, as it is
called in the military _ by the president under the law enacted
only months earlier and more than two years after his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces blocked the
dismissal of Goldsmith, who currently is serving in the civil
engineering squadron at Lackland AFB near San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court's 3-2 ruling said ejecting Goldsmith from
the Air Force, which would deprive him of military health care,
under a subsequently enacted law amounts to double-jeopardy and ex
post facto punishment, both of which are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Supreme Court ruling, written by Justice David H.
Souter, said the decision to boot Goldsmith from the military was
an administrative decision and not part of the punishment meted out
by the court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Executive action to drop ... (Goldsmith) from the rolls falls
outside the ... (military court's) statutory jurisdiction,'' Souter
wrote, adding that other avenues of appeal are open to the officer.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith's attorney, John Economidy of San Antonio, said he and
the major plan, as suggested by the justices, to appeal the
discharge move to the Air Force Board of Correction for Military
Records.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Economidy said, he would try to negotiate with
the Air Force to end the litigation and the effort to forcibly
discharge Goldsmith, who on July 1 will have served 20 years, the
threshold for military retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
