<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPIES-AIRLINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPINE AIRLINES OWNER GETS ULTIMATUM FROM GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In yet another twist in one of Asia's
longest-running corporate dramas, Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has given the embattled owner of Philippine Airlines a week
to come up with $200 million for the debt-ridden company.
</P>
<P>
   If the owner, Lucio C. Tan, cannot produce the funds by next
Sunday, Estrada will force him to relinquish control, according to
Jose Pardo, the Philippine minister of trade and industry, who
joined Estrada and Tan at a meeting at midnight on Sunday in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Pardo said Estrada would then auction Philippine Airlines to the
highest bidder. The airline, which is the oldest in Asia and is
known as PAL, has been sinking under $2.2 billion in debt and
eroding revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks partly to support from Estrada, Tan has held off his
creditors by promising to inject $200 million _ half his own money
and half from a partner. But his effort to find an outsider has
come to naught, as would-be investors, including other airlines,
have balked at his involvement in management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucio Tan has been dillydallying,'' Pardo said. ``We told him:
`You can't buy more time. We're denying you that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tan, who is attending a conference of investors here with
Estrada, did not return a call seeking comment. A tobacco-and-beer
tycoon, Tan is one of the richest men in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   If Estrada holds to his ultimatum, it may finally resolve the
future of Philippine Airlines, which was shut down by Tan last
September in a labor dispute and reopened with the intercession of
Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   The key word is ``may,'' since every previous climax in the PAL
story _ including the abrupt shutdown _ has proved to be a mere
prologue to further twists and turns. Estrada has taken a hard line
with Tan before, without forcing him to surrender his grip on the
57-year-old airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estrada still owes big favors to Lucio Tan for giving him the
financial resources to run for president,'' said Jim Eckes, an
aviation consultant at Indoswiss Aviation Ltd. in Hong Kong. ``But
I don't think, even with that closeness, it can help Tan to
maintain control this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tan's options were narrowed two weeks ago when one
of PAL's largest creditors, the Export-Import Bank of the United
States, announced plans to seize four of its planes.
</P>
<P>
   The bank had previously endorsed a plan to rehabilitate the
airline _ after Tan had agreed to cede day-to-day management to a
team of executives from Cathay Pacific Airlines. But Tan took back
the chief executive title in late April, relegating the team from
Cathay Pacific to a subordinate role.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for the Export-Import Bank, which attributes
many of PAL's problems to Tan. The bank withdrew its support and
warned Philippine regulators that it planned to seize four Boeing
747s.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Tan had tried to placate the creditors by
recruiting the German national airline, Lufthansa &UR; ,  &LR; to provide
consulting services. But Eckes said that was unlikely to satisfy
the banks unless it was accompanied by Tan's departure from
management.
</P>
<P>
   Pardo said that Tan now accepted that ``his management style has
not met the test of creditors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine government has taken charge of trying to find a
partner, and Pardo said he had received expressions of interest
from two investor groups, one in the Middle East and one in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged that it would be tough to wrest
Philippine Airlines from its controlling shareholder. Tan has
poured more than $500 million into PAL since he gained control of
the airline. Formerly a state company, it was spun off after the
ouster of the Philippine dictator Ferdinand E. Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes he can see a light at the end of the tunnel,
because of his efforts to streamline the operations,'' Pardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Philippine Airlines has whittled down its costs by
selling planes and cutting its work force to 8,800 from 14,000,
analysts say it is still one of the most bloated Asian carriers. To
be profitable with its current fleet of 22 planes, Eckes said PAL
would have to cut its work force 50 percent further.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Tan has in his favor is Estrada's unflagging desire to
keep the flagship airline of the Philippines aloft. But Pardo said
Tan's intractable attitude was fraying the president's patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Tan, `You're putting to test a relationship,' '' he
said. ``It's bordering on presumptuousness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
