<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S GOVERNING PARTY OPENS NATIONAL PRIMARY TO ALL VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The governing party Monday formally broke with the
tradition under which Mexican presidents have handpicked their
successors, approving extensive new party rules to govern a
nationwide primary election, scheduled for November 7, that will
select its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules, approved Monday in nearly unanimous votes at a
party convention here, were immediately scrutinized by skeptical
politicians and analysts searching for ways in which they might
allow President Ernesto Zedillo to maintain presidential control
over the nomination. But several analysts said the rules appeared
to leave few ways to fix the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to conceive of a new system that's as radical a
change as possible from the old one, then this is it,'' said
Federico Estevez, a prominent political scientist here. ``This
system is just not very controllable. The risk will be great for
the president that his man, if he has one, won't be selected. Money
and influence will matter, but all kinds of surprises can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, written by party leaders appointed by
Zedillo, all Mexican citizens with voting credentials will be
allowed to participate in the primary. The governing party, known
as the PRI, experimented for the first time with primary elections
in several gubernatorial races last year, concluding that opening
the nominating process to Mexican voters helped restore party
popularity. PRI fortunes had dropped so dramatically over the
previous decade that in 1997 the party for the first time lost
control of the federal Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party, whose Spanish initials
are PRI, has won every presidential election since its founding in
1929, and each of 10 successive presidential candidates since
Manuel Avila Camacho in 1940 has been designated by their
predecessor in a secret process known as the ``dedazo,'' literally
the ``fingering of the candidate.'' The rules outlined Monday
formally abolish that autocratic tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to Monday's convention, Jose Antonio Gonzalez
Fernandez, whom Zedillo appointed as party president in March,
acknowledged that the old nominating system ``converted the
presidential succession into a traumatic and conflictive moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the name of the man or woman who will be the PRI's
presidential candidate will no longer come out of the president's
office,'' Gonzalez said. ``I don't expect, as party leader, to
receive a telephone call with the name of somebody who is the
designated candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez made his speech in a meeting at PRI headquarters in
downtown Mexico City of the PRI's National Political Council, made
up of some 350 congressional deputies, labor bosses, former Mexico
City mayors, rural political chiefs, and other senior party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules the council approved Monday, PRI politicians who
wish to appear on the ballot in the primary must resign their
government posts by June 15, register as pre-candidates by July 15,
and begin barnstorming for votes only on August 1, when the formal
primary campaign would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed rules, potential candidates would have to
agree to participate in a public debate among all contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Nov. 7 primary will be the candidate
attracting a majority of votes in the largest number of the
country's 300 electoral districts, rather than winning a simply
majority of votes nationwide. The candidate will be formally sworn
in as the PRI candidate on Nov. 20. The presidential elections are
scheduled for July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules will force at least four PRI politicians who have
expressed interest in the nomination to resign public posts if they
wish to contend: the interior minister, Francisco Labastida Ochoa,
the social development minister, Esteban Moctezuma Barragan, the
governor of Tabasco state, Roberto Madrazo Pintado, and the
governor of Veracruz, Miguel Aleman Velasco.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo and two other PRI leaders, Manuel Bartlett Diaz, the
ex-governor of Puebla state, and Humberto Roque Villanueva, a
former party president, are already campaigning openly for the
nomination and will apparently be forced to suspend their
activities, which have included expensive television campaigns,
until the formal opening of the campaign in August.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, the PRI is to issue campaign spending limits
and establish a new party committee to monitor fundraising and
spending by those seeking the nomination.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zedillo first formally proposed that the PRI revise its
candidate selection procedures in a March speech short on details.
Zedillo's aides later interpreted the speech as outlining a system
in which not one nationwide but several regional primaries would
elect delegates to a subsequent party convention, American-style,
which would pick the PRI candidate. Many analysts said that
proposal would allow Zedillo to maintain control over the
nominating process, by packing the convention if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Under the nominating rules outlined Monday, however, a party
convention simply does not figure; the PRI's presidential nominee
will emerge as the winner of the nationwide primary. One analyst
who criticized the process Zedillo outlined in March was Augustin
Basave, an ex-congressman who has founded a PRI caucus pressing for
increased party democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised,'' Basave said Monday. ``I thought the
president and his men would look for some kind of safety valve that
would give them a way to eliminate candidates they don't like. But
if there's no party convention, then that's one less barrier to
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, political analysts have been insisting that
Labastida, the interior minister, is Zedillo's preferred candidate.
In a nationwide poll published Monday by the Mexico City newspaper
El Universal, however, Labastida trailed Aleman, the Veracruz
governor, among voter preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The likely candidate of the pro-business National Action Party,
Vicente Fox Quesada, led in the poll. A distant second was
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, the leftist Mexico City mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
