<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-NYT     05-17 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IN THE NEWS: EHUD BARAK, AGAIN IN COMMAND
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The man who was elected prime minister of Israel on
Monday is accustomed to being in command: Ehud Barak, 57, left the
military just four years ago, after a beribboned 36-year career as
platoon leader, tank-battalion chief, senior intelligence analyst
and, from 1991 to 1995, head of the Israeli Army general staff.
</P>
<P>
   In a breathtakingly rapid political ascent, the freshly retired
lieutenant general was appointed interior minister in the Labor
government led by Yitzhak Rabin. After Rabin's assassination in
1995, Barak became foreign minister under Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, with the dust barely brushed off his epaulets, he
seized control of the Labor Party in the aftermath of Peres' loss
to Benjamin Netanyahu in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As his television advertisements relentlessly reminded Israeli
voters, Barak is the most decorated soldier in the country's
history. The late Rabin, another general-turned-politician, was
said to have remarked long ago that if Barak did not one day become
chief of staff, ``there is something wrong with the system.''
</P>
<P>
   His most celebrated military exploit _ the 1972 storming of a
Sabena airliner hijacked by Palestinian guerrillas at Tel Aviv's
airport _ is seen in retrospect as a classic Barak operation in its
meticulous planning and precise execution. All 97 hostages were
freed. The elite antiterror unit he commanded, the Sayeret Matkal,
included Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Burnishing his reputation, Barak crossed into Lebanon a year
later disguised as a woman on a mission in which three leaders of
the Palestine Liberation Organization were assassinated in their
Beirut hideout.
</P>
<P>
   But like many career military officers, Barak is not a man of
bravado, associates say, but of ``extraordinary caution,''
methodically assessing input from many sources before making
irrevocable decisions. He approached the election campaign not like
a former commando, they say, but like the Stanford-trained systems
analyst that he also is.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by Labor's one-point defeat in 1996, when he served as
campaign manager, Barak attributed the loss not to Netanyahu's
hard-line nationalism or television skills, but to Labor's
strategic mistakes and organizational oversights. As the Labor
Party leader, Barak rebuilt a grass-roots get-out-the-vote machine,
while recruiting high-priced American pollsters and media
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Barak graduated with a degree in physics and mathematics from
the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 1968, and received a master's
in economic engineering systems from Stanford University a decade
later. But as a schoolchild, his former classmates report, he was
considered a bit dreamy, renowned more for his skill as a
lockpicker than for his academic prowess.
</P>
<P>
   A charter member of Israel's Ashkenazi elite, Barak is the child
of Zionist pioneers. He was born in Feb. 12, 1942, in a kibbutz his
immigrant parents helped found in the remote Heffer valley, near
the Lebanese border. The family drama was typical of early Zionist
settlers: His father and uncle, after witnessing their parents'
killing by Cossacks in Lithuania, had fled to what was then
British-run Palestine as teen-agers, with little money and no local
family or friends, hoping to build a new life and a new Jewish
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Barak first met his wife, Nava, a teacher, while both were
serving in the Army. They have been married for 30 years and have
three daughters, and now live in Kochav Yair, a Tel Aviv suburb.
</P>
<P>
   By birth alone, Barak would qualify as the quintessential sabra,
the native-born Israeli of legend. But like the cactus fruit for
which they are named, second-generation Israelis are supposed to be
prickly on the outside and sweet on the inside. Barak is neither.
His bland, controlled demeanor is said by aides and rivals alike to
mask fierce competitiveness and intellectual rigor, even arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Until the final weeks of the campaign, Barak was viewed
primarily in contrast to the sharply defined images of his rivals
and predecessors: Shimon Peres, the ``New Middle East'' visionary;
Benjamin Netanyahu, the ``Greater Israel'' ideologue; and Yitzhak
Rabin, the slain warrior-turned-peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, telling aspects of his character came gradually into
focus: the tinkerer who likes to dismantle and rebuild fine clocks,
the pianist who practices finger runs on his desk during political
briefings, the jaded consumer of military intelligence who inspects
ostensibly neutral data for hidden bias.
</P>
<P>
   More important, as he emphasized his desire to revive
negotiations with the Palestinians, Israelis were reminded of
Barak's personal commitment to the peace effort. In 1994, as Army
Chief of Staff under Rabin, he supervised the first troop
withdrawals from Jericho and the Gaza Strip, and played what he
proudly recalls as a pivotal role in securing a peace treaty with
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his few memorable speeches as an opposition leader,
Barak praised Netanyahu's further withdrawal from Hebron in 1997,
saying Israelis must ``free ourselves of the burden of ruling the
Palestinians, who have been residents of this land for hundreds of
years.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-0518-     05-17 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-0518-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARAK OUSTS NETANYAHU, ISRAELIS LOOK FOR UNITY AFTER TENSE
CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    EDs: This story will be updated following Barak's statement.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-BARAK-0518.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Offering a message of unity and change to a
conflict-weary public, left-wing army hero Ehud Barak scored a
landslide defeat Monday over the combative Benjamin Netanyahu to
become Israel's next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Youths reveling in Tel Aviv's Rabin Square celebrated the win as
a return to the ideology of peacemaking championed by slain Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a mentor to Barak. Even in the narrow
streets of religious Jerusalem, a right-wing stronghold, young
Israelis drove with Barak banners on their cars and honked in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But, most analysts saw the vote as mainly a rejection of
Netanyahu's divisive leadership, which had been based on alliances
with the country's right-wing and fundamentalist religious parties.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection was sound and unprecedented. In a country known
for close elections, exit polls on Israeli television predicted
late Monday that Barak won with about 58 percent of the vote to
Netanyahu's 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, considered a tenacious battler, conceded defeat by
10:30 p.m. (local time), just a half-hour after polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   Just 49 years old and now Israel's youngest former prime
minister, Netanyahu also told supporters that he was taking a break
from politics and relinquishing the leadership of his right-wing
Likud Party, which was thrashed in the separate balloting for
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, after the storm is over, after the election campaign is
over, the time has come to calm down and to heal the wounds,''
Netanyahu said in congratulating Barak, his former Army commander.
</P>
<P>
   Observers from the Holy Land to Washington had focused on the
election as key to reducing tensions in the Middle East, which have
increased since Netanyahu froze the Oslo peace process in December.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton, who had clashed repeatedly with
Netanyahu over the peace process and at times even refused to meet
with him, avoided any public endorsement of Barak during the
campaign. But, he was pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also invited Barak, who was helped by Clinton political
consultant James Carville, to the White House as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will be the 10th prime minister in Israel's 51-year
history. A father of three daughters and Stanford University
engineering graduate, Barak is a former general and Israel's most
decorated soldier. He is famous for disguising himself as a woman
on a mission to assassinate PLO leaders in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   One old army buddy, Danny Michaelson, described Barak as an
``iceman'' under pressure. Now, the 57-year-old Barak faces a
multitude of thorny issues of concern to those inside and outside
of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He has promised to resume the Oslo peace process and, maybe even
more tricky, given himself a year to pull Israel's troops out of
the 17-year war in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most pressing to Israelis is whether the secular Barak
will exclude from his government the fundamentalist parties that
have been expanding their influence over Israel's way of life.
</P>
<P>
   That issue was instrumental in turning Israel's 1 million-strong
community of Russian immigrants, most of whom are secular, against
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Russians turned, Barak was a decided underdog.
Doubters said the cerebral, short and paunchy Barak was too stiff
compared to the quick-tongued and telegenic Netanyahu, known by his
nickname, ``Bibi.''
</P>
<P>
   But his message of hope capitalized on the public's
dissatisfaction with three years of tumultuous Netanyahu
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Barak toured polling places to chat with volunteers
monitoring the vote -- dozens of whom were in the commandos with
him. Behind the normally heavy security detail and flanked by
guards with M-16 rifles, he met briefly with supporters in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the Israeli people want to see a new way of
government. People want to see unity, change and hope and we are
determined to bring it to them,'' he shouted over the applause and
a nearly violent crush of dozens of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Famously cautious and methodical, Barak had still not made his
victory speech by even 1:30 a.m. (local time) Tuesday. He was
reportedly planning to address the throngs in Rabin Square, where
Rabin was killed four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other Israelis, however, were already reacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibi is gone!'' yelled 21-year-old Neta Shteiner(cq), from the
passenger side of a Fiat Tempra in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so bad. He was lying, he was cheating,'' said driver
Yoav Cohen, 22. ``Now, the peace process will be better, quicker.
Everything will be more honest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this the election of backlash,'' said political analyst
Uri Dromi, of the Israel Democracy Institute. ``Most Israelis were
just fed up with what this prime minister was up to . . . you
cannot be in power for long anywhere if you base your power on the
extremists and that is what Bibi Netanyahu did.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders were clearly eager to rid themselves of
Netanyahu, who they repeatedly said they did not trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message the Israeli people sent out tonight was that they
want to make peace with the Palestinians and that they want
change,'' said Saeb Erekat, the top Palestinian peace negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has 45 days to form a parliamentary government. That task
will be made tougher by Monday's vote, which fragmented the
parliament into a host of small parties. In addition to the loss of
several seats by Netanyahu's Likud, the parliament vote seemed to
accentuate the religious-secular rift in Israel. Both
ultra-religious and anti-religious parties picked up seats.
</P>
<P>
   The split parliament vote was expected from the typically
contentious five-month campaign. Israel, a country of six million
people, is comprised of news-addicts who love politics. Voter
turnout was expected to be the usual 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Several planeloads of Israelis living in the United States
returned to vote and police reported more than 150 complaints about
possible voter fraud. A few people were arrested trying to vote
with others' identification cards and fist fights broke out between
some party activists.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the race hinged on the personality of Netanyahu, the
prime minister whose campaign and message began to unravel in
recent days. He desperately accused Barak of being a pawn and ally
of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In his three year term, Netanyahu seemed captive to the extreme
right wing members of his coalition. He had even enraged an Israeli
ally, the late King Hussein of Jordan, by attempting to apprehend a
Hamas official under Hussein's tacit protection. He quarreled
constantly with his own cabinet ministers and many of the moderates
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing Israelis enjoyed the influence Netanyahu granted to
ultra-religious parties in his government and the green light he
gave to the construction of Jewish settlements in the disputed West
Bank -- land that the Oslo process is supposed to divvy up between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted that terrorism against Israelis had dropped
significantly during Netanyahu's term, which he claimed was a
result of demands he placed on Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was elected in 1996 as the hard-line alternative after
a series of Palestinian suicide bombings. In what supporters see
has a penalty for his own success against terror, Israelis did not
pick up on Netanyahu's security message this time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he did not try to remind them. His commercials showed
video from old bus bombings. His increasingly shrill attacks
accused Barak of being weak against the Arabs and, eventually,
actually making political deals with Arabs figures.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the message failed and it was Barak's message
that carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   Even Netanyahu loyalists seemed ready for the loss when going to
the polls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Netanyahu loses we will be fine,'' said 25-year-old
Asher Shakani, an ultra-religious theology student in Jerusalem.
``There is still a God in the sky looking out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
