<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-BARAK-BOS &LR;      05-17 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK BRINGS UNUSUAL TALENTS TO ISRAELI POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The most highly decorated soldier in Israel's
history, Ehud Barak, proved Monday he could marshal his military
skills and the forces loyal to him on Israel's political
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   But the question ahead for the new prime minister is whether
those abilities as a commander in uniform will serve the country in
achieving ``the unity, and change, and hope'' that he has promised
to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Short and compact, Barak, 57, does not look the part of the
Israeli hero his lifetime of military accomplishments has made him.
</P>
<P>
   The most enduring image of him in his campaign commercials was a
black-and-white photograph of a young man with thick black hair
standing on the wing of a plane with a pistol strapped to his
waist. The image was broadcast nightly, as he portrayed himself as
a man who will be tough on security issues.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph is from the day after he led his elite commando
unit in the 1972 storming of a hijacked Sabena Airline's passenger
jet and freed the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   His exploits through three decades of conflict in the Middle
East became legendary: the assassination of Arab militants,
intelligence operations behind enemy lines, harrowing helicopter
escapes, and engineered wiretappings straight out of a Tom Clancy
novel.
</P>
<P>
   But the man is complex, somehow shy and brash at the same time.
His face is soft and round, but his movements are stiff and
straight out of the military. He is known to enjoy fixing pocket
watches and clocks, a master of technical engineering. He is a
skilled pianist and relaxes by playing sonatas in the quiet of his
home.
</P>
<P>
   He is a protege of the former general and slain prime minister,
Yitzhak Rabin, who signed the historic Israeli-Palestinian peace
agreeement in 1993 and was killed by a Jewish religious extremist
for it. Barak has said he ``adored'' Rabin and in many ways has
styled his political career after him.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak is also derided by critics on the left for trying to
``out-Bibi Bibi,'' referring by nickname to defeated Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, who has left the peace process deadlocked. As a
freshman member of the Knesset, Israel's parliament, Barak voted
against Rabin's last major agreement with the Palestinians in 1995.
He has maintained a tough image on security throughout his campaign
while simultaneously showing TV ads with photographs of himself
standing beside Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   As one friend put it, he is ``more Rambo than Rabin.''
</P>
<P>
   He was raised on a kibbutz, or collective farm, the son of an
electrician and Polish immigrant. Born Ehud Brog, he changed his
name in 1972 to the Hebrew ``Barak,'' which means ``lightning.''
Its secondary meaning in the Hebrew dictionary is ``bright and
shining.'' He came of age steeped in the secular Zionism of the
founding years of the Israeli state.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the military in 1959, he quickly rose through the
ranks. Within three years, he was a commander in the army's elite
commando unit.
</P>
<P>
   In the Six-Day War in 1967 he served as a reconnaissance group
commander. In the 1973 Middle East War, he was a tank batallion
commander on the southern front in Sinai. At the age of 37, he was
promoted to brigadier general. By 1991, he assumed the post of
chief of staff and the rank of lieutenant general, the highest in
the Israeli military. He has won the Israeli equivalent of five
medals of honor, making him the most decorated soldier in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shrum, part of the trio of American political strategists
he hired to help him win the election, said his unique technical
skills were evident the first time they met. They gathered in a Tel
Aviv office to discuss political strategy, and Barak was trying to
tell Shrum about technological advances that could improve the way
teleprompters work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can play Chopin, take a watch apart, tell us that we
should redesign the Teleprompter, run a military, run a campaign,
and in the end master Israeli politics? I don't think I've ever
seen anyone like him,'' said Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   Avshalom Horan, 54, a close friend of Barak since he served in
Barak's elite unit in 1963, said, ``He has an amazing mind, a
combination of technical genius and intuition. He was a brilliant
commander and you could trust your life on his decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The military environment is very nondemocratic, so the
decision-making process is very personal. It is done individually,
and he is very strong at that,'' Horan added.
</P>
<P>
   ``His challenge will be to succeed in achieving unity _ and this
will require something more than military leadership. I think he
can do it, he has already done it in this election. His success
depends on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
