<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-SERBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS BRING TANKS TO BORDER BESEIGED BY SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLAJ, Albania _ The sporadic, mostly one-sided ground war along
the northern Albanian border may not remain lopsided much longer.
</P>
<P>
   As Serbian troops continue to shell a half-dozen nearby
villages, forcing Albanians to abandon their homes, the Albanian
army Monday made what locals described as its first show of
strength in the region. Nine tanks, an armored personnel carrier,
and a truckload of soldiers passed through Golaj midafternoon
Monday, headed in the direction of the Albania-Yugoslavia border,
just kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, heavy shelling could be heard and dark plumes of
smoke could be seen in the hills on the Albanian side of the
border. Despite a flash similar to the one that typically
accompanies tank artillary, it was unclear whether the Albanian
soldiers had simply taken up positions or were engaging the Serbian
soldiers in direct conflict for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But the tanks alone marked an apparant escalation of Albania's
role in the two-month-old conflict. Until now, border skirmishes
have been between Serbian soldiers and the Albanian border patrol
or the Kosovo Liberation Army, which maintains three training camps
in the area. NATO has handled all air strikes, although the US
Army's powerful Apache helicopters have so far gone unused.
</P>
<P>
   The tanks appeared in Kruma, to the south, only minutes after
the monitor with the local office of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe explained that the Albanian army had
likely stayed away to avoid provoking the Serbs. In recent weeks,
shelling by Serbs has emptied at least five border villages and
destroyed three houses. Some displaced Albanians who lived along
the border also spoke of forced labor and killed cattle.
</P>
<P>
   From a short distance, Monday's initial shelling appeared to
take place in Qafa Prushit, where tens of thousands of Kosovar
refugees initially entered Albania on foot to circumvent Serbian
landmines. The border post has been unofficially bombed out of
existences by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be more than a maneuver,'' said Bjorn Kuhne, the
OSCE monitor who followed tanks column from Kurma to Golaj. ``I was
waiting for it. I was surprised the military had stayed so far away
from the border. I'm surprised this took so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Villagers _ both those driven from their home and those
overwhelmed by the influx of Kosovar refugees _ appeared elated by
the army's unexpected presence. All along the winding 30- minute
route on a dirt road, children shouted and waved. The soldiers on
the well-worn, outdated tanks appeared excited too, waving and
smiling as they passed through Golaj going northeast on a road that
dead ends on the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for the government to do something, but they do
nothing,'' Vehvi Malaj, 53, shouted before the army arrived. ``My
whole village is totally emptied ... we all left together, walking
through the mountain during the night because it was safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bislim Malaj, 55, ``We didn't have time to take anything
but our children and maybe a little food.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with 300 people, the Malajs said, they were forced from
their homes after the Serbs began shelling their village in late
April. Armed with hunting rifles, perhaps 10-15 men sent their
wives and children on and stayed behind to protect their homes. But
the Malajs had no weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Men from another village, Letaj, regularly make the hour hike
from Golaj to their homes under cover of darkness, hunkering down
in the mushroom-shaped bunkers that are everywhere in Albania in
hopes of protecting their property.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's ethnic cleansing campaign has sent thousands of
refugees pouring into the lush mountainous areas known as the Has
district. Five of its 12 villages have been emptied, and only three
days ago artillery shells landed on the hills of Golaj. Although
the heaviest shelling continues farther to the north, locals must
now take care when they walk, because shell fragments that look
like small cans are sometimes found on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shoot at Albanian shepherds; they shoot at Albanian
cows,'' said Letif Koleci, a displaced Albanian, who added that he
had seen Serbs planting land mines inside Albania's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kruma, the district's largest town, has seen its population
more than double to 40,000, with Kosovar refugees and displaced
Albanians. Golaj, whose center is no more than a collection of
crumbling buildings, has doubled in number, too, with 2,100
displaced Albanians and 6,558 refugees now living with host
families there, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhne, the OSCE monitor, said the NATO airstrikes have only
exacerbated the Albanian evacuation, since the Serbs simply hide
from the airplanes and then retaliate with more shelling later.
Serb soldiers have also made brief incursions into Albania to get
rocks for fortifications and to provoke the border police, people
said. Several weeks ago, two villages were hit with fire launchers.
But until Monday's shelling, Kuhne said, ``the Serbian attacks
appeared to be on the wane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the shelling started, there really was no KLA presence
around here,''' he said. ``There was no real reason for them to
shell this side of the border, except to clear the border and to
cause chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Albanian government does not officially discuss KLA
operations in the country and the KLA does not officially admit its
presence there, rebel soldiers could be seen around the district
Monday. A half-dozen lunched at a restaurant in Kruma. A man
wearing a KLA teeshirt briefly followed the tank column and ordered
that no photographs be taken.
</P>
<P>
   The three training camps, including one that can hold as many as
1,500 soldiers, are an open secret. The KLA has also tried to
recruit young Kosovars and displaced Albanians who must relocate to
Kruma and the surrounding villages, residents and newcomers said
through a translator Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Now both the people who live in the area and those who were
forced to relocate here are worried that the Serbs will start
shelling farther into the interior. Hoping to get home again, they
don't want to be forced to move south or east or any more than they
already have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
