<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-REDISTRICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES ORDER TRIAL IN NORTH CAROLINA REDISTRICTING CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court set the bar a bit higher Monday
for federal courts faced with cases that challenge whether a
political district was drawn primarily to elect a minority
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The justices rejected a summary judgment by a three-judge
federal panel in a North Carolina case and ordered a full trial. At
issue is whether one of the state's 12 U.S. House districts was
unconstitutionally configured to make election of a black more
likely.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from the Supreme Court's 1993 ruling that
outlawed racial gerrymandering unless there is ``a compelling
governmental interest.'' The fallout from that decision has
affected districting in a number of states.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Monday to reject the summary judgment was
unanimous, but the case again revealed a 5-4 split on the
substantive issue of whether race can be an overriding
consideration in drawing political districts.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the justices subscribed to the view, in an opinion by
Justice Clarence Thomas, the court's only black, that the evidence
before the three-judge court ``tends to support an inference that
the state drew its district lines with an impermissible racial
motive ... .
</P>
<P>
   ``Summary judgment, however, is appropriate only where there is
no genuine issue of material fact ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Four other justices joined in a separate, concurring opinion,
written by Justice John Paul Stevens, that raises questions about
whether race was the principal issue in how the North Carolina
district was drawn.
</P>
<P>
   The district is 47 percent black and held by Rep. Mel Watt, a
black Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The current district was drawn after the court's 1993 decision
that led to invalidating an earlier map. The original district was
more than 50 percent black and snaked for 160 miles across the
central and southern portions of the state, sometimes along a path
no wider than Interstate 85.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Reed, a professor at DePaul University College of Law in
Chicago who has represented black plaintiffs in a number of voting
rights cases, said the court ``took the easy way out'' by ruling on
the summary judgment issue.
</P>
<P>
   When courts begin to review cases arising from redistricting
that will follow the 2000 Census, Reed said, ``they just have to be
more careful. They're not allowed to make assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Glavin, president of Southeastern Legal Foundation, which
has challenged affirmative action plans, said the decision means a
closer examination of the Legislature's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   He said a trial could show that the new Watt district was the
result of political gerrymandering _ packing the seat with
Democratic voters _ rather than a racial maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said the latest North Carolina case was the first to reach
the Supreme Court on the basis of a summary judgment. Most of the
other cases have gone to the high court after a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Thomas in his reasoning were Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and
Anthony M. Kennedy _ the five who have provided the majority in the
earlier racial districting cases.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting in those previous cases were Stevens and the judges
who joined in his concurrence Monday: Justices David H. Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
