<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-TREATMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON PATIENTS TO GET TUMOR-STARVING DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Patients in Boston will be the first volunteers this
fall to receive doses of endostatin, the tumor-starving drug whose
dramatic effects in mice have galvanized the medical community and
raised hopes of cancer patients everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin is the most potent yet discovered of substances
called angiogenesis inhibitors, which can destroy the blood vessels
that feed tumors _ without harming normal cells.
</P>
<P>
   In combination with other drugs, these inhibitors may open a new
chapter in which cancer will be kept harmlessly in check for many
years, without exposing patients to the grueling side effects of
today's treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The trials will be undertaken at Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer
Care, which includes the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Brigham and
Women's Hospital, and Massachusetts General Hospital, said
officials of EntreMed, the Maryland biotechnology company that is
developing the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The initial test, known as a Phase I trial, could take a year or
more, and will involve only about 25 patients in Boston. It is
sponsored by EntreMed, which licensed the rights to develop
endostatin from Boston's Children's Hospital. Two similar Phase I
trials, sponsored by the National Cancer Institute, will begin
after the Boston trials are underway. The two other centers are the
M.D. Anderson Cancer Institute in Houston and the University of
Wisconsin in Madison.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston volunteers will be referred by cancer specialists at
the three hospitals. Candidates for the trial must have solid
tumors, including lymphoma. Some will have failed other therapies,
while some may not have been given other treatments, researchers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The initial trial's purpose is solely to check for adverse side
effects, but researchers will be looking for any signs that the
drug is halting the tumors' progress. If the drug is found safe,
EntreMed will move to larger Phase II studies that begin to
evaluate a drug's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's exciting, but of course you always have the risk
that something will fail'' in early testing, said Dr. Judah
Folkman, the Harvard and Children's Hospital researcher who has led
the field of angiogenesis research for 30 years. Endostatin, along
with another natural substance, angiostatin, was discovered in
Folkman's laboratory. About 20 less potent angiogenesis inhibitors
are already being tested in humans, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman will be on the team analyzing the results of the trials.
Supervising the research will be Dr. Donald Kufe, who heads a group
at the Dana-Farber that tests new cancer agents.
</P>
<P>
   Kufe said Monday that because endostatin has been so free of
toxic effects in animals, the researchers hope to quickly raise the
doses given to human patients, with the aim of giving them enough
of the drug to determine whether it's effective.
</P>
<P>
   In safety tests at EntreMed, monkeys were given endostatin in
doses ``up to 300 times what you would give a human, and there was
still no toxicity,'' said Mary Sundeen, an EntreMed spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Kufe said enrollment of patients will not begin until fall, and
eligibility requirements are still being worked out. ``We don't
have waiting lists,'' he said in an interview. ``When the time
comes we'll be evaluating patients for entry.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, information about the trial will be posted on
the World Wide Web at http://www.dana-farber.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
