<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Atlanta, it's hip to be proud
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A cynic might have looked at Outkast Day at City Hall
and seen just another feel-good photo op, but it was more than
that. It was as purely Atlanta an event as you're likely to see for
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday luncheon, orchestrated by City Council member Michael
Julian Bond, brought together a classic Atlanta combination _
senior citizens, politicians, hiphop stars and recording industry
executives _ to celebrate both National Senior Citizens' Month and
the achievements of Outkast, the hottest act with Atlanta's LaFace
Records.
</P>
<P>
   Outkast, for those who don't know, are the duo of Big Boi and
Andre, who along with the other young artists of the extended
``Dungeon Family'' probably constitute the most revolutionary
musical development to have occurred in our town since Ray Charles
walked into a Georgia Tech radio studio in 1955 and recorded ``I
Got a Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also being sued by Rosa Parks, the civil rights
heroine, over the song which bears her name.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Rosa Parks,'' which seems to be mostly about partying
down, actually has to do with Rosa Parks is one of those riddles by
which the young are forever able to bedevil the old. But she was
offended by the lyrics, and objected to her name being used without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, then, the need for some image polishing had something
to do with the decision to bring a hundred senior citizens downtown
in limos for lunch, courtesy of LaFace.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, however, Outkast reflected a sense of
connectedness with their elders long before they got sued by one of
them. It is one of the things that makes them distinctively
Southern: Groups from New York and Los Angeles don't sing the joys
of cruising in a Cadillac with ``me and you, and your mama and your
cousin, too.''
</P>
<P>
   They are said to be socially conscious, which listeners can
decide for themselves, but they are indisputably place-conscious,
so much so that kids in Sweden now feel some familiarity with
Atlanta sites Perry Homes, East Point and Decatur. Being honored at
City Hall had to be a kick, for two young men who used to ride
MARTA making up rhymes and dreaming of the big time.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the seniors seemed proud of their local stars,
Rosa Parks and the limo ride notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Robert Hodo, who plays the harmonica on ``Rosa Parks,''
gave the invocation. The tireless community organizer, Ella May
Brayboy _ herself the heroine of countless voter turnout drives _
accepted a $2,500 check for the Fulton County Council on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have brought attention to seniors. May God bless you and
your families and may you keep on keeping on,'' she told the young
rappers.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell came by to say the media pays scant
attention to good things like this and too much to the crime news,
although Big Boi and Andre have had a lot to say about crime
themselves. Labor Commissioner Michael Thurmond called them a
``perfect example for all young men in our city.''
</P>
<P>
   So it had all the elements: a little self-aggrandizement,
commercial motive, plenty of politics - with a thoroughly genuine
sense of civic pride at the core. There were enough good intentions
to go around, and something in it for everybody. And what could be
more Atlanta than that?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
