<SLUG> BC-BBN-SMOLTZ-DISABLED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz placed on DL with inflamed elbow
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Same elbow. Same discomfort. Same prognosis. For the
third time in two years, the Atlanta Braves placed John Smoltz on
the 15-day disabled list Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really come to hate those initials,'' Smoltz said. ``It's
safe to say none of my children will have the initials D.L.''
</P>
<P>
   The club made the decision following an afternoon examination by
orthopedist Joe Chandler, who determined through an MRI that while
there was no ligament or tissue damage in Smoltz's right elbow, it
was inflamed. Chandler also removed more than 2 c.c.'s of fluid
from the joint, which has twice since 1994 required surgery for
calcium deposit and bone chip removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco (last Monday) really took a lot out of me and my
side session (Friday) really wasn't very good at all,'' said Smoltz
(5-1), whose 2.59 ERA is third lowest in the National League. ``It
went through this the whole second half (of 1998) so it's nothing
new. But usually, it goes away during the game after two or three
innings. It really didn't (Sunday) in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The move will cost Smoltz three starts and left-hander Bruce
Chen will be called up from Class AAA Richmond to fill his spot in
the rotation. In the meantime, the club brought up right-handed
reliever Russ Springer to help shore up the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating for John because he doesn't want to do it,''
manager Bobby Cox said. ``It's just a matter where I have to use my
own judgement on this and make the right decision. If we're in
September, it's a different story. The season would almost be over
and you go for it. Right now, you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
