<SLUG> BC-MARILYNQUAYLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quayle's wife says women can have it all
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Veering away from politics _ and not even mentioning
her husband's presidential campaign _ Marilyn Quayle told 200 women
Monday they can have it all, with the right mix of work, family and
attention to self.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of former Vice President Dan Quayle gave a bootstraps
formula for success at a motivational conference for working women
dubbed ``Powerchicks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect anyone to open doors for you. You have to
open your own doors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no references to government solutions in her keynote
speech, only an admonition that dwelling on ``women's issues''
fosters discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   She mentioned her husband only once, when she recounted the Cobb
County, Ga. connection that led to her invitation. Several years
ago, Dan Quayle was approached by Matt Towery, an author and former
Republican activist who was writing a book called ``Powerchicks,''
about the influence of women in government and business. (The
conference drew its name from the book.)
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's wife, who did not know Towery, admitted she was
initially put off by the title: ``Oh, come on, Dan,'' she recalled
saying. ``Yeah, I really want to be involved with something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But she ended up in the book, as did five other women who headed
a roundtable discussion at the conference sponsored by Kennesaw
State University: Gail Evans, CNN vice president; Vicki Escarra,
Delta Air Lines vice president; Xernona Clayton, TBS producer; Tina
Flaherty, marketing executive; and Betty Siegel, Kennesaw State
president.
</P>
<P>
   Towery noted the irony that he, with his conservative
background, would end up inspiring a gathering of women determined
to shake up the old male-dominated workplace.
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle sees no inconsistency in her pro-career stance and
the social conservatism of her husband. She's headed to New
Hampshire this weekend to campaign for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social conservatives believe that both parents should spend
more time child-rearing,'' she said in an interview, referring to
her husband's well-known ``Murphy Brown'' speech on family values.
``To say that women should only be powerful in the home is
ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle carried the theme into the luncheon speech, advocating a
mix of child-rearing, professional growth and civic life. The trick
is to focus on one at a time, whether it be a few days or a few
years devoted to each. ``You can have it all. It's just hard to
have it all at once,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Quayle has three children in their 20s, a law practice
with a focus on mergers and acquisitions, seats on several
corporate and charitable boards, a yen for mountain-climbing
(though she's afraid of heights) and a notion that she'd like to
study architecture. ``I like taking homes apart and putting them
together again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a level of activity that could inspire inferiority, but not
in everyone. ``It's not that you have to be superhuman,'' said
Charlotta Dunkin, who took time from her job as manager of a
computer programming department to rub shoulders with other
powerchicks. ``You just have to set your goals, balance them and
keep focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Farber writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
