<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDISTRICT-COX     05-17 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDISTRICT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redistricting gets new rules from Supreme Court
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday laid down new markers
in the still-simmering dispute over how courts and legislatures
determine if political districts have been drawn with an
unconstitutional emphasis on race.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling in a North Carolina case, the high court returned to the
district court for trial a challenge by a group of white voters to
the 12th congressional district held by Rep. Mel Watt (D-N.C.), who
is black.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court ruled last year that Watt's district, the subject
of three previous Supreme Court cases since 1993, was
unconstitutional because race was the predominant factor in its
redrawing. The lower court held no trial, ruling instead on a
motion for summary judgment by the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the high court ruled unanimously that the lower court
should have held a trial in order to answer the key fact in
dispute: was the motivation of the North Carolina legislature
political or racial when it created the district in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   ``The task of assessing a jurisdiction's motivation...is not a
simple matter,'' Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the majority.
``It is an inherently complex endeavor, one requiring the trial
court to perform a 'sensitive inquiry into such circumstantial and
direct evidence of intent as may be possible.'''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling will be closely scrutinized by courts and
legislatures around the country, coming as it does on the eve of
the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Following that national head count, legislatures will once again
redraw the political maps for Congress, state legislature and local
jurisdictions to reflect shifts in population.
</P>
<P>
   In previous cases, including one involving Georgia's 11th
Congressional district from 1995, the high court has ruled that
race cannot be the predominant factor in drawing district
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of those rulings was to invalidate portions of
congressional maps from Louisiana to North Carolina. Below the
congressional level, plaintiffs also challenged the
constitutionality of state legislative maps, county and school
board districts.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, county commission and school board boundary lines in
Putnam County are still in litigation over claims of racial
gerrymandering.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling will make it more difficult for plaintiffs to
challenge a redistricting plan on racial grounds, said Neil
Bradley, the associate director of the American Civil Liberties
Union southern regional office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just automatically win because you say the word
'race,''' Bradley said. ``The message to the district court judges
is that you really have to go into details.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the high court did not rule on the merits of the North
Carolina case, Thomas highlighted the central issue posed by the
case: Did the North Carolina legislature put more black voters into
the 12th District because they were black, or because they were
likely to vote Democratic?
</P>
<P>
   The issue is central because the courts have long recognized
that districts can be drawn for political reasons, such as
protecting incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas noted that when given a choice, the North Carolina
legislature included majority black precincts in District 12. On
the face, such choices would appear to support the claim that race
was a factor, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas also highlighted the expert testimony of a witness
for the state, who showed that the black voters chosen were also
much more likely to vote Democratic _ supporting the state's claim
that these voters were chosen for political, not racial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prior decisions have made clear that a jurisdiction may
engage in constitutional political gerrymandering, even it so
happens that the most loyal Democrats happen to be black Democrats
and even if the state were conscious of that fact,'' Thomas wrote.
``Evidence that blacks constitute even a supermajority in one
congressional district while amounting to less than a plurality in
a neighboring district will not, by itself, suffice to prove that a
jurisdiction was motivated by race in drawing its district lines
when the evidence also shows a high correlation between race and
party preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
