<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENACE-REVIEW-LADN     05-17 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENACE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISAPPOINTING `EPISODE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Rating: 2 stars 
(Editor's note: We are also retransmitting a MENACE-REVIEW by film
critic Bob Strauss that moved Saturday, May 8)  
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When making ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' George Lucas would have done well to follow the words of
that little green guru Yoda who once wisely instructed: ``Do. Or do
not. There is no try.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas had 16 years to think about how he wanted to continue his
``Star Wars'' saga. In fact, since he says he had the whole series
mapped out from the beginning, Lucas has really had some 25 years
to tweak the text that has become the holy writ of American pop
culture.
</P>
<P>
   And he still botched it. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Phantom Menace'' boasts a brilliantly realized
visual design and a couple of terrific action sequences, the movie
fails to bring its audience into its dazzling alien worlds. The
characters are bland, the script too chatty, the humor too
infantile.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the worst elements of ``Return of the Jedi'' _ Ewoks! _
and combine them with a complex, uninvolving story that never quite
taps into the series' mythology and you have an idea how
disappointing this new installment is. ``The Phantom Menace''? Try
``The Phantom Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatal flaw here can be summed up in three words: Jar Jar
Binks. This computer-generated amphibious Jedi sidekick stumbles
around in bell-bottoms speaking in an often unintelligible Jamaican
patois, supplying strained ``comic relief'' by stepping in alien
doo-doo and making jokes about flatulence.
</P>
<P>
   Caught up in his own technical wizardry, Lucas doesn't seem to
care that the character grates like nails on a chalkboard. (If, as
rumored, Jar Jar meets his maker in the next movie, it will be the
most celebrated death in motion picture history.)
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas clearly loves Jar Jar, and that's the problem with
this movie. ``The Phantom Menace'' emphasizes computer effects at
the expense of storytelling, completely losing the sense of joy and
wonder that made the original movie so much fun.
</P>
<P>
   As a director (and this is his first movie since 1977's ``Star
Wars''), Lucas famously has only two sets of instructions:
``faster'' or ``more intense.'' Here he doesn't seem to have
bothered with either, and his cast, which includes some pretty
talented actors, flounders. But, boy, that Jar Jar sure is amazing
to watch, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the only time you wish ``The Phantom Menace'' were a
silent movie. (This despite Ben Burtt's impressive sound design.)
The dialogue, never the series' strong suit to begin with, is
particularly tinny and often needlessly dense. In the first film,
Alec Guinness summed up the Force concisely in a sentence or two.
Here, someone is always blabbing about the mythology, giving the
movie the feel of a computer-generated civics lesson. (Memo to
Lucas: Show. Don't tell.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' certainly borrows freely from the previous
three films, now episodes IV, V and VI in the series. Taking place
some 40 years before ``Star Wars,'' we meet Anakin Skywalker (Jake
Lloyd), a cute 9-year-old moppet who, we know, eventually grows up
to become Darth Vader. There's an imperious princess (Natalie
Portman) trying to protect her little planet from the oppressive
Federation and its starship blockade. There's a mentoring Jedi
(Liam Neeson) given to solemn pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   Other blasts from the past: A spaceship breaks down. There's a
funeral pyre and an awards ceremony. Large, menacing objects
explode. We revisit Tatooine, home of Skywalker and a skeletal
C-3PO, who meets his robot pal R2-D2 for the first time. There are
lots of weird aliens, but no cantina (or cantina band).
</P>
<P>
   The creatures themselves are a wonder to behold. Lucas uses some
2,000 effects shots in ``The Phantom Menace,'' and there's
something interesting to look at in practically every frame of the
movie. A 12-minute pod race scene that zaps young Skywalker and
competing alien racers through canyons and desert landscapes plays
as a thrilling outer space homage to the chariot race in
``Ben-Hur.'' (Note: The sound here is just as remarkable as the
visuals.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, such involving moments are too few and far
between. ``The Phantom Menace'' has a stilted, solemn tone and
sorely lacks the presence of a sarcastic space cowboy like Han Solo
who could lighten some of the saga's ponderous load.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson's Jedi, Qui-Gon, who finds Anakin and anoints him the
Chosen One (being born to a virgin probably doesn't hurt the kid's
cause), is a solid but flat presence. As the young Obi-Wan Kenobi,
Ewan McGregor does a fine vocal impersonation of a young Guinness
but has a second-banana part. Lloyd and Portman, playing Luke and
Leia's future parents, appear sadly adrift.
</P>
<P>
   The best new character, the devilish Sith lord Darth Maul (love
that double-bladed lightsaber), is grievously underused, appearing
on screen for maybe 10 minutes. Yoda, Jaba the Hut, Terence Stamp
and Sam Jackson also turn up for brief cameos, their personalities
apparently too sophisticated to cut into Jar Jar's screen time.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone _ even (and especially) the die-hard fans _ will have
their gripes about this movie. That doesn't mean it will be
unloved. With its pint-sized hero and sophomoric humor, ``The
Phantom Menace'' clearly has been geared toward kids, the
demographic that most loudly clamors for the toys and the tie-ins.
It's just a shame that Lucas has left everyone else so
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you could view ``The Phantom Menace'' as the (shaky)
foundation for the next two movies, episodes where we'll see Anakin
turn to the Dark Side. (You won't get any hint of that change from
Lloyd's ordinary performance here.)
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good, but Lucas could have explored some of
those character issues and themes during this movie's 133-minute
running time. Instead, it plays as a hollow design exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Lower your expectations. Drastically. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
