<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-WELFARE-(2TAKE     05-17 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-WELFARE-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT SAYS STATES CANNOT RESTRICT WELFARE FOR NEW
RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., Pa., Calif., Okla., D.C., Mass.)  (rm) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a ringing endorsement of the right of equal
citizenship for rich and poor alike, the Supreme Court ruled Monday
that state welfare programs may not restrict new residents to the
welfare benefits they would have received in their home states.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 decision declared unconstitutional California's two-tier
welfare system and, by implication, the provision of the 1996
federal welfare law that authorized California's approach. Fifteen
states had accepted Congress' invitation to hold newcomers, for
their first year of residency, to the benefit levels of the states
from which they had moved.
</P>
<P>
   Federal courts have uniformly been striking the new programs
down, however, and they have been in effect only briefly if at all.
The California law had twice been blocked from taking effect by the
federal appeals court in San Francisco. New Jersey paid $585,000
this year to some 250 newcomers to whom the state had paid lower
welfare benefits before last summer, when its law was struck down
by the federal appeals court in Philadelphia. New York's similar
law was blocked in state court, and Connecticut repealed its law in
1997 because of the constitutional doubts.
</P>
<P>
   In the majority opinion Monday, Justice John Paul Stevens said
the Constitution prohibited states from dividing their residents
into classes and from discriminating among them. ``Citizens of the
United States, whether rich or poor, have the right to choose to be
citizens `of the state wherein they reside,' '' Stevens said,
quoting from the opening sentence of the 14th Amendment and adding,
``The states, however, do not have any right to select their
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justice Clarence Thomas dissented. The chief justice called the
challenged law ``a reasonable measure falling under the head of a
good-faith residency requirement,'' similar to requirements of
residency for voting, getting a divorce, or obtaining reduced
tuition at state universities.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the ruling's obvious significance for welfare policy, it
has potentially enormous implications for constitutional doctrine
because of the route the court took to reach its result.
</P>
<P>
   While the court's precedents in this area have relied on a
loosely defined ``right to travel'' _ a much-critiqued phrase that
does not appear in the Constitution _ the majority anchored its
decision in the explicit language of the 14th Amendment, which
provides, ``No state shall make or enforce any law which shall
abridge the privileges or immunities of citizens of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   This sentence from section one of the 14th Amendment, known as
the privileges or immunities clause, has been buried for years
under the weight of adverse Supreme Court precedent that has
treated the clause as a dead letter since shortly after the 14th
Amendment was ratified. In a ruling known as the Slaughter-House
cases, in 1873, a 5-4 majority held that the privileges or
immunities clause applied only to the privileges of national
citizenship and not to the states.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevens on Monday revived the issue by quoting at length
from the dissent in the Slaughter-House cases, in which Justice
Joseph P. Bradley said: ``A citizen of the United States has a
perfect constitutional right to go to and reside in any state he
chooses, and to claim citizenship therein, and an equality of
rights with every other citizen; and the whole power of the nation
is pledged to sustain him in that right.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the privileges or immunities clause has been
championed by legal scholars across the ideological spectrum, for
different if convergent reasons. Both liberals and conservatives
see it as a potentially powerful source of individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives are attracted to it because the historical
evidence supports the Framers' understanding that the privileges of
citizenship included the right to pursue an occupation and own
private property. Liberals see the clause as a basis for protecting
individual rights, one that is more secure, because it is more
closely tied to the Constitution's text, than the general due
process guarantee to which the court turned for this purpose after
burying the privileges or immunities clause.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear how far the justices are prepared to take
the revival of the privileges or immunities clause beyond the
context of interstate travel. But however modest, the step the
court took in this case won an enthusiastic reception from
constitutional analysts who are most often ideological adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Mellor, president and general counsel of the
Institute for Justice, said the court's approach was ``very
exciting for constitutional jurisprudence'' because the privileges
or immunities clause could protect ``many attributes of citizenship
that people think of as part of the American dream.'' The
conservative legal organization represents entrepreneurs who are
trying to conduct business free of state regulation.
</P>
<P>
   On the liberal side, Professor Laurence H. Tribe of Harvard Law
School said the decision was ``quite wonderful'' because the
privileges or immunities clause was potentially the basis for ``a
jurisprudence of fundamental personal rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In his dissenting opinion Monday, Thomas said that while the
majority had misapplied the clause in striking down the law at
issue, ``I would be open to re-evaluating its meaning in an
appropriate case.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   California, which has one of the country's most generous benefit
systems, had estimated that the lowered benefits for newcomers
would save $10.9 million in an annual welfare budget of $2.9
billion. Stevens noted that ``an even-handed, across-the-board
reduction of about 72 cents per month for every beneficiary would
produce the same result.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that ``the state's legitimate interest in saving
money provides no justification for its decision to discriminate
among equally eligible citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, Saenz vs. Roe, No. 98-97 (known until earlier this
year as Anderson vd. Roe), was brought by the American Civil
Liberties Union of Southern California on behalf of two welfare
recipients, who had moved to California from Oklahoma and
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Under California's law, their benefits would have been lowered
by more than $200 a month to match the levels in their former
states.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens indicated that the decision should not call into
question a state's right to require a nonresident to pay more for a
hunting license or for university tuition, because discrimination
between residents and nonresidents was permissible under some
circumstances while discrimination among categories of residents
was not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
