<HEADLINE>
LYCOS LOOKS TO NEOPLANET FOR SOFTWARE LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ariz.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc., the Waltham, Mass. Internet portal, thinks it has
found a way to boost its popularity by doing an end-run around
Microsoft Corp.'s dominance of the computer desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos announced a deal Monday with NeoPlanet Inc., a Phoenix,
Ariz. firm that makes customized Internet software for Microsoft
Windows computers. Under the deal, NeoPlanet software will
automatically direct users to Web sites run by the Lycos Network,
such as the Lycos search service, the Tripod Web site- hosting
service and the Wired Digital news service.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos will market the NeoPlanet software to computer makers as
the primary browser on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   NeoPlanet's software forms a user interface or ``skin'' that
rests on top of Microsoft's own browser, which is built into the
Windows 98 operating system. The computer still uses Microsoft's
browser, but NeoPlanet lets computer makers give the browser a
customized look and feel _ without violating their contractual
obligation to distribute Microsoft's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway 2000 Inc., a major maker of home computers, signed an
alliance last week with CMGI Inc., which owns about 20 percent of
Lycos. Jeff Crown, Lycos' vice president of corporate development,
said that Gateway may use the NeoPlanet browser skin to create its
own customized browser, which would direct customers to Gateway and
Lycos Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   NeoPlanet is also at work on a browser skin that will work with
a new version of America Online Inc.'s Netscape Navigator browser,
set for release later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Lycos is purchasing an equity stake of up to 9
percent in FairMarket Inc., a Woburn, Mass. company that provides
Internet hosting services for companies that run on-line auctions.
Lycos plans to use FairMarket to host its own auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Lycos stock rose 1 3/8 to 108 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
