<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK IN THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Dominik Hasek worked in privacy Monday, but he
didn't get any.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the overriding presence of the Sabres' ubergoalie in
this city and on this team that his most secret quirks _ of which,
like most geniuses at work, he has plenty _ become public fodder.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hasek practiced by himself for 20 minutes instead of
joining his teammates for a crisp 40-minute workout, there was an
epidemic of speculation. And when coach Lindy Ruff expressed
concern about the Buffalo savior's health _ specifically, the
lingering effects of a groin strain suffered three months ago _
alarms could be heard across Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that this was the eve of Game 6 at Marine Midland
Arena _ the Sabres' second chance to eliminate the Bruins from the
best-of-seven Eastern Conference semifinals _ and further
considering that Hasek is almost maniacal in his zeal to face a
fusillade of shots in practice, the slightest deviation from the
norm raised eyebrows, if not blood pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Now for a dose of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody involved _ Hasek, his teammates, and his coach _ fully
expect him to play Tuesday night. And it is not unusual for Hasek
to opt for a separate session in which he faces a couple of
shooters, as was the case Monday, if he feels subpar physically or
is coming off a rough game. In this case, both scenarios apply.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said the groin injury suffered Feb. 17 against Toronto _
which caused Hasek to miss 12 games and prompted him to visit a
specialist in Germany _ has been ``maybe a little bit'' more
bothersome in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been hurting for 2 1/2 months,'' said Ruff. ``He gets
treatment before and after practice. It's just gotten where he
notices it again. Every day, he goes through a 40-minute process of
ice and massage. I don't believe it's any worse. It's a state where
if he's thinking about it, you know it's bothering him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff also acknowledged that Hasek's health was a consideration
when he was lifted from Sunday's 5-3 loss in Boston after the
Bruins built a 4-1 lead with three second-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did contribute,'' said Ruff. ``I think it did affect his
play. It affected his positioning on some of his saves.''
</P>
<P>
   And on three he didn't make in the second period _ a Sergei
Samsonov one-timer from the right circle into the far side of the
net, a Mattias Timander blast from the point, and a two-on-none
break that culminated in Jason Allison's feed to Dmitri Khristich
for the fourth goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he wishes he had the Samsonov shot back,'' said Ruff.
``He didn't see Timander's. And if he feels all right, he'd play
the fourth goal differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who detests alibis almost as much as he does relaxation,
wouldn't duck culpability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play well,'' he said. ``No excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But he conceded that on the Khristich goal, ``in my mind, I
probably saved my groin'' and didn't challenge the attackers with
his usual abandon. ``But it won't happen anymore,'' he added,
``because I feel bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise his groin: ``It's always pretty same. I've been playing
hurt the last 2 1/2 months.''
</P>
<P>
   But with characteristic stoicism, he won't allow himself to
believe it when it matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not OK,'' he said. ``But in a game, I don't think about
it. Once I go on the ice, I have to play 100 percent all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday he went on the ice only with Sabre spares Rob Ray and
Jean-Luc Grand-Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 20-25 minutes with a couple of players,'' he said.
``My head is clear and I'm ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ruff said, ``Everybody's concerned,'' that sentiment
apparently hasn't reached Hasek's teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed fine,'' reported Ray. ``He's just a guy, when he has
a bad day, he works his butt off. He felt he had a bad day Monday
and wanted to work on some things. We were mostly just shooting,
working his glove and blocker.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding volunteers to work with him was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gonna go out,'' said center Michael Peca, ``but I
decided not to. I wanted to save my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't out there,'' said winger Dixon Ward. ``They wanted
someone who could lift the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ward did contribute perhaps the best diagnosis of the entire
health crisis and the Sabres' attitude toward it: ``I'm never
concerned about Dom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
