<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO PAY ALBANIANS FOR HOUSING KOSOVO REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the refugee population in Albania expected to
reach over 900,000 this summer, the United States announced on
Monday that it will pay thousands of Albanian families to host new
Kosovo refugees in their homes until a peace settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also said on Monday that it had selected a site
where it would build a second refugee camp in Albania to house
another 20,000 refugees. Already, the United States has opened Camp
Hope in southern Albania, which will eventually house 40,000
refugees. And the United States has offered asylum to 20,000
refugees who have begun arriving here.
</P>
<P>
   The three programs _ offering stipends for Albanian host
families, building camps in Albania and relocating refugees outside
the Balkans _ are all part of the United Nations and NATO programs
in Albania and Macedonia that have mushroomed over the past month
to accommodate Kosovar refugees fleeing Yugoslav troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where we can say we can handle the
refugees,'' said Brian Atwood, director of the Agency for
International Development.
</P>
<P>
   Other NATO countries, led by Germany, Italy and Britain, have
built camps in Macedonia and Albania to house more than 100,000
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pentagon officials said on Monday they now believe
that more than 5,000 ethnic Albanians have been massacred by
Yugoslav forces as part of President Slobodan Milosevic's campaign
to expel Albanians from the province of Kosovo; these officials
said the final death toll may be much higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fear that a significant percentage of the 100,000 draft-age
men who have been reported missing will never again appear and may
be dead,'' said Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Both NATO and the Pentagon said on Monday that they have
received fresh reports that Yugoslav troops are using Kosovar
Albanians as human shields around military targets to prevent NATO
from hitting them. There were new reports, as well, that the
Kosovar Albanians killed in last week's NATO bombing of a Serb
military compound in southern Kosovo had been herded up and placed
there as human shields, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   However, those new reports came from refugees and are not
conclusive evidence that Milosevic's forces purposefully installed
the displaced Albanians around the military posts.
</P>
<P>
   With the mounting civilian casualties from NATO air attacks,
both European and U.S. officials have sought to deflect criticism
of the air campaign. NATO has already admitted that casualties were
variously caused by bombs that fell short of their targets, such as
the attack on Nis that hit a hospital rather than an airfield, or
by mistaken targeting, as in the bombing of the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade. With the suggestions that Milosevic is using Kosovar
Albanians as human shields, both NATO and the Pentagon are also
laying the blame for these deaths at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that as many as half or certainly a third of the
people who may have been killed in NATO attacks were put their
specifically by Milosevic as human shields,`` said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said on Monday that they were tracking three
large bands of displaced ethnic Albanians, numbering between 40,000
and 70,000 in each group, who were trying to flee Kosovo but who
were being held back by Yugoslav troops. It is from these bands of
homeless Albanians that Yugoslav troops have herded out the
civilians who have been used as human shields at military compounds
and other obvious NATO targets, according to these officials.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing danger for these homeless Albanians, NATO
and the United States continue to rule out flying cargo planes over
Kosovo to drop food, fearing the planes will be hit by Yugoslav
anti-aircraft fire. Atwood said today that the United States is
continuing to work with private voluntary groups to figure out an
airlift plan, but they have yet to ask permission from Milosevic to
drop the food.
</P>
<P>
   A United Nations team arrived in Belgrade on Monday to assess
the needs of Serbian as well as Kosovar civilians from the war. To
date, only the International Committee of the Red Cross and a
Greek, Russian and Swiss consortium have won permission from both
Milosevic and NATO to truck in supplies to Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
