<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER WHO LOST SON IN CHECHNYA LOSES QUEST FOR DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Three summers ago, Alexander Tolbonen, a scrawny lad of
18 only recently drafted into Russia's Interior Ministry army, set
off from his rural northern Russian hometown to fight rebel
guerrillas in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other Russian servicemen who died in the
breakaway region, Tolbonen never came back. Since the day in
September 1996, when she learned of his death, Tolbonen's mother,
Anna, has been trying to get the state to admit it was wrong to
send her only son to war.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Boris N. Yeltsin won his day in court over
the war in Chechnya. Anna Tolbonen lost hers. And over two years
after Russian troops withdrew from Chechnya, violence continued to
rock the Caucasus republic.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, lawmakers in the lower house of parliament, the
State Duma, fell 17 votes short of impeaching Yeltsin on the count
of launching the disastrous conflict, which killed an estimated
80,000 people between 1994 and 1996 but failed to quell a
separatist rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   In a much quieter decision, Russia's Supreme Court struck down a
decision by a court in Petrozavodsk, the capital of Tolbonen's home
region of Karelia, that had ordered the Interior Ministry to pay
damages for the loss of her son.
</P>
<P>
   And in events that barely made the news, three Russian officers
were killed in a shootout on the border of Chechnya, bringing the
death toll in such incidents to 10 servicemen in the past month. On
Sunday, an explosion killed five more people at a Russian military
base in Vladikavkaz, a regional capital near Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The violence demonstrated that the May 1997 peace agreement did
not brought peace to Chechnya, which won de facto independence, but
lost all semblance of law and order amid battles by armed factions,
violent crime and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, after suffering a humiliating defeat of its army to a
poorly armed band of rebels, continues to face loss of life and
ongoing instability in the Caucasus. Meanwhile, the brutal Russian
aerial bombardments of Chechen towns during the war diminished
Russia's prestige as a democratic nation, a stain made no less
embarrassing by Moscow's official indignation over NATO airstrikes
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechnya conflict gave birth to another irony when Yeltsin
picked Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin to replace Yevgeny
Primakov as prime minister. Opposition lawmakers fought hard to
impeach Yeltsin over his resposibility for Chechnya. But Monday
they seemed at least willing to consider approving Stepashin in a
confirmation vote scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, as head of Russian counterintelligence in 1994, was
one of the chief instigators of the failed Chechnya campaign. Poor
intelligence about rebel forces was one of the reasons for Russia's
early setbacks in the war. Stepashin was later fired for botching
an effort to release hostages held by Chechen guerrillas in the
Russian town of Budyennovsk in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the impeachment attempt was about politics, not
justice. The State Duma itself voted down draft resolutions
condemning the war in Chechnya proposed by the antiwar Yabloko bloc
in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Yabloko leader Grigory Yavlinsky reminded the house that the
remains of nearly 400 unidentified servicemen and civilians killed
in the war still lie in refrigerators in southern Russia, awaiting
burial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boris Nikolayevich has not found money yet to bury the people
whom he himself sent to death,'' Yavlinsky said of Yeltsin on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin is not the only one who has forgotten about
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extraordinary that Russia has sunk in to almost
immediate amnesia about the war,'' said British journalist Tom de
Waal, author of a book on the Chechnya conflict. ``In any normal
country there would have been political fallout; people would have
resigned; there would have been calls for justice, for
compensation, for lessons to be learned. In Russia there has been a
numbing silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Tolbonen was one mother who tried to break that silence.
Her lawsuit charged that the Interior Ministry was negligent to
send her son, a green draftee, to a deadly conflict. To her
surprise, Petrozavodsk Judge Mikhail Balitsky ordered the Interior
Ministry to pay her $4,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy was 18 years old, he had never fired a gun, he had
never sniffed gumpowder,'' Balitsky said in an interview,
explaining his decision. ``My opinion, as a judge, as a father, is
that it was wrong to send such boys to Chechnya in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning an appeal to a higher court in April, Tolbonen
invited a reporter to her sparsely furnished home in Sheltozero, a
bumpy two-hour ride south of Petrozavodsk. Her husband, Alexander
Shevchenko, is unable to work because of an injury. Tolbonen
borrows money from neighbors for bread, and feeds her family by
growing vegetables on a small plot.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to talk about her son, she took a framed portrait of the
shelf in her small, sparely furnished apartment and hugged it,
crying softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired _ I spent all my energy on this, and I'm not sure
it's worth it,'' she said. Three weeks later, the Supreme Court
issued its ruling reversing Balitsky's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry won the appeal by arguing that Tolbonen's
parents are already receiving compensation for his death. That
monthly sum equals about $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, the ministry's lawyers argued, the military was
only following orders. They suggested that Tolbonen try suing
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondents Dmitry Shalganov contributed to this report
from Sheltozero and Anastasia Saschikhina from Moscow.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
