<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-EMISSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TO INTRODUCE CLEANER PICKUP TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (dal) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ The Ford Motor Co. said Monday that starting
this autumn its new pickup trucks, including the nation's
best-selling vehicle, would produce no more air pollution than
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Because of more lenient federal standards that have existed for
a quarter-century, full-sized pickups and sport-utility vehicles
are currently allowed to produce two and a half times as much
smog-causing gas as cars, and will be allowed to produce five times
as much next year when tighter rules for cars take effect.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford said that beginning with the 2000 model year, the
800,000 full-sized pickup trucks it makes annually, including the
top-selling F-150, will meet current pollution standards for cars.
All but the largest models will meet even the tighter rules taking
effect next year, and would meet the Clinton administration's
recently proposed standard for large pickups in the 2004 to 2007
model years.
</P>
<P>
   For Ford Ranger compact pickups, which sell at an annual rate of
360,000, emissions will be reduced in the 2001 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief executive and president, said Ford
wanted someday to make all light trucks _ a category that includes
pickup trucks, sport-utility vehicles and minivans _ as clean as
cars. Automakers that produce the cleanest light trucks could
benefit commercially, he said, adding, ``It's the right thing to do
and it is a competitive advantage for those enterprises that can do
it, while still balancing customer and shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency, welcomed Ford's decision to make cleaner pickups, saying,
``through their leadership, Americans will be driving cleaner
vehicles and breathing healthier air.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it would not charge extra for the improved catalytic
converters and engine controls necessary to achieve the gains, nor
would the new equipment affect the vehicles' performance. The
change will probably cost the company about $100 per truck.
</P>
<P>
   Federal pollution standards for pickup trucks and sport-utility
vehicles were made more lenient than for cars when the rules were
developed in the early 1970s. The reasoning was that such vehicles
were used mainly by small businesses, which worried that the
pollution-control technology of the time would make the vehicles
less powerful for heavy loads. But now that such vehicles account
for half of all family vehicles, the situation has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Covering 1.1 million pickups a year, or a third of the nation's
pickup truck market, Ford's move is the latest in a series of
decisions by automakers to go beyond federal requirements in
reducing pollution by light trucks. Last autumn, Ford began
voluntarily building all its sport-utility vehicles to run as clean
as cars.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules approved early last year require automakers to
reduce emissions from minivans and the smaller sport-utility
vehicles and pickup trucks in the 2001 model year, although not to
car levels. Several automakers have complied early with these rules
_ for example, in Jeep Wranglers and Honda Passports.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford has been virtually alone in also reducing emissions
from full-sized light trucks, for which federal regulations are
particularly lenient. Toyota has reduced emissions from its Land
Cruiser and Lexus LX-470 full-sized sport-utility vehicles, and
plans to make its new Tundra full-sized pickup truck, which goes on
sale this autumn, meet the same low-emissions standards as the Ford
vehicles. But General Motors and DaimlerChrysler A.G., Ford's main
rivals in the full-sized light truck market, have not moved in this
direction and said Monday that they had no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of rejecting environmental concerns, a growing
number of auto executives say the public cares enough to make
cleaner-running vehicles a commercial success. But other managers
disagree, contending that few automobile buyers actually understand
emissions issues. ``People don't really care, they just presume
that we meet the standards and the standards are stringent,''
Bernard Robertson, senior vice president for North American
engineering at DaimlerChrysler, said in an interview last month.
</P>
<P>
   Light truck sales now equal car sales as millions of families
have been abandoning sedans. But the shift, combined with the ever
greater number of miles that Americans are driving each year, has
prompted concern. ``The emissions from our cars, particularly from
the larger, less efficient vehicles, threaten to erode many of the
air quality gains America has achieved,'' President Clinton said in
his weekly radio address on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced then that the EPA was proposing strict new
pollution regulations for gasoline and automobiles, to take effect
in 2004. The proposal, for which a public comment period will end
on Aug. 2, would require particularly steep reductions in pollution
from full-sized light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative depends partly on the administration's national
air quality targets, which a federal appeals court rejected on
Friday. EPA officials insist that the gasoline and automobile plan
can proceed without those targets, because previous air quality
targets remain in force and smog will worsen and violate those
targets unless something is done.
</P>
<P>
   But Nasser said that Monday's decision had nothing to do with
the legal battles. Indeed, Ford officials said they had been
working for months on Monday's plan, making sure that they could
mass produce vehicles as clean as promised.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the auto industry worry that unilateral pollution
reductions of the sort undertaken by Ford will only encourage
regulators to set even tougher emissions standards. ``You can't
satisfy the regulatory mind,'' grumbled a senior engineer for a
Japanese automaker, after insisting on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ford executives contend that tighter emissions standards are
inevitable and that if affordable technology exists before the
standards take effect, it might as well be put on cars and other
family vehicles. ``Government regulators aren't stupid, they don't
live in a vacuum, they follow the technology'' and will quickly
require automakers to use it, said Helen Petrauskas, Ford's vice
president for safety and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto executives say privately that until the last of couple
years, there was a ``gentleman's agreement'' among at least the
Detroit automakers not to compete on environmental issues. Ford has
broken that informal understanding by repeatedly and very publicly
going beyond what federal regulations require since early last
year, to the fury of executives at rival companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
