<SLUG> BC-FANS-FINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER SEEKS FINES FOR FANS WHO TRASH PLAYING VENUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A city councilor has proposed a new ordinance that
would slap a $50 fine on fans who throw objects onto the ice or the
parquet at the Fleet Center, or on the playing field at Fenway
Park.
</P>
<P>
   A state law already prohibits throwing objects onto playing
surfaces, but prosecutors must prove the person meant to cause
injury. The city law, proposed by Councilor Daniel F. Conley (Hyde
Park), would have no such requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require passage by the City Council and the
signature of Mayor Thomas M. Menino.
</P>
<P>
   Conley said he drafted the measure after a recent Bruins game
where objects were thrown onto the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't reflect well on our city when a handful of unruly
fans disprupts a game on national TV,'' Conley said. ``For some
reason with hockey in particular, you have individuals who have
never played the sport, and they don't understand how dangerous it
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Conley, an avid hockey player himself, said that ``even a piece
of tape on the ice is enough to knock you over.'' He said it was a
public safety issue because fans could be struck by hurled objects
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Conley said the ordinance has the support of Fleet Center chief
executive Richard Creswick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
