<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN PURSUES INDEPENDENT COURSE TOWARD PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Republican presidential hopeful Sen. John McCain of
Arizona carries a Douglas MacArthur-like message on the conflict in
Kosovo that has given him some recognition in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to be involved in a foreign conflict, you
must figure out the price ... and do what is necessary to win,''
said the 62-year-old former prisoner of war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain appears to be taking the opposite approach in his bid
for the GOP nomination, which he cheerfully acknowledges has
``about as much chance as a snowball in Gila Bend, Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtful, reflective and independent-minded, McCain doesn't
use employ the TV sound bites, sexy themes and partisan rhetoric
that have been keys to victory in recent presidential nomination
races.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about meaty issues like restructuring the military to
emphasize rapid intervention around the world. He continues to
champion campaign finance reform legislation that has been treated
as anathema by Republican Senate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   McCain promises no negative campaigning. He singles out for
praise Democrats such as Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey and former
Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I lose this campaign, I lose,'' he said Monday in a meeting
with Seattle Post-Intelligencer editors. ``I get to live in Arizona
with my wife and four children. I get to serve in the United States
Senate, which is a great job and high responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   It happens that snow has fallen this spring, not in Gila Bend
but in Arizona's Sonora Desert. And McCain is showing signs of
catching on. A recent New Hampshire poll showed him rising from 5
percent to 14 percent support, well behind Texas Gov. George W.
Bush but not too far behind Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected praise came from Dole's spouse, former Senate
Majority leader Bob Dole, who said he is thinking of giving money
to ``my friend'' McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to keep good people in the race,'' Dole told
The New York Times. ``So I've thought about ways to help McCain in
particular.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is unyielding on limiting the influence of money and
political action committees on running for office. He notes that
most House and Senate members support reform, but have been
thwarted by a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems we have majority rule in most democratic
institutions, except the U.S. Senate,'' he said. He noted the
influence of lobbyists, joking that ``The Telecommunications Act of
1996 protected everyone but the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain is chairman of the influential Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee, and as such, his campaign has
become a magnet for donations from Washington, D.C., lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   He took $113,000 in PAC donations last month. While far behind
Bush, he reported $2.7 million cash on hand. And he was raising
money in Seattle Monday. He toured such companies as Airborne
Express and Amazon.com, and held a $1,000-a-head fundraiser Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   McCain promises to be a different kind of president than Bill
Clinton, who has concentrated on domestic issues and offered up
``bite-sized'' programs such as support of uniforms in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would spent a lot more time on foreign policy and national
security,'' said McCain. ``I would spend time talking and think
long-term policy, not policy du jour.''
</P>
<P>
   He would bring to the White House sages ``who think
conceptually'' to develop a bottoms-up approach to key issues _
China's emergence as a superpower, ethnic and tribal strife in the
world, and the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would seek to reduce what he calls ``the bitter
partisanship that permeates what we do in the nation's capital.''
He promised a kind of bipartisan blast from the past, seeking
counsel of such wise men as former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger, President Carter's security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski,
and George Bush security aide Gen. Brent Scowcroft.
</P>
<P>
   McCain indicated he would revive other aspects of lost
bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   A rare western Republican who says his party should do more on
the environment, McCain said he would emphasize reforming and
reauthorizing such environmental laws as the Endangered Species Act
and Clean Air Act. He talked about depletion of the ozone layer and
increased ocean temperatures that have decimated the world's coral
reefs.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has emerged as a Senate centrist in the gun control
debate, insisting that regulatory loopholes be closed on such
questions as retrieval of handguns from pawn shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The availability of guns to young people is an issue that
needs to be addressed,'' he said. ``We need to respect both public
opinion and the fundamental protection of our right to bear arms.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his wife Cindy have four children, ages 7 to 14. They
have, as parents, received a pre-Littleton education in the
bombardment of young people with violent and explicit videos,
records, and Internet material.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a video game our 11-year-old had that was filled with
gratuitous violence. A guy went from room to room mowing people
down,'' said McCain, who confiscated the game.
</P>
<P>
   The McCains also found their 13-year-old and neighbor kids in
Phoenix were looking at explicit material on the Internet, ``things
I had never seen people doing to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a U.S. senator has advantages. The McCains and neighbor
parents called a meeting and invited an FBI agent to lecture the
kids on child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared the pants off 'em,'' Cindy McCain said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, her husband promised, he will call for a universal
ratings system so parents know the violence content of what their
children are watching and hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
