A0712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-POPULAR-COX     05-17 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-POPULAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corporate aircrafts fly in face of declining profits
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Billionaire investor Warren Buffet once called his
aircraft ``The Indefensible,'' referring to its high price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, he named it ``The Indispensable.''
</P>
<P>
   Others apparently share those sentiments because corporate
aircraft have made a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Buffet, for example, likes them so much he bought Executive Jet,
a company that arranges for companies to share Gulfstream jets.
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Bosco, a spokeswoman for the National Business
Aircraft Association, said the industry is doing well because more
companies realize the use of corporate jets ``represents a very
productive and efficient use of employees' time. That's why this is
referred to as a business tool. Basically, it's an office in the
sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosco said about 8,000 companies operate business aircraft, from
turbo props to high-end jets like the ones made by Savannah,
Ga.-based Gulfstream. That's up from 6,600 companies in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, many corporations came under fire from
shareholders for owning pricey corporate aircraft in the face of
declining profits. Many decided to shed themselves of these perks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some companies opt for private air travel to avoid delays
at airports, the hassles of baggage check-in and retrieval, and
just for the ability to arrange flights to meet their schedules.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an executive using a corporate jet can hit several
sites in a day. Such a trip might require an overnight stay using
airline service. ``An employee can make it back in time for
dinner,'' Bosco said.
</P>
<P>
   And given the increasing global nature of business, executives
can dash to foreign lands at a moment's notice. A nonstop flight
between New York and Tokyo takes Gulfstream's GV about 12 hours, 40
minutes, compared with nearly 14 hours on commercial jets
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Jameson Inns owns two twin-engine planes to get
its employees to hotel properties throughout the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   President Craig Kitchin said many hotels are located in smaller
markets ``where commercial air isn't convenient, especially if you
have two or three people traveling. There's the convenience of
being able to leave when you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Kitchin's company acquired another hotel company,
which broadens its markets. For that reason, he said, the company
might consider using a private jet in a time-share arrangement with
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   That aspect of corporate travel is on the upswing, said Richard
Aboulafia, an analyst with the Teal Group in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Fractional ownership ``doesn't show up as huge capital spending.
You can get it off your books.''
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia estimated that 1999 would be a major growth year for
the market, which reached $7.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate aircraft industry is on ``an exceptional high
right now.'' Although, he warned, it could be headed downward as
supply catches up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, Aboulafia said, it's likely to be a correction
and not a major plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
