<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULFSTREAM-COX     05-17 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULFSTREAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    General Dynamics makes bid for Gulfstream in $5.3 billion stock
swap
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Savannah, Ga.'s luxury jet-maker Gulfstream Aerospace
would become part of military contractor General Dynamics under a
buyout announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics said it plans to acquire Gulfstream _ one of
Georgia's best-performing public companies of late _ in a
one-for-one stock swap valued at $5.3 billion at Monday's opening
share prices.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Chabraja, chairman of Falls Church, Va.,-based General
Dynamics, said Gulfstream would become a wholly owned subsidiary
``with no change to its existing management, operations, facilities
or work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream executives said the new ownership should benefit the
company by improving access to growth capital and international
markets. A name for the subsidiary wasn't announced, but the
gold-plated Gulfstream brand almost certainly will survive.
</P>
<P>
   The company has built sleek, high-priced business jets for more
than 30 years, with more than 1,000 in use around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream built a record 61planes last year and posted profits
of $225 million on revenue of $2.43 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It makes two planes, the $38 million GV and the $28 million GIV,
and sells them to corporations, governments and the rich and
famous. It also offers ``fractional ownership'' _ basically a time
share.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been primarily owned since 1990 by New York
investment firm Forstmann Little &AMP; Co. The firm initially watched
Gulfstream's fortunes plummet but then overhauled management and
engineered a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann Little took Gulfstream public in 1996 and has made
more than $1.5 billion on stock sales. It would essentially trade
its remaining 23 percent stake for an investment in General
Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's opening prices of $55.63 for Gulfstream and $71.44
for General Dynamics, the stock swap represented a $16-a-share
premium for Gulfstream shareholders when announced before the
market opened.
</P>
<P>
   But initial investor reaction markedly cut that premium.
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics shares tumbled $6.18 3/4 to $65.25, while
Gulfstream shares climbed $6.06 1/4 to $61.68 3/4. The true value
of the transaction won't be clear until closing, which executives
said they expect to occur in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes walkaway provisions if General Dynamics' share
price averages below $63 for a 15-day period prior to a Gulfstream
shareholder vote, or if a better offer emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream's annual shareholder meeting had been scheduled this
week but is now delayed to an unspecified date.
</P>
<P>
   The company's financial rebound _ coupled with Forstmann
Little's desire to reap the profits _ had spurred talk of a buyout.
But analysts hadn't expected General Dynamics to be the acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   The Falls Church, Va.-based company exited the aircraft business
in 1993, when it sold a jet fighter business to Lockheed Martin. It
now makes submarines, tanks and electronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is a little bit of surprise and the street is
viewing it as somewhat of a negative,'' said Paul Marshall of the
Robert W. Baird investment firm, an arm of Northwestern Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really moves away from what General Dynamics has done in
the recent past, which has been to acquire mostly defense
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of baffling to be honest,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics said it will make Gulfstream the foundation of
a revived aviation arm.
</P>
<P>
   Chabraja said General Dynamics expects to use its efficient
manufacturing and design expertise to ``add significant value'' to
Gulfstream, but he did not offer any specific plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream has about 4,500 employees at its main jet plant and
headquarters in Savannah, along with another 3,200 elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Executives there said corporate ownership will provide greater
long-term stability. They also said General Dynamics' focus on
electronics and military business may aid sales of Gulfstream jets
for special government missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a strong parent company like General Dynamics, a
continuing investment in the growth of this company is possible,''
said Gulfstream President and Chief Operating Officer W.W. ``Bill''
Boisture Jr. ``We certainly see good stable employment going
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream has a history of moving back and forth between
independence and control by a larger company.
</P>
<P>
   It was originally a a unit of aircraft-maker Grumman Corp., then
became independent in 1978 under the leadership of aviation
entrepreneur Allen E. Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Chrysler Corp. bought Gulfstream, but five years later
Paulson and Forstmann Little &AMP; Co. engineered an $850 million
buyback.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Gulfstream's fortunes sagged under the weight of
buyout debt and a recession. Forstmann Little Chairman Theodore J.
Forstmann in 1993 named himself chairman and began a management
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann, who calls his tenure at Gulfstream ``the most
rewarding experience of my business career,'' would remain chairman
of the subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream launched the GV in 1995 while continuing to produce
the older and smaller GIV. The dual product line _ a first for the
company _ hit the market just as the surging economy sparked new
demand for corporate aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The market for top-end business jets remains a narrow and
cyclical one, however, and Canadair is now selling a GV rival
called the Global Express.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing and Airbus are marketing business jet
versions of the smallest airliners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gulfstream is a strong company with a strong product,'' said
Richard Aboulafia, an aviation analyst with Teal Group. ``Whether
(General Dynamics) can make more money than Gulfstream or do a
better job remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
