<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL THEY BE UP, OR DOWN (AND OUT)? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They're up, they're down. They are Hall of Famers one
period, a skating shame the next. They can chase Dominik Hasek from
the net one game, but can't get their names on the scoresheet, can
barely stand up on skates, in another.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Black 'n' Gold hockey team is a baffling bunch in the
playoff season of '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what it is,'' said forward Steve Heinze, only
minutes after the Bruins played a couple of sizzling periods
Sunday, for a 4-1 lead, and hung on for a 5-3 win over the Sabres.
``I just saw our team pyschologist and even he asked me, `What is
it? Why is it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fred Neff is the team psychologist, and he said Monday that
Heinze was one of three players he approached after the game,
soliciting opinions about why the club's play had undergone such
dramatic swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked out of my own curiosity, really, because I'm still
learning, too,'' said Neff. ``I want to understand it as well. It's
not something they really wanted to talk about after a win, but I
felt, hey, if not now, then when? Their answer was pretty much, `I
don't know.' That's OK, we'll delve into it in Sports Psychology
101 at another time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason(s), Sunday's game was the polar opposite of
the Bruins' 3-0 loss Friday night in Marine Midland Arena. After
taking a 2-1 lead into the third period of Game 3 two nights
earlier, only to collapse and lose, 3-2, the Bruins showed up in
Game 4 in desperate need of recovering their game.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious from the drop of the puck Friday night, however,
that their minds remained in suspended animation. The clock may
have been turned ahead by 48 hours, but they still were playing
with the same lethargy and lack of emotion that crept into their
game two nights earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to chase the blues away, they also barely were able to
chase the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an excuse, but I think that was part of it,'' said
No. 1 center Jason Allison. ``We played a couple of very good
periods in Game 3, then lost, and we felt we blew it with a bad
third period. The next game, it was like we couldn't get over it.
Maybe that sucked a little bit of the life out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritty center Tim Taylor, disappointed and angry after the
team-wide poor showing in Game 4, agreed that there was a carryover
of bad karma from the Game 3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to admit that, but it hurt us in Game 4,'' said
Taylor, who needs a series of pain-killing shots to his shoulder
and ribs to suit up. ``No question it carried over in Game 4. You
can say, `Be ready, don't let it happen,' and what have you, but
the truth is, it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor drew a direct comparison between his infamous
toe-in-the-crease viloation in last year's playoffs to what
happened in Games 3 and 4 with the Sabres. In Game 3 of the first
round against the Capitals last season, the Bruins appeared to have
the winning goal _ and a 2-1 series advantage _ until video replay
showed Taylor's miscreant toe had crept an inch or two into Olaf
Kolzig's crease. The Capitals went on to win, 3-2, and 48 hours
later the two sides returned to the ice with the emotional
sledgehammer still pounding on the Bruins' heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens? We lose, 3-0,'' said Taylor, who collected a
pair of key assists in Sunday's win, playing on a reconfigured line
that found Taylor and longtime linemate Rob DiMaio joined by
skilled winger Sergei Samsonov. ``You're ready physically, everyone
always is at this time of the year, and in your mind you think you
are ready _ but the truth is, you aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it just isn't there, and it's because of this
emotional roller coaster you're riding. Pat (Burns) likes to say,
`It's not how hard you get kicked to the curb that counts _ it's
how fast you get up.' Well, we didn't get up; we were still
hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing elimination in Game 5, the Bruins were back at their
puck-pursuing best, virtually unfazed when the Sabres connected for
a 1-0 lead on a quirky goal by Curtis Brown with only 37 seconds
ticked off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there, you could see we were better,'' said Allison.
``It would have been easy to say, `Oh, my God, here we go again.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In part they were prompted by fear. An elimination game puts a
scare, and an accompanying emotional boost, into every team.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins also were motivated by an emotional plea from
their captain, Ray Bourque, who reminded one and all that there are
only so many kicks at the can. Before the start of the series, the
38-year-old Bourque referred to his Bruins as ``their team,''
noting that the present and the future of the club lies in the
hands of younger, vital performers, such as Allison, Samsonov, and
Anson Carter.
</P>
<P>
   As Sunday's faceoff approached, Bourque reminded everyone that
wishing upon tomorrow can be a dangerous practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't always think,'' said Bourque, now finishing up his 20th
NHL season, ``that you have another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Allison, for one, projected himself into the
not-so-distant future. How would he feel, he wondered, if he were
sitting home and watching the Stanley Cup finals on TV?
</P>
<P>
   How would he feel if one of the teams playing was the Buffalo
Sabres?
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, God forbid, but you could play in this league for five
years and not even get out of the first round,'' said Allison, well
aware that the Bruins broke just such a drought with their
first-round victory over Carolina this season. ``That kind of makes
you look ahead right there, and maybe you say to yourself, `Why
couldn't we have won that second round?'
</P>
<P>
   ``When the playoffs started, I think everyone saw there wasn't a
dominating team in the Eastern Conference _ any one of eight teams,
including us, could get to the finals. Here we are now, and we're
one of four teams that could get there. I know, for me, it made me
think, `How disappointed would I be if Buffalo is that team?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Which Bruins team will show up for Game 6 Tuesday night in
Buffalo? If Allison's and Taylor's carryover theory holds, there's
a good chance they'll come out with their Game 5 faces. They not
only have the confidence of the Sunday win to motivate them, but
the added boost that the Sabres pulled Hasek after 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's good that we got him out of there,'' said
Taylor. ``That's a big plus. Let's say we'd had a 2-1 lead going
into the third, and we won a tight one, 3-2 or something, and Hasek
was great. It wouldn't be the same. Instead, we go in thinking,
`Hey, we got to him. We got to Hasek!' If you can get to him once
like that, then obviously he is thinking. Instead of us thinking,
`OK, where are we going to shoot it to beat this guy?' maybe he's
wondering, `Hmm, where are these guys going to shoot?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 of the Mind Games begins at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
