<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMMER LEADS A `DIFFERENT' YANKEES TO FENWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The words still bother Don Zimmer after all these
years. ``They choked!'' He didn't like hearing it in 1978, when he
managed the Red Sox. And he likes it even less today, as interim
manager of the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer heard words to that effect all last week as the defending
World Series champions went through a five-game losing streak that
finally ended Sunday with a 2-1 victory over Chicago. He'll hear it
again if the Yankees, who led the Red Sox by a game going into
Monday night, should drop out of the top spot in the American
League East in a three-game series that starts Tuesday night at
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   It is only May, far too early to settle bragging rights. But
it's always special when the ancient rivals square off for the
first time. The rematch is next week in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelve days ago, everything was wonderful,'' said Zimmer. ``We
were 10-12 games over .500 and everything was great. But it got
turned around and we lost five in a row. Hopefully it can turn
around again in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand reading, `They choked.' I saw it in 1978 when
our team stopped hitting and lost a 12- or 14-game lead _ just like
our team did this year for 3-4 days. Then (the '78 Sox) started
playing the way we were capable of again and forced a playoff by
making up two games in the last week. To this day, I don't know how
anyone can use the word `choke' for a team that won 99 games.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yankees-Red Sox series always generates extra discussion among
fans in Boston and New York. It would be bizarre enough to see
Roger Clemens pitching in a Yankee uniform in Fenway Park (he is
eligible to come off the disabled list Thursday). Having Zimmer
show up as Yankee manager, while Joe Torre continues his recovery
from prostate cancer, is another added touch.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected development is that the Red Sox, who finished
22 games behind a Yankee team that won 114 regular-season games
last year, are neck and neck for first place with a team to which
most everybody conceded the division title. If you are a Yankee
fan, this just cannot happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was true that we weren't playing too well,'' said Yankees
outfielder Paul O'Neill. ``Offensively, we're not scoring runs.
We've wasted a couple of good pitching performances until Sunday.
By no means have we lost faith in what this team can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think we're going to win the division. That's what
we're here to accomplish, no matter if we win by 22 games like we
did last year or whether we win it by a couple of games. Last year
spoiled a lot of people. But we said from Day One this season, last
year was last year. We're here to win a division and then roll the
dice on reaching the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee team that comes to Fenway is by no means the same one
that won 125 games overall last year. Clemens, the five-time Cy
Young winner, is the most notable new face, obtained in a trade
from Toronto that coast the Yankees David ``Perfect Game'' Wells,
infielder Homer Bush, and lefthanded specialist Graeme Lloyd. You
no longer will see Darryl Strawberry or Tim Raines, either. But
mainstays O'Neill, Chuck Knoblauch, Derek Jeter, Chili Davis, Scott
Brosius, Bernie Williams, and Tino Martinez all are back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had two strong relievers from the get-go in the
bullpen,'' said Zimmer. ``Last year we had Strawberry coming off
the bench and hitting three-run homers. We had a professional
hitter in Tim Raines. We had Homer Bush, who sat on the bench and
when we needed a pinch runner to steal second base came in and
stole second base. I'm not grading our team today. But I am saying
it's a different team.''
</P>
<P>
   And the results have been different. On May 18 last year, the
Yankees were 28-9, had a 3 1/2-game lead, and had won five of
seven. Today, they are 21-15 and have lost five of six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' said Martinez, ``but nothing to fret
about. We had a slump last year but it happened in August and we
had a big lead. When it happens at the beginning of the season,
people notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All teams hit those kind of streaks. You have to battle
through them and get hot again. We can very easily turn around and
win 8-10 in a row and it will all be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of things that don't seem right about the
Yankees these days, starting at the top. Owner George Steinbrenner
has yet to publicly explode, though his presence at Yankee Stadium
Sunday was duly noted, as was his pleasure with the victory.
General manager Brian Cashman, who could do no wrong in 1998, has
had to work even harder in 1999, with fewer results so far. The
loss of Strawberry, who also underwent treatment for cancer and
then ran afoul of the law, was unexpected. The absence of Lloyd in
the bullpen came up more than once during the recent slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned in the previous seasons that a good year has no
impact on the next year,'' said Cashman. ``Any time you defend a
championship, teams are going to be out gunning to knock you down.
We're not talking about a season that has gone down the drain. We
still have a winning record and are in first place. I don't see
anything for us to panic about. And as long as we continue to play
hard, do the little things, and take advantage of the other teams'
mistakes, we'll do fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Torre is a larger problem than the club wants to
admit. He had surgery March 18 and was expected to be out 8-12
weeks. Torre actually is up and about the clubhouse, consulting
players and Zimmer, but he refrains from the daily media sessions
at which he often took the heat off his players last year. So part
of Zimmer's job is to take on all comers. Suddenly, his days in
Boston don't seem so hectic anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my two years of coaching and five years of managing
in Boston,'' said Zimmer, thankful for any reprieve from a barrage
of ``what's wrong with the Yankees?'' questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had good teams there. We were fighting for something every
year. To me, that's what makes a difference. We had some good
offensive teams and were always in something right down to the
wire. That's why I can honestly say I love Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't be saying that Tuesday. He is a Yankee now, and
even one of the darkest moments of his career _ Bucky Dent's home
run that turned around the 1978 one-game playoff _ has become
fodder for just another funny Zimmer story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the Yankees as a coach in 1983,'' he recalled, ``and
rented Dent's house in New Jersey. Nice house, I thought. But when
I went inside, I saw white shag carpeting and a picture of Bucky in
his home run swing. I walked in the next room, same thing. Go to
the bedroom, same thing. Every room had a picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran into him somewhere along the line much later and
couldn't wait to talk to him. I said I turned all the pictures face
down and spit tobacco juice on his shag carperting. He laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the past week, a little humor does break the tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know we haven't been playing baseball well,'' said
Davis, whose home run produced the only New York runs Sunday. ``We
don't like to get beat, especially at home. You have to put those
things behind you. Still, it could wind up as a good wakeup call
for us. It makes us realize that everybody we play this year will
be out to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we don't have one or two people who make or break
a team,'' said O'Neill. ``I think we have a group of people who
come together day in and day out and help us win. Some days it's
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is taking the Red Sox for granted, either, said Martinez.
New York was 4-2 against Boston at Yankee Stadium last year, 3-3 at
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox are a good team,'' said Martinez. ``But then, we
have several in our division. If their pitching stays healthy,
they're going to be tough to beat. They don't have Mo Vaughn back
but they have a bunch of guys who put the ball in play and make
things happen, which is what you do when you don't have home
runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
