<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S LARGEST OIL PRODUCER TO TAKE OVER COMPETITOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Lukoil, Russia's largest oil company, announced Monday
that it planned a new share issue and stock swap to acquire another
domestic oil company, a move analysts said would give Lukoil a
sizable presence in one of the most promising oilfields in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Lukoil declined to identify the company it would buy, but oil
analysts here believe it to be Komitek, a small holding concern in
far northwestern Russia. Lukoil executives had said in the past
that they were holding acquisition talks with Komitek. With proven
reserves of 1.36 billion barrels, Komitek is far smaller than
Lukoil, which has reserves of about 16.86 billion barrels. But the
acquisition would allow Lukoil to consolidate a position it has
been building over the last year through buyouts and partnerships
with Western companies in the Timan Pechora basin, an oil shelf
that holds at least several billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Such deposits are increasingly valuable with the rise in oil
prices in the last several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal makes very much sense, businesswise,'' said Erik
Wigertz, an oil analyst with Brunswick Warburg, a brokerage firm
here. ``It gives Lukoil control over much of the major oil assets
in northwest Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition talks helped to lift Lukoil common shares nearly
13 percent, to $9.20, and its preferred shares rose 9 percent, to
$3.40. But the increase also reflected a broad rally in the Russian
stock market on news from Saturday that an impeachment effort
against President Boris Yeltsin had failed. The benchmark Russian
Trading System index rose 11.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement Monday, Lukoil said it would seek approval
at its annual shareholders meeting in late June for an issue of
11.5 million preferred shares. The share issue would dilute
preferred shares by about 12.5 percent, but most of those holders
are management and employees of Lukoil who had agreed in broad
terms last year to the issuing of preferred shares. Lukoil would
then swap the preferred shares for equity in the acquired company.
Lukoil said the terms of the swap would be announced by June 15.
</P>
<P>
   The investment banks Dresdner Kleinwort Benson and Nikoil have
been chosen as financial consultants for the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to this, Lukoil prices will most assuredly go up,''
said Valery Nesterov, an oil analyst with Flemings UCB, a Moscow
unit of the British investment house Robert Fleming Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of 1998, Lukoil has steadily moved into the
Timan Pechora region. The company's main fields are in western
Siberia, but those fields are gradually being depleted. As a
result, Lukoil has staked out major positions in southern Russia
and the northern Caspian Sea region, and now, northern Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already acquired an exploration company called
Arkhangelsk Geoldobychiye, which holds licenses to drill in some of
the best sites in the Timan Pechora region. Lukoil entered into a
project with Conoco, a unit of DuPont, called the Northern
Territories, which over time may yield about a billion barrels. It
is also involved in the Timan Pechora Co., a consortium of oil
concerns including Texaco and Exxon that has rights to fields with
an estimated twobillion barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Komitek, this is an inevitability,'' said James Henderson,
an oil analyst with the Moscow brokerage firm Renaissance Capital.
``Lukoil is now the driving force in the region, and Komitek was a
junior company in comparison. And you need a major player like
Lukoil to bring in the foreign investment and the government
agreements to build the infrastructure to get the oil out of
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
