<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUS DAMAGED BASKETBALL STAR'S HEART, EXAMINER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The chief Massachusetts medical examiner said once
again Monday that Celtics star Reggie Lewis died because his heart
was damaged by a common virus and weakened by structural defects,
and that cocaine use played no role in his death.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in the medical malpractice lawsuit filed by Lewis's
widow, Dr. Richard Evans said scarring on Lewis's heart had been
caused by adenovirus, a simple virus spread by coughing and
sneezing. In addition, the aorta and mitral valve in Lewis's heart
were malformed, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans's testimony reiterated the findings made by a team of
local and out-of-state consultants four months after the
27-year-old Lewis collapsed and died while casually shooting
baskets at Brandeis University on July 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   It also mirrored the conclusions reached by state officials
after a review of the original autopsy findings in March 1995. The
review was prompted by a report in The Wall Street Journal
suggesting that cocaine use was a likely factor in Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lewis's autopsy report, the former Celtics captain
died of a ``terminal arrhythmia'' caused by myocarditis, an
inflammation of the heart muscle that can cause scar tissue. That
scar tissue, in turn, can trigger fatal arrhythmias, uncontrolled
flutterings of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who supervised the investigation into the cause of
Lewis's death, said three other medical conditions also were
factors in the death: cardiac hypertrophy, or enlargement of the
heart; mild coarctation, or narrowing, of the aorta, the main
artery that carries blood from the heart; and mild mitral valve
prolapse, or malformation of the valve on the left side of the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination by an attorney for Dr. Gilbert H.
Mudge Jr., Lewis's chief cardiologist, Evans acknowledged that four
medical consultants who assisted with the autopsy made no mention
of healed myocarditis _ the heart condition Evans reported as a
cause of Lewis's death _ in their reports to him.
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy findings became the subject of considerable
controversy following publication of the Journal article, which
suggested that medical officials may have been under pressure not
to raise the possibility of cocaine use in the autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   The article also quoted two of the autopsy consultants _
cardiologist Jeffrey Isner of St. Elizabeth's Medical Center in
Brighton and John Fallon, a pathologist formerly of Massachusetts
General Hospital and now of Mount Sinai Medical Center and School
of Medicine in New York _ as saying the scarring to Lewis's heart
was ``consistent with'' the use of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Journal story was published, state health
officials ordered another investigation of Lewis's death. Conducted
by State Police, the review confirmed the autopsy's original
findings and found nothing to confirm that Lewis's widow, Donna
Harris-Lewis, or any other member of his family had pressured the
medical examiner's office to avoid mentioning cocaine as a possible
cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   From the witness stand Monday, Evans said several factors led
him to conclude that cocaine played no role in Lewis's death. For
one, he said, ``Cocaine often has to be used again and again and
again over time in order to produce significant heart damage,'' and
the player's heart did not show scarring consistent with repeated
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Evans also said other parts of Lewis's body, such as his
kidneys, showed no sign of cocaine damage, as they might if Lewis
had used the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no indication this man had been a chronic user of
this drug,'' Evans said. ``I did not get the idea at all that I was
looking at multiple repeated bouts of a noxious stimulant to the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans also noted that hospital records indicated Lewis had
suffered from an upper respiratory infection the winter before his
death, suggesting a recent bout with adenovirus.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that his findings were backed by Jesse Edwards, a
former president of the American Heart Association and a consultant
on the Lewis case. But Mudge's attorney, William J. Dailey Jr.,
suggested Monday that Edwards has never viewed a cocaine-damaged
heart in the course of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that I absolutely know that,'' said Evans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
