<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CVS BUYS SOMA.COM IN MOVE TO ESTABLISH ONLINE PHARMACY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that could signal tough competition for online
pharmacies, the CVS Corp., a leading drugstore chain, said Monday
it had purchased Soma.com, the first Internet drug store, for $30
million in CVS stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is expected to close next month, gives CVS a
head start over other established drugstore chains like Walgreen
Co. and Rite Aid that have yet to bring their offerings fully
online, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they said, the low price suggests the slow
progress online pharmacies have made since entering the
electronic-commerce fray with great fanfare earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a major victory for brick-and-mortar retailing, that a
dot.com company doesn't believe its business model is viable enough
just as a dot.com company,'' said Mark Husson, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch. ``Either CVS has gotten the biggest bargain in
history, or these online drugstores aren't worth very much as
stand-alone pharmacies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pigott, chief executive of Soma, said the deal represented
``a winning combination, out of necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, Internet-only pharmacies have been
unable to join many insurance networks that cover prescription
medications. As a result, no online pharmacy can guarantee that all
customers will have their prescriptions covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge barrier,'' Pigott said.
</P>
<P>
   Many health insurers hire outside companies to perform
mail-order subscription re-fills, which account for roughly 15
percent of the estimated $100 billion prescription market. Since
online pharmacies perform essentially the same service as
mail-order companies, some insurers have balked at the competition.
Pigott said some insurers, whom he declined to identify, ``have
told us they have their own plans for going online, and that has
made things very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as with traditional pharmacies, prescriptions are the
lynchpin of a successful drug store, since they attract the
customers, who then also buy other health-related items. Indeed,
Soma and its main rivals, Drugstore.com and Planetrx, have
projected that a large chunk of total revenues will come from
non-prescription items.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Dunlevy, an analyst with Thomas Weisel Partners, an
investment banking firm, said Planetrx and Drugstore.com would
eventually break the stalemate. ``Given the traffic on
Drugstore.com already, the insurance companies are going to get on
the bandwagon,'' she said. ``The only question is when.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without the insurers, the Internet-only pharmacies
suddenly face a fierce competitor in CVS, which claims more than 55
million prescription customers and more than 9,000 insurance
providers. In effect, that means nearly all insured customers who
visit the Soma site will have their prescription covered. CVS's
substantial marketing dollars and buying power will also insure
that it can survive price competition with Internet rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Zigerelli, executive vice president of corporate
development for CVS, said the company bought Soma for the same
price it would have paid to build its own site.
</P>
<P>
   CVS and Soma executives said Soma would continue to operate
under its own name and Web address until late summer, when it would
switch to the CVS location. Meanwhile, the CVS site will gradually
adopt components of the Soma site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
