</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAL-MART-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAL-MART SETTLES LAWSUIT WITH MEXICAN COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Filed in the ``a'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRAVIS E. POLING and ADOLFO PESQUERA  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Lawyers for Wal-Mart Stores and a Mexican company
settled a breach-of-contract lawsuit Monday as a Texas jury
prepared to consider punishing the huge American retailer with
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides declined to reveal the settlement amount, but a
Wal-Mart statement said the deal would force the company to take a
3-cents-per-share charge against earnings, or roughly $133.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Bexar County jury ruled that Wal-Mart and a
subsidiary should pay $624 million in actual damages to the Valores
Corp., a grocery wholesaler in Monterrey, Mexico. The panel was to
meet again Monday in state District Judge Martha Tanner's courtroom
to set punitive damages against Wal-Mart and its subsidiary, the
McLane Co. Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for both sides worked over the weekend to reach a
settlement and finalized a deal Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart issued a statement early Monday saying an agreement had
been reached for ``less than'' the actual damages of $624 million.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement stems from a 1993 breach-of-contract lawsuit
filed by Valores against Bentonville, Ark.-based Wal-Mart and
McLane, a wholesale grocery company headed by Drayton McLane, the
Temple, Texas, businessman who owns Major League Baseball's Houston
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Valores claimed that McLane _ at the behest of Wal-Mart
officials _ backed out of an agreement to team up in a wholesale
grocery distribution company in Mexico. Documentation in the
Valores lawsuit also showed that the final paperwork on the Valores
deal with McLane was slowed because Wal-Mart was working out a deal
in Mexico with that country's largest retailer, CIFRA, to create a
chain of Sam's Club warehouse stores in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   While talking to jurors after the settlement, Kendall
Montgomery, co-counsel for Valores, passed out magnetic buttons _
part of a courtroom exhibit during the five-week trial _ picturing
a handshake and the words ``There was an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, who were dismissed after the settlement, said they
agreed with the plaintiffs and would have awarded as much $1.8
billion in punitive damages if given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Cedillo, the lead lawyer for Valores, jokingly said he
would try to back out of the settlement if that was the case. One
juror screamed, ``No! We're not going back to court.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-week courtroom battle of big business embittered some
of the jurors. None of the 12 jurors and four alternates would be
quoted by name.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Friday's verdict, one juror said: ``We wanted to
make a statement that _ whether its an American company or not _ a
company can't go across the border, sign a deal with somebody and
then just drop that for another deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagal Wheatley, a lawyer for Wal-Mart, called the settlement
``a business decision'' and said an appeal would have taken at
least another three years of costly legal wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than to spend several more years in litigation, the
better course was to attempt to achieve a settlement that makes
much more sense than the verdict the jury rendered,'' Wheatley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery also characterized the decision as a smart business
decision for the family-owned Valores. He said it would now be
``business as usual'' for the 70-year-old Mexican company owned by
the Chapa family.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart did not regard the lawsuit as being a threat to future
earnings. The company said it wasn't involved in any lawsuit other
than those that were ``routine (and) incidental to its business,''
according to its annual report dated April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The agreed-upon settlement made few waves on Wall Street. The
company's stock closed at $45.69, down 69 cents in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange. Volume was 6.2 million, lower than the
average of 9 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, too, were generally unconcerned. ``This is not going
to be an issue for investors,'' said Bernard Sosnick of JW Genesis
Capital Markets in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Wayne Hood of Prudential Securities in Atlanta agreed
that ``this won't affect Wal-Mart's ongoing store operations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
