<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SODA-BOMB-COX     05-17 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SODA-BOMB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exploding soda bottle sends students scurrying
 &HT;    By Katherine Ullmer and Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The empty school cafeteria at Ankeney Junior High
School in Beavercreek said it all Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Half-eaten sandwiches, chocolate chip cookies with just one bite
gone, a nickel left on one tray, a dime on another. About 50 trays
or lunches left in a hurry. A large, gray trash can near the food
line, full of empty pop cans for recycling, showed little sign of
earlier events.
</P>
<P>
   About 12:30 p.m. Monday, a plastic pop-bottle exploded inside
the trash can, emptying the 880-student school and leaving some
parents in near panic when they heard various reports about an
``explosion'' at the school over the radio or television around
1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By late Monday, police charged a 16-year-old boy with a
delinquency count of inducing panic and took the teen to the Greene
County Juvenile Detention Center. The teen is expected to appear in
juvenile court today. A second student who police questioned was
released.
</P>
<P>
   No students or teachers were injured, though school custodian
Carl Watson and school security guard Christy Davis, received minor
burns. The two apparently touched some sort of ``acid'' or chemical
used to make the plastic pop bottle bomb, Beavercreek Police Sgt.
George Moody said. Watson refused treatment and Davis was
transported to Grandview Hospital, where she was treated and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who was doing his normal lunch-time cafeteria duty and
standing next to the trash can when the explosion occurred,
returned to clean the room up after police left the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like a small fire cracker,'' he said. ``It was very
serious when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninth-grader Steven Scott, 15, was in the cafeteria when he
heard a loud bang across the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was a (potato) chip bag bursting at first ...
but it was a lot louder than that,'' Scott said, adding a few girls
screamed and then a hush came over the cafeteria as everyone tried
to figure out what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said students didn't panic and filed out orderly when
they heard the fire alarm go off.
</P>
<P>
   Moody described the bomb as 16- or 20-ounce plastic pop bottle
``with some type of acidy solution that went off in a trash can. If
it had been a more militant type explosive, we would have had a
bomb squad,'' he said. Moody said police got a call at 12:31 p.m.
from someone at the school on the report of a minor explosion. No
bomb threat had been called in previous to the explosion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As students stood outside, police and school officials searched
lockers and made a room-by-room search to make sure no other
explosives were in the school. None were found.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities would not say whether they believed the device was
made at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we are investigating the matter thoroughly,''
Beavercreek City Schools Superintendent G. Ronald Bickert said.
</P>
<P>
   He said students were evacuated as a precautionary measure in
the wake of the tragedy at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., which has heightened parents' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have become very anxiety ridden, very concerned about
their children. We are concerned about their children and about
them so we have decided any incident at this point in time based on
the intensity of the concerns we would evacuate the building to
make sure a thorough investigation is conducted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As teachers stood with groups of students outside the building,
parents rushed to a field near a baseball diamond where the
children waited. Returning to their vehicles many had their arms
draped around their children.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Vincent said she almost drove her van into a ditch
hurrying to park. Once there, she couldn't find her son, Matt, 13,
a seventh grader. She said teachers assured her he was probably on
one of the buses called to take students home early, around 2 p.m.
Unnerved from worry, ``I couldn't remember what bus he rides,'' she
said. ``If all these kids wanted to do was raise the anxiety level
of fear and panic of parents, teachers and their fellow students by
doing this, they've done it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believes every school in the district should have
an armed police guard to keep kids safe, and that if it takes a tax
to pay for it, everyone should be willing to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Parent Mike Creech said he heard about an ``explosion'' at the
school while watching TV. ``I flew over here,'' he said. He
retrieved his daughter Kelly, 14, an eighth grader. ``I'm pretty
scared,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to this school growing up, and we never had anything
like this,'' Creech said. ``I just don't understand why kids have
to resort to this kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Wright was disturbed by what happened. Her son, Thomas
Wright, a seventh grader, was standing in the lunch line not far
from the trash can when the explosion occurred. He said the
incident makes him a little nervous to go back to the school, where
classes will be held until June 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kids thinking it's funny and they are going to scare
people but they are really causing people problems and they are
going to hurt somebody,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   After all of the students had left, Principal David Elliott
returned to the school building at 3:20 p.m. He said none of the
students expressed fear to him, but ``I supposed this is probably
bound to generate some. Our job now is to work with the students to
try to help them feel better about their level of safety in the
school environment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said student assemblies would be held at the school this
morning about student responsibility and safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important for us to try to maintain every
sense of a normal school environment, that we have to try to work
with the students and let them know they have to be responsible for
their behavior and if they are aware of any potential threatening
behaviors they need to share that information with authorities,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Ullmer and Margo Rutledge Kissell write for the Dayton
Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
