<HEADLINE>
ANDALUSIAN DRIVES  
 BRAZILIAN AIR PASS  
 MILLENNIUM'S EVE IN PARIS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I'm planning a driving trip in Spain and would like
to see Andalusia's White Towns. Can you give me some tips on
possible routes? _ Sandy R. Richardson, Seattle(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The White Towns in the region of Andalusia in southern Spain
are some 25 villages distinguished by their large numbers of
whitewashed buildings. There are several driving routes, but
tourism officials suggest that the trip start in Arcos de la
Frontera and end in Ronda, or vice versa, a distance of about 44
miles, which can be covered in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Arcos, with a population of 27,000, is on the banks of the
Guadalete River, and was inhabited in the Roman era. Its historic
section includes the Condes de Aguila Palace, a former home of
Muslim rulers and the Santa Maria de la Asuncion Church, done in
the Gothic-Mudejar style, both from the 15th century.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Ronda, population 34,500, was founded by the Celts.
It straddles the spectacular gorge cut by the Guadalevin River. The
Ronda bullring, built in 1785, is considered the oldest
bullfighting plaza still in use in Spain. The old town gates
include the 13th-century Puerta de Almocabar.
</P>
<P>
   Between the start and finish of the drive are such picturesque
towns as Ubrique, known for its leather goods, and Zahara de la
Sierra, next to the reservoir of the same name, a village that
Arabs founded in the eighth century and that has been declared a
national monument.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the drive, you can use either Highway N-342 or the
narrower, more winding C-344. Maps are available at the tourist
offices in Arcos (34-95) 6-702-264 and in Ronda (34-95) 287-1272,
which are generally open daily from 10:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other routes are the 30-mile Central Route, which goes
from Zahara de la Sierra to Prado del Rey, and includes a loop
through the towns of Grazalema, Villaluenga del Rosario, Benaocaz,
Ubrique, El Bosque, and Benamahoma; the 32-mile Western Route, from
Villa-martin to Algar, going through Espera, Bornos and Arcos de la
Frontera; the 44-mile Northern Route from Puerto Serrano to Olvera
and passing through Algodonales, El Gastor, Setenil, Alcala del
Valle and Torre Alhaquime; and the 40-mile Eastern Route from Ronda
to Algatocin, including Montejaque, Cortes de la Frontera, Atajate
and Benadilid.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Tourist Office of Spain, 666
Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10103; (212) 265-8822. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Do you know anything about a Brazilian air pass? _
Sophia R. Perkins, Albany, N.Y.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're planning on taking more than two round-trip flights
within Brazil, the Brazilian Air Pass is the economical way to go.
It must be bought outside Brazil, either through travel agencies or
through the foreign offices of Brazilian airlines, like Varig or
Transbrasil. If bought at an airline office, the passenger must use
all the coupons with that airline. If bought through a travel
agent, such as Brazil Nuts, (800) 553-9959, the visitor can use
different airlines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pass is valid for 21 days and offers from five to nine
coupons. Prices depend on the number of coupons and whether it's
high season (Dec. 10 to Feb. 29 and June 25 to July 25) or low
season (March 1 to June 24 and July 26 to Dec. 9).
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a five-flight pass costs $540 in the high season
and $490 in the low season. In comparison, a recent one way, coach
fare from Rio de Janeiro to Fortaleza on Varig was $470. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I plan to spend New Year's Eve in Paris and would
like information on special events for the millennium. _
Annie-France Von Arx, Rumson, N.J.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. New Year's is always a big deal in Paris, but this year you
can even celebrate it aboard what is being billed as the biggest
helium balloon in the world. Exhibits, a parade and special
performances are among the other possibilities in the city's $6.5
million greeting to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Some events will start this summer and run through the end of
next year. Information is featured on the city's Web site in
English, www.paris-france.org.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some events that might interest you:
</P>
<P>
   The Opera Bastille will be putting on Verdi's ``Falstaff'' in a
new production starring Jean-Philippe Lafond throughout December,
including on Dec. 31. Tickets, which range from $10 to $68, will go
on sale in September. Beginning Oct. 18, you can order tickets by
calling (33-8) 36.69.78.68. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Dec. 18 to Dec. 30 (excluding the 19th and 25th), the Opera
Garnier will present three short ballets: ``Capriccio'' by George
Balanchine, ``Reversibilite,'' by Michel Kelemenis, and ``Le Rire
de la Lyre'' by Jose Montalvo. On Dec. 31 a special event called
``The Year 2000'' is being planned, but details won't be available
until the end of next month. Information: (33-8) 36.69.78.68. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Dec. 10 to 31, 16 performances of ``The Nutcracker,''
reinterpreted and choreographed by Maurice Bejart, will be staged
at the newly restored Theatre du Chatelet, on the Place du
Chatelet, which is scheduled to reopen in early October. Call
(33-1) 40.28.28.00 or www.chatelet-theatre.com for updated
information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The balloon ride is offered from July 1 to Dec. 31, 2000, during
daylight hours at the Parc Andre Citroen in the 15th
arrondissement. About 30 people at a time will get a 10-minute
panoramic view of the city. The cost is $10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illumination will be a central New Year's theme, with more than
150 of the city's monuments lighted, including Paris' 36 bridges
and the promenades along the quays of the Seine. One way to get a
good view is on the Ferris wheel that will be installed on the
Place de la Concorde. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Place du Trocadero, overlooking the Eiffel Tower in the 16th
arrondissement, will be the gathering place for those who want to
watch the Tower's countdown clock; a light show is scheduled
shortly after midnight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Day, a parade will wind through the streets of
Montmartre. It begins at 2 p.m. from the Rue des Martyrs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While most major hotels and restaurants have been booked for
months (or years), their lobbies and bars _ such as the Ritz
Hotel's Bar Vendome or the bar at the Bristol _ promise to be
festive, if crowded, places to experience a luxurious millennial
atmosphere without having to worry about making reservations.
</P>
</TEXT>
