<HEADLINE>
ROME, PARIS, WARSAW? POLISH TOURISM GIANS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poland has no Eiffel Tower or Colosseum, and the soot of a
half-century of communism is only beginning to wear off. But
according to the latest statistics of the World Tourism
Organization, since communism's collapse 10 years ago, Poland has
catapulted itself from 18th place among European countries as
tourist destinations, to No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Poland has dressed itself up since the old days,
when few vacationers from non-Communist countries ventured to its
Baltic Sea resorts or frolicked in the snow at Zakopane, the ski
resort in the Tatra Mountains. But in the last decade, new hotels
have gone up at a furious pace in Warsaw, the capital, and major
cities like Szczecin and Cracow.
</P>
<P>
   The Polish national airline, LOT, has upgraded its fleet. And
the national tourist agency, Orbis, has been broken up into
manageable units overseeing bus service, hotel operations and
tours.
</P>
<P>
   In glossy American magazines like the New Yorker, Poland makes
its pitch as a tourist playground. (``G'day,'' says the Australian
traveler to the Polish shopkeeper, in a typical ad. ``No, Gdansk,''
comes the retort, referring to Poland's Baltic port.)
</P>
<P>
   By last year, Poland had nearly 19 million tourist arrivals
(which the tourism organization defines as visitors staying at
least one night in paid accommodations). It drew a million more
visitors than Austria. Only France, the perennial No. 1, Spain,
Italy and Britain did better.
</P>
<P>
   But Poland in the same tourism class as France, Spain and Italy?
``Basically, it's totally misleading,'' said John Borrell, the
owner of a lodge south of Gdansk, referring to the way the
statistics are kept.
</P>
<P>
   Borrell, a British writer who retired to Poland to run Kania
Lodge, a quaint, tile-roofed resort in the Kashubian lake region,
is an unabashed booster of his adopted land. Since opening his
lodge not long after the downfall of communism, he has seen
business flourish, and this year he expects to add another 15 beds
to the 20 the lodge now has.
</P>
<P>
   Weekends see foreign diplomats and businessmen, as well as
young, affluent Poles from Warsaw's new emerging middle class
flocking to Kania Lodge. And increasingly, tourists from Western
countries like Britain and Denmark are landing at the Gdansk
airport, 12 miles to the north.
</P>
<P>
   But while Warsaw got its new Sheraton, and Trusthouse Forte, the
British chain, spent millions to refurbish the fabled Bristol Hotel
there, outside the large cities there are still few signs of
investment in the sort of small, homey tourist accommodations for
which areas of western Europe, from Tuscany to Touraine, are
famous.
</P>
<P>
   What partly explains Poland's statistical leap forward, said
Henryk Handszuh, who follows Polish tourism for the World Tourism
Organization, is the huge jump in visitors to the country that
began when borders were opened and visa restrictions dropped after
the fall of communism.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, he said, millions of people from neighboring
countries _ Germany to the west; Ukraine, Belarus and Russia to the
east _ flocked to Poland. People from eastern Germany, on day
trips, stocked up on inexpensive but wholesome farm products and
household goods; Ukrainians and Russians came for longer stays, and
returned home laden with meats, vegetables and household
appliances, for resale in their own impoverished economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to international definitions, this is not official
trade, done industrially, so it's tourism,'' Handszuh said.
</P>
<P>
   The receipts are substantial. In 1998, tourism revenues totaled
$8.4 billion, roughly equivalent to one-fourth of Poland's foreign
exports, and about one-third of that came from cross-border
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Poland hasn't made advances in
conventional tourism. In recent months, as the economic crisis in
Russia has cut buying power in countries to the east of Poland and
the war in Kosovo has caused a slight slowdown in reservations from
far-off places, cross-border receipts have fallen. But tourism
revenues from affluent Western countries like the United States,
Britain, France and Finland, have continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the number of visitors from the United States _ many of
Polish origin or Jewish families returning in search of their roots
_ rose 13 percent, to more than 270,000. Visitors from Britain were
up almost 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Poland's hope, said Krzysztof Lopacinski, director of the
Institute of Tourism in Warsaw, is for vacation tourism to continue
to expand. Already, hotel facilities are improving in the region of
Poznan, in western Poland, and in Lower Silesia, in the southwest,
a revival of the old German-founded spa culture is under way. In
eastern Poland, the Masurian lake district is attracting
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Big hopes are placed in the nomination of Cracow, with its
splendid cathedral and castle of the former kings of Poland on the
fabled Wawel Hill, as one of nine European cultural capitals for
the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
