<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGERS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOROS ADVISERS TO ESTABLISH SEPARATE FIRM
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three top investment specialists at Soros Fund
Management, the famed hedge fund company headed by billionaire
investor George Soros, are leaving the company to start their own
investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   The departing managers, Liefcq D. Rosenblatt, Mark D. Sonnino
and Gabe Nechamkin, have worked at Soros Fund Management for 11
years, heading up the firm's ``special situations'' investment
team, which has been one of the company's best, and steadiest,
performers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Their resignations come as Soros' largest funds continue to post
poor results, which began with last fall's global market decline.
</P>
<P>
   The managers will create a new firm called Satellite Asset
Management, and will be joined by three other Soros employees in
the special situations group.
</P>
<P>
   The group has specialized in buying distressed securities _
stocks and bonds of companies facing severe financial difficulties
or bankruptcy _ and in merger arbitrage, which involves trying to
profit from incremental movements in the value of companies that
have already announced plans for mergers or acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite Asset Management will employ the same strategies,
managing money for private and offshore investors, the group said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The special situations group has consistently recorded annual
profits even as the Soros funds were losing millions of dollars
through risky bets in emerging markets, hedge fund industry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Those officials said the departures were spurred in part by the
managers' desire to capitalize on their own investing profits and
to steer away from the sometimes-volatile performance that can
result from the risky global financial bets of the Soros funds.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Rosenblatt said, ``We are proud of the job we've
done for all the investors in the Soros funds, and especially of
the fact that we have been able to perform with such steadiness
over an extended period of time.'' The group claimed that it has
not had a losing year since joining Soros in January 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Pattison, a spokesman for Soros Fund Management, said the
firm ``can confirm that the parting is amicable, and that the
relationship was mutually beneficial and favorable to both
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Soros and Stanley Druckenmiller, who manages the $6.75 billion
Quantum fund, the firm's largest hedge fund, declined to comment on
the departures, according to Pattison.
</P>
<P>
   The Satellite managers said that during a transition period,
they would continue to manage more than $2 billion in arbitrage and
high-yield investments for Quantum and other Soros funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Quantum fund gained 12.4 percent in 1998, lagging far behind
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index and most equity mutual funds. Most
of the gain was contributed by the special situations group.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the fund lost more than 15 percent of its value in
the first quarter, in part because of bad bets on the Japanese yen.
Another Soros fund, the Quota fund, managed by S. Nicholas Roditi,
lost 14.5 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The poor results have led to rumors in the industry that
Druckenmiller would leave the Soros funds. Last week,
Druckenmiller, 45, said at an investment conference in London that
the speculation was unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison, the Soros spokesman, reiterated the denials on Monday.
``There is no truth to the stories whatever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, recent events have raised questions about the ability of
the Soros firm to maintain its prominence in the fast-growing world
of hedge funds. The Soros funds, which are incorporated in Curacao,
the Netherlands Antilles, are not registered for sale to U.S.
investors. But their performances are widely watched around the
world, in large part because of Soros' reputation as an astute
investor.
</P>
<P>
   But some trouble signs began to emerge last year. In August,
after Russia became the latest emerging market to suffer big
declines, Druckenmiller disclosed that Soros' funds had lost $2
billion in Russian markets during the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Then in October, Soros announced that he was considering closing
his Emerging Growth fund, which had lost more than 30 percent of
its value in the first 10 months of the year. But in January, he
decided to keep the fund open, citing complaints about the possible
closing from investors.
</P>
<P>
   Also last October, Roditi, one of the firm's brightest stars,
began a two-month medical leave. At the time, the fund was down
nearly 14 percent for the year. Roditi returned to the firm and the
Quota fund in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
