<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, May 17, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston Chronicle
sports stories, please call 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURTS-GERRYMANDERING (Washington) _ In a ruling watched closely
by politicians around the country, the Supreme Court makes it
harder for judges to invalidate election districts on the grounds
that the state legislatures setting the boundaries did so largely
for racial reasons. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-WELFARE (Washington) _ Calling California's welfare law
``a discriminatory scheme,'' the Supreme Court strikes down the
1997 measure, which would have granted the state's newcomers lower
welfare benefits than those received by residents who have lived
there longer. The 7-2 decision, which could affect 14 other states,
says the limit on benefits for new residents violates their
constitutional right to travel. By MARK HELM. (1stld-writethru
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-NUDE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court returns to the
issue of nude dancing, agreeing to review a Pennsylvania ruling
that the form of entertainment is protected by the constitutional
right to freedom of speech and expression. By JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-LICENSES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to judge
the validity of a federal law that closes state motor vehicle
records to the public. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CINC (Washington) _ The Supreme Court bolsters the
president's power as the commander-in-chief by upholding a decision
to discharge an HIV-positive Air Force officer imprisoned for
having unprotected sex. By JOHN C. HENRY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART-SUIT (San Antonio) _ Wal-Mart and a Mexican wholesale
grocery dealer reach a settlement as a jury prepared to consider
punitive damages against the Arkansas-based discount retailer. On
Friday, the jury found that Wal-Mart and one of its subsidiaries
acted with malice when it broke a partnership deal to distribute
groceries throughout Mexico, awarding the Valores Corp. $624
million. By TRAVIS POLING. (Also filed in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HACKER (Sugar Land, Texas) _ Ryan David Schwarz, 23,
has a problem: He's on probation for computer hacking and as part
of his probation is forbidden to use a computer. But as a student a
student in Baylor University, he says he needs a computer to at
least write term papers and to do some basic research. A year shy
of completing his probation, Schwartz faces a motion to have his
probation revoked. By PATTI MUCK. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS (San Antonio) _ Coverage of Game 1 of action between
the Los Angeles Lakers and San Antonio Spurs. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
