<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKING-STUDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survey shows human touch better in banking
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's somewhat odd that the world's No. 1 maker of
automated teller machines is touting the fact that people prefer
live tellers to their mechanical counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton-based NCR Corp. released the findings Monday of a survey
showing how Americans prefer to do their banking.
</P>
<P>
   In response to queries about how customer-oriented NCR was, the
company hired independent research company BMRB International,
which surveyed 1,237 Americans by telephone. The verdict: real-life
human interaction still beats dealing with someone over the
telephone or a faceless ATM.
</P>
<P>
   ``People appreciate the sense of security and personal
interaction that teller transactions offer,'' said Per-Olof Loof,
senior vice president of NCR's Financial Solutions Group, which
supplies banks with customer-oriented solutions ranging from ATMs
to data warehouses and branch automation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey findings:
</P>
<P>
   73 percent of Americans use a bank teller to make deposits.
</P>
<P>
   45 percent still visit a bank teller at least three times a
month.
</P>
<P>
   62 percent of people use ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   48 percent telephone their bank at least once a month.
</P>
<P>
   11 percent use a personal computer to do banking.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the 25 percent of Americans with online access at
home use their computer for banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This supports our long-held belief that customers are seeking
old-fashioned service with a personal touch,'' said Geoffrey
Phillips, a spokesman for Dayton-based Liberty Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing acceptance of alternative banking,'' said
Phillips, pointing out Liberty Savings' addition of ATMs in the
area and expanded telephone access to customers. ``However, being
able to talk to a teller is going to continue to be important to
many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lander, a spokesman for NCR's Financial Solutions Group
in London, said the survey results didn't bother NCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not too unhappy about it. We make a lot of stuff that
goes into automated bank branches and that makes tellers' lives
easier by having data at their fingertips,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just have technology for technology's sake,'' Lander
said. ``But it (also) doesn't mean people are going to stick with
bank tellers forever and a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year NCR shipped a record 46,509 ATM machines to its
customers worldwide. NCR controls more than one quarter of the
world's ATM market and one third of the U.S. market, according to
the latest Nilson Report, which tracks the ATM market.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Townsend writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
