<HEADLINE>
BY DESIGN: SCARVES AS SUN SHIELDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last year, hip downtown girls were wrapping their
heads in little triangular kerchiefs tied under their hair in back.
The scarves were not so easy to find then but are now widely
available in a variety of colors and patterns and a range of
prices. Aside from being fashionable, they are useful in summer for
protecting the hair from sun damage.
</P>
<P>
   Cejon's scarves come in pastel floral prints and in solid pink,
white or black for $12 at Macy's and $12.50 at Bloomingdale's.
Macy's also has them in pink, lilac or black checks, also at $12.
</P>
<P>
   Lord &AMP; Taylor's choices include embroidered silks ($20) and
cottons ($15) by Spinosa in solids or patterns, and printed or
solid cottons by Charlotte ($12).
</P>
<P>
   More upscale versions are available at Barneys New York,
including a green-and-blue plaid, a giraffe print and a dancing
girls print, $40 each, all from Buzz by Jane Fox, and crocheted
triangles by Tracy Watts in a choice of eight colors, including
red, pink, purple and ivory ($98).
</P>
</TEXT>
