<SLUG> BC-HP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT PACKARD'S PROFITS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (dal) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hewlett-Packard Co. reported second-quarter
earnings Monday that beat Wall Street estimates for the third
consecutive quarter, although revenue growth remained sluggish. But
orders grew by 10 percent, and executives said they expected
double-digit revenue growth in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter ended April 30, Hewlett-Packard reported earnings
of $918 million, or 88 cents a diluted share, up 34 percent
compared with $685 million, or 65 cents a share, in the period a
year earlier. Per-share figures reflect a reduction in shares
outstanding from 1.08 billion to 1.05 billion shares. Revenue rose
3 percent, to $12.4 billion from $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Hewlett-Packard, based in Palo Alto, Calif.,
to earn 80 cents a share, according to the First Call Corp., which
tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard executives said the improved results reflected
both better execution of the company's strategy as well as the
first signs of economic recovery in Asia. The company's sales in
Asia improved across all product lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the third consecutive quarter that we've exceeded
street expectations,'' said Lewis E. Platt, the company's chairman
and chief executive. ``We executed well and turned in an excellent
bottom line, and we're encouraged by improved order growth of 10
percent. Clearly, our challenge is to convert order growth into
stronger growth in revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's order rate reflected a strong turnaround from
the first quarter, when total orders were down 1 percent compared
with figures in the quarter a year earlier.
 &UR;  &LR; ``It's probably the best one of these reports we've seen in some
time,'' said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan.
``They're talking about strong order growth in enterprise systems;
they held their own in PC's, and printers were good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard reported its results after the close of the
market. But in anticipation of a strong quarter, the company's
shares rose $4.5625, to $88.75, a new 52-week high. Analysts said
the consistent earnings showed the company's ability to cut costs
and operate efficiently and that the improvement in orders
indicated renewed growth going forward.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares have been rising since March, when the
company announced that it would split into two companies, one to
focus on computers, printers and scanners, the other on electronic
test equipment and medical technology products.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wayman, Hewlett-Packard's chief financial officer, said
that the realignment of Hewlett-Packard into two companies was
insignificant for earnings in the second quarter. However, he added
that he did expect the costs associated with the creation of two
companies to increase noticeably in the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
