<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS: CROPPED PANTS IN FLOWERED PRINTS, AND STEP ON IT! 
ADULATING JULIA ROBERTS  
 SHOE PRODIGIES
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Pants Flowering
</P>
<P>
   Last week, tanned and relaxed from a week of trekking in Utah,
Bud Konheim returned to his office at 525 Seventh Ave. to hear news
that really got his pulse going. His business partner, the designer
Nicole Miller, said she wanted to make cropped pants in flower
prints, and what's more, she wanted them designed, manufactured and
in the company's 30 boutiques in two weeks. Konheim, the company's
president, was for it, because, he said, ``all the cropped pants
out there are black or white, and they're going to be boring in 10
minutes.'' He also loves producing something immediately, rather
than six months in advance, which has become industry practice.
That's too sedate for him.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours, Ms. Miller had made a trouser pattern and
ordered three floral prints from a local fabric supplier. Asked if
anything had inspired her to do flowers, Ms. Miller smiled and
said: ``What do you mean? Like Gucci?'' Unlike Gucci's flashy
prints, however, Ms. Miller chose a subdued pattern, because, she
said, ``when you're wearing pants, it's better small.''
</P>
<P>
   Konheim didn't design a special print. ``Nobody cares if some
genius came up with a new flower,'' he said. ``A flower is a
flower.''
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to have one of its local factories cut 500
pairs, to sell for $85 each in Nicole Miller boutiques this month.
That number could change. ``The thing that's good about this kind
of item is that the risk is tiny,'' Konheim said. ``But if it turns
out to be great, hey, I know how to make more.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts in a Calvin
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts, the star of the new British comedy ``Notting
Hill,'' was at the post-premiere party last week at the Cipriani
catering hall on 42nd Street, saying that, no, she wasn't playing
herself in the movie, which is about a famous movie star. ``There
may be a similar thread that as an actor you can hang on to, but
Anna Scott is not me,'' said Ms. Roberts, alluding to her character
in the picture, which also stars Hugh Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts may not be Ms. Scott, but, to borrow a line from the
film, there was something ``surreal but nice'' about seeing such a
big star off screen. When Ms. Roberts, dressed in a slinky black
Calvin Klein dress with a keyhole back, emerged from a private
room, reporters waiting for her might have been tempted to act like
characters in the movie who gushed, ``I love your work!'' It was as
if the movie were still playing _ from the Ziegfeld Theater on 54th
Street to Cipriani, as the curious pushed forward and the
television camera lights bounced off Ms. Roberts' curly head.
</P>
<P>
   Young Shoe Ideas
</P>
<P>
   When Marlene Saunders' students at the Adolph S. Ochs Academy on
West 53rd Street began drawing pictures of sneakers and stilettos a
few months back, little did they imagine that their work would be
celebrated by the shoe designer Stuart Weitzman. Weitzman and the
300 sixth, seventh and eighth graders in Ms. Saunders' class at the
academy, which is part of Public School 111, were similarly
obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like to do something that's highly motivational, and
shoes are something that they're always talking about,'' Ms.
Saunders said. ``The kids are very tuned into shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The students and the designer got together. (Ms. Saunders saw
one of his advertisements in Vogue and phoned him.) Weitzman was so
taken with the originality of the drawings _ like Alda Fernandez's
rendition of a leopard-print boot as a snarling cat, or Eric
Brito's picture of a shoe as a sinking Titanic _ that he also sent
someone from the advertising agency to speak to them.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday and Wednesday evening, the students and their families
have been invited to a lemonade and cookies party at Weitzman's
boutique at 625 Madison Ave., where their drawings will be on
display for a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
