<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC CANCELS LONGTIME SERIES, WILL OFFER FEWER SITCOMS IN FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't laugh. NBC is getting serious. Two seasons ago, its
prime-time lineup boasted 18 comedies. Last season, it was down to
14. Next fall, the number of yukfests (or yuckfests, as the case
may be) will be 10. Eleven, if you count a new one-hour series
described as a ``comedy/drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, this new emphasis on the dramatic doesn't include room
for ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' one of the finest dramas in
the history of television. After seven seasons of struggling for a
bigger audience, the gripping, superbly acted show about homicide
cops in Baltimore joins five other veteran series at the NBC
guillotine, along with six that had their premieres this season.
</P>
<P>
   One of the canceled series, ``Mad About You,'' is bowing out
voluntarily after seven workhorse seasons, but ``NewsRadio'' (five
seasons), ``Caroline in the City'' (four), ``Working'' (two) and
``Lateline'' (two) officially got their pink slips with
``Homicide'' Monday as NBC unveiled for the advertising community
its 1999-2000 prime-time lineup. The fall schedule has five new
dramas, two new comedies and not much diversity as NBC tries to
hang on to its top-rated position among the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesdays and Thursdays will continue to be four-comedy nights at
NBC, but on Mondays the network will cut back to two. The rest of
the week _ Sunday, Wednesday, Friday and Saturday _ will be
mirthless, or at least mercifully free of the bane of all viewers:
the sitcom laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   The big winner in the new crop of shows is likely to be ``Stark
Raving Mad,'' a comedy that replaces ``Veronica's Closet'' in the
cushy spot on Thursdays between ``Frasier'' and ``ER.''
(``Veronica,'' which deserved the ax, moves to Mondays.)
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' co-creator John Wells, whose ``Trinity'' tanked quickly
this season, returns with two new dramas, one co-produced by Aaron
Sorkin, creator of ABC's acclaimed ``Sports Night.'' Dick Wolf,
producer of ``Law &AMP; Order,'' adds a spinoff of the long-running
series, called ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a summary of NBC's new fall entries:
</P>
<P>
   Third Watch. One-hour drama from Wells about paramedics,
firefighters and police officers who work the 3-to-midnight shift.
Best character name: Bosco, a ``glory-hungry'' cop played by Jason
Wiles.
</P>
<P>
   Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit. One-hour drama about New York
police who investigate the most heinous crimes. Best character
name: Donald Cragen, only because it's the second time around for
Dann Florek's feisty police captain.
</P>
<P>
   The Mike O'Malley Show. Half-hour comedy about a bachelor who
realizes his slacker days are numbered. Best character name:
Weasel, Mike's best buddy.
</P>
<P>
   The West Wing. Hourlong drama that sounds a bit like Sorkin's
film, ``The American President.'' Sorkin is co-creator with Wells.
Cast includes Rob Lowe as deputy communications director. Best
character name: Josiah Bartlett (president of the United States),
played by Martin Sheen.
</P>
<P>
   Stark Raving Mad. Half-hour comedy from Steven Levitan, creator
of ``Just Shoot Me.'' Tony Shalhoub, the cabbie from ``Wings,''
plays a chaotic but successful author; Neil Patrick Harris, the
Doogie from ``Doogie Howser, M.D.,'' is his obsessively meticulous
editor. Best character name: Ian Stark, apt for a writer of horror
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Cold Feet. One-hour comedy/drama about three couples vacillating
between commitment and the opposite of commitment. Best character
name: Pick from among Adam, Shelley, Pete, Jenny, Karen or David.
</P>
<P>
   Freaks and Geeks: One-hour drama set in a suburban high school
in 1980. Best character name: Take your pick again; there's Sam,
Lindsay, Neal, Bill, Daniel, Nick and Ken.
</P>
<P>
   NBC also announced four midseason series ready to step into the
breach. Two are animated comedies: ``Sammy,'' based on comedian
David Spade's father, and ``God, the Devil and Bob,'' about an
autoworker trying to save the world. The others are ``The Others,''
a drama about people who connect with the spirit world, and
``M.Y.O.B,'' a comedy about a teen runaway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
