<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Phantom Menace' a big deal for everyone _ except cast
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News SErvice
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The wait is over.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people across the United States will start lining up
tonight for the 12:01 a.m. premiere of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace.'' The audience for the around-the-clock, first-day
showings of the hotly anticipated Star Wars prequel is expected to
top the 4.7 million people who saw ``The Lost World: Jurassic
Park,'' the record holder for biggest single-day gross, on its
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the country queues up at theaters, where will
the creators and cast of The Phantom Menace be spending the film's
opening day?
</P>
<P>
   George Lucas (writer, director, executive producer): ``I'm going
to be off on a beach in the South Pacific someplace. As far away
(as I can be), with no phone. I'm not going to know what happens.
I'm going to be just as happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick McCallum (producer): ``The Coronet (Theatre) in San
Francisco. Then on the 21st, L.A., Mann's Westwood and Chinese
(Theaters). I'm going to the real stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson (Qui-Gon Jinn): ``I think I'm going to be en route
to join Jay Leno (on The Tonight Show ). I'll still be on a
publicity tour, as such.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Portman (Queen Amidala): ``Taking my A.P. Bio
(advanced-placement biology) final.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel L. Jackson (Mace Windu): ``Opening day, I think I'm
working. I'm shooting that day. I might drive by a theater and see
how many people are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Best (Jar Jar Binks): ``I'm going to be in the Ziegfeld
(Theatre in New York) at one time or another to see this movie.
Because the people who go see movies at the Ziegfeld are die-hards.
They are die-hard fans of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
