<P>
   WHALE-HUNT (Neah Bay, Wash.) _ WHAL18 _ For the first time in
more than 70 years, Makah Indians seeking to reclaim their
whale-hunting tradition harpooned and killed a gray whale off the
Pacific coast this morning.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Sunde and Michael Barber. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   WHALE-FOOD (Seattle) _ If the leaders of the Makah keep their
word, the 1,600 members of their tribe will soon be eating tons of
whale meat and blubber. The problem the tribe now faces is how to
cook the gray whale it killed Monday. Most everyone involved in
cooking the last whale the Makah caught, 70 years ago, is gone.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Seattle) _ Republican presidential hopeful Sen. John
McCain of Arizona carries a MacArthur-like message on the conflict
over Kosovo: ``If you are going to be involved in a foreign
conflict, you must figure out the price ... and do what is
necessary to win.'' But McCain appears to be taking the opposite
approach in his bid for the nomination, which he cheerfully
acknowledges has ``about as much chance as a snowball in Gila Bend,
Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   NETHERCUTT-DOONESBURY (Washington) _ Term limits advocates have
mounted billboards, run television ads, and churned out news
release after news release in their efforts to shame Rep. George
Nethercutt into honoring his pledge to not serve more than six
years. But over the weekend, they got the kind of boost money can't
buy. ``Doonesbury'' lampooned Nethercutt, R-Wash., as ``the Weasel
King'' in the kind of political satire that makes one question the
wisdom of the old adage that there's no such thing as bad
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story has moved in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NBC (Undated) _ NBC announces its new fall lineup and, by
omission, what's been canceled.
