<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-MEDICARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL GROUP SAYS MEDICARE CUTS DEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hospital industry, which says it has been
devastated by steep payment cuts in Medicare that Congress enacted
two years ago, Monday released a report claiming that the cuts were
far more extensive than lawmakers intended.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, Congress aimed to eliminate
the federal budget deficit while also cutting taxes. To find
offsetting reductions in federal spending, lawmakers ordered
changes in the Medicare system they said would trim $53 billion in
payments to hospitals nationwide between 1998 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the true cuts total $71 billion, or 33 percent more than
Congress anticipated, the American Hospital Association said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, seven out of 10 hospitals will lose money on Medicare
patients by the time the 1997 law takes full effect in three years,
the industry group said. The average profit margin on Medicare
patients in 2002 will fall to between negative 4.4 percent and
negative 7.8 percent, depending on how quickly hospital costs rise,
the group added.
</P>
<P>
   The estimates were calculated by The Lewin Group, a health care
research and consulting firm, which had been commissioned to study
the 1997 law by the hospital group. Using the slogan ``Real pain
for real people,'' the organization is lobbying Congress to reverse
some of the budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals nationwide say they are being forced to lay off staff
and close services, such as home health visits, because of the
budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Their claim was bolstered last month when Moody's Investors
Service, the credit rating agency, reported that the credit
worthiness of US nonprofit hospitals was sinking fast. The agency
said it downgraded the credit rating of 21 nonprofit hospitals in
the first quarter of 1999 with $4 billion in debt, far ahead of the
9 downgrades on $1.5 billion in debt for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's said hospitals were in declining financial shape because
of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act _ but also because of lower
payments from managed care insurance companies and because
hospitals lost money in buying physician practices and insurance
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, several large hospitals reported losses for
the first quarter of 1999, including Massachusetts General
Hospital, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Brigham and Women's
and UMass Medical Center in Worcester. Those hospitals had either
made money or lost far less money in the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts hospitals rely on Medicare for $3 billion a year,
or about 30 percent of their revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The state hospital association had been saying that
Massachusetts hospitals would lose $1.7 billion in payments over
the five-year life of the Balanced Budget Act. But the Lewin Group
figures put the lost payments at over $2.1 billion, said Ronald
Hollander, president of the Massachusetts Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   The American Hospital Association said the Medicare cuts were
larger than Congress intended for two reasons. The cuts grew in
size once federal agencies put the lawmakers' intent into specific
regulatory language, and the Congressional Budget Office, which
calculates the financial impact of legislation, understated the
effect on hospitals of some aspects of the new Medicare law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
