</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN RENEWS PRESSURE ON ALLIES FOR KOSOVO GROUND ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, France, Italy)  (With KOSOVO-BRITAIN, KOSOVO-MILITARY) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Britain is renewing its pressure on NATO
allies to consider a ground attack in Kosovo so that refugees can
return home before winter sets in.
</P>
<P>
   In separate appearances at NATO headquarters and with fellow
foreign ministers from the European Union on Monday, Foreign
Minister Robin Cook revived an earlier British proposal to send
ground troops into Kosovo without a peace agreement. The troops
would be sent after weeks more of allied air bombardment when
Yugoslav forces were weakened to the point where they could only
put up scattered resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France pressed the United States and other allies on
the same plan three weeks ago, just before the meeting in
Washington commemorating NATO's 50th anniversary. But the
differences were so pronounced then that the issue was left off the
formal agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance agreed instead to step up the air campaign. Since
then, the intensifying air attacks appear to have left the Yugoslav
military weakened but unbowed.
</P>
<P>
   Given the time it would take to deploy a ground force, the
British have become concerned that time is running out for a
possible land attack that would help the refugees return home
before winter.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 22,000 British, French, German and American troops
are in Macedonia and Albania, well below the number that NATO would
need to wrest control of Kosovo from the 40,000 Yugoslav soldiers
and police there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is aware of the severity of the Balkan winter and
that a military campaign in the Balkan winter is not a readily
practical objective,'' Cook said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cook is going to Washington on Thursday, where he is expected to
press his point with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of casualties and domestic dissent, the White House has
said NATO should stick with its airstrikes for now. A ground attack
would also pose major problems for some other NATO nations,
particularly Italy and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said
the United States is opposed to ground troops. ``The U.S. position
is clear,'' Leavy said. ``We're steadfast against this.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the current NATO campaign came Monday from retired
Gen. Colin Powell, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff during the
Gulf war, who said that NATO might have achieved victory earlier if
it had not excluded using ground forces against the Yugoslavs in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have argued for a campaign that, if it couldn't
include ground troops, then don't take away also the threat of
ground troops,'' said Powell, in an address at the National Press
Club.
</P>
<P>
   There has been growing pressure in the Italian government for a
bombing moratorium. And on Monday the Italian foreign minister,
Lamberto Dini, complained that NATO's airstrikes ``certainly have
not produced the results that have been expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema has proposed a plan under which
the U.N. Security Council, with Russian and Chinese agreement,
would pass a resolution supporting NATO's position on Kosovo and
then order a bombing halt as an inducement for President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia to comply. NATO has rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Without referring to ground troops, the NATO secretary-general,
Javier Solana, has agreed with the overall objective outlined by
Cook, but has never explicitly said how NATO can be assured of
achieving it.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said in an interview with the BBC over the weekend that
the allies would return the refugees ``before the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   The British plan would mark a sharp departure from NATO's
original plan, which is to send in a peacekeeping force, but only
if Milosevic agrees and withdraws his troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, NATO envisioned a peacekeeping force of 28,000
soldiers to carry out this mission, including 4,000 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, has been
updating an earlier military assessment of what it would now take
to carry out the peacekeeping mission. The allies' current thinking
is that they would need perhaps 50,000 troops to help police and
rebuild devastated villages in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's argument is that airstrikes may weaken the Yugoslav
military to the point where a land attack can be carried out
successfully without large-scale allied casualties, a situation
they have called a ``semi-permissive environment.'' At the same
time, Britain is concerned that a long, drawn-out air campaign may
not compel Milosevic to yield to NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question we must examine very carefully,'' Cook said
Monday. ``How much longer can the Yugoslav army continue before
reaching a point where it cannot provide organized resistance?
Javier Solana is reviewing when we could take advantage of the
success we're having against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The morale of Yugoslav army troops in Kosovo is waning, Cook
insisted, citing reports from Kosovo rebel leaders to whom he has
been speaking by satellite phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of the bombing has been to keep the Serb units
apart and divide them up,'' Cook said. ``They cannot concentrate.
They cannot regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cook was the first senior NATO official to assert that Yugoslav
forces brought Kosovo refugees down from mountain hiding places and
forced them to remain around dug-in artillery and a command post in
Korisa that were bombed on Friday. Yugoslav officials have
contended that NATO intentionally attacked civilians, while NATO
contends that it aimed at and hit a military target and was unaware
beforehand that the civilians were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the Serb forces that took the refugees off that
hillside,'' Cook said. ``It was the Serb forces that concentrated
them near the command post. It was the Serb forces that made them
not go back to their dwellings, but made them assemble between
those two courtyards.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there are 80 documented cases in which Yugoslav troops
had used refugees as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the contentions about Yugoslav tactics, the 19-member
NATO alliance is as divided now over the British plan as it was
last month. Greece and Hungary have ruled out staging a land
invasion from their soil.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany is now trying to keep
the Greens, a party in his political coalition, from splintering
over the issue and bringing down his government. Schroeder met
Monday in Helsinki, Finland, with Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari, who has been asked by NATO to serve as a mediator with
Milosevic over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian Parliament's concern goes well beyond any ground
action, as leftist lawmakers in Rome are insisting that the Italian
coalition government demand that NATO suspend bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to paper over the strains, NATO's spokesman, Jamie Shea,
sought to shore up support for the air war, now approaching the end
of its second month, while at the same time addressing the issues
raised by Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air campaign still has work to do,'' Shea said. ``We want
to see Yugoslav forces in an even worse shape.''
</P>
<P>
   One NATO diplomat suggested that the British were isolated.
``This is like the dog that didn't bark,'' the diplomat said.
``Britain is the only one pushing this, and it's because they don't
want to be caught unprepared if it ever comes to this, and they
want to push Clinton to take a little more engaged stance.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior officer on the Joint Chiefs of Staff in Washington
voiced the Pentagon's concern that any discussion of ground troops,
other than peacekeepers enforcing an agreement, would distract the
allies' attention from the air war.
</P>
<P>
   Voicing the hope that the airstrikes alone might still persuade
Milosevic to accept the allies' terms, the officer said that
several additional A-10 tank-killing jets and Marine Corps FA-18
Hornets were preparing to fly to the region this week as part of
176 additional aircraft requested by Clark.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook and other British officials, including Prime Minister
Tony Blair, say they are pointing out the realities of the
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said NATO must not become trapped by the conditions it
imposed on Milosevic and allow him to dictate the timing of when a
ground force enters Kosovo to escort the hundreds of thousands of
refugees home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said that Milosevic has no veto,'' Cook said.
``We're not going to hang around in Macedonia until there is a
grand signing ceremony in front of flags and cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the minister added in a note of caution, ``We do need to
know when it will be appropriate, when it will be safe, and when it
will be right to enter Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
