<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT WARNS HE MAY SHELVE BILL WITH GUN RESTRICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott warned Democrats
on Monday that if they did not agree to strictly limit debate and
get to a vote on a juvenile-crime bill, preferably by Tuesday
night, he might put the legislation on the shelf so that the Senate
could proceed to other business.
</P>
<P>
   That warning, delivered on the floor of the chamber Monday
afternoon, seemed to heighten the possibility that the bill and the
various gun control measures that have been attached to it would
come to naught, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's remarks, and the responses they elicited from Democrats,
underscored the degree to which the bill has become enmeshed in
intense political maneuvering, with members of each party striving
to portray their colleagues across the aisle as stubborn,
unreasonable obstacles in the path of progress.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would provide $1 billion in grants to help local
governments prevent, prosecute and punish juvenile crime. But in
the wake of the Colorado school shootings last month, it has also
become a vehicle for amendments imposing new limits on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Democrats were unwilling to pare their list of
amendments because they wanted to goad Lott into putting the bill
aside. Then, Republicans charged, the Democrats will blame
Republicans for the destiny of amendments that the Senate has
already approved, including provisions that would restrict minors'
access to semiautomatic assault weapons and promote background
checks on people who buy firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democrats think they have found a good issue,''
Lott said in the chamber as he made clear that he would not spend
much more time now on the juvenile-crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said that Lott was overstating his concerns about
the time already devoted to the bill _ a week _ and that he was the
one not interested in passing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority leader is paving the way to kill this bill and to
shift the blame, mostly because of the gun-related issues that have
come up during this debate,'' said Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said late last week that he wanted work on the bill wrapped
up by Tuesday. But it became clear Monday that because of
parliamentary procedures put in place at the end of last week, the
Senate on Tuesday will debate another measure, concerning liability
problems posed by the year 2000 computer bug, unless the members
reach unanimous consent to turn back to the crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said on Monday that the terms of that consent were a strict
limit on debate, and he suggested 6 p.m. Tuesday as a finishing
point. But he was rebuffed by Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, who
was speaking for Democrats in the chamber at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been dilatory,'' Wellstone said. ``We're going
through the amendments. That's how you do it in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott replied that the Senate simply had to move on to other
pressing matters, like a vote on an emergency spending bill to pay
for the military effort in the Balkans. If the Senate moved on,
further debate on the juvenile-crime bill would be delayed past
Memorial Day and possibly for months.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that they had winnowed their own list of
remaining amendments to seven but that Democrats still had more
than 40. Democrats would not specify the number of amendments they
still had but said they too were trying to shorten the list.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Democratic aide said some Democrats were reluctant to
shorten the debate on the bill because they felt it was to their
political advantage either to prolong discussions about gun control
or to have Lott end those discussions and be perceived as less
concerned about gun control than they are.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking reflects their belief that in the wake of the
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., last month, most American
voters now agree with the Democrats' longtime advocacy of more
stringent regulations for firearms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
