<HEADER>
A0757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-TICKS-COX     05-17 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TICKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outdoor activities may tick off many
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN CO., Ohio _ Let the biting begin.
</P>
<P>
   A mild winter and a warm spring have caused the number of ticks
_ particularly the dog tick _ to surge over last year, experts say.
While this is good news for the blood-sucking arachnids, it means
tense moments for the urban transplants and outdoor enthusiasts
encountering them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to be a bad tick year,'' Chris Dauner,
assistant park manager for Caesar Creek State Park in Warren
County, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dauner, who spends much of his workday outside, has found ticks
crawling on him this season. Dan Collins, director of environmental
health for the Warren County Combined Health District, has pulled
20 from his dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But Dauner stresses that more ticks shouldn't mean less time
outdoors, provided campers and enthusiasts take precautions. He
suggests people check themselves for ticks, wear long pants with
the ankles closed and monitor bites for telltale signs of Lyme
Disease or Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these diseases pop up each year in Ohio. The Ohio
Department of Health received reports of 49 Lyme Disease cases and
10 Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever cases in 1998, said Bob Restifo, a
medical entomologist with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In Warren County, the combined health district recorded 10 cases
of Lyme Disease during over the plast decade, but none in the plast
four years, Collins said. Health officials haven't encountered
Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever in at least a decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County Health Department has recorded 23
instances of Lyme Disease and three cases of Rocky Mountain Spotted
Fever since 1990, officials said. Figures for Greene and Miami
counties weren't available Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dog ticks, which carry Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever, account for
much of the state's tick population. But instances of Lyme Disease
continue to outpace Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever, even though the
deer tick that which carries the disease, is rarely found in the
state. Restifo said only nine deer ticks have been found in Ohio
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   People sometimes contract the disease while traveling out of
state. Others theorize that disease-carrying deer ticks come into
the state on raccoons hitching rides on trains and trucks or by
falling off of migratory birds, said Mark Case, supervisor for
Montgomery County Health Department's bureau of special services.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, health departments, hospitals, clinics and
individuals have sent the state health agency 500 ticks for
identification or disease testing, Restifo said. That's twice the
number the agency received during the same period in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone sees the increase, though. Miami County extension
agent Jeff Layman believes the grub worm and carpenter bee
populations grew this year, but he doesn't see a similar increase
for ticks, he said. Greene County extension agent Jerry Mahan knows
there's are a lot of ticks out there, but not necessarily any more
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in Warren County. The health district office receives six
or seven calls each week from people asking questions about ticks
and the diseases they carry, Collins said. In a typical year, the
office receives one call each week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many calls to rolling into Collins' office come from people who
moved to Warren County from larger cities. Though they may have
encountered the bug before, they find them in much larger numbers,
which prompts a flurry of questions for health officials, he said.
One woman who moved to the rural county from Detroit had never
before seen a tick, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep both families and pets safe from ticks, experts say to
keep grass and other vegetation around homes cut short. They also
advise wearing light-colored clothing so ticks can be easily seen;
tucking pants into the socks; using bug repellants.
</P>
<P>
   Don't smash the bugs while they're on the skin since their
bodily fluids can spread infection, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Collins has his own method for disposing of them once they're
pulled from his dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing to do is flush them down the toilet,'' Collins
said. ``That's what I do with mine. I've never seen one swim back
up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
