<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOM-DIARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALCOM X FAMILY MAY TRY TO BLOCK AUCTION OF DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his coat pocket the day he died, Malcolm X carried a small
red diary, scribbled with notes of of upcoming meetings and phone
numbers of personal friends like actor Ossie Davis.
</P>
<P>
   When assasins burst into the Audobon Ballroom and fired 16
bullets into the civil rights leader's body, three tore through the
diary, leaving it punctured and stained with his blood.
</P>
<P>
   The tattered, tiny diary became evidence when three men went on
trial for Malcom X's murder in 1965, and a valuable piece of
history, logged and stored in the city's municipal archives.
</P>
<P>
   Now, somehow it has been removed from its file in a Brooklyn
warehouse, and turned up for sale at a San Francisco auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm X's children are stunned by the book's mysterious
disappearance, and want it returned. The city is investigating
whether the diary was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very intimate item as far as the last moments of
their father's life is concerned and they were shocked and angry to
find it appear at an auction house on the west coast,'' said James
Fleming, a Manhattan-based lawyer for Malcolm X's family. ``They
very much would like it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The family is prepared to go to court, if necessary, to halt the
scheduled May 27 auction at Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The auction house claims it took it on good faith that an
unidentified seller had legitimately acquired the red imitation
leather booklet. It was expected to be sold for as much as $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The seller said he bought the 146-page datebook from another
unidentified seller who, in a letter signed ``to whom it may
concern'', claimed he had purchased the diary in the early 1990s
when the New York City Police Department was purging its files.
</P>
<P>
   New York City officials, however, said it is not customary to
sell the personal effects of muder victims.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said late Monday that city officials told him that they
could find no evidence that the diary had been part of any police
department purging.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of such activity there is only one conclusion _
the item was stolen,'' Fleming said. ``We will work with the city
to get the auction house to voluntarily discontinue the auction of
the diary and if they don't then we'll go to California and get an
injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Butterfield and Butterfield said the auction house
would remove the diary from the auction if city officials can prove
that it was stolen or illegitimately acquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would anxiously await paperwork from the city attorney, and
at that point we would most likely remove it from sale should
questions about title be raised,'' said Levi Morgan, a spokesman
for the 134-year-old firm that enjoys a high reputation in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the New York City law department said
officials were still trying to trace the diary's route from
Brooklyn to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains names and phone numbers of Malcolm's friends
and associates, personal notes and details of his schedule. For
example, a few days after he was gunned down, Malcolm was scheduled
to attend a meeting at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   City officials thought the diary was in a manila envelope inside
a New York Police Department evidence voucher listing one ``1965
Red Diary with 3 bullet holes (belonging to) Malcolm X Little.''
</P>
<P>
   But the envelope was empty on Friday when Kenneth Cobb, director
of the New York City Municipal Archives, went to check.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb said there is no way to tell right now when the diary was
taken out of the envelope. ``I'd certainly like to know that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The archives had inherited two boxes of files, which included
the now empty envelope, from the Manhattan District Attorney's
office in 1993, 25 years after the case involving Malcolm's killing
was closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the diary was stolen then it would have happened somewhere
between the police property property room, the district attorney's
office and the municipal archives,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   In most crime cases, city officials said, evidence is passed to
the archives after 25 years in the district attorney's office. They
said family members can claim items after a case is closed.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said Malcolm X's children knew the city had been storing
material from their father's murder and were ``shocked'' to learn
that the diary was being sold by a San Francisco auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm's children want to make their father's artifacts
available to the public in a proper setting, Fleming said, adding
that the slain black nationalist's family would be happy to provide
the municipal archives a copy of the diary.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Byron Rushing (D-South End) said any sale should be
stopped, and questions about the diary's ownership answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a historical perspective this is a very important
document that would be of extreme interest to scholars and
researchers,'' said state Rep. Byron Rushing (D-South End), who is
a historian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
