<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VOICES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY ISRAELI VOTERS, IT WAS A QUESTION OF CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the end, Ariella Bivas said, it was Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's character that decided her vote on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving a polling station on Monday morning, Mrs. Bivas, 35,
said she had voted for Ehud Barak, but not because his peace
platform was so different from Netanyahu's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both want to make peace because that's what the people
want, and they'll both have to give up territory,'' said Mrs.
Bivas, who had not supported Netanyahu in the 1996 election either.
``What bothered me was that the country is being led by a person
who is dishonest and untrustworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Character issues figured prominently in conversations with
voters who chose Barak, many of whom felt that Netanyahu's style
and statements had undermined good government and polarized
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used his power for incitement and divisiveness,'' said
Tamar Greidinger, 40. ``There was a lot of hatred, and it will take
a long time to rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   In what became a bitter campaign laced with blunt ethnic
appeals, Netanyahu had repeatedly lashed out at liberal ``elites''
who he said despised the groups that had brought him to power and
were the core of his governing coalition: working-class Sephardic
Israelis of Middle Eastern and North African origin, Russian
immigrants and ultra-Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But even some voters who had backed Netanyahu, in this election
and the last, cited character as a decisive factor, arguing that
his tough posture was an asset for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's brilliant and clever, he stood firm and protected the
Land of Israel,'' said Marusia Nagar, 50. ``He stuck to his
principles, withstanding pressure at home and from the whole world,
including America. It wasn't a simple matter. He had to walk a fine
line between the Jewish settlers and the Oslo agreements, putting
his own government at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Mor, 26, who was also casting a vote for Netanyahu for a
second time, said this stance had brought results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security has improved under Bibi, there are fewer terrorist
attacks,'' he said. ``He was strong on that issue, and Arafat
definitely had to take that into account. Arafat wants Barak,
because he knows that he'll give in more easily.''
</P>
<P>
   But at polling stations on Monday, it was clear that significant
numbers of Netanyahu's former supporters had deserted him,
disenchanted by a style of government that alienated even some of
Netanyahu's closest political allies.
</P>
<P>
   Meir, a taxi driver who would only give his first name, voted
for Netanyahu in the 1996 election after Palestinian bus bombings
shook his faith in the Labor-led government of Shimon Peres. Since
then, he said, Netanyahu had squandered the faith people had put in
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for Bibi because the terrorist attacks were a
catastrophe, and I figured that it can't get any worse,'' Meir
said. ``He was young and new and I thought I would give him a
chance. But he turned out to be an operator and a manipulator, and
he let the ultra-Orthodox run wild. His policies left us isolated
in the world, and he had a negative impact on our political
culture. His only interest was political survival, no holds
barred.''
</P>
<P>
   Nissim, a 39-year-old of Iraqi origin from the depressed Katamon
neighborhood, also switched from Netanyahu to Barak, attracted by
his promise to create jobs and improve education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted economic change,'' Nissim said, declining to give his
full name. ``In my neighborhood we have no after-school programs
that will keep the kids busy in the afternoons. We need subsidized
day-care centers. I have four children and I can barely make it
through the month. The economy is more important right now than
security.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As news of Barak's victory spread through Jerusalem on Monday
night, elated supporters honked their car horns downtown. Earlier
in the day, Netanyahu's backers, who were sluggish during the
campaign, made an 11th-hour effort to close the gap with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign volunteers handed out stickers and leaflets to
motorists, and sound trucks plastered with Netanyahu's pictures
plied the streets, booming out campaign jingles.
</P>
<P>
   Members of ultra-Orthodox parties allied with Netanyahu worked
hard to get out every last vote. At one polling station, two men
from one ultra-Orthodox party assisted a paraplegic from their car.
Vehicles driven by party workers ferried people to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In ultra-Orthodox neighborhoods, wall posters carried rabbinic
injunctions to vote for Netanyahu, asserting that it was ``a sacred
duty'' to vote for the candidate who was more likely to uphold
``the spirit of religion and the tradition of Israel.''
Ultra-Orthodox pirate radio stations broadcast calls throughout the
day to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Netanyahu's message wore thin, no longer
resonating with most Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a polling station, Najat Mahanna, 62, a die-hard
Sephardic supporter of Netanyahu, sang the praises of the prime
minister. ``He's strong and he doesn't give in easily,'' she said.
``He wants a real peace, not a fake peace in which we give and the
Arabs do what they want. We shouldn't just give.''
</P>
<P>
   But Raheli Mizrahi, 23, who is dating Mrs. Mahanna's son, shot
back: ``No one wants to give, but we have no choice. We have to
live with them and they're also human beings. Bibi's too
stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't live in the past, you have to deal with today's
reality,'' Ms. Mizrahi went on. ``At least Barak will make peace.
That's the main thing _ that there should be peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
