<HEADER>
A0764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFL-WARFIELD-LAWSUIT-     05-17 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-WARFIELD-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio man files lawsuit against NFL famer Warfield
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ What's the value of an introduction to National
Football League Hall of Fame star Paul Warfield?
</P>
<P>
   At least $620,000 and still counting, a local man's lawsuit
scheduled for a Tuesday U.S. District Court trial in Dayton claims.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit hinges on Washington Twp. businessman Richard J.
Rentz's contention that his introduction of Warfield to two Miami,
Fla., businessmen led to them to a lucrative license to design,
manufacture and distribute National Football League athletic
sportswear that feature team and NFL logos.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the introduction and license, Rentz was to
receive 1 percent of the gross sales of Dynasty Apparel Industries,
Inc., according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the evidence Rentz will introduce to prove this verbal
contract are tape recordings of his telephone conversations with
Warfield and Dynasty principals Armando Mendez and Ignacio Mendez.
</P>
<P>
   Rentz's attorney, Christopher J. Cornyn, said he believes the
recordings ``support the premise that there was a contract entered
into between Mr. Rentz and Dynasty Apparel.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1990, the lawsuit claims, Armando Mendez met
Rentz at a baseball game in Cincinnati and they soon became
acquainted socially.
</P>
<P>
   Ignacio Mendez and Armando Mendez told Rentz that their
business, Dynasty, ``would stand to substantially profit
financially'' if they could secure an NFL apparel license.
</P>
<P>
   Rentz, in turn, ``offered to secure the personal services'' of
Warfield, who was dismissed as a defendant in the lawsuit, to
obtain the license from NFL Properties, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said Rentz knew Warfield because Warfield was renting one
of Rentz's properties for a placement service company he operated
here.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting on Oct. 30, 1990, Ignacio Mendez, Armando Mendez
and Warfield met with Rentz in Dayton and agreed to pay Rentz 1
percent of Dynasty's gross NFL sales for his personal services in
assisting them in obtaining the license, the lawsuit claims.
</P>
<P>
   But after ``numerous conversations and meetings,'' Ignacio
Mendez told Rentz in January 1991 that Dynasty did not receive an
NFL license ``through the efforts of Paul Warfield but primarily
through the services of another undisclosed individual,'' the
lawsuit claims.
</P>
<P>
   Warfield, the lawsuit claims, ``concealed that he was the
promoter of a closely held Ohio corporation registered under the
name of Jemesco which was incorporated in December 1990 for the
purpose of obtaining or assisting in the obtaining of one or more
NFL apparel licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing Warfield from the lawsuit, Chief U.S. District
Court Judge Walter H. Rice found that there was not a contract
between Warfield and Rentz.
</P>
<P>
   Dynasty also denies there was a valid contract with Rentz and
insists it never made any promises of payments to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jemesco, Cronyn states, has a joint venture with Dynasty in
which Jamesco receives 3 percent of Dynasty's gross sales, which
has made Warfield ``a very wealthy man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the inception of the Dynasty-Jemesco licensing
relationship with NFL Properties, Dynasty has accumulated gross
sales of NFL licensed merchandize in the aggregate amount of
$62.952 million,'' according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Dynasty has subsequently secured similar licenses with the
National Basketball Association, Major League Baseball and the
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The jury trial is expected to last three days.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Hills writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
