<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO DECIDE HOW FAR STATE, LOCAL GOVERNMENTS CAN GO IN
BANNING NUDE DANCING IN BARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim) 
 
By JENNIFER DAY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
Pennsylvania's high court was wrong to strike an ordinance
prohibiting nude dancing in public as a violation of the First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, in Barnes vs. Glen Theatre Inc., the court
issued a divided decision upholding a similar Indiana ordinance.
The city of Erie, Pa., contends the Supreme Court of Pennsylvania
disregarded precedent set by that decision in ruling that the
Erie's 1994 ordinance prohibiting ``appearing in a state of
nudity'' in a public place is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our courts are bound by precedent, whether that precedent is
agreeable to the jurists or not,'' wrote Gregory Karle, an attorney
for the city, in his brief urging the justices to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a lawsuit filed in 1994 by Kandyland, an
Erie establishment that provides nude dancing. It was supported by
two local theater companies that were concerned the ordinance would
prevent dramatic productions, such as ``Hair'' and ``Equus,'' both
of which contain nudity.
</P>
<P>
   An Erie County court found the ordinance an unconstitutional
violation of the First Amendment, and the city appealed. The
appellate court reversed that ruling, using a second U.S. Supreme
Court ruling to determine which opinion in Barnes should be
considered precedent-setting.
</P>
<P>
   The state appellate court decided that the ordinance should have
been tested according to guidelines articulated by U.S. Supreme
Court Justice David Souter in Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Further, it found the Erie ordinance survived the test, which
required that the law had to be designed to ``prevent secondary
effects associated with adult entertainment,'' and should be
allowed to stand.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court of Pennsylvania, however, overturned the lower
court, finding the justices' decision ``hopelessly fragmented'' and
a ``hodgepodge of opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the appeals court ruled that Souter's opinion set a
binding standard, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled that no
single opinion commanded a majority of five justices, so there was
no binding precedent.
</P>
<P>
   The state's high court then conducted its own review as to
whether the ordinance was intended to ``impact negatively on the
erotic message of the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   It ruled that it was attacking expression based on its content
and struck down the ordinance as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philip Friedman, an attorney for Kandyland, argued the city did
not ignore the ruling in Barnes. In his brief, he wrote that even
if Souter's decision was treated as precedent-setting, the city
never presented evidence to show there were harmful effects
resulting from nude dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he wrote, the city was clearly targeting dancing in
venues such as Kandyland because it allowed nudity in a production
of ``Equus.``
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pennsylvania Court viewed the Erie ordinance as
content-based as the only difference between nudity at Kandyland
and nudity in `Equus' was the message conveyed by the dancer,''
Friedman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arguments, which will focus on whether the Pennsylvania court
willfully ignored the U.S. Supreme Court's established precedent,
will be heard this fall or early in the new year. A decision will
be rendered before July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
