<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. TEAM ARRIVES IN BELGRADE TO STUDY REFUGEE CONDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A U.N. mission has arrived here on its
way to Kosovo, where it hopes to establish the fate of tens of
thousands of refugees in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   Headed by the undersecretary-general for emergency relief,
Sergio Vieira de Mello, the 13-member team plans to spend two to
three days in Kosovo, despite NATO's refusal to guarantee its
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot wait for a settlement of the problem to assist the
immense need of the people inside Kosovo,'' Vieira de Mello said at
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   NATO supported the mission and had given assurances, but not
guarantees, for its safety, he added. NATO had advised the group to
give 48 hours' notice of its itinerary, use clearly marked vehicles
and to travel only by day.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. official said none of the parties had welcomed the
mission. The Yugoslav government, which will escort the mission
throughout, had nevertheless promised a certain flexibility, Vieira
de Mello said. The mission had also informed the Kosovo Liberation
Army of its plans, and it awaited a response.
</P>
<P>
   The main aim is to review civilians' conditions like shelter,
food and health, as well as human rights. ``Human rights are
everything,'' Vieira de Mello said.
</P>
<P>
   One objective is to find people reportedly taking refuge in the
hills, he said, but he conceded that such work would be extremely
difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
