<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-17 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANS WINTER SHELTER FOR 1 MILLION REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO planners are preparing to shelter up to one
million refugees from Kosovo in Albania for the winter, in case the
war in the Balkans does not end soon and Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic unleashes a flood of new exiles.
</P>
<P>
   Masses of ethnic Albanians who were driven from their homes by
fear of the ethnic-Serb-dominated Yugoslav military or fear of NATO
bombers almost derailed the NATO campaign against Yugoslavia in its
early days, as their sheer numbers threatened to destabilize
Macedonia and widen the war.
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, Yugoslav forces near border crossings into
Albania and Macedonia have been turning back trains packed with
refugees and groups of refugees on foot, causing Western officials
to worry that Milosevic may be building up escape pressure among
the hundreds of thousands of displaced Kosovars prior to releasing
a large mass all at once.
</P>
<P>
   With the war in its 55th day Monday, J. Brian Atwood, who is
administrator of the Agency for International Development and the
chief US refugee-relief official, announced a joint US-United
Nations program to shelter an additional 345,000 Kosovar Albanians
with host families in Albania proper.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to recruiting more host families in Albania, Atwood
said about 4,000 unused buildings in the country have been
identified that could be converted to shelters once they were
repaired and winterized.
</P>
<P>
   He said studies have begun on how to winterize the refugee
camps, most of which are tent cities and would require, at minimum,
floors and heaters. While an immediate decision to winterize the
camps was not necessary, he said it would take ``a couple months''
to do the work once the research is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 900,000 ethnic Albanians have fled or were expelled from
Kosovo, a province in Serbia where they once made up 90 percent of
the population, since the onset of NATO's campaign to stop
persecutions by Serbs which had long been driving Kosovar Albanians
out at a slower rate. About that number remain in the province, an
estimated 700,000 of them as displaced persons, unable to return to
their homes and livelihoods, according to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said that although officials do not expect all 700,000 to
be pushed out of Kosovo ``we've been surprised before'' _ by the
huge numbers in the early days of the conflict -- ``and we have to
prepare for the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects that the Yugoslavian regime will want to
retain about 300,000 ethnic Albanians in Kosovo for use as human
shields against NATO strikes, and to serve propaganda purposes, but
that ``there is a real possibility that 400,000 more people will
come out. It depends on the state of the diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In other major developments Monday:
</P>
<P>
   --Television in Montenegro, a small republic which is part of
Yugoslavia but which has broken ranks with Serbia in the current
crisis, reported that riots were occurring in Serbian towns whose
residents opposed their men being sent to Kosovo. Broadcasts
monitored by the BBC reported that a crowd of angry Serbs in
Aleksandrovac lynched the chairman of the town assembly, and that
in Krusevac more than 5,000 people, mainly women and children,
gathered to demand the return of soldiers from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO military strikes slowly began to spread over the country
after two days in which the pace of activity was severely limited
by the weathers. Several fuel depots were hit, and missiles struck
a military airport in the suburbs of Belgrade. Residents reported
hearing planes and heavy anti-aircraft fire in various parts of the
capital. Underscoring fears the conflict could spread, witnesses
said Serb artillery Monday shelled an area along the border with
Albania after nine Albanian tanks approached within a mile of the
frontier. The shelling stopped when the Albanians withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   --German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder traveled to Finland for a
meeting with President Martti Ahtisaari, who is working with
Russian special envoy Victor Chernomyrdin to broker an end to the
fighting, and to Italy, where Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, like
Schroeder himself, is under domestic pressure to make peace. No
information was released about the meeting in Finland. In Italy,
D'Alema's spokesman said, the two leaders discussed a proposal for
an immediate ceasefire based on a UN resolution accepting NATO's
program for returning the refugees to Kosovo. US Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott is to meet Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   --Greek officials said Foreign Minister George Papandreou
planned to propose a temporary 48-hour halt to the bombing to give
diplomacy time to work. In a newspaper interview, Papandreou said
he would make the same proposal to Moscow and Washington. Belgrade
would have to give a positive response to the truce, he said, or
bombing would resume.
</P>
<P>
   --Ibrahim Rugova, a pacifist Kosovar Albanian leader, said that
photos of him shaking hands with Milosevic and signing a document
calling for an end to the airstrikes were taken under duress, and
that he allowed them to be taken in an effort to gain freedom for
his family. Rugova and his family were allowed to leave Yugoslavia
May 5. They went first to Rome, then settled in Bonn, where he
repudiated the propaganda photos in an interview with a leading
German newspaper. Rugova said he would visit refugee camps in
Macedonia next week, and advocated continued NATO bombing until
Serb forces leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   --Hundreds of unarmed Yugoslav troops poured into Cetinje, an
ancient capital of Montenegro and home of its present-day
independence movement. Tensions between soldiers and residents were
reportedly running high, but there was no violence. ``I'm afraid
that everything will blow up, possibly,'' said Dragisa Burzan,
Montenegro's deputy prime minister and spokesman for the republic's
reform-minded administration. Military police were chased from the
area last month after they tried to hand out draft notices.
</P>
<P>
   The program to create more housing for refugees in Albania will
include a stipend to be paid host families by the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees and a one-time assistance package of
essential household goods from the United States, such as
mattresses, clothing, cooking implements and blankets. Host
families also will receive an increase in food rations.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive payment from the UN will be $30 per host family
each month, plus $10 for each refugee the family takes in, an
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood and other US officials, who reviewed the refugee-relief
efforts during and after Monday's briefing at the State Department,
said the International Committee of the Red Cross and some Greek
non-governmental organizations have been given limited
opportunities to deliver food and medical supplies to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But, they said, no decision has been made about the possibility
of air-dropping the large quantities which are believed to be
needed. A State Department official said last week that air-drops
would begin within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how effective it's going to be,'' said
Lieutenant General John M. McDuffie, director of the Pentagon
logistics directorate.``I mean, we really wouldn't know if we're
feeding the Serbs or if we're feeding the IDPs'' -- internally
displaced people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
