u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-VOTE-NYT &LR;      05-17 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ISRAEL SELECTS A NEW LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 18:
</P>
<P>
   The decisive election victory of Ehud Barak, and the rejection
of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu after three years in office,
is a political earthquake in Israel and throughout the Middle East.
Now Barak, one of the most decorated military men in Israeli
history, confronts a full range of opportunities and perils. He has
promised to unify the country's feuding factions, revive peace
negotiations with the Palestinians and energize the economy, though
he has provided few details on how to achieve these aims. His first
priority must be to form the broadest possible ruling coalition in
parliament, consistent with his principles and the need for bold
action.
</P>
<P>
   The voting suggested that Israelis had grown impatient with the
slow and erratic peace process under Netanyahu, whose claims that
Barak would weaken Israel seemed to backfire. In three turbulent
years in office, Netanyahu was a tough and eloquent defender of
Israeli security needs. He reached important agreements on Hebron
and parts of the West Bank, but each was defended as a grudging
step rather than put forward as part of a larger strategic vision
enlisting the Palestinians as Israel's partners. Netanyahu's
concession statement was gracious, in contrast with the angry and
divisive tone of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns in the election for parliament show that, as
expected, smaller splinter parties made gains at the expense of the
larger parties headed by both Barak and Netanyahu. But while the
Labor Party lost a few seats, the Likud bloc all but collapsed, and
is certain to go through a bitter leadership fight now that
Netanyahu has resigned as party leader. Barak should be able to
construct a center-left ruling coalition. But it will be difficult
for him to reconcile conflicting demands among all groups that
might wish to join his government, especially those representing
Russians, Sephardic Jews and a new party of secular Jews that
criticized the grip of religious Jews on the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat and other Arab leaders hailed Barak's victory, and
indeed the election may portend an easier time in negotiations over
the final status of a Palestinian homeland, the contentious issue
of Israeli settlements on the West Bank and Jerusalem and even
negotiations with Syria. No doubt President Clinton will move
quickly to help restart the discussions in these areas. But
Palestinians should not expect any dramatic changes. One reason
Barak won was that he convinced voters that he would not trifle
with Israeli security. The Palestinians, who avoided violence
during the campaign, would do well to continue in that vein.
</P>
<P>
   With Barak's victory, Israelis have proven themselves to be
impatient voters. This is the second time in a row they have
repudiated a sitting prime minister and turned to someone basically
untested from the younger generation. Barak, a stolid campaigner
who pulled well ahead of Netanyahu in the last few days, surely
knows that it can happen again. His toughest challenge may be to
restore a sense of unity of purpose to a divided electorate, which
has grown weary of having its divisions exploited by politicians.
Israel's new prime minister has won an overwhelming victory few of
his supporters thought would be possible a few weeks ago. He must
now heal his nation and reawaken the dormant peace effort. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
