<HEADLINE>
WHEN GOLF BALLS BECOME EASELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Like master painters, some pro golfers decorate
their golf balls with fancy artwork or personal messages.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But this isn't beauty for the sake of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   There is a method to the madness of marking a Max Flight, a
method to ensure a PGA pro doesn't whack the wrong Wilson out of
the rough. Those methods will be on display this week when 113
golfers tee off at the MasterCard Colonial beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Playing your golf ball, and not the ball of your playing
partner, can be a tricky proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo was believed to be the only golfer to mark his ball with
No. 11, in honor of winning his first two Masters championships in
a playoff on the 11th hole. But on the second day of the 1994
British Open, Faldo lost his tee shot in the heavy rough on the
course in Turnberry, Scotland, and mistakenly hit Jim McGovern's
lie. Faldo took a two-stroke penalty, triple-bogeyed and finished
the tournament tied for eighth place.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers on the PGA Tour mark their golf balls to avoid a
Faldo-like miscue in a variety of ways for a variety of reasons.
For instance, on some of Tiger Woods' balls is the animal that
bears his namesake. John Daly has the University of Arkansas
razorback stamped on his ball. Duffy Waldorf has his golf balls
marked by his wife and children with messages and reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Frazar has superstitions about the number he uses to
mark his ball. For him, the number on his Titleist could in some
weird way have an impact on the score he shoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't use No. 4s because I don't want to shoot a four on a
hole,'' Frazar said. ``I practice with No. 4s, but if I hadn't used
them all up by Thursday, I just throw them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope, I like using the No. 3s. A three is good on any hole.
And I'll use a No. 2. But never, never a No. 4.''
</P>
<P>
   For other golfers, there is not a whole lot of magic involved
with marking their balls. If one golfer in a twosome uses a blue
magic marker to identify his ball, the other golfer might use a red
magic marker. Some golfers simply have their initials engraved on
the ball. But initials can have their drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad thing about putting your initials on the balls is that
when you give them out and a guy hits one into the pool or
something,'' said Billy Ray Brown. ``A golf club member finds the
ball and thinks I'm the one that hit the ball crazy into the pool.
I say, `Hey, it wasn't me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Painting Pinnacles for identification purposes has, of course,
gone on for a long time. The late Ben Hogan would put a black dot
on his ball, but he took it a step further. He'd pour about 100 or
so Spaldings or McGregors into a tub of Epsom salt, then rotate
each ball to see the position of the dot to find if the core was
evenly weighted. He'd use the ones that were, toss out the ones
that weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben tried to identify the variables he could control,'' said
Hogan's biographer, Curt Sampson, ``and Ben was a control freak
when it came to golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan was meticulous and is not known to have hit the wrong
ball. But despite hours of preparation, some golfers still do the
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a shadow on the ball in some deep rough at a pro-am
in Las Vegas,'' said D.A. Weibring. ``It was on the same line as my
amateur's ball was. It looked like my ball. But as soon as I hit
it, I knew it was wrong. When that happens in a pro-am, that is
when the relationship between the `pro' and the `am'
deteriorates.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth native Clark Dennis has taken great precautions not
to mistake his ball for another. Marked on the balls he uses are
his kids' initials, CWD and TAD _ for Clark William Dennis and
Thomas Alexander Dennis, four dots on each side of the number on
the ball, and a solid line through the word, ``professional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got it all marked up so that I can't possibly mistake it
for anyone else's,'' Dennis said. He then turned to his wife,
Vickie, and said, ``We can't have anymore kids, or I'll run out of
room on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vickie: ``Oh, I think we can squeeze one more in.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
