<HEADLINE>
COOL FEATURES IN STORE FOR PGATOUR.COM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine being at work on a Thursday or Friday afternoon and
being able to follow your favorite PGA Tour golfers via a
customized, real-time leader board while you're accessing
PGATour.com.
</P>
<P>
   While you have one eye on the boss, a tiny leader board pops up
as a separate window on your Web browser with live stroke-by-stroke
updates of your favorite golfer(s).
</P>
<P>
   For typical golf fans, it beats getting elbowed in a gallery
full of fans. For fantasy-golf enthusiasts, it's a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's pretty cool,'' said Charlie Schmitt, general
manager of PGATour.com.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if it pans out as planned, it will be.
</P>
<P>
   However, the feature won't be available until at least July 1 or
until PGATour.com's agreement with SportsLine USA is complete.
</P>
<P>
   For fans who intend to follow this week's MasterCard Colonial at
Colonial Country Club in Fort Worth, it's not cool _ but it should
be worth the wait. A customized leader board is expected to be just
one of the enhancements in store for the July relaunch of
PGATour.com (www.pgatour.com); the staffs for the PGA Tour and
SportsLine USA are meeting today to brainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The multiyear agreement between Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based
SportsLine USA and the Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla.-based PGA to
co-produce the 2-year-old site is based on each organization's
accurate perception that each site complements the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the kind of deal where we felt we were really stronger
together than apart,'' Schmitt said.
</P>
<P>
   PGATour.com has real-time scoring for PGA Tour, Senior PGA Tour
and Nike Tour events and multimedia features, all powered by IBM.
SportsLine's GolfWeb has news from the United States Golf
Association, LPGA, European PGA Tour and other international tours
in addition to content about travel and commerce for the average
hacker.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also increases exposure for PGATour.com.
SportsLine USA, which produces CBS SportsLine, has steadily
increased its assets by absorbing domestic and international sports
sites the past five months. SportsLine already has a sizable sports
presence on America Online, the Web's most-popular site.
</P>
<P>
   ``By combining what we had in place, we now have by far the best
golf destination on the Web,'' said Michael Levy, president of
SportsLine USA.
 &LR; subheds:Bytes
</P>
<P>
   SportsLine goes Euro: In SportsLine's continuing expansion to
everything sports, it has announced that it has partnered with
Intel, MediaOne, and Reuters to create SportsLine Europe.
</P>
<P>
   SportsLine plans to use the multilanguage site to focus on
soccer, auto racing, rugby, cricket, skiing and other
European-style sports. The first SportsLine Europe sites will be
developed for the United Kingdom, Netherlands, France, Germany,
Sweden and Italy. The first, in Britain, is expected to be
operational by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see any of the other sports companies, CNN/SI or
ESPN.com, with an interest or making a move in this direction,''
Levy said. ``We see a void and a great opportunity to build the
biggest site out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com spokesman Eric Handler said ESPN.com also has plans to
build an international audience through its relationship with ESPN
International, which has 20 networks overseas amounting to 150
million households in 21 languages.
 &LR; subheds:Chatter
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: One place that a spit wad from New York Jets
linebacker Bryan Cox can't hit anyone is in cyberspace. The
flamboyant Cox is a scheduled chat participant on NFL.com at 11
a.m. tomorrow ... Nikki McCray of the WNBA's Washington Mystics, 7
tonight, CBS SportsLine ... Cincinnati Bengals linebacker Takeo
Spikes, 3 p.m. today, NFL.com.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
