<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO HEAR DRIVERS' PRIVACY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., S.C., Neb. Fla., Pa.)  (dal) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court broadened its exploration of
federalism issues on Monday by agreeing to decide whether Congress
had violated states' rights when it prohibited state motor vehicle
agencies from revealing personal information about drivers who did
not consent to the disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The case is an appeal by the Clinton administration of a ruling
last year that declared the Drivers Privacy Protection Act of 1994
unconstitutional. The 2-1 ruling, by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Richmond, Va., said that the law had offended ``our
system of dual sovereignty'' by telling the states what they could
and could not do with their drivers' records.
</P>
<P>
   The law has been unpopular among the states, where marketers and
operators of commercial databases had provided a new source of
revenue in return for access to names, addresses, telephone numbers
and medical and disability information on licensed drivers. New
York earned $17 million in one recent year from charging for access
to the state's computers for examining driver information. Media
organizations have also objected to the law on the ground that it
blocks public access to information.
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by states in federal courts nationwide, the law has
so far been upheld in two federal circuits and struck down in two
others. That made Supreme Court review almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The court has been deeply split on federalism issues, with most
recent cases decided by votes of 5-4 in favor of the states. This
case is especially interesting, beyond the fate of the Drivers
Privacy Protection Act, because the 4th Circuit majority wrote an
aggressively states' rights opinion that requires the justices to
confront the meaning and implications of some of their most
disputed recent precedents.
</P>
<P>
   All but inviting the justices to overturn a 1985 decision that
made federal minimum wage-and-hour regulations applicable to state
employees, the appeals court quoted from Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist's dissenting opinion in that 5-4 case, which itself
contained an unusually explicit vow to revisit the issue ``in
time'' and to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The case Monday, Reno vs. Condon, No. 98-1464, originated with a
lawsuit filed by South Carolina seeking an injunction against
enforcement of the drivers' privacy law.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law in response to the murder of an actress,
Rebecca Schaeffer, whose home address was obtained by a stalker
using motor vehicle records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence gathered by Congress revealed that that incident was
similar to many other crimes in which stalkers, robbers and
assailants had used state motor vehicle records to locate, threaten
and harm victims,'' the administration said in its Supreme Court
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In voiding the law, the 4th Circuit interpreted the Supreme
Court's precedents as permitting Congress to bind the states only
to generally applicable laws. This law failed that test, the
appeals court's majority said, because only states operated motor
vehicle departments. When the justices hear the case in the fall,
the administration is likely to argue vigorously that the 4th
Circuit misread the precedents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the court began its annual end-of-term rush, these were among
the justices' other actions on Monday:
</P>
<P>
   Car Seizure
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled, 7-2, that police do not need a warrant to seize
a car that they have reason to believe is subject to forfeiture
because it has been used to commit a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The decision overturned a ruling by the Florida Supreme Court
that held that police should have obtained a warrant before
seizing, from an office parking lot, a car that they had videotaped
months earlier being used to deliver cocaine. After a search of the
car turned up two pieces of crack cocaine in the ashtray, the owner
was charged with and convicted of drug possession.
</P>
<P>
   All states except Nebraska have laws that classify automobiles
as subject to forfeiture under similar circumstances and that
permit seizure without a warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court Monday, Justice Clarence Thomas said that
Supreme Court precedents going back many decades had upheld
warrantless seizure of contraband, particularly in public places
where no invasion of privacy is involved.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justices John Paul Stevens and Ruth
Bader Ginsburg said the court should have adhered to the basic
presumption that a warrant was required. Although there are
exceptions to the warrant requirement, they said, the decision
Monday ``suggests that the exceptions have all but swallowed the
general rule.'' The case was Florida vs. White, No. 98-223.
</P>
<P>
   Nude Dancing
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed to revisit the question of whether states can
ban nude dancing, an activity that the court's precedents regard as
having some ``expressive content'' entitled to a measure of
protection under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In the court's last treatment of the subject, in a splintered
1991 decision, the justices held that nude dancing could be
regulated as long as the goal was not to suppress a message but to
protect health and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the court has become more protective of
speech and more demanding of states that offer vague or unsupported
justifications for their speech regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court struck down a
nude-dancing ban in Erie, rejecting the city's argument that the
ban was justified as a crime-control measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it highly circuitous to prevent rape, prostitution,
and other sex crimes by requiring a dancer in a legal establishment
to wear pasties and a G-string before appearing on stage,'' the
state court said. Pennsylvania's appeal, Erie vs. Pap's a.m., No.
98-1161, asked the justices to clarify the law in this area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
