<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-TCU-TWO-SPORT-TEX </SLUG>
 
TCU's Huffman looks back on a two-sport course in college 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Nearing the end of a career that has brought
him All-America recognition and national acclaim as an outstanding
two-sport athlete, TCU third baseman Royce Huffman feels that a
brief testimonial is called for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have to thank \Rbaseball coach\S Lance Brown,'' he
said, ``for taking a chance on me when I was a short, fat
freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice call, Lance. Take a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has a year of football eligibility remaining,
Huffman is winding down a four-year baseball career that earned him
second-team All-America status in 1998 and has made him a strong
candidate for postseason honors this year.
</P>
<P>
   It has also left him at or near the top of virtually every
career category in the school record book, as the second-place
Frogs (29-24, 19-10) ready themselves for the Western Athletic
Conference tournament that starts tomorrow and runs through
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Huffman is TCU's career leader in hits (310), doubles (58), home
runs (42), total bases (514), runs batted in (218) and walks (154).
He has the second-highest career batting average (.3995) and also
ranks second in slugging percentage (.662), games played (208),
at-bats (776) and runs (222).
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he tied the single-season record for hits (89) and
compiled the second-highest batting average at .420. Thus far, he
has 87 hits this year and is hitting .422 with 13 home runs and 57
RBI.seasons, including 115 in a row _ a string that ended last week
when a sprained ankle benched him for the second game of the San
Jose State series. He was back in the lineup the next day, batting
1-for-3 as the designated hitter.]
</P>
<P>
   He has had a string of 115 consecutive starts that ended two
weeks ago when a sprained ankle benched him for the second game of
the San Jose State series. He was back in the lineup the next day,
batting 1-for-3 as the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Known in TCU football circles as ``Slash'' for his multipurpose
play as punter/runner/receiver/punt returner/passer, Huffman has
been Old Reliable for four years in the baseball program. In
Brown's view, he has also been something of a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing you can say about Royce is that
every year he's been here, he's gotten better,'' Brown says.
``That's a very hard thing to do, especially for someone who was
good to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``You rarely see a player do that _ somewhere in there they'll
have a bad year, or sometimes just level off. But Royce has worked
every day to improve himself, and I think what he has achieved
there is probably more amazing than all his records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot about the type of person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   For Huffman, the explanation is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never be personally satisfied with any season,'' he says.
``Not until I bat 1.000 and hit a million home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his focus at the moment is on the WAC tournament,
Huffman says it sometimes hits him that his TCU career is nearly
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to think about it,'' he says, ``especially being
a senior and not knowing exactly when it will end. I only know it
seems to me like I just got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it started four years ago when the members of a team
from Elkins High School in Missouri City, near Houston, scattered
like buckshot across the Texas collegiate landscape.
</P>
<P>
   They had just finished a 32-2 state championship season, and
Huffman _ also the quarterback on the football team _ had earned
all-state honors for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Among others, the group included Rice outfielder Jason Gray,
Texas A&AMP;M outfielder Steve Truitt and Baylor second baseman Eric
Nelson. There was also pitcher Kip Wells, who left Baylor after
last season as a first-round draft choice of the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was also a guy named Mike Peterson, who was drafted by
the Rockies,'' Huffman said. ``There were about 12 to 14 seniors
who got Division I scholarships. We all grew up together, and we've
known each other all our lives. We're still very close, and
everyone keeps up with everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of that group, Huffman _ whose father, Royce, played
football at TCU from 1970-72 _ made a choice dictated solely on the
opportunity to play both football and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my coach to tell the recruiters that,'' Huffman says.
``The school that offered me the chance was TCU.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved fortuitous. Last fall, as TCU rose from the dead
under new football coach Dennis Franchione, /Sports Illustrated''
identified Huffman as one of the top 10 dual athletes in America.
</P>
<P>
   Undrafted in baseball last year, Huffman remains uncertain about
his immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have said the reason I wasn't drafted was because
of football,'' he says, ``but I don't really know what the deal
was. I want to play \Rpro\S baseball, and I still have a year of
\Rfootball\S eligibility left at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the ideal situation would be to do both, but I'll just
have to wait and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, I guess I'm reaching a point where one part of
your life ends, and it's time to start something new.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
