</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN REJECTING NETANYAHU, ISRAELIS CHOOSE A MAN OF RESTRAINT
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ISRAEL-VOTE, ISRAEL-BARAK)  
(rm) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The leftist Meretz Party presented the political
commercial most insulting to Benjamin Netanyahu during this
campaign. It showed him dancing furiously, faster and faster, to
the music of a klezmer band whose musicians were ultra-Orthodox
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   It was a merciless mocking of the prime minister of Israel.
Critics of Netanyahu found it uproariously funny. Yet it also left
them sad, many said in interviews. It was time, they said, to have
a leader who didn't open himself up to such ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   It would be insulting both to Ehud Barak and to the Israeli
electorate to suggest that this was nothing more than a
throw-out-the-Netanyahu vote.
</P>
<P>
   Very clearly, Israelis were not just rejecting but choosing,
too. Weary of conflict, they were electing what they considered the
best path to internal and external peace, a resolution of both the
conflicts within their society and those on their borders. They
wanted normalcy, order, and integrity in government.
</P>
<P>
   And to get these things, they wagered, with the choice of Barak,
on an old model: a kibbutznik and decorated general who to them
seemed capable of both toughness and compassion. They wanted
someone who could be as conciliatory as he was firm, and someone
without the taint of corrupt associates.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Netanyahu's Cabinet members and his former chief of staff
are under criminal investigation. One of his closest allies, Aryeh
Deri, leader of the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, was recently
convicted on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   In Barak, Israelis consciously, or unconsciously, chose a former
protege of the late Yitzhak Rabin, although one who, like he did,
faces his first term in office after decades of experience as a
commander but little experience in the consensus politics of
governing.
</P>
<P>
   Barak deliberately evoked the link with Rabin throughout his
campaign. Following his lead, his supporters spontaneously gathered
at Rabin Square in Tel Aviv Monday night, where he ended up
delivering a second victory speech. Many talked about his victory
serving as a means for them to resolve the undigested trauma of
Rabin's death.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in the way he ran his very professional campaign,
skillfully led them to these conclusions and associations. Gerald
Steinberg, a political scientist here, called the campaign ``a
triumph of avoidance.'' It was totally intentional.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of a prime minister who was the relentless
subject of national attention, Barak bet that a low profile would
be a strong selling point. And he didn't bet blindly. Using an army
of consultants, he conducted continuous field polls, and
cross-tabulated the results with every sector of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is not a man lacking in self-confidence, and running for
the top office in Israel is hardly an exercise in humility. Yet as
much as could be possible within the constraints of his character
and the campaign, Barak did not blow his own horn.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again in the last few months, the trait he demonstrated
most clearly was restraint. And in the volatile Mideast, that can
be a very appealing characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu is too provocative and too controversial to heal
this nation,'' said Tamar Harel, a saleswoman in Jerusalem. ``For
three years, everything has been about Bibi. It's time for Israel
to be the important subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Ben David, a hotel worker, agreed. ``Barak is my flavor of
the day, because he's vanilla,'' he said. ``I'm dying to be bored.
That would be so normal. To have a boring leader who just does his
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Brainy, competitive and and capable of being a show-off, Barak
resisted all temptation to display this part of himself on the
public stage. Last week, he was on the verge of giving a classical
piano concert to Russian immigrants in Rishon Letzion. The piano
was supposedly on the stage, awaiting his fingers. But he must have
sensed that while his direct audience would have loved it, the
larger Israeli public might have be tempted to poke fun. He didn't
play.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Barak made a strategic choice to present himself as a
calm, almost bland voice of reason and integrity: the dovish hawk,
the Maimonides-quoting secular Jew. Tonight he quoted scripture and
appealed to his ``brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that many chose Barak because they did not like
Netanyahu. For all those who admired the prime minister because he
was ruthless, there were others who were depressed by the way he
antagonized both associates and leaders of other countries.
</P>
<P>
   This election was clearly a referendum on Netanyahu, whose
personality loomed large on the Israeli stage for the last three
years. He galvanized the Israeli public in a way that is probably
without precedent. Those who chanted ``Go, Bibi!'' at his rallies
idolized him with a loyal passion; those who criticized him,
including did so with what seemed to be outraged enmity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rabin was hated by the right wing for his policies,'' Nachum
Barnea, a columnist for the Yedioth Arhonoth newspaper wrote on
Monday. ``Netanyahu was hated both by left and right because of his
character, because of his winks, because of his shocking
appearances. The hatred went overboard _ what Menachem Begin could
be forgiven for, Netanyahu could not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak successfully co-opted a principal part of Netanyahu's
appeal. Netanyahu has hammered the phrase ``peace with security''
into the Israeli psyche. Only he could deliver a peace agreement
with teeth, he said _ one that guaranteed Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   With his military credentials, however, Barak seemed tough
enough to many Israelis, and few believed he would jeopardize
Israel's security after a career spent fighting terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
