<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Britain renewed its pressure on NATO allies to consider a
ground attack in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bad weather forced NATO to scale back its raids.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yugoslav media reported that in the first five weeks of the
campaign, NATO attacks caused more than $100 billion in damage in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder arrived in Finland for
talks on Kosovo with President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER DEVELOPMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A U.N. team toured sites bombed by NATO in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, at the beginning of its 10-day mission to assess relief
needs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovo political leader, said in Bonn,
Germany, that he was under duress when he called in Belgrade for a
halt to the airstrikes.
</P>
