<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO, HOUSTON OFFICIALS DISCUSS POSSIBLE TRAVEL WARNING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Zuniga) 
 
By JO ANN ZUNIGA 
and JENALIA MORENO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The consul general of Mexico in Houston met Monday
with city police officials to discuss the police shootings of three
Mexican citizens, incidents that caused some Mexican officials to
consider warning citizens not to travel to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Consul General Rodulfo Figueroa said police officials
agreed to give him those details of their investigations next week.
He also said he had offered to give a cultural sensitivity course
at the police academy.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Fred King would provide no details of
Figureroa's meeting with Assistant Chief J.L. Breshears, Capt.
Richard Holland of the homicide division and community liaison
Faustino Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discussion is ongoing, but we cannot reveal the substance,''
King said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican government officials said last week that they were
considering warning their citizens to avoid traveling to Houston,
the fourth-largest city in the nation, because they were unhappy
with the investigations into the shooting deaths of Eulogio Perez
last month, Pedro Oregon Navarro in July and Uvaldo Garcia
Armedariz in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope we do not have to issue such an advisory,''
Figueroa said.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon was shot 12 times by Houston police in an aborted drug
bust. Oregon had a gun but tests showed it was not fired. Garcia
was shot by officers responding to a domestic disturbance call when
he brandished a chair and began charging at one. Eulogio Perez was
shot last month when he fired at officers after being stopped,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior government official in Mexico City, who asked not to be
identified, said the Mexican government has never considered
issuing such a travel warning before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are upset certainly because there is a pattern emerging
here,'' he said. ``We feel that this is our duty to put a warning
to our citizens who very often go to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   He said such a warning would come from Mexico's foreign affairs
department and would probably be posted on the Internet. However,
he said, only two to three million of the 93 million Mexicans have
access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said they don't want to issue such a warning
because it could affect business between Houston and Mexico, but
they said they would not tolerate Mexicans being shot by police.
</P>
<P>
   Port of Houston Authority Commissioner Vidal Martinez said
business ties with Mexico might have already been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is being looked at as being anti-Latin or
anti-Hispanic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Cantu, a Houston Latino activist, criticized Mexico's
threat as ``political strategy for internal consumption in
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted Mexico's human rights violations against its own
citizens and U.S. tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico doesn't have a leg to stand on and thus cannot accuse
nor has any credibility to accuse others,'' Cantu said.
</P>
<P>
   City Council member Orlando Sanchez said his office is also
reviewing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo is scheduled to speak in June
at an economic conference in San Antonio. He has canceled any plans
to also visit Houston, Dallas or Austin, but consul general
Figueroa said that cancellation had to do with time limitations and
not the possible advisory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
