<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-MARROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE DIVIDED OVER HIGH-DOSE BREAST CANCER TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y., Mich.)  (mk) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cancer experts at an international conference here on
Monday were in such disagreement over the best way to treat
advanced breast cancer that one of them, Dr. Karen Antman of
Columbia University, said she was jokingly advised by her
colleagues to wear a flak jacket while making her presentation.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were five studies testing the efficacy of a
controversial procedure: high-dose chemotherapy followed by bone
marrow transplant or, more commonly, by a transplant of stem cells,
specialized cells that help marrow regenerate, from the patient's
own blood.
</P>
<P>
   Summaries of the studies, which were formally presented here
Monday, had been posted on the Internet last month, and their
equivocal results caused consternation among advocates of the
procedure and women who contemplate having it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the treatment has been proved to help people with
leukemia and other cancers affecting the blood and immune system,
it has never been definitively proved useful in breast cancer.
Nonetheless, since the 1980s it has been held out by some doctors
as the best hope of survival for women whose outlook is grim
because their breast cancer has spread to 10 or more underarm lymph
nodes, or even farther, to bones or other organs. About 12,000
American women with breast cancer have undergone the high-dose
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The five studies were discussed Monday in a vast, echoing hall
the size of a football field at the Georgia World Congress Center,
where 20,000 cancer experts from 70 countries were attending the
annual meeting of the American Society of Clinical Oncology. There
was so much interest in the data that two extra conference halls
were set up with video equipment to hold the overflow crowd from
the main hall.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the studies were from the United States, one from
Scandinavia, one from France and one from South Africa. Only the
South African study showed a benefit from high-dose treatment; the
other four simply showed no difference in survival between women
given high doses and those receiving standard therapy.
</P>
<P>
   When the summaries were released, experts said the high-dose
technique still merited further study. They also suggested that new
data and scientific debate at the meeting might shed more light on
the findings and help patients decide whether to undergo the
treatment, which has harsher side effects and greater risks than
standard treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But patients and doctors hoping for guidance from Monday's
meeting might have been disappointed. ``It won't change anything,''
said Dr. Larry Norton of the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center
in New York, an author of one of the papers that said no benefit
had yet been shown. ``People who like to transplant will continue
to transplant, and people who don't will continue not to.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his co-authors, Dr. William Peters of the Karmanos Cancer
Center at Wayne State University in Detroit, said it was important
for women to make sure they had the procedure done at a center that
performed at least 20 a year. He said that at centers that did
fewer transplants, there was a higher death rate from complications
from the procedure itself.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's meeting, two researchers who did not participate in
the studies, Dr. Antman of Columbia University and Dr. Gabriel
Hortobagyi of the Anderson Cancer Center at the University of
Texas, presented their views on the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Hortobagyi called the findings disappointing, and though he said
they deserved further study, he also said that at this time
bone-marrow transplant could not be recommended to women as having
any advantage over standard therapy. He said the South African
study must be replicated by other researchers to determine whether
the findings held up.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Antman found the studies encouraging, saying that if the
findings seemed disappointing, it was because the data were being
examined too early. She said that with time the high-dose treatment
might prove to prolong women's survival and also give them more
time free of signs of the disease, a major factor in determining
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   High-dose treatment is one of the most contentious subjects in
breast cancer therapy. Passionate advocates who have staked their
careers on it say it is the only hope for women with advanced
disease. But opponents argue that the hope is false and that women
should not be subjected to the risks and harsh side effects of the
treatment, because it has not been proved to lengthen their
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment itself can be fatal: In early studies, the toxic
drugs killed 15 percent to 20 percent of patients, and though some
centers now report death rates of 3 percent or less, some studies
that combine data from different centers still report rates
averaging 7 percent. Side effects go far beyond the nausea,
vomiting, diarrhea, fatigue and hair loss usually associated with
chemotherapy. They include severe infections, bleeding, organ
damage and painful mouth sores that may make it impossible to eat
for weeks on end.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Monday's meeting said they could not explain why
the South African findings on high-dose treatment were so different
from those of other researchers, though the South Africans used
different drugs from those given in the United States and also
performed the high-dose procedure in a different way. In other
studies, patients were first given a course of standard treatment,
followed by the high doses. But the South African team, led by Dr.
Werner Bezwoda of the University of Witwatersrand Medical School in
Johannesburg, gave patients the high doses right away, without the
initial course of standard therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers said that going straight to high doses might be
the secret to Bezwoda's success, and they suggested that other
teams should try it as well. But one researcher said a group of
scientists had asked the National Cancer Institute to send a
scientist to South Africa to re-examine the study data.
</P>
</TEXT>
