<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0817 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKRUPTCY-SFCHRON &LR;      05-17 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bill Would Make It More Difficult to File for Bankruptcy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Many people who file for bankruptcy protection could find it much
harder to escape their debts if a bill recently passed by the U.S.
House of Representatives is signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ inspired by a growing credit crisis that prompted 1.4
million U.S. households to file for bankruptcy last year _ will be
debated soon by the Senate, perhaps as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   That record number of bankruptcy filings _ in the face of a
strong, growing economy _ was about five times the number filed in
1984. California, with 12 percent of the nation's population,
accounted for 205,000 filings, or nearly 15 percent of the national
total.
</P>
<P>
   The filers were allowed to wriggle out of an estimated $40
billion in debts. Virtually all of that _ equivalent to $150 per
U.S. resident _ is likely to get passed along to other consumers in
the form of higher prices and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed bill would greatly strengthen the hand of the
credit card industry by allowing card issuers to legally challenge
individual bankruptcy filings.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, though, say the root of the problem isn't abuse of
the present law. They accuse creditors of making credit too
tempting and accessible for people in marginal _ or worse _
financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the bill on May 5 by a lopsided 313-to-108 vote
after heavy lobbying by banks, credit card issuers, retailers and
finance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, the bill would tighten the qualifications
for Chapter 7 bankruptcy filings. Under Chapter 7 of the federal
bankruptcy law, you can shrug off all your debts and start again
with a clean financial slate.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill would make it harder to qualify for Chapter 7 by
subjecting filers to a strict income and means test.
</P>
<P>
   The test could force many filers into Chapter 13 instead. Under
Chapter 13, individuals must agree to a schedule of payments that
would liquidate at least part of their debts.
</P>
<P>
   At present, federal bankruptcy judges are free to determine
which individuals qualify for Chapter 7 or Chapter 13 and which are
not legally entitled to bankruptcy protection. In practice, more
than 70 percent of filers wind up in Chapter 7.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House-approved bill, judges would be allowed less
discretion.
</P>
<P>
   A Chapter 7 filing probably would be prohibited if both of the
following are true:
</P>
<P>
   _The filer's household income exceeds the state median. (In
California, that figure is $58,000.)
</P>
<P>
   _The bankruptcy trustee affirms that the filer should be able,
over a five-year period, to pay back either $5,000 or 25 percent of
the outstanding debt, whichever is less.
</P>
<P>
   The judge could make exceptions in special cases _ for example,
if the filer or another member of the household has serious medical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains numerous other provisions that give creditors
more legal rights and restrict the ability of debtors to walk away
from their obligations.
</P>
<P>
   It allows creditors to sue to challenge individual bankruptcy
filings, and it exempts creditors from certain types of
class-action lawsuits brought successfully by debtors in the past.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sears Roebuck paid around $300 million in penalties
and reimbursements in the past two years to settle class-action
lawsuits accusing it of improperly collecting credit card debts
from 180,000 bankruptcy filers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House-approved bill, such class actions would be
prohibited, according to Frank Torres, legislative counsel for
Consumers Union. Debtors who felt they were mistreated by their
creditors would have to file suit individually, he says, and
chances are they wouldn't, because of the attorney fees.
</P>
<P>
   Torres is one of those who blame the credit card industry for
fueling the bankruptcy crisis.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that card issuers mailed out 3.8 billion solicitations
last year, most of them offering tempting and ``misleading'' teaser
interest rates good for only a few months before rates of 18
percent and higher kick in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who might not have been extended credit 10 years ago
now get it,'' he observes. ``That includes people who can be
severely affected by small changes in the economy. Then the credit
industry wonders why people go bankrupt, and wants the government
to take the responsibility off their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres urges financially shaky consumers to fight temptation, to
``think twice before you pull out the plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Use credit cards only to buy absolutely essential goods and
services for which you don't have cash on hand, he says _ not for
impulse purchases that you can't afford. If you let the credit
balance mount up, he warns, the interest charges can overwhelm you.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Climo, group director for financial industry affairs with
the American Bankers Association, disputes the notion that
creditors offer credit indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the never-ending torrent of credit card
solicitations, applicants are carefully screened once they apply,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in no creditor's interest to extend credit if a person
doesn't have the capacity to pay,'' she insists.
</P>
<P>
   A co-sponsor of the House bill, Representative George W. Gekas,
R-Pa., hailed its passage as a blow against financial chicanery. He
contends that people ``who can afford to pay their debts'' are
abusing the bankruptcy system, using it as ``a financial planning
tool.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous horror stories to support that
contention _ for example, cases where people binged on
ultra-expensive vacations just before filing for bankruptcy,
knowing that they wouldn't be able to pay their credit card
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the bill also cite former Baseball Commissioner
Bowie Kuhn, actor Burt Reynolds and the late Texas Governor John
Connally, all of whom were permitted to keep multimillion-dollar
homes after filing for bankruptcy, thanks to liberal homestead
exemptions in their states.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, the nationwide homestead exemption would
be capped at $250,000 _ meaning that any value in the home above
that figure could be taken by the bankruptcy trustee to settle
debts.
</P>
<P>
   This provision of the bill was weakened, however, by states
rights advocates in the House. Under a compromise, the bill permits
state legislatures to override the cap by allowing homestead
exemptions greater than $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bill does require two years of residency in a state before a
bankruptcy filer can take advantage of that state's homestead
exemption. The idea is to discourage debtors from moving out of
states with low homestead caps and into those with high ones or
none at all.
</P>
<P>
   It's not certain that the House bill will become law.
Congress-watchers say the Senate is less hawkish toward bankruptcy
filers, and that a final, compromise version could be watered down.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, President Clinton has vowed to veto any bankruptcy
bill that he considers too harsh. And he has stated outright that
the bill passed by the House fits that description.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lopsided vote in the House suggests that a
presidential veto could get overridden. It takes a two-thirds vote
of both houses to override a veto, but the House bill was approved
by just under three-fourths of those voting.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Randall Newsome, a federal bankruptcy judge in Oakland,
says the House version of the bill could have ``nightmarish
consequences'' for bankruptcy courts, adding greatly to the
bureaucratic burden.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the bill requires bankruptcy applicants to produce
their three most recent income-tax returns, to help the bankruptcy
trustee assess their finances.
</P>
<P>
   If they fail to do so within a specified period, their cases
would be automatically dismissed. They can file again, but the
second time around they get only 30 days to complete the entire
bankruptcy procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy applicants, by and large, are not sophisticated or
well informed, Newsome observes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them, who may not be able to lay hands on their old tax
returns, will be out of luck because ``there are no exceptions'' to
that requirement. Newsome envisions an avalanche of aborted
filings, dismissals and reapplications that will overtax his court
and its staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we have to go through all this?'' Newsome wonders. ``Is
it to move people into Chapter 13? No. It sounds to me as though it
is to keep them out of the bankruptcy system altogether.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
