<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 No Way to Skip Bill For '96 Tax Goof
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I contributed $2,000 to my Individual Retirement Account
in 1996 and deducted that much from my income in figuring my taxes
for the year. Recently, I received a notice from the Internal
Revenue Service informing me that I was not allowed to make the IRA
contribution because I did not have any earned income.
</P>
<P>
   My only income is from a pension, interest, dividends and rents;
I earn no wages. They want me to pay taxes on the $2,000, plus
interest on the unpaid tax, and penalties. Is there any way for me
to avoid this? Can I plead ignorance? Also, is there some way for
me to take the $2,000 out of the IRA without paying a penalty?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You definitely will have to pay the taxes and
interest on the $2,000 you improperly deducted from your income for
1996. There is no escaping that because, as the IRS indicated, you
had no earned income.
</P>
<P>
   As for the penalty, try appealing it to the IRS. IRS spokesman
Jesse Weller makes the well-worn point that ``ignorance of the law
is no excuse.'' But he says that if you had a sound reason for
thinking that you were entitled to make the $2,000 contribution
that year, you should explain it in a detailed letter. Don't get
your hopes up _ but you should at least try.
</P>
<P>
   You are entitled to withdraw the $2,000 from your IRA without
penalty, and you had better do it promptly _ along with any
earnings the money has produced. The longer your money remains in
the IRA, the more the IRS can penalize you. And don't forget to pay
taxes on the earnings as well as the principal.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you are younger than 59-1/2 years old, you will
have to pay not only income taxes on the earnings, but also a 10
percent early withdrawal penalty on those earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the story: Always read the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P vs. Russell 2000
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me the difference between the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index and the Russell 2000 index? I hear both of them mentioned
a lot, but nobody bothers to explain what they are.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: There is a huge difference in the makeup of those two
indexes.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index consists of 500 of the largest
publicly held companies in the United States, spread across every
major industry. Among the stocks are Microsoft, General Electric,
Intel, IBM and Citigroup, to mention a random few. Taken together,
the 500 represent the bulk of the value of all stocks traded in
U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 is near the other end of the spectrum. It
consists of 2,000 small to midsize public companies. Have you ever
heard of Agribiotech, Brookdale Living, Felcor Lodging and Regency
Realty? All of them _ and a lot of other nonhousehold names _ can
be found on the Russell 2000 roster.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a huge difference in the way the two indexes have
performed.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks have been relatively weak during the raging bull
market of the past four-plus years, while big-name companies have
been overachievers. Since the end of 1994, the S&AMP;P 500 has enjoyed
an average annual gain of about 30 percent. During that same
period, the Russell 2000 has gained an average of about 15 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
   A Penny Saved
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in purchasing a penny stock _ a company
valued at less than $1 per share. I am prepared to invest $10,000,
but my broker at Merrill Lynch tells me that this will cost me in
the neighborhood of $700 in commissions, or 7 percent of the
purchase price. Is there some less costly way to purchase these
shares?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: There almost always is a less costly alternative to
Merrill Lynch. Venerable old Merrill, bless its heart, regards
itself as the Tiffany of the brokerage industry and charges
Tiffany-like commissions to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Try one of the online discount brokers instead. You probably can
make the trade you describe through most of them for a commission
of less than $200. I would rather not recommend any particular
broker, but I'll point out _ as an example _ that Suretrade
 &LR; (www.suretrade.com)  &LR; would charge you $112.95 in commissions to
buy 10,000 shares of a $1 stock.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad you didn't tell me the name of the stock or what _ if
anything _ the company does. If you had, I might have been tempted
to tell you not to risk your money _ or at least not so much of it.
Penny stocks as a class are notoriously risky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
