<DOCNO> NYT19990517.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETSEY-JOHNSON-FASHIO     05-17 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETSEY-JOHNSON-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETSEY JOHNSON: HONOR FOR A LIFE OF CELEBRATING YOUTH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Betsey Johnson bounces into a room exuding energy, her
rag-mop of blatantly dyed red hair swinging, you half expect her to
turn a cartwheel. But no. ``I do only two cartwheels a year,'' she
said. That would be at the finale of her spring and fall runway
shows, where they are as much of a signature as the colorful jersey
prints and sweaters, the laced-up corsets and frilly petticoats she
finds new ways of showing every season.
</P>
<P>
   But she did turn a mental cartwheel when she heard about the
special award she will be getting for ``timeless talent'' from the
Council of Fashion Designers of America on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely shocked,'' Ms. Johnson said the other day,
curled up in a chair in her sunny yellow and hot pink Seventh
Avenue showroom. ``I really did not expect anything until Lifetime
Achievement time. There was buzz before, but there was never an
award for me. I'm not at that mega-level with Donna and Calvin and
Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sales are less than $40 million a year, a fraction of what
those high-powered designers sell. And she knows she would never
get the Designer of the Year Award from the council, because she
doesn't follow fashion trends and is rarely taken seriously as a
designer by her peers or the fashion magazines. But Ms. Johnson has
survived for more than 30 years despite changes in fashion that she
has pretty much ignored, sticking to what she calls a formula.
``It's no big thing,'' she said. ``Take a leotard and add a
skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration came from her early training as a dancer, and
she has managed to work enough variations on the theme to
constantly attract a new generation of young women who find the
clothes both comfortable and feminine. And affordable, to boot,
with prices from $60 to $300. (Since 1996 there has also been
Ultra, a second line with more costly fabrics and trimmings, priced
from $500 to $1,000.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If a girl comes to me first for a prom or a bar mitzvah and
she likes the way she looks and her boyfriend likes the way she
looks,'' Ms. Johnson said, ``she'll come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kal Ruttenstein, the senior vice president for fashion direction
of Bloomingdale's, said: ``Everybody talks about the fact that a
designer who wants a long life in fashion has to have a look and
keep updating and refining it. Betsey Johnson was one of the first
to establish a look back in the '60s. She's always had her own
little niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Herman, the president of the fashion designers' council,
calls her one of the first ``emancipated'' designers. ``Back in the
'60s,'' he said, ``she was at the forefront of designers doing
clothes that were not expensive. She never overreached herself. She
found her metier very quickly. Her clothes changed slightly but
have always been consistently irreverent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not getting the award this year because of this year's
collection or last year's collection,'' he said. ``There's
something to be said for history. There's something to be said for
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson is a perennially youthful 56 in tight T-shirts and
stretch denim Capris, who readily admits to having had breast
implants when she was 48 and a face lift at 50. ``I used to design
for my body, which was flat-chested with big hips,'' she said.
``That's why my clothes were tight on top with full skirts.''
</P>
<P>
   She felt she needed the face lift to look good for public
appearances, photography and television, which she is doing more
and more frequently. Yet her stomach does cartwheels when she
thinks about the thank-you speech she will make at the fashion
awards ceremony, this year renamed the American Fashion Awards. (An
edited version will be shown on E! Entertainment Television on June
13.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never be able to get through saying the speech,'' she
said, her voice choking up and her heavily made-up hazel eyes
filling with tears.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long wait since 1971, the year she received a Coty
Fashion Critics Award for the innovative knits she designed for a
junior sportswear house called Alley Cat. (It was the same year in
which Halston was honored for his high-fashion work and Elsa
Peretti for her jewelry.)
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Betsey Johnson had made a name for herself in the
mod '60s, designing for a string of hip boutiques called
Paraphernalia and the trendy Betsey Bunky Nini boutique in
Manhattan. She had already established the exuberant, cheerfully
sexy style she stuck with after Alley Cat folded and she was
reduced to freelance work and designing children's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '70s my girl moved up to work and dress-for-work
clothes, and my customer disappeared,'' Ms. Johnson recalled.
``Then all of a sudden in the late '70s there were the English and
punk and the CBGB's. That kind of youth thing came in again, so I
thought maybe it's my time again. But I couldn't get anyone to put
money behind me. I decided I needed a partner.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978 she hooked up with Chantal Bacon, who had been in charge
of sales for Betsey Johnson Kids, and opened the Betsey Johnson
business with money she had made in the stock market, help from her
father and a bank loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chantal was from New Jersey, but she'd been a model in London
in the '60s and was a friend of rock stars,'' Ms. Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bacon also knew how to run a business, it turned out, and
the partnership has endured. They now have 26 boutiques, including
four in New York and one in London, and sell to major stores like
Neiman Marcus as well as to 700 specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our partnership is better than a marriage,'' Ms. Johnson said.
``We keep our private lives separate, but we've been through a lot
together. She keeps the books and I keep the look.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Ms. Johnson first put her toe in the business pond
when she ran a dancing school while attending high school in
Connecticut. She was born in Wethersfield, outside Hartford, and
started to study dancing at age 4 _ ballet, jazz, tap and
acrobatic. She learned the construction of clothes by making
patterns and samples of dance costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Syracuse University, followed by a summer guest
editorship in 1964 at Mademoiselle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betsey was a blond bombshell, so full of beans and so
talented,'' recalled Edith Raymond Locke, who was the magazine's
fashion editor at the time. ``It all began with her making a
T-shirt top. It was the era of the tight high armhole, and we all
thought it was terrific. We ran a little thing about it in the
Mademoiselle shopping column and she got orders. Then Paul Young
called and said he needed a young, with-it designer for this new
company called Paraphernalia.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, a British retailer, who brought the swinging London
concept to New York, featured Ms. Johnson's designs alongside those
of such '60s icons as Mary Quant and Emmanuelle Khanh. In March of
1966, Mademoiselle ran a photograph of Julie Christie wearing a $35
dress designed by Betsey Johnson for Paraphernalia, and soon her
clothes were being worn by the likes of Twiggy, Penelope Tree,
Brigitte Bardot and Raquel Welch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edie Sedgwick was my fitting model at Paraphernalia,'' Ms.
Johnson recalled. ``For five years I had nobody say do this or do
that. It was so fabulous. I'd go to work every day and think, `What
do I want to wear?' If it sold, I still had a job. There was
nothing negative. Now, you have to think of the negative and the
positive constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the positive success of winning an award, two
negatives have intruded on her recently: the breakup of her third
marriage, and the departure from her business of her 24-year-old
daughter, Lulu, who has worked with her mother virtually all her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for the first time in my life looking at what else would I
have done if fashion wasn't there,'' Lulu Johnson explained. ``I'm
taking acting classes with Stella Adler. Not that I want to be an
actress. I'm talking about hosting on MTV or something like that.
...'' Her voice trailed off.
</P>
<P>
   But she will still be an unofficial sounding board. ``She is so
cut out for this business, a real natural,'' her mother said,
obviously regretting the loss of her daughter's everyday presence.
``I always talk over my ideas with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Lulu Johnson has a style of her own, her opinion will
always be valued. As her mother said: ``In the '60s there was a
look. In the '70s there was a look, and in the '80s. Now, it's a
free-for-all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
