<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEC-SFCHRON &LR;      05-17 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Former Insignia Execs Settle SEC Charges
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Two former officials of Insignia Solutions agreed yesterday to pay
a total of $100,000 to settle Securities and Exchange Commission
charges that they falsified the software-maker's 1996 financial
results.
</P>
<P>
   David Gibbs and Stuart McIntosh, formerly sales executives at
the British company's U.S. headquarters in Fremont, will pay
penalties of $75,000 and $25,000, respectively, to end an SEC
lawsuit that accused them of scheming to inflate Insignia's
revenue. Insignia's stock is publicly traded in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement of the suit, filed yesterday in U.S.
District Court in San Francisco, the two also agreed to permanent
injunctions barring them from violating anti-fraud provisions of
federal securities laws. The two neither admitted nor denied the
SEC charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate SEC administrative action, Insignia agreed to
cease and desist from violating federal financial reporting
requirements. The company didn't admit wrongdoing, and the agency
didn't impose a fine.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said Gibbs and McIntosh shipped far more software than
they knew distributors could sell and that they entered secret
agreements with them that granted unusually liberal return rights.
To conceal the over-shipment, the two ordered a subordinate to
report only 10 percent of the inventory held by distributors,
according to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Insignia restated its 1996 financial results in May 1997,
trimming previously reported sales by $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company addressed the matter and gave full cooperation to
the SEC,'' said Timothy Roake, Insignia's outside attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs and McIntosh left Insignia about the time the company
restated earnings. The two couldn't be reached for comment.
Insignia makes software that permits computers with different
operating systems, such as Apple McIntoshes and Windows-based PCs,
to communicate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
