<HEADLINE>
POLITICS: TAKING THE `HELP' OUT OF `HELPMATE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editorial Observer)  
 (af)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 18: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Elizabeth Dole seriously wants to be a presidential
candidate, the first thing she is going to have to do is lock up
her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm her biggest fan and supporter,'' Bob Dole told Richard
Berke of The New York Times this week. Dole then went on to say
that he was thinking about writing a check to Sen. John McCain,
Mrs. Dole's competitor.
</P>
<P>
   With spouses like this, who needs opponents? Dole, who benefited
mightily from his wife's nonstop campaigning during his two runs
for president, says he wants to ``do for her what she did for me.''
But it is hard to imagine Elizabeth Dole philosophically
announcing, in the middle of a critical fund-raising period, that
her husband could always quit if things didn't pick up. ``If
there's no response out there, or if it looks impossible, this is
not her whole life,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously does not have a clue about what his wife actually
``did'' for him _ the abnegation of self and perpetual
cheerleading. When asked how Mrs. Dole would fare in a race against
Al Gore, her husband opined ``It's too early to tell.'' The correct
answer, obviously, is ``terrific.'' Elizabeth Dole went around
saying ``terrific'' in one form or another through two campaigns
during which her husband's performance was almost always
non-terrific in the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   There was a drop _ well, perhaps a whole gallon _ of bile in the
former presidential candidate's remarks. Asked why he never
memorized his speeches as Mrs. Dole does, her husband said, ``I
knew a lot about issues,'' which seems to hint that his wife
doesn't. Anybody who has heard Bob Dole speak off the cuff
understands that the proper response would be: ``I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   People have been wondering why Bob Dole chose to appear in TV
commercials about erectile dysfunction right at the time that Mrs.
Dole was launching her bid for a prize he had always wanted for
himself. The effort to educate fellow prostate cancer victims was
commendable, but the timing seemed peculiar. Was it principle or a
deeply sublimated desire to distract attention from his wife? The
betting continues, but when Dole started talking about how he was
looking for ``ways to help McCain in particular,'' the odds
certainly shifted in the direction of subconscious sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   At best, Dole seems to be taking the tone of one of those awful
Little League parents who specialize in withholding praise.
Defending his wife's lack of specificity on the stump, Dole said:
``You're going to get more answers than you ever thought from
Elizabeth once she hits her stride. And she's getting there. She's
got to catch up after eight years in the Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this is a presidential campaign in which the Republican
front-runner, George W. Bush, has yet to emerge from his Fortress
of Solitude in Austin. There are plenty of men out there talking
generalized glop, and Elizabeth Dole has made some surprising, and
specific, position statements on gun control, abortion and the
situation in Kosovo. We all know she is spontaneity-deprived, a
heavily programmed candidate. But her husband's failure to come
racing to her defense full throttle makes you want to get in there
and argue for her side.
</P>
<P>
   Being a politician on the national level requires an enormous
amount of ego, and while all candidates say they are in it to make
America a better place in the next millennium, a lust for the
center spotlight is usually an important factor. Perhaps a person
with the psyche of a candidate is simply incapable of spending
months directing all conversations toward the merits of somebody
else. If so, Lord help Hillary Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
