<SLUG> BC-DOW-REUTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES AND REUTERS FORM JOINT INTERNET VENTURE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dow Jones &AMP; Co. and Reuters Group PLC, perennial
rivals in the business of business information, are combining
forces to create an Internet-based service providing corporate news
and information for professionals, the two companies announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second Internet-related initiative to be announced by
Dow Jones within the last month. But unlike Dowjones.com, a site
for individual investors, which is being built from the ground up,
this joint venture will take the existing news articles distributed
on Dow Jones Interactive and its erstwhile competitor, Reuters
Business Briefing, and distribute them over the Internet, including
links to relative corporate data like securities filings or
executive biographies.
</P>
<P>
   The combined 1998 revenues of the competitors was $225 million.
The new company, Dow Jones Reuters Business Interactive LLC,
expects to earn 60 percent of its revenue from North and South
America, and most of the rest from Europe and Asia, the markets
where the company hopes to grow most quickly, according to Timothy
M. Andrews, the joint venture's president and chief executive.
Currently, 95 percent of Dow Jones' revenue is earned in the
Americas, and most of Reuters' revenue comes from Europe (70
percent) and Asia (10 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The kind of information delivered on Dow Jones Interactive and
Reuters Business briefings is tailored for professionals who want
to be alerted to developments in their own industry or others, but
do not have a stock trader's need for second-by-second
developments. Neither these two services nor the new venture, which
is expected to start within a year, will carry breaking news
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the wire services of the two companies will
remain competitive. As Philip Melchior, the chief operating officer
of Reuters' corporate and media information group, said at Monday's
news conference, ``Global interest would not be best served by
having one global news wire.'' Competition, he said, is likely to
produce better products, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, depending on the volume of news, they will carry complete
stories about the day's developments anywhere from 10 minutes to a
couple of hours after the news happens in addition to extensive
archives of their own and many other outlets' articles and
transcripts. Among the industries that the service will focus on
are financial services, computer hardware and software, chemicals,
aerospace, telecommunications, automotive and media and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Peter R. Kann, the chairman and chief executive of Dow Jones,
appeared at the New York news conference Monday, side by side with
a blurry video image of Peter Job, the Reuters chief executive. Job
noted, ``It's very rare that two well-established organizations
have such a coincidence of interest in a specific business that we
can get together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows how quickly the world is changing and how size
matters,' said Lauren Rich Fine, a media analyst with Merrill
Lynch. ``For the business user this is a very powerful
combination,'' she added. But she also pointed out that users with
broader interests in medical and scientific developments might
prefer the competing service provided by the Dialog Corp. PLC. The
dominant service in the industry, Lexis Nexis, offers a comparably
broad range of information, including extensive legal archives.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wagner, Dialog's chief executive, put out a news release
Monday in which he gave a backhanded welcome to the new competitor,
saying, ``What is interesting to note is that this new service will
be comprised mainly of news. As we have said many times before,
news is increasingly a commodity, available for free on numerous
Internet sites. In this context, news-only services are more and
more difficult to sell on a stand-alone basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
