<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA: AMERICAN MISSION
</P>
<P>
   Former Defense Secretary William J. Perry will travel to
Pyongyang by the end of the month in what could be the first
meeting between a presidential envoy and top North Korean leaders.
The State Department declined to confirm the mission, which was
announced by South Korea, but a senior U.S. diplomat said it could
be announced soon. The State Department said the U.S. was sending
the North another 400,000 metric tons of food aid, just ahead of a
planned first inspection on Wednesday of a suspected nuclear site.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Sanger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: MORE POLITICAL VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. spokesman in East Timor, David Wimhurst, accused
anti-independence thugs of killing at least five villagers and
terrorizing many others in an attempt to disrupt a referendum on
independence set for August. He called on security forces to halt
the violence, saying, ``Words by the Indonesian government are not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Mydans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: PRISON DIRECTOR GETS A LAWYER
</P>
<P>
   The imprisoned former director of Tuol Sleng prison, known by
his revolutionary nickname, Duch, has selected a lawyer. He is the
second Khmer Rouge leader to do so, following the military
commander Ta Mok. The lawyer, Ka Savuth, 61, said he had lost 2
brothers and 20 other relatives to the Khmer Rouge between 1975 and
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Mydans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: COMPROMISE REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionist Party rejected a proposal by the British and
Irish governments to end the deadlock over IRA disarmament that is
preventing the formation of a power-sharing regional government.
The Ulster Unionists said the proposal did not meet its demand that
the IRA start ``credible and verifiable'' disarmament before two
members of the group's political wing, Sinn Fein, can take seats in
the new cabinet of the Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   James F. Clarity
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: AMERICAN KIDNAPPED
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Aaron Burchell, a helicopter technician working for a
British oil company, was kidnapped over the weekend as he traveled
by taxi in northeast Colombia, near the area where three American
human rights workers were abducted and killed in March. The police
attributed the kidnapping to the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, which have a history of taking civilians for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rohter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BALANCING THE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Treasury showed a surplus of about $456 million
during the first quarter of 1999 because of budget cuts and
increased tax collection, measures undertaken to cushion an
expected drop in revenues caused by falling petroleum prices. The
surplus was nearly four times greater than in the same period in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Dillon
</P>
</TEXT>
