<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-PRI-0518-COX     05-17 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S RULING PARTY TO ALLOW FOLLOWERS TO PICK PRESIDENTIAL
CANDIDATE
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After more than 70 years in power, Mexico's ruling
party announced Monday it has voted to hold the first-ever primary
election to allow followers to select their candidate for Mexico's
2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party, or
PRI, has won Mexico's presidency, sometimes under a cloud of
suspicion of fraud. The party's candidate has always been
hand-picked by the man who won Mexico's presidency before him.
</P>
<P>
   That secret selection process, dubbed the ``dedazo,'' or ``big
finger,'' will be replaced later this year by a national vote
conducted in 300 electoral districts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The party will supervise the vote Nov. 7 of this year. Because
there is no party registration list, the vote will be open to any
Mexican with a voter registration card.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big step for the PRI, one that changes 70 years of
history,'' said analyst Luis Linares of the Mexico City think tank,
Specialized Information Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what's lacking is a series of points that define who are
going to be the possible candidates, where the polling booths are
going to be and who is going to control it all,'' Linares added.
</P>
<P>
   Polls are showing that Mexico's July 2000 election could be the
most competitive ever because strong challengers to the PRI are
emerging, including Vicente Fox of Mexico's conservative National
Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI is deeply divided over who would be its best contender;
even before Monday's announcement, several PRI politicians had
already broken with the tradition of waiting for the president to
pick his successor and begun television ad campaigns to tout
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the PRI is obligated to go through its own democratic
transition,'' PRI party president Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez
said Monday in a statement commenting on the new selection rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country has advanced toward democracy . . ,'' he said,
``but within (the party) we haven't done enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Gonzalez's comments were passed out to the press
before the vote had been officially counted.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to establish a nationwide primary with open voting
to select the 2000 candidate was made by the PRI's 331-member
National Political Council. Three hundred and seven members voted
for allowing the direct vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight voted for a system that would allow a convention of
political advisers to select a candidate and only twelve voted for
a convention of delegates to have that power.
</P>
<P>
   The new party rules also bar contenders from campaigning for the
primary before Aug. 1. There are limits of spending and no
government funds can be used.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
