<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S LITTLE REST FOR THE WEARY AND BATTERED EWING
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing was grimacing and laboring like a man staggering
through the desert by the end of Sunday's Game 5 in Miami. Worn
down by injury, depleted by exhaustion, he pushed the boundaries of
his threshold for pain to help win a first-round playoff series for
the Knicks that had everything riding on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, futures and major franchise decisions were at stake when
Ewing's performance left Allan Houston in position to hit a
dramatic game-winning shot that propelled the Knicks into the
second round, where they will face the Atlanta Hawks in Game 1
Tuesday night at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Another matchup with a Georgetown center _ this time Dikembe
Mutombo _ another test of Ewing's physical limitations. Ewing is
expected to start Game 1 even though he was writhing in pain during
the third and fourth quarters Sunday because of a muscle strain in
his rib cage. This is on top of his sore left Achilles' tendon, and
on top of the tendinitis in his knees.
</P>
<P>
   How far can he go before his tolerance for pain snaps? It seems
almost unfair to expect him to replicate his 22-point, 11-rebound
performance in Game 5 on 48 hours' rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can expect that,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said
during a conference call before his team departed for Atlanta
Monday. ``On Sunday, that was a man who went above and beyond in
terms of pain tolerance. I don't think you can do that on a nightly
basis. Hopefully, he can play effectively. With the schedule, who
knows? Whatever he can give us, we're thankful for.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's health will be pivotal to a series that may lack the
soap opera subplots of the Knicks' playoff rivalry with the Heat _
especially since these two teams have not met in the post-season
since 1971 _ but is still vital to the job security of Van Gundy,
whose status is considered unstable unless the team advances to the
conference finals. But with the Heat series so emotionally and
physically draining, Van Gundy is wary of a hangover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be right both mentally, emotionally and physically
as much as we can,'' Van Gundy said. ``We don't want to give one
away from a mental standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The intense edge of their series with the Heat was a great
motivation for the Knicks, but it is not as if they have not had
their brushes with the Hawks. On April 9, the gangly, sharp-edged
Mutombo threw an elbow that knocked out one of Chris Childs' teeth.
After he had put his tooth in his locker following the game, Childs
vowed revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get him back,'' Childs said. ``It's going to be a
12-round fight. You can call Don King. It was an intentional elbow.
I'd already passed the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   After the league fined Mutombo $7,500 and Childs cooled down,
the Knicks' game against the Hawks on April 28 unfolded without
further incident. But in that last meeting of the season, there was
a competitive back-and-forth that surfaced between Latrell Sprewell
and Steve Smith as they tried to one-up each other.
</P>
<P>
   While the Heat-like animosity is not there, there will be an
edge to this four-of-seven-game series if only because both teams
are physical. On the surface, the No. 4-seeded Hawks do not elicit
awe. They are a bare-bones team that relies on three rugged players
for the heavy lifting _ Mutombo, Smith and Mookie Blaylock. Without
the injured Alan Henderson, the Hawks are even more limited
offensively. Time after time, their core of veterans has relied on
intimidating, tenacious defense and has got by despite injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize how talented they are,'' Van Gundy said.
``They beat Indiana three out of four, and beat us two of three.
They quietly and efficiently go about their business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks took the season series against the Knicks with
Blaylock leading the way. As many point guards before him have
done, Blaylock took advantage of the Knicks' soft perimeter
defense. Childs, who has been limping with a thigh contusion, is
the better defender against Blaylock. But most often, Charlie Ward,
who has had difficulty keeping track of Blaylock, will be on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the defensive burden will fall on Houston as well.
Defending against Miami's Dan Majerle and Voshon Lenard is far less
risky than trying to stop Smith. Houston has had problems trying to
limit Smith's diverse game. He can shoot a 3-pointer, post up with
his 6-foot-8-inch frame, drive and hit his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Smith is different,'' Van Gundy said. ``Reggie Miller is
a big-shot player, but more catch-and-shoot. Steve has a very
versatile game. He can hurt you in so many ways. He's a legit
6-foot-8, great size. And so Allan has got to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   So does any Knick who dares to venture in the paint for a layup.
Mutombo is always a threat to wield an elbow and shatter a nose. He
has broken three noses this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes teams jump-shooting teams,'' Van Gundy said. ``It's
also foolish just to shoot over him. You've got to be
intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to dilute Mutombo's impact is to make him defend his
man. And if Ewing is able to drag his body on the floor, his range
will force Mutombo to do something besides sit back and swat away.
Whatever Ewing has left will be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Often this season, Ewing has not been thought of in such
praiseworthy terms. There were cries for his role at age 36 to be
reduced, for him to defer to the up-tempo style some of his
teammates wanted to run. There were times when Ewing did step back
this season, but Sunday was not one of them. Too much on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Him getting out on the floor uplifts our team,'' Van Gundy
said. ``In the fourth quarter, when he got another injury, and his
Achilles was killing him, and he plays like he did, that to me says
it all about him.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Van Gundy, Ewing's unwavering supporter for 10 years,
understands the limitations on heroics. Before the Knicks' series
with the Hawks begins, he will most likely have the same kind of
conversation he had with Ewing before the Heat matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I didn't want him to be frustrated with what
he couldn't do, because he couldn't be Patrick Ewing the whole
Miami series,'' Van Gundy said. ``I wanted him to think about what
he could do to win the series, because that was more than
enough.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
