<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SUDDENLY, EWING HAS A `PRESENCE'
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds., spelling Micheal, in 3rd graf, is CQ)  
(ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you hear what Steve Smith had to say about Patrick Ewing
after Smith and the Atlanta Hawks finished off the Detroit Pistons
and set the Knicks in their playoff sights?
</P>
<P>
   ``The man has a presence,'' said Smith, obviously a couch potato
on Sunday afternoon, when Ewing heroically grimaced and gimped his
way past Alonzo Mourning in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like yesterday, not last June, that the entire National
Basketball Association and half the planet was bowing in the
presence of old what's-airs-name. Suddenly Ewing, 0 for 13 in pro
championship attempts, ``has a presence.'' To borrow from the
immortal logic of Micheal Ray Richardson (``ship be sinkin''' ...
how low can it go? ... ``sky's the limit''), the bar has been
lowered and the sky's the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson is certainly a second-round playoff presence, and
people can now clearly see beyond the graffiti on his arms and what
the fuss is about. Tim Duncan, definite presence. Shaquille
O'Neill, Reggie Miller, Karl Malone and a platoon of talented
Portland Trail Blazers are all present and accounted for in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen, not here. But then, neither is Michael Jordan or
the charred remains of his Chicago Bulls. Yet for some reason, they
are insisting on going through with the playoffs this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Remember all the talk of how the NBA would curl up in the fetal
position and cry itself to sleep after Jordan retired? That
speculation seems to have been counterfeit, not counting Pat Riley,
who at the very moment is dreaming that it was Kareem, not
Mourning, posting up against Ewing late in the fourth quarter of
Game 5. Sky hook's the limit. Dream on, Riles.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern, the ever-sanguine commissioner, had a standard
response to questions about the Jordan Apocalypse. ``The sun will
come up and the Celtics will go to training camp,'' Stern liked to
say. Unfortunately, training camp for everyone was delayed by
Stern's lockout, and the resulting 50-game regular season was a
blur of busted bodies and butchered plays. At least now, in the
light of May, the sun has come out, and an entertaining batch of
playoff teams have stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   Any minute now, the television ratings will be released, and we
may learn that at precisely 14 minutes after four Sunday afternoon,
there was a .16 percent decline in viewership from the same time
slot last season. This will indicate that an electrical storm took
out two dozen sets just north of Dubuque, but, quite frankly, who
cares?
</P>
<P>
   If I can watch Xavier play Mississippi State in the college
tournament, I can enjoy the young and hungry Sacramento Kings in
the playoffs. All I know is that every time I turned on an NBA
playoff game during the last week, it was May Madness, right down
to the last seconds of regulation or overtime. In a few of them _
especially those featuring the Kings _ the final score wasn't
47-44, and even the Knicks experienced a couple of games when they
accelerated their dribble and experienced the joy of what was once
known as the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   They probably won't set any scoring records against the Hawks,
starting in Game 1 tonight in Atlanta. Most of the recent games
between these teams have been uglier than Knicks versus Heat, but
just as fierce, without the mutual contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Who could hate the Hawks, who for years have played in a
half-empty building and have a point guard named Mookie? To his
credit, when the owner Ted Turner was pressured to build a new
arena in the Gingrich-ville suburbs, he said nothing doing, we're
staying downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's coach is the all-time game winner, the classy Lenny
Wilkens, out of Boys High in Brooklyn. The Hawks' best player,
Steve Smith, gave $6 million to his alma mater, Michigan State.
Dikembe Mutombo points his finger at lane trespassers like a
nursery school teacher and swings his elbows like he's playing
roller derby, but he's also trying to raise $44 million to
construct a hospital in his native Democratic Republic of Congo.
Mutombo steps up to take his crack at Ewing in the round two of the
Georgetown intramurals. He has a profound shot-blocking presence,
but the Knicks have the better team, especially with two Atlanta
starting forwards injured and maybe out.
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost surreal that these Knicks could be favored to
win any series, being that they've been teetering at the edge of a
cliff for months, with only Ernie Grunfeld being shoved over.
Survival is the game now, for Jeff Van Gundy, the beleaguered
coach, and Ewing, the battered star.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't Jordan, and the ratings may yet sink, but the drama is
building, and the sky's the limit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
