<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DRANSFELDT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE SHORT RUN, DRANSFELDT IS IMPRESSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers like what they've seen from Kelly
Dransfeldt at shortstop. His performance _ while Royce Clayton has
been on the disabled list _ reinforces the possibility he could be
the Rangers' second baseman of the future.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dransfeldt is expected to return to the minor leagues Friday
when Clayton comes off the disabled list. Dransfeldt will continue
to play shortstop at Triple-A Oklahoma in case Clayton gets hurt
again, but the Rangers know that won't be his position next year.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton signed a four-year, $18 million contract in the
off-season, and second baseman Mark McLemore and third baseman Todd
Zeile are free agents. Dransfeldt can play second and third, but
his offense seems to suggest second base is the more logical spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure for a third baseman to hit,''
general manager Doug Melvin said. ``A lot of guys fail at third
base because they couldn't hit enough; they're expected to hit 20
home runs and drive in a lot of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt hit 27 home runs and drove in 112 runs in 471 at-bats
in the minor leagues last year, splitting time between Class-A Port
Charlotte and Double-A Tulsa. But the Rangers don't see that kind
of power potential yet at the major-league level, even though he
hit his first home run Sunday against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is he doesn't have third-base power potential,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``From what I've seen of Kelly
Dransfeldt, he's a major-league shortstop. That's his natural
position. There's no doubt in my mind he can play second base in
the major leagues. But you'd have to have a special offensive team
for him to play third base.''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore can't be discarded lightly, now that he's healthy
again. He's a team leader, steady defensively and was batting .328
going into last night's game. The Rangers would also be without a
leadoff hitter if Dransfeldt replaces McLemore and Ruben Mateo
takes over for Tom Goodwin in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said Dransfeldt's future will be decided at the end of
the year. But the decision might have to come sooner if the Rangers
still need pitching this season. Dransfeldt's play has not gone
unnoticed by major-league scouts at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to play shortstop in the major leagues,'' Dransfeldt
said. ``I've been there my whole life, and I feel most comfortable
there. But you definitely have to be adaptable, especially if
you're a young player coming up, just to get a chance to play.''
 &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
