<SLUG> BC-USWEST-GLOBAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: SOUND OF FCC SILENCE IN A BIG MERGER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(dal) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In all of the analysis of Monday's $37 billion merger of U S
West Inc., the smallest of the regional Bell phone giants, and
Global Crossing Ltd., the international communications upstart, the
most telling commentary may have been the sound of silence coming
from the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Telecommunications Act of 1996, none of the Bells are
currently allowed to sell long-distance voice or data
communications in their traditional service areas. Through its
pending acquisition of the Frontier Corp., Global Crossing is set
to become the nation's No. 5 long-distance carrier with about 10
percent of its domestic long-distance revenue generated in U S
West's 14-state region.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a Bell company tried to merge with a long-distance
carrier _ when SBC Communications discussed such a deal with the
AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1997 _ Reed E. Hundt, then the commission's chairman,
called such a combination ``unthinkable.'' And that was before AT&AMP;T
and SBC had even announced anything.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as U S West and Global Crossing announced their deal
as expected, William E. Kennard, Hundt's successor, told a meeting
of the National Consumers League in Washington: ``We have to be
careful in trying to be too categorical about this _ in saying that
all mergers are bad, that we've reached a point where we can't have
any more mergers. They all have different competitive dynamics.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on the U S West-Global Crossing deal in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Global Crossing is no AT&AMP;T and U S West is no SBC. Perhaps
Monday's deal makers simply lacked the star power, or the market
power, to elicit an immediate response from the commission.
</P>
<P>
   But in his diplomacy, Kennard seemed to feed a growing hunch
among the Bells that their time may have come _ that they can
expect to win broad entry into the long-distance market over the
next 18 months, that the FCC will not try to slow the wave of
telecommunications takeovers, and that they ought to move quickly
to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   While the ultimate timetable for the Bells' getting
long-distance approval remains unclear, it became fairly clear on
Monday that the regulatory hurdles standing before U S West and
Global Crossing, while significant, are not monumental.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that in the big scheme of things, Frontier's
long-distance business is relatively small, and the portion of it
that comes from U S West's territory is tiny _ about $110 million
last year, according to Robert Annunziata, Global Crossing's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Frontier's No. 5 standing in the long-distance
business, Hundt, the regulator the Bells loved to hate when he was
in office, said Monday: ``No. 5 is just too small. I think that
being No. 5 in long distance is not a material objection to the
merger.''
</P>
<P>
   John T. Nakahata, who resigned as Kennard's chief of staff late
last year, said, ``If there's not a lot of long-distance traffic
from the U S West region, it's not clear there should be
significant regulatory issues.''
</P>
<P>
   James D. Ellis, SBC's general counsel, said, ``I don't mean to
minimize it or say it will not take a lot of effort,'' but added,
referring to U S West and Global Crossing, ``If I were in their
position and the deal otherwise makes sense, I would not see this
as a barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they offer long-distance service within their regions,
the Bells must convince the FCC that they have opened their
networks to potential competitors. No Bell company has yet passed
that test, and there does not appear to be a provision for a waiver
from it. U S West appears to be further away from winning
long-distance approval than the other Bells.
</P>
<P>
   But a combined U S West-Global Crossing could remove the
conflict as simply as selling Frontier's customers within U S
West's region to another company. Given the relatively small
importance of that particular slice of the combined companies'
business, selling it could be a small price to pay.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to imply that the FCC will simply roll over. People
close to the commission said Monday that such a sale could pose
problems of its own, in that telling people they can no longer use
the long-distance provider of their choice may not serve the public
interest. And it is also not a great way to build customer
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The GTE Corp., which is slogging through regulatory reviews as
it tries to merge with Bell Atlantic, has about 100,000
long-distance customers in states included in Bell Atlantic's
region, and they can be expected to generate about $50 million in
annual long-distance revenue.
</P>
<P>
   That is less than half the size of Frontier's long-distance
business in U S West's region, and still GTE has resisted selling
those customers.
</P>
<P>
   For U S West and Global Crossing, the bigger problem stemming
from U S West's regulatory situation might not be in winning
approval of their deal but in fully exploiting it afterward. U S
West's region includes Seattle, Portland, Ore., Phoenix and Denver,
and the combined company will be prohibited from selling
long-distance voice or data communications to users in any of those
places.
</P>
<P>
   Many communications analysts are expecting Bell Atlantic to get
into the long-distance market in New York and SBC to win approval
for Texas perhaps this fall. Some of the Bells appear to be
expecting those events to open the floodgates for them to win
long-distance approval in broad stretches of the country.
</P>
<P>
   They may be mistaken, but if they are right, their best ally may
turn out to be AT&AMP;T. As AT&AMP;T prepares to invade the Bells' core
local communications markets by way of cable television systems,
some of the regional Bells are expecting to win compensatory breaks
from the FCC, some Bell executives said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
