<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE LISTS LEGAL DEBTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's financial holdings have
remained steady throughout the last year, but because of his
impeachment, his legal bills soared, according to financial
disclosure forms released Monday by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual financial statement, which requires only a range
of figures rather than precise numbers, the president and his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, reported assets of $1.2 million to $5.57
million for 1998. The biggest chunk _ worth more than $1 million
but less than $5 million _ came from a blind trust in Mrs.
Clinton's name.
</P>
<P>
   The assets fall within the same range as they did in 1997. A
year earlier, the assets ranged from $760,000 to $1.7 million and
were raised substantially by the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear from this year's report how much the Clintons have
benefited from the stock market's continued rise, but a White House
official said their assets were at the lower end of the range.
</P>
<P>
   The president owed an estimated $10 million in legal bills
stemming from his defense in the Monica Lewinsky affair and in the
Paula Jones suit. His legal defense fund, which has collected about
$4.5 million since it was set up in January 1998, paid $2.6 million
of Clinton's legal fees. This was reported as a gift on the
disclosure statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reported owing the Washington law firms of Williams &AMP;
Connolly more than $1 million and Skadden, Arps, Slater, Meagher &AMP;
Flom more than $1 million. The president also reported owing
$100,000 to $250,000 to the Little Rock, Ark., firm of Wright,
Lindsey &AMP; Jennings and $250,000 to $500,000 to Mayer, Brown &AMP;
Platt.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons reported keeping more than $18,000 in gifts from
various individuals. These included a film frame of ``Animaniacs''
from Steven Spielberg, the director, valued at $400, and a
collection of videos of the top 100 movies, as rated by the
American Film Institute, worth $1,750, from Sumner M. Redstone, the
chairman of Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive gift the Clintons kept was a saxophone and
two books, worth a total of $3,000, from an individual in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Simon, the singer, gave Clinton a framed oil painting
worth $300, and Sammy Sosa gave him a bat and Cubs jersey with his
signature, worth $350. Robert Squier, the political consultant,
gave him a ``Doonesbury'' cartoon, inscribed by the cartoonist,
Garry Trudeau, worth $1,500. The Clintons also kept a cashmere
sweater coat from Mongolia valued at $395.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, reported assets of
$1.4 million to $1.7 million, including properties in Arlington,
Va., and Carthage, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
