<HEADLINE>
MILSTEIN SUES REDSKIN OFFICIALS, ALLEGING SABOTAGE OF BID
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howard Milstein charged Monday in a federal lawsuit that his
group's $800 million bid to acquire the Washington Redskins was
sabotaged by John Kent Cooke, the team's president, and Charley
Casserly, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit against Cooke and Casserly, Milstein and his
brother, Edward, contended that the two Redskins officials
orchestrated a clandestine plan to keep the team in their hands.
The Milsteins also accused certain National Football League
officials of complicity in the failure of their Washington Sports
Ventures firm to buy the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by the team, Cooke said, ``If I must, I
will gladly defend myself against these petulant charges, which
have no merit whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   A league spokesman declined to comment on the lawsuit, which was
filed in Federal District Court in Washington. The Milsteins have
extensive real estate holdings in the New York area, and a group
they headed bought the Islanders professional hockey team last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees of the estate of Jack Kent Cooke, John's father,
approved the sale to the Milsteins in January, but the offer was
withdrawn last month when it lacked the support of enough team
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke also made an offer, of $680 million, which he withdrew
after the Milsteins backed out. Daniel Snyder, a partner in
Washington Sports Ventures with the Milsteins, then organized an
$800 million offer, which is expected to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges that Cooke and Casserly lobbied NFL owners
against the Milsteins, leaked false information to the news media
and worked with league officials to frustrate the bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after the trustees entered into the sales contract,'' the
Milsteins charged, ``Cooke continued his secret campaign to
frustrate the outcome of the public auction and block the sale of
the Redskins to anyone other than himself.'' Cooke's actions, it
was alleged, violated his responsibility as an executor of his
father's estate to secure the highest price.
</P>
<P>
   Other executors directed Cooke not to attend the NFL owners'
meetings in March. Still, the suit alleged, Cooke boasted that he
had lined up enough votes to block the sale ``and that he would
ultimately take control of the Redskins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milsteins' lawsuit charged that various league officials
offered Cooke waivers of financial rules that where not available
to Milstein or other bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The Milsteins and the league wrangled repeatedly over the amount
of debt included in their bid and how the financing was to be
structured. But such concerns, they charged, ``were plainly a sham
because of the blatant double standards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
