<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      05-17 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDTORIAL: IS THIS FIGHT NECESSARY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 18: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has the raw political strength to
run Schools Chancellor Dr. Rudy Crew out of town. He clearly
believes that as an ``agent of change,'' he has the right to rout
anyone he thinks moves too slowly. But this would be a good time
for the mayor to show that strength can be used for conciliation as
well as raw conquest. Keeping Crew in place would be good for the
stability of New York City's school system. It would allow time for
analyzing the managerial and educational progress the chancellor
says he has made. It would also serve Giuliani's political interest
by showing that he can curb the authoritarian streak that troubles
many of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Giuliani is entirely to blame for the
sudden freeze in relations between two guys who used to loaf around
the Gracie Mansion fireplace, drinking Scotch and smoking cigars.
But for mayoral aides to say that Giuliani's patience with Crew has
evaporated along with their friendship misses the point that
professionalism on both sides, not friendship, must be the enduring
basis for educational reform.
</P>
<P>
   The war of words that began two months ago has a Rashomon
quality. Each participant has his own version of the mixture of
machismo, ideology and hurt feelings that brought the two to
swords' point. Giuliani felt betrayed when the chancellor said he
would resign over the mayor's voucher plan. Crew felt demeaned by
the mayor's comment that the school system should be ``blown up.''
Each man has grievances that roll on for miles. But as the prison
guard said in ``Cool Hand Luke,'' what we really have here is ``a
failure to communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   What we also have here is a school system with more than a
million students who will be hurt if there is a traumatic,
politically riven change at the top. Up to two years will be lost
in searching for a new chancellor and allowing him or her to settle
in. From the standpoint of continuity and protecting gains that
have been made, it makes far more sense for Giuliani to finish his
term with the chancellor he praised until recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city cannot afford revolving-door chancellors,'' Bronx
Borough President Fernando Ferrer said at a gathering of black and
Hispanic officials supporting Crew. The event made another
important point. Given the mayor's reputation for a tin ear on race
relations, the removal of a black Chancellor widely regarded as
effective would further alienate New York's minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani insists that he cannot deliver the improved schools he
promised without a chancellor committed to fundamental change. That
formulation slights the chancellor's gains in imposing tougher
standards, reforming corrupt school boards, monitoring local
superintendents and pushing to end principals' tenure. Crew, for
his part, has let it be known that he is tired of being bullied,
and he is lobbying the state legislature and the city council to
strengthen his hand. Both men, it seems to us, are being needlessly
apocalyptic.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is right on some issues, such as the need to replace
the Board of Education with a body answering to the mayor. Crew is
right on the deleterious effect Giuliani's voucher program would
have. The two men appear to be resolving differences over social
promotion and can surely settle other issues using that
old-fashioned technique _ negotiation between grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Provided Crew does not become mindlessly provocative, the
greater responsibility to restore dialogue rests with Giuliani. In
governing, the person who has the power ought to make the peace, if
it is in the public interest. Right now the public interest lies in
stable leadership and orderly moves toward reform, rather than the
precipitate, litmus-test approach to reform adopted by Giuliani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
