<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0852 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-FOUNDATION-TEX     05-17 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-FOUNDATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ'S FOUNDATION TO AID BOY WITH LEUKEMIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez has had
a grip on major-league base runners for several years. His hold on
the base paths is so tight that runners don't often stray too far
from first base.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the seven-time All-Star catcher is taking his hands-on
approach in another direction _ his foundation and Britton Chism of
Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Britton, 3, suffers from a rare form of leukemia called Acute
Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL), of which there are two types _ Type B
and Type T. Britton has the more rare Type T, and the revamped Ivan
``Pudge'' Rodriguez Foundation has chosen Britton as the first area
child it will aid with a grant. Britton's medical bills already
have reached $53,000, and his insurance policy covers only 80
percent of the costs, according to his mother, Mary Meenen.
</P>
<P>
   Although openly seeking corporate sponsorship, it's exactly what
Rodriguez and his foundation have wanted all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund was set up to support families in the Metroplex and
Puerto Rico, but Pudge wanted to get more of a hands-on approach,''
said Jamie Adams, executive director of the Ivan ``Pudge''
Rodriguez Foundation. ``Now we are trying to concentrate on
individuals, where in the past we were aimed at charities and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge wants a one-on-one basis relationship with the people he
helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1993, in conjunction with The Dallas Foundation, the
Ivan ``Pudge'' Rodriguez Foundation has raised nearly $200,000 in
six years, with most money coming from Rodriguez himself. Adams
said the foundation expects to grant $35,000-$40,000 in aid to
families in Puerto Rico and the Fort Worth-Dallas area in 1999 with
an increased amount of money granted in each of the following
years. Through the Dallas Foundation, the Ivan ``Pudge'' Rodriguez
Foundation has donated money to the Texas Neurofibromatosis
Foundation Fund, the Ronald McDonald Houses of Fort Worth and
Dallas, Children's Medical Center of Dallas, and American Cancer
Society of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez built a youth baseball field in Fort Worth and said he
aspires to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love kids,'' Rodriguez said. ``I do what I can to help them
because they are all special and they mean a lot to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I turned pro I wanted to help kids, all kids. I
wish I could do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first choice of the new ``hands-on'' foundation, recently
relocated to a suite at The Ballpark in Arlington, is
coincidentally a Texas Rangers fanatic. Britton always dons his No.
7 jersey, knows most of the starting lineup, and hits baseballs
until dark. He has all the catching gear of a major-league player,
and is in the process of ``negotiating'' a red mask to replace his
black one.
</P>
<P>
   Already in his young life, baseball is playing an important
role. In fact, Britton's father, Randy Chism, discovered the
cancerous lumps on his son's neck two months ago, while the two
were playing their daily game of catch in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Chism initially thought his son had mononucleosis or
strep throat, but a few visits to the doctor proved otherwise.
Britton was diagnosed with leukemia March 11, and the road since
his diagnosis has not been an easy one. It's been a combination of
good days and bad days, but Britton's mother said being chosen by
Ivan Rodriguez has brought unexpected joy to Britton. The family is
very grateful, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the thought of Pudge gets him excited,'' said Meenen, a
teacher at Austin Elementary in Grand Prairie. ``To have this
happen is just a dream for Britton. We are very thankful for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Chism, 29, said he has accepted his son's illness,
appreciates the opportunities provided by the foundation, but is
anxiously awaiting the return of their normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love what they are doing for Britton and for us ... if he
knew what a dream come true was, this would be it,'' Chism said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would trade it all back if I could have him healthy. We
are just trying to keep a normal life, but it's weird because this
is not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two months, life has been anything but normal for
Britton's family.
</P>
<P>
   Three days a week, twice a day, Britton takes his antibiotic
drugs. He takes an oral dosage of chemotherapy and receives
``normal'' chemotherapy treatment every Friday in sessions ranging
from 21/2 to seven hours. The routine will continue for the next
21/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he will get better and there is an end to this,'' Chism
said. ``We'll just ride it out to the end, and he'll be back to
normal in no time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiding Britton's family and families like his is the goal of the
Ivan ``Pudge'' Rodriguez Foundation, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a ways to go, but this is what it's all about,''
said Adams as he watched Britton run around the foundation's suite
at The Ballpark. ``The family is great and he is full of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' assistant, Jennifer Garza, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look how happy he is just to take a picture with a Pudge
poster,'' Garza said. ``That's the best the part of all this,
seeing how happy he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's so neat.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
