5-17 -- Mexican farm workers cut and package spinach at the Philip
A. Schmitt &AMP; Son Farm. Behind split-level shutters, vinyl siding
and drawn curtains in nearly every town and village on Long Island,
tens of thousands of legal and illegal immigrants from Central
America and Mexico are jammed into subdivided houses and
partitioned apartments, working in local fields and restaurants
while biding their time in invisible suburban slums. (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) FARMINGVILLE, N.Y. -- May 17, 1999 -- IMMIG-SUBURBS-2,
5-17 -- Guadeloupe Crespo Alvarez's foot was crushed by a truck a
few weeks ago while he was hauling bricks on a day job. The boss
sent him home with a pill, but no pay, he says, and the hospital
refuses to operate because he has no medical insurance. Now he
cannot make the $200 rent that he pays for his bunk in a ranch
house crammed with 16 strangers. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- May 17, 1999 --IMMIG-SUBURBS-2, 5-17
-- Three girls who share their small room with their mother. Behind
split-level shutters, vinyl siding and drawn curtains in nearly
every town and village on Long Island, tens of thousands of legal
and illegal immigrants from Central America and Mexico are jammed
into subdivided houses and partitioned apartments, biding their
time in invisible suburban slums. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) FARMINGVILLE, N.Y. -- May 17, 1999 -- IMMIG-SUBURBS-1,
5-17 -- A group of men, mostly immigrants from Mexico and Central
America, gather around a truck asking for work. With unemployment
under four percent in many counties on New York's Long Island,
experts and local officials say many jobs filled by immigrant labor
would not get done. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WEINING, China -- May 17, 1999 -- CHINA-LAKE, 5-17 --
Cao Hai means sea of grass, and its marshy waters show why. The
poor families on the lake want it drained for cropland. But the
Chinese government, which tried draining it in the 1970's, now
guards the area as a nature reserve. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 17, 1999 -- USWEST-GLOBAL, 5-17 --
Robert Annunziata, head of Global Crossing Ltd., with Solomon
Trujillo, right, chairman of US West, after formally announcing
their merger deal. In all of the analysis of Monday's $37 billion
merger of U S West Inc., the smallest of the Bell local phone
giants, and Global Crossing Ltd., the international communications
upstart, the most telling commentary may have been the sound of
silence coming from the Federal Communications Commission.(Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 17, 1999 -- SOCIAL-PHOBIA-DRUGS-2, 5-17
-- Students in a course on dealing with extreme shyness, known
clinically as social phobia, conducted by Charles di Cagno
background, second from right. Formally identified in 1980, social
phobia today ranks as the third most prevalent psychiatric disorder
in the United States after substance abuse and depression,
affecting an estimated 19 million Americans according to the
Anxiety Disorders Association of American. (Linda Rosier/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 17 -- BETSEY-JOHNSON-FASHION-3, 05-17 --
The interior of Betsey Johnson's store in Soho. Ms. Johnson has 26
boutiques, including four in New York and one in London, and sell
to major stores like Neiman Marcus, Nordstrom and Saks Fifth Avenue
as well as to 700 specialty stores. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 17 -- BETSEY-JOHNSON-FASHION-2, 05-17 --
Clothing designer Betsey Johnson, right, helps her daughter, Lulu,
24, with one of her dresses. Lulu, who has worked with her mother
virtually all her life, has decided to leave the business. ``She is
so cut out for this business, a real natural,'' Betsey says,
obviously regretting the loss of her daughter's everyday presence.
``I always talk over my ideas with her.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 17 -- BETSEY-JOHNSON-FASHION-1, 05-17 --
Clothing designer Betsey Johnson poses in front of one of the many
murals in her Seventh Avenue showroom. On June 2, Ms. Johnson will
be receiving an award from the Council of Fashion Designers of
America for ``timeless talent.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 17, 1999 -- SOCIAL-PHOBIA-DRUGS, 5-17 --
Barry Greenblatt, a participant in a support group that helps him
deal with his extreme shyness, after a recent session. Greenblat
suffers from an extreme form of shyness called social phobia.
Formally identified in 1980, social phobia today ranks as the third
most prevalent psychiatric disorder in the United States after
substance abuse and depression, affecting an estimated 19 million
Americans according to the Anxiety Disorders Association of
American. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEWTON, Mass. -- May 17, 1999 -- BRUSH-MAN-BOS, 05-17 --
Al Cohen with some sample of his wares. At age 47, Cohen is a
six-day-a-week door-to-door Fuller Brush salesman. ``I'm the last
of a dying breed,'' admits the 30-year sales veteran. ``But I have
a customer base of about 1,000 that I've built up over the years
and I enjoy serving them.'' (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 17, 1999 -- SCI-BALLET-PREGNANCY, 5-17 --
Stacey Calvert, a ballerina with the New York City ballet, with her
six month-old daughter Ayla during an exercise session. Looking on
is Calvert's colleague Margaret Tracy with her six month-old son
Avery. This month, both ballerinas had their post-baby debuts, and
the experience made it clear that it is far easier to get in great
shape soon after pregnancy or other disruptive events if one has
been in great shape to begin with. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 17, 1999 -- SCI-OFFICE-SURGERY-2, 5-17 --
Dr. Marc Koch, an anesthesiologist who travels to doctor's offices,
setting up his equipment for a client. As more surgical proceedures
are taking place in the less expensive settings of doctors' private
offices, this has set off an escalating nationwide debate on how to
insure patients' safety as the complicated modern technology of
anesthesia and surgery floats free of hospital regulations and into
less-restricted settings. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 17, 1999 -- SCI-OFFICE-SURGERY-1, 5-17 --
Dr. Marc Koch, an anesthesiologist who travels to doctor's offices,
on a bus to his next appointment. As more surgical proceedures are
taking place in the less expensive settings of doctors' private
offices, this has set off an escalating nationwide debate on how to
insure patients' safety as the complicated modern technology of
anesthesia and surgery floats free of hospital regulations and into
less-restricted settings. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- May 17, 1999 -- SCI-VENTER-GENOME-2,
5-17 -- Dr. J. Craig Venter, foreground, and Dr. Hamilton Smith
once decoded the genes of a bacterium. Now they have larger
targets. A private venture headed Venter is racing the Human Genome
Project for the greatest prize of biology: the key to human genetic
inheritance. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- May 17, 1999 -- SCI-VENTER-GENOME, 5-17
-- Dr. J. Craig Venter with the computers that will be used in a
project to sequence the entire three billion letters of human DNA.
A private venture headed Venter is racing the Human Genome Project
for the greatest prize of biology: the key to human genetic
inheritance. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) JERUSALEM -- May 17, 1999 -- ISRAEL-VOTE-2, 05-17 --
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu casts his vote Monday morning
during Israel's general election. Voting at a school in his
Jerusalem neighborhood, Netanyahu called for ``national unity''
after a fiery campaign. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERUSALEM -- May 17, 1999 -- ISRAEL-VOTE-1, 05-17 -- A
smiling Ehud Barak greets cheering supporters outside a voting
station on Monday. After three minor candidates dropped out of the
race for prime minister over the weekend, Israel's most decorated
soldier is heavily favored to unseat Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in Monday's general election. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
