<SLUG> BC-BERGER-AWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIA GIVING AWARDS TO REPORTER AND NOVELIST
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Alaska, Calif., Mich.)  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie LeDuff, a reporter for The New York Times, and Joan
Didion, a novelist and contributor to The New Yorker magazine and
The New York Review of Books, are scheduled to receive awards from
Columbia University's Graduate School of Journalism on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   LeDuff is the recipient of the 1999 Meyer Berger Award, which is
given for distinguished reporting about New York City in the
tradition of Meyer Berger, who originated the About New York column
in The New York Times in 1939. The award has been presented since
1960, the year after Berger's death.
</P>
<P>
   LeDuff was cited for profiles of Mike Sheehan, who spent 25
years as a police officer and detective before becoming a reporter
for WNYW-TV, and of 81-year-old Ruby Jean Johnson, a prominent
personality during the Harlem Renaissance who was found strangled
last year in her Harlem apartment.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the University of Michigan, LeDuff received a
master's degree in journalism from the University of California at
Berkeley. He is a former reporter for The Alaska Fisherman's
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Didion, the recipient of the 1999 Columbia Journalism Award,
is the author of several novels and works of nonfiction, from
``Slouching Towards Bethlehem'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 1968) to
``The Last Thing He Wanted'' (Knopf, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   With her husband, John Gregory Dunne, she has also written
several screenplays, including ``Up Close and Personal'' (1996).
She is a graduate of the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
