<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: COX EDITORS.
 &HT;    Cox Newspapers Washington Bureau budget advisory for Tues., May
18, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is an update on the status of Cox Washington
Bureau FOREIGN daily stories:
</P>
<P>
   budget ADD, has MOVED:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PRI-0518 _ MEXICO CITY _ After more than 70 years in
power, Mexico's ruling party announced Monday it has voted to hold
the first-ever primary election to allow followers to select their
candidate for Mexico's 2000 presidential election. For decades, the
ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI, has won Mexico's
presidency, sometimes under a cloud of suspicion of fraud. The
party's candidate has always been hand-picked by the man who won
Mexico's presidency before him. That secret selection process,
dubbed the ``dedazo,'' or ``big finger,'' will be replaced later
this year by a national vote conducted in 300 electoral districts
nationwide. (Ferriss).
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call:
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 301-809-3419; 301-910-6248
(cellular).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
