<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORIST-SUSPECT-NYT     05-17 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERROR SUSPECT'S INDICTMENT TO BE SOUGHT AFTER TALKS FAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After eight months of secret negotiations in which
the government sought to win the cooperation of a suspected chief
lieutenant to Osama bin Laden, talks have broken down between the
parties, and federal officials have decided to seek his indictment,
lawyers said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Ali A. Mohamed, 46, is a former sergeant in the
U.S. Army who is suspected of switching sides and joining what
federal prosecutors have described as a worldwide terrorist
conspiracy led by bin Laden against Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, which could be returned as early as this week,
is expected to include a charge of conspiring to kill American
citizens abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers suggest that the government became involved in a
worldwide effort beginning in the early 1990s to find people in the
bin Laden organization who could describe its inner workings. The
government's major known success so far has been a shadowy figure
referred to only as ``CS-1,'' who appears to have left the group
and begun to cooperate with investigators around 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrest of Mohamed in September, which has officially
been kept secret by the government, raised hopes that the
authorities might be able to press him into providing a more
contemporary look at the group and its reputed leader.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed, a former major in the Egyptian army, was granted a visa
to enter the United States in 1985 and eventually became an
American citizen. In 1986, he enlisted in one of the American
Army's elite units, at Fort Bragg, N.C., and while there began
traveling to the New York City area, where he trained a group of
Islamic militants in basic military techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the group, which was based in Brooklyn, were
later convicted of plotting a series of terrorist attacks in New
York, including the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed also made at least two trips to Afghanistan to train
rebel commanders in military tactics, officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has been indicted in the bombings of the two American
embassy buildings in Africa in August and in other acts of
terrorism abroad. He remains a fugitive, as do other members of his
group named in the public indictments.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the government's effort to win cooperation from
Mohamed, the authorities have kept him under a cloak of secrecy
rarely seen in the public courts, closing the courtroom when he
first appeared before a judge, listing him in the dockets as ``John
Doe,'' and holding him in a high security cell in the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe that Mohamed established ties with bin
Laden as early as 1991. He became adept at obtaining false
documents for bin Laden's organization, officials have said, and
assisted with logistical tasks for bin Laden, such as his move in
1991 from Afghanistan to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   While at Fort Bragg, where he spent three years as a supply
sergeant assigned to Special Forces, Mohamed was befriended by
other Army officers who said they found him to be engaging and
intelligent, although his support for Islamic causes and curiosity
about intelligence matters raised some questions. He was honorably
discharged in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He had lived much of the last decade in California, and was
charged last Sept. 11 after testifying before a federal grand jury
in Manhattan that was investigating bin Laden's activities.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the federal investigation refused comment on
Monday night, as did a defense lawyer, James Roth, who represents
Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the government's long and delicate negotiation
with Mohamed had ultimately failed to persuade him, in effect, to
switch sides again, and become an informant against bin Laden and
his group.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, in cases where the government seeks to win a
suspect's cooperation, investigators will entertain a proffer, or
offer of information, from the suspect about the evidence or leads
he may be able to provide. The suspect will often then seek, in
return, leniency in sentencing, or perhaps seek to avoid prison
altogether and to be placed in the witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan, which is leading
the bombing investigation, is known to have a strict policy of
requiring that potential cooperating witnesses disclose all that
they know, even topics of which the government may not yet be
aware.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the talks with Mohamed suggests that he may not
have been as forthcoming as the government believed he could be, or
that he offered what prosecutors saw as a mixture of truths and
lies, which would have disqualified him under the rules from
obtaining a traditional cooperation agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
