<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES END MIXED, WITH THE DOW DROPPING 59.85 POINTS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed Monday, in large part because of an
afternoon rally in technology shares. But with Federal Reserve
policy makers scheduled to meet Tuesday to discuss a possible
increase in interest rates, investors were reluctant to make new
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volume was low, as it should be when you don't know what you
are looking at,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about interest rates rose significantly on Friday after
the government reported that consumer prices rose at their fastest
clip in nine years during April.
</P>
<P>
   The report sent stocks sharply lower on Friday, and broad-based
selling continued when markets opened on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While stocks sensitive to the interest rate, like banks and
financial service companies, suffered throughout the session,
reports that Hewlett-Packard and Dell Computer were set to post
better-than-expected quarterly earnings helped to stem the decline
during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At the closing bell, the Dow Jones industrial average, down by
167 points at one point, stood at 10,853.47, a loss of 59.85
points, or six-tenths of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indexes did better.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by strong gains in Microsoft, America Online and Dell,
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which had also been lower
for much of the session, reversed course and closed up 1.69 points,
or one-tenth of a percent, at 1,339.49. And the Nasdaq composite
index gained 33.98 points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,561.84.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology stocks really turned things around,'' said
Michael Molnar, a managing director in retail sales and trading at
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rally, most stocks had a tough day. Almost two
stocks fell for every one that rose on the New York Stock Exchange,
and 61 of the S.&AMP; P. 500's 89 industry groups declined.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, volume was light, at 679.7 million shares. On
the Nasdaq market, 788 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Few analysts expect the Fed to raise interest rates on Tuesday,
but many think the central bank will signal that it is leaning
toward a rate increase in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Most traders and analysts see a rate increase as an unqualified
negative for the stock market. But Molnar said it could be
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the market would necessarily view it as a
negative,'' he said. ``The selloff in the bond market has been so
substantial that a surprise move by the Fed now might be seen as
being pre-emptive. If anything, a pre-emptive move has more appeal
than more waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial services stocks, which are most sensitive to changes
in interest rates, were losers Monday. And auto stocks slumped
after a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst said sales might have
peaked.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup fell 1, to 70. J.P. Morgan &UR;  &LR; slumped 4, to 135 15/16.
Bank One declined 1}, to 60 5/16. And Merrill Lynch lost 1 11/16,
to 79 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor was the biggest loser in the S.&AMP; P. 500, dropping 3
1/16, to 57 11/16. And General Motors, a Dow component, declined 2
13/16, to 80 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of a strong earnings report helped to send
Hewlett-Packard's stock higher. The stock rose 4 9/16, to 88}.
After the close, the world's second-biggest computer maker reported
quarterly earnings that beat Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which is expected to report its results Tuesday, was
another good performer. It rose 2 1/16, to 43\.
</P>
<P>
   America Online was the most actively traded issue on the New
York Stock Exchange, jumping 10 1/16, to 136.
</P>
<P>
   Concern that the combination of U S West and Global Crossing
will be closely scrutinized by regulators caused prices of both
companies to fall Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U S West fell 4[, to 58[. Meanwhile, Global Crossing slipped 1[,
to 60\.
</P>
<P>
   Other long-distance companies gained. Qwest rose 6[, to 90~ and
Level 3 Communications gained 3 15/16, to 88{.
</P>
</TEXT>
