<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S COYNESS FEEDS SPECULATION OF A SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ He didn't really say anything. He hedged, hinted
and dodged, but in the end, New York Gov. George Pataki said
absolutely nothing Monday about either his political plans or a
gathering shrouded in secrecy that he has called for next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that did not stop this state capital _ and, to a
lesser degree, Washington, D.C. _ from buzzing with speculation
about what the governor intends, and precisely what he meant by his
oblique comments Monday morning at an Albany supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Most intriguingly, with the governor's testing of the
presidential waters failing to gather any momentum, he repeatedly
refused Monday to rule out a campaign, instead, for the U.S. Senate
next year. Such a campaign would put him in a primary battle
against New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ with whom Pataki has had
a long, bitter feud _ and perhaps a November showdown with Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, one of the governor's closest aides, Zenia
Mucha, tried to dispel the rumor of a Senate candidacy, leaving
unanswered the question of why the governor would be so coy about a
prospect that he had rejected in the past, and that a top adviser
says he still rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki acknowledged that he had called a meeting of prominent
Republicans from around the state, including state legislators and
members of Congress, in Manhattan next Monday, and that the
gathering will include some kind of announcement from him. The
people invited say they have no inkling what the topic will be,
adding to the cloak-and-dagger air. The few Pataki confidants who
claim to know the agenda for the event are not saying.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday at a Price Chopper supermarket,
Pataki steadfastly refused to answer questions about a possible
Senate campaign, put to him by reporters no fewer than eight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens next Monday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that he had ruled out a Senate race in the past, he
said, ``Then I've said it in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marc Humbert of The Associated Press asked why the governor
could not simply give a clear answer, Pataki said: ``I like
aggravating you, Marc. It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a striking turnabout for a governor who said in
December, ``I would think it's more likely that the Hindenburg
would come back together than I would step down as governor and
become senator.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, a Senate Republican, Thomas Libous of Binghamton,
said: ``Anything is possible. If he were to announce for the U.S.
Senate, it would not surprise me a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, director of the mayor's political exploratory
committee, told a reporter, ``We know about as much as you do
regarding the governor's plans.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, Ms. Mucha, Pataki's communications
director, said of the Hindenburg analogy: ``The governor stands by
that statement. The governor has not changed his position on that
matter. His position remains unchanged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
