<HEADLINE>
NHL IS MONITORING INTIMIDATION FACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After Game 5 of this Eastern Conference semifinal,
Bruins coach Pat Burns and Sabres coach Lindy Ruff engaged in a
sort of off-ice trench warfare designed to help their respective
clubs curry some favor with the officials.
</P>
<P>
   The skippers took their cases to the public, saying their
players were being targeted, their players were being cheap-shotted
behind the play, their players should have drawn more penalties.
</P>
<P>
   An old trick, really. Sure, the series has been hard-hitting,
quite a bit nasty and desperate as the teams head into Game 6 in
Buffalo Tuesday. But NHL director of officiating Bryan Lewis said
the league is monitoring all the matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be the time of year when it becomes, I don't
want to say a secondary story, we don't want to be a secondary
story, but we had a preplayoff meeting and one of the subjects was
intimidation,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The intimidation to which Lewis refers is the type demonstrated
by Burns and Ruff Sunday, trying to gain an edge, however small.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Burns reiterated his position, saying the officials
hadn't made it easy for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given it to us early,'' said Burns. ``How many times
have we been put five-on-three all year, maybe once or twice? In
this series, it seems to be every game. I don't want to get into
that situation but they've certainly used it a lot, about how we
were playing and how Ray Bourque was getting away with things. I've
watched the last couple of games and Mike Peca has been getting
away with murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns acknowledged, ``You have to get people's attention
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Burns said, enforcer Ken Belanger couldn't even
step on the ice without being targeted as a penalty waiting to
happen. Lewis said that was patently false.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this what this is, intimidation?'' said Lewis. ``Belanger
is entitled to go out on the ice and play, don't slash, don't hack,
don't elbow or do whatever. It's his game to play the same as it is
for everyone else. We don't hit the ice with the idea that someone
is being targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of aggressive players who play at playoff time
and you can see they don't break the rules. It's not pick on
Belanger or Smith or Jones or whomever. Is this part of the
intimidation language? I don't know if it is or isn't. You'd have
to ask Pat Burns that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just try to not get drawn into those debates. We know
there's going to be controversy. It's not something we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the issue comes down to subjectivity. One man's
two-minute minor is another man's non-call. Lewis said there's
another category of penalty called the ``one-minute infraction'':
something has been done, but it's not enough to warrant a minor
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I could sit in the press box and you'd say, `I think
that's a penalty' and I'd write down, `Good non-call,' '' he said.
``So that debate goes on. You're dealing with two teams who are
battling for the rights to play on. We try to separate ourselves
from what is a genuine concern and what isn't. It's just a
heightened awareness to our end of the business. We're all talking
now about short series.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said it's expected that coaches, general managers, and
even players will try to sway the officials, whether by yakking at
them during the game, waiting for them after the game _ as Burns
pointed out about Ruff _ or going public at news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this hockey talk? It seems to be,'' said Lewis. ``I have
too much respect for the coaching staffs to say we don't have
concerns or issues. But to do it via (the media), I'm not too sure
if that's the way to get it properly addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we start to factor in what is intimidation or a form of
intimidation in either direction by either club. That becomes the
series supervisor's role, and Denis Morel has raised with me some
legitimate concerns, yes. It's his responsibility to provide
continuity from game to game. His role and his responsibility are
to remove the prejudiced point of view which we know is there,
everyone knows is there, then address what is a legitimate concern
in order to forewarn the officials. From there, he can set aside, I
don't want to say a frivolous claim of foul but those things that
are not the important matters that have to be addressed game to
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
