<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRS SCALES BACK EFFORTS TO COLLECT UNPAID TAXES
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service tax collectors, under intense pressure
from Congress to be nicer to taxpayers, have drastically scaled
back efforts to collect unpaid taxes, newly available statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the drop-off in enforcement is because the IRS has been
shifting some resources to pay for customer service, new computers
and retraining. But IRS officers in six states said the biggest
reason for the retreat was their fear of being dismissed for
running afoul of a new law intended to protect taxpayers from
overzealous collectors.
</P>
<P>
   FORD TO IMPROVE TRUCK EMISSIONS
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor said that starting this autumn, its new pickup
trucks, including the nation's best-selling vehicle, would produce
no more air pollution than do cars.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL DYNAMICS TO BUY JET MAKER
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics announced it would acquire Gulfstream
Aerospace, a maker of corporate jets, in a $5.3 billion stock swap.
The deal elicited mixed reaction on Wall Street, where General
Dynamics stock tumbled nearly 10 percent. It would return General
Dynamics, which specializes in making nuclear submarines, surface
ships and armored tanks, to a business it once exited.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END MIXED AS DOW FALLS
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed as investors waited to see what the
Federal Reserve would decide on Tuesday. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 59.85 points, or six-tenths of a percent, to
10,853.47. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 1.69 points,
to 1,339.49, and the Nasdaq composite index gained 33.98 points, or
1.34 percent, to 2,561.84.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year &UR;  &LR; bond fell to 5.89 percent from 5.92
percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE BOOK SELLERS CUT PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com cut the prices of best-selling books by 50 percent
and was matched within hours by its Internet rivals, Borders.com
and Barnesandnoble.com. All will almost certainly lose money on the
sales.
</P>
<P>
   AN ULTIMATUM FOR PHILIPPINE AIRLINES
</P>
<P>
   The embattled owner of Philippine Airlines, Lucio C. Tan, has
been given a week by Joseph E. Estrada, the president of the
Philippines, to come up with $200 million for the debt-ridden
company, or to relinquish control. If Tan cannot produce the money,
Estrada will auction Philippine Airlines to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT DELAYS NET PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department, a few hours after starting a fee-based
search engine for federal government Internet sites and documents,
delayed the project to review whether it conflicts with the
administration's policy on unrestricted access to government data.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS AT HEWLETT BEAT FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard reported second-quarter earnings that beat Wall
Street estimates for the third consecutive quarter.
</P>
<P>
   CVS BUYS AN ONLINE PHARMACY
</P>
<P>
   CVS bought Soma.com, the first Internet pharmacy, for $30
million in stock, getting a head start over rival drugstore chains
as Walgreen and Rite Aid.
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEES LEAVING AT&AMP;T MUSIC UNIT
</P>
<P>
   More than half the employees of AT&AMP;T's digital music company A2B
are leaving to join Reciprocal, which creates software for managing
rights to digitally distributed material. They will start a music
division.
</P>
</TEXT>
