<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYOFFS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
 
NBA playoffs are wacky, wide open 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Given the dramatic, wacky first round of the
NBA playoffs, perhaps the league should change its slogan to I Love
This Parity!
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's mid-May, and seven teams still have legitimate hopes of
winning the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be more competitive with Michael
\RJordan\S on the sidelines,'' Utah Jazz forward Karl Malone said.
``And, boy, were we right. Surviving is the name of the game, and
it only gets tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight teams battling in conference semifinals the next 10
days, apparently only the Philadelphia 76ers and their one-man
Allen Iverson show would shock the league by winning the title. The
San Antonio Spurs, Portland Trail Blazers, Los Angeles Lakers,
Jazz, Indiana Pacers, Atlanta Hawks and New York Knicks each played
well enough during the regular season and first round to show the
ability to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team that goes into Miami and wins twice in the playoffs
is a contender,'' said Pacers coach Larry Brown, referring to the
Knicks, who became the second No. 8 seed in NBA history to knock
off a No. 1. ``The seedings don't mean a thing anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite advancing, every team except the Blazers and Pacers had
major weaknesses exposed. The Spurs lost at home to the
scoring-impaired Minnesota Timberwolves; the Lakers couldn't guard
6-foot-6 forward Charles Barkley in the post; the Jazz was
uncharacteristically rattled by the Sacramento Kings; the Hawks
were blown out by 16 and 21 in consecutive games; the Knicks
suffered major physical and emotional letdowns after victories
against the Miami Heat; and the 76ers are the ultimate one-man
gang.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastern Conference, the Pacers seem to be the favorites
because the two teams they tied for best record _ Miami and Orlando
_ were upset in the first round. Indiana, which swept Milwaukee,
has won 11 consecutive playoff games at Market Square Arena after
defeating Philadelphia, 94-90, last night, and has the calm,
veteran leadership of coach Larry Bird and guard Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pacers try to contain Iverson and his 30-point
outbursts, the fourth-seeded Hawks and eighth-seeded Knicks each
have game-dominating defenses anchored by former Georgetown centers
(Patrick Ewing and Dikembe Mutombo) and clutch scorers at shooting
guard (Allan Houston and Steve Smith). Their rugged series should
be close and low-scoring; neither team topped 86 points in three
regular-season meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As close as I think the teams are matched now, I think our
defense could be a decisive factor,'' Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens
said. ``From what I've seen, a couple of stops here and there could
take you a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, the Jazz were an 8-foot hook from
Vlade Divac away from a shocking elimination Sunday. They will
either be re-invigorated by their escape or worn out by survival.
The deep Blazers, disappointed at not facing a Kings team they went
4-0 against, enter tonight's Game 1 at Delta Center off their
longest rest of the season after sweeping the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs proved capable of completely shutting down an
opponents' offense with the inside tandem of Tim Duncan and David
Robinson, but got little production off its bench against
Minnesota. The Lakers, meanwhile, are suddenly clicking offensively
despite often falling into the trap of dumping the ball to
Shaquille O'Neal then standing and watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're peaking,'' said O'Neal, who averaged 29.5 points per
game in the four-game dismantling of the Houston Rockets. ``If we
play hard and play together, we can win this whole thing.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
