u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMAN-AD-COLUMN-NYT     05-17 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS TRIES SOMETHING NEW: PROMOTING ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, which went public earlier this month when
it sold shares, plans to go public again, this time with its first
global advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with ads this week in print outlets worldwide, Goldman
intends to define itself as the blue-chip investment bank that
listens _ and never gives the same advice twice to its corporate
clients. All its advertising will carry the same tag line:
``Unrelenting Thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will not catch competitors flat-footed. Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Citigroup, J.P. Morgan
and many others heavily outspend Goldman to market their brands.
Many of these firms have recently introduced new advertising
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, however, has long been a happy enigma, known by its
clients but largely inscrutable to outsiders. Visitors have to look
hard to find the Goldman name on its headquarters at 85 Broad
Street in downtown Manhattan. Like all investment banks, Goldman
promotes deals it is involved in with staid print ads in the
financial press, known as tombstones. But rarely has it tried to
define itself publicly or reduce its mission to a pithy phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman executives insist that the timing of the campaign is
purely coincidental with the stock offering earlier this month. But
both are part of the firm's plan to emerge from its shell. It faces
increasingly tough competition from investment banks that often
have more capital and much bigger ad budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the noise out there, it's good to remind people who
we are and how we do business,'' said David W. May, Goldman's vice
president for global marketing. ``We need to have a consistent
presence for the brand regardless of market conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman declined to comment in detail on the campaign, citing
Securities and Exchange Commission rules about seeking publicity
just after a public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected for a firm where employees have only
recently begun to wear blue Oxford shirts instead of the once
uniform white, Goldman's ads are tame and understated. By Madison
Avenue standards, the message is subtle.
</P>
<P>
   One print ad features identical twins. The caption reads: ``If
we ever find two companies that are exactly alike, we'll offer two
recommendations that are exactly alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Another shows a wide-eyed man at a hair salon examining his
pointy coiffure. The text: ``An honest opinion. Extremely rare when
asking about a future spouse, a new haircut, or whether you should
sell your company.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman will spend about $10 million on the campaign this year,
according to industry experts. The ads, designed by Ammirati Puris
Lintas of New York, a unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies,
will appear in publications like The Financial Times of London, The
Economist, The Wall Street Journal, The New York Times and Business
Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firm does not have a client base of 50 million people like
some of our competitors,'' May said. ``It has a very small target
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other Wall Street firms are also scrambling to put out a
fresh message, especially after a series of mergers that reduced
some well-known independent firms, like Smith Barney and Dean
Witter, to subsidiaries of giant corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, one of the financial industry's heaviest
marketers, introduced a campaign in March that plays down its
historic symbol, the bull, in favor of the abstract theme, ``human
achievement.'' Merrill plans to spend $75 million on that campaign
alone.
</P>
<P>
   And Morgan Stanley now uses as its corporate slogan ``We measure
success one investor at a time'' _ the ad line of the old Dean
Witter, the retail brokerage firm it merged with in 1997. The
firm's overall ad spending is estimated by industry experts at more
than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, a smaller investment bank
that is controlled by AXA's Equitable Companies, plans a
significant marketing push after it sells shares in its online
brokerage subsidiary, DLJ Direct, that would dwarf Goldman's
outlay.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Shevack, chief executive of Partners &AMP; Shevack/Wolf, an
advertising agency in New York owned by the Wolf Group, said that
Goldman needed to respond to the brand-building efforts of
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really need to pre-emptively brand the company vis a vis
the competition,'' Shevack, whose agency does not represent any of
the companies discussed here, said. ``They're trying to communicate
with a rarefied business population. But otherwise, it's no
different than Tide. You have to distinguish yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Goldman had an opportunity to do that now that others
are consolidating. Some well-honed brands, Shevack said, are
getting lost in the merger mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the others firms are worried about how to maintain the
equity they built up in their brands, while Goldman can approach it
with a clean slate,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
