<HEADLINE>
CASE-NEW HOLLAND DEAL REFLECTS TREND IN FARM INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Iowa)  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The deal that was struck Monday to combine Case Corp.
and New Holland NV, two of the world's largest makers of farm and
construction equipment, is just the latest effort to consolidate an
embattled farm industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. economy remains robust, the sharp drop in
commodity prices that began just over a year ago has jolted nearly
every company in the agriculture business, and many have chosen to
combine in mergers that promise to cut costs and bring renewed hope
to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal making, of course, has raised concerns among some farm
organizations that fear the long-term effects of a highly
concentrated industry in which corporate farms dominate and smaller
farmers have fewer and fewer choices.
</P>
<P>
   But a host of companies tied to the agriculture market _ from
seed and fertilizer concerns to tractor makers and farm
cooperatives _ are rethinking the way they do business and finding
ways to team up.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, which has been moving aggressively to establish a
position in the life-sciences business, has acquired Pioneer
Hi-Bred, the world's largest seed company. Cargill and Continental
Grain, the two largest grain traders, agreed to merge in November.
And just last week, Farmland Industries and Cenex Harvest States,
two of the nation's largest food cooperatives, agreed to join
forces, creating a company with $20 billion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, it was Case and New Holland officials saying that new
synergies and productivity gains would create an awesome
combination with the kind of global heft that would make the new
entity a strong rival to Deere &AMP; Co., the world's largest maker of
farm equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Case and New Holland had been suffering, like other farm
equipment makers, through what analysts say is a nearly 25 percent
drop in the sales of farm equipment in the last year, with little
expectation that the farm economy would improve much this year.
Profits are down substantially from a year ago, and the stocks of
both companies had been sharply depressed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   So Monday's deal, one that calls for New Holland, which is 71
percent owned by Fiat of Italy, to pay about $4.3 billion, or $55 a
share, for Case, suggests that restructuring at a time when
globalization is all the rage was simply not enough for the farm
equipment makers, according to analysts. There needed to be a
bigger company to restructure.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, which had combined sales of nearly $12 billion
in 1998, will be based in Racine, Wis., where Case is now based.
Jean-Pierre Rosso, the chief executive at Case who will head the
new company, said at a news conference here that he expected the
company to save up to $500 million annually within the next four
years. The company will sell both the Case and New Holland lines of
tractors, combines and construction equipment. But administrative
and other operations will be fused and financial services outfits
united in a company that will soon be renamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about cutting costs,'' said Lisa Shalett, who
covers the farm equipment industry for Sanford C. Bernstein. ``This
is a huge deal, but we won't see one of these for a while. This was
the last stroke in an evolutionary consolidation of the farm
equipment industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say that because the agriculture industry
is already so highly concentrated and because the Justice
Department is scrutinizing this concentration, it is unlikely there
will be other such deals.
</P>
<P>
   Bold moves by Monsanto, DuPont, Cargill and several meat
packers, including IBP, have also raised concern among farmers in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very grave concerns about this whole concentration
trend because when there is that kind of concentration, those with
power exert more power,'' said Gene Paul, president of the National
Farmers Organization in Ames, Iowa. ``There are that many fewer
buyers that we can buy from.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul said that his organization was most concerned about grain
companies and food processors, but that the general trend was
troublesome and one that farmers' organizations were pushing the
Justice Department to look into.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Duvick, a food industry analyst at Bank of America, said
the deal between Case and New Holland might be seen in its broadest
context as a result of a farm economy that could remain depressed
for some time because of a weak outlook for commodity prices around
the globe and changes related to the Freedom to Farm Act.
</P>
<P>
   Low commodity prices and pressures from big retailers are
squeezing farmers and middlemen, thereby reaching suppliers of farm
products and equipment. And that, he said, was what led to the
Case-New Holland deal, which was brokered by Credit Suisse First
Boston; Goldman, Sachs, and Lazard Freres.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is tied together,'' Duvick said. ``This is a new
era in agriculture, one in which we've already seen a major
consolidation of the industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
