<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEARCH ENGINE IS STOPPED HOURS AFTER DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A few hours after starting a fee-based search
engine for federal government Internet sites and documents, the
Commerce Department put the project off Monday to review whether it
conflicts with the Clinton administration's policy on unrestricted
access to government information.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce officials said the administration wanted to review the
joint venture by the National Technical Information Service and
Northern Light Technology Inc. from all policy angles, not just
that of the Information Service, which is a for-profit agency.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that the project was being delayed came several
hours after the Information Service and Northern Light officials
held a news briefing to demonstrate the search engine at the
National Press Club and after newspaper articles about the project
had appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``In announcing the product and joint venture with Northern
Light, we did not anticipate any conflict with government
information policies,'' the acting under secretary for technology,
Gary R. Bachula, said in a statement. ``But questions that have
arisen today point up the need for a review of this service from a
policy perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachula added, ``Specifically, press reports today raise
questions of consistency with government information policy, and we
want to make sure that this search service, which was to be sold by
subscription, is appropriate and fits within government policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's longstanding policy is to insure that all
government information is open and unrestricted, the Commerce
Department said. Any fees are to cover only the cost of
dissemination.
</P>
<P>
   The National Technical Information Service, a Commerce
Department agency that falls under Bachula's purview, by law
charges users for its products and services.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Information Service is financed from fees for its
products and services. It is also authorized by law to enter joint
ventures with private-sector entities to make government
information not otherwise available accessible to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed fee in the Northern Light joint venture would be
for the use of the search engine. The government data that the
search engine, to be known as usgovsearch.com, would analyze would
remain free and accessible independently to the public, the
department emphasized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
