<SLUG> BC-REFORM-RABBIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY RABBI TO HEAD REFORM CONFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New Jersey, Pittsburgh)   (dal) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There could hardly be a more transformative moment than this to
take over the reins of the largest rabbinical organization in the
country, the Reform movement's Central Conference of American
Rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, after two years of soul-searching, deliberation and
debate, the 1,700-member conference will vote at its convention in
Pittsburgh on a new platform of 10 principles that will define what
it means to be a Reform Jew in the 21st century. The following day,
it will install Rabbi Charles A. Kroloff, 63, the senior rabbi at
Temple Emanu-El in Westfield, N.J., as president.
</P>
<P>
   Kroloff will start his two-year term with the prospect of
recognition and respect for the Reform movement in Israel, after
Monday's electoral defeat of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu by
Ehud Barak, which seems likely to dilute the power of Orthodoxy
over the other branches of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will mean that Americans will feel more
comfortable about their relationship with Israel,'' Kroloff said.
``We should have a prime minister who understands the needs of
non-Orthodox Jews in Israel, and he understands that the future of
Israel depends on an end to religious coercion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the view of many, if the Principles for Reform Judaism, the
fourth set in 110 years, are approved as expected, they will mark a
return to more traditionalism.
</P>
<P>
   The platform calls for increased familiarity with and use of
Hebrew, and for more emphasis on the mitzvoth, the 613 laws and
commandments of daily living. It also spells out the importance of
Tikkun Olam, the call to repair the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some rabbis and congregational leaders have criticized the
principles for signaling a return to Orthodoxy, or as one critic
put it, ``Conservative Judaism Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The principles do call for more tradition but in a very modest
way that emphasizes personal autonomy,'' Kroloff said Monday. ``No
one says you must do X, Y or Z in order to be a good Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Kroloff said another priority of his administration would be to
address the emerging shortage of rabbis and other religious
professionals. Forty-six students are being ordained at Hebrew
Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion at commencement
ceremonies in New York and Cincinnati this year but there were 80
positions to be filled at congregations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to improve rabbis' quality of life. ``My main
crusade for the next two years will be to put more emphasis on
taking care of ourselves so that we can take better care of others
and also have a life,'' he said, referring to the constant demands
on a rabbi's time.
</P>
<P>
   Kroloff, who entered Yale at 16, was ordained at Hebrew Union
College in 1960 and served in several synagogues before joining
Temple Emanu-El in Westfield in 1966. He and his wife, Terry, have
two sons, a daughter and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   He takes his own advice about leisure to heart, by sailing,
working out and trying to learn golf. ``If I were not a rabbi,'' he
said, ``what I really wanted to do was to be first baseman for the
Mets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
