<HEADLINE>
ROBERT GOLDMAN, 60, BRIDGE ACE WHO WON 4 WORLD TEAM TITLES
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Texas, Ga., La.)  (ms) 
 By ALAN TRUSCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Goldman, the winner of four world bridge titles, died of
a heart attack on Sunday. He was 60 and lived in Highland Village,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He died on the way to a hospital, said his stepdaughter, Renee
DeSaye of Atlanta. He had just returned from a tournament in
Boissier City, La.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's four world titles were the Bermuda Bowl for Open Teams
in 1970, 1971 and 1979 and the Mixed Teams in 1972. He was on the
World Bridge Federation's list of Grand Masters, players of the
highest rank.
</P>
<P>
   From 1968 to 1974, he was a member of the Aces team, which
dominated the American tournament scene and had several epic
battles with the Italian Blue Team.
</P>
<P>
   He won 13 major national team titles: the Vanderbilt in 1971,
1973, 1978, 1997 and 1998; the Spingold in 1969, 1978, 1983, 1986
and 1988, and the Reisinger in 1970, 1976 and 1980. He finished
second in three events 12 times. He also won seven other national
titles and hundreds of regional titles, and ranked ninth on the
all-time list of master point winners.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, he and Paul Soloway were the anchor pair
in a series of Internet challenge matches.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman was named the American Contract Bridge League's Honorary
Member for 1999, and is scheduled to be inducted into the league's
Hall of Fame in San Antonio in July.
</P>
<P>
   His bridge activities were wide-ranging away from the card
table. He taught classes, compiled computer practice hands and
created a program to evaluate bidding probabilities. He wrote
scripts for a bridge television series and two books, ``Aces
Scientific'' (self-published, 1973) and ``Winners and Losers at the
Bridge Table'' (Max Hardy, 1979).
</P>
<P>
   Goldman devised many conventions, notably Super Gerber and
Exclusion Blackwood. He was a consultant to the bridge league in
appeals, conventions and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Other survivors are his wife, Bettianne; his son, Quinn; another
stepdaughter, Cherri McKinstry of Dallas, and a stepson, Russel
Taylor of Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
