<HEADLINE>
N.Y. LEGISLATURE ENDS COMMUTER TAX
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.J., Conn.)  (dal) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Unabashedly using its power to try to influence
an upcoming suburban election, the Legislature on Monday brushed
aside Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's protests and voted to rescind a
33-year-old tax on commuters who work in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which Gov. George Pataki said he would sign, carves
at least $210 million _ and as much as $360 million _ from the city
treasury. It was approved after legislative leaders from both major
parties, acting with surprising dispatch in a year when the Capitol
has often seemed paralyzed by partisanship, decided that a tax cut
would bolster their respective candidates in a May 25 special
election for a state Senate seat northwest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to pass the bill left even some supporters
acknowledging privately that lawmakers were perhaps not setting the
best example by altering the city's longstanding tax structure with
no hearings or study, little debate and political considerations at
the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   The measure created unusual rifts in a Legislature where party
discipline rarely breaks, pitting loyalists against one another and
urban members against suburban ones. The dissenters were
Republicans and Democrats from the city, many of whom passionately
denounced the measure.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Roy Goodman, a Manhattan Republican who is a close
ally of Giuliani, said the bill would ``go down in the annals of
this house as one of the most foolish pieces of fiscal folly ever
perpetrated on the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's prime sponsor, state Sen. Dean G. Skelos, a Nassau
County Republican, repeatedly defended the measure as an
appropriate move by the state to lighten the tax burden on suburban
residents at a time when the city enjoys a surplus of more than $2
billion and wants hundreds of million of dollars in tax cuts for
its residents and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a matter of sticking it to the city or doing
anything negative for New York City,'' Skelos said at a news
conference before the vote. ``The issue is one of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 commuters pay the tax, which is .45 of 1 percent
on earned income for most people. The bill approved Monday would
repeal the tax for New York State residents, 58 percent of the
total, who pay $210 million annually. But if the courts rule that
the tax must also end for other commuters, who mostly live in New
Jersey and Connecticut, the cost to the city could reach $360
million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York City Council, the average commuter
earns $88,000 a year, while the average city resident earns nearly
$43,000.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and City Council Speaker Peter F. Vallone, whose
proposed city budgets have been upset by the sudden tax cut, vowed
to go to court to challenge it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
