<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA JURY HEARS OFFICER DESCRIBE BLOODY GLOVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A police officer testified Monday that a fellow
officer charged with torturing Abner Louima had borrowed a pair of
gloves from him, and that the gloves were returned with blood on
them. Investigators later identified that blood as Louima's.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Mark Schofield, also testified that he later heard
the defendant, Officer Justin Volpe, tell two other officers, ``I
broke a man down.'' But a defense lawyer got Schofield to
acknowledge that he did not know whether Volpe's remark concerned
Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield said under questioning in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn that he had not heard what Volpe, or the officers he had
been speaking with, said before that remark and that he had not
heard the other officers respond.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came at the trial of Volpe and three other
officers charged with brutalizing Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian
immigrant, after his arrest in a street melee outside a Brooklyn
nightclub in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield said that just before he lent the gloves to Volpe at
the 70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn, Volpe was carrying a
``stick-like object'' toward the restroom area of the station
house, where prosecutors say Volpe tortured Louima with a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield said that there may already have been blood on the
black leather gloves when he lent them to Volpe, either from
injuries that Schofield sustained in the street melee or from a
second man he had helped arrest near the disturbance. But he said
that there was more blood on them when Volpe returned them, and
that Volpe said as he handed them back, ``Thanks, sorry about the
gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution contends that the additional blood came from
Louima when Volpe, wearing the gloves, beat Louima in the restroom
and then shoved a stick into his rectum and his mouth, inflicting
major internal injuries, while a second officer, Charles Schwarz,
held Louima down.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, has conceded that DNA testing
has shown that Louima's blood was on the gloves, but he argued in
his opening argument two weeks ago that the blood could have come
from facial injuries Louima suffered during the arrest outside the
nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg got Schofield to acknowledge that it was not unusual
for a police officer to put on gloves when dealing with bleeding
prisoners, as a precaution against infection with the AIDS virus or
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   He also got Schofield to acknowledge that the ``stick-like
object'' he had seen in Volpe's hands could have been a nightstick.
The prosecution says the stick Volpe used against Louima was part
of a broken broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg also highlighted Schofield's testimony that Volpe
dissuaded him from discarding the gloves. Instead, Schofield said,
Volpe told him to just ``rinse them off,'' which Schofield did.
Kornberg appeared to be suggesting that Volpe would not have
dissuaded him from discarding the gloves if he had done something
wrong with them.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and Schwarz are among four officers being tried on charges
of violating Louima's civil rights. In addition to being charged
with torturing Louima in the station house bathroom, Schwarz and
Volpe are accused of joining the two other defendants, Thomas
Bruder and Thomas Wiese, in beating Louima in a police car before
he arrived at the station house. Prosecutors from the U.S.
attorney's office in Brooklyn say the officers mistakenly thought
Louima had punched Volpe during the street melee.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is charged with trying
to cover up the beating in the police car. All the defendants
insist the charges are untrue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schofield testified that a week after Louima was injured, he
decided to tell a Police Department investigator about lending
Volpe the gloves. In the hours before he spoke to the investigator,
he said, he had two telephone conversations with Bellomo that, he
suggested, left him with the impression that the sergeant did not
want him to provide investigators with the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a bad feeling I had,'' he said, adding that the sergeant
``basically told me he didn't want to see anyone go to jail'' or
``anyone get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo's lawyer, John Patten, has said that his client did not
take part in a cover-up attempt, but that he had told investigators
that Schofield had ``pertinent information'' about the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
