<SLUG> BC-BKN-SANDOMIR-TVSPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: WALTON TALKS HIMSELF INTO POST-SEASON FORM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Walton was so jazzed for a Knicks-Indiana game last month
on NBC that he held a basketball for the entire telecast. ``I
caressed it all game,'' he said Monday from Indianapolis. ``I could
never hold onto it enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A taut matchup always sends Walton further into the bosom of
basketball. Maybe that's why during the Knicks' 78-77 victory over
Miami on Sunday, Walton did not chastise anyone with his trademark
put-down, ``Oh, that's terrible!''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out players' shortcomings, but not once was anything
or anyone ``terrible,'' or one tier of judgment below, ``awful.''
Walton has toned down his harsher views lately, but not from a
sudden attack of charity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting better games,'' he said. ``In a 1-point game,
things aren't so terrible. Maybe they're ill advised. Maybe they're
awful. But I save `terrible' for game-losing plays.''
</P>
<P>
   High in the ether of his excitement, Walton creates a
provocative and self-deprecating type of analysis that combines
bluntness, loopiness and the inexplicable. Sometimes, even Walton
admits, his brain and mouth conspire against each other, and he
isn't always certain what will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   As a public service, here is The Walton English-to-English
Dictionary, featuring scraps of Sunday's analysis with translations
provided Monday:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It's not how many shots you make, it's how many shots you
take,'' Walton said, after he noted that Patrick Ewing was shooting
seven for 14.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``It's better to go five for 21 than four for
five.'' Further explanation, please: ``That's the concept I grew up
under. It's what John Wooden taught us, that you know you're
playing well by how many shots you've taken.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``As Alonzo Mourning prepares for the biggest game of his
career, it's important to recognize just how far he has come in his
Tom Wolfe novel-like life,'' he said about the Miami center during
the pre-game show.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Alonzo's life just goes in so many directions and
keeps falling back to the center.'' As it happens to all Masters of
the Universe.
</P>
<P>
   - ``He puts his body on the line. He has the scars to prove it.
Now he's got a little bit of ice cream on the foul line,'' he said,
as Terry Porter prepared to sink the free throws that put Miami
ahead, 77-74.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``You've been out in the desert all day, bloodied,
scarred and scratched, and someone puts a delicious bowl of ice
cream in front of you. It's the easy part at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I don't know if Jimi Hendrix and Woodstock is what Latrell
Sprewell is about,'' the devoted Deadhead and child of the 60s
said.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The comment requires having seen Sprewell's new
commercial for And 1, which shows his hair being cornrowed as
Hendrix's electric version of ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' plays in
the background. The formerly pony-tailed Trail Blazer said:
``Latrell's not worthy of Jimi. I didn't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   But you had to like the teamwork of Walton, Steve Jones and Tom
Hammond. Three-in-the-booth groupings are often messy and
pointless, but this trio makes it work because Walton and Jones,
former Portland teammates, offer very different analyses and
comfortably insult each other. Hammond is a straight man, who
orchestrates the conflict and commentary deftly. When placed on
separate games, Jones and Walton are rarely as good as they are in
tandem.
</P>
<P>
   Walton has also been summoned for extra playoff duty, analyzing
playoff games on TNT and TBS with Marv Albert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I turn on the TV, I see you,'' Hammond said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your worst nightmare,'' Walton said.
</P>
<P>
   MARCIANO REPRISE
</P>
<P>
   As documented here recently, Showtime's ``Rocky Marciano'' film,
which was shown Saturday night, was riddled with errors, like a
contrived meeting between Marciano and Joe Louis in a psychiatric
hospital. Marciano died in a plane crash eight months before Louis
entered the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We admit that didn't happen,'' said Rob Cowan, the film's
producer. ``There were certain elements of license you need to take
to tell a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowan said the decision was made to alter Marciano's life by
creating a surreal, fake epiphany with Louis rather than dwell on
the facts of his final day. The movie Marciano couldn't die; he
needed a ``turn in his character literally hours before he died,''
Cowan said.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Louis scene was fabricated to parallel Marciano's
emotional scene with Louis after he knocked him out in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it wrong to show that the man he hero-worshiped was
hospitalized and in a tragic situation, and that he may have gone
to visit him?'' Cowan asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is, unless the film had been labeled a work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The film used a montage to portray Marciano's amateur career as
one of goofy incompetence. A cheap shot. But Cowan changed the
truth of Marciano's first amateur bout, in which he was
disqualified for kicking his opponent in the groin. ``Did we want
to see a cheap shot at that point?'' Cowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, only if it's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the real facts of the life of man, you don't need to
say, as Cowan did: ``There are a lot of accuracies in the film. But
I think the Marciano family has been pushing too hard on the
discrepancies.''
</P>
<P>
   What a concept _ lobbying for accuracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
