<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE YANKEES: TRYING TO MAKE A FIRST-PLACE TEAM BETTER
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner was host of a staff meeting after
the Yankees' game on Sunday, and as always, he wanted answers, he
wanted input, he wanted accountability, and he probably wanted to
yell at somebody. The Yankees are 21-15, good enough to win the
American League East, but they have been playing far less
effectively than anyone expected, including the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling development of last week was the mysterious
players meeting, called after back-to-back losses to the Anaheim
Angels: either the on-field leaders of this team _ Joe Girardi is
at the fore _ see serious internal problems developing or they
overreacted, and for the Yankees' fans, neither possibility can be
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good team that can be great again, but adjustments
need to be made as they begin a three-game series Tuesday night in
Boston, with David Cone pitching against Pedro Martinez of the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   THE ROSTER: Identify 25 productive and useful players for the 25
spots on the roster. The situation with the third-string catcher
Mike Figga is an embarrassment _ he is the only player who has been
on a major league roster all season who has not played in a game _
and there is a strong sense in many corners of the Yankees'
clubhouse that front-office stubbornness is hurting the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have two catchers capable of working full time,
Girardi and Jorge Posada, and there is no need for Figga.
Steinbrenner likes Figga and doesn't want to lose him, but Figga is
28, hardly a young prospect, and given his recent hibernation in
the bullpen, his skills have probably eroded. And there is a fair
chance no one would claim him on waivers, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have far greater need for an extra outfielder with
some speed (Tony Tarasco, perhaps?), someone who can pinch-run. But
if Steinbrenner continues to cling to Figga, then Don Zimmer, the
interim manager, should use him at the end of one-sided games, as
he uses Clay Bellinger and Luis Sojo; when Figga is on the team, he
should be part of the team. To operate in any other way only gnaws
at the fabric of the team.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander Tony Fossas has pitched in five games, allowing
seven of the 10 batters he has faced to reach base. The Yankees
must figure out if that is enough evidence to determine whether the
41-year-old Fossas is not good enough; if so, then get somebody
else. Dan Naulty pitched two and a third innings on Friday and two
innings on Saturday against Chicago _ a risk for someone with a
history of injury trouble _ in part because Zimmer doesn't trust
Fossas with multiple innings. The Yankees should add a pitcher they
trust.
</P>
<P>
   THE CLUBHOUSE: Re-acquire Tim Raines from Oakland. The Yankees
have missed Manager Joe Torre's steady presence, and in a similar
way, they have badly missed Raines' high-pitched cackle. Raines has
fun and manages to makes others smile even on bad days, and he
provided the Yankees with a sense of humor in recent years; last
week's slump revealed the intense Yankees as a sometimes humorless
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, Tino Martinez, Chuck Knoblauch and others rage
inwardly, and the player considered Raines' heir as class cut-up _
24-year-old Derek Jeter _ is too young to tease and joke and force
others to take themselves a little less seriously. Raines is a
part-timer for the Athletics, with 55 plate appearances in 26
games, making a modest salary of $600,000. He is a good role
player, too, someone who could pinch-hit for Girardi or Sojo or
fill in for Shane Spencer in left field. Go get him.
</P>
<P>
   THE LINEUP: Switch Jeter and O'Neill in the batting order. Jeter
clearly is the Yankees' best hitter now, leading them in average
(.362) and extra-base hits (22), and he is mature enough to handle
the move from the No. 2 spot to No. 3 _ which will be his in a few
years, anyway. But O'Neill could be the major benefactor of this
change, because it might scare managers from always using
left-handers against O'Neill in the late innings, and he is hitting
just .139 over all against lefties, compared with .319 against
right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   On 17 occasions in the Yankees' first 36 games, opposing
managers have called on left-handed relievers to face O'Neill in
the late innings, and almost without exception they have also
allowed the reliever to pitch to the two batters who follow
O'Neill, Bernie Williams and Tino Martinez _ the logic being that
Williams, a switch-hitter, is about equal as a left-handed or
right-handed batter and that Martinez is left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Placing Jeter between O'Neill and Williams would force opposing
managers to make an extra decision, and often use another pitcher.
Sure, they could throw the lefty against O'Neill, but would they
risk leaving him in against Jeter, the Yankees' best right-handed
batter, and then Williams? Some managers would use the lefty
against O'Neill, then bring in a right-hander to pitch to Jeter and
Williams and then go back to a lefty against Martinez and the
switch-hitter Chili Davis. Since most teams aren't stocked with
three left-handed relievers, a manager would be forced to choose
between exhausting his supply of lefties or permitting an
unfavorable matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of Spencer, too, has given the Yankees a long
string of right-handed batters, from Spencer at No. 7 to Jeter at
No. 2; flip-flopping O'Neill and Jeter would break up that
grouping. Speed is not really an issue, either: O'Neill runs OK and
would not clog the bases, and Jeter could steal bases hitting ahead
of Williams, who hits more ground balls than anybody else on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   THE BULLPEN: Stick Ramiro Mendoza in the bullpen and leave him
there. Mendoza is a terrific pitcher who would have more value to
the Yankees being available every day than once every five days, as
a starter. The next time a starter gets hurt and must miss a turn,
then call up somebody from Class AAA to step into the rotation and
let Mendoza blossom in the bullpen. The bullpen has been erratic,
but there is potential for greatness. Jason Grimsley is among the
game's most dominant middle relievers right now, with his power
sinker. Opponents are batting .114 against him in his nine May
appearances, though whether he can maintain his success remains to
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza can be great in relief, Jeff Nelson will most likely
come back healthy this week, Mike Stanton's one start seems to have
stabilized his control, and there is always Mariano Rivera, who has
converted 10 of 11 save chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
