<SLUG> BC-FERRARO-BENEFIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL STARS FAIL TO SAVE FERRARO BENEFIT
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everything was set: A room at the Yale Club was
reserved for Wednesday evening, a formal invitation was issued by
New York's two U.S. senators, and, best of all, there was the
promise of an appearance by President Clinton. It was all in the
service of helping Geraldine Ferraro raise money to pay back the
debt from her unsuccessful Senate campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, Ms. Ferraro scrapped the $1,000-a-head
fund-raiser after determining that fewer than 100 people had agreed
to show up, a quarter of what she had hoped for, president or no
president.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the ``Salute to Geraldine Ferraro'' had been canceled
came in the form of a revised schedule issued by the White House
last night for Clinton's trip to New York on Wednesday, which had
him returning to the White House five hours earlier than had been
announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fantasies of originally there being 400 people,''
Patricia Everet, the event coordinator hired by Ms. Ferraro to
organize the fund-raiser, said Monday night. ``As we got more
realistic about it, we had hoped for maybe 150 to 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just ain't happening, as they say,'' she said with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   The debt was from Ms. Ferraro's campaign for Senate last year.
Although she entered the race on a burst of publicity, she went on
to lose the Democratic primary to Charles Schumer, who went on to
defeat the Republican incumbent, Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro, who was the Democratic Party's 1984 candidate for
vice president, was not available for comment Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proved to be one of the most successful fund-raisers
the Democratic Party has ever had, and New York has proved to be
one of his favorite places to gather money. But Ms. Everet and
other Democrats said that a number of forces had served to derail
this particular event, notwithstanding the star power she had
enlisted _ Clinton, Schumer, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Rep.
Nita M. Lowey of Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, they noted, it is often difficult to persuade
people to contribute money to a campaign that has already failed.
And that particularly holds true when the politician is not
expected to run for public office again. After losing to Schumer,
Ms. Ferraro announced that her years in politics were over.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Everet also said that many of Ms. Ferraro's regular
supporters had already contributed the maximum amount of money
allowed to her campaign. And Democrats in New York have long
complained that donors in the state have become exhausted by
Clinton's frequent visits to raise money in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the purposes for Clinton's trip to New York is to
attend a fund-raising luncheon for the Democratic National
Committee. The other is to attend the dedication of the
Pennsylvania Station redevelopment project.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Ferraro's disclosure statement filed with the
Federal Election Commission, her total debt from the 1998 campaign
was nearly $1 million, including $400,000 she had lent the campaign
herself and does not have to repay.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, she is required to repay the debt owed to
lenders other than herself; otherwise, it would be considered a
contribution far in excess of campaign limits. As a matter of
practice, though, such debts often linger for years, especially for
a candidate who has left politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
