A1033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-MUTOMBO-NYT     05-17 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-MUTOMBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS' MUTOMBO IS UP FOR THE KNICKS' CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Knicks-Heat matchup was prime-time drama, the
Knicks-Hawks is akin to MacNeil and Lehrer reuniting. New York and
Atlanta have not played against each other in the post-season since
1971, and their current rivalry is based on a litany of
grind-it-out, halfcourt games that cause viewers to channel-surf
for Allen Iverson and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup between Patrick Ewing, the old warrior, and Dikembe
Mutombo, the shot-blocking prodigy, when New York and Atlanta begin
their Eastern Conference semifinal series Tuesday night may seem
anticlimactic after Ewing and New York vanquished Alonzo Mourning
and Miami in the first round, a pulsating series that went down to
the last second on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Mutombo's legacy of getting knocked out before the
conference finals could change the perception going into the
series.
</P>
<P>
   During some off-seasons, Ewing has given Mourning grief about
emotionally draining playoff losses. In others, Mourning has
returned the favor. Either way, there was always a healthy dose of
trash-talk exchanged between the former Georgetown centers.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever they came back to their old campus each summer for
friendship and basketball, Mutombo could not help feeling a little
left out.
</P>
<P>
   His Atlanta Hawks were good, but as the Eastern Conference
playoffs wore on each season, the 7-foot-2-inch Congo native with
the booming baritone voice would always find himself in a designer
suit at courtside watching his fellow former Hoyas play.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he decided that this was not acceptable. ``Patrick and
I can have dinner before the game,'' Mutombo said Monday. ``We can
have an orange juice after the game. But when we come to the court,
our friendship will be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``This is something special to play against someone
you know half your life and grow up with in the game. I love to see
it happen. He might be a lucky guy. He played Mourning and me in
the same year. I got to be the one that finishes him. I know that
he finished Mourning. Now I got to finish him.''
</P>
<P>
   Aging, defensive-minded and recuperating from a grueling
first-round series, Mutombo and the Hawks have much in common with
the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo will be 33 in June. The Hawks' other two marquee players
_ point guard Mookie Blaylock and shooting guard Steve Smith _ are
33 and 30, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Along with their other two starters, Ty Corbin, 36, and Grant
Long, 33, they all played more than 40 minutes in the Game 5
victory against the Detroit Pistons on Sunday. But Lenny Wilkens,
the winningest coach in National Basketball Association history, is
playing down the notion that his team may be too tired and too sore
to make this a long series.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bench, however, leaves a lot to be desired. Anthony
Johnson, a reserve point guard, played only 10 minutes Sunday.
Allan Henderson, the team's usual sixth man, is not expected to
play after being struck in the eye in the last Sunday of the
regular season. Though Wilkens did not completely rule his
availability out, Henderson is suffering from double vision.
</P>
<P>
   After LaPhonso Ellis underwent surgery for a hernia in March,
the reserves Corbin and Long essentially became starters. Forward
Chris Crawford is expected to play despite rehabilitating a
separated right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the Hawks have their positives. They gave up the fewest
points of any team in the league, and a key against the Knicks may
be their ability to not give up open shots.
</P>
<P>
   As clutch offensively as he can be, Smith is also a versatile
defender. He guarded Joe Dumars, Jerry Stackhouse and Grant Hill at
various times in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock came into the last 10 games of the season shooting only
37 percent and has clearly had one of his least-productive seasons.
But in the last 10 games, he made 40 percent of his 3-pointers and
began to move the ball around the perimeter again.
</P>
<P>
   And Mutombo is finally starting to develop an offensive game,
using drop-step moves to get closer to the basket in order to use
his jump hook. He now bends down into the post like a weight lifter
about to engage in a set of squats. He is determined not to feel
sorry for a proud but pained Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a lot of respect for him; that's my brother,''
Mutombo said. ``But when I'm on the floor, I do what I can to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Game 5, Mutombo predicted that the Hawks would beat the
Pistons. At the price of getting ribbed by his off-court friends
and on-court rivals this summer, the center went out on a limb
again Monday. After all, he figures Ewing can only have bragging
rights for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will guarantee we will win the series, but it's going to be
a tough series,'' Mutombo said. ``I'm getting to the middle of my
career when I want to win something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
