u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAVEZ-BIRTHDAY-COX     05-17 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-BIRTHDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cesar Chavez Day approved in House
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Beginning next year, Texas will commemorate
Cesar Chavez's birthday with an optional state holiday, making the
legendary labor and civil rights leader the first Hispanic to be
honored with a Texas holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Monday followed the Senate in approving a bill
designating March 31 as ``Cesar Chavez Day.'' Gov. George W. Bush
has described the measure as a fitting tribute to Chavez, who died
in 1993, and has said he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norma Chavez, the El Paso Democrat who sponsored the bill
in the House, wiped away tears after her colleagues approved the
measure without debate. Chavez is not related to the late labor
leader but said the measure was ``spiritual and personal'' for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's environment, when we're looking for leaders who
promote nonviolent actions in a community that is filled with hate
and violence, we need young leaders to emulate someone like Cesar
Chavez, who found a different way to demonstrate his frustration,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday will be optional, meaning that state offices will
remain open but state employees can choose to take the day off with
pay in exchange for working on another state holiday, such as San
Jacinto Day, Confederate Heroes Day, or Emancipation Day. Rosh
Hashanah, Yom Kippur and Good Friday are the other optional state
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, when Chavez took the helm of the United Farm Workers
union, most Americans saw the burgeoning civil rights movement as a
black and white issue. Chavez, the son of migrant farm workers,
helped changed that.
</P>
<P>
   An advocate of nonviolence, Chavez galvanized public support on
behalf of farm workers, many of them illegal immigrants who endured
miserable work conditions. By the time he died at age 66, he was
also viewed as a leader of Hispanics living in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez began his most famous campaign in 1968, when he urged
Americans not to buy table grapes produced in California's San
Joaquin Valley until growers agreed to union contracts. The boycott
was a huge success: One poll found that 17 million Americans had
stopped buying grapes, and in 1970 growers agreed to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chavez said she hopes the optional state holiday will
eventually evolve into a full state holiday and then a national
one. California and Arizona have enacted legislation similar to
Texas' and similar bills are pending in New Mexico and the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
