<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-ENDANGERED-SPECIE     05-17 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ENDANGERED-SPECIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Radical effort to save endangered species pleases some, peeves
others
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Efforts to save Florida's endangered
plants and animals are taking two steps forward and, some
environmental groups say, two steps back.
</P>
<P>
   This morning in Boca Raton, U.S. Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt will sign a long-awaited federal plan aimed at rescuing 68
endangered and threatened species from extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists call it a sweeping attempt to restore wildlife and
habitat across 26,000 square miles in South and Central Florida,
from the crocodile and manatee to plants such as Small's milkpea
and the deltoid spurge. The plan, the largest of its kind ever
attempted, departs from the usual, piecemeal approach of helping
species one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   However, publicly available versions of the plan have drawn
criticism from some environmentalists, who said it lacks tough
rules and specific actions. Many of those details will await the
plan's next stage, said Jay Slack, a field supervisor for the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   On a similar front, the state Game and Fresh Water Fish
Commission last week adopted rules that supporters say will lead to
creation of restoration blueprints for imperiled species.
</P>
<P>
   But the rules also require the state _ for the first time _ to
consider economic costs before declaring a species endangered or
threatened. Before then, the species can be considered only a
``candidate.'' That guarantees it protection from intentional harm
but might not safeguard its habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is going backwards,'' said Brian Scherf of the
Florida Biodiversity Project.
</P>
<P>
   Game Commissioner Julie Morris disagreed. ``I think it's a
strong, positive step,'' she said of the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups said they need to know more about the federal plan
and the state rules. For South Florida, the fate of many of the
species will really depend on yet another effort: a $7.8 billion
federal plan for restoring the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sweeping federal plan ``is inherently incapable itself
in causing the changes necessary to recover most of these
species,'' said Charles Lee of the Florida Audubon Society. ``The
only way we're going to get to that is to put the Everglades in
some semblance of working order.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Estenoz, an Everglades activist for the World Wildlife
Fund, said she's still waiting for the final version of the federal
plan. ``As a concept, we're very supportive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan drew more scathing criticism from the Miccosukee Indian
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can have all the plans in the world, but they'll just be
autopsy reports if they don't take the actions needed to help the
species survive,'' tribal consultant Joette Lorion said.
</P>
<P>
   Slack said the agency took public comments into account while
creating the plan's 2,200-page final version, which it intends to
distribute sometime this summer. The wildlife service has no
estimated price tag for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   By design, he said, the plan leaves it to scientists, landowners
and other groups to work out many details of how to help specific
species. ``We want to have all the stakeholders at the table,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
