<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      05-17 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK OUSTS NETANYAHU IN A LANDSLIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Handing a landslide victory to Labor party candidate
Ehud Barak and his message of ``unity, change and hope,'' Israeli
voters Monday dramatically swept from office Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and rejected a campaign focused on fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this moment on, we are all together now, we are one
nation,'' Barak said at a packed rally of cheering supporters early
Tuesday. ``I intend to be the prime minister of everybody. Whatever
disagreements we have, we are brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Channel One Television gave the decorated former army
chief 58.5 percent of the votes to 41.5 percent for the Likud
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 17 percent margin of victory, based on exit polls,
was viewed as a historic mandate for Barak's left-of-center
coalition brought together under the banner of ``One Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Final results are not expected until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Within a half hour of the exit polls, Netanyahu conceded defeat
and said he was also stepping down as Likud leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tempest of the election is passing, now we have to quiet
it down. We have to also unify,'' Netanyahu told stunned and silent
Likud supporters at the party's Tel Aviv headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will lead Israel into the final phase of the peace process
with Palestinians. Monday &UR;  &LR; night, even as Katyusha rockets rained
down on northern Israel, Barak vowed to to pull Israeli troops out
of Lebanon within one year. Still, most voters focused their
concerns in this election not on security issues, but on deep
divisions within Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, voters focused on Israel's economy and a profound
rift between the religious minority and secular majority. Barak
also faces challenges in the ethnic politics that pit the
Sephardim, or Jewish immigrants from North Africa and Arab states,
against the Ashkenazim, the established European elite.
</P>
<P>
   With a turnout of nearly 80 percent of the country's 4.2 million
voters, Israelis cast ballots for what ended up as a two-way race
for prime minister after three candidates from smaller parties
dropped out in the final days. Voters also cast ballots for a new
120-member Knesset, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Barak's vow to unify the country, voting showed a
further fragmentation of the Knesset, and will pose an immediate
challenge to Barak's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the intensifying divisions along the religious-secular
lines, the strictly observant Orthodox Shas Party emerged stronger
than ever, picking up an estimated four seats in the parliament and
holding its position as the third largest party. An adamantly
secular party that was not represented in the current Knesset won
an estimated six seats.
</P>
<P>
   Yaron Ezrahi, of the Israel Democracy Institute and a political
analyst, said, ``This is a surprising and decisive edge for Barak,
which in Israeli electoral terms has to be seen as a landslide.''
</P>
<P>
   For 22 years, Israel's largest parties _ Labor and Likud _ have
traded leadership but always by only a few percent of the vote in
the parliament, a trend which continued even when Israel changed
from a parliamentary system to direct elections for prime minister
in 1996. The result has been an intense and often vitriolic
political discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Barak pointedly did not attack Netanyahu despite the incumbent's
attempts to draw him into a combative political campaign. The
Israeli voters seemed Monday to express their approval of that
approach.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and European capitals, often frustrated by
Netanyahu's hard line in the peace process, swiftly welcomed
Barak's victory and his goal of breaking the deadlocked peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who had given Netanyahu several diplomatic
snubs, said, ``I look forward to working closely with Ehud Barak
and his new government as they strive to reach that goal with their
Palestinian and Arab partners.''
</P>
<P>
   After a meteoric rise to power, Netanyahu, 49, known by
supporters and detractors alike as ``Bibi,'' won an upset victory
over Labor's Shimon Peres in 1996. But Netanyahu held a razor-thin
margin of 61-59 in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was accused by critics of being held hostage by the
Orthodox and nationalist extremists within his coalition who
threatened to take down his government. The bloc of Russian
immigrant voters, led by Natan Sharansky, was particularly put off
by the Orthodox control of the Interior Ministry, which oversees
immigration. Russian immigrants turned against Netanyahu in
significant numbers on the religious issue.
</P>
<P>
   In January, some of Netanyahu's fractious former partners
finally took down the government and forced him to call early
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Reuven Hazan, a Hebrew University political science professor,
said, Netanyahu ``promised too much to too many, and ended up
delivering too little to all of them. That's why they brought him
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu also suffered a wave of defections through his tenure
from some of the most popular leaders within his coalition. Two of
them, his former military chief of staff, Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, and
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, broke off to form a Center
Party. On the eve of the election, that party made a stunning and
decisive move by pulling out of the race and shifting its support
to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, seeing the polls shifting against him in the final
weeks of the election, resorted to a campaign that emphasized
security concerns. He resurrected the images of bus bombings that
won him a narrow election in 1996. He made a dangerous and
desperate attempt to put the future of Jerusalem at the center of
debate by threatening to use force to shut down PLO offices in
Jerusalem. As the city faced an explosion of violence if the
offices were shut down, Israel's High Court ruled against
Netanyahu, and even his own supporters criticized the move as
politically motivated. Netanyahu also pointed a finger of blame at
Israel's academic elite and the left leaning media, saying they had
conspired to remove him from office. At a rally, he led a chant of
``They're afraid. They're afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Ezrahi said:``For Netanyahu this is more than
a political defeat. Bibi was coldly evicted from his office by the
Israeli people who reacted against his way of appealing to the
negative feelings of fear and anxiety and resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ezrahi added, ``It simply does not work in Israel. I think this
will put an end to the bad blood we've seen for so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnon Lord, a columnist for the popular daily newspaper Yediot
Ahronot and a supporter of Netanyahu, said the key to Netanyahu's
defeat was his alignment with the ultra-Orthodox parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis vote according to the current threat,'' Lord said.
``In 1996, it was terror. Tuesday, it was the threat of
theocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibi became identified with Shas, and Shas posed a big theat
to the Israeli middle class. Many right-wing, secular voters
prefered somebody like Barak instead of a combination leading to
theocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lord added that Netanyahu's achievements were considerable.
``Despite what they say, he had the materials of a great statesmen,
not a politician. He destroyed the political machine around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing before his supporters, Netanyahu said that his
hard-line policies on security had ``almost put a stop to
terrorism.'' He said he felt he had ``built the foundation for the
future of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he would also resign from the Likud leadership, Netanyahu
added, ``I believe that the time has now come to be with my family,
with my wife and my children, and to see where my path will take
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's path to power has been meticulously crafted in the image
of his mentor and former military commander, the slain Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin. Rabin, a hawk turned dove, was the
architect of the historic 1993 peace agreement. Barak expressed
reservations about Rabin's peace plan when it was formed, but still
used his close association with Rabin to help his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech, Barak stood at the podium, flanked by
his family and Rabin's widow, Leah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that if Yitzhak is looking down on us from heaven, then
he is proud of us, just as we are proud of him,'' Barak said. ``He
knows we, together, will fulfill his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   While he spoke some 15,000 supporters were amassing at Rabin
Square in Tel Aviv, the plaza where Rabin was shot Nov. 4, 1995, by
a Jewish religious extremist opposed to his plan. A memorial to
Rabin usually decorated with flowers and candles was swarmed with
young people wearing T-shirts plastered with Barak stickers.
Supporters danced and cheered as loudspeakers blared peace songs.
</P>
<P>
   Huge posters of a young Rabin loomed like icons over the crowd.
A banner read, ``Hope is returning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here twice in my life, when Rabin was assassinated and
the second time is now,'' said Yuval Amon, 50. ``This is a new
chance for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Lallo, 50, said, ``When Rabin was killed everything went
backwards, now we can make peace with ourselves and the Arabs. . .
. Barak will do it, but we may have to push him. He won't have a
choice but to move ahead. The light is turned back on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
