<SLUG> BC-PAULA-JONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones' psychic hotline slow to catch on
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Perhaps David Felger should have consulted
his psychics before signing on Paula Jones as spokeswoman for his
Boca Raton-based dial-a-destiny hotline.
</P>
<P>
   The woman made famous for accusing President Clinton of luring
her to an Arkansas hotel suite in 1991 isn't attracting many
callers who want a fortune-teller's take on their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a horse race, we'd be off to a slow start,'' said
Felger, president of the Zodiac Group Inc., the company that runs
the Paula Jones Celebrity Psychic Network.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who this year settled her sexual harassment lawsuit
against President Clinton for $850,000, signed a contract in
February giving her a 90-day trial as a spokeswoman for the
hotline. If the calls start coming _ at $3.49 a minute _ Jones, 33,
could extend her contract for five years, said Felger, who refused
to say how much Jones is being paid.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Carpenter-McMillan, Jones' former spokeswoman, told the
New York Daily News: ``I am so, so opposed to her doing this. It's
really damaging, but hey, that's her choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gordon, who identified himself as a celebrity promoter
working with Jones in New York, said Monday the contract could be
worth as much as $350,000 for Jones, who is living with her two
sons in Arkansas. Gordon said he works on commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Paula has a big career ahead of her,'' Gordon said.
``She sings really well. We're looking at a country album.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon five years ago predicted similar country-western success
for his then-wife LaToya Jackson. The two divorced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Felger said he has advertised Jones' number in Cosmopolitan, the
Globe, the National Enquirer and True Romance . But even with a
boost from Time magazine, which ran a picture of the ad complete
with phone numbers this week, business is off to a slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're cautiously optimistic,'' Felger said. ``Like any
product looking for a celebrity endorsement you're looking for
someone who is high profile, someone who has identity with the
people you're trying to market to. But like anything in mass
marketing, it's trial and error.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Jones mystique brings in callers, Felger predicted there
could be television spots in her future.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains: Will Jones become a successful psychic
diva?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Hildegard, a ``psychic'' on the network
who said she'd have to talk with Jones herself. ``I work by
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
