<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROM-BOMB-COX     05-17 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROM-BOMB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bomb at prom broke up more than a dance
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Marvelous Washington's Palm Beach Lakes
classmates are ``walking around like zombies,'' unsure how to
comprehend the nail-studded pipe bomb that scuttled their prom
Saturday night, unsure whether they want to reschedule the dance
they'd been waiting for most of their high school years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, principals and police at five other high schools
scrambled Monday to ensure their proms wouldn't meet a similar
fate.
</P>
<P>
   School Police Chief Jim Kelly said he will review prom security
plans for Spanish River, Boca Raton, Wellington, Glades Central and
Royal Palm Beach high schools and decide how to beef them up by
midweek. That is likely to mean more police and adults at the
dances and sweeps through the buildings with bomb-sniffing dogs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to anticipate every angle we can,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   The prom ended Saturday when a Sheraton Hotel security guard
spotted a pipe bomb in a white paper bag in a planter near the
student dance.
</P>
<P>
   School police are interviewing students, and a $2,500 reward is
offered for information leading to an arrest. Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms agents say they aren't certain students were
the target _ it could have been meant for hotel guests or
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb was described as a simple, potentially lethal
instrument made from parts virtually anyone could buy. The ATF sent
it to Atlanta to confirm that it was made to blow up and to check
for fingerprints, said spokesman Dale Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that it sat in a hallway planter outside the prom
ballroom very long, said Jim Bolin, the Sheraton's general manager.
He said the area is cleaned daily, security guards check the area
often and people who take care of the plants make weekly rounds.
</P>
<P>
   In case the bomb was meant for students, bomb-sniffing dogs
scoured the school before students returned to class Monday
morning, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, students such as senior Heather Whitmore and her friends
say they are uneasy. ``We were talking about how we don't feel safe
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Students, parents and administrators have been jittery ever
since two students killed 12 classmates and a teacher in Colorado
last month. Several Palm Beach County schools have since been
evacuated after bomb threats. But the Sheraton incident was the
first time a real bomb has been found. With five more proms and
graduation coming up, the incident fueled the tension.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said security traditionally is tighter for graduation and
this year will be no different. The yearly graduation events have
long been a target of bomb threats by disaffected students.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, most students were more concerned about the proms.
</P>
<P>
   Marvelous Washington, who is president of the senior class at
Palm Beach Lakes High, still is stunned that her prom ended three
songs after it began. Monday, she asked student leaders if they
were interested in trying again. The responses were mixed, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitmore isn't sure she wants to return to the Sheraton, she
said. And then there's the matter of cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saved since the beginning of last year _ five bucks here,
$10 there,'' said Whitmore, who scraped together $400. ``A lot of
people couldn't afford it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Principal Nate Collins spent the morning negotiating another
night with the Sheraton Hotel in West Palm Beach. The junior class
invested $7,000 on the event. Tickets went for $50. Collins had not
worked out a date by Monday afternoon. Representatives from the
senior class said they favored a compromise _ perhaps a semi-formal
affair that wouldn't take such a toll on their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb hasn't curbed many students' determination to enjoy the
final bash of the year, most of which are scheduled for this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prom is this Saturday and I'm crossing my fingers,'' said
Shaz Asghar, a senior at Royal Palm Beach High and president of the
countywide student council. ``It was the major talk around school
today, but plans are as usual. We feel no one at school would do
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Spanish River students said the incident barely warranted
mention in their Boca Raton halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is a concern,'' said senior Coleman Rawls,
who plans to attend Spanish River's $165-per-couple event at the
Boca Raton Resort and Club. ``We're totally different schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Spanish River senior Wesley Vaux, ``This is Boca. We can't
have bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent Peter Victoria believes Boca Raton High will keep his
daughter safe. ``They'll take the extra measures. But then, what
else are you going to do? You can't lock (the students) up. I mean,
she's 18 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Boca Raton High Principal Diana Harris already evacuated her
campus once because of a bomb threat. She doesn't want to see her
students' prom spoiled the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be held hostage by these events, but you can't
disregard them either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Isger writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Clay Lambert and Angie Scharnhorst contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
