<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-SOUTHLAND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD TOSS PLACES TEXAS-ARLINGTON SHOT PUTTER AMONG NATION'S
ELITE
</HEADLINE>
 CONFERENCE TRACK-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Her coach knew it was coming weeks ago.
Marsha French didn't even realize it when it happened.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't take the Texas-Arlington junior long to figure out
that her best shot put of the year, a Southland Conference-record
54 feet, 111/4 inches, not only won her the conference title but
moved her into the No. 3 spot in the nation in her event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a terrible throw,'' French said. ``They told
me afterward my release was good, but my form was off and I was way
off balance. But, whatever gets it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday at Homer Bryce Stadium, the shot went farther than all
but two collegiate shot putters have put it this year. French,
whose previous best was 53-93/4, passed Leslie Vidmar of Kent
(54-83/4) on the national list but trails national leader Seilala
Sua of UCLA (56-4) and Cheree Hicks of Syracuse, who moved into
second with a toss of 56-21/2 last weekend at a meet in Chapel
Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   And with the NCAA Outdoor Championships on the horizon, more
distance might be left in French, who has also tentatively
qualified for the USA Track and Field national championships June
24-26 in Eugene, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can throw farther still,'' Texas-Arlington field events
coach Wayne Cunnings said. ``I've seen her get out more explosively
than she did on that throw. With her size and strength and speed,
it's definitely possible. Tuesday, not everything was perfect and
she still threw almost 55 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got a little more left in her for nationals. When she
gets everything right, she's going to go 57 feet. We train so
she'll throw her best at the end of the year, and here she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunnings said he knew French was due for a big throw because she
consistently has thrown 50-52 feet in practice over the past two
weeks. French, on the other hand, wasn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned with practice results,'' said French, who
sat out last season before transferring from Northeast Louisiana.
``It's always what you do at meets, and I hadn't done much lately.
I still feel like I'm behind because of that year off. I should be
throwing 58 or 59 feet by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Her performance Monday was more than good enough for the
Mavericks, who blew out to the expected lead in the team race,
leading second-place McNeese State 42-33 after five events. In
addition to French's victory, the Mavericks scored points with
Ashley Dorsey's third-place finish in the shot put, Monika Rolle's
second in the long jump and a 3-5 finish in the heptathlon by
Theresa Soderlund and Stephanie Willis.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-Arlington men had their problems in the field events,
scoring fewer points than expected. Matt Swain finished seventh in
the shot put, and Brandon Berger fought through hamstring injuries
to compile 6,200 points in the decathlon, but he could not crack
the top eight places. Berger also failed to make the finals in the
javelin.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Horn began to turn the tide in the long jump, reaching
24-21/2 to take third behind Marcel Williams of Stephen F. Austin,
who upset national leader Kenta Bell of Northwestern State with a
leap of 25-71/2. Horn also ran the fastest qualifying time in the
100 meters at 10.62.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington stood eighth after four events with 10 points,
25 behind first-place Stephen F. Austin and Northwestern State. The
Mavericks expect to get most of their points in Tuesday's running
finals, with two runners each qualified in the 400 _ including top
qualifier Patrick James with an SLC-best 46.85 _ the 1,500 and the
110 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The meet was suspended midway through last night's running
preliminaries. Qualifying heats for the 800 meters, 400 hurdles and
200 meters as well as finals in the women's 3,000 and the men's
3,000 steeplechase are scheduled for Tuesday morning.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
