</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'LL BE FRANK VS. FRANK AT WCC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month ago, the Franks _ Sanchez at Pepperdine and Cruz at
Loyola Marymount _ both shrugged off a possible meeting in the West
Coast Conference baseball championship series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither team may make it,'' said Cruz, the head coach at LMU,
and Sanchez agreed.
</P>
<P>
   They were both wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, ranked No. 12 and the winner of the WCC's Coast
Division, plays at West Division-winner LMU this weekend with the
winner of the best-two-of-three series earning an automatic bid to
the NCAA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The opening game is Friday at 3 p.m. Game two is Saturday at
noon, and if necessary, a third game will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great tribute to both teams to be playing for
the conference championship,'' Sanchez said. ``It's well-deserved
by both programs.''
</P>
<P>
   LMU (31-25, 18-12) clinched the West Division Sunday with a 12-3
win over Santa Clara. The Lions, who swept the Waves at home in
April to earn home-field advantage for this series, needed to win
two out of their last three games to win the division. LMU, unlike
the Waves, most likely won't receive an at-large berth if they lose
the series.
</P>
<P>
   Twelfth-ranked Pepperdine (42-12, 21-9) clinched the Coast
Division two weeks ago. Sanchez said he doesn't think the Waves
lost any momentum because they clinched so early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how you get there,'' he said, ``but that you
get there. Like (the) Super Bowl. . . Does (clinching early) help
or hurt you?''
</P>
<P>
   The first game should feature two standout sophomore pitchers.
Pepperdine's Jay Adams, a right-hander who is 9-1, became the staff
ace by midseason. LMU right-hander Billy Traber (8-5) leads the WCC
in strikeouts. Traber beat Santa Clara Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Powerful statement: Even if UCLA (30-29) doesn't get an
at-large bid to the playoffs, Bill Scott's season is worth a second
look.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, a sophomore left fielder from Alemany High, led the
Bruins in batting average (.372) home runs (25) and RBI (79). His
home run total was the seventh-best in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to have a better season next year,'' said Scott,
who will play in the prospect-heavy Cape Cod League this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Scott wears No. 44 _ the same number worn by sluggers Hank
Aaron, Reggie Jackson and Willie McCovey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been 16 at Alemany,'' Scott said. ``That number was
already taken . . . and I said `Not too many people have 44.' To
wear 44 you have to have a little power. I'm going to stick with it
as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wright stuff: Two years after making what he called the best
decision in his life, UC Santa Barbara outfielder Brad Wright
almost hit .400.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a senior who played at both Crespi and Agoura high
schools, was batting .390 entering the Gauchos' loss at CSUN last
week. He ended at .377 with two homers and 36 RBI. He transferred
from Cal to UCSB after his sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches did some things that were questionable (with my
playing time),'' Wright said. ``I didn't see myself getting a fair
shot there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Team first: Don't accuse Loyola Marymount's Matt Riordan of
thinking about personal achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, a junior from Westlake High, was a triple shy of the
cycle entering his final at-bat last week against Cal State
Northridge. He hit a drive to the gap in right-center field, but
instead of charging to third to get the cycle, Riordan stopped at
second base for his second double of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He went 5 for 6 with five RBI in the Lions' 15-7 win.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rebirth for Anteaters: UC Irvine dropped baseball in 1992,
but it appears the program is coming back after students voted to
raise their fees $33 to support the athletic department. The sport
is expected to be reinstated for the 2001-02 school year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Showing his stuff: UCLA freshman right-hander Josh Karp, who
turned down a reported $2 million offer to sign with the Atlanta
Braves after last year's draft, was 7-3 with a 4.26 ERA this
season. Opponents batted .258 against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Karp) has tremendous presence,'' UCLA head coach Gary Adams
said. ``There are a lot of guys with a better arm than Josh Karp.
It's all about how you compete.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the horn: &UR; !off &LR;  Cal State Los Angeles senior Steve
Brown, a pitcher-infielder from Birmingham High, closed his college
career with a no-hitter against Cal State Stanislaus on April 30.
CSLA freshman third baseman Jay Caligiuri (Camarillo) batted .309
and was a California Collegiate Athletic Association honorable
mention selection. . . . USC knocked out Washington All-American
Jeff Heaverlo after five innings Sunday. Heaverlo, a projected
first-round draft pick in June, was charged with 12 runs, all
earned, on 13 hits. . . . Cal Poly SLO freshman Bryan Gant,
Chatsworth's starting left fielder last year, led the Broncos in
batting average (.374) this season. Gant, who batted leadoff for
most of the year, was 11 for 11 in stolen base attempts. . . . UCSB
shortstop Jeff Bannon, a sophomore from Camarillo High, batted .286
with 14 homers and 46 RBI this season. . . . Nevada sophomore
pitcher Matt Rainer (Royal) went 10-3 in the regular season to help
the Wolf Pack finish second in the Big West Conference and clinch a
likely at-large playoff berth. Rainer's twin brother Michael
pitches for CSUN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
