<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PLEASED WITH RESULTS OF ISRAELI ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add 10 grafs, beginning: Last month, Clinton ...)  (mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration greeted the results of
the Israeli election on Monday with public decorum, congratulating
the winner, Ehud Barak, but with private satisfaction that Benjamin
Netanyahu had lost.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's relations with Netanyahu started off poorly
and deteriorated to the point where Clinton snubbed the Israeli
leader during a visit by him here two years ago. Their personal
differences were barely papered over during tortuous negotiations
last October that ended in a modest pact brokered by Clinton
between Israel and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when exit polls showed Barak likely to win by a large
margin, a senior administration official noted approvingly that
Israeli commentators were calling the results a ``blowout,'' the
Israeli term for a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the last Israeli election, when Clinton embraced
Shimon Peres as the best hope for peace, exulted in early polling
that predicted his victory and then was disappointed and
embarrassed to find he had backed a loser, the administration
remained circumspect about this race.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton looked on as three of his own best campaign
advisers, led by James Carville, moved to Israel and helped Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton telephoned both Netanyahu and Barak late Monday
afternoon. In a statement afterward, Clinton said he reaffirmed to
Barak that he would ``work energetically for a just, lasting and
comprehensive peace that strengthens Israel's security.'' Vice
President Al Gore called Barak early Monday evening from a hotel
room in Boston and later called Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   In the fairly grim landscape of Clinton's foreign policy
problems at the moment, Barak's victory came as good news.
</P>
<P>
   He is perceived by administration officials as a military figure
of stature who will be more conducive than Netanyahu to dealing
with the final phase of talks with the Palestinians, the critical
negotiations that will help define Israel's future.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have also said that Barak, with his
military background, is different in outlook than the former Labor
Party leader, Shimon Peres. Barak, they have said, will be
steadfast in ensuring that Israel's security is protected as the
peace process moves forward.
</P>
<P>
   It was too early to tell how soon the process, originally set
out in accords made in Oslo in 1993 and 1995 and then last October
at Wye, Md., would resume, a senior administration official said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Clinton tried to edge the process along by sending a
letter to Arafat warning him against unilaterally declaring a
Palestinian state but going further than before toward endorsing an
eventual Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In that letter, Clinton said the United States was prepared to
convene a new set of peace talks within six months after the
Israeli elections. With Barak the winner, those talks _ to address
critical outstanding questions like the status of Jerusalem,
security relations between Israel and the Palestinian entity, the
future of refugees and regional water rights _ are now likely to be
convened sooner than six months, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Netanyahu government spells the end of some of
the most acid moments in personal relations between Israeli and
American leaders. Clinton and Netanyahu did not get along, and
neither did Netanyahu and the secretary of state, Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   During her first visit to Israel as secretary of state in
September 1997, Albright said in a speech in Jerusalem that a
``time out'' was needed on new Jewish settlements. At a private
dinner afterward at his home, Netanyahu angrily criticized her
comments as one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   On her departure the next day, Albright said she would not
return ``to tread water'' on progress toward peace, and she made
clear that she did not believe that Netanyahu was serious about
carrying out the Oslo agreements.
</P>
<P>
   From December 1997 to February 1998, Albright held three rounds
of talks, separately, with Netanyahu and Arafat, trying to restart
the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   During that period and in later months, when the groundwork was
laid for the summit meeting between Netanyahu and Arafat last
October, the administration complained that Netanyahu was a
difficult negotiating partner for a simple reason. When Labor was
in power, administration officials said, Washington's approach was
often to take ideas offered by the Israelis and sell them to
Arafat. But with Netanyahu, there was nothing to work with or to
sell, they said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the Wye River talks, enough common ground had
been found for steps to promote fulfillment of the agreement on
limited Palestinian self-rule signed more than three years before.
But the steps that Netanyahu and Arafat agreed to in the ``land for
security'' talks were put on hold by the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's victory essentially makes the role of United States as
mediator easier. Once he forms a government, administration
officials are expected to start immediately laying the groundwork
for resumed peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   They will be dealing with a government backed by a broad
spectrum of opinion that opinion polls indicate accepts the
inevitability of a limited Palestinian quasi-state in most of the
West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
