<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KARESH-WILDLIFE-NYT &LR;      05-17 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARESH-WILDLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MACHO LITERARY UPDATE FROM A BIG-GAME HEALER
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You think you're traveling too much for work?
Consider the life of Dr. William B. Karesh, a wildlife
veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   January, shlepping his usual 220 pounds of medical equipment, it
was down to a Kaa-Iya National Park in Bolivia to advise about
animal handling techniques, then to Patagonia to inspect seals and
sea lions. March, it was the Central African Republic, to help
develop preventive health care for gorillas. Then the Democratic
Republic of the Congo, to anesthetize the 600-pound antelopes
called Bongos (right, Bongos in the Congo) and put on radio
collars.
</P>
<P>
   There are also those unscheduled trips, as when Karesh was in
Congo last fall and got word of trouble in Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a big die-off'' _ this is zoological lingo for many
animals dying off _ Karesh says. Gazelles. ``Probably tens of
thousands of carcasses at 30 below zero. We get up, the sun is low,
they're out there frosted with snow.''
</P>
<P>
   A pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like powdered sugar. Everything was frozen. With the wind
chill, it was 80 degrees below.''
</P>
<P>
   Another pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not. I love to exaggerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearied, ladies, of those New York fellows who can brag only
about bagging an account? You might be interested in Karesh, 44,
who has been chased by elephants, bitten by penguins, nibbled by
leeches, and who, given his rather melancholic reports of love in
the wild, might be interested in you.
</P>
<P>
   An internationally recognized expert on wildlife conservation
and disease, Karesh, whom everyone calls Billy, heads the Field
Veterinary Program of the Wildife Conservation Society, which, in
addition to managing New York City's zoos, supports 300 research
projects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Working out of his home base at the Bronx Zoo (his actual home
is an apartment on City Island, furnished with a 15-year-old couch
and a chair he got when his mother moved _ you get the picture?),
he travels the world. When he's in New York, you might find him
outside his office at the zoo, shooting empty darts at targets on
the wall of the Wildlife Conservation Building, darts being used to
anesthetize animals or do medical biopsies.
</P>
<P>
   Karesh has also written a book, ``Appointment at the End of The
World,'' (Warner Books), which will be published next month.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance it looks to be that increasingly rare literary
species, the manly memoir. The dedication lists half a dozen
women's names, including Chloe no accent ``somewhere out there in
Africa, who recently reminded me of what a wonderful world we live
in.'' There are many photos of Karesh, biceps bulging, in
sleeveless khaki vests. And an opening that could figure in a
Hemingway contest:
</P>
<P>
   ``Loaded with a heavy backpack, I'm holding a rifle in my right
hand as I inch forward on the hard, dry ground. Forty yards ahead
is a herd of elephants, each animal weighing a few tons or more. A
startled, shiny brown seven-foot-long cobra . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Additional reading reveals a modest and generous voice.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the book, Karesh seems uneasy about the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It was his editor who demanded he personalize his own work,
Karesh said at a publishing party at the St. Regis Hotel last week,
and who also did a search with the computer, ``replacing we, we, we
with I, I, I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a computer,'' the editor said proudly, at the sidelines.
``It was me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a bench outside his office, having a slice of pizza,
Karesh reiterates.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't do this work alone, he said as his colleagues,
strolling by and seeing a reporter, give him the too-casual glance
that a lion passing another's kill might convey. Karesh broods. His
colleagues are going to hate him, he says. That editor. She said he
had to be a character.
</P>
<P>
   The bulging bicep pictures?
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave her 300 photos,'' Karesh says, ``Those are the ones she
chose. They gave me a lot of money, I figured I had to do what they
told me.''
</P>
<P>
   The macho consideration:
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get a big rush being close to an elephant, but I don't
get closer than I need to be. I swear what feels the best is
helping people help animals.''
</P>
<P>
   The macho consideration, continued:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just the doofus that does this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He always has, you might say. As a child in Charleston, S.C.,
(mother was an artist, father owned clothing stores) William Karesh
rescued orphaned birds and squirrels so regularly that The
Charleston Evening Post wrote an article about him. He got his
veterinary degree at the University of Georgia. Ten years ago he
was hired to start the Field Veterinary Program. He loves the life,
except for the aforementioned problems with romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can meet a woman, be deeply in love with them, then we have
to physically part ways because of the work,'' Karesh says. ``A
month or two later, I hear she's fallen in love with somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the ladies, what of Chloe, ``somewhere in Africa''?
</P>
<P>
   She's an elephant. Karesh and a Wildlife Conservation Society
team found her in the Central African Republic, anesthetized her
and attached a radio collar.
</P>
<P>
   She ended up 100 miles away in her search for food, causing a
logging company to limit cutting in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the emotional part of being way out in the jungle and
being able to touch her and work with her and have us help her help
her species just really touched me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
