<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC LIVES: THE DUKE'S CREW AND DR. CREW TOO 
BACKSTREET BOYS MEET PET FOOD GUY 
A LITTLE `RAGTIME' IN THE CHAPEL 

</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES BARRON WITH NINA SIEGAL AND MARCELLE S. FISCHLER   
(ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
THE DUKE'S CREW AND DR. CREW TOO 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never mind the trumpet. Wynton Marsalis was singing
and playing the piano. His cousin, Maurice Shelton, a chef from New
Orleans, was cooking Louisiana-style gumbo, red beans and rice.
</P>
<P>
   Marsalis' apartment on the Upper West Side was crowded. The
musician and actor Don Cheadle was there. So was the Lincoln Center
Jazz Orchestra, which had just played at Alice Tully Hall, the last
stop on a 36-city tour in celebration of the Duke Ellington
centennial.
</P>
<P>
   So was Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, whose father was a
clarinetist and played occasional gigs with Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a big supporter of our kids,'' Dr. Crew said of
Marsalis, ``and he's been a moral support to me, practically from
the day I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTREET BOYS MEET PET FOOD GUY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If only someone had made some introductions first.
Leonard N. Stern, meet the Backstreet Boys. Boys, meet Stern, chief
executive of a pet food and publishing conglomerate that also has
substantial real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Stern wondered why all the fuss. There he was,
waiting for the lights to go down at the premiere of ``Star Wars:
Episode One _ The Phantom Menace'' on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``First thing, a big, big security guard comes over and says,
`Move out of your seats,''' Stern said. ``I looked at the guy like
he's crazy. I said, `I'm not going anyplace.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then these perfectly nice guys sit down,'' he said. ``They
were wearing what I thought was funny-looking clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then fans clamoring for autographs swarmed around them. The
autograph they were clamoring for was not Stern's. ``The girls
would look and put their hands on their mouths and do what in my
day they did for Frank Sinatra or Elvis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Stern struck up a conversation. ``I said, `What do you
do for a living?' My wife gave me a good kick. She knew. I was
sitting next to a big blond guy. He wasn't upset at all.''
 &QL; 
A LITTLE `RAGTIME' IN THE CHAPEL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alton Fitzgerald White played two matinees on Sunday.
The first _ 22 miles from Broadway, where he stars as the pianist
Coalhouse Walker Jr. in the musical ``Ragtime'' _ was his debut at
the Brookville Reformed Church on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   How did he get from Broadway to Brookville? Last year, White
attended a friend's wedding at the church, liked the vibes and
struck up a friendship with the pastor, the Rev. Allan B. Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't singing to a standing-room-only crowd on Sunday
morning. There were only about 100 worshipers on hand. Many of the
seats at the front of the 267-year-old chapel were empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the theater, the orchestra seats are the more expensive
ones,'' Ramirez said. ``Here you can have orchestra seats and you
don't have to pay a high price.''
</P>
<P>
   First White stood in the aisle and sang ``Make Them Hear You''
from ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can sing, but God gives you the quality of your
voice,'' he said. ``He gave me a beautiful voice and I fell in love
with the applause.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he delivered one of the soul-searching poems he composes
between scenes in his dressing room at the Ford Center for the
Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The church debut, he said, was a good warm-up for his afternoon
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is about hope and faith and courage and justice,'' he
said. ``The show is like a sermon. It really is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
