<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE ON WHITMAN MOUNTS FOR NEW CURBS ON ABORTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Connecticut, New York)   (dal) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Hoping that the political pressure of a Senate
race will cause Gov. Christie Whitman to yield on the issue,
Assembly Republicans have begun their most promising effort yet in
a decade-old fight to require parental notification before an
abortion can be performed on a minor.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's Judiciary Committee has scheduled hearings on
Thursday for the legislation, and even some Democrats concede in
private that the proposal has enough support not only to sail
through the committee but to win approval in the full Assembly by a
veto-proof majority.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has yet to take a position on the parental notification
legislation, but since becoming governor, she has developed a
national reputation as a moderate Republican and she favors
abortion rights. And in 1997, she incurred the wrath of many
conservatives when she vetoed a measure banning a form of late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The notification bill is sponsored by Assemblyman John E. Rooney
and Assemblywoman Marion Crecco, with a dozen cosponsors, and, most
important, has the solid backing of the speaker, Jack Collins. In
the State Senate, which is also under Republican control, the
legislation is being sponsored by Sen. Gerald Cardinale and Sen.
Anthony R. Bucco and has at least a half-dozen cosponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require doctors to notify a parent or guardian
before performing or inducing an abortion on an unmarried girl
under 18. Doctors would be required to notify a parent either
personally or by certified mail, and an abortion could not be
legally performed until at least 48 hours after the parent has been
notified. The girl would be allowed to petition a Superior Court
judge for a waiver of the notification if she is a victim of abuse,
cruelty or neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who performs an abortion in violation of the law would be
subject to fines ranging from $1,000 to $5,000 and could be sued by
the minor's parent.
</P>
<P>
   At least 29 states, including neighboring Pennsylvania, require
some form of parental notification or counseling before a minor can
receive an abortion. And there have been repeated attempts in most
of the other states to pass similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, there have been various attempts to pass a
parental notification bill in New York, and none of them have come
close to succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, a girl under 16 cannot obtain an abortion
without receiving counseling from a physician, nurse, physician's
assistant or a qualified counselor who must explain the alternative
choices for managing the pregnancy, including adoption and
abortion. The counselor must also discuss the possibility of
involving the girl's parents in the decision, but notification of
the parents is not required.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have consistently shown that most New Jersey residents
back the right of a woman to have a legal abortion. But in an
attempt to establish a beachhead in the fight over the issue,
anti-abortion forces have tried since 1989, without success, to get
a parental notification bill through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   There are circumstances that make the looming fight markedly
different than the previous ones over the issue. It will be the
first time that the proposed legislation has reached a committee
for a hearing, a sign that supporters believe that they may finally
have the votes to muscle the bill onto the Assembly floor, where it
would have a good chance of passing with the help of Collins.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the more recent fights over abortion, most notably
the raucous debate in 1997 over the late-term procedure that
opponents call partial birth abortion, abortion rights supporters
have counted on a powerful group of political allies, starting with
Mrs. Whitman, to stave off any serious encroachments.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, abortion opponents have changed their strategy,
toned down the oratory and are counting on some fortuitous timing
to help clear the path. They believe that Mrs. Whitman, who came
under blistering attack from conservatives when she vetoed the
late-term abortion bill in June 1997, may be hard pressed to risk
rekindling that anger as she prepares to seek the Republican
nomination for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parental notification is a moderate position, and if the
governor is smart, she will sign this bill,'' said Marie Tasy,
director of public and legislative affairs for New Jersey Right to
Life. ``I think a majority of people in New Jersey, including some
who are pro-choice, support the idea of parental notification. It
is only a minority of abortion extremists that oppose this type of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Senate has a much more significant core of moderate
Republicans than the Assembly, but its leader, Donald T.
DiFrancesco, shares some of the same political pressures as Mrs.
Whitman. As president of the Senate, DiFrancesco is next in line in
succession for governor (New Jersey has no lieutenant governor),
and he would complete the final year of Mrs. Whitman's second term
if she was elected to the Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco, a moderate who supports abortion rights, has
already said that he will seek the governorship on his own in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that DiFrancesco will take a stance on the issue
until after the Assembly acts. And although the legislation has a
base of support among some Senate Republicans, the outcome in that
chamber is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   Leading one of the most strident lobbying efforts on behalf of
the notification bill is New Jersey Right to Life. Founded in 1972
and claiming a membership of 125,000 households, it is the oldest
and largest anti-abortion organization in the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
