<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BYRD-FAMILY-COX     05-17 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BYRD-FAMILY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Byrd's family angry about bill's failure
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Senate's failure to pass a hate-crimes law
named after dragging-death victim James Byrd Jr. was a slap in the
face to his family, nephew Darrell Verrett said Monday in a
telephone interview with The Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed and angry, members of Byrd's family have scheduled
a news conference today in Jasper and have pledged to return to
Austin as often as necessary to get a stronger hate-crimes law
approved in Texas. But they don't plan to directly blame Gov.
George W. Bush for the bill's failure even though the governor took
strong criticism for not publicly injecting himself into the
emotional debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him personally if he would use his influence to help
pass the bill,'' Verrett said of the governor. ``He told me, `No.'
We just have to accept that and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Saturday he did offer suggestions for compromise
before the proposal ran out of time for Senate consideration
Friday. Earlier, the governor had said only that he would consider
the bill if it cleared the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal named after Byrd, a black man dragged to his death
in Jasper last year, would have made it more serious to commit
crimes against people because of bias against specific
characteristics, including gender, race and sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family, mainly my grandparents, want to express their
disappointment at how the hate-crimes legislation was handled,''
Verrett said. ``We're more angry now. Even though Texas is the site
of the most terrible hate crime recently, it still doesn't see fit
to have stronger hate-crimes legislation. It's like a slap in the
face for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' current hate-crimes law makes it more serious to commit
crimes against people based on bias. Supporters of the proposed
Byrd Act say the law is too vague and needs strengthening and
clarification.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett said although the family doesn't plan to point fingers
or assign blame for the bill's fate, he believes the proposal would
have fared better if Bush weren't expected to begin running for
president after the legislative session. The inclusion of sexual
orientation as one of the protected groups could have presented
problems for Bush in the Republican presidential primary, but Bush
said that was never his problem with the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett said the bill would have helped his family to reach
closure on his uncle's brutal death. Because the men accused of
Byrd's slaying face the death penalty _ one already has been
convicted and sentenced to death _ the Byrd Act would not have
applied. Verrett said it might have prevented future hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want any family going through what we have,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, sponsored the proposal and
has helped the family organize today's news conference, which will
include Stella Byrd, James Byrd's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said she's given the family no advice or direction on
what to say, adding that family members are shocked that the bill
did not pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this shock caused them to want to say something about
it,'' Thompson said. ``They recognize that the persons that are
accused of causing the demise of their uncle are going on trial and
they are going to get some justice. But I think they looked at this
bill as a deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have helped,'' Verrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett also said that Byrd family members will return to Austin
for the next legislative session and for as many sessions as
necessary to get stronger hate-crimes legislation passed.Juan B.
Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jelizondo(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
