<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAMOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: PITCHING (YES, PITCHING) HAS RED SOX BATTLING YANKS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost by way of introduction, Jose Offerman would begin spring
training interviews by saying, ``I'm not Mo Vaughn.'' It was not a
line from a comedy routine like the one that gave the Broadway play
``I'm Not Rappaport'' its title. The newest member of the Boston
Red Sox was simply explaining that no matter how much the team paid
him, he was not going to hit home runs and drive in runs the way
Vaughn did.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman has contributed significantly to the Red Sox offense,
but he was right. He hasn't been Mo. No one in Boston has. The Red
Sox don't have a hitter in the top 10 in batting average, on-base
percentage, slugging percentage, home runs, runs batted in, runs
scored or total bases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Red Sox, for six weeks at least, have fooled a lot of
purported experts, and they've done it on the part of the Dan
Duquette plan that few people bothered to notice. It's called
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Remember pitching? Some readers may not be old enough to
remember when teams had pitching. Very few do now. The Red Sox
happen to be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a good pitching staff, you should be able to
contend,'' Duquette, the Red Sox general manager, said. ``You look
on that scoreboard every night and see teams scoring more than 10
runs. The strength of our club is the pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fenway Park Tuesday night the Yankees will see the strength
of the Red Sox strength. They will face Pedro Martinez, who is as
good and as overpowering a pitcher as baseball has today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for Pedro Martinez,'' Duquette said. ``He's just
been brilliant every game out.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 7-1 record, a 1.81 earned run average and 91 strikeouts
(30 in his last two starts), Martinez is the class of the American
League. Not only does he lead the league in victories and
strikeouts and is second in ERA (behind David Cone, whom he opposes
Tuesday night), but he also leads in fewest walks per nine innings
(1.7) and has the third-lowest opponents' batting average (.202).
</P>
<P>
   If that's not daunting enough for a team to anticipate, Martinez
has an impressive new playmate who will start the second game of
the three-game series with the Yankees. He is Juan Pena, 22 years
old next month, and a native of the Dominican Republic, like
Martinez, though by way of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox promoted Pena from the minor leagues after Bret
Saberhagen, who himself had been pitching well (2-1, 1.75), went on
the disabled list with a strained muscle in his right shoulder. In
two starts, the right-handed rookie has allowed one run and struck
out 15 in 13 innings for a 2-0 record and 0.69 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave the ball club a lift by giving us those quality
innings in his first two starts,'' Duquette said by telephone from
Boston yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the offense Offerman and Nomar Garciaparra and some
others have provided, and the Red Sox are in a position few
expected them to be at any time this season. It's a good enough
start to make a man feel vindicated. Does Duquette?
</P>
<P>
   ``From what?'' he responded. ``I didn't do anything to be
vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   During the winter no general manager was more maligned than
Duquette. No team suffered greater abuse than the Red Sox. ``We
couldn't figure that out,'' he said. ``We did have a decent year
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won the wild-card spot in the playoffs last season
even though they finished 22 games behind the Yankees. They beat
Cleveland in the first game of their series, then led in each
subsequent game but lost the next three. Then they botched the
Vaughn re-signing and lost him to the California Angels, and the
criticism cascaded.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Sunday morning dawned, they were tied for the first
place with the Yankees, whom they play three times both this week
and next. And they could easily be ahead of the Yankees had Tom
Gordon, their exceptional closer with saves in 47 consecutive
opportunities, not strained his elbow. He is back, but his
substitutes squandered 8 saves in 16 chances.
</P>
<P>
   What does this all mean? Are the Red Sox a pretender or
legitimately a contender? Can their pitching _ it could get even
better after the All-Star Game break when Ramon Martinez, Pedro's
older brother, completes his recovery from shoulder surgery and
joins the rotation _ carry them through the next four and a half
months?
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, has
talked recently about 1978 more than he ever has since that
disaster of a season for the Red Sox, whom he managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Boston,'' Zimmer declared the other day, looking
forward to this trip. He also told about renting Bucky Dent's house
in Wyckoff, NJ, in 1983 when he joined the Yankees as a coach. The
house, he said, perhaps exaggerating, had shaggy white carpet and a
picture in every room of Dent hitting the playoff-game home run
that killed him and the Red Sox in '78.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw Dent, Zimmer related, ``I told him I took the
pictures and put them face down and I spit tobacco juice on the
shag carpet.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Zimmer feels so liberated from that nightmarish season,
is he in for another psychic jolt? Could this be the year the Red
Sox get their revenge for 1978, knocking off the Yankees when they
thought they were invincible masters of the baseball world?
</P>
<P>
   What a devilish thought to muse upon as the Red Sox and the
Yankees play each other this week and next. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
