<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMEN-AKERS-ART-N     05-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-AKERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BATTERED PIONEER PRESSES ON FOR U.S. DESPITE INJURIES AND
ILLNESSES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ At halftime of the United States' 5-0 exhibition
victory over the Netherlands on Thursday, Michelle Akers approached
Coach Tony DiCicco and said, ``I have to come out.'' Nothing more
was said, and DiCicco immediately found a replacement. Akers had a
familiar flushed, hollow look of exhaustion. After so many years
together on the soccer field, DiCicco can read her face as if it
were an X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   Akers broke the first ground for women's soccer in America. She
scored the first goal for the national team, produced both American
goals in the victorious final of the inaugural Women's World Cup in
1991 and earned the first contract for a shoe endorsement. She is
chasing her teammate Mia Hamm to become the leading scorer in the
history of the game, male or female. But her success has come at a
great cost in injury and illness, and in recent years she has
seemingly spent as much time in the emergency room as the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   Her knees are latticed with the scars of so many operations that
she has lost count _ 10, 11, 12, she can't remember. She still has
the remnants of a black eye and numbness in her cheek and mouth
after breaking three bones below her left eye in a head-on
collision with another player in February. And since 1991 she has
struggled with chronic fatigue syndrome, which leaves her with
debilitating migraines, low blood pressure, memory loss, dizziness,
bouts of vomiting and an overwhelming feeling of lassitude.
</P>
<P>
   While her teammates celebrated at a University of Georgia
sorority house upon winning the 1996 Olympic gold medal, Akers'
only liquid refreshment came intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel empty, and I can't recover no matter what I eat or
drink, or how much I rest,'' Akers said recently, describing her
symptoms as she slumped on a couch in the lobby of the Milwaukee
Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   At 33, she is struggling to find a measure of durability for the
1999 Women's World Cup, which begins on June 19. Somehow, Akers
finds a way to keep going, and even when she is running on fumes,
her game is marked by fierce determination. In the heat of the
Atlanta Olympics, she managed to play the full 90 minutes in four
of five games, and she sent the United States' semifinal match into
overtime with a penalty kick against Norway. Whatever she can give
during the World Cup, DiCicco said, he will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle is the first player that created universal acceptance
of the women's game,'' DiCicco said. ``People like Pele and Franz
Beckenbauer, they saw her play and realized that women could play
the game as skillfully and tactically proficient as men could. The
way she heads passes. Her shot is incredibly hard with long-range
accuracy. She can put a player onto the ball with 40-yard passes,
right- and left-footed, and score a goal from 25 or 30 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Her teammates call her Mufasa, after the ``Lion King''
character, because of her mane of brown curls, and they tease her
about her forgetfulness. But they also know that she planted the
seeds for what has become a bountiful harvest of women's soccer.
The game is popular enough now that Hamm does commercials with
Michael Jordan and has her own signature Barbie doll. The Americans
dream of selling out the 93,000-seat Rose Bowl for the World Cup
final on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``She taught us what it's like to be professional,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   The national team's co-captain, Julie Foudy, added, ``She leaves
her heart and soul on the field, along with a few teeth and bone
chips.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers joined the women's national team upon its founding in
1985. Financing for the team seemed to come from the proceeds of a
parking meter. There were no salaries, only $10-a-day meal money,
$15 for top players. While training for their first road trip, to
Italy, Akers said, the American women were housed not in a plush
hotel but in a college dormitory along with the participants in a
high school cheerleading camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We woke up to cheerleaders yelling their heads off,'' Akers
said.
</P>
<P>
   She scored the team's first official goal on that trip, and six
years later she pounded home 10 goals in 6 games of the 1991 World
Cup, including two in the 2-1 victory over Norway in the final.
Before the tournament, she split one of her knees open by falling
on a sprinkler during training. The wound required 35 stitches and
left her knee seamed like a baseball. A doctor warned Akers that
the wound might split open upon hard contact, but she played anyway
and scored more goals than anyone else. She is one of only four
women who have scored at least 100 career goals, with 102. The
others are Mia Hamm and Elisabetta Vignotto, with 107 each, and
Carolina Morace, with 105. Vignotto and Morace, both Italian, are
retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style of living is to jump in wholeheartedly and leave it
all hanging out,'' Akers said. ``I'm either going to crash big time
or I'm going to celebrate big time.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the low-post pummeling at forward, the 5-foot-10-inch,
150-pound Akers has moved to the defensive midfield, where she can
still control a game with her calm presence, her ability to spray
passes to her teammates and her resolve to control air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The question for the World Cup is not her talent, but her
stamina. Akers said she had tried antidepressants and birth-control
pills in an attempt to stimulate her blood pressure, but she
reacted adversely to both. Other medication that might help her is
banned as performance-enhancing.
</P>
<P>
   She is trying to maintain her health through diet and rest. She
carries water to remain hydrated and she avoids dairy products, to
which she is allergic. Although she paved the way for endorsements
for her teammates, Akers is the only star on the team currently
without a shoe contract, refusing to expend excessive energy on
public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen,'' Akers said. ``This is
day by day. I can only do the best I can to conserve energy and
prepare for the World Cup. If it's not there on the day I need it,
it's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added: ``I'm hanging tough. I'll get the job done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-17-99 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
