<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREWERS NIP METS, 7-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Consistency is something Bobby Jones has strived for
since he put together an All-Star first half of the 1997 season.
But after a strong start this year, Jones has been struggling, and
on Monday night at Shea Stadium he had a second straight dismal
outing.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching on an extra day's rest because of elbow tenderness,
Jones allowed 7 runs and 11 hits in five and two-thirds innings in
a 7-6 loss to the struggling Milwaukee Brewers. In his previous
start, Jones yielded a career-high eight runs in Colorado in five
and a third innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did make things interesting during the late going in a
game that had the dawdling pace of an American League evening,
taking 3 hours 51 minutes, by scoring three times in the eighth.
Roger Cedeno had two stolen bases in the inning, and John Olerud
drove in two runs with a line-drive double off the right-field
fence. But Bob Wickman struck out Robin Ventura on a full-count
sinker to strand runners at first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Wickman also struck out Jermaine Allensworth looking on an 0-2
pitch with runners on first and third to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Jones (3-2) has had three strong outings followed
by three adequate outings, followed by two outings he would love to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Over his first three starts this season, Jones allowed 3 earned
runs in 21 innings, and he was 3-0. His next three starts were all
no-decisions in which he allowed 11 earned runs in 18 innings.
</P>
<P>
   And after his last two starts _ both losses _ have pushed his
earned run average to 5.22, there is reason to wonder which is the
real Bobby Jones?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Jones yielded two runs in the first inning, but
Mike Piazza evened the score with his fifth homer of the season, a
two-run shot to left off the Milwaukee left-hander Scott Karl (5-1)
in the bottom half.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers scored twice more in the third on four hits,
including a tie-breaking double from the former Met Jeromy Burnitz.
The Mets pulled within a run on Olerud's run-scoring single in the
fifth, but Milwaukee scored three more runs in the top of the sixth
to take a 7-3 lead and chase Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
